<L>Infinite harmes bene and eke &thorn;e teeres</L>
<L N="2828">Of olde folk and folk of tendere &yogh;eres</L>
<L>In all &thorn;e toun for deth of &thorn;is Thebean</L>
<L>ffor him &thorn;er wepen bo&thorn;[e] child and man</L>
<L>So grete weping was &thorn;er [non] certayn</L>
<L N="2832">Whan Ector was [y]brou&yogh;t and fressh ysclayn</L>
<L>To Troy allas &thorn;e pite &thorn;at was &thorn;ere</L>
<L>Cracching of chekes renting eke of here</L>
<L>Whi woldest &thorn;ou be dede &thorn;ise wommen crie</L>
<L N="2836">And haddest gold ynoghe and emelye</L>
<L>No man myght glade Theseus<MILESTONE N="40a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Sauyng his olde fadere Egeus</L>
<L>That knewe &thorn;is worldes transmutacioun</L>
<L N="2840">As he had sene it vp and do&umacr;n</L>
<L>Ioie after woo and woo aftere gladnesse</L>
<L>And shewe&thorn; hem ensample and liknesse</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t as &thorn;er dyed neuer man quod he</L>
<L N="2844">&thorn;at he ne lyued in er&thorn;e in som degre</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t so ther lyued neuere man he seide</L>
<L>In al &thorn;is world &thorn;at somtyme he ne deyed</L>
<L>&thorn;is world is nou&yogh;t but a &thorn;orght fare ful of woo</L>
<L N="2848">And we bene pilgrymes passing to and froo</L>
<L>De&thorn; is an ende of euery worldly sore</L>
<L>And ouer al &thorn;is &yogh;it seide he mychel more</L>
<L>To &thorn;is effecte ful wisely to enhorte</L>
<L N="2852">&thorn;e puple &thorn;at &thorn;ei. hem shul recomsorte</L>
<L>Duke Theseus wi&thorn; al his bisy Cure</L>
<L>Taste&thorn; nowe where &thorn;at &thorn;e sepulture</L>
<L>Of good Arcite may best ymaked be</L>
<L N="2856">And eke most honurable of degre</L>
<L>And atte last he toke conclusion</L>
<L>That &thorn;er as first Arcite and Palamon
<PB REF="00000112.tif" N="82"></L>
<L>Had for loue &thorn;e bataile hem bitwene</L>
<L N="2860">&thorn;at in &thorn;e self groue swete and grene</L>
<L>&thorn;er as he had his Amerous desires</L>
<L>His compleynt and for loue his hote fires</L>
<L>He wold[e] make a fire in which &thorn;e office</L>
<L N="2864">ffuneral he my&yogh;t hem all complice</L>
<L>He lete anon comaunde to hakke and hewe</L>
<L>&thorn;e okes olde and leye hem on a rewe</L>
<L>In colpons wel araied forto brenne</L>
<L N="2868">His Officers with swift[e] fote thei renne</L>
<L>And ri&yogh;t anon at his comaundement</L>
<L>And aftere Theseus ha&thorn; ysent</L>
<L>Aftere a beer and it al ouer spradde</L>
<L N="2872">Wi&thorn; clo&thorn; of gold the ricchest &thorn;at he hadde</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e same sute he clo&thorn;er Arcite<MILESTONE N="40b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Vpon his hondes [were] his gloues white</L>
<L>Eke on his hede a croune of laurere grene</L>
<L N="2876">And in his hand a swerde ful bri&yogh;t and kene</L>
<L>He laide him bare &thorn;e visage vnto &thorn;e bere</L>
<L>Ther wi&thorn; he wepte &thorn;at pite was to here</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e puple shulde sene hym all</L>
<L N="2880">Whan it was daie he brou&yogh;t hym to &thorn;e hall</L>
<L>&thorn;at rore&thorn; of &thorn;e crie and of &thorn;e sorowe sone</L>
<L>&thorn;oo gan &thorn;is woful Thebean Palamon</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; flotery berd and ruggy asshy heres</L>
<L N="2884">In clo&thorn;es blake dropped al wi&thorn; teeres</L>
<L>And passing o&thorn;er of weping Emelie</L>
<L>She rewfullest of al &thorn;e companye</L>
<L>In as moche as &thorn;e seruyse shuld be</L>
<L N="2888">&thorn;e more noble and riche in his degre</L>
<L>Duke Theseus lete for&thorn; &thorn;e stedes bringe</L>
<L>That trapped were in steel al gliteringe</L>
<L>And keuered wi&thorn; &thorn;e armes of Dame Arcite<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>or</I> Daine]</NOTE></L>
<L N="2892">Vppon &thorn;ise stedes grete and white</L>
<L>Ther stoden folk of which oon bare his sheelde</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er his spere vpon his hondes helde
<PB REF="00000113.tif" N="83"></L>
<L>The iij. bare wi&thorn; him bowe turkeys</L>
<L N="2896">Of brent gold was &thorn;e caas and eke &thorn;e harneys</L>
<L>And riden for&thorn; a paas wi&thorn; sory chere</L>
<L>Towardes &thorn;e groue as &yogh;e shul after here</L>
<L>The noblest of &thorn;e Grekes &thorn;at &thorn;er were</L>
<L N="2900">Vpon her shulders cariden &thorn;e berc</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; sclak[e] paas and yen rede and wete</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh out &thorn;e Cite by &thorn;e maister strete</L>
<L>&thorn;at sprad was al wi&thorn; blak and wonder hye</L>
<L N="2904">Ri&yogh;t of &thorn;e same is &thorn;e strete ywrie</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;e Ri&yogh;t honde went olde Egeus</L>
<L>And on &thorn;at o&thorn;er side Duke Theseus</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; vesselles in her hondes of gold ful fyne</L>
<L N="2908">Al ful of hony. mylk. [and] blood. and wyne</L>
<L>Eke Palamon with ful grete companye<MILESTONE N="41a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And aftere &thorn;at come wooful Emelie</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; fire in hand as was &thorn;at time &thorn;e Gyse</L>
<L N="2912">To do &thorn;e office of funeral seruise</L>
<L>High labour / and ful grete apparaillinge</L>
<L>Was at &thorn;e seruyse and at &thorn;e fire makinge</L>
<L>That wi&thorn; his grene top &thorn;e heuene raught</L>
<L N="2916">And xx<SUP>ti</SUP> fadmes in brede &thorn;e armes raught</L>
<L>This is to seine &thorn;e bowes were so brode</L>
<L>Of strawe first &thorn;er was leide mony a lode</L>
<L>But howe &thorn;e fire was maked vp[on] hi&yogh;t</L>
<L N="2920">Ne eke &thorn;e names howe &thorn;e trees hi&yogh;t</L>
<L>As Oke. fir. birch. asp. alder. Elme. popelere.</L>
<L>Wilowe. holme. playn. assh. box. Chesteyn. bynd. laure.</L>
<L>Mapel. &thorn;orne. becche. ewe. hasell. wypultre.</L>
<L N="2924">How &thorn;ei were felled shal not be tolde for me</L>
<L>Ne howe &thorn;e goddes ronnen vp and doun</L>
<L>Disherites of her habitacioun</L>
<L>In whiche &thorn;ei wonden in rest and pees</L>
<L N="2928">Nymphes. ffawnes and amadries</L>
<L>Ne howe &thorn;e beestes ne &thorn;e briddes alle</L>
<L>ffledden for fere whan &thorn;ei were falle
<PB REF="00000114.tif" N="84"></L>
<L>Ne howe &thorn;e grounde agast was of &thorn;e li&yogh;t</L>
<L N="2932">That was not wonte to se &thorn;e sonne bri&yogh;t</L>
<L>Ne how &thorn;e fire was couched first wi&thorn; stre</L>
<L>And &thorn;an wi&thorn; drie stikkes clouen a &thorn;ree</L>
<L>And &thorn;an wi&thorn; grene wode and spicerie</L>
<L N="2936">And &thorn;an wi&thorn; clo&thorn;e of gold and [wi&thorn;] perrie</L>
<L>And Garlondes honging wi&thorn; mony a floure</L>
<L>The myrr &thorn;ensence with swete odoure</L>
<L>Ne how arcite lay among al &thorn;is</L>
<L N="2940">Ne what richesse aboute his body is</L>
<L>Ne howe Emely as was &thorn;e Gise</L>
<L>Put in &thorn;e fire of funeral seruise</L>
<L>Ne howe she swowned whan made was &thorn;e fire</L>
<L N="2944">Ne what she spak ne what was her desire</L>
<L>Ne what Ielous men in &thorn;e fire cast<MILESTONE N="41b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;e fire was grete and brente fast</L>
<L>Nowe howe some cast her sheelde and some her spere</L>
<L N="2948">And of her vestementes which &thorn;ei were</L>
<L>And Coppes ful of mylke and wyne and blood</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e fire &thorn;at brent as it were wode</L>
<L>Ne howe &thorn;e greges wi&thorn; an huge route</L>
<L N="2952">Thrise riden al &thorn;e fire aboute</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;e lift honde wi&thorn; a loude shoutinge</L>
<L>And thries wi&thorn; her speres clateringe</L>
<L>And thries how &thorn;e ladise gan crie</L>
<L N="2956">Ne howe &thorn;at lad was homward Emely</L>
<L>Ne how arcyte is brent in asshen colde</L>
<L>Ne how &thorn;e liche-wake was [y]holde</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at nyght ne howe &thorn;e Grekes pleye</L>
<L N="2960">The wake-plaies kepe I not to seie</L>
<L>Who wrastele&thorn; best naked with oile anoynt</L>
<L>Ne who [that] bare him best in no dysioynt</L>
<L>I wil not tellen all howe &thorn;ei [ben] gone</L>
<L N="2964">Home til Athenes whan &thorn;e play is done</L>
<L>But shortely to &thorn;e point &thorn;an wil I wende</L>
<L>And make[n] of my longe tale an ende
<PB REF="00000115.tif" N="85"></L>
<L>By processe and by length of &yogh;eres</L>
<L N="2968">Al stinte is &thorn;e mournyng and &thorn;e teeres</L>
<L>Of Greges by oon general assent</L>
<L>Than semed me &thorn;er was a parlement</L>
<L>At Athenes vpon a certeyn point and caas</L>
<L N="2972">And amonge pointes [ther] yspoken waas</L>
<L>To haue wi&thorn; certeyn contrees alliance</L>
<L>And haue of Thebeanes fully obeisance</L>
<L>ffor which this noble theseus an&omacr;n</L>
<L N="2976">Lete sende[n] after gentile Palamon</L>
<L>Vnwist of him what was &thorn;e cause and whi</L>
<L>But in his blake clo&thorn;es sorowfully</L>
<L>He come at his comaundement in hie</L>
<L N="2980">Tho sente Theseus for Emelye</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;ei were sette and huyst was al &thorn;e place<MILESTONE N="42a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And Theseus abiden ha&thorn; &thorn;e space</L>
<L>Or eny worde come fro his wise brest</L>
<L N="2984">His yen sette he &thorn;er hym lest</L>
<L>And such a sad visage he sighed stille</L>
<L>And after &thorn;at ri&yogh;t &thorn;us he seide his wille</L>
<L>The firste mouer of &thorn;e cause aboue</L>
<L N="2988">Whan he first made &thorn;e faire cheyn of loue</L>
<L>Gret was &thorn;e effecte and high was his entent</L>
<L>Wel wist he why and what &thorn;erof he ment</L>
<L>ffor wi&thorn; &thorn;at faire cheyne of loue he bonde</L>
<L N="2992">The fuyre. &thorn;e. Eire &thorn;e water and &thorn;e londe</L>
<L>In certeyn boondes &thorn;at &thorn;ei may not flee</L>
<L>That same prince and &thorn;at same mouer quod he</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; stablesshed in &thorn;is wrecched world adoun</L>
<L N="2996">Certeyn days and Dominacioun</L>
<L>To al &thorn;at is engendred in &thorn;is place</L>
<L>Ouer &thorn;e whiche day &thorn;ei may not pace</L>
<L>Al mowe &thorn;ei &yogh;it &thorn;e daies abregge</L>
<L N="3000">Ther nys noon autorite to legge</L>
<L>ffor it is proued by experience</L>
<L>But that me lust declare my sentence
<PB REF="00000116.tif" N="86"></L>
<L>Than may men by &thorn;is order discerne</L>
<L N="3004">That &thorn;ilk mouer stable is and eterne</L>
<L>Wel may men knowe but it be a fool</L>
<L>That euery part darrayueth fro his hool</L>
<L>ffor nature ha&thorn; not taken his bygynnyng</L>
<L N="3008">Of no partie or of catel of no &thorn;ing</L>
<L>But oon &thorn;inge &thorn;at parfit is and stable</L>
<L>Descendinge so til it be corruptable</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore of his wise purueaunce</L>
<L N="3012">He ha&thorn; so wel bysette his ordynaunce</L>
<L>&THORN;at specifie of &thorn;ingges and progressiones</L>
<L>Shullen endure by successiones</L>
<L>And not eterne wi&thorn; oute eny lye</L>
<L N="3016">This maist &thorn;ou vnderstond and see atte ye</L>
<L>Lo the Oke &thorn;at hath so longe a norshinge<MILESTONE N="42b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffro &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at it bygynne&thorn; furst to springe</L>
<L>And ha&thorn; so longe a lif as &yogh;e may se</L>
<L N="3020">&YOGH;it at &thorn;e laste waasted is &thorn;e tree</L>
<L>Considere&thorn; eke howe &thorn;at &thorn;e herde stone</L>
<L>Vnder our fete on which we treden and gone</L>
<L>&YOGH;it .&yogh;. waste&thorn; it as it lith in &thorn;e way</L>
<L N="3024">&thorn;e Brode Ryuer somtyme wexe&thorn; dray</L>
<L>&thorn;e grete townes so wide wane and wende</L>
<L>Than &thorn;e see &thorn;at al &thorn;is &thorn;ing ha&thorn; ende</L>
<L>And man and womman so we wil also</L>
<L N="3028">That nede&thorn; in oon of &thorn;e teermes twoo</L>
<L>&thorn;at is to sayn in you&thorn;e or ellis in age</L>
<L>He mote be dede &thorn;e kinge as wel as page</L>
<L>Some in his bed some in &thorn;e depe see</L>
<L N="3032">Some in &thorn;e large felde as &yogh;e may see</L>
<L>Ther helpe&thorn; nou&yogh;t al go&thorn; &thorn;at ilk waye</L>
<L>&thorn;an may I seie &thorn;at al &thorn;is &thorn;ing wil deye</L>
<L>What make&thorn; &thorn;is but Iubiter &thorn;e king</L>
<L N="3036">&thorn;at is prince and cause of al &thorn;ing</L>
<L>Couerting al vnto his propre wille</L>
<L>ffrom which it is darreyude so&thorn; to telle
<PB REF="00000117.tif" N="87"></L>
<L>Aud here agayne no creature on lyue</L>
<L N="3040">Of no degre availle&thorn; forto stryue</L>
<L>Than is it wisdome as &thorn;enke&thorn; me</L>
<L>To make vertue of necessite</L>
<L>And take it wel &thorn;at we may not eschew</L>
<L N="3044">And namely &thorn;at . &thorn;at to vs all is dwe</L>
<L>And who so grucche&thorn; ou&yogh;t he do&thorn; foly</L>
<L>And rebell is to him &thorn;at al may gye</L>
<L>And certeynly a man ha&thorn; most honour</L>
<L N="3048">To dyen in his excellence and flour</L>
<L>Whan he is siker of his good name</L>
<L>&thorn;an ha&thorn; he done his frende ne hym no shame</L>
<L>And gladder au&yogh;t / his frende . ben of his deth</L>
<L N="3052">Whan wi&thorn; honour y&yogh;olden is vp &thorn;e breeth</L>
<L>Than whan his name appalled is for age<MILESTONE N="43a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor al for&yogh;eten is his vassalage</L>
<L>Than is &thorn;e best as for a wor&thorn;i fame</L>
<L N="3056">To dyen whan he is best of name</L>
<L>The Contrarie of al &thorn;is is wilfulnesse</L>
<L>Why grucche we whi haue we heuynesse</L>
<L>That goode Arcite of Chyualre &thorn;e flour</L>
<L N="3060">Departed is wi&thorn; dwete and wi&thorn; honour</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e foule prison of &thorn;is liff</L>
<L>Whi grucchen here his cosyn and his wiff</L>
<L>Of his welfare &thorn;at loue&thorn; hem so wel</L>
<L N="3064">Can he hem &thorn;onk. nay god wote neuer a dell</L>
<L>That bo&thorn; his soule and eke hem [self] offende</L>
<L>And &yogh;it &thorn;ei mowe not hir lustes amende</L>
<L>What may conclude of &thorn;is longe serie</L>
<L N="3068">But after woo I rede vs be merie</L>
<L>And &thorn;anken Iubiter of al his grace</L>
<L>And or we departen from &thorn;is place</L>
<L>I rede we made of sorowes twoo</L>
<L N="3072">Oo parfite Ioie lasting euermoo</L>
<L>And loke nowe wher most sorowe is her Inne</L>
<L>&thorn;er at wil I furst bygynne
<PB REF="00000118.tif" N="88"></L>
<L>Suster quod he &thorn;is is my ful assent</L>
<L N="3076">Wi&thorn; all thaues here of my parlement</L>
<L>That Gentile Palamon &yogh;our owne knyg&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;at serue&thorn; &yogh;ou wi&thorn; wille herte and my&yogh;t</L>
<L>And euer ha&thorn; do si&thorn;en &yogh;e first hym knewe</L>
<L N="3080">&thorn;at &yogh;e shal of &yogh;oure grace vpon hym rewe</L>
<L>And taken [hym] for husbonde and for lord</L>
<L>Lene me &yogh;oure honde for &thorn;is is our accord</L>
<L>Lete se nowe of &yogh;oure womanly pite</L>
<L N="3084">He is a kingges bro&thorn;er sone parde</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou&yogh;e he be a poor bachiler</L>
<L>Si&thorn; he ha&thorn; serued &yogh;ou so mony a &yogh;ere</L>
<L>And had for &yogh;ou so grete aduersite</L>
<L N="3088">It most be considered leue&thorn; me</L>
<L>ffor gentel Mercy ou&yogh;t to passen ri&yogh;t<MILESTONE N="43b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Than seide he &thorn;us to Palamon &thorn;e kny&yogh;t</L>
<L>I trowe &thorn;ere nede litel sermonynge</L>
<L N="3092">To make &yogh;ou assente to &thorn;is &thorn;inge</L>
<L>Comme&thorn; nere and take&thorn; &yogh;oure lady by &thorn;e honde</L>
<L>Bytwix hem two was made anon &thorn;e bonde</L>
<L>&thorn;at hi&yogh;te Matrimoyne or mariage</L>
<L N="3096">By all &thorn;e counsaile and [the] baronage</L>
<L>And &thorn;us wi&thorn; al[le] blisse and melodye</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; Palamon ywedded Emelye</L>
<L>And god &thorn;at al &thorn;is world ha&thorn; wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="3100">Send hym his loue &thorn;at ha&thorn; it dere bou&yogh;t</L>
<L>ffor nowe is Palamon in al[le] wele</L>
<L>Lyuynge in al blisse in ricches and in hele</L>
<L>And Emely him loue&thorn; so tenderly</L>
<L N="3104">And he hir serue&thorn; so gentely</L>
<L>Was neuer no worde hem bitwene</L>
<L>Of Ielousie or eny o&thorn;er tene</L>
<L>Thus ende&thorn; &thorn;e tale of Palamon and Emelye</L>
<L N="3108">And god saue al &thorn;is faire companye</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; Here ende&thorn; &thorn;e knyghtes tale</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000119.tif" N="89">
<HEAD>&amp; here bygnne&thorn; &thorn;e Prologe of &thorn;e Milleres tale &para; The Prologe</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;e knyght had &thorn;us his tale told</L>
<L>In al the companye nas &thorn;er &yogh;onge ne olde</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne seide it was a noble storie</L>
<L N="3112">And wor&thorn;i to be drawe in memorie</L>
<L>And namely the gentels euerechon</L>
<L>Our hooste loughe and swore so mot I gon</L>
<L>This go&thorn; a ri&yogh;t vnbokeled is &thorn;e male</L>
<L N="3116">Lat se nowe who shal telle ano&thorn;ere tale</L>
<L>ffor trewly &thorn;e game is wel bygonne</L>
<L>Now telle&thorn; &yogh;e sir monke &yogh;if &yogh;e conne</L>
<L>Somwhat to quyte wi&thorn; &thorn;e knyghtes tale</L>
<L N="3120">The Miller &thorn;at for-dronke was al pale</L>
<L>So &thorn;at vnne&thorn;es vppon his hors he satte</L>
<L>He wold availe nei&thorn;e hode ne hatte</L>
<L>Ne abide no man for his curtesie<MILESTONE N="44a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3124">But in Pilates vois he bygan to crie</L>
<L>And swore by armes blode and bones</L>
<L>I can a noble tale for &thorn;e nones</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e which I wil now quyte &thorn;e kny&yogh;tes tale</L>
<L N="3128">Our [hooste] seghe &thorn;at he was dronke of ale</L>
<L>And seide abide Robyn leue brother</L>
<L>Somme better man shal telle vs first ano&thorn;er</L>
<L>Abide and [let] us wirche thriftely</L>
<L N="3132">By goddes soule quod he &thorn;at wil not I</L>
<L>ffor I wil speke or ellis go my way</L>
<L>Our hooste answerd seye on a deuel way</L>
<L>Thou arte a fool &thorn;i witt is ouercommen</L>
<L N="3136">Now harkene&thorn; quod &thorn;e myllere al and som</L>
<L>&para; But first I make a protestacioun</L>
<L>&thorn;at I am dronke I knowe it by my soun</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore &yogh;if I mysspeke or say</L>
<L N="3140">Wite it &thorn;e Ale of suthwerk I &yogh;ou pray
<PB REF="00000120.tif" N="90"></L>
<L>ffor I will telle a legend and a liff</L>
<L>Bo&thorn; of a Carpenter and [of] his wiff</L>
<L>How &thorn;at a clerke reft the wri&yogh;tes cappe</L>
<L N="3144">The reue answerd and seide stint of &thorn;i clappe</L>
<L>Lat be &thorn;i lewde dronken harlotrie</L>
<L>It is a synne and eke a grete folye</L>
<L>To appeyren eny man or hym diffame</L>
<L N="3148">And eke to bringe wives in such name</L>
<L>&THORN;ow maist ynowe of o&thorn;er &thorn;ingges seine</L>
<L>&THORN;is dronken Millere spake ful sone ageyn</L>
<L>And seide leue bro&thorn;er oswalde</L>
<L N="3152">Who ha&thorn; no wif. is no kukwold</L>
<L>But I seie not &thorn;erfor &thorn;at &thorn;ou art oon</L>
<L>Ther ben ful good[e] wyues mony on</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
<L N="3156">. . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whi art &thorn;ou angry wi&thorn; my tale nowe</L>
<L>I haue a wiff parde as wel as &thorn;ou/</L>
<L>&YOGH;it nolde I for &thorn;e oxen in my plogh</L>
<L N="3160">Take vpon me more &thorn;an ynogh</L>
<L>As demen of my seluen &thorn;at I were oone<MILESTONE N="44b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I wil bylieue &thorn;at &thorn;at I am none</L>
<L>An husbond shuld not be inquesitif</L>
<L N="3164">Of goddes priuete ne of his wif</L>
<L>So he may finde goddes foyson &thorn;ere</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e remenant nede&thorn; nat to enquere</L>
<L>What shuld I more seie but &thorn;e Millere</L>
<L N="3168">He nyl his wordes for no man for-bere</L>
<L>But tolde his Chirles tale in his manere</L>
<L>Me for&thorn;enke&thorn; &thorn;at I shal reherce it here</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore euery gentil wi&yogh;t I preie</L>
<L N="3172">Deme&thorn; not for goddes loue &thorn;at I seie</L>
<L>Of euel entent but for I mote reherce</L>
<L>Her tales alle be &thorn;ei better or wors/</L>
<L>Or ellis fals somen of my matere</L>
<L N="3176">And &thorn;erfore who list it not here
<PB REF="00000121.tif" N="91"></L>
<L>Torne ouer &thorn;e lief and chese ano&thorn;er tale</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;e shul fynde ynow grete and smale</L>
<L>Of historial &thorn;inge &thorn;at touche&thorn; gentilnesse</L>
<L N="3180">And eke moralite and holynesse</L>
<L>Blame not me &yogh;if &thorn;at ye chese amys</L>
<L>The Millere is a cheerle &yogh;e knowe wel &thorn;is</L>
<L>So was the Reue eke and other moo</L>
<L N="3184">And harlotrie &thorn;ei told bo&thorn; twoo</L>
<L>Avise &yogh;ou and put me out of blame</L>
<L>And eke men shal not make ernest of game</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER><B>Thus ende&thorn; &thorn;e prologe.</B><NOTE PLACE="end">[<I>No break in the MS.</I>]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000122.tif" N="92">
<HEAD>And here by|gynne&thorn; &thorn;e Millers Tale. &para; Narracio</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whilom &thorn;er was dwelling in Oxenford</L>
<L N="3188">A riche gnof &thorn;at gestes helde to bord</L>
<L>And of his craft he was a Carpenter</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; him &thorn;er was dwelling a pore scolere</L>
<L>Had lerned arte but al his fantasie</L>
<L N="3192">Was turned forto lere Astrologie</L>
<L>And cowde a certeyn of conclusions</L>
<L>To demen by interrogacions.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at men axed him incerteyn houres<MILESTONE N="45a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3196">Whan &thorn;at men shuld haue drou&yogh;te of shoures</L>
<L>Or &yogh;if men axed him what shuld byfalle</L>
<L>Of euery &thorn;ing I may not rekne alle</L>
<L>This tale was cleped hende Nicholas</L>
<L N="3200">Of derne loue and priue solas</L>
<L>And &thorn;erto he was sclegh and ful priue</L>
<L>And liche to a maiden meke to see</L>
<L>A chambre had he in &thorn;at ostelrie</L>
<L N="3204">Allone wi&thorn;-out eny companye</L>
<L>fful fetist dight wi&thorn; herbes swote</L>
<L>And he hym. self as swete as is &thorn;e rote</L>
<L>Of licorace or ony sytuale</L>
<L N="3208">His almagist and bokes grete and smale</L>
<L>His aster-laboure longinge for his arte</L>
<L>His awgryme stones layen ful faire aparte</L>
<L>On shelues couched at his beddes heuede</L>
<L N="3212">His presse ykeuered wi&thorn; a falding rede</L>
<L>And al aboue &thorn;er lay a gay sautrie</L>
<L>On which he made on nyghtes melodye</L>
<L>So swetely &thorn;at al &thorn;e chambre ronge</L>
<L N="3216">And angelus ad virginem he songe</L>
<L>And after &thorn;at he songe &thorn;e kingges note</L>
<L>fful ofte blessed was his mery &thorn;rote
<PB REF="00000123.tif" N="93"></L>
<L>And &thorn;us &thorn;e swete Clerk his tyme spente</L>
<L N="3220">Aftere his frendes fynding and his rente</L>
<L>This Carpentere had wedded newe a wiff</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at he loued more &thorn;an his liff</L>
<L>Of xviij. &yogh;ere she was of age</L>
<L N="3224">Ielous he was and kept hir streit in cage</L>
<L>ffor she was wily and yonge and he was olde</L>
<L>And demed hym self to be like a Cukwolde</L>
<L>He knewe not Caton for his wit is rude</L>
<L N="3228">&THORN;at bad man shuld wedde his similitude</L>
<L>Men shul wedde aftere her estate</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;ou&thorn;e and elde is oft at debate</L>
<L>But sith he was fallen in &thorn;e snare<MILESTONE N="45b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3232">He most enduren as o&thorn;er folk his care</L>
<L>ffair was &thorn;is yonge wif and &thorn;er wi&thorn; all</L>
<L>As eny wesell her body gent and small</L>
<L>A seynt she wered barred al of silk</L>
<L N="3236">A barmeclo&thorn;e as white as morn[e] mylk</L>
<L>Vpon her lendes ful of mony a gore</L>
<L>White was hir smok and enbrauded al byfore</L>
<L>And eke be-hinde on her coler aboute</L>
<L N="3240">Of Cole-blak silk with-Inne and eke wi&thorn;-oute</L>
<L>The tapes of hir white volipere</L>
<L>Were of &thorn;e same sute of hir colere</L>
<L>Hir Philett brode of silk and sette ful hie</L>
<L N="3244">And sikerly she had a lykerous ye</L>
<L>fful smal ypulled were her browes twoo/</L>
<L>And &thorn;oo were bent and blake as eny sloo/</L>
<L>She was more blisful on to se</L>
<L N="3248">&thorn;an is &thorn;e newe Perient tree</L>
<L>And softer &thorn;an &thorn;e woll is of ei&thorn;er</L>
<L>And by hir girdel henge a purs of leder</L>
<L>Tasshed wi&thorn; silk and perled with latoun</L>
<L N="3252">In al &thorn;is worlde to seke vp and doun</L>
<L>Ther nys no man so wise &thorn;at cou&thorn;e &thorn;enche</L>
<L>So gay a popelot or [such] a wenche
<PB REF="00000124.tif" N="94"></L>
<L>fful bri&yogh;t was the shynyng of her hwe</L>
<L N="3256">Than in &thorn;e toure &thorn;e noble forged newe</L>
<L>But of her songe it was as loude and &yogh;erne</L>
<L>As eny swalowe sittinge on a beerne</L>
<L>&THORN;erto she cou&thorn;e skippe and make a game</L>
<L N="3260">As eny kid or calf folowing his dame</L>
<L>Her mou&thorn;e was swete as braket or meth</L>
<L>Or horde of apples leide in hay or heth</L>
<L>Wynsinge she was as is a Ioly colt</L>
<L N="3264">Longe as a mast and vpward as a bolt</L>
<L>A broche she bare on her loue coler</L>
<L>As brode as is &thorn;e boos of a bokelere</L>
<L>Her shoes were laised on her legges hie<MILESTONE N="46a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3268">She was a Primeroll a Pigges nye</L>
<L>ffor eny lorde to liggen in his bedde</L>
<L>Or &yogh;it for eny [good] &yogh;eman to wedde</L>
<L>Now sir and eft sir. and so bifelle &thorn;e caas</L>
<L N="3272">That on a day &thorn;is heende Nicholas /</L>
<L>ffelle wi&thorn; &thorn;is yonge wif forto rage and play</L>
<L>While &thorn;at her husbonde was at osenay</L>
<L>As clerkes bene ful subtile and ful queynte</L>
<L N="3276">And prively he kau&yogh;t hur by &thorn;e queynte</L>
<L>And seide ywis but I haue my wille</L>
<L>ffor deerne loue of &thorn;e lemman I spille</L>
<L>And helde hure fast by &thorn;e haunche bonys</L>
<L N="3280">And seide lemman my will at onys</L>
<L>Or I wil die as god me saue</L>
<L>And she spronge as a colt in traue</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; her hede sche wried fast away</L>
<L N="3284">She saide I wil not kisse &thorn;e by my fay</L>
<L>Wy labbe quod she latt be Nicholas</L>
<L>Or I wil crie out harowe and alas</L>
<L>Do way &yogh;oure hondes for &yogh;our curtesie</L>
<L N="3288">This Nicholas gan mercy forto crie</L>
<L>And spake so faire and profred him ful fast</L>
<L>&thorn;at she her loue graunted hym atte last
<PB REF="00000125.tif" N="95"></L>
<L>And swoor hir oo&thorn;e by seint Thamas of kent</L>
<L N="3292">That she wolde bene at his comaundement</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at she may hir laizere wel aspie</L>
<L>Myn husbonde is so ful of Ielousie</L>
<L>&THORN;at but &yogh;e waite wele and by prive</L>
<L N="3296">I woote ri&yogh;t wel I ne am but dede quod she</L>
<L>&YOGH;e mote be ful deerne as in &thorn;is caas</L>
<L>Nay &thorn;erof care &yogh;ou not quod Nicholaas</L>
<L>A Clerk has li&thorn;erly bysette his while</L>
<L N="3300">But &yogh;if he cou&thorn;e a carpenter begile</L>
<L>And &thorn;us &thorn;ei acorded and sworne</L>
<L>To awaite a tyme as I haue seide biforn</L>
<L>Whan Nicholas had don &thorn;us euery dele<MILESTONE N="46b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3304">And twakked her aboute &thorn;e lendes welle</L>
<L>He kisse&thorn; her swete and take&thorn; his sautrie</L>
<L>And pleie&thorn; fast and make&thorn; melodye</L>
<L>&thorn;an fille it &thorn;us &thorn;at to &thorn;e parissh chirche</L>
<L N="3308">Cristes werkes for to wirche</L>
<L>This good wif went vpon an halyday</L>
<L>Hir forhede shoon as bri&yogh;t as eny day</L>
<L>So was it wasshe whan she left her werk</L>
<L N="3312">Now was &thorn;ere of &thorn;e chirch a parissh clerk</L>
<L>&THORN;e which was cleped absalon</L>
<L>Crulle was his heer and as &thorn;e golde shone</L>
<L>And strouted as [a] fanne large and brode</L>
<L N="3316">fful streite and euene laie his Ioly shode</L>
<L>His rudde was rede his eyen grey as goos</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Powles wyndowes corven in his shoos</L>
<L>In hosen rede he wente fetisly</L>
<L N="3320">I-clad he was ful smal and proprely</L>
<L>Al in a kirtel of light wagett</L>
<L>fful faire and &thorn;ikke ben &thorn;e poyntes sette</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-vpon he had [a] gay surplise</L>
<L N="3324">As white as is &thorn;e blossom on [the] rise</L>
<L>A mery child he was so god me saue</L>
<L>Wel coude he late blood [and] clippe and shaue
<PB REF="00000126.tif" N="96"></L>
<L>And make a chartere of londe or a quytaunce</L>
<L N="3328">In xx<SUP>ti</SUP> maners coude he trippe and daunce</L>
<L>After the scole of Oxenforde &thorn;oo</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; his legges casten to and froo</L>
<L>And pleyen songes on a small rybibe</L>
<L N="3332">Some he songe a loude quynybe</L>
<L>As as wel coude he pley on a gytern</L>
<L>In al &thorn;e towne nas brewhous ne taucrn</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne viset wi&thorn; his solas</L>
<L N="3336">&thorn;er eny gailerd tapster was</L>
<L>But soth to sayn he was somdele squeymous</L>
<L>Of fartinge and of speche daungerous</L>
<L>This Absolon &thorn;at was Ioly and gay<MILESTONE N="47a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3340">Go&thorn; wi&thorn; a sensure on &thorn;e sonday</L>
<L>Sensinge &thorn;e wyues of &thorn;e parissh fast</L>
<L>And mony a louely loke on hem he cast</L>
<L>And namely on &thorn;e Carpenters wiff</L>
<L N="3344">To loke on hyr him &thorn;ou&yogh;t a mery liff</L>
<L>She was so propre. swete. and likerous</L>
<L>I dar wel say and she had be a mous</L>
<L>And he a Catt he wold hire hent an&omacr;n</L>
<L N="3348">This parissh clerk &thorn;is Ioly absolon</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; in his herte such a loue longynge</L>
<L>That of no wiff toke he non offringe</L>
<L>For curtesie he seide he wolde none</L>
<L N="3352">The mone whan it was ny&yogh;t bri&yogh;t shone</L>
<L>And absolon his gitern ha&thorn; [i]take</L>
<L>For paramours he &thorn;ou&yogh;te forto wake</L>
<L>And for&thorn;e he go&thorn; Ielous and amerous</L>
<L N="3356">Til he come to &thorn;e Carpenter[e]s hous</L>
<L>A litel aftere &thorn;e Cok had ycrowe</L>
<L>And dressed hym vnder a shette wyndowe</L>
<L>That was vpon &thorn;e Carpenter[e]s walle</L>
<L N="3360">He singe&thorn; in his vois gentile and smalle</L>
<L>Now dere lady &yogh;if &thorn;i wil be</L>
<L>I prei &yogh;ou &thorn;at &yogh;e wil rewe on me
<PB REF="00000127.tif" N="97"></L>
<L>Ful wel according to his giternynge</L>
<L N="3364">This Carpentere a-woke and herd hym singe</L>
<L>And spake vnto his wif and seide anon</L>
<L>What alison herest &thorn;ou not Absolon</L>
<L>&THORN;at chaunte&thorn; &thorn;us vndere our boures wall</L>
<L N="3368">And she answerd her husbond &thorn;er wi&thorn; all</L>
<L>&YOGH;is god wote Iohn I here it euery dele</L>
<L>&thorn;is passe&thorn; for&thorn; what wil &yogh;e than but wele</L>
<L>ffro day to day &thorn;is Ioly absolon</L>
<L N="3372">So wowe&thorn; hire &thorn;at hym was woo-bygon</L>
<L>He wake&thorn; al &thorn;e ny&yogh;t and al &thorn;e day</L>
<L>He kembe&thorn; his lockes brode and made hem gay</L>
<L>He wowe&thorn; hir by menes and brocage<MILESTONE N="47b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3376">And swoor he wolde bene her wne page</L>
<L>He Synge&thorn; brokking as a nyghtyngale</L>
<L>He sent her pyment Methe and spised ale</L>
<L>And wafres pyping hote out of &thorn;e glede</L>
<L N="3380">And to hir often he profered mede</L>
<L>ffor some wil be wonnen for ricches</L>
<L>And some for strokes and some for gentilnesse</L>
<L>Somtyme to shewe his lightnesse and maisstrie</L>
<L N="3384">He pleieth herawdes vpon a scaffold hie</L>
<L>But what availle&thorn; him as in &thorn;is caas</L>
<L>So loueth she &thorn;is hende Nicholaas</L>
<L>That Absolon may blawe &thorn;e buke horn</L>
<L N="3388">He ne had for his labour but a scorn</L>
<L>And &thorn;us she make&thorn; absolon her Ape</L>
<L>Al his eernest turne&thorn; but to a Iape</L>
<L>ffor so&thorn;e &thorn;is prouerbe it is no lye</L>
<L N="3392">Men seien &thorn;us alway &thorn;e ny&yogh;te sclie</L>
<L>Make&thorn; &thorn;e feer loue to be loth</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;at absolon be wode or wroth</L>
<L>By cause &thorn;at he fer was from her si&yogh;t</L>
<L N="3396">This Ni&yogh;te Nicholas stode in his li&yogh;t</L>
<L>Nowe bere &yogh;ou wel thou hende Nicholas/</L>
<L>ffor absolon may waille and singe allas
<PB REF="00000128.tif" N="98"></L>
<L>And so by-felle it on a Saterday</L>
<L N="3400">This Carpentere was gone to Osnay</L>
<L>And hende Nicholas and Alison</L>
<L>Accorded were to &thorn;is conclusion</L>
<L>&THORN;at Nicholas shal shapen hym a wile</L>
<L N="3404">This sely Ielous husbonde to begile</L>
<L>And if so be &thorn;e game went a ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>She shulde sclepe in his arme al &thorn;at ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>For &thorn;is [was] his desire and hers also</L>
<L N="3408">And ri&yogh;t anon wi&thorn;-oute wordes moo/</L>
<L>This Nicholas no lenger wold tarie</L>
<L>But do&thorn; ful softe into his chamber carie</L>
<L>Both mete and drinke for a daye or tweye<MILESTONE N="48a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3412">And to hir husbonde bad hir for to seie</L>
<L>If &thorn;at he asked after Nicholas</L>
<L>She shulde seie she nyst not wher he was</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;at day she see hym not wi&thorn; ye</L>
<L N="3416">She trowed &thorn;at he was in maladye</L>
<L>ffor no crie her maide can calle</L>
<L>He nolde answere for nou&yogh;t that may bifalle</L>
<L>This passe&thorn; for&thorn; al &thorn;e Saterday</L>
<L N="3420">That Nicholas stille in his bed lay</L>
<L>And ete and slepte and [dede] what hym lest</L>
<L>Til sonday &thorn;at &thorn;e sonne go&thorn; to rest</L>
<L>This sely Carpenter ha&thorn; grete mervaile</L>
<L N="3424">Of Nicholas or what &thorn;ing my&yogh;t hym aile</L>
<L>And saide I am a-drad by seynt Thomas</L>
<L>It stondeth not a-ri&yogh;t wi&thorn; Nicholas</L>
<L>God shilde &thorn;at he deyed sodenily</L>
<L N="3428">This world is nowe ful tikil sikerly</L>
<L>I seghe to-day a coors born to chirche</L>
<L>That now on monday I segh fast wirche</L>
<L>Go vp quod he to his knaue anon</L>
<L N="3432">Clepe at his door or knokke wi&thorn; a ston</L>
<L>Loke howe it is and telle me boldely</L>
<L>&thorn;is knaue went him vp ful sturdely
<PB REF="00000129.tif" N="99"></L>
<L>And at the Chamber door while &thorn;at he stode</L>
<L N="3436">He cried an knokked as he were wode</L>
<L>What howe what do &yogh;e maister Nicholay</L>
<L>Howe may &yogh;e sclopen al &thorn;is longe day</L>
<L>But al for nou&yogh;t he herd neuer a word</L>
<L N="3440">An hoole he foonde ful lowe vnder a bord</L>
<L>Ther as &thorn;e Catt was wonte forto crepe</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e hole he loked in ful depe</L>
<L>And atte last he had of him a si&yogh;t</L>
<L N="3444">&thorn;is Nicholas satte euere gaping vp ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>As he had kiked on &thorn;e newe moone</L>
<L>And doune he go&thorn; and told his maister sone</L>
