<L>ffor he was heled of his malady</L>
<L>fful oft paramours he gan defie</L>
<L>And wepe&thorn; as do&thorn; a child &thorn;at is ybete</L>
<L N="3760">A softe paas he went ouer &thorn;e strete
<PB REF="00000138.tif" N="108"></L>
<L>Vnto a smyth men clepen dann Gervase</L>
<L>That in his forge smyte&thorn; plowh harnase</L>
<L>He sharpeth share and culter bisily</L>
<L N="3764">This absolon knokke&thorn; al Esily</L>
<L>And seide vnto Gervays and &thorn;at anon</L>
<L>What who art &thorn;ou it am I absolon</L>
<L>What Absolon. what cristes swete tre</L>
<L N="3768">Why rise &yogh;e so rathe .o benedicite</L>
<L>What eile&thorn; &yogh;ou som gay gerle god it wote</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; brou&yogh;t &yogh;ou &thorn;us [up]on &thorn;e Vyritote</L>
<L>By seynt Noet &yogh;e whote wele what I mene</L>
<L N="3772">&THORN;is Absolon ne rou&yogh;te not a bene ./</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;is pley no word a&yogh;ein he gaf<MILESTONE N="53a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>He had more towe on his dystaf</L>
<L>&THORN;an Gervais knewe and seide frende so dere</L>
<L N="3776">&THORN;e hote Cultere in &thorn;e Chymeney here</L>
<L>As lene it me I haue &thorn;erwi&thorn; to don</L>
<L>I wil bringe it a-geyn ful sone</L>
<L>Gervais answerd certes were it gold</L>
<L N="3780">Or in a poke nobles al vntold</L>
<L>Thou shuldest haue as I am trewe smyth</L>
<L>A cristes foo what wil &yogh;e do &thorn;erwith</L>
<L>Therof quod absolon be as be may</L>
<L N="3784">I shal tellen it &thorn;e to morowe day</L>
<L>And caught &thorn;e Culter by &thorn;e colde stele</L>
<L>fful soft out atte door he gan stele</L>
<L>And went vnto &thorn;e Carpentere walle</L>
<L N="3788">He koughed first and knokked &thorn;er wi&thorn; all</L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;e wyndowe right as he did eere</L>
<L>&THORN;is Alison answerde who is &thorn;ere</L>
<L>&THORN;at knokke&thorn; so I waraunt it a &thorn;eef</L>
<L N="3792">We nay quod he god wote my swete leef</L>
<L>I am &thorn;ine absolon &thorn;ine derlinge</L>
<L>Of gold quod he I haue &thorn;e brou&yogh;t a rynge</L>
<L>My modere &yogh;aue it me so god me saue</L>
<L N="3796">fful fyn it is and &thorn;erto wel ygraue
<PB REF="00000139.tif" N="109"></L>
<L>This wil I &yogh;euen &thorn;e if &thorn;owe me kisse</L>
<L>&thorn;is Nicholas was risen forto pisse</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou&yogh;t he wold amenden al &thorn;e Iape</L>
<L N="3800">He shulde kisse his ers er &thorn;at he scape</L>
<L>And vp &thorn;e wyndowe did he hastely</L>
<L>And out his ers he putte&thorn; priuely</L>
<L>Ouer &thorn;e buttok to &thorn;e haunche bon</L>
<L N="3804">And &thorn;erwi&thorn; spake &thorn;is clerk &thorn;is absolone</L>
<L>Speke swete bridde I not wher &thorn;ou art</L>
<L>&THORN;is Nicholas anon lete fleigh a fart</L>
<L>As grete as it had bene a &thorn;onder dent</L>
<L N="3808">&THORN;at wi&thorn; &thorn;e stroke he was almost yblent</L>
<L>And he was redy wi&thorn; his yren hote<MILESTONE N="53b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And Nicholas in &thorn;e ers he smote</L>
<L>Of go&thorn; &thorn;e skyn an honde brede aboute</L>
<L N="3812">&THORN;e hote culter brenned so his toute</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e smerte he wende forto deye</L>
<L>As he were wood for woo he gan to crye</L>
<L>Help water water helpe for goddys hert</L>
<L N="3816">This Carpenter out of his slomber stert</L>
<L>And herde oon crien water as he were wode</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou&yogh;t allas now commeth noes flode</L>
<L>He sette hym vp wi&thorn;out[e] wordes moo</L>
<L N="3820">And wi&thorn; an axe he smote &thorn;e cord a two</L>
<L>And doun go&thorn; alle he fonde nei&thorn;er to selle</L>
<L>Brede nor Ale til he com to &thorn;e selle</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;e floor and ther a swoun he lay</L>
<L N="3824">Vp stert hir Alison and Nicholay</L>
<L>And criden out and horowe in &thorn;e strete</L>
<L>&THORN;e neighbours bo&thorn; smale and grete</L>
<L>Ronnen forto gawren on &thorn;is man</L>
<L N="3828">&THORN;at a swonn lay bo&thorn; pale and wan</L>
<L>ffor wi&thorn; &thorn;at falle he brusten ha&thorn; his arme</L>
<L>But stonden he most vnto his owne harme</L>
<L>ffor whan he spak he was anon born doun</L>
<L N="3832">Wi&thorn; hende Nicholas and alisoun
<PB REF="00000140.tif" N="110"></L>
<L>Thei tolde euery man &thorn;at he was wode</L>
<L>He was agast so of &thorn;e Noes flode</L>
<L>&THORN;orgh fantasie &thorn;at of his vanyte</L>
<L N="3836">He had ybou&yogh;t hym kneding tubbes &thorn;re</L>
<L>And had hem honged in &thorn;e roof aboue</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he preied hym for goddys loue</L>
<L>To sitten in &thorn;e roof par companye</L>
<L N="3840">&thorn;e folk gan laughen at his fantasie</L>
<L>And to the Roof &thorn;ei kepen and &thorn;ei gape</L>
<L>And turned al his harme vnto a Iape</L>
<L>ffor what so &thorn;is Carpenter answerd</L>
<L N="3844">It was for nou&yogh;t no man his reson herd</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; o&thorn;es grete he was so sworn a doun<MILESTONE N="54a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That he was holden woode in al &thorn;at toun</L>
<L>ffor euere clerk anoon ri&yogh;t helde wi&thorn; o&thorn;er</L>
<L N="3848">&thorn;ei seide &thorn;e man is wood my leue bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>And euere wight gan laughen at his strif</L>
<L>Thus swyued was &thorn;e Carpenter[e]s wiff</L>
<L>ffor al his keping and his Ielousie</L>
<L N="3852">And Absalon ha&thorn; kissed her nethere ye</L>
<L>And Nicholas is scalded in his toute</L>
<L>This tale is don and god saue al &thorn;e route.</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER><B>&para; Here ende&thorn; &thorn;e mylers tale.</B><NOTE PLACE="end">[<I>No break in the MS.</I>]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000141.tif" N="111">
<HEAD>&para; And &thorn;us bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e Prologe of &thorn;e Reues tale<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Cap. 3<SUP>m.</SUP></NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan folk han laughen at &thorn;is nyce cas</L>
<L N="3856">Of absolon and hende Nicholas</L>
<L>Dyuers folk dyuersly &thorn;ei seide</L>
<L>But for &thorn;e more parte &thorn;ei lou&yogh;e and pleide</L>
<L>Ne at &thorn;is tale I seghe no man hym greue</L>
<L N="3860">But it were only Oswold &thorn;e Reue</L>
<L>Bycause he was of Carpenter[e]s craft</L>
<L>A litel Ire in his herte laft</L>
<L>He gan to grucche and blamed it a lite</L>
<L N="3864">So thick quod he ful wele quou&thorn; I &thorn;e quyte</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; blering of a proude Millers ye</L>
<L>If &thorn;at me list to speke of Ribawdye</L>
<L>But ik am olde me list not pley for age</L>
<L N="3868">Gras tyme is done my foder is forage</L>
<L>This white top write&thorn; myn olde &yogh;eeres</L>
<L>Myn hert is al so mowled as myn heeres</L>
<L>But if I fare as do&thorn; an open-ers</L>
<L N="3872">&thorn;at ilke fruyte is euer lenger &thorn;e wers</L>
<L>Til it be roten in Mullok or in stre</L>
<L>We olde men I drede so fare we</L>
<L>Til we be roten can we not be ripe</L>
<L N="3876">We hopen alway while &thorn;e hert wil pipe</L>
<L>ffor in our wille &thorn;er stikketh euer a naile</L>
<L>To haue an hoor heer and a grene taile</L>
<L>As ha&thorn; a leke for &thorn;ough our my&yogh;t be gon<MILESTONE N="54b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3880">Our wille desire&thorn; foly euer in oon</L>
<L>ffor whan we may not don &thorn;an wil we speke</L>
<L>&YOGH;it in oure asshed olde is fire yreke</L>
<L>ffour gledes han we which I shal deuyse</L>
<L N="3884">Auauntinge lying. angre. and coueitise</L>
<L>Thise four sparkles longe&thorn; vnto elde</L>
<L>Our olde lymes may wel bene vnwelde
<PB REF="00000142.tif" N="112"></L>
<L>But wil ne shal not faille &thorn;at is soth</L>
<L N="3888">And &yogh;it haue I alwaye a coltes toth</L>
<L>As mony &yogh;ere as it is passed henne</L>
<L>Si&thorn; &thorn;at my tap of lif byganne to renne</L>
<L>ffor sikerly whan I was born an&omacr;n</L>
<L N="3892">De&thorn; drough &thorn;e tappe of lif and lete it gon</L>
<L>And euere si&thorn;en ha&thorn; so &thorn;e tap yronne</L>
<L>Til at almost al empty is &thorn;e tonne</L>
<L>The strem of lif now droppe&thorn; on &thorn;e chymbe</L>
<L N="3896">&thorn;e sely tunge may wel rynge and chymbe</L>
<L>Of wrecchednesse &thorn;at passed is ful yore</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; olde folk saue dotage is no more</L>
<L>&para; Whan &thorn;at our ooste had herde &thorn;is sermonynge</L>
<L N="3900">He gan to speke as lordly as a kinge</L>
<L>He seide what amounte&thorn; al &thorn;is witte</L>
<L>What shal we speke alday of holy writte</L>
<L>The deuel made a Reue forto preche</L>
<L N="3904">Or of a Souter shipman or a lecche</L>
<L>Say for&thorn; &thorn;i take and tary not &thorn;e tyme</L>
<L>Loo Depford and it is almost prime</L>
<L>Lo Grenwich &thorn;at mony a shrewe is Inne</L>
<L N="3908">It were hie tyme &thorn;i tale forto bygynne</L>
<L>&para; Now Sirs quod &thorn;is Oswold &thorn;e Reue</L>
<L>I prei &yogh;ou al &thorn;at &yogh;e &yogh;ou not greue</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh;e I answere and somdele sette hys houwe</L>
<L N="3912">ffor leeful it is wi&thorn; force. force of shouwe</L>
<L>This dronken Miller ha&thorn; ytolde vs here</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;at bigiled was a Carpentere</L>
<L>Perauenture in scorn for I am oon<MILESTONE N="55a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3916">And by &yogh;oure leue I shal hym quyte anon</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t in his Cheerles teermes wil I speke</L>
<L>I prei to god his nekke mot alto-breke</L>
<L>He can wel in myn ye seen a stalk</L>
<L N="3920">But in his owne he can not seen a balk</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; Thus ende&thorn; &thorn;e Prologe of &thorn;e Reue</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000143.tif" N="113">
<HEAD>And here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e Reeues tale</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At Trumpington not fer fro Caunterbruge</L>
<L>Ther go&thorn; a broke and over &thorn;at a bruge</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;e whiche broke &thorn;er stonte a melle</L>
<L N="3924">And &thorn;is is verrey so&thorn; &thorn;at I &yogh;ou telle</L>
<L>A Millere was &thorn;ere dwelling mony a day</L>
<L>As ony Pecok he was proude and gay</L>
<L>Pipen he cou&thorn;e an sisshen and nettes bete</L>
<L N="3928">And turne Coppes and wel wrastel and shete</L>
<L>Ny by his belt he bare a longe panade</L>
<L>And of a swerd ful trenchant was &thorn;e blade</L>
<L>A Ioly popper bere he in his pouche</L>
<L N="3932">Ther nas no man for perile durst hym touche</L>
<L>A Sheffeld thwytel bere he in his hose</L>
<L>Rounde was his face and camoyse was his nose</L>
<L>As pilled as an ape was his sculle</L>
<L N="3936">He was a market beter atte fulle</L>
<L>&thorn;er nas no wight &thorn;at durst hond on hym legge</L>
<L>But if he swore he shuld anon abegge</L>
<L>A theef he was forso&thorn; of corn and mele</L>
<L N="3940">And &thorn;at a sleegh and vsaunt forto stele</L>
<L>His name was hoten deyne&yogh;ouse Symkyn</L>
<L>A wif he hadde commen of nobel kyn</L>
<L>The person of &thorn;e toune her fader was</L>
<L N="3944">Wi&thorn; hir he &yogh;aue ful mony a panne of bras</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at Symkyn shuld in his blood allie</L>
<L>She was yfostred in a nonrie</L>
<L>ffor Symkyn wold[e] no wif as he seide</L>
<L N="3948">But she were wel ynorshed and a mayde</L>
<L>To Sauen his Astate of &yogh;emanrie<MILESTONE N="55b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And she was proude and peert as is a pie</L>
<L>A ful feire sight was it vpon hem twoo/</L>
<L N="3952">On holy daies byforn hir wold he goo/
<PB REF="00000144.tif" N="114"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his typet bounden aboute his hede</L>
<L>And she come aftere in a gite of rede</L>
<L>And Symkyn had[de] hosen of &thorn;e same</L>
<L N="3956">&thorn;er durst no wi&yogh;t clepe hur but dame</L>
<L>Was noon so hardy &thorn;at went by &thorn;e way</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; hir dorst ones rage or play</L>
<L>Bat if he wold be sclayn of Symkyn</L>
<L N="3960">Wi&thorn; panade and wi&thorn; knyf or boydekyn</L>
<L>ffor Ielous folk ben perylous euermoo</L>
<L>Algates &thorn;ei wolde her wyues wenden soo</L>
<L>And eke for she was somdell smoterlich</L>
<L N="3964">She was as digne as water in a dich</L>
<L>As ful of hoker and of bismare</L>
<L>Hire &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at a lady shuld hir spare</L>
<L>What for her kynrede and her nortelrie</L>
<L N="3968">&THORN;at she had lerned in &thorn;e Nonerie</L>
<L>A dou&yogh;tere had[de] &thorn;ei bitwene hem twoo</L>
<L>Of xx<SUP>ti</SUP> &yogh;ere wi&thorn;-outen ony moo/</L>
<L>Sauyng a childe &thorn;at was of half &yogh;ere age</L>
<L N="3972">In cradel it lay and was a propre page</L>
<L>This wenche thik and wel ygrowe was</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Camoys nose and eyen as grey as glas</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; buttokes brode and brestes round and hie</L>
<L N="3976">But ri&yogh;t faire was hur heor I wil not lye</L>
<L>&para; The person of &thorn;e toune for she was so faire</L>
<L>In purpoos was to make hir his aire</L>
<L>Bo&thorn; of his Catell and of his messuage</L>
<L N="3980">And straunge he made it of hur mariage</L>
<L>His purpoos was to bystowe hir hie</L>
<L>Into som wor&thorn;i blood of Auncetrie</L>
<L>ffor holy churches good most be despended/</L>
<L N="3984">On holy chirche blood &thorn;at is descended/</L>
<L>Therfore he wold his holy blood honoure<MILESTONE N="56a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;oo &thorn;at he holy churche shuld devoure</L>
<L>Grete soken ha&thorn; &thorn;is mellere out of doute</L>
<L N="3988">With whete and malt of al &thorn;e londe aboute
<PB REF="00000145.tif" N="115"></L>
<L>And namely &thorn;er was a grete colege</L>
<L>Men clepen &thorn;e solere halle atte Cauntebrigge</L>
<L>Ther was her whete and eke her malt ygrounde</L>
<L N="3992">And on a day it happed in a stounde</L>
<L>Sik lay &thorn;e manciple on a maladie</L>
<L>Mon wenden wishly &thorn;at he shuld[e] dye</L>
<L>ffor whiche &thorn;e Millere stale bo&thorn; mele and corn</L>
<L N="3996">An hundred tyme more &thorn;an byforn</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;er byforne he stale but curteisly</L>
<L>But nowe he was a &thorn;eef outrageously</L>
<L>ffor which &thorn;e wardeyne chidde and made fare</L>
<L N="4000">But &thorn;erof sette &thorn;e Millere not a tare</L>
<L>He craked booste and swore it was not soo/</L>
<L>&thorn;an were &thorn;ere yonge scolers two</L>
<L>That dwelten in &thorn;e halle of which I seie</L>
<L N="4004">Teestif &thorn;ei were and lusty forto pleye</L>
<L>And only for her merth and reverye</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;e wardeyn bisily &thorn;ei crie</L>
<L>To &yogh;eue hem leue but a litel stounde</L>
<L N="4008">To goo to melle and se her corn y-grounde</L>
<L>And hardely &thorn;ei dorst lay her nekke</L>
<L>&thorn;e Millere shuld not stele hem half a pekke</L>
<L>Of corn ne by sleight ne by force hem reue</L>
<L N="4012">And at &thorn;e last &thorn;e wardeyn &yogh;af hem leue</L>
<L>Iohn hight &thorn;at oon an Aleyn hi&yogh;t &thorn;at o&thorn;er</L>
<L>Of oon toune were &thorn;ei born &thorn;at hight[e] strother</L>
<L>fferre in &thorn;e nor&thorn;e I can not telle where</L>
<L N="4016">This Aleyn make&thorn; redy al his gere</L>
<L>And on an hors &thorn;e sak he cast an&omacr;n</L>
<L>ffor&thorn; go&thorn; Aleyn &thorn;e Clerc and also Iohn</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; good swerde and bokeler by her side</L>
<L N="4020">Iohn knewe &thorn;e way hym neded no gyde</L>
<L>And atte Mille &thorn;e Sak a doune he laith<MILESTONE N="56b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Alayn spake first alhaille Symonde in fai&thorn;</L>
<L>How fare&thorn; &thorn;i fare dou&yogh;tere and &thorn;i wiff</L>
<L N="4024">Aleyn welcome quod Symkyn be my liff
<PB REF="00000146.tif" N="116"></L>
<L>And Iohn also how nowe what do &yogh;e here</L>
<L>By god quod Iohn Symond nede ha&thorn; no pere</L>
<L>Hym byhoue&thorn; serue hym self &thorn;at ha&thorn; no swayn</L>
<L N="4028">Or ellis he is a fool as clerkes sayne</L>
<L>Our manciple I hope he wil be dede</L>
<L>Swa worchen hym ay &thorn;e wanges in his hede</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore is I commen and eke Aleyn</L>
<L N="4032">To Grynde our corn and carie hit hom ageyn</L>
<L>We prey &yogh;ou spede vs hepen &thorn;at &yogh;e may</L>
<L>It shal be done quod Symkyn be my fay</L>
<L>What wil &yogh;e done while &thorn;at it is in hande</L>
<L N="4036">By God ri&yogh;t by the hoper wil I stande</L>
<L>Quod Iohn and see how gates &thorn;e corn go&thorn; Inne</L>
<L>&YOGH;it sagh I neuere be my fadere kynne</L>
<L>How &thorn;at &thorn;e hoper wagge&thorn; til and fraye</L>
<L N="4040">Aleyn Answerd Iohan wiltowe swaye</L>
<L>&thorn;an wil I be byne&thorn;e by my croune</L>
<L>And se howe gate the mele falles adoun</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e trough &thorn;at shal be my disport</L>
<L N="4044">Quod Iohn in faath I may bene of &yogh;our sorte</L>
<L>I is as il a Miller as is &yogh;e</L>
<L>This Millere smyled of her nycete</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou&yogh;t al &thorn;is is don but for a wile</L>
<L N="4048">&thorn;ei wene &thorn;at no man may hem bygyle</L>
<L>But by my &thorn;rift &yogh;it shal I blere her ye</L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;e slei&yogh;t in her philosophie</L>
<L>The more queynte Clerkes &thorn;at &thorn;ei make</L>
<L N="4052">&thorn;e more wil I stele whan I take</L>
<L>In stede of floure &yogh;it wil I &yogh;eue hem brenne</L>
<L>The grettest clerkes ben not &thorn;e wisest men</L>
<L>As whilom to &thorn;e wolf &thorn;us spake &thorn;e mare</L>
<L N="4056">Of alle her arte counte I nou&yogh;t a tare</L>
<L>Out at &thorn;e Dore he go&thorn; ful priuely<MILESTONE N="57a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at he seghe his tyme softely</L>
<L>He loke&thorn; vp and doune til he ha&thorn; founde</L>
<L N="4060">The Clerkes hors &thorn;er as he stode ybounde
<PB REF="00000147.tif" N="117"></L>
<L>Behinde &thorn;e mylle vndere a leueselle</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e hors he go&thorn; hym faire and welle</L>
<L>He strepe&thorn; of &thorn;e bridel ri&yogh;t an&omacr;n</L>
<L N="4064">And whan &thorn;e hors is louse he gynne&thorn; to gon</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e fenne where wilde Mares renne</L>
<L>And for&thorn;e-wi&thorn; &thorn;orgh &thorn;ikke and &thorn;orgh &thorn;enne</L>
<L>This Mellere go&thorn; ageyn no word he seide</L>
<L N="4068">But do&thorn; his note and wi&thorn; &thorn;ise clerkes pleide</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at her corn was faire and welle ygrounde</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;e mele is sakked and ybounde</L>
<L>This Iohn go&thorn; oute and fonde her hors away</L>
<L N="4072">And gan to crie harowe and walowway</L>
<L>Our hors is lost aleyn for goddis banes/</L>
<L>Steppe on &thorn;i fete come of man / al at anes</L>
<L>Allas our wardeyn ha&thorn; our palfray lorn</L>
<L N="4076">This Aleyn forgate bo&thorn; mele and corn</L>
<L>Al was out of his mynde his husbondrie</L>
<L>What whilk way is he gon he gan to crie</L>
<L>&THORN;e wif come lepinge inward at a renne</L>
<L N="4080">She seide alas &yogh;oure hors go&thorn; to &thorn;e fenne</L>
<L>With wilde mares as fast as he may goo</L>
<L>Vn&thorn;onke come on his honde &thorn;at bonde hym soo/</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at better shuld haue knette &thorn;e reyn</L>
<L N="4084">Allas quod Iohn Aleyn for cristes peyn</L>
<L>Lay doune &thorn;i swerde and I wil myn alswaa</L>
<L>I is ful swift god wate as is a Raa</L>
<L>By goddes hert he shal not scape vs bathe</L>
<L N="4088">Whi ne had &thorn;ou putte &thorn;e Capel in &thorn;e lathe</L>
<L>Ilhaile by god Aleyn &thorn;ou is a fonne</L>
<L>Thise sely clerkes han ful fast yronne</L>
<L>Touard &thorn;e fenne bo&thorn;en aleyn an eke Iohn</L>
<L N="4092">And whan &thorn;e Miller segh &thorn;at &thorn;ei were gon</L>
<L>He half a busshel of her floure ha&thorn; take<MILESTONE N="57b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And bad his wif go knede it in a cake</L>
<L>And seide I trowe &thorn;e clerkes weren a-ferde</L>
<L N="4096">&YOGH;it kan a Miller make a clerkes beerde
<PB REF="00000148.tif" N="118"></L>
<L>ffor al her arte &yogh;it lat hem gon her way</L>
<L>Lo wher &thorn;ei gon &yogh;e lat &thorn;e children play</L>
<L>They gete him not so lightly by my croun</L>
<L N="4100">Thise sely clerkes rennen vp and doun</L>
<L>With kepe. kepe. stonde. stonde. Iossa warderere</L>
<L>Ga qwistel &yogh;ou I shal kepe hym here</L>
<L>But shortely til it was verrey ny&yogh;t</L>
<L N="4104">&thorn;ei cou&thorn;e not &thorn;oughe &thorn;ei did al her my&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;eire Capel cauche he ranne alway so fast</L>
<L>Til in a dicche &thorn;ei caught him at &thorn;e last</L>
<L>Wery and wete as beestis in &thorn;e reyne</L>
<L N="4108">Comme&thorn; sely Iohn and wi&thorn; hym comme&thorn; aleyn</L>
<L>Allas quod Iohn &thorn;e day &thorn;at I was born</L>
<L>Nowe are we dryuen til he&thorn;ing and to scorn</L>
<L>Our corn is stolle men wil vs foles calle</L>
<L N="4112">Bo&thorn; &thorn;e wardeyn and our felawes alle</L>
<L>And namely &thorn;e Meller weylawaye</L>
<L>&thorn;us pleyne&thorn; Iohn as he go&thorn; by &thorn;e waye</L>
<L>Toward the Melle and baiard in his honde</L>
<L N="4116">The Millere sitting by &thorn;e fire he fonde</L>
<L>ffor it was nyght and fer&thorn;er myght he nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>But for &thorn;e loue of god &thorn;ei hym bisou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Of harborowe and of ease as for her penye</L>
<L N="4120">&thorn;e Millere seide a&yogh;ein if &thorn;er be enye</L>
<L>Such as it is &yogh;ete shal &yogh;e haue &yogh;oure parte</L>
<L>Myn hous is streite but &yogh;e han lerned arte</L>
<L>&YOGH;e can by argumente make a place</L>
<L N="4124">A myle brode of xx<SUP>ti</SUP> fete of space</L>
<L>Lat se nowe if &thorn;is place may suffise</L>
<L>Or make it rowmer wi&thorn; speche as is &yogh;our gise</L>
<L>Now Symond seide &thorn;is Iohn be seynt Cutberd</L>
<L N="4128">Ay is &thorn;ou mery . and &thorn;at is faire answerde</L>
<L>I haue herde seye men shal taken of two &thorn;ingges<MILESTONE N="58a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Such as he fint or take such as he bringes</L>
<L>But specialy I prey &thorn;ee hooste dere</L>
<L N="4132">Gete vs some mete and drink and make vs chere
<PB REF="00000149.tif" N="119"></L>
<L>And we wil paien trewly atte fulle</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; empty hondes men may not haukes tulle</L>
<L>Lo here our siluer redy forto spende</L>
<L N="4136">This Mellere to &thorn;e toune his dou&yogh;ter sende</L>
<L>ffor Ale and brede and rosted hem a goos</L>
<L>And bonde her hors for he shuld no more go loos</L>
<L>And in his owne chambre he made a bedde</L>
<L N="4140">Wi&thorn; shetes and wi&thorn; chalons faire yspredde</L>
<L>Nou&yogh;t from his owne bedde .x. fete or xij.</L>
<L>His doughter had a bed al by hir selue</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t in &thorn;e same chambre by and by</L>
<L N="4144">It myghte be no bette and cause why</L>
<L>&thorn;er was no rommer herborowe in &thorn;e place</L>
<L>&thorn;ei soupen and &thorn;ei speken hem to solace</L>
<L>And drynken euere stronge ale atte beste</L>
<L N="4148">About mydny&yogh;t went &thorn;ei to reste</L>
<L>Wel ha&thorn; &thorn;is Mellere vernyssed his hede</L>
<L>fful pale he was for-dronken and not rede</L>
<L>He &yogh;eske&thorn; and he speke&thorn; &thorn;orgh &thorn;e nose</L>
<L N="4152">As he ware in &thorn;e quakke or on &thorn;e pose</L>
<L>To bedde he goo&thorn; and wi&thorn; hym go&thorn; his wif</L>
<L>As eny Iaye he light was and Iolif</L>
<L>So was her Ioly whistel wel ywette</L>
<L N="4156">&THORN;e Cradel at her beddis fete is ysette</L>
<L>To Rokken and to &yogh;eue &thorn;e child to souke</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at dronken was al in &thorn;e crouke</L>
<L>To bedde went &thorn;e doughter ri&yogh;t an&omacr;n</L>
<L N="4160">To bedde go&thorn; Aleyn and also Iohn</L>
<L>&thorn;er nas no more hem neded no dwale</L>
<L>This Mellere ha&thorn; so wisly bebbed ale</L>
<L>&thorn;at as an hors he snorte&thorn; in his slepe</L>
<L N="4164">Ne of his tale behynde he toke no kepe</L>
<L>His wif bare him a Burdon a ful stronge<MILESTONE N="58b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Men myght here &thorn;e routing &thorn;ens a forlonge</L>
<L>The wenche route&thorn; eek par companye</L>
<L N="4168">Aleyn &thorn;e Clerk &thorn;at herd &thorn;is melodye
<PB REF="00000150.tif" N="120"></L>
<L>He pouked on Iohn and seide slepestowe</L>
<L>Herde &thorn;ou euere sclike a sang or nowe</L>
<L>Lo sclike a conplinge is ytwix hem alle</L>
<L N="4172">A wilde fire on her bodies falle</L>
<L>Who herkened euere sclike a ferly &thorn;inge</L>
<L>&YOGH;e &thorn;ei shal haue &thorn;e floure of euel endinge</L>
<L>This lange ny&yogh;t &thorn;er tydes men no reste</L>
<L N="4176">But &yogh;it na fors al shal be for &thorn;e beste</L>
<L>ffor Iohn seide he as euere mote I &thorn;rive</L>
<L>If &thorn;at I may &yogh;on wenche &thorn;an wil I swyve</L>
<L>Some esement ha&thorn; lawe shapen vs</L>
<L N="4180">ffor Iohn &thorn;er is a lawe &thorn;at sei&thorn; &thorn;us</L>
<L>That if a man in oon point be agreued</L>
<L>That in ano&thorn;er he shal be releued</L>
<L>Our corn is stollen so&thorn;ly it is no nay</L>
<L N="4184">And we han had an euel fit to day</L>
<L>And syn I shal haue no amendement</L>
<L>Ageyn my losse I wil haue esement</L>
<L>By goddes saule it sal na no&thorn;er be</L>
<L N="4188">&thorn;is Iohn answerde Aleyn avise &thorn;e</L>
<L>The Mellere is a perilous man he seide</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at he out of his sclepe abreide</L>
<L>He myghte don vs bo&thorn; a vylenye</L>
<L N="4192">Aleyn answerd I counte hym not a flye</L>
<L>And vp he rist and by &thorn;e wenche he crepte</L>
<L>This wenche lay vpri&yogh;t and faste sclepte</L>
<L>Til he so nygh was er she my&yogh;te spie</L>
<L N="4196">&thorn;at it had bene to late forto crie</L>
<L>And shortely for to seie &thorn;ei were at on</L>
<L>Nowe pleye Alayn for I wil speke of Iohn</L>
<L>This Iohn lith stille a forlonge way or two</L>
<L N="4200">And to hym self he make&thorn; wamenting and woo</L>
<L>Allas quod he &thorn;is is a wikke Iape<MILESTONE N="59a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Now may I seie &thorn;at I is but an ape</L>
<L>&YOGH;it ha&thorn; my felawe somwhat for his harme</L>
<L N="4204">He ha&thorn; &thorn;e mellers dou&yogh;ter in his arme
<PB REF="00000151.tif" N="121"></L>
<L>He Auntre&thorn; hym and ha&thorn; his nedes spedde</L>
<L>And I ly as a draf sak in my bedde</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is Iape is tolde ano&thorn;er day</L>
<L N="4208">I shal be holde a daff a cokenay</L>
<L>I wil arise and aunter be my fath</L>
<L>Vnhardy is vnsely &thorn;us men sath</L>
<L>And vp he roos and softely he went</L>
<L N="4212">Vnto &thorn;e Cradel and in his arme hit hent</L>
<L>And bare it soft vntil his beddes fete</L>
<L>Sone aftere &thorn;e wif her rowting lete</L>
<L>And gan to wake and went her out to pisse</L>
<L N="4216">And come agein and gan her cradel mysse</L>
<L>And groped here and &thorn;ere but she foond noon/</L>
<L>Allas quod she I had almost mysgon</L>
<L>I had almost go to &thorn;e clerkes bedde</L>
<L N="4220">Ey benedicite &thorn;an had I foule yspedde</L>
<L>And for&thorn; she go&thorn; til she &thorn;e cradel fonde</L>
<L>She grope&thorn; alway for&thorn;er wi&thorn; her honde</L>
<L>And fond &thorn;e bed and &thorn;ou&yogh;t nou&yogh;t but of good</L>
<L N="4224">By cause &thorn;at &thorn;e cradel by it stode</L>
<L>And nyste wher she was for it was derk</L>
<L>But faire and wel she crepte in to &thorn;e clerk</L>
<L>And lith ful stille and wolde haue kau&yogh;t a slepe</L>
<L N="4228">Wi&thorn;-In a while &thorn;is Iohn &thorn;e clerk vp lepe</L>
<L>And on &thorn;is good[e] wif hee lei&thorn; ful sore</L>
<L>So mery a fitte ne had she not ful &yogh;ore</L>
<L>And prike&thorn; harde and depe as he ware<NOTE PLACE="marg">[? MS]</NOTE> madde</L>
<L N="4232">&THORN;is Ioly lif han &thorn;ise two clerkes ladde</L>
<L>To &thorn;at &thorn;e iij. coke bygan to singe</L>
<L>Aleyn wexe wery. in &thorn;e daw[e]nynge</L>
<L>ffor he had swonken al &thorn;e longe ny&yogh;t</L>
<L N="4236">And seide fare wel malyn sweete wi&yogh;t</L>
<L>The day is come I may no lenger byde<MILESTONE N="59b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But euermo where so I go or ride</L>
<L>I am &thorn;ine owne clerk so haue I sele</L>
<L N="4240">Now dere lemman quod she go fare wele
<PB REF="00000152.tif" N="122"></L>
<L>But er &thorn;ou goo. on &thorn;inge I wil &thorn;e telle</L>
<L>Whhan &thorn;at &thorn;ow wendest homward by &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> melle</L>
<L>Right at &thorn;e entre of &thorn;e door be-hinde</L>
<L N="4244">Thow shalt a Cake of half a busshel fynde</L>
<L>That was ymaked of &thorn;ine owne mele</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at I helpe my Sire forto stele</L>
<L>And good lemman god &thorn;e saue and kepe</L>
<L N="4248">And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word almost she gan to wepe</L>
<L>Aleyn vprist and &thorn;ou&yogh;t er &thorn;at it dawe</L>
<L>I wol go crepen in by my felawe</L>
<L>And fonde &thorn;e cradel wi&thorn; his honde anon</L>
<L N="4252">By god &thorn;ought he alwrong / I haue mysgon</L>
<L>Myn hede is toty of my swynk to nyght</L>
<L>&THORN;at make&thorn; me &thorn;at I go not aright</L>
<L>I wote wele by &thorn;e cradel I haue mysgo</L>
<L N="4256">Here lith &thorn;e meller and his wif also</L>
<L>And for&thorn; he go&thorn; on twenty delway</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e bedde &thorn;er as &thorn;e meller lay</L>
<L>He wende haue cropen by his felawe Iohn</L>
<L N="4260">And by &thorn;e Meller in he crept anon</L>
<L>And kaught him by &thorn;e nek and soft he spake</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;ou Iohn &thorn;ou swyneshede awake</L>
<L>Of Cristes saule and here a noble game</L>
<L N="4264">ffor by &thorn;at lord &thorn;at called is seint Iame</L>
<L>As I haue &thorn;ries in &thorn;is shorte ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>Swyved &thorn;e Mellers dou&yogh;ter bolt vpri&yogh;t</L>
<L>Whilst &thorn;ow hast as a Coward ben agast</L>
<L N="4268">Ye fals harlot quod &thorn;e Mellere hast</L>
<L>A fals traitour. fals clerk quod he</L>
<L>&THORN;ow shalt be dede by goddes dignyte</L>
<L>Who durste be so bolde to disparage</L>
<L N="4272">My dou&yogh;ter &thorn;at is come of swich lynage</L>
<L>And by &thorn;e &thorn;rote bolle he kau&yogh;t aleyn<MILESTONE N="60a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And he him hent dispitously ageyn</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e nose he smote hym with his fist</L>
<L N="4276">Doune ranne &thorn;e blody streme vpon his brist
<PB REF="00000153.tif" N="123"></L>
<L>And in &thorn;e floor wi&thorn; nose and mou&thorn; to-broke</L>
<L>&thorn;ei walowen as don two pigges in a poke</L>
<L>And vp &thorn;ei goon and doune anon</L>
<L N="4280">Till &thorn;at &thorn;e Mellere spurned at a ston</L>
<L>And downe he felle bakward vpon his wiff</L>
<L>&thorn;at wist no &thorn;inge of &thorn;is nyce striff</L>
<L>ffor she was falle a slepe a litel wi&yogh;t</L>
<L N="4284">Wi&thorn; Iohn &thorn;e clerk &thorn;at waked had al ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;e falle out of her slepe she braide</L>
<L>Help holy crosse of bromholm she saide</L>
<L>In manus tuas lorde to &thorn;e I calle</L>
<L N="4288">Awake Symond &thorn;e feend is on me falle</L>
<L>Myn hert is broken help I ne am but dede</L>
<L>&thorn;ere lith vpon my wombe and on myn hede</L>
<L>Helpe Symkyn for &thorn;ise fals clerkes fi&yogh;t</L>
<L N="4292">This Iohn stert vp as fast as euere he my&yogh;t</L>
<L>And grasped by &thorn;e walles to and fro</L>
<L>To fynden a staf and she stert vp also</L>
<L>And knewe &thorn;e Eisters bet &thorn;an did Iohn</L>
<L N="4296">And by &thorn;e walle she fonde a staf an&omacr;n</L>
<L>And segh a litel shymering of a li&yogh;t</L>
<L>ffor at an hole in shone &thorn;e mone bri&yogh;t</L>
<L>And by &thorn;at li&yogh;t she segh hem bo&thorn;[e] two</L>
<L N="4300">But sikerly she nyste who was who</L>
<L>But as she seegh a white &thorn;inge in her eye</L>
<L>And whan she gan &thorn;is white &thorn;ing aspie</L>
<L>She wende &thorn;e Clerk had wered a volipere</L>
<L N="4304">And wi&thorn; &thorn;e staf she drough ay ner and nere</L>
<L>And wende han hitte &thorn;is Aleyn atte fulle</L>
<L>And smote &thorn;e Mylere on &thorn;e pyled skulle</L>
<L>&THORN;at doun he goth and cried harowe I dye</L>
<L N="4308">Thise Clerkes bette hym wel and lete hym lye</L>
<L>And Greie&thorn; hem and toke her hors anon<MILESTONE N="60b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And eke her/ mele and on her way &thorn;ei g&omacr;n</L>
<L>And at the Melle &yogh;it &thorn;ei toke her Cake</L>
<L N="4312">Of half a busshel floure ful wel ybake
<PB REF="00000154.tif" N="124"></L>
<L>Thus is &thorn;e proude Mellere wel ybete</L>
<L>And hath ylost &thorn;e grynding of &thorn;e whete</L>
<L>And paide for &thorn;e soper euery dell</L>
<L N="4316">Of aleyn and of Iohn &thorn;at bette hym well</L>
<L>His wiff is swyued and his dou&yogh;tere als</L>
<L>Lo such it is a Miller to be fals</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfor &thorn;is prouerbe is seide ful soth</L>
<L N="4320">Hym ther not wene wele &thorn;at euel doth</L>
<L>A Gilour shal hym self begiled be</L>
<L>And god &thorn;at sitte&thorn; hegh in mageste</L>
<L>Saue al &thorn;e company grete and smale</L>
<L N="4324">Thus haue I quytte &thorn;e Meller in my tale</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER><B>&para; Thus Endeth &thorn;e Reues Tale</B><NOTE>[<I>No break in the MS.</I>]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000155.tif" N="125">
<HEAD>And here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e Cokes tale</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The Coke of london while &thorn;e Reue spak<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; The Prologe</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor Ioye him &thorn;ou&yogh;t he clawed hym on &thorn;e bak</L>
<L>Ha. ha. quod he for cristes passion</L>
<L N="4328">This Millere ha&thorn; a sharpe conclusion</L>
<L>Vpon his argument of harbigage</L>
<L>Wel seide Salomon in his langage</L>
<L>Ne bringe not euery man into &thorn;ine hous</L>
<L N="4332">ffor herbowringe by nyght is perilous</L>
<L>Wel ou&yogh;t a man avised forto be</L>
<L>Whoom &thorn;at he brou&yogh;t into his pryvete</L>
<L>I prey to god so &yogh;eue me sorowe and care</L>
<L N="4336">If euer si&thorn;en I hight hogge of ware</L>
<L>Herd I Meller better ysette a werke</L>
<L>He had a Iape of malice in &thorn;e derke</L>
<L N="4340">And &thorn;erfor if &yogh;e vouche sauf to here</L>
<L N="4339">But god forbede &thorn;at we stynt heere</L>
<L>A tale of me &thorn;at am a poor man</L>
<L>I wil &yogh;ou telle as wel as euer I can</L>
<L>A litel Iape &thorn;at felle in our Cite<MILESTONE N="61a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4344">Our hooste answerd and seide I graunte it &thorn;e</L>
<L>Now telle on Rogger and loke &thorn;at it be good</L>
<L>ffor mony a paast hast &thorn;ou laten blood</L>
<L>And mony a Iak of Douer last &thorn;ou sold</L>
<L N="4348">&thorn;at ha&thorn; be twies hoote and twies cold</L>
<L>Of mony a pilgryme hast &thorn;ou cristes curs</L>
<L>ffor of &thorn;i Persely &yogh;it fare &thorn;ei &thorn;e wors</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ei han eten wi&thorn; &thorn;i stobel goos</L>
<L N="4352">ffor in &thorn;i shoppe is mony a flee loos</L>
<L>Now telle on gentil Rogger by &thorn;i name</L>
<L>But &yogh;it I prei &thorn;e be not wro&thorn; for game</L>
<L>A man may say ful so&thorn; in game and play</L>
<L N="4356">&THORN;ow seist ful so&thorn; quod Rogger be my fay
<PB REF="00000156.tif" N="126"></L>
<L>But so&thorn; play quade play as &thorn;e flemmyng sai&thorn;</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore henry balyf by &thorn;i fei&thorn;</L>
<L>Be &thorn;ow not wro&thorn; er we departen here</L>
<L N="4360">&thorn;oughe &thorn;at my tale be of an ostylere</L>
<L>But na&thorn;elees I wil not tellen it &yogh;it</L>
<L>But er we part I-wis &thorn;ou shalt be quyt</L>
<L>And &thorn;erwi&thorn; al [he] lough and made chere</L>
<L N="4364">And saide his tale as &yogh;e shal after here</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER><B>&thorn;us ende&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e cokes tale</B><NOTE>[<I>No break in the MS.</I>]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000157.tif" N="127">
<HEAD>And here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e Cokes tale<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; The Cokes Tale.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>APrentis whilom dwelled in our Cite</L>
<L>And of a craft of vitalers was he</L>
<L>Gailard he was as gold-fynch in &thorn;e shawe</L>
<L N="4368">Broun as &thorn;e bery. a propre short felawe</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; lockes blake ykempt ful fetisly</L>
<L>Daunce he cou&thorn;e so wel and Iolily</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was cleped Perkyn reveilour</L>
<L N="4372">He was as ful of loue and paramour</L>
<L>As is &thorn;e hyve ful of hony swete</L>
<L>Wel was &thorn;e wenche wi&thorn; him my&yogh;t mete</L>
<L>And euery Bridale wold he sing and hoppe</L>
<L N="4376">He loued bette &thorn;e Tauern &thorn;an &thorn;e shoppe</L>
<L>ffor whan &thorn;er eny ridynge was in chepe<MILESTONE N="61b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e Shoppe &thorn;idere wold he lepe</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at he had al &thorn;e si&yogh;t yseyn</L>
<L N="4380">And daunsed wel wold he not come ageyn</L>
<L>And gader hym a mayne of his sort</L>
<L>To hoppe and synge and make such disport</L>
<L>And &thorn;er &thorn;ei setten steuen forto mete</L>
<L N="4384">To pleyn at &thorn;e dis in such a strete</L>
<L>ffor in &thorn;e toune nas &thorn;er no prentys</L>
<L>&thorn;at fairrer cou&thorn;e cast a peire of dys</L>
<L>&thorn;an perkyn cou&thorn;e and &thorn;erto he was free</L>
<L N="4388">Of his dispence in place of pryvete</L>
<L>That fonde his maister wel in his chaffare</L>
<L>ffor oft tymes he fonde his boxe ful bare</L>
<L>ffor sikerly a prentise Reveilour</L>
<L N="4392">&THORN;at haunte&thorn; dis ryot and paramour</L>
<L>His maister shulde in his shop abye</L>
<L>Al haue he not part of &thorn;e mynstralcie</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;eft and riot &thorn;ei ben conuertible</L>
<L N="4396">Al conne he pley on gitern or rubible
<PB REF="00000158.tif" N="128"></L>
<L>Reuel and trou&thorn;e as in a lough degre</L>
<L>&thorn;ei ben ful wro&thorn; alday as men may see</L>
<L>&THORN;is Ioly Prentis wi&thorn; his maister bode</L>
<L N="4400">Til he were nygh out of his prentisehode</L>
<L>Al were he snybbed erly or late</L>
<L>And somtyme ladde wi&thorn; revel to Newgate</L>
<L>But atte last his maister hym by&thorn;ou&yogh;te</L>
<L N="4404">Vpon a day whan he his paper sou&yogh;te</L>
<L>Of a prouerd &thorn;at sei&thorn; &thorn;is same word</L>
<L>Wel bette is roten appel out of horde</L>
<L>&thorn;an &thorn;at it rote al &thorn;e remenaunte</L>
<L N="4408">So fare&thorn; it by a ryotous seruaunte</L>
<L>It is moche lasse harme to lat hym passe</L>
<L>&thorn;an he sheed alle &thorn;e seruauntes in &thorn;e place</L>
<L>Therfor his maister &yogh;aue hym a quytaunce</L>
<L N="4412">And bad hym goo wi&thorn; sorowe and meschaunce</L>
<L>And &thorn;us &thorn;is prentise had his leue.<MILESTONE N="62a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Now lat him riot al &thorn;e ny&yogh;t or leue</L>
<L>And for &thorn;er is no &thorn;eef wi&thorn;-out a louke</L>
<L N="4416">&thorn;at helpe&thorn; hym to waasten or to souke</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at he bribe can or borowe may</L>
<L>Anon he sent his bedde and his aray</L>
<L>Vnto a conper of his owne sort</L>
<L N="4420">&thorn;at loued dys [and] reuel and disport</L>
<L>And had a wif &thorn;at helde for countenaunce</L>
<L>A Shop and swyued for her sustenaunce<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000159.tif" N="129">
<HEAD>APPENDIX TO GROUP A.</HEAD>
<HEAD>[THE SPURIOUS TALE OF GAMELYN.]</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Spurious Link.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But here-of I wil pas as nowe</L>
<L N="2">And of yonge Gamelyn I wil telle &yogh;ou.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Tale.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Li&thorn;es and listne&thorn; and harkne&thorn; a-ri&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; &thorn;e tale of yonge Gamelyne</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;e shul here of a doughty kny&yogh;t</L>
<L>Sir Iohn of boundes was his name</L>
<L N="4">He coude of Norture and of mochel game</L>
<L>Thre sones &thorn;e knyght had and wi&thorn; his body he wan</L>
<L>The eldest was a moche schrewe and sone bygan</L>
<L>His bre&thorn;er loued wel her fader and of him were agast</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;e eldest deserued his faders curs and had it atte last</L>
<L>&THORN;e good knyght his fadere lyued so yore</L>
<L>&THORN;at de&thorn; was commen to hym . and handled hym ful sore</L>
<L>&THORN;e Good knyght cared sore . sik &thorn;er he lay</L>
<L N="12">How his children shuld lyuen after his day</L>
<L>He had ben wide where . but non husbonde he was</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e londe &thorn;at he had it was purchas/</L>
<L>ffayn he wold it were dressed among hem alle</L>
<L N="16">That eche of hem had his parte as it my&yogh;t falle</L>
<L>&thorn;oo sente he in to contrey after wise kny&yogh;tes</L>
<L>To helpen delen his londes; and dressen hem to ri&yogh;tes</L>
<L>He sent hem word by letters; &thorn;ei shul hie blyve</L>
<L N="20">Yf &thorn;ei wolk speke wi&thorn; hym; whilst he was a lyve
<PB REF="00000160.tif" N="130"></L>
<L>Whan &thorn;e kny&yogh;tes harden sik &thorn;at he lay</L>
<L>Had &thorn;ei no rest nei&thorn;er: ny&yogh;t ne day</L>
<L>Til &thorn;ei come to hym; &thorn;er he lay stille</L>
<L N="24">On his de&thorn;es bedde/ to abide goddys wille</L>
<L>Than seide &thorn;e good knyght seke &thorn;er he lay<MILESTONE N="62b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Lordes I &yogh;ou warne for so&thorn; wi&thorn;-out nay</L>
<L>I may no lenger lyuen here in &thorn;is stounde</L>
<L N="28">fsor &thorn;orgh goddis wille; de&thorn; droue&thorn; me to grounde</L>
<L>&thorn;er nas noon of hem alle; &thorn;at herd hym ari&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ei ne had routh; of &thorn;at ilke kny&yogh;t</L>
<L>And seide sir for goddes loue; dismay &yogh;ou nou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="32">God may don boote of bale; &thorn;at is now ywrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;an speke &thorn;e good kny&yogh;t; sik &thorn;er he lay</L>
<L>Boote of bale god may sende; I wote it is no nay</L>
<L>But I bisecche &yogh;o<SUP>u</SUP> kny&yogh;tes for &thorn;e loue of me</L>
<L N="36">Go&thorn; and dresse&thorn; my londes; among my sones &thorn;re</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e loue of god dele&thorn; not amys</L>
<L>And forgete&thorn; not Gamelyne; my &yogh;ong sonne &thorn;at is/</L>
<L>Take&thorn; hede to &thorn;at oon as wel as to &thorn;at o&thorn;ere</L>
<L N="40">Seelde &yogh;e seen eny hier . helpen his bro&thorn;ere</L>
<L>&thorn;oo lete &thorn;ei &thorn;e knyght lyen; &thorn;at was not in hele</L>
<L>And wenten into counsell his londes forto dele</L>
<L>Forto delen hem alle to on; &thorn;at was her &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="44">And for Gamelyn was &yogh;ongest he shuld haue nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>All &thorn;e londe &thorn;at &thorn;er was; &thorn;ei dalten it in two</L>
<L>And lete Gamelyne &thorn;e &yogh;onge; without londe goo</L>
<L>And eche of hem seide to other ful loude</L>
<L N="48">His bre&thorn;eren my&yogh;t &yogh;eue him londe whan he good cowde</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;ei had deled &thorn;e londe at her wille</L>
<L>&thorn;ei commen to &thorn;e knyght . &thorn;er he lay stille</L>
<L>And tolde him anoon; how &thorn;ei had wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="52">And &thorn;e knyght &thorn;ere he laye liked it ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&para; Than seide &thorn;e kny&yogh;t; be seint Martyne</L>
<L>For al &thorn;at &yogh;e han done; &yogh;it is the londe myne</L>
<L>fsor goddis loue neighbours . stonde&thorn; alle stille</L>
<L N="56">And I wil delen my londe; after myn owne wille
<PB REF="00000161.tif" N="131"></L>
<L>Iohn myne eldest sone; shal haue plowes fyve</L>
<L>&thorn;at was my faders heritage; whan he was alyve</L>
<L>And my myddelest sone .v. plowes of londe</L>
<L N="60">&thorn;at I halpe forto gete with my ri&yogh;t honde</L>
<L>And al myn o&thorn;ere purchace of londes and ledes<MILESTONE N="63a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;at I bique&thorn;e Gamelyn . and al my good stedes</L>
<L>And I biseche &yogh;ou good men &thorn;at lawe conne of londe</L>
<L N="64">For Gamelynes loue; &thorn;at my quest stonde</L>
<L>Thus dalt &thorn;e kny&yogh;t . his londe by his day</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t on his de&thorn; bed sik &thorn;er he lay</L>
<L>And sone afterward he lay stoon stille</L>
<L N="68">And deide whan tyme come; as it was cristes wille</L>
<L>Anoon as he was dede and vnder gras graue</L>
<L>Sone &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> elder bro&thorn;er; giled &thorn;e &yogh;onge knaue</L>
<L>He toke into his honde his londe and his lede</L>
<L N="72">And Gamelyne him seluen to clo&thorn;e and to fede</L>
<L>He clo&thorn;ed him and fedde him/ euell and eke wrothe</L>
<L>And lete his londes forfare; and his houses bo&thorn;e</L>
<L>His Parkes and his wodes; and did no &thorn;ing welle</L>
<L N="76">And si&thorn;en he it abou&yogh;t on his owne felle</L>
<L>So longe was Gamelyne in his bro&thorn;ers halle</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e strengest of good will &thorn;ei douted hym alle</L>
<L>&THORN;er was noon &thorn;er-Inne nei&thorn;er &yogh;onge ne olde</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;at wold wrethe Gamelyn. were he neuer so bolde</L>
<L>Gamelyne stood on a day; in his bro&thorn;eres &yogh;erde</L>
<L>And byganne wi&thorn; his hond/ to handel his berde</L>
<L>He &thorn;ou&yogh;t on his landes &thorn;at lay vnsowe</L>
<L N="84">And his fare okes &thorn;at doune were ydrawe</L>
<L>His Parkes were broken/ and his deer reued</L>
<L>Of alle his good stedes/ noon was hym byleued</L>
<L>His hous were vnhilled/ and ful euell di&yogh;t</L>
<L N="88">Tho &thorn;ou&yogh;t Gamelyne/ it went not ari&yogh;t</L>
<L>&para; Afterward come his bro&thorn;er walking &thorn;are</L>
<L>And seide to Gamelyn. is our mete &yogh;are</L>
<L>Tho wrathed him Gamelyn/ and swore by goddys boke</L>
<L N="92">&THORN;ow shalt go bake &thorn;i self/ I wil not be &thorn;i coke
<PB REF="00000162.tif" N="132"></L>
<L>What bro&thorn;er Gamelyne howe answerst &thorn;ou nowe</L>
<L>&thorn;ou spekest neuere such a word as &thorn;ou dost nowe</L>
<L>By fei&thorn;e seide Gamelyn; now me &thorn;enke&thorn; nede</L>
<L N="96">Of al &thorn;e harmes &thorn;at I haue; I toke neuere &yogh;it hede.</L>
<L>My parkes bene broken; and my dere reued<MILESTONE N="63b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of myn armes ne my stedes; nou&yogh;t is byleued</L>
<L>All &thorn;at my fader me byqua&thorn;e; al go&thorn; to shame</L>
<L N="100">And &thorn;erfor haue &thorn;ou goddes curs; bro&thorn;ere be &thorn;i name</L>
<L>&thorn;an spake his bro&thorn;er &thorn;at rape was and rees</L>
<L>Stond stille Gadlynge and holde &thorn;i pees</L>
<L>Thou shalt be fayn to haue; &thorn;i mete and &thorn;i wede</L>
<L N="104">What spekest &thorn;ow gadeling . of londe or of lede</L>
<L>Than seide Gamelyn; &thorn;e child so &yogh;ing</L>
<L>Cristes curs mote he haue; &thorn;at me clepeth Gadelinge</L>
<L>I am no wors Gadeling; ne no wors wi&yogh;t</L>
<L N="108">But born of a lady and gete of a kny&yogh;t</L>
<L>Ne dorst he not to Gamelyn neuere a foot goo</L>
<L>But cleped to hym his men; and seide to hem &thorn;oo/</L>
<L>Go&thorn; and bete&thorn; &thorn;is boye and reue&thorn; hym his witte</L>
<L N="112">And lat him lerne ano&thorn;er tyme; to answer me bette</L>
<L>Than seide &thorn;e Child &yogh;onge Gamelyn</L>
<L>Cristes curs mote &thorn;ou haue; bro&thorn;er art &thorn;ou myn</L>
<L>And if I shal algates be beten an&omacr;n</L>
<L N="116">Cristes curs mote &thorn;ou haue; but &thorn;ou be &thorn;at on</L>
<L>And anon his bro&thorn;er in &thorn;at grete hete</L>
<L>Made his men to fette staues Gamelyn to bete</L>
<L>Whan euery of hem had a staf ynommen</L>
<L N="120">Gamelyn was werre . whan he segh hem commen</L>
<L>Whan Gamelyne segh hem commen. he loked ouer all</L>
<L>And was ware of a pestel; stode vnder &thorn;e wall</L>
<L>Gamelyn was li&yogh;t and &thorn;ider gan he lepe</L>
<L N="124">And droof alle his bro&thorn;eres men ri&yogh;t sone on an hepe</L>
<L>And loked as a wilde lyon. and leide on good wone</L>
<L>And whan his bro&thorn;er segh &thorn;at; he byganne to gon</L>
<L>He fley vp into a loft; and shette &thorn;e door fast</L>
<L N="128">&thorn;us Gamelyn wi&thorn; his pestel. made hem al a-gast
<PB REF="00000163.tif" N="133"></L>
<L>Some for Gamelyns loue. and some for eye</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ei droughen hem to halues whan he gan to pleye</L>
<L>&para; What nowe seide Gamelyn; euel mote &yogh;e the</L>
<L N="132">Wil &yogh;e bygynne contecte; and so sone flee</L>
<L>Gamelyn sou&yogh;t his bro&thorn;er; whider he was flowe<MILESTONE N="64a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And seghe where he loked out a wyndowe</L>
<L>Bro&thorn;ere seide Gamelyn. come a litel nere</L>
<L N="136">And I wil teche &thorn;e a play at &thorn;e bokelere</L>
<L>His bro&thorn;ere him ansuerde. and seide by seint Richere</L>
<L>&thorn;e while &thorn;at pestel is in &thorn;ine honde. I wil come no nere</L>
<L>Bro&thorn;er I wil make &thorn;i pees; I swer by cristes oore</L>
<L N="140">Cast away &thorn;e pestel. and wre&thorn;e &thorn;e no more</L>
<L>I most nede seide Gamelyn wre&thorn; me at onys</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou wold make &thorn;i men. to breke my bonys</L>
<L>Ne had I hadde mayn and my&yogh;t in myn armes</L>
<L N="144">To han hem fro me . &thorn;ei wold haue don me harmes</L>
<L>Gamelyn seide his bro&thorn;er be &thorn;ou not wroth</L>
<L>Forto sene &thorn;e han harme. me were ri&yogh;t loth</L>
<L>I ne did it not bro&thorn;er but for a fondinge</L>
<L N="148">ffor to loken wher &thorn;ou art stronge and art so &yogh;enge</L>
<L>Come a doune &thorn;an to me and graunt me my bone</L>
<L>Of oon &thorn;ing I wil &thorn;e axe and we shal sau&yogh;t sone</L>
<L>Doune &thorn;an come his bro&thorn;er &thorn;at fikel was and felle</L>
<L N="152">And was swi&thorn; sore a-feerd of &thorn;e pestelle</L>
<L>He seide bro&thorn;er Gamelyn axe me &thorn;i bone</L>
<L>And loke &thorn;ou me blame but I it graunte sone</L>
<L>&THORN;an seide Gamelyn bro&thorn;er I-wys</L>
<L N="156">And we shul be at on. &thorn;ou most graunte me this</L>
<L>All &thorn;at my fader me by-qua&thorn;. whilst he was alyue</L>
<L>&THORN;ow most do me it haue. if we shul not strive</L>
<L>&THORN;at shalt &thorn;ou haue Gamelyn I swere bi cristes oore.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at &thorn;i fadere &thorn;e by-qua&thorn;e. &thorn;ough &thorn;ou wold haue more</L>
<L N="161">Thy londe &thorn;at lith ley. wel it shal be sawe</L>
<L>And &thorn;ine houses reised vp &thorn;at bene leide ful lawe</L>
<L>Thus seide &thorn;e knyght . to gamelyn wi&thorn; mou&thorn;e</L>
<L N="164">And &thorn;ou&yogh;t on falsnes as he wel cou&thorn;e
<PB REF="00000164.tif" N="134"></L>
<L>&thorn;e kny&yogh;t &thorn;ou&yogh;t on treson. and gamelyn anon</L>
<L>And wente and kissed his bro&thorn;er and whan &thorn;ei were at on</L>
<L>Alas yonge Gamelyn no &thorn;ing he ne wist</L>
<L N="168">Wi&thorn; such fals treson . his bro&thorn;er him kist</L>
<L>Ly&thorn;eneth and listene&thorn; and holde&thorn; &yogh;our tonge<MILESTONE N="64b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &yogh;e shul here talking of Gamelyn &thorn;e &yogh;onge</L>
<L>&para; Ther was &thorn;ere bisiden cride a wrastelinge</L>
<L N="172">And &thorn;erfore &thorn;er was sette a ramme and a ringe</L>
<L>And Gamelyn was in wille to wende &thorn;erto/</L>
<L>fforto preuen his my&yogh;t what he coude doo</L>
<L>Bro&thorn;ere seide Gamelyn by seint Richere</L>
<L N="176">&thorn;ow most lene me to ny&yogh;t a litel coursere</L>
<L>That is fresshe fro &thorn;e spore on for to ride</L>
<L>I most on an erand a litel here beside</L>
<L>By god seide his bro&thorn;er/ of stedes in my stalle</L>
<L N="180">Goo and chese &thorn;e the best spare non of hem alle</L>
<L>Of stedes and of coursers &thorn;at stoden hem byside</L>
<L>And telle me good bro&thorn;er whider &thorn;ou wilt ride</L>
<L>Here beside bro&thorn;er is cried a wrastelinge</L>
<L N="184">And &thorn;erfore shal be sette a ram and a ringe</L>
<L>Moche worchip it were bro&thorn;ere to vs alle</L>
<L>Might I &thorn;e ram and &thorn;e ring bring home to &thorn;is halle</L>
<L>A stede ther was sadeled smertly an skete</L>
<L N="188">Gamelyn did a peire spores fast on his fete</L>
<L>He sette his foote in &thorn;e stirop &thorn;e stede he bistrode</L>
<L>And towardes &thorn;e wrasteling &thorn;e yong childe rode</L>
<L>&para; Whan Gemelyn &thorn;e &yogh;onge was riden out atte gate</L>
