<L>And &thorn;at nyght dwelled &thorn;e oon wi&thorn; &thorn;e o&thorn;er</L>
<L>On the morowe seide Gamelyn to Sir Ote &thorn;e hende</L>
<L N="756">Bro&thorn;er he seide I mote forso&thorn; from &yogh;o<SUP>u</SUP> wende</L>
<L>To loke howe my &yogh;onge men leden her liff</L>
<L>Whedere &thorn;ei lyuen in Ioie or ellis in striff</L>
<L>By god seide Sir ote &thorn;at is a colde rede</L>
<L N="760">Nowe I se &thorn;at alle &thorn;e Carke shal fal on my hede</L>
<L>ffor whan &thorn;e Iustise sitte and &thorn;ou be not yfound</L>
<L>I shal anoon be take and in &thorn;i stede I-bound</L>
<L>Bro&thorn;er seide Gamelyn dismay &yogh;ou nou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="764">ffor by seint Iame in Gales &thorn;at mony men ha&thorn; sou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&YOGH;if that god almy&yogh;ty holde my lif and witte</L>
<L>I wil be redy whan &thorn;e Iustice sitte</L>
<L>Than seide sire Ote to gamelyn god shilde &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> from shame</L>
<L N="768">Come whan &thorn;ou seest tyme and bring vs out of blame</L>
<L>&para; Li&thorn;ene&thorn; and listene&thorn; and holde &yogh;ou stille</L>
<L>And &yogh;e shul here howe Gamelyn had al his wille</L>
<L>Gamelyn went vnder &thorn;e wode Ris</L>
<L N="772">And fonde &thorn;er pleying &yogh;eng men of pris</L>
<L>&thorn;o was &yogh;ong gamelyn ri&yogh;t glad ynou&yogh;e</L>
<L>Whan he fonde his men vnder wode bou&yogh;e</L>
<L>Gamelyn and his men talkeden in fere</L>
<L N="776">And &thorn;ei had good game her maister to here
<PB REF="00000181.tif" N="151"></L>
<L>His men tolde him of auentures &thorn;at &thorn;ei had found</L>
<L>And Gamelyn tolde hem a&yogh;ein howe he was fast bounde</L>
<L>While Gamelyn was outlawe had he no cors</L>
<L N="780">&thorn;er was no man &thorn;at for him ferde &thorn;e wors</L>
<L>But Abbottes and Priours monk and chanone</L>
<L>On hem left he nou&yogh;t whan he my&yogh;t hem nome</L>
<L>While Gamelyn and his men made mer&thorn;es ryve</L>
<L N="784">&thorn;e fals knyght his bro&thorn;er euel mot he thryve</L>
<L>ffor he was fast about bo&thorn; day and o&thorn;er<MILESTONE N="73a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor to hiren &thorn;e quest to hongen his bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>Gamelyn stode on a day and byheeld</L>
<L N="788">&THORN;e wodes and &thorn;e Shawes and &thorn;e wild feelde</L>
<L>He &thorn;ou&yogh;t on his bro&thorn;ere how he hym byhette</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wold be redy whan &thorn;e Iustice sette</L>
<L>He &thorn;ou&yogh;t wel he wold wi&thorn;-out delay</L>
<L N="792">Come to-fore &thorn;e Iustice to kepen his day</L>
<L>And saide to his &yogh;onge men dighte&thorn; &yogh;ou &yogh;are</L>
<L>ffor whan &thorn;e Iustice sitte we most be &thorn;are</L>
<L>ffor I am vnder borowe til &thorn;at I come</L>
<L N="796">And my bro&thorn;er for me to prison shal be nome</L>
<L>Be seint Iame seide his &yogh;onge men and &thorn;ou rede &thorn;erto</L>
<L>Ordeyn how it shal be and it shal be do</L>
<L>While Gamelyn was commyng &thorn;er &thorn;e Iustice satte</L>
<L N="800">&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> fals kny&yogh;t his bro&thorn;er for&yogh;ate he not &thorn;at</L>
<L>To hire &thorn;e men of &thorn;e quest to hangen his bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>&thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;ei had not &thorn;at oon &thorn;ei wold haue &thorn;at o&thorn;er</L>
<L>Tho come Gamelyn from vnder &thorn;e wode Ris</L>
<L N="804">And brou&yogh;t with hym &yogh;onge men of pris</L>
<L>I see wel seide Gamelyn &thorn;e Iustise is sette</L>
<L>Go a-forn adam and loke how it spette</L>
<L>Adam went into &thorn;e halle and loked al aboute</L>
<L N="808">He segh &thorn;er stonde lordes grete and stoute</L>
<L>And Sire Ote his bro&thorn;er fetred ful fast</L>
<L>&THORN;oo went Adam out of halle as he were a-gast</L>
<L>Adam seide to Gamelyn and to his felawes all</L>
<L N="812">Sire Ote stout fetered in &thorn;e mote hall
<PB REF="00000182.tif" N="152"></L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>If gode &yogh;eue vs grace wel forto doo</L>
<L N="816">He shal it abigge &thorn;at it brou&yogh;t &thorn;erto /</L>
<L>&THORN;an seide Adam &thorn;at lockes had hore</L>
<L>Cristes curs mote he haue &thorn;at hym bonde so sore</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou wilt Gamelyn do after my rede</L>
<L N="820">&THORN;er is noon in &thorn;e halle shal bere away his hede</L>
<L>Adam seide Gamelyn we wil not do soo</L>
<L>We wil slee &thorn;e giltif and lat &thorn;e o&thorn;ere goo/</L>
<L>I wil into &thorn;e halle and with &thorn;e Iustice speke<MILESTONE N="73b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="824">Of hem &thorn;at bene giltif I wil ben awreke</L>
<L>Late no skape at &thorn;e door take &yogh;onge men &yogh;eme</L>
<L>ffor I wil be Iustise &thorn;is day domes to deme</L>
<L>God spede me &thorn;is day at my newe werk</L>
<L N="828">Adam come with me for &thorn;ou shalt be my clerk</L>
<L>His men answerde hym. and bad done his best</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou to vs haue nede &thorn;ou shalt finde vs prest</L>
<L>We wil stonde wi&thorn; &thorn;e while &thorn;at we may dure</L>
<L N="832">And but we worchen manly pay vs none hure</L>
<L>&YOGH;onge men said Gamelyn so mote I wel &thorn;e</L>
<L>A trusty maister &yogh;e shul fynde me</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t &thorn;ere &thorn;e Iustise satte in &thorn;e halle</L>
<L N="836">Inne went Gamelyn amonges hem alle</L>
<L>Gamelyn lete vnfetter his bro&thorn;er out of bende</L>
<L>&thorn;an seide Sir Ote his bro&thorn;er &thorn;at was hende</L>
<L>&thorn;ow haddest almost Gamelyn dwelled to longe</L>
<L N="840">ffor &thorn;e quest is out on me &thorn;at I shuld honge</L>
<L>Bro&thorn;er seide Gamelyn so god &yogh;eue me good rest</L>
<L>&thorn;is day shul &thorn;ei be honged / &thorn;at ben on &thorn;e quest</L>
<L>And &thorn;e Iustise bo&thorn; &thorn;at is &thorn;e Iuge man</L>
<L N="844">And &thorn;e Sherreue also. &thorn;orgh hym it bigan</L>
<L>Than seide Gamelyn to &thorn;e Iustice</L>
<L>Now is &thorn;i power done. &thorn;e most nedes rise</L>
<L>&THORN;ow hast &yogh;euen domes &thorn;at bene euel di&yogh;t</L>
<L N="848">I wil sitten in &thorn;i sete and dressen/ hem ari&yogh;t
<PB REF="00000183.tif" N="153"></L>
<L>The Iustise satte stille and roos not anone</L>
<L>And Gamelyn cleued his cheke bone</L>
<L>Gamelyn toke him in his armes and no more spake</L>
<L N="852">But threwe hym ouer &thorn;e barre and his arme brake</L>
<L>Dorst noon to Gamelyn seie but good</L>
<L>ffor feerd of &thorn;e company &thorn;at with-out stoode</L>
<L>Gamelyn sette hym doun in &thorn;e Iustise sete</L>
<L>And Sire Ote his bro&thorn;ere by hym. and Adam at his fete</L>
<L>Whan gamelyn was sette in &thorn;e Iustise sede</L>
<L>Herken of a bourde &thorn;at Gamelyn dede</L>
<L>He lete fetter &thorn;e Iustise and his fals bro&thorn;ere<MILESTONE N="74a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="860">And did hem come to &thorn;e barre &thorn;at on with &thorn;at o&thorn;ere</L>
<L>Whan gamelyn had &thorn;us ydone had he no rest</L>
<L>Til he had enquered who was on his quest</L>
<L>fforto demen his bro&thorn;er sire Ote forto honge</L>
<L N="864">Er he wist what &thorn;ei were hym &thorn;ou&yogh;t ful longe</L>
<L>But as sone as Gamelyn wist where &thorn;ei were</L>
<L>He did hem euerechone fetter in fere</L>
<L>And bringgen hem to &thorn;e barre &amp; setten in rewe</L>
<L N="868">By my fei&thorn; seide &thorn;e Iustise &thorn;e sherrue is a shrewe</L>
<L>&thorn;an seide Gamelyn to &thorn;e Iustise</L>
<L>&thorn;ou hast &yogh;oue domes of &thorn;e worst assise</L>
<L>And &thorn;e xij. Sesoures &thorn;at weren on &thorn;e quest</L>
<L N="872">&thorn;ei shul be honged &thorn;is day so haue I good rest</L>
<L>Than seide &thorn;e sheref to &yogh;onge Gamelyn</L>
<L>Lord I crie &thorn;e mercie bro&thorn;er art &thorn;ou myn</L>
<L>&thorn;erfor seide Gamelyn haue &thorn;ou cristes curs</L>
<L N="876">ffor and &thorn;ow were maister. I shuld haue wors</L>
<L>fforto make short tale and not to longe</L>
<L>He ordeyned hym a quest of his men stronge</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iustise and &thorn;e Sirreue bo&thorn; honged hie</L>
<L N="880">To weyuen wi&thorn; &thorn;e ropes and &thorn;e winde drye</L>
<L>And &thorn;e xij. Sisours sorowe haue &thorn;at rekke</L>
<L>All &thorn;ei were honged fast by &thorn;e nekke</L>
<L>&thorn;us ende&thorn; &thorn;e fals kny&yogh;t wi&thorn; his trecherye</L>
<L N="884">&thorn;at euere had lad his lif in falsnesse and folye
<PB REF="00000184.tif" N="154"></L>
<L>He was honged by &thorn;e nek and not by &thorn;e purs</L>
<L>&thorn;at was &thorn;e mede &thorn;at he had for his faders curs</L>
<L>Sire Otes was eldest and Gamelyn was &yogh;enge</L>
<L N="888">Wenten to her frendes / and passed to &thorn;e kinge</L>
<L>&THORN;ei maden pees wi&thorn; &thorn;e king of &thorn;e best sise</L>
<L>&THORN;e king loued wel sir Ote &amp; made hym iustise</L>
<L>And after &thorn;e king made Gamelyn in est and in west</L>
<L N="892">&THORN;e cheef Iustice of his free forest</L>
<L>All his wi&yogh;t &yogh;onge men &thorn;e king forgaf her gilt</L>
<L>And si&thorn;en in good office &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> king ha&thorn; hem pilt</L>
<L>Thus wanne Gamelyn his land and his lede</L>
<L>And wreke him on his enemyes . and quytte hem her mede</L>
<L>And Sire Ote his bro&thorn;er made him his heire</L>
<L>And Si&thorn;en wedded gamelyn a wif good and faire</L>
<L>They lyued to-gidere &thorn;e while &thorn;at crist wold</L>
<L N="900">And si&thorn;en was Gamelyn grauen vnder mold</L>
<L>And so shul we all; may &thorn;er no man fle</L>
<L>God bring vs to &thorn;at Ioye &thorn;at euer shal be</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER><B>here ende&thorn; &thorn;e tale of &thorn;e Coke.)</B><NOTE>[<I>The Prologue and Tale of the Shipman follow, without any break in the MS.</I>]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000185.tif" N="155">
<HEAD><B>&para; And Thus</B> gynne&thorn; <B>&thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e shipman</B><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 74, <I>back</I></NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nowe frendes seide our hoost so dere<NOTE PLACE="marg"><B>&para; The Prologe</B>.</NOTE></L>
<L>How like&thorn; &yogh;ou by Iohn &thorn;e pardonere</L>
<L>ffor he ha&thorn; vnbokeled wel &thorn;e male</L>
<L N="4">He ha&thorn; vs tolde ri&yogh;t a thrifty tale</L>
<L>As touching of mysgouernaunce</L>
<L>I prey to god &yogh;eue hym good chaunche</L>
<L>As &yogh;e han herd of &thorn;ise retoures &thorn;re</L>
<L N="8">Now gentil Marynere hertely I preye &thorn;e</L>
<L>Telle vs a good tale and &thorn;at ri&yogh;t anon</L>
<L>It shal be done by god &amp; by seint Iohn</L>
<L>Seide &thorn;is marinere as wel as euer I can</L>
<L N="12">And ri&yogh;t anoon his tale he bygan.</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER><B>&para; Thus ende&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e shipman.</B><NOTE>[<I>No gap in the MS.</I>]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="B" TYPE="group">

<PB REF="00000186.tif" N="156">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="168">
<HEAD>GROUP <B>B.</B> (&beta;. FRAGMENT III.)</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&sect; 4. THE SHIPMAN'S TALE.</HEAD>
<HEAD>And here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e shipman tale<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 74, <I>back</I></NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><B>A</B> Merchaunt whilom dwelled in seynt denys</L>
<L>&THORN;at riche was for which men held hym wys</L>
<L>A wif he had of excellent bewte</L>
<L>And companable and reuerent was she</L>
<L>Which is a &thorn;ing &thorn;at cause&thorn; more dispence</L>
<L N="1196">&THORN;an wor&thorn; is al &thorn;e chere and reuerence</L>
<L>&THORN;at men hem done at feestes and at daunces</L>
<L>such salutacions and countenaunces</L>
<L>Passe&thorn; as do&thorn; &thorn;e shadowe vpon a wall</L>
<L N="1200">But woo is hym &thorn;at payen mote for all</L>
<L>The Sely husbond algate he mot paye</L>
<L>He mote vs clo&thorn;e and vs aray</L>
<L>ffor his owne worship richely<MILESTONE N="75a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1204">In which aray we dauncen Iolily</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at he may not perauenture</L>
<L>Or ellis list noon such spence endure</L>
<L>But &thorn;enke&thorn; &thorn;at it is waast and ylost</L>
<L N="1208">&thorn;an mote ano&thorn;er paien for &thorn;e cost</L>
<L>Or lene vs gold and &thorn;at is perilous</L>
<L>This noble marchaunt helde a noble hous</L>
<L>ffor which he had alday grete repayre</L>
<L N="1212">ffor his largesse and for his wif was faire</L>
<L>&thorn;at wonder is but herkene&thorn; to my tale</L>
<L>Amonge all his gestis . grete and smale</L>
<L>Ther was a monk a faire man and a bold</L>
<L N="1216">I trowe xxx<SUP>ti</SUP>. wynter he was olde</L>
<L>That euer in oon was drowing to &thorn;at place</L>
<L>&thorn;is yonge monk &thorn;at was so faire of face
<PB REF="00000187.tif" N="157"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="169"></L>
<L>Aqueynted was so wi&thorn; &thorn;at good man</L>
<L N="1220">. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1224">And eke &thorn;is monke of which I byganne</L>
<L>Were bo&thorn; twoo yborn in oo vilage</L>
<L>&thorn;e monke hym cleymed as for cosynage</L>
<L>And he a&yogh;ein sei&thorn; not ones nay</L>
<L N="1228">But was as glad &thorn;erof as foule of day</L>
<L>ffor to his hert it was a grete plesance</L>
<L>Thus bene &thorn;ei knyut wi&thorn; eterne aliance</L>
<L>And eche of hem gan o&thorn;er ensure</L>
<L N="1232">Of bre&thorn;erode &thorn;e whiles her lif may dure</L>
<L>ffree was dan Iohn and namely of dispence</L>
<L>As in &thorn;at hous and ful of diligence</L>
<L>To do plesaunce and also grete costage</L>
<L N="1236">He for&yogh;ate not to &yogh;eue &thorn;e lest page</L>
<L>In alle &thorn;at hous but after her degre</L>
<L>He &yogh;aue &thorn;e lord and si&thorn;en his Mayne</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at he came some maner honest &thorn;ing</L>
<L N="1240">ffor which &thorn;ei were as glad of his commyng</L>
<L>As foule is fayne whan &thorn;e sonne vpriseth</L>
<L>No more herof as nowe for &thorn;is suffise&thorn;</L>
<L>But so byfelle &thorn;is marchaunt on a day</L>
<L>Shope hym to make redy his aray<MILESTONE N="75b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Towarde &thorn;e toune of Brugges for to fare</L>
<L>To byen &thorn;er a porcioun of ware</L>
<L>ffor which he ha&thorn; to Paris sent an&omacr;n</L>
<L N="1248">A massagere and preied ha&thorn; dan Iohn</L>
<L>&thorn;at he shuld come to seynt denys to pleyn</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hym and wi&thorn; his wif a day or tweyn</L>
<L>Or he to brugges went in al wise</L>
<L N="1252">This noble monk of which I &yogh;ou devise</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; of his abbot as hym list licence</L>
<L>Bycause he was a man of high prudence
<PB REF="00000188.tif" N="158"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="170"></L>
<L>And eke an officere out forto ride</L>
<L N="1256">To seen her graunges and her beernes wide</L>
<L>And vnto seint denys he comme&thorn; anon</L>
<L>Who was so welcome as my lord dan Iohn</L>
<L>Our dere cosyn ful of curtesie</L>
<L N="1260">With him brou&yogh;t he a Iubbe of Maluesie</L>
<L>And eke ano&thorn;er ful of fyne vernage</L>
<L>As volatile as ay was his his vsage</L>
<L>And &thorn;us I lat hem .ete. bo&thorn; drink and playe</L>
<L N="1264">This merchaunt and &thorn;is monk a day or twaye</L>
<L>The .iij. day &thorn;is Marchaunte vp arise&thorn;</L>
<L>And on his nede sadly hym aviseth</L>
<L>And vp into his counter hous go&thorn; he</L>
<L N="1268">To rekne wi&thorn; him self as wel may be</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ilk &yogh;ere hou &thorn;at it wi&thorn; hym stode</L>
<L>And how he despended had his good</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;at he encresed were or non</L>
<L N="1272">His bokes and his bagges mony on</L>
<L>He lei&thorn; to-fore him on his countyng boord</L>
<L>fful riche was his tresour and his hord</L>
<L>ffor whiche ful fast his counter door he shette</L>
<L N="1276">And eke he nold &thorn;at no man shuld hym lette</L>
<L>Of his acomptes for &thorn;e mene tyme</L>
<L>And &thorn;us he sitte til it was passed prime</L>
<L>Dan Iohn was risen in &thorn;e morowe also</L>
<L N="1280">And in &thorn;e Gardyne walked to and fro</L>
<L>And ha&thorn; his &thorn;ingges seide ful curteisly<MILESTONE N="76a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>This good wif come walking prively</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e Gardyne &thorn;er he walked soft</L>
<L N="1284">And hym salueth as he ha&thorn; don ful oft</L>
<L>A mayden childe cam in her companye</L>
<L>Which as hure lust she may gouern and gye</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;it vndere &thorn;e &yogh;eerd was &thorn;e mayde</L>
<L N="1288">O deer Cosyn myn dan Iohn she seide</L>
<L>What eile&thorn; &yogh;ou so rathe to arise</L>
<L>Nece quod he it au&yogh;t ynough suffise
<PB REF="00000189.tif" N="159"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="171"></L>
<L>V. houres forto slepe vpon a ny&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1292">But it were for an olde palled wi&yogh;t</L>
<L>As ben &thorn;ise wedded men &thorn;at lye and dare</L>
<L>As in a forme sitte a wery hare</L>
<L>Were al for-straught wi&thorn; houndes grete and smale</L>
<L N="1296">But dere nece whi ben &yogh;e so pale</L>
<L>I trowe certes &thorn;at oure good man</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; &yogh;ow labored si&thorn; &thorn;e nyght bygan</L>
<L>That &yogh;ou were nede to resten hastely</L>
<L N="1300">And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word he lough ful merely</L>
<L>And of his owne &thorn;ou&yogh;t he wex al rede</L>
<L>This faire wif gan to shake her hede</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;us / &yogh;e god wote al quod she</L>
<L N="1304">Nay Cosin myne it stont not so wi&thorn; me</L>
<L>ffor by &thorn;at god &thorn;at &yogh;aue me saule and lif</L>
<L>In all &thorn;e rewme of fraunce is &thorn;er no wif</L>
<L>&thorn;at lasse lust ha&thorn; to do &thorn;at sorie play</L>
<L N="1308">for I may syngen alas and wele away</L>
<L>That I was born but no wi&yogh;t quod she</L>
