<L N="1612">As be not wro&thorn; but lat vs laugh and play</L>
<L>&YOGH;e shullen my Ioly body haue to wedde</L>
<L>By god I nyl not paye &yogh;ou but abedde
<PB REF="00000198.tif" N="168"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="180"></L>
<L>ffor&yogh;eue it me myn owne spouse dere</L>
<L N="1616">Turne hiderward and make better chere</L>
<L>This Marchaunte seye &thorn;er was no remedye</L>
<L>And forto chide it ner but foly</L>
<L>Sy&thorn;ens &thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;ing may not amended be</L>
<L N="1620">Now wif he seide and I for&yogh;eue it &thorn;e</L>
<L>But be &thorn;i lif ne be no more so large</L>
<L>kepe bette my good &thorn;is &yogh;eue I &thorn;e in charge</L>
<L>&thorn;us enden now my tale and god vs sende</L>
<L N="1624">Tailling y-nowe into our lyues ende.</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER><B>&para; Thus ende&thorn; &thorn;e shipmannys tale</B><NOTE>[<I>No break in the MS.</I>]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000199.tif" N="169">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="181">
<HEAD><B>And here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e</B> priores.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; &thorn;e prologe.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 80, <I>back</I></NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WEl seid by corpus dominus quod our hoste</L>
<L>Now longe mote &thorn;ou saile by &thorn;e coste</L>
<L>Sire Gentile Maister gentyl marynere</L>
<L N="1628">God &yogh;eue &thorn;e monk a Ml. last quade &yogh;ere</L>
<L>A ha felowes be&thorn; ware of such a Iape</L>
<L>&THORN;e Monk put in &thorn;e mannys hode an ape</L>
<L>And in his wyues eke by seint Austyn</L>
<L N="1632">Drawe&thorn; no mo monkes into &yogh;our Inne</L>
<L>But now passe ouer &amp; lat vs seke aboute</L>
<L>Who shal now telle first of al &thorn;e route</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er tale and wi&thorn; &thorn;at word he saide</L>
<L N="1636">As curteisly as it had bene a Mayde</L>
<L>My lady Priores by &yogh;oure leue</L>
<L>So &thorn;at I wist I shulde &yogh;ou not greue</L>
<L>I wolde deme &thorn;at &yogh;e telle shuld</L>
<L N="1640">A tale next if so be &thorn;at &yogh;e wold</L>
<L>Now wil &yogh;e vouche sauf my lady dere</L>
<L>Gladly quod she and seide in &thorn;is manere.<MILESTONE N="81a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<TRAILER><B>Thus ende&thorn; &thorn;e prologe.</B><NOTE>[<I>No break in the MS.</I>]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000200.tif" N="170">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="182">
<HEAD><B>And here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e</B> Priores <B>tale of Alma redemptoris mater.</B></HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[The Prologue.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O lord our lord &thorn;iname how merveilous<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Domine dominus noster. &THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> Priores tale cap</NOTE></L>
<L>Is in &thorn;is large world ysprad quod she</L>
<L>ffor nou&yogh;t only &thorn;i laude precious</L>
<L N="1646">Perfourmed is by men of dignite</L>
<L>But by &thorn;e mou&thorn;e of Children &thorn;i bounte</L>
<L>Perfourmed is for in our brest soukinge</L>
<L N="1649">Somtyme shewen &thorn;ei &thorn;ine heryinge</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Wherfor in laude as I can best and may</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e and of &thorn;e white lile floure</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at &thorn;e bare and art a maide alway</L>
<L N="1653">To telle a storie I wol do my laboure</L>
<L>Nou&yogh;t &thorn;at I may encrece her honoure</L>
<L>ffor she he[r] self is honure and &thorn;erto rote</L>
<L N="1656">Of bounte next her sone of soules bote</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O Modere Mayden o. maiden moder fre</L>
<L>O bussh vnbrent brennyng in Moises si&yogh;t</L>
<L>But vanysshe&thorn; doune fro &thorn;e deite</L>
<L N="1660">&thorn;orgh &thorn;ine humblesse &thorn;e goost &thorn;at in &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> li&yogh;t</L>
<L>Of whos vertue whan he in &thorn;ine hert ali&yogh;t</L>
<L>Conceyued was &thorn;e faders sapience</L>
<L N="1663">Helpe me to telle it in &thorn;i reuerence</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LAdy &thorn;i bounte and &thorn;ine magnificence</L>
<L>&thorn;i vertue and &thorn;i grete humilite</L>
<L>&thorn;er may no &thorn;ing expresse in no science</L>
<L N="1667">ffor somtyme lady er men preie to &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;ow gost byforn of &thorn;i benignite</L>
<L>And getest vs to li&yogh;t &thorn;orgh &thorn;i preire</L>
<L N="1670">To gyden vs vnto &thorn;i sonne so clere
<PB REF="00000201.tif" N="171"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="183"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>My Conyng is to waike . o blesful quene</L>
<L>fforto declare &thorn;i grete wor&thorn;inesse<MILESTONE N="81b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;at I ne may &thorn;e weght not susteyne</L>
<L N="1674">But as a childe of xij mon&thorn;e elde or lesse</L>
<L>&thorn;at can vnne&thorn;es eny word expresse</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t so fare I and &thorn;erfore I &yogh;owe preye</L>
<L N="1677">Gide&thorn; my songe &thorn;at I shal of &yogh;ou seie</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[THE TALE.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ther was a child in a grete Cite</L>
<L>Amonges cristen folk in Iwerye</L>
<L>Susteyned by a lord of &thorn;at cuntre</L>
<L N="1681">ffor foule vsure &amp; lucre of vilany</L>
<L>Hatful to Crist and to his companye</L>
<L>And &thorn;orghe &thorn;e strete men my&yogh;t ride &amp; wende</L>
<L N="1684">ffor it was fre and open at euery ende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A litel scole of Cristen folk &thorn;er stode</L>
<L>Doune at &thorn;e fer&thorn;er ende in which &thorn;er were</L>
<L>Children an hepe ycome of cristes blode</L>
<L N="1688">&thorn;at lerned in &thorn;at scole &yogh;ere by &yogh;ere</L>
<L>Such manere doctrine as men vsed &thorn;ere</L>
<L>&thorn;is is to saie to syngen and to rede</L>
<L N="1691">As smale children done in her childhede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Amonges &thorn;ise children was a widowes sone</L>
<L>A litel Clergioun .vij. &yogh;ere of age</L>
<L>&THORN;at day by day to scole was his wone</L>
<L N="1695">And eke also wher he segh &thorn;e ymage</L>
<L>Of cristes modere had he in vsage</L>
<L>As him was tau&yogh;t to knele adoun and seie</L>
<L N="1698">His Aue marye as he go&thorn; by &thorn;e weye
<PB REF="00000202.tif" N="172"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="184"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thus ha&thorn; &thorn;is widowe her litel childe tau&yogh;t</L>
<L>Our blesful lady cristes moder dere</L>
<L>To worship ay and he forgate it nou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1702">ffor sely child wil alday sone lere</L>
<L>But ay whan I remembre me on &thorn;is matere</L>
<L>Seint Nicholas stant euere in my presence<MILESTONE N="82a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1705">ffor he so &yogh;onge to crist did reuerence</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This childe his litel boke lernynge</L>
<L>As he satte in &thorn;e scole at his prymere</L>
<L>He <B>Alma redemptoris</B> / herd singe</L>
<L N="1709">As Children lered her antiphonere</L>
<L>And as he durst he drow hym ner and nere</L>
<L>And harkened ay &thorn;e wordes and &thorn;e note</L>
<L N="1712">Til he &thorn;e first vers cou&thorn;e al by rote</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nou&yogh;t wist he what &thorn;e latyn was to say</L>
<L>ffor he so &yogh;onge and tender was of age</L>
<L>But on a day his felawe gan he pray</L>
<L N="1716">To expoune hym &thorn;e songe in his langage</L>
<L>Or tellen him whi &thorn;is songe was in vsage</L>
<L>This preide he hym to construe and declare</L>
<L N="1719">fful ofte tyme vpon his knees bare</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His felawe which &thorn;at elder was &thorn;an he</L>
<L>Answerd him &thorn;us &thorn;is songe I haue herd say</L>
<L>Was maked of our blisful lady fre</L>
<L N="1723">Her to salue and eke her forto pray</L>
<L>To bene our helpe and socour whan we dey</L>
<L>I Can no more expounde in &thorn;is matere</L>
<L N="1726">I lerne songe I can but smal gramere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And is &thorn;is songe ymade in Reuerence</L>
<L>Of Cristes modere seide &thorn;is Innocent</L>
<L>Now certes I wil done my diligence</L>
<L N="1730">To conne it er cristmas be went
<PB REF="00000203.tif" N="173"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="185"></L>
<L>&thorn;oo &thorn;at I for my primere shal be shent</L>
<L>And shal be beten &thorn;ries in an houre</L>
<L N="1733">I wil it konne our lady to honoure</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His felawe tau&yogh;t hym homward priuely</L>
<L>ffro day to daye til he cou&thorn;e it by rote<MILESTONE N="82b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;an he songe it wel and boldely</L>
<L N="1737">ffro word to word acording to &thorn;e note</L>
<L>&thorn;rise on a day it passe&thorn; &thorn;orgh his &thorn;rote</L>
<L>To scoleward and hamward whan he went</L>
<L N="1740">On cristes modere sette was his entent</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As I haue seide &thorn;orgh-oute &thorn;e Iwerye</L>
<L>&thorn;is childe as he came to and froo</L>
<L>fful merely &thorn;an wold he singe and crye</L>
<L N="1744">On <B>alma redemptoris</B> euermoo</L>
<L>The swetnesse ha&thorn; his hert perced so</L>
<L>Of cristes modere &thorn;at to hir to prey</L>
<L N="1747">he can not stint of syngyng by &thorn;e wey</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Our furst foo &thorn;e serpent Sathanas</L>
<L>&thorn;at ha&thorn; in Iwes his waspes nest</L>
<L>Vpswal and seide o Ebraike puple alas</L>
<L N="1751">Is &thorn;is a &thorn;ing to &yogh;ou &thorn;at his honest</L>
<L>&thorn;at such a boy shal walken as hym lest</L>
<L>In &yogh;oure despite and singgyng of such sentence</L>
<L N="1754">Which is a&yogh;einst &yogh;oure lawes reuerence</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>From &thorn;ennes for&thorn; &thorn;e Iwes han conspired</L>
<L>This Innocent out of &thorn;is world to chace</L>
<L>In homycide &thorn;erto han &thorn;ei hured</L>
<L N="1758">&thorn;at in a Aley had a prive place</L>
<L>And as &thorn;e childe gan forby forto pace</L>
<L>&thorn;is cursed Iwe him hent and helde fast</L>
<L N="1761">And kitte his &thorn;rote and in a pitte hym cast
<PB REF="00000204.tif" N="174"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="186"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I say &thorn;at in a wardrobe &thorn;ei hym drwe</L>
<L>Wher &thorn;at &thorn;ise Iwes purgen entraile</L>
<L>O cursed folk of herawdes al nwe/</L>
<L N="1765">What may &yogh;oure euel tent &yogh;o<SUP>u</SUP> availe</L>
<L>Mordere wil out it wil not faile.</L>
<L>And namely &thorn;er honure of god shuld sprede<MILESTONE N="83a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1768">&thorn;e blood out crie&thorn; of &yogh;oure cursed dede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O Matir sounded to virginite</L>
<L>Now maist &thorn;ow syngen folowing euere in on</L>
<L>&thorn;e white lombe celestial quod he</L>
<L N="1772">Of which &thorn;e grete euaungelist seynt Iohn</L>
<L>In Pathmos wrote which seyn &thorn;ei &thorn;at gon</L>
<L>Byfore &thorn;is lombe and singe a songe al nwe</L>
<L N="1775">That neuer flesshly wommen &thorn;ei knewe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This poor widowe waite&thorn; al &thorn;at ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>After this litel childe. but home cam he nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>ffor whom as sone as it is daies li&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1779">Wi&thorn; face pale for drede and bisy &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>She ha&thorn; atte scole and ellis whe[re] him sou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Til fynaly she gan so fer espie</L>
<L N="1782">&THORN;at he was sene last in &thorn;e Iwerye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wi&thorn; moders pite in her brest enclosed</L>
<L>She go&thorn; as &thorn;ou&yogh;e she were half out of mynde</L>
<L>To euery place wher she ha&thorn; supposed</L>
<L N="1786">By liklihede her child to fynde</L>
<L>And euere on cristes modere meke and kynde</L>
<L>She cried and at &thorn;e last &thorn;us she wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1789">Amonge &thorn;e cursed Iwes she him sou&yogh;t</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>She freyne&thorn; and she preie&thorn; pitously</L>
<L>To euery Iwe &thorn;at dwelte in &thorn;ilk place</L>
<L>To telle her if her child went hem bye</L>
<L N="1793">&thorn;ei seiden nay but Ihesus of his grace
<PB REF="00000205.tif" N="175"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="187"></L>
<L>&yogh;aue in her &thorn;ou&yogh;t inwi&thorn; a litel space</L>
<L>That in &thorn;at place after her sone she cried/</L>
<L N="1796">Ther he was cast in a pitte beside</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O grete god &thorn;at perfourmed &thorn;i lawde</L>
<L>By mou&thorn;e of Innocence lo here &thorn;i my&yogh;t<MILESTONE N="83b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>This Gemme of chastite &thorn;is emeraude</L>
<L N="1800">And eke of Marterdom &thorn;e rubie bri&yogh;t</L>
<L>Ther he wi&thorn; &thorn;rote y-corue lay vpri&yogh;t</L>
<L>He <B>alma redemptoris</B> gan to singe</L>
<L N="1803">So longe &thorn;at al &thorn;e place gan to rynge</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The Cristen folk &thorn;at &thorn;orgh &thorn;e strete went</L>
<L>Inne comen forto wondren on &thorn;is &thorn;inge</L>
<L>And hastely &thorn;ei for &thorn;e prouost sent</L>
<L N="1807">He come anone wi&thorn;-out tariynge</L>
<L>And herie&thorn; crist &thorn;at is of heuen kynge</L>
<L>And eke his modere honoure of man kynde</L>
<L N="1810">And after &thorn;at &thorn;e Iwes lete he bynde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This child wi&thorn; pitous lamentacion</L>
<L>Vptaken singyng his songe alway</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; honure of grete procession</L>
<L N="1814">&thorn;ei Carien hym to &thorn;e next abbay</L>
<L>His modere swownyng by &thorn;e bere lay</L>
<L>Vnne&thorn;es my&yogh;t &thorn;e puple &thorn;at was &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="1817">&thorn;is new Rachell bring fro his bere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wi&thorn; torment and with shameful de&thorn; ilkon</L>
<L>This prouost do&thorn; &thorn;ise Iwes to sterue</L>
<L>&thorn;at of &thorn;is mordre wist and &thorn;at an&omacr;n</L>
<L N="1821">He nolde none such cursednesse obserue</L>
<L>Euel he shal haue &thorn;at euel wol deserue</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore wi&thorn; wilde hors he did hym drawe</L>
<L N="1824">And after &thorn;at he henge him by &thorn;e lawe
<PB REF="00000206.tif" N="176"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="188"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Vppon &thorn;is bere ay lith &thorn;is Innocent</L>
<L>Byforn &thorn;e chief autere whiles masse last</L>
<L>And after &thorn;at &thorn;e Abbot wi&thorn; his Couent</L>
<L N="1828">had spedde hem forto bury hym fast</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;ei holy water on hym cast</L>
<L>&YOGH;it spake &thorn;e child whan spreynt was &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> holy watere<MILESTONE N="84a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1831">And songe .<B>O alma redemptoris matere</B></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This Abbot which &thorn;at was an holy man</L>
<L>As monkes be or ellis ou&yogh;ten to be</L>
<L>&thorn;is &yogh;onge childe to coniure &thorn;ei bygan</L>
<L N="1835">And saide good child I hailse &thorn;e</L>
<L>Be vertue of &thorn;e holy trinite</L>
<L>Telle me what is &thorn;i cause to singe</L>
<L N="1838">Si&thorn;en &thorn;at &thorn;i &thorn;rote is kitte at my semynge</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>My &thorn;rote is kitte vnto my nek bone</L>
<L>Saide &thorn;is child and as be way of [k]ynde</L>
<L>I shuld haue deied longe tyme a-gone</L>
<L N="1842">But Ihesu crist as &yogh;e in bokes fynde</L>
<L>Wol &thorn;at his glorie last and be in mynde</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e worship of his moder dere</L>
<L N="1845">&yogh;it may I singe .<B>o Alma</B>. loude and clere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This welle of me[r]cye cristes modere swete</L>
<L>I loued alway as aftere my connynge</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;an I my lif shuld lete.</L>
<L N="1849">To me she cam and bad me for to singe</L>
<L>&thorn;is Anteme verrely in my mynd deyinge</L>
<L>As &yogh;e han herd . and whan &thorn;at I had songe</L>
<L N="1852">Me &thorn;ou&yogh;t she leide a greyn vpon my tonge</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wherfore I singe and singe mote certeyn</L>
<L>In honure of &thorn;e blisful martere fre</L>
<L>Til of my tunge of taken is &thorn;e greyn</L>
<L N="1856">And aftere &thorn;at &thorn;us seide she to me
<PB REF="00000207.tif" N="177"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="189"></L>
<L>My litel childe now wol I fecche &thorn;e</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;e greyn is fro &thorn;i tunge ytake</L>
<L N="1859">Be not agast I wil &thorn;e not forsake</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This holy monke &thorn;is abbot hym mene I</L>
<L>His tunge out kaught and toke away &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> greyn/<MILESTONE N="84b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And he &yogh;aue vp &thorn;e goost ful softely</L>
<L N="1863">And whan &thorn;e abbot had &thorn;is wonder seyn</L>
<L>His salte teeres striked doun as reyn/</L>
<L>And gruf he fille al plat to &thorn;e ground</L>
<L N="1866">And stille he lay as he had bene ybound</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The Couent eke lay vpon &thorn;e payment</L>
<L>Weping and herying cristes moder dere</L>
<L>And after &thorn;at &thorn;ei rise and for&thorn; bene went</L>
<L N="1870">And toke away &thorn;is martere fro his bere</L>
<L>And in a toumebe of Marble stonys clere</L>
<L>Enclosen &thorn;ei his litel body swete</L>
<L N="1873">Ther he is nowe god leue vs forto mete</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O yonge hugh of lyncoln sclayn also</L>
<L>With cursed Iwes as it is notable</L>
<L>ffor it nys but a litel while agoo</L>
<L N="1877">Prei eke for vs we sinful folk vnstable</L>
<L>&thorn;at of his mercy god so merciable</L>
<L>On vs his grete mercy multiplie</L>
<L N="1880">ffor reuerence of his modere marye.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER><B>&para; Here ende&thorn; &thorn;e priores tale.</B><NOTE>[<I>The Man of Law's Prologue and Tale follow in the MS.</I>]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="B" TYPE="group">

<PB REF="00000208.tif" N="178">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="129">
<HEAD>GROUP <B>B.</B> (&alpha;. FRAGMENT II.)</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&sect; 1. MAN OF LAW'S HEAD-LINK.</HEAD>
<HEAD>PETWORTH MS.</HEAD>
<HEAD>And here by|gynnes &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e man of lawe<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 84, <I>back</I></NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Prologus viri legis</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Oure hoost segh wel &thorn;at &thorn;e bri&yogh;t sonne</L>
<L>&thorn;e arke of &thorn;is artificial day hadde ronne</L>
<L>&thorn;e feer&thorn; part and half an houre or more</L>
<L N="4">And &thorn;ough he were not depe expert in lore</L>
<L>He wist it was &thorn;e xviij. day</L>
<L>Of Aprile &thorn;at is massagere to may</L>
<L>And seghe wel &thorn;at &thorn;e shadowe of euery tre</L>
<L N="8">Was as in length &thorn;e same quantite</L>
<L>&thorn;at was &thorn;e body erecte &thorn;at caused it</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore by &thorn;e shadowe he toke his witte</L>
<L>&THORN;at Phebus which &thorn;at shoon so clere and bri&yogh;t</L>
<L N="12">Degrees was xlv. clombe on hight</L>
<L>And for &thorn;at day as in &thorn;at latitude<MILESTONE N="85a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Hit was .x. of &thorn;e clok he gan conclude</L>
<L>And sodeynly he pli&yogh;t his hors about</L>
<L N="16">Lordingges quod he I warne &yogh;ow al &thorn;is route</L>
<L>&thorn;e feer party of &thorn;is day is goon</L>
<L>Now for &thorn;e loue of god and of seint Iohn</L>
<L>Lese&thorn; no tyme as ferfor&thorn; as &yogh;e may</L>
<L N="20">Lordingges &thorn;e tyme it waste&thorn; bo&thorn; ny&yogh;t and day</L>
<L>And stele&thorn; from vs what priuely slepinge</L>
<L>And what &thorn;ourgh neglygence in our wakinge</L>
<L>As do&thorn; &thorn;e streme &thorn;at turne&thorn; neuere agayn /</L>
<L N="24">Descending from &thorn;e mounteyn into playn</L>
<L>Wel can Senec and many a philosophre</L>
<L>Byweillen tyme more &thorn;an gold in Cofre</L>
<L>ffor losse of Catel may recouered be</L>
<L N="28">But losse of tyme shende&thorn; vs quod he
<PB REF="00000209.tif" N="179"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="130"></L>
<L>It wil not come a&yogh;ein wi&thorn;-outen drede</L>
<L>No more &thorn;an wil Malkyns Maidenhede</L>
<L>Whan she ha&thorn; lost it in her wantonesse</L>
<L N="32">Lat vs nout mowlen &thorn;us in Ydelnesse</L>
<L>Sire man of lawe quod he so haue I blesse</L>
<L>Telle vs a tale anoon as forward es</L>
<L>&YOGH;e bene submitted &thorn;ourgh &yogh;our fre assent</L>
<L N="36">To stonden in &thorn;is cas at my Iuggement</L>
<L>Aquite&thorn; &yogh;ou nowe of &yogh;oure biheest</L>
<L>&thorn;an han &yogh;e done &yogh;oure devoire at &thorn;e leest</L>
<L>Oost quod he depardeux ich assent</L>
<L N="40">To breke forward is not myn entent</L>
<L>Biheest is dette and I wil holde fayne</L>
<L>Al my biheest I can no better seyne</L>
<L>ffor such lawe as a man &yogh;eue&thorn; ano&thorn;er wi&yogh;t</L>
<L N="44">He shuld hym self vsen it by ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>Thus wil our text but na&thorn;eles certeyne</L>
<L>I can ri&yogh;t now no trusty tale seyne</L>
<L>&thorn;at chaucere &thorn;ou&yogh;t he can but lewdely</L>
<L N="48">On meters and in rymyng craftely</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; seide hem in such englissh as he can<MILESTONE N="85b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of olde tyme as knowe&thorn; mony a man</L>
<L>And if he haue nou&yogh;t seide hem leue bro&thorn;er</L>
<L N="52">In oo boke he ha&thorn; seide in a-no&thorn;er</L>
<L>ffor he ha&thorn; told of louers vp and doun</L>
<L>Moo &thorn;an Ovide made mencioun</L>
<L>In his Epistels &thorn;at bene ful olde</L>
<L N="56">What shuld I tellen hem si&thorn; &thorn;ei be tolde</L>
<L>In &yogh;ou&thorn;e he made of Ceys and Alcione</L>
<L>And si&thorn; ha&thorn; he spoke of euerychone</L>
<L>Thise noble wyues and &thorn;ise louyers eke</L>
<L N="60">Who so &thorn;at wol his large volom seke</L>
<L>Cleped &thorn;e Seintes legende of Cupide</L>
<L>&thorn;er may he see &thorn;e large woundes wide</L>
<L>Of lucresse and of Babylan Tysbe</L>
<L N="64">&thorn;e swerd of Dido for &thorn;e fals ene
<PB REF="00000210.tif" N="180"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="131"></L>
<L>The tre of Phillis for hir demophon</L>
<L>&thorn;e pleynte of Dyanyre and of Hermyon</L>
<L>Of Andrian and of ysiphilee</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;e barayn Isle stonding in &thorn;e see</L>
<L>&THORN;e dreynt leander for his erro</L>
<L>The teres of Elyne and eke &thorn;e woo</L>
<L>Of Brixseid and of &thorn;e ladomya</L>
<L N="72">The cruelte of quene Medea /</L>
<L>&THORN;e litel children honging by &thorn;e hals</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e Iason &thorn;at was of loue so fals</L>
<L>Of ypinistra penolope Alceste</L>
<L N="76">&YOGH;oure wivehode he commende&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;e best</L>
<L>But certeynly no worde ne write&thorn; he</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ilk wicke ensample of canace</L>
<L>&THORN;at luffed her oune bro&thorn;ere synfully</L>
<L N="80">Of suche cursed storis I seie fye</L>
<L>Or ellis of Tiro Appolloneus</L>
<L>How &thorn;at &thorn;e cursed king Antiocus</L>
<L>Biraft his dou&yogh;ter of her maydenhede</L>
<L N="84">&THORN;at is so horrible a tale for to rede</L>
<L>Whan he her drewe &thorn;orgh-out &thorn;e pament<MILESTONE N="86a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;erfor he of ful avisement</L>
<L>Nold neuer write in none of his sermons</L>
<L N="88">Of such vnkinde abhomynacions.</L>
<L>Ne I ne wil none reherce if &thorn;at I may</L>
<L>But of my tale how shal I done &thorn;is day</L>
<L>Me were loth be likned doutlees</L>
<L N="92">To muses &thorn;at men clepen pieriades</L>
<L>Methanorphoseos wote what I mene</L>
<L>But na&thorn;elees I recche not a bene</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh;e I come after hym wi&thorn; hawe bake</L>
<L N="96">I speke in prose and lat hym rymes make</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word he wi&thorn; a sobre chere</L>
<L N="98">Bygan his tale as &yogh;e shal after here</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER><B>&para; Thus ende&thorn; &thorn;e prologe</B><NOTE>[<I>no break in the MS.</I>]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000211.tif" N="181">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="132">
<HEAD>And here by|gynne&thorn; &thorn;e Mannys of lawe Tale<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Incipit fabula</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Prologue.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="99">Ohateful harme condicion of pouert</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;rust wi&thorn; cold with hunger so confounded</L>
<L>To asken help &thorn;e shamest in &thorn;ine hert</L>
<L N="102">If &thorn;owe now aske wi&thorn; nede art &thorn;ou so wounded</L>
<L>&THORN;at verrey nede vnwrappe&thorn; al &thorn;i wonud hed</L>
<L>Maugre in &thorn;ine hede &thorn;ou most for indigence</L>
<L N="105">Or stele or begge or borowe &thorn;i dispence</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thow blamest crist and seist ful bitterly</L>
<L>He mysdeparte&thorn; ricches temporal</L>
<L>&THORN;i neighbour &thorn;ow witest sinfully</L>
<L N="109">And saist &thorn;ou hast to litel and he ha&thorn; all</L>
<L>Parfay seist &thorn;ou somtyme he rekne shall</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at his tale shal brenne in &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> glede</L>
<L N="112">ffor he nou&yogh;t helpe&thorn; nedeful in her nede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Herken what is &thorn;e menyng of &thorn;e wise</L>
<L>Bett is to dyen &thorn;an haue indigence</L>
<L>&thorn;i self neighboure wil &thorn;e despise</L>
<L N="116">If &thorn;ou be poor fare wele &thorn;i reuerence.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it of &thorn;e wise man take &thorn;is sentence<MILESTONE N="86b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Al &thorn;e daies of poor men ben wikke</L>
<L N="119">Be war &thorn;erfore er &thorn;ou come in &thorn;at prikke</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou be poor &thorn;i bro&thorn;er hate&thorn; &thorn;e</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;i freendes fleen fro &thorn;e alas</L>
<L>O riche marchauntes ful of wele be &yogh;e</L>
<L N="123">O noble prudent folk as in &thorn;is cas</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure bagges bene not filled with ambees aas</L>
<L>But wi&thorn; sise cynk &thorn;at renne&thorn; for &yogh;our chance</L>
<L N="126">At Cristes mas mery may &yogh;e daunce
<PB REF="00000212.tif" N="182"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="133"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;e seken londe and ffe for &yogh;our wynnyngges</L>
<L>As wise folk &thorn;at knowen al &thorn;e state</L>
<L>Of regnes &yogh;e bene fadere of Tithenges</L>
<L N="130">And tales bo&thorn;en of pees &amp; debate</L>
<L>I was ri&yogh;t nowe of tales desolate</L>
<L>Ner &thorn;at a marchaunt gone is mony a &yogh;ere</L>
<L N="133">Me taught a tale which &thorn;at &yogh;e shal here<NOTE PLACE="end">[Only the usual stanza-gap of a line in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="part">

<PB REF="00000213.tif" N="183">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="134">
<HEAD>[TALE. PART I.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In Surry whilom dwelt a companye</L>
<L>Of Chapmen riche and &thorn;erto sadde and trewe</L>
<L>&thorn;at wide where setten her spicerie</L>
<L N="137">Clo&thorn;es of golde and saten riche of hue</L>
<L>Her chaffare was so &thorn;rifty and so nwe</L>
<L>&thorn;at euery wi&yogh;t ha&thorn; deynte to chafare</L>
<L N="140">Wi&thorn; hem and eke to sellen hem her ware</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nowe fille it &thorn;at &thorn;e maisters of &thorn;at sort</L>
<L>Han shapen hem to Rome forto wende</L>
<L>Were it for chapmanhode or for disport</L>
<L N="144">Noon o&thorn;er massage wold &thorn;ei &thorn;ider sende</L>
<L>But commen hem self to Rome &thorn;is is &thorn;e ende</L>
<L>And in suche place as &thorn;ou&yogh;t hem auauntage</L>
<L N="147">ffor her entent &thorn;ei taken her herbergage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Soiourned han &thorn;ise merchaundes in &thorn;at toun<MILESTONE N="87a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A certeyn tyme as fille to her plesaunce</L>
<L>But so byfelle &thorn;at &thorn;e excellen renoun</L>
<L N="151">Of &thorn;e Emperour dou&yogh;tere Dame Castaunce</L>
<L>Reported was with euery circumstaunce</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;ise Surryen merchauntz in such wise</L>
<L N="154">ffro day to day as I shal &yogh;ou deuise</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This was &thorn;e comon vois of euery man</L>
<L>Our Emperour of Rome god hym see</L>
<L>A doughter ha&thorn; &thorn;at si&thorn;e &thorn;e world bygan</L>
<L N="158">To rekne as wel her goodnes as bewte</L>
<L>Nas neuere such ano&thorn;er as is she</L>
<L>I prei to god in honure hir sustene</L>
<L>And wolde she were of al Europe &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> quene<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Europia est tercia / pars mundi</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000214.tif" N="184"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="135"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN hure is hegh bewte wi&thorn;-oute pride</L>
<L>&yogh;ou&thorn;e wi&thorn;-out grenehode or folye</L>
<L>To all her werkes vertue is her gide</L>
<L N="165">Humblesse ha&thorn; sclayn in hire al tyrannye</L>
<L>She is a myrour of al Curtesie</L>
<L>Hire herte is verrey chambere of holynesse</L>
<L N="168">Her hand mynystre of fredam for almesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And al &thorn;is vois was so&thorn; as god is trewe</L>
<L>But nowe to purpoos lat vs turne ageyn</L>
<L>&thorn;ise Merchauntz han do fraught her shippes newe</L>
<L N="172">And whan &thorn;ei han &thorn;is blisful Maiden seyn</L>
<L>Howe to Surrey ben &thorn;ei went ageyn</L>
<L>And done her nedes as &thorn;ei han do &yogh;ore</L>
<L N="175">And lyuen in wele I can say &yogh;ou no more</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now fille it &thorn;at &thorn;ise marchauntes stoden in grace</L>
<L>Of hym &thorn;at was &thorn;e Sawden of Surrye</L>
<L>ffor whan &thorn;at &thorn;ei came from eny strange place</L>
<L N="179">He wolde of his benygne Curtesie.</L>
<L>Make hem good chere and bysilie aspie<MILESTONE N="87b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ti&thorn;ingges of sondry rewmes forto lere</L>
<L N="182">&thorn;e wondres &thorn;at &thorn;ei my&yogh;t se or here</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Amonges o&thorn;ere &thorn;ingges specialy</L>
<L>Thise marchauntes han hym tolde of dame custaunce</L>
<L>So grete noblesse in ernest ceriously</L>
<L N="186">&thorn;at &thorn;is sowden ha&thorn; caught so grete plesaunce</L>
<L>To han her figure in his remembraunce</L>
<L>And al his lust and al his bysy cure</L>
<L N="189">Was forto loue her &thorn;e whilis his lif may dure</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Perauenture in &thorn;e &thorn;ikke large book</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at cloped is heuene ywriten was</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; sterres whan &thorn;at he his birth toke</L>
<L N="193">&thorn;at he for loue shuld han his deth allas
<PB REF="00000215.tif" N="185"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="136"></L>
<L>ffor in &thorn;e sterres clerer &thorn;an is &thorn;e glas /</L>
<L>y-writen god wote who coude it rede</L>
<L N="196">&thorn;e de&thorn;e of euery man with-outen drede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In Sterris mony a wynter &thorn;er byforn<NOTE PLACE="marg"><Q><L>&para; Ceptra pharonei fratrum discordia thebe</L><L>&para; fflammam phetentis deutalionis aque</L><L>&para; In stellis priami. species audacia turni</L><L>&para; Sensus vlixeus herculies que vigor</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>Was writen &thorn;e de&thorn; of Ector achilles</L>
<L>Of pompe Iulius er &thorn;ei were born</L>
<L N="200">&thorn;e strif of Thebes and of hercules /</L>
<L>Of sampson turuno and of Socrates</L>
<L>&thorn;e de&thorn; but mennys wittes ben so dulle</L>
<L N="203">&thorn;at no wi&yogh;t can wel rede it at &thorn;e fulle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This souden for his prive counsell sent</L>
<L>And shortly of &thorn;is matere forto pase</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; to hem declared his entent</L>
<L N="207">And seide hem certeyn but he my&yogh;t haue grace</L>
<L>To haue custance wi&thorn;-Inne a litel space</L>
<L>He nas but dede and charged hem in hie</L>
<L N="210">To shapen for his lif somme remedye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Dyuers men dyuers &thorn;ingges seiden</L>
<L>&thorn;e argumentz Custen vp and Doun<MILESTONE N="88a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Mony a sotele reson for&thorn; &thorn;ei leiden</L>
<L N="214">&thorn;ei speken of magik and abusion</L>
<L>But fynaly as in conclusion</L>
<L>&thorn;ei can not seen in &thorn;at non auauntage</L>
<L N="217">Ne in noon o&thorn;er way sauf mariage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Than segh &thorn;ei &thorn;ere in such difficulte</L>
<L>Be way of reson forto speke al playn</L>
<L>By cause &thorn;at &thorn;er was such dyuersite</L>
<L N="221">Bytwene hor bo&thorn; lawes &thorn;at &thorn;ei seyn</L>
<L>&thorn;ei trowe &thorn;at no cristen prince wold fayn</L>
<L>Wedden his childe vnder oure lawes so swete</L>
<L N="224">&thorn;at vs was taught be Mahoun our prophete
<PB REF="00000216.tif" N="186"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="137"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And he answered ra&thorn;er &thorn;an I lese</L>
<L>Custance I wil be Cristened doutlees</L>
<L>I mote bene hers I may non o&thorn;ere chese</L>
<L N="228">I prei &yogh;ou holde &yogh;oure argumentes in pees</L>
<L>Saue&thorn; my lif and be&thorn; not rechelees</L>
<L>To geten hure &thorn;at ha&thorn; my lif in cure</L>
<L N="231">ffor in &thorn;is woo I may not longe endure</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>What nede&thorn; gretter dilatacion</L>
<L>I saye by tretis and Embassadrye</L>
<L>And by &thorn;e popes mediacion</L>
<L N="235">And alle &thorn;e cherch and all &thorn;e Chivalrye</L>
<L>&thorn;at in destruccion of Mawmetrie</L>
<L>And in encrees of cristes lawe dere</L>
<L N="238">&thorn;ei bene acorded so as &yogh;e shal here</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now &thorn;at &thorn;e Sawden and his Baronage</L>
<L>And al his lieges shuld ycristened be</L>
<L>And he shal haue custance in mariage</L>
<L N="242">And certeyn gold I note what quantite</L>
<L>And herto founden sufficient suerte</L>
<L>This same accorde was sworn in ei&thorn;er side<MILESTONE N="88b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="245">Now faire custaunce almy&yogh;ty god &thorn;e gyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now wold somme men waiten as I gesse</L>
<L>&thorn;at I shulde tellen al &thorn;e purviaunce</L>
<L>That &thorn;e Emperour of his noblesse</L>
<L N="249">ha&thorn; shapen for his dou&yogh;ter dame Custaunce</L>
<L>Wel may men knowe &thorn;at so grete ordynaunce</L>
<L>May no man telle in a litel clause</L>
<L N="252">As was araied for so hie a cause</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bisshopes bene shapen wi&thorn; hure forto wende</L>
<L>Lordes ladys kny&yogh;tes of renoun</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er folk ynow &thorn;is is &thorn;e ende</L>
<L N="256">And notified is &thorn;orgh-out &thorn;e toun
<PB REF="00000217.tif" N="187"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="138"></L>
<L>That euery wi&yogh;t with grete deuocioun</L>
<L>Shulde preye crist &thorn;at he &thorn;is mariage</L>
<L N="259">Resceyue in gre and spede &thorn;is viage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The day is commen of her departinge</L>
<L>I seie &thorn;e wooful day fatal is come</L>
<L>That &thorn;er may be no lenger tariynge</L>
<L N="263">But for&thorn;ward &thorn;ei hem dressed al and some</L>
<L>Custance &thorn;at with sorowe is al ouercome</L>
<L>fful pale arist and dresse&thorn; hure to wende</L>
<L N="266">ffor wel shee see&thorn; &thorn;er is noon o&thorn;ere ende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Allas what wondere is it &thorn;ou&yogh;e she wepte</L>
<L>&thorn;at shal be sent to straunge naci&omacr;n</L>
<L>ffro frendes &thorn;at so tenderly her kepte</L>
<L N="270">And to be bounden vnder subiecci&omacr;n</L>
<L>Of oon she knowe&thorn; nou&yogh;t his condici&omacr;n</L>
<L>Husbondes bene all good and han ben &yogh;ore</L>
<L N="273">&thorn;at knowen wives I dar seie &yogh;ou no more</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fadere she seide &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> wrecched child custance</L>
<L>Thi &yogh;onge dou&yogh;tere fostred vp so soft<MILESTONE N="89a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Cap. 9</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;e my modere my souereyn plesaunce</L>
<L N="277">Ouer al &thorn;inge outaken crist aloft</L>
<L>Custaunce &yogh;oure child hire recomannde&thorn; oft</L>
<L>Vnto &yogh;oure grace for I shal to Surrye</L>
<L N="280">Ne shal I neuere seyn &yogh;ow more wi&thorn; ye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Allas vnto &thorn;e Barbarye nacion</L>
<L>I most anoon si&thorn; it is &yogh;oure wille</L>
<L>But crist &thorn;at starf for oure redempcion</L>
<L N="284">So &yogh;eue me grace his heestes to fulfille</L>
<L>I wrecched womman no fors &thorn;ou&yogh;e I spille</L>
<L>Wommen ben born to thraldom and penaunce</L>
<L N="287">And to bene vnder mannes gouernaunce
<PB REF="00000218.tif" N="188"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="139"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I trowe at Troye whan purrus brak &thorn;e wall</L>
<L>Or ylyon &thorn;at brent Thebes &thorn;at Cite</L>
<L>Nor Rome for &thorn;e harme &thorn;orgh Hanyball</L>
<L N="291">&THORN;at Romaynes han venqwisshed tymes &thorn;re</L>
<L>Nas herd such tendere weping for pite</L>
<L>As in &thorn;e Chambere for her departinge</L>
<L N="294">But for&thorn; she mote wher she wepe or singe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O first mouynge cruel firmament<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Vnde Philomeus libro .j<SUP>o</SUP>. c<SUP>o</SUP>. 8<SUP>o</SUP>. primi motus celi duo sunt quorum vnus est qui mouet totum semper ab oriente &amp; occidente vno modo super orbes &amp; cetera. Ita aliter vero motus est qui mouet orbem stellarum currencium contra motum primum viz ab occidente in orientem super alios duos polos &amp; cetera. Omnes .enim. concordati sunt quod elocciones sint debiles nisi in divitibus. habent .enim. isti licet debilitentur eorum electiones radicem .i. nativitates eorum qu&aelig; confortat omnem planetam debilem in Itinere. Hec. Philosophus.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;ine dyurnal sweigh &thorn;at crowdest aye</L>
<L>And hurlest al from eest to occident</L>
<L N="298">That naturelly wold hold ano&thorn;er waye</L>
<L>&thorn;i Crowding sette &thorn;e heuene in such araye</L>
<L>At &thorn;e bygynnyng of &thorn;is feers viage</L>
<L N="301">That cruel mars ha&thorn; sclayn &thorn;is mariage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Infortunat ascendent tortuous</L>
<L>Of which &thorn;e lord is helplees falle allas</L>
<L>Out of his Angle in to &thorn;e derkest hous</L>
<L N="305">O Mars o Atazir in this caas</L>
<L>O feble mone vnhappy bene &thorn;i paas./</L>
<L>&thorn;ow knettest &thorn;e &thorn;er &thorn;ou art not receyued<MILESTONE N="89b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="308">Ther &thorn;ou were wele fro &thorn;ennes now art &thorn;ou weyued</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Imprudent Emperour of Rome alas<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Inspirant</NOTE></L>
<L>Was &thorn;er no Philisophre in al &thorn;i toun</L>
<L>Is no tyme bette &thorn;an o&thorn;er in such cas /</L>
<L N="312">Of viage is &thorn;er non election</L>
<L>Namely to folk of high condicion</L>
<L>Nat whan a roote is of a bir&thorn; yknowe</L>
<L N="315">Allas &yogh;e bene to lewde or to sclowe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The shippe is brou&yogh;t &thorn;is woful faire mayde</L>
<L>Solempnely wi&thorn; euery circumstaunce</L>
<L>Nowe Ihesu crist be wi&thorn; &yogh;ou al she seide</L>
<L N="319">Ther is no more but fare wel faire Custaunce
<PB REF="00000219.tif" N="189"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="140"></L>
<L>She peyne&thorn; hure to make good countenaunce</L>
<L>And for&thorn;e I lete hire saile in &thorn;is manere</L>
<L N="322">And turne I wil ageyn to my matere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The modere of &thorn;e Sowden welle of vices</L>
<L>Espied ha&thorn; her sones pleyn entent</L>
<L>Howe he wil lete his olde sacrifises</L>
<L N="326">And ri&yogh;t anone she for her counsel sent</L>
<L>And &thorn;ei ben commen to knowe what she ment</L>
<L>And whan assembled was &thorn;is folk in fere</L>
<L N="329">She sette her doune and seide as &yogh;e shal here</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lordes quod she &yogh;e knowe euerichon</L>
<L>Howe &thorn;at my sone in poynt is forto lete</L>
<L>&thorn;e holy lawes of our akkaron</L>
<L N="333">&YOGH;euene by goddes massagere Makamete</L>
<L>But on avowe to grete god I hete</L>
<L>&thorn;e lif shal ra&thorn;er out of my body sterte</L>
<L N="336">Or makametes lawe out of myn herte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>What shuld vs tyden of &thorn;is newe lawe</L>
<L>But &thorn;raldome to our bodies and penaunce<MILESTONE N="90a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And afterward in helle to ben drawe</L>
<L N="340">ffor we reveied Mahonne our creaunce</L>
<L>But lordes wil &yogh;e maken assurance</L>
<L>As I shal sein assenting to my lore</L>
<L N="343">And I shal make vs sauf for euermore</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Thei sworen and assenten euery man</L>
<L>To lyve and dye wi&thorn; hure and by hure stonde</L>
<L>And euery in &thorn;e best wise he can</L>
<L N="347">To strengthen hure shal al his freendes fonde</L>
<L>And she ha&thorn; &thorn;is emprise taken on honde</L>
<L>Which &yogh;e shal here &thorn;at I shal devise</L>
<L N="350">And to hem alle she spak in &thorn;is wise
<PB REF="00000220.tif" N="190"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="141"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>We shul first feyn vs cristendom to take</L>
<L>Cold watere shal not greue vs but a lite</L>
<L>And I shal suche a reuel and feest make</L>
<L N="354">&thorn;at as I trowe I shal &thorn;e Sowden quite</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou&yogh;e his wif be cristned neuer so white</L>
<L>She shal haue nede to wassh awaye &thorn;e rede</L>
<L N="357">&thorn;ough she a font ful of water wi&thorn; her lede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O Sawdenesse Roote of Iniquite</L>
<L>Virago &thorn;ou Semyram &thorn;e Second</L>
<L>O Serpent vnder femyninete</L>
<L N="361">Like to &thorn;e Serpent depe in helle ybound</L>
<L>O feyned womman al &thorn;at may confound</L>
<L>Vertue and Innocence &thorn;orgh &thorn;i malice</L>
<L N="364">Is bredde in &thorn;e as nest of euery vice</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O Sathan envious si&thorn; &thorn;ilk day</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou were chased fro our heritage</L>
<L>Wel knewest &thorn;ou to wommen &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> old way</L>
<L N="368">&thorn;ou madest Eva to bringe in seruage</L>
<L>Thow wilt fordone cristen mariage</L>
<L>Thyn Instrument so wele away &thorn;e while</L>
<L>Makestowe of wommen wham &thorn;ou wilt begile<MILESTONE N="90b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This Sowdonesse whom I &thorn;us blame and warye</L>
<L>Lat prively her counsel gone her way</L>
<L>What shuld I in &thorn;is tale lenger tarye</L>
<L N="375">She ride&thorn; to &thorn;e Sawden on a daye</L>
<L>And seide him &thorn;at she wold reneye her laye</L>
<L>And Cristendom of preestes hondes fonge</L>
<L N="378">Repenting she he&thorn;en was so longe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Biseching him to done her &thorn;at honoure</L>
<L>&thorn;at she most han &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> cristen folk to feest</L>
<L>To plesen hem I wil do my labour</L>
<L N="382">&thorn;e Sawden sei&thorn; I wil don at &yogh;our heest
<PB REF="00000221.tif" N="191"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="142"></L>
<L>And knelinge &thorn;onke&thorn; hure of &thorn;at request</L>
<L>So glad he was he nyst what to seye</L>
<L N="385">She kist her sone and hom she go&thorn; her way</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[PART II.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Arriued bene &thorn;ise cristen folk to londe</L>
<L>In Surrye wi&thorn; a grete solempne Route</L>
<L>And hastely &thorn;is Sowden sent his sonde</L>
<L N="389">ffurst to his modere and al &thorn;e regne aboute</L>
<L>And seide his wiff was commen out of doute</L>
<L>And preide hure forto riden ageyn &thorn;e quene</L>
<L N="392">The honure of his regne to sustene</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Grete was &thorn;e prees and rich was tharray</L>
<L>Of Surriens and romaynes met yfere</L>
<L>The modere of &thorn;e Sowden riche and gay</L>
<L N="396">Resceyue&thorn; her wi&thorn; as glad a chere</L>
<L>As eny modere my&yogh;t her dou&yogh;ter dere</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e next Cite &thorn;er beside</L>
<L N="399">A soft paas solempnely &thorn;ei ryde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Naught trowe I &thorn;e triumphe of Iulius</L>
<L>Of which &thorn;at lucan make&thorn; such a boost</L>
<L>Was ryallere ne more curious<MILESTONE N="91a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="403">Than was &thorn;e assemple of &thorn;is blisful hoost</L>
<L>But &thorn;is scorpion &thorn;is wikke goost</L>
<L>&thorn;e Sawdenesse for al her flateringe</L>
<L N="406">Cast vnder &thorn;is ful mortally to stynge</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The Sowden comme&thorn; hym self sone after &thorn;is</L>
<L>So Rialli &thorn;at wonder is to telle</L>
<L>He welcomme&thorn; hure with alle ioye and blis</L>
<L N="410">And &thorn;us in mer&thorn;e and Ioie I lete hem dwelle
<PB REF="00000222.tif" N="192"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="143"></L>
<L>&thorn;e froyte of &thorn;is matere &thorn;at I telle</L>
<L>Whan tyme come men &thorn;ou&yogh;t it for &thorn;e best</L>
<L N="413">That reuell stint and men gon to her rest</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The tyme come &thorn;is olde Sawdenesse</L>
<L>Ordeyned ha&thorn; &thorn;is feest of which I told</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e fest cristen folk hem dresse</L>
<L N="417">In general bo&thorn; &yogh;enge and old</L>
<L>Here may men feest and rialte bihold</L>
<L>And deyntes moo &thorn;an I can &yogh;o<SUP>u</SUP> devise</L>
<L N="420">But al to dere &thorn;ei bou&yogh;t it er &thorn;ei rise</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O sodeyn woo &thorn;at euer art successoure<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Semper mundane leticie tristicia repentina succedit. Mundana ergo felicitas multis amaritudinibus est respersa Extrema gaudii. luctus occupat. Audi ergo salubre consilium in die bonorum ne immemor sis malorum.</NOTE></L>
<L>To worldly blisse sp[r]ayned is wi&thorn; bitternesse</L>
<L>&thorn;e end of &thorn;e ioye of our worldely laboure</L>
<L N="424">Woo occupie&thorn; &thorn;e fyne of our gladnesse</L>
<L>Herk &thorn;is counsaille for &thorn;i sikernesse</L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;i glade day haue in &thorn;i mynde</L>
<L N="427">&thorn;e vnwar woo or harme &thorn;at comme&thorn; behinde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For shortely forto tellen at oon word</L>
<L>The Sowden and &thorn;e cristen euerechone</L>
<L>Bene al to-hewe and stikked at &thorn;e bord</L>
<L N="431">But it were oonly dame custance allone</L>
<L>&THORN;is olde Sawdenes &thorn;is cursed krone</L>
<L>ha&thorn; wi&thorn; her frendes done &thorn;is cursed dede</L>
<L>ffor she her self wold al &thorn;e cuntre lede<MILESTONE N="91b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NE &thorn;er nas Surrien noon &thorn;at was conuerted</L>
<L>&thorn;at of &thorn;e counsaille of &thorn;e Sawden wote</L>
<L>&thorn;at he nas al to-hewe er he asterted</L>
<L N="438">And Custaunce han &thorn;ei take anon fote hoot</L>
<L>And in a shippe al steerless god woote</L>
<L>&thorn;ei han hure sette and bidden her lerne saile</L>
<L N="441">Out of Surry ageynward to ytaile
<PB REF="00000223.tif" N="193"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="144"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A certeyn tresour &thorn;at she &thorn;ider ladde</L>
<L>And so&thorn;e to seyn vitaile grete plente</L>
<L>They han her &yogh;euen and clo&thorn;es eke she hadde</L>
<L N="445">And ffor&thorn; she saille&thorn; in &thorn;e salt see</L>
<L>O my custaunce ful of benygnyte</L>
<L>O Emperours &yogh;onge dou&yogh;tere dere</L>
<L N="448">He &thorn;at is lord of fortune be &thorn;i stere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>She blesse&thorn; and wi&thorn; ful pitous voys</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e Crois of crist &thorn;us seid she</L>
<L>O cleer o. welful autere holy croys</L>
<L N="452">Rede of &thorn;e lambes blood ful of pite</L>
<L>That wessh &thorn;e world from &thorn;e olde iniquyte</L>
<L>Me from &thorn;e feende and from his clawes kepe</L>
<L N="455">&thorn;at day &thorn;at I shal drenche in &thorn;e depe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Victorious tree protection of trewe</L>
<L>That oonly wor&thorn;i were for to bere</L>
<L>The king of heuene wi&thorn; his woundys newe</L>
<L N="459">The white lombe &thorn;at hirte was with a spere</L>
<L>fflemer of feendes out of hym and here</L>
<L>On which &thorn;i lyues fei&thorn;fully extenden</L>
<L N="462">Me kepe and &yogh;eue myght my lyf tamenden</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Yeeres and daies fleet &thorn;is Creature</L>
<L>Thorgh-out &thorn;e see of Grece vnto &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> strayte</L>
<L>Of Marrok as it was hir aventure<MILESTONE N="92a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="466">O mony a sory mele nowe may she baite</L>
<L>After her deth ful oft may she wayte</L>
<L>Er &thorn;at &thorn;e wilde wawes wil her dryve</L>
<L N="469">Vnto &thorn;e place &thorn;ere she shal aryue</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>MEn myghten axen whi she was not sclayn</L>
<L>Eke atte feeste who myght her body saue</L>
<L>I Answere to &thorn;at demannde agayn</L>
<L N="473">Who saued Danyel in &thorn;e horrible caue
<PB REF="00000224.tif" N="194"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="145"></L>
<L>Ther euery wi&yogh;t saf he maister or knaue</L>
<L>Was wi&thorn; &thorn;e leon frette or a-stert</L>
<L N="476">No wight but god &thorn;at hem bare in his hert</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>GOd list to shewe his wonderful myracle</L>
<L>In hir? &thorn;at shee shulde seen his my&yogh;ty werkes</L>
<L>Crist which &thorn;at is to euery harme triacle</L>
<L N="480">By certayne meenes oft / as knowen clerkes</L>
<L>Do&thorn; &thorn;ing for certeyn ende &thorn;at ful derk es</L>
<L>To mannys witt? &thorn;at for our ignoraunce</L>
<L N="483">Ne kon not knowe his prudent puruyaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now si&thorn; she was not at &thorn;e feest ysclawe</L>
<L>Who kepte her from &thorn;e drenching in &thorn;e see</L>
<L>Who kepte Ionas in &thorn;e fisshes mawe</L>
<L N="487">Til he was spowted vp at Nynyve</L>
<L>Wel may men knowe it was no wi&yogh;t but he</L>
<L>What kept puple Ebrayk from drenchinge</L>
<L N="490">Wi&thorn; drie feet &thorn;orgh out &thorn;e see passinge</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Who bad &thorn;e foure spiretes of tempest</L>
<L>That power han bo&thorn; annoyen londe and see</L>
<L>Bo&thorn; nor&thorn;e and sou&thorn;e and also west and Eest</L>
<L N="494">Annoye&thorn; nei&thorn;er See londe ne tree</L>
<L>So&thorn;ly &thorn;e Comannder of &thorn;at was he</L>
<L>That from &thorn;e tempest ay &thorn;is womman kept</L>
<L>As wel whan she woke as whan she sclepte<MILESTONE N="92b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Where my&yogh;t &thorn;is womman mete or drynk haue</L>
<L>Thre &yogh;ere or more how laste&thorn; hir vitaille</L>
<L>Who fedde &thorn;e Egipcien mary in &thorn;e Caue</L>
<L N="501">Or in desert noon but Crist saunz faille</L>
<L>V. Ml. folk it was as grete mervaille</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; loues .v. and fisshes two to fede</L>
<L N="504">God sent his foysen at her grete nede
<PB REF="00000225.tif" N="195"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="146"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>She dryue&thorn; for&thorn; into our Occi&amacr;n</L>
<L>Thorgh-out oure wilde See to atte last</L>
<L>Vnder an hold &thorn;at nempne I ne can</L>
<L N="508">ffor in Nourth humberlond &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> wawe hire cast</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e sonde her shipp stiked so fast</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ennes wold it not of al a tyde</L>
<L N="511">The wille of Crist was &thorn;at she shuld abide</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The Constable of &thorn;e Castel doun is fare</L>
<L>To seen &thorn;is werk and al &thorn;e ship he sou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And fonde &thorn;is wery womman ful of care</L>
<L N="515">He fonde also &thorn;e tresoure &thorn;at she brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>In her langage mercy she bysou&yogh;t</L>
<L>The lif out of her body forto twynne</L>
<L N="518">Hire to delyuere of woo &thorn;at she was Inne</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A Maner latyn corrupte was her speche</L>
<L>But algates &thorn;er-by was she vnderstonde</L>
<L>The Constable whan he list no lengere seche</L>
<L N="522">This wooful womman brou&yogh;t he to &thorn;e londe</L>
<L>She knele&thorn; doune and &thorn;onke&thorn; goddys sonde</L>
<L>But what she was she wolde no man seye</L>
<L N="525">ffor foule ne faire &thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;at she shuld deye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>She seide she was so mased in the See</L>
<L>&thorn;at she forgate hure mynde by hure trou&thorn;e</L>
<L>The Constable of hire ha&thorn; so grete pite<MILESTONE N="93a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="529">And eke his wiff &thorn;at &thorn;ei wepen for rou&thorn;e</L>
<L>She was so diligent wi&thorn;-outen slou&thorn;e</L>
<L>To serue and plese euerech in &thorn;at place</L>
<L N="532">That al her louen &thorn;at loken on her face /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The Constable and dame Ermengeld his wiff</L>
<L>Were paynymes and &thorn;at contray euerywhere</L>
<L>But Hermengilt loued hure ri&yogh;t as hir liff</L>
<L N="536">And Constance ha&thorn; so longe soiourned &thorn;ere
<PB REF="00000226.tif" N="196"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="147"></L>
<L>In Orisons wi&thorn; mony a bitter tere</L>
<L>Til Ihesu ha&thorn;e conuerted &thorn;orgh his grace</L>
<L N="539">Dame hermengild Constablesse of &thorn;at place</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In all &thorn;at londe durst none cristen route</L>
<L>Alle Cristen folk ben fledd fro &thorn;at cuntre</L>
<L>Thorgh paynymes &thorn;at conquered &thorn;er aboute</L>
<L N="543">&thorn;e plages of &thorn;e north by lond and see</L>
<L>To wales fledde &thorn;e Cristiante</L>
<L>Of olde Bretoynes dwellin in &thorn;e Ile</L>
<L N="546">Ther was hure refute for &thorn;e mene while</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But &yogh;it nas neuere cristen Bretoyne so exiled</L>
<L>That &thorn;er nas somme in her priuetee</L>
<L>Honoured Crist and he&thorn;en folk begyled</L>
<L N="550">And ny&yogh;e &thorn;e Castel such &thorn;er dwelled thre</L>
<L>That oon of hem was blynde and my&yogh;t not see</L>
<L>But it were wi&thorn; &thorn;ilk yen of his mynde</L>
<L N="553">With which men seen after &thorn;at &thorn;ei bene blynd</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bri&yogh;t was &thorn;e sonne as in &thorn;at somers day</L>
<L>ffor whiche &thorn;e constable and his wif also</L>
<L>And Custance han ytake &thorn;e ri&yogh;t way</L>
<L N="557">Toward &thorn;e see a forlonge way or two</L>
<L>To pleien and to romen to and froo /</L>
<L>And in her walk &thorn;is blynde man &thorn;ei mette</L>
<L>Croked and olde wi&thorn; fast eyen yshett<MILESTONE N="93b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In &thorn;e name of crist cried &thorn;is blynd Bretoun</L>
<L>Dame hermegild &yogh;eue me si&yogh;t agayn</L>
<L>This lady wexe a-fraied of &thorn;e soune</L>
<L N="564">Lest &thorn;at her husbond shortely forto seyne</L>
<L>Wold hure for Ihesu cristes loue haue slayn</L>
<L>Til Custance made hure bold and bad hire wirche</L>
<L N="567">The wille of crist as dou&yogh;ter of his chirche
<PB REF="00000227.tif" N="197"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="148"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The constable wexe abasshed of &thorn;at sight</L>
<L>And seide what amounte&thorn; al &thorn;is fare</L>
<L>Custance answerd Sire it is cristes my&yogh;t</L>
<L N="571">&THORN;at helpe&thorn; folk out of &thorn;e fendes snare</L>
<L>And so ferfor&thorn; she can our lay declare</L>
<L>&thorn;at she &thorn;e constable er it was eve</L>
<L N="574">Conuerte&thorn; and on crist made hym byleue</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This Constable nas no &thorn;ing lord of &thorn;is place</L>
<L>Of which I speke &thorn;er he Custaunce fonde</L>
<L>But kepte it strongly mony a wynter space</L>
<L N="578">Vnder Alla king of all Nor&thorn;humberlonde</L>
<L>&thorn;at was full wise and wor&thorn;i of his honde</L>
<L>Ageyne &thorn;e scottes as men may wel here</L>
<L N="581">But turne I wil ageyn to my matere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sathan &thorn;at euere vs waite&thorn; to begile</L>
<L>Seghe of Custance al hure perfeccioun</L>
<L>And cast anone howe he my&yogh;t quyte her while</L>
<L N="585">And made a yonge knyght &thorn;at dwelt in &thorn;e toun</L>
<L>Loue hire so hoot of foule affeccioun</L>
<L>&THORN;at verrely hym &thorn;ou&yogh;t he shulde spille</L>
<L N="588">But he of hire ones my&yogh;t haue his wille</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He wowe&thorn; hure but it availle&thorn; nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>She wolde do no synne by no weye</L>
<L>And for despite he compased in his &thorn;ou&yogh;t<MILESTONE N="94a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="592">To make hure a shameful dee&thorn; to dye</L>
<L>He waite&thorn; whan &thorn;e constable was away</L>
<L>And priuely vpon a ny&yogh;t he crept</L>
<L N="595">In hermengildes Chambre while she slept</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wery for-waked in her Orisons</L>
<L>Slepe&thorn; Custance and hermengild also /</L>
<L>This knyght &thorn;ourgh Sathanas temptacions</L>
<L N="599">Al softly is to &thorn;e bed y-goo
<PB REF="00000228.tif" N="198"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="149"></L>
<L>And kitte &thorn;e &thorn;rote of hermengild atwoo</L>
<L>And laide &thorn;e blody knyf by dame Custaunce</L>
<L N="602">And went his waye &thorn;er god &yogh;eue hym meschaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sone after Comme&thorn; &thorn;is Constable home agayn</L>
<L>And Eke Alla &thorn;at kinge was of &thorn;at londe</L>
<L>And segh his wiff dispitously slayn</L>
<L N="606">ffor whiche ful oft he wepte and wronge his honde</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e bedde &thorn;e blody knyf he fonde</L>
<L>By dame Custaunce allas what my&yogh;t she say</L>
<L N="609">ffor verry woo her witte was al away</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So kinge Alla was tolde al &thorn;is meschaunce</L>
<L>And eke &thorn;e tyme and where and in what wise</L>
<L>&thorn;at in a shipp was founden &thorn;is Custaunce</L>
<L N="613">As here byforn &yogh;e han herde devise</L>
<L>The kingges hert of pite gan agrise</L>
<L>Whan he seye so benigne a creature</L>
<L N="616">ffalle in dissese and in mysauenture</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For as &thorn;e lombe toward &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> deth is brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>So &thorn;is Innocent stant to-fore &thorn;e king</L>
<L>&THORN;is fals kny&yogh;t &thorn;at ha&thorn; &thorn;is treson wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="620">Bere&thorn; hure on honde &thorn;at she ha&thorn; do &thorn;is &thorn;ing</L>
<L>But na&thorn;elees &thorn;er was grete mournyng</L>
<L>Amonge &thorn;e puple and seie &thorn;ai can not gesse</L>
<L>Tha[t] she had done so grete a wickednesse<MILESTONE N="94b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For &thorn;ei han seyn her euere so vertuous</L>
<L>And louyng hermengile ri&yogh;t as her liff</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is bare witnesse euerich in &thorn;at hous</L>
<L N="627">Saue he &thorn;at hermengild slowe with his knyff</L>
<L>This gentile kinge ha&thorn; kau&yogh;t a gret motiff</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is witnesse and &thorn;ou&yogh;t he wold enquere</L>
<L N="630">Depper in &thorn;is caas trou&thorn;e forto lere
<PB REF="00000229.tif" N="199"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="150"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Allas Custance &thorn;ow nast no champyon</L>
<L>Ne fighte Canstowe nat so wele away</L>
<L>But he &thorn;at for oure redempcion</L>
<L N="634">And bonde Sathan and lye&thorn; hym &thorn;er he lay</L>
<L>So be &thorn;i strong Champion &thorn;is daye</L>
<L>ffor but Criste on &thorn;e miracle kith</L>
<L N="637">Wi&thorn;-owten gilt &thorn;ou shalt be slayn as swi&thorn;e</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>She sette her doune on knees and &thorn;er she seide</L>
<L>Immortal god &thorn;at sauedest Susanne</L>
<L>ffro fals blame and &thorn;ou merciful maide</L>
<L N="641">Marye I mene dou&yogh;ter to seint Anne</L>
<L>Byforn whoos childe aungels sing Osanne</L>
<L>If I be giltlees of &thorn;is felonye</L>
<L N="644">My socoure be for ellis shal I dye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Haue &yogh;e not sene somtyme a pale face</L>
<L>Among a prees of him &thorn;at ha&thorn; be ladde</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e de&thorn;e where as he gete no grace</L>
<L N="648">And swich a coloure in his face ha&thorn; hadde</L>
<L>Men my&yogh;t knowe his face &thorn;at was bistadde</L>
<L>Amonge alle &thorn;e faces of &thorn;at route</L>
<L N="651">So stant Custance and loke&thorn; hire aboute</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O quenes lyuynge in prosperite</L>
<L>Duchesses and &yogh;e ladies euerechone</L>
<L>Haue some rou&thorn;e on her aduersite<MILESTONE N="95a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="655">An Emperours dou&yogh;tere stant allone</L>
<L>She ha&thorn; no wi&yogh;t to whom to make her mone</L>
<L>O blood real &thorn;at stondest in &thorn;is drede</L>
<L N="658">ffer bene &thorn;i frendes at &thorn;i grete nede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This Alla king ha&thorn; swich compassioun</L>
<L>As Geltile hert is fulfilled of pite</L>
<L>&thorn;at from his eyen ranne &thorn;e water doun</L>
<L N="662">Now hasteli do fecche a boke quod he
<PB REF="00000230.tif" N="200"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="151"></L>
<L>And if &thorn;is knyght wil swere howe &thorn;at she</L>
<L>&thorn;is womman sclowe &yogh;it wil we vs avise</L>
<L N="665">Whom &thorn;at we wold shuld be our Iustise</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A breton booke writen with euaungelies</L>
<L>Was fette and &thorn;er-on he swore anone</L>
<L>She giltif was in &thorn;e mene whiles</L>
<L N="669">An honde him smote vpon &thorn;e nekke bone</L>
<L>&thorn;at doune he felle at ones as a stone</L>
<L>And bo&thorn;e his eyen brast out of his face</L>
<L N="672">In si&yogh;t of euery body in &thorn;at place</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A voys was herde in general audience</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;ou hast disslaundered giltelees</L>
<L>&thorn;e dou&yogh;ter of holy church in high presence</L>
<L N="676">Thus hastowe done and &yogh;it I mot hold my pees</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is mervaile agast was all &thorn;e prees</L>
<L>As mazed folk &thorn;ei stoden euerechone</L>
<L N="679">ffor drede of wreche sauf Custance alone</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Grete was &thorn;e drede and eke &thorn;e repentaunce</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at hadden wrong suspecioun</L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;is cely Innocent Custaunce</L>
<L N="683">And for &thorn;is miracle in conclusioun</L>
<L>And by Custance Mediacioun</L>
<L>&THORN;e kinge and mony ano&thorn;er in &thorn;at place</L>
<L>Conuerted were &thorn;onked be goddis grace<MILESTONE N="95b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This fals knyght was sclayn for his vntrou&thorn;e</L>
<L>By Iuggement of Alla hastifly</L>
<L>And &yogh;it Custance ha&thorn; of his de&thorn; gret rou&thorn;e</L>
<L N="690">And after &thorn;is Ihesus of his mercye</L>
<L>Made Alla wedden ful solempnely</L>
<L>This holy maiden &thorn;at is so bri&yogh;t and shene</L>
<L N="693">And &thorn;us ha&thorn; crist made Custance a quene
<PB REF="00000231.tif" N="201"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="152"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But who was wooful if I shal not lye</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is wedding but donegild and no moo /</L>
<L>The kingges modere ful of Tyrannye</L>
<L N="697">Hire &thorn;ou&yogh;t her cursed hert brast a two</L>
<L>She wold not her sone had done so /</L>
<L>Hire &thorn;ou&yogh;t a despite &thorn;at he shulde take</L>
<L N="700">So straunge a creature vnto his make</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ME list not of &thorn;e Chaf ne of &thorn;e stre</L>
<L>Make so longe a tale as of &thorn;e corne</L>
<L>What shuld I tellen of &thorn;e Rialte</L>
<L N="704">Of mariage or which cours go&thorn; byforne</L>
<L>Who blowe&thorn; in trompe or in an horne</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> ffrwte of euery tale is forto seye</L>
<L N="707">&thorn;e[i] and drinke . &thorn;ei daunce singe or pley .</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thei gone to bedde as it was skil and ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;at wives bene ful holy &thorn;ingges</L>
<L>&thorn;ei most take in pacience a nyght</L>
<L N="711">Such manere necessaries as ben plesingges</L>
<L>To folk &thorn;at han ywedded hem with ringges /</L>
<L>And laye a litel her holynesse aside</L>
<L N="714">As for &thorn;e tyme it may none o&thorn;ere betide</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>On hire he gate a knaue child anone</L>
<L>And to a bisshope and his Constable eke</L>
<L>He toke his wif to kepe whan he is gone<MILESTONE N="96a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="718">to scotlond ward his foomen for to seke</L>
<L>Nowe faire Custance &thorn;at is so humble and meke</L>
<L>So longe is goon wi&thorn; child til &thorn;at stille</L>
<L N="721">She halt her chambere abiding cristes wille</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The tyme is come a knaue child she bere</L>
<L>Mauricius atte fontstone &thorn;ei hym calle</L>
<L>&thorn;is Constable do&thorn; for&thorn; come a massagere</L>
<L N="725">And wrote to his kinge &thorn;at cleped was Alle
<PB REF="00000232.tif" N="202"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="153"></L>
<L>Howe &thorn;at &thorn;is blisful tydyngges is byfalle</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er tydingges spedeful forto seye</L>
<L N="728">He take&thorn; &thorn;e lettre and for&thorn; he go&thorn; his waye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This Massagere to done his auauntage</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e kingges modere ride&thorn; swi&thorn;e</L>
<L>And salwe&thorn; hire ful faire in his langage</L>
<L N="732">Madame quod he . &yogh;e may be glad and bli&thorn;e</L>
<L>And &thorn;onke&thorn; god an hundred &thorn;ousand si&thorn;e</L>
<L>My lady quene ha&thorn; child wi&thorn;-outen doute</L>
<L N="735">To Ioie and blisse of al &thorn;is regne aboute</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lo here &thorn;e lettres seled of &thorn;is &thorn;inge</L>
<L>&THORN;at I mot bere wi&thorn; al &thorn;e hast I may</L>
<L>If &yogh;e wil ou&yogh;t vnto &yogh;oure sone &thorn;e kinge</L>
<L N="739">I am &yogh;oure seruaunte bo&thorn; ny&yogh;t and day</L>
<L>Dongild answerd not not at &thorn;is tyme</L>
<L>But here al ny&yogh;t I wil &thorn;ou take &thorn;i rest</L>
<L N="742">To morowe wil I saye what me lest</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This Massagere dronk sadly ale and wyne</L>
<L>And stollen were his lettres prively</L>
<L>Out of his boxe whilst he slepte as a swyn</L>
<L N="746">And counterfeted was ful subtily</L>
<L>A no&thorn;ere lettre wrou&yogh;t ful synfully</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e kinge directe of &thorn;is matere</L>
<L>ffrom his Constable as &yogh;e shal after here<MILESTONE N="96b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The lettre spak &thorn;e Quene delyuered was</L>
<L>Of so horrible a fendlich creature</L>
<L>That in &thorn;e Castel noon so hardy was</L>
<L N="753">&thorn;at eny while dorst &thorn;er-Inne endure</L>
<L>The modere was an Elf by auenture</L>
<L>Ycome by Charmes or by sorcerye</L>
<L N="756">And euery wight hate&thorn; her companye
<PB REF="00000233.tif" N="203"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="154"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WOo was &thorn;is kinge whan he &thorn;is lettre had seyne</L>
<L>But to no wi&yogh;t he tolde his sorowes sore</L>
<L>But of his owne honde he wrote ageyne</L>
<L N="760">Welcome &thorn;e sonde of crist for euermoore</L>
<L>To me &thorn;at am nowe lered in his lore</L>
<L>Lord welcome be &thorn;i lust and &thorn;i plesaunce</L>
<L N="763">My lust is putte al in &thorn;ine ordynaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wepe&thorn; &thorn;is child al be it foule or feire</L>
<L>And eke my wiff vnto myn home commynge</L>
<L>Crist whan him list may sende me an heire</L>
<L N="767">More a-greable &thorn;an &thorn;is is to my likinge</L>
<L>This letter he cele&thorn; prively wepinge</L>
<L>Whiche to &thorn;e massagere was take sone</L>
<L N="770">And for&thorn; he go&thorn; &thorn;er nys no more to done</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O Massagere fulfilled of dronkenesse<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Quid turpius ebrioso cui fetor in ore. tremor in corpore. qui promit stulta. prodit occulta Cui mens alienatur facies transfor|matur nullum enim latet secretum. vbi regnat Ebrietas.</NOTE></L>
<L>Stronge is &thorn;i bree&thorn; &thorn;i lymmes flateren ay</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou by-wreiest al sikernesse</L>
<L N="774">Thy mynde is lorn &thorn;ou Iangelest as a Iaye</L>
<L>Thi face is turned in a newe aray</L>
<L>Ther dronkenesse regne&thorn; in ony route</L>
<L N="777">Ther nys no counsell hidde wi&thorn;-oute doute</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O Donegild I ne haue noon englissh digne</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;i malice and &thorn;i tyrannye<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>line repeated in MS, with</I> tirannye, <I>as the first line of</I></NOTE><MILESTONE N="97a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore to &thorn;e fende I &thorn;e resigne</L>
<L N="781">Lat hym enditen of &thorn;i traterye</L>
<L>ffy mannyssh fy. o nay by god I lie</L>
<L>ffy feendissh spirit . for I dar wel telle</L>
<L N="784">Thowe &thorn;ou here walk &thorn;i spirit is in helle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This massagere comme&thorn; fro &thorn;e feende agayn</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e kingges moders court he li&yogh;t</L>
<L>And she was of this massagere ful fayn</L>
<L N="788">And plesed him in al &thorn;at euere she my&yogh;t
<PB REF="00000234.tif" N="204"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="155"></L>
<L>He drank wel his girdel vnder pi&yogh;t</L>
<L>He sclepe&thorn; and he ffronte&thorn; in his gise</L>
<L N="791">Al nyght to &thorn;e sonne gan arise</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ofte were his lettres stolle euerechone</L>
<L>And counterfeted lettres in &thorn;at wise</L>
<L>&THORN;e kinge commaunde&thorn; his constable anone</L>
<L N="795">Vp peyn of hongyng on an high Iwyse</L>
<L>That he ne shulde suffre in no wise</L>
<L>Custance wi&thorn;-Inne his regne forto abide</L>
<L N="798">Thre daies and a quarter of a tyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But in &thorn;e same ship as he hire fonde</L>
<L>Hure and her yonge sone and al her gere</L>
<L>He shulde putte and croude fro &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> londe</L>
<L N="802">And charge hure &thorn;at she neuere eft come &thorn;ere</L>
<L>O my Custance wel may &thorn;i goost haue fere</L>
<L>And sleping in &thorn;i dreme bene in penaunce</L>
<L N="805">Whan donegil cast all hir ordinaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This Massagere on morowe whan he woke</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e Castel halt &thorn;e next waye</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e Constable he &thorn;e lettre toke</L>
<L N="809">And whan &thorn;at he &thorn;is pitous lettre saye</L>
<L>fful oft he seide allas and walawaye</L>
<L>lord Crist quod he howe may &thorn;is lettre endure<MILESTONE N="97b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="812">So ful of synne is mony a creature</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O my&yogh;ty god if &thorn;at it be &thorn;i wille</L>
<L>Si&thorn; &thorn;ou art ri&yogh;tful Iuge how may it be</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou wilt suffren Innocentz to spille</L>
<L N="816">And wicked folk regnen in prosperite</L>
<L>O good Custance allas so woo is me</L>
<L>&thorn;at I mote be &thorn;i turmentour or deye</L>
<L N="819">On shames deth &thorn;er nys noon o&thorn;ere waye
<PB REF="00000235.tif" N="205"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="156"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wepen bo&thorn; &yogh;onge and olde in al &thorn;at place</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;e kinge &thorn;is cursed lettre sent</L>
<L>And Custance wi&thorn; a dedly pale face</L>
<L N="823">&thorn;e fer&thorn;e day toward her ship she went</L>
<L>But na&thorn;elees she take&thorn; in good entent</L>
<L>&thorn;e wille of Crist and kneling in &thorn;e stronde</L>
<L N="826">She saide lorde o. welcome be &thorn;i sonde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He &thorn;at me kept from &thorn;e fals blame</L>
<L>While I was in &thorn;e londe amonges &yogh;ou</L>
<L>He kan me kepe from harme and eke fro sham</L>
<L N="830">In salt See al-&thorn;ou&yogh;e I se not howe</L>
<L>As stronge as euer he was he is ri&yogh;t nowe</L>
<L>In hym trust I and in his modere dere</L>
<L N="833">&thorn;at is to me my saille and eke my stere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hire litel child lay weping in her Arme</L>
<L>An kneling pitously to him she seide</L>
<L>Pees litel sone I wil do &thorn;e noon harme</L>
<L N="837">Wi&thorn; &thorn;at her keerchef of her hede she breide</L>
<L>And ouer his smale yen she it leyde</L>
<L>And in her Arme she lulle&thorn; it ful fast</L>
<L N="840">And in to heuene her yen vp she cast</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Modere quod she and maide bri&yogh;t marie</L>
<L>So&thorn;e is &thorn;at &thorn;orowe wommennys eggement<MILESTONE N="98a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Mankinde was lorn and dampned ay to dye</L>
<L N="844">ffor which &thorn;i child was on croys yrent</L>
<L>&thorn;i blisful eyen segh al his turment</L>
<L>&thorn;an is &thorn;er no comparison bytwene</L>
<L N="847">&thorn;i woo and any woo man may sustene</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thowe seghe &thorn;i sone yslayn bifore &thorn;ine eyen</L>
<L>And &yogh;it now lyue&thorn; my litel child parfay</L>
<L>Now lady bri&yogh;t to whoom al woful crien</L>
<L N="851">Thowe glory of wommanhode &thorn;ou faire may
<PB REF="00000236.tif" N="206"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="157"></L>
<L>&thorn;ow hauen of refute bri&yogh;t sterre of day</L>
<L>Rewe on my child &thorn;at of &thorn;i gentilnesse</L>
<L N="854">Rewest on euery Rwefull in distresse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O litel child allas wat is &thorn;i gilt</L>
<L>&thorn;at neuer wrou&yogh;test synne as &yogh;it parde</L>
<L>Why wil &thorn;ine harde fadere haue &thorn;e spilt</L>
<L N="858">O mercye dere constable quod she</L>
<L>As lat my litel child dwelle here with &thorn;e</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ou darst not fauour hym for blame</L>
<L N="861">So kisse him onys in his faders name</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Therwi&thorn; she loke&thorn; bacward to &thorn;e lande</L>
<L>And saide fare wel husbond rewthlees</L>
<L>And vp she rest and walke&thorn; doun &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> stronde</L>
<L N="865">Toward &thorn;e shippe hire folowe&thorn; al &thorn;e prees</L>
<L>And euere she preie&thorn; her child to hold his pees</L>
<L>And take&thorn; her leue and with an holy entent</L>
<L N="868">She blesse&thorn; hire and into ship she went</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Availed was &thorn;e ship it is no drede</L>
<L>Abundantly for hire a longe space</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er necessaries &thorn;at shulde nede</L>
<L N="872">She had ynowe heryed be goddes grace</L>
<L>ffor wynde and weder almy&yogh;ty god purchase</L>
<L>And bringe hure home I can no better seye<MILESTONE N="98b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="875">But in &thorn;e See she drive&thorn; for&thorn; her weye</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[PART III.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alla &thorn;e kynge comme&thorn; home sone after &thorn;is</L>
<L>Vnto his Castel of &thorn;e which I tolde</L>
<L>And axe&thorn; wher his wif and his child is</L>
<L N="879">The Constable gan about his hert cold
<PB REF="00000237.tif" N="207"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="158"></L>
<L>And pleynly al &thorn;e manere he hym told</L>
<L>As &yogh;e han herde I can telle it no bettere</L>
<L N="882">And shewe&thorn; &thorn;e kinge his seele and his lettere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And seide lord as &yogh;e commaunded me</L>
<L>Vp peyn of de&thorn;e so haue I done certeyne</L>
<L>This massagere tormented was til he</L>
<L N="886">Most be-knowen and tellen plat and pleyne</L>
<L>ffrom nyght to ny&yogh;t in what place he had leyne</L>
<L>And &thorn;us by witte and subtil enqueringe</L>
<L N="889">Ymagened was by whom &thorn;is harme can sprynge</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The honde was knowen &thorn;at &thorn;e lettere wrote</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e venyme of &thorn;is cursed dede</L>
<L>But in what wise certeynly I note</L>
<L N="893">&thorn;e effecte is &thorn;is &thorn;at Alla out of drede</L>
<L>his modere sclowe &thorn;at mony men pleynly rede</L>
<L>That for she tratour was to her legeaunce</L>
<L N="896">Thus ende&thorn; old donegild with meschaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The Sorowe &thorn;at &thorn;is Alla ny&yogh;t and day</L>
<L>Make&thorn; for his wif and for his child also</L>
<L>Ther nys no tunge &thorn;at it telle may</L>
<L N="900">But now wil I vnto Custance goo</L>
<L>That flete&thorn; in &thorn;e See in peyn and woo</L>
<L>V. &yogh;ere and more as liked cristes sonde</L>
<L N="903">Er &thorn;at her shippe approched vnto londe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Vnder an hethen Castell atte last</L>
<L>Of which &thorn;e name in my tixt no&yogh;t I fynde<MILESTONE N="99a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Custance and eke &thorn;e child &thorn;e see vp cast</L>
<L N="907">Almy&yogh;ty god &thorn;at saue&thorn; al man kinde</L>
<L>Haue on custaunce and her childe som mynde</L>
<L>&thorn;at fallen is in hethen hand eft sone</L>
<L N="910">In poynt to spille as I shal telle &yogh;ou sone
<PB REF="00000238.tif" N="208"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="159"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Downe fro &thorn;e Castell com&thorn;e &thorn;ere mony a wi&yogh;t</L>
<L>To gawen on &thorn;is ship and on custance</L>
<L>But shortely from &thorn;e Castel on a ny&yogh;t</L>
<L N="914">The lordes steward god &yogh;eue hym meschaunce</L>
<L>A theef &thorn;at had reyned our creaunce</L>
<L>Come into shipp allone and seide he shuld</L>
<L N="917">Her lemman be where so she wold or nold</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Woo was &thorn;is wrecched womman &thorn;oo bygone</L>
<L>Her childe cried and she cried pitously</L>
<L>But blisful mary halpe hure ri&yogh;t anone</L>
<L N="921">ffor wi&thorn; her strogelinge wel and my&yogh;tely</L>
<L>&thorn;e theef fille ouer bord al sodeynly</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e See he dreynt for vengeance</L>
<L N="924">And &thorn;us ha&thorn; crist vnwemmed kepte custance</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O foule lust of luxurie lo &thorn;ine ende<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; O extrema libidinis turpitudo que non solum mentem effeminat. sed <I>et</I> corpus eneruat semper sequuntur dolor &amp; penitencia post &amp;cetera.</NOTE></L>
<L>Not only &thorn;at &thorn;ou fayntest mannys mynde</L>
<L>But verrely &thorn;ou wilt his body shende</L>
<L N="928">&thorn;e ende of &thorn;i werk or of &thorn;i lustes blynde</L>
<L>Is compleynyng how mony one may men fynde</L>
<L>&thorn;at nou&yogh;t for werk somtyme but for &thorn;entente</L>
<L N="931">To done &thorn;is synne bene ei&thorn;er slayn or shente</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>How may &thorn;is weike womman han &thorn;is strength</L>
<L>Hire to defend a&yogh;einst &thorn;is Renegat</L>
<L>O Golyas vnmesurable of length</L>
<L N="935">How my&yogh;t dauid make &thorn;e so mat</L>
<L>So yonge and of armure so desolat</L>
<L>How durst he loke vpon &thorn;i dredful face<MILESTONE N="99b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="938">Wel may men seen it was but goddes grace</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Who &yogh;af Iudith corage or hardynesse</L>
<L>To scleen hym Olesphernus in his tent</L>
<L>And to delyuere out of wrecchednesse</L>
<L N="942">The puple of god I seye for &thorn;is entent
<PB REF="00000239.tif" N="209"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="160"></L>
<L>That ri&yogh;t as god spirit and vigor sent</L>
<L>To hem and saued hem out of meschaunce</L>
<L N="945">So sent he my&yogh;t and vigor to Custaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For&thorn; go&thorn; &thorn;e shippe &thorn;orowe-out &thorn;e narow mou&thorn;e</L>
<L>Of Iubaltar and scepte dryuyng aye</L>
<L>Som tyme west and somtyme nour&thorn;e and sou&thorn;e</L>
<L N="949">And somtyme Este ful mony a wery daye</L>
<L>Til Cristes modere blessed be &yogh;e aye</L>
<L>ha&thorn; scapen &thorn;orgh her endelees goodnesse</L>
<L N="952">To make an ende of al her hevynesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now lat vs stynt of Custance but a throwe</L>
<L>And speke we of &thorn;e Romayn Emperour</L>
<L>&thorn;at out of Surry ha&thorn; by letters knowe</L>
<L N="956">&thorn;e sclaughter of Cristen folk and dishonoure</L>
<L>Doon to his dou&yogh;ter by a fals tratour</L>
<L>I mene &thorn;e Cursed wicked Sowdenesse</L>
<L N="959">That at &thorn;e feest lete scleen bo&thorn; more and lesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For which &thorn;e Emperour ha&thorn; sent anon</L>
<L>His Senatour wi&thorn; real ordynaunce</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er lordes god wote mony on</L>
<L N="963">On Surriens to taken hie vengeaunce</L>
<L>They brennen sleen and bringgen hem to meschaunce.</L>
<L>fful mony a day but shortely &thorn;is is &thorn;ende</L>
<L N="966">Homword to Rome &thorn;ei shapen hem to wende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This senatour repaire&thorn; with victorye</L>
<L>To Romeward saillinge ful Rially<MILESTONE N="100a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And mette &thorn;e Shippe dryuyng as sei&thorn; &thorn;e storye</L>
<L N="970">In which Custance sitte ful pitously</L>
<L>No &thorn;ing ne knewe what she was ne why</L>
<L>She was in such aray . ne she nyl sey</L>
<L N="973">Of her astaat &thorn;ough &thorn;at she shulde deye
<PB REF="00000240.tif" N="210"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="161"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HE bringe&thorn; her to Rome and to his wiff</L>
<L>He &yogh;aue hure and her &yogh;onge sone also</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;e Senatoure she lad her liff</L>
<L N="977">Thus can our lady bringen out of woo</L>
<L>Wooful Custance and mony an o&thorn;er moo</L>
<L>And longe tyme dwelled she in &thorn;at place</L>
<L N="980">In holy werkes euer as was hire grace</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The Senatours wif her Aunte was</L>
<L>But for al &thorn;at she knewe her neuere &thorn;e more</L>
<L>I wil no lenger tarien in &thorn;is cas</L>
<L N="984">But to kinge Alla which I spake of yore</L>
<L>&THORN;at for his wiff wepe&thorn; and sighe&thorn; sore</L>
<L>I wil retorne and lete I wil Custance</L>
<L N="987">Vnder &thorn;e Senatours gouernaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Kynge Alla which &thorn;at had his modere sclayn</L>
<L>Vpon a day felle in such repentaunce</L>
<L>&thorn;at if I shortely tellen shal and playn</L>
<L N="991">To Rome he comme&thorn; to resceyuen his penance</L>
<L>And putte him in &thorn;e Popes ordinance</L>
<L>In by and lowe and Ihesu crist bysou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="994">ffor&yogh;eue his wicked werkes &thorn;at he wrou&yogh;t</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The fame anon &thorn;orowe Room toune is born</L>
<L>How Alla &thorn;e king shal commen in pilgrimage</L>
<L>By herberiours &thorn;at wenten hym biforn</L>
<L N="998">ffor which &thorn;e Senatoure as was vsage</L>
<L>Rode hym a&yogh;ein and mony of his lynage</L>
<L>As wel to shewen his hie magnificence<MILESTONE N="100b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1001">As to doon eny king a Reuerence</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Grete chere do&thorn; &thorn;is noble Senatour</L>
<L>To kinge Alla and he to hym also</L>
<L>Euerech of hem do&thorn; o&thorn;ere grete honour</L>
<L N="1005">And so byfelle &thorn;at in a day or twoo
<PB REF="00000241.tif" N="211"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="162"></L>
<L>This Senatour is to king Alla goo /</L>
<L>To feest and shortely if I shal not ly</L>
<L N="1008">Custance sone in his Companye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Somme men wold seyn atte request of Custance</L>
<L>This Senatour ha&thorn; ladde &thorn;is child to fest</L>
<L>I may not tellen euery Circumstance</L>
<L N="1012">Be as be may &thorn;er was he atte leest</L>
<L>But so&thorn;e is &thorn;is &thorn;at at his moders hest</L>
<L>Byforn alla duringe &thorn;e metes space</L>
<L N="1015">The Childe stode loking in &thorn;e kingges face</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This Alla kinge ha&thorn; of &thorn;e child gret wonder</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e Senatoure he seide anoon</L>
<L>Whoos is &thorn;at faire childe &thorn;at stonde&thorn; &yogh;onder</L>
<L N="1019">I noot quod he by god and be seynt Iohn</L>
<L>A modere he ha&thorn; but fadere ha&thorn; he non</L>
<L>&thorn;at I of wote and shortly in a stounde</L>
<L N="1022">He told Alla how &thorn;at &thorn;is child was founde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But god wote quod &thorn;is Senatour also</L>
<L>So vertuous a lyuere in my liff</L>
<L>Ne segh I neuere as she ne herd of mo</L>
<L N="1026">Of worldly wommen / mayde ne wiff</L>
<L>I dar wel seide she had leuer a knyff</L>
<L>&thorn;orowe-out her brest &thorn;an bene a womman wicke</L>
<L N="1029">&thorn;er is no man cou&thorn;e bringe hire to &thorn;at prikke</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now was &thorn;is Childe as like vnto custance</L>
<L>As possible is a creature to be<MILESTONE N="101a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>This Alla ha&thorn; &thorn;e face in remembrance</L>
<L N="1033">Of Dame Custance and &thorn;eron mused he</L>
<L>If &thorn;at &thorn;e childes modere were ou&yogh;t she</L>
<L>&thorn;at is his wif and priuely he si&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1036">And spedde hym fro &thorn;e table &thorn;at he my&yogh;t
<PB REF="00000242.tif" N="212"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="163"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Perfay he &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;e fantom is in myn hede</L>
<L>I ou&yogh;t demen of skilful Iuggement</L>
<L>That in &thorn;e salt se my wif is dede</L>
<L N="1040">And afterward he made his argument</L>
<L>What wote I &yogh;if &thorn;at crist ha&thorn; hider sent</L>
<L>My wiff by see as wel as he her sent</L>
<L N="1043">To my cuntre from &thorn;ennes as she was went</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And aftere anoon home wi&thorn; &thorn;e Senatoure</L>
<L>Go&thorn; alla forto see &thorn;is wonder chance</L>
<L>This Senatour do&thorn; Alla grete honoure</L>
<L N="1047">And hastifly he sent aftere Custance</L>
<L>But truste&thorn; wel her lust nou&yogh;t to dance</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at she wist wherfor was &thorn;at sonde</L>
<L N="1050">Vnne&thorn;es on her fete she my&yogh;t stonde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan Alla segh his wif faire he her grette</L>
<L>And wepte it was reu&thorn;e forto see</L>
<L>ffor atte first loke he on hir sette</L>
<L N="1054">He knewe wel verrely &thorn;at it was she</L>
<L>And for sorowe as dombe stant as a tre</L>
<L>So was hert shette in her distresse</L>
<L N="1057">Whan she remembred his vnkindenesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Twise she swowne&thorn; in his owne si&yogh;t</L>
<L>He wepte and him excuse&thorn; pitously</L>
<L>Nowe god quod he and his halowes bri&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1061">So wisly on my soule haue mercy</L>
<L>&thorn;at of &yogh;oure harme as giltelees am I</L>
<L>As is Maurice Mi sone so lik &yogh;oure face<MILESTONE N="101b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1064">Ellis &thorn;e feend me fecche out of &thorn;is place</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Longe was &thorn;e sobbyng and &thorn;e bitter peyne</L>
<L>Er &thorn;at her wooful hertes my&yogh;ten cese</L>
<L>Grete was &thorn;e pite forto here hem pleyne</L>
<L N="1068">&thorn;orgh whiche pleyntes gan her woo encrees
<PB REF="00000243.tif" N="213"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="164"></L>
<L>I prei &yogh;ou all my labour to relees</L>
<L>I may not tellen her woo vntil to morowe</L>
<L N="1071">I am so wery to speke of her sorowe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But fynaly whan &thorn;at &thorn;e so&thorn;e is wist</L>
<L>That Alla giltlees was of her woo</L>
<L>I trowe an C. tymes ben &thorn;ei kist</L>
<L N="1075">And suche a blisse is &thorn;er ytwix hem twoo</L>
<L>&thorn;at saue &thorn;e Ioie &thorn;at leste&thorn; euermoo</L>
<L>&thorn;er is non like &thorn;at eny creature</L>
<L N="1078">Ha&thorn; seyne or shal while &thorn;e world may dure</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Tho preied she her husbond mekely</L>
<L>In relief of her longe pitous pyne</L>
<L>&thorn;at he wolde prei hure fadere specialy</L>
<L N="1082">&thorn;at of his maieste he wold enclyne</L>
<L>To vouche sauf with him som day to dyne</L>
<L>She preied him eke he shulde by no way</L>
<L N="1085">vnto her fader no word of hire say</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Somme men wold seyn how &thorn;at &thorn;e childe Maurice</L>
<L>Do&thorn; &thorn;is massage vnto &thorn;e Emperour</L>
<L>But as I gesse alla was not so nyce</L>
<L N="1089">To him &thorn;at was of so souereyn honour</L>
<L>As he &thorn;at is of cristen folk &thorn;e flour</L>
<L>Sent eny childe but it is bette to deme</L>
<L N="1092">He went him self and so it may wel seme</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This Emperour ha&thorn; graunted gentilly</L>
<L>To come to dyner as he hym bysou&yogh;t<MILESTONE N="102a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And wel rede I he loked bisily</L>
<L N="1096">Vpon &thorn;is child and on his dou&yogh;ter &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Alla go&thorn; to his Inne and as hym ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Arraied for &thorn;is feest in euery wise</L>
<L N="1099">As ferfor&thorn; as his conyng may suffice
<PB REF="00000244.tif" N="214"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="165"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The morowe come and Alla can hym dresse</L>
<L>And eke his wif &thorn;is emperour forto mete</L>
<L>And for&thorn; &thorn;ei ride in Ioie and in gladnesse</L>
<L N="1103">And whan she segh her fadere in &thorn;e strete</L>
<L>She li&yogh;t a-doune and falle&thorn; hym to fete</L>
<L>ffadere quod she &yogh;oure &yogh;onge child Custance</L>
<L N="1106">Is nowe ful clene out of &yogh;oure remembrance</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I am &yogh;oure dou&yogh;tere Custance quod she</L>
<L>&thorn;at whilom &yogh;e sent vnto Surray</L>
<L>It am I fadere &thorn;at in &thorn;e salt see</L>
<L N="1110">Was putte allone and dampned forto dye</L>
<L>Good fader now I yow mercye crye</L>
<L>Send me no more vnto noon he&thorn;enes</L>
<L N="1113">But &thorn;onke my lord here of his kindenes</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Who can &thorn;e pitous Ioye tellen alle</L>
<L>Bitwixe hem &thorn;re si&thorn; &thorn;ei ben &thorn;us ymette</L>
<L>But of my tale make an ende I shal</L>
<L N="1117">The day go&thorn; fast I wil no lenger lette</L>
<L>This glad folk to dyner &thorn;ei hem sette</L>
<L>In Ioye and blisse at mete I lat hem dwelle</L>
<L N="1120">A &thorn;ousand fold wel more &thorn;an I can telle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This child Maurice was si&thorn;en Emperour</L>
<L>Made by &thorn;e pope and lyued cristenly</L>
<L>To cristes churche he did grete honour</L>
<L N="1124">But I lat al &thorn;is story passen by</L>
<L>Of Custance is my tale specialy</L>
<L>In olde romayn Gestes may men fynde<MILESTONE N="102b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; A mane vsque ad vesperam mutabitur tempus. tenent tympanum &amp; gaudent ad sonum organi.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mawrices lif I bere it not in mynde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This king Alla whan he his tyme say</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Custance his holy wif so swete</L>
<L>To Engelond ben &thorn;ei come &thorn;e ri&yogh;t way</L>
<L N="1131">Wher as &thorn;ei lyve in Ioie and in quiete
<PB REF="00000245.tif" N="215"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="166"></L>
<L>But litel while it laste&thorn; I &yogh;ou hete</L>
<L>Ioie of &thorn;is world for tyme wil not abide</L>
<L N="1134">ffrom day to ny&yogh;t it chaunge&thorn; as &thorn;e tyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Who lyued euere in suche delite a day<NOTE PLACE="marg">Quis vnquam vnicam diem totam duxit in sua delecta|cione iocundam quem in aliqua parte die reatus consciencie vel im|petus ire vel motus concupiscencie inde non turbauerit quem liuor invidie vel ardor auaricie vel timor superbie non vexauerit. quem aliqua iactura vel offensa vel passio non commouerit &amp; cetera.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at ne meued ei&thorn;er conscience</L>
<L>Or Ire or talent or somkyn affray</L>
<L N="1138">Envie or pride. or passion or offence</L>
<L>I ne seie but for &thorn;is ende &thorn;is sentence</L>
<L>&THORN;at litel while in Ioye or in plesaunce</L>
<L N="1141">Laste&thorn; &thorn;e blisse of alla wi&thorn; Custaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For de&thorn; &thorn;at take&thorn; of high and lough his rente</L>
<L>Whan passed was a &yogh;eer euene as I gesse</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is world &thorn;is kinge alla he hente</L>
<L N="1145">ffor whoom Custance ha&thorn; ful grete hevynesse</L>
<L>Now lat vs preien god his saule blisse</L>
<L>And Dame Custance fynally to seye</L>
<L N="1148">Toward &thorn;e towne of Rome go&thorn; her weye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>TO Rome is come &thorn;is holy creature</L>
<L>And fynde&thorn; her frende hool and sound</L>
<L>Now is she scaped all hure auenture</L>
<L N="1152">And whan she her fadere ha&thorn; yfounde</L>
<L>Doune on her knees falle&thorn; she to grounde</L>
<L>Weping for tendernesse in hert blith</L>
<L N="1155">She herie&thorn; God an C. thousand si&thorn;e</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In vertue and holy Almesdede</L>
<L>&thorn;ei lyuen all and neuere a sondrie wende<MILESTONE N="103a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Til de&thorn; departe hem &thorn;is lif &thorn;ei lede</L>
<L N="1159">And fare&thorn; now wel my tale is at an ende</L>
<L>Now Ihesu crist &thorn;at of his my&yogh;t may sende</L>
<L>Ioye after woo gouerne vs in his grace</L>
<L N="1162">And kepe vs all &thorn;at ben in &thorn;is place</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER><B>&para; Here ende&thorn; &thorn;e tale of &thorn;e man of lawe</B><NOTE>[<I>The Squire's Prologue follows in the MS.</I>]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000246.tif" N="216">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="167">
<HEAD>And here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e sqwiere<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 103</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Oure hoost vpon his stiropes stood anon<NOTE PLACE="marg">&Verbar; &thorn;e prologe</NOTE></L>
<L>And seide good men herkene&thorn; euerychon</L>
<L>This was a &thorn;rifty tale for &thorn;e nones</L>
<L N="1166">Sire parissh preest quod he for goddes bonys</L>
<L>Telle vs a tale as was &thorn;i forward yore</L>
<L>I se wele pat &yogh;e leerned men in lore</L>
<L>Can moche good by goddes dignyte</L>
<L N="1170">&thorn;e Parsone hym answered benedicite</L>
<L>What eile&thorn; &thorn;e man so synfully to swere</L>
<L>Oure hoost answerd O Iankyn be &yogh;e &thorn;ere</L>
<L>I smelle a lollard in &thorn;e wynde quod he</L>
<L N="1174">Howe good men quod our hoost herkne&thorn; me</L>
<L>Abide&thorn; for goddis digne passion</L>
<L>ffor we shal haue a predicacion</L>
<L>&thorn;is lollard here wil prechen vs somwhat</L>
<L N="1178">Nay by my fader soule &thorn;at shal he nat</L>
<L>Seide &thorn;e Sqwier here shal he nat preche</L>
<L>He shal no gospel glosen here ne teche</L>
<L>He leue&thorn; al in &thorn;e grete god he</L>
<L N="1182">He wolde sowen som difficulte</L>
<L>Or springell Cokel in oure clene corn</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore hoost I warne &thorn;e byforn</L>
<L>Mi Ioly body shal a tale telle</L>
<L N="1186">And I shal Clynken &yogh;ou so mery a belle</L>
<L>&THORN;at I shal waken al &thorn;is companye</L>
<L>But it shal not bene of Philosophie</L>
<L>Ne Phislyas ne teermes queynt of lawe</L>
<L N="1190">&THORN;er is but litel latyn in my mawe<NOTE PLACE="end">[The Squire's Tale follows in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="F" TYPE="group">


<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000247.tif" N="217">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="479">
<HEAD>&para; The Sqwiers Tale.<MILESTONE N="103b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[headline]</NOTE></HEAD>
<HEAD>And here by|gynne&thorn; &thorn;e Sqwiers tale. /</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At Sarray in &thorn;e land of Tartarye<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; ffabula Armigeri</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;er dwelt a kyng &thorn;at werried Russye</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh which &thorn;er deyed mony a dughty man</L>
<L N="12">&thorn;is noble king was cleped Cambynskan</L>
<L>Which in his tyme was of so grete renoun</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;er nas nowhere in no regioun</L>
<L>So Excellent a lord in al &thorn;inge</L>
<L N="16">Hym lacked nou&yogh;t &thorn;at longed to a kynge</L>
<L>As of &thorn;e secte of which &thorn;at he was born</L>
<L>He kepte his lay to which &thorn;at he was sworn</L>
<L>And &thorn;erto he was hardy wise and riche</L>
<L N="20">And pitous and Iust alway ylich</L>
<L>Soo&thorn; of his worde benygne and honurable</L>
<L>Of his corage as ony centre stable<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; centrum circuli</NOTE></L>
<L>&yogh;ong fresshe and stronge in Armes desirous</L>
<L N="24">As eny bachilere in al his hous</L>
<L>A faire persone he was and fortunat</L>
<L>And kept alway so wel rial astat</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;er nas nawhere such a no&thorn;er man</L>
<L N="28">This noble kinge &thorn;is tartre Cambynskan</L>
<L>had two sones on Eltheta his wiff</L>
<L>Of which &thorn;e eldest hight Algarsiff</L>
<L>&thorn;at o&thorn;er was cleped Camballo</L>
<L N="32">A doughtere had &thorn;is wor&thorn;i kinge also</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;ongest was and hi&yogh;t Canace</L>
<L>But forto telle &yogh;ou al her beute</L>
<L>It li&thorn;e not in my tunge ne in my connynge</L>
<L N="36">I dar not vndertake so hye a &thorn;inge
<PB REF="00000248.tif" N="218"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="480"></L>
<L>Myn engelissh eke is insufficient</L>
<L>It most bene a ritther excellent</L>
<L>&thorn;at kou&thorn;e his colours longyng for &thorn;at arte</L>
<L N="40">If he shuld here discryve eny part</L>
<L>I am noon suche I most speke as I can</L>
<L>And so byfelle &thorn;at &thorn;is Cambynskan</L>
<L>Hath xx<SUP>ti</SUP> wyntere born his diademe<MILESTONE N="104a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="44">As he was wonte fro &yogh;ere to &yogh;ere I deme</L>
<L>He lete &thorn;e feest of his natiuite</L>
<L>Done Crien &thorn;orgh Sarray his Cite</L>
<L>&thorn;e last Idus of March after &thorn;e &yogh;ere</L>
<L N="48">Phebus &thorn;e sonne ful Iolyf was and clere</L>
<L>ffor he was nye his exaltacion</L>
<L>In Martes face and in his mancion</L>
<L>In Aries &thorn;e Colerik &thorn;e hote signe</L>
<L N="52">fful lusty was &thorn;e weder and benigne</L>
<L>ffor which &thorn;e fowles a&yogh;einst &thorn;e sonne shene</L>
<L>What for the seson and &thorn;e &yogh;onge grene</L>
<L>fful loude songe hir affeccions</L>
<L N="56">Hem semed han geten hem proteccions</L>
<L>A&yogh;einst &thorn;e swerd of wynter kene and cold</L>
<L>This Cambynskan of which I haue &yogh;ou told</L>
<L>In Rial vestement sitte vpon his des</L>
<L N="60">Wi&thorn; dia[de]me ful high in his paleys</L>
<L>And halt his feest so solempne and so riche</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;is world ne was &thorn;er non it liche</L>
<L>Of which if I sal telle al &thorn;e araye</L>
<L N="64">Than wold it occupie a somers daye</L>
<L>And eke it nede&thorn; nat to devise</L>
<L>And euery cours &thorn;e order of her seruise</L>
<L>I wil not telle of her strange sewes</L>
<L N="68">Ne of her swannes ne her heron-sewes</L>
<L>Eke in &thorn;at londe as tellen kny&yogh;tes olde</L>
<L>There is som mete &thorn;at is for deynte holde</L>
<L>That in &thorn;is londe men recche but small</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;er nys no man &thorn;at may reporten all
<PB REF="00000249.tif" N="219"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="481"></L>
<L>I wil not tary &yogh;ou for it is pryme</L>
<L>And for it is no frute but losse of tyme</L>
<L>Vnto my furst I wil haue my recours</L>
<L N="76">And so byfell &thorn;at after &thorn;e &thorn;red recours</L>
<L>Whil &thorn;at &thorn;is kinge sitte &thorn;us in his nobleye</L>
<L>Herkenyng his menstralles her &thorn;ingges pleye</L>
<L>Byforn him at &thorn;e boord deliciously<MILESTONE N="104b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="80">Inne atte halle door so sodeynly</L>
<L>Ther come a knyght vpon a stede of bras</L>
<L>And in his honde a brood myrour of glas</L>
<L>Vpon his &thorn;ombe he had of gold a rynge</L>
<L N="84">And by his side a naked swerd hangynge</L>
<L>And vp he ride&thorn; to &thorn;e heigh boord</L>
<L>In al &thorn;e halle ne was &thorn;er spoke no word</L>
<L>ffor merveile of &thorn;is knyght hym to biholde</L>
<L N="88">fful bisily &thorn;ei wayten &yogh;onge and olde</L>
<L>This stronge knyght &thorn;at come &thorn;us sodeynly</L>
<L>Al armed saue his hede ful richely</L>
<L>Salued &thorn;e king &thorn;e quene and lordes alle</L>
<L N="92">By ordere as &thorn;ei seten in &thorn;e halle</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; so high reuerence and obeysance</L>
<L>As wel in speche as in his countenance</L>
<L>&thorn;at Gawayne wi&thorn; his olde curtasie</L>
<L N="96">&thorn;ou&yogh;e he come ageyn out of ffarye</L>
<L>Ne coude him nou&yogh;t amende with no word</L>
<L>And after &thorn;is bifore &thorn;e highe bord</L>
<L>He wi&thorn; a manly vois saide his massage</L>
<L N="100">After &thorn;e forme vsed in his langage</L>
<L>With-out vice of sillable or of lettre</L>
<L>And for his tale shulde seme &thorn;e bettere</L>
<L>Accordant to his wordes was his chere</L>
<L N="104">As teche&thorn; arte of speche hem &thorn;at it lere</L>
<L>Al be it &thorn;at I can not sowne his styele</L>
<L>Ne can not clymben ouer so hi&yogh;e a styele</L>
<L>&YOGH;it say I &thorn;is &thorn;at as to comune entente</L>
<L N="108">Thus moche amounte&thorn; al &thorn;at euere he ment
<PB REF="00000250.tif" N="220"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="482"></L>
<L>If it so be &thorn;at I haue it in my mynde</L>
<L>He seide &thorn;e kynge of Arabye and of ynde</L>
<L>My liege lord on &thorn;is solempne day</L>
<L N="112">Salwe&thorn; &yogh;ou as he best can and may</L>
<L>And seende&thorn; &yogh;owe in honur of &yogh;our feste</L>
<L>By me &thorn;at am redy al at &yogh;oure heeste</L>
<L>This stede of bras &thorn;at esily &amp; well<MILESTONE N="105a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="116">Can in a space of a day naturel</L>
<L>This is to saye in <I>four and twenti</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS xxiiij.]</NOTE> houres</L>
<L>Wher so &yogh;ou lust in drou&yogh;t or in shoures</L>
<L>Beren &yogh;oure body in to euery place</L>
<L N="120">To which &yogh;oure hertes wilne&thorn; forto pace</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-oute wemme of &yogh;ou &thorn;orow foule or fare</L>
<L>Or if &yogh;ow list to flee as hie in &thorn;e Eire</L>
<L>As do&thorn; an Egle whan him list to sore</L>
<L N="124">This same stede shal bere &yogh;ou euermore</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen harme til &yogh;e be where &yogh;ou list</L>
<L>&thorn;ow &thorn;at &yogh;e sclepen on his bak or rest</L>
<L>And turne a&yogh;ein wi&thorn; wri&thorn;ing of a pynne</L>
<L N="128">He &thorn;at it wrou&yogh;t cowde ful mony a gynne</L>
<L>He waited mony a constellacion</L>
<L>Or he had doo &thorn;is operaci&omacr;n</L>
<L>And knewe ful mony a seal and mony a bonde</L>
<L N="132">This myroure eke &thorn;at I haue in myn honde</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; suche a my&yogh;t &thorn;at men may in it see</L>
<L>whan &thorn;er shal fallen eny aduersite</L>
<L>Vnto &yogh;our regne or vnto &yogh;our self also</L>
<L N="136">And openly who is &yogh;oure freend or ffoo /</L>
<L>And ouer al &thorn;is if eny lady bri&yogh;t</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; sette her hert in eny maner wi&yogh;t</L>
<L>If he be fals she shal his treson see</L>
<L N="140">His newe loues and al his subtilite</L>
<L>So openly &thorn;at &thorn;er shal no &thorn;ing hide</L>
<L>wherfore ageyn &thorn;is lusty somers tyde</L>
<L>This myrour and &thorn;is ryng &thorn;at &yogh;e may see</L>
<L N="144">He ha&thorn; sent to my lady Canacee
<PB REF="00000251.tif" N="221"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="483"></L>
<L>&yogh;oure excellent dou&yogh;tere &thorn;at is here</L>
<L>&thorn;e vertue of &thorn;is rynge if &yogh;e wil here</L>
<L>Is &thorn;is; &thorn;at if her list it forto were</L>
<L N="148">Vpon her thombe or in her purs it bere</L>
<L>&thorn;er nys no fowle &thorn;at flee&thorn; vnder &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> heuene</L>
<L>&thorn;at he ne shal vnderstond his steuene</L>
<L>And knowe his menyng openly and pleyne<MILESTONE N="105b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="152">And answere him in his langage ageyne</L>
<L>And euery gras &thorn;at growe&thorn; vpon rote</L>
<L>She shal wel knowe and whome it wil do bote</L>
<L>And be his woundes neuere so depe and wide/</L>
<L N="156">This naked swerd &thorn;at honge&thorn; by my side</L>
<L>Such vertue ha&thorn; &thorn;at what man so &yogh;e smyte</L>
<L>&thorn;orowe-out his armure it wil kerue and bite</L>
<L>were it as thikke as is a braunched oke</L>
<L N="160">And what man &thorn;at is wounded with &thorn;e stroke</L>
<L>Shal neuere be hool til &thorn;at &yogh;ou list of grace</L>
<L>To stroke him with &thorn;e plat in &thorn;ilk place</L>
<L>Ther he is hirt &thorn;is is as moche to seyn</L>
<L N="164">&yogh;e mote with &thorn;e plat swerde ageyn</L>
<L>Stroke hym in the wounde and it wil close</L>
<L>This is a verrey so&thorn;e wi&thorn;-outen glose</L>
<L>It faille&thorn; nou&yogh;t &thorn;e whilis it is in &yogh;our holde</L>
<L N="168">And whan &thorn;is kny&yogh;t ha&thorn; &thorn;us &thorn;is tale tolde</L>
<L>He ride&thorn; out of &thorn;e halle and doun he li&yogh;t</L>
<L>His stede which &thorn;at shoon as sonne bri&yogh;t</L>
<L>Stant in &thorn;e courte stille as eny stoon</L>
<L N="172">This knyght is to his chambre lad an&omacr;on</L>
<L>And is vnarmed and to &thorn;e mete I-sette</L>
<L>&thorn;e presentes bene ful richely fette</L>
<L>This is to seyn &thorn;e swerd and &thorn;e Mirrour</L>
<L N="176">And born anoon vnto &thorn;e hie toure</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; certeyn officers yordeyned &thorn;erfore</L>
<L>And vnto Canacee &thorn;e ryng is bore</L>
<L>Solempnely &thorn;er she sitte atte &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> table</L>
<L N="180">But sikerly wi&thorn;-oute eny fable
<PB REF="00000252.tif" N="222"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="484"></L>
<L>&thorn;e hors of bras &thorn;at may not be remewed</L>
<L>It stant as it were to &thorn;e grounde yglwed /</L>
<L>&thorn;er may no man out of &thorn;e place it drive</L>
<L N="184">ffor noon engyn of wyndas or polyve</L>
<L>And cause whi for &thorn;ei can not &thorn;e craft</L>
