<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The norice of digestion is sclepe</L>
<L N="348">Gan on hem wynke and bad hem take kepe</L>
<L>&thorn;at moch mete and labour wil haue rest</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; a galping mou&thorn;e hem albycast</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;at it was tyme to lye adoune</L>
<L N="352">ffor blood was in his domynacioun</L>
<L>Cheresshe&thorn; blood natures frende quod he</L>
<L>&thorn;ei &thorn;onken hym galping by two or &thorn;re</L>
<L>And euery wight gan drowen hym to his rest</L>
<L N="356">As sclepe hem bad &thorn;ei toke it for &thorn;e best
<PB REF="00000257.tif" N="227"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="489"></L>
<L>Her dremes mow not be tolde for me</L>
<L>fful were her hedes of ffumosite</L>
<L>&thorn;at causet dreem of which &thorn;er is no charge</L>
<L N="360">&thorn;ei sclepen til it was pryme large</L>
<L>&thorn;e moste parte but it were Canacee</L>
<L>She was ful mesurable as wommen be</L>
<L>ffor of her fadere had she take her leue</L>
<L N="364">To goo to rest sone after it was Eue</L>
<L>Her list not appalled forto be<MILESTONE N="108b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor on &thorn;e morowe vnfeestlich forto see</L>
<L>And sclepte hure first sclepe and awoke</L>
<L N="368">ffor such a Ioie she in her herte toke</L>
<L>Bo&thorn; of her queynt rynge and of her myrour</L>
<L>&thorn;at xx<SUP>ti</SUP> tyme she chaunged her colour</L>
<L>And in her sclepe ri&yogh;t for impression</L>
<L N="372">Of her myrour she had a vision</L>
<L>wherfore er &thorn;at &thorn;e sonne vp gan glide</L>
<L>She cleped vpon her maistresse here beside</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;at hir list forto arise</L>
<L N="376">&thorn;ise olde wommen &thorn;at bene gladly wise</L>
<L>As is her maistresse answerd hir an&omacr;n</L>
<L>And seide Madame whidere wold &yogh;e g&omacr;n</L>
<L>&thorn;us erly for folke bene al in rest</L>
<L N="380">I wil quod she arise for me lest</L>
<L>No lenger slepen but walken aboute</L>
<L>Her Maistresse clepe&thorn; wommen a grete route</L>
<L>And vp &thorn;ei risen wel . ten or twelue</L>
<L N="384">Vprise&thorn; fresshe Canace her selue</L>
<L>As roddy and bri&yogh;t as &thorn;ei &thorn;e &yogh;onge sonne</L>
<L>&thorn;at in &thorn;e Ram is ten degrees vp ronne</L>
<L>Noon hier was he whan she redy was</L>
<L N="388">And for&thorn; she walked esily a pas</L>
<L>Arraied aftere &thorn;e lusty seson sote</L>
<L>li&yogh;tly forto prey and walk on fote</L>
<L>Nat but .v. or .vj. of her mayne</L>
<L N="392">And in a trenche fer in &thorn;e park/ goo&thorn; she
<PB REF="00000258.tif" N="228"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="490"></L>
<L>The vapour which &thorn;at fro &thorn;e erthe glode</L>
<L>Make&thorn; &thorn;e sonne to seme rody and brode</L>
<L>But na&thorn;elees it was so faire a si&yogh;t</L>
<L N="396">&THORN;at it made all her hertes forto li&yogh;t</L>
<L>What for &thorn;e seson and &thorn;e mowrnynge</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e fowles &thorn;at she herde synge</L>
<L>ffor ri&yogh;t anoon she wist what &thorn;ei ment</L>
<L N="400">Ri&yogh;t by her songe and knewe al her entent</L>
<L>&para; The knotte whi &thorn;at euery tale is told<MILESTONE N="109a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&yogh;if it be taried til lust be cold</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at han it herkened after &yogh;ore</L>
<L N="404">&THORN;e Sauour passe&thorn; euer lenger &thorn;e more</L>
<L>ffor ffulsomnesse of prolixite</L>
<L>And by &thorn;is same reson &thorn;enke&thorn; me</L>
<L>I shuld vnto &thorn;e knotte condescende</L>
<L N="408">And maken of her walking sone an ende</L>
<L>&para; Amydde a tree for-drye as white as chalke</L>
<L>As Canacee was plaiyng in her walke</L>
<L>&thorn;er satte a fawcon ouer her hede ful hie</L>
<L N="412">&thorn;at wi&thorn; a pitous vois so gan to crie</L>
<L>&thorn;at alle in &thorn;e wode resed of her crie</L>
<L>And beten had her self so pitously</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; bothe her wenges to &thorn;e rede blode</L>
<L N="416">Ranne endelonge &thorn;e tre &thorn;er as she stode</L>
<L>And euer in oon she cried alway and shright</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; her beke her seluen so she pi&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;er ne was Tigre ne cruel beest</L>
<L N="420">&thorn;at dwelle&thorn; ei&thorn;er in wode or in forest</L>
<L>&thorn;at ne wold haue wepte if &thorn;at she wepe cou&thorn;e</L>
<L>ffor sorowe of hir she shright alway so lou&thorn;e</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;er nas neuere &yogh;it man on lyue</L>
<L N="424">If &thorn;at I coude a fawcon wel discryve</L>
<L>&thorn;at herd of such ano&thorn;er of fairnesse</L>
<L>As wel of plummage as of gentilnesse</L>
<L>Of shappe of al &thorn;at my&yogh;t rekned be</L>
<L N="428">A fsawcon peregryne &thorn;an semed she .
<PB REF="00000259.tif" N="229"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="491"></L>
<L>Of fremde londe and eueremore as she stode</L>
<L>She swowned nowe and nowe for lakke of blood</L>
<L>Til wel nygh is she fallen fro &thorn;e tre</L>
<L N="432">This faire kyngges doughter &thorn;is Canace</L>
<L>&thorn;at on her fynger bere &thorn;e queynte rynge</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh which she vnderstode wel euery &thorn;inge</L>
<L>&thorn;at eny foule may in his ledne seyne</L>
<L N="436">And coude answere him in his ledne ageyne</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; vnderstonde &thorn;at &thorn;is fawcon seide<MILESTONE N="109b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And wel nygh for &thorn;e rou&thorn;e almest she deide</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e tree she go&thorn; ful hastely</L>
<L N="440">And on &thorn;is faucon loke&thorn; ful pitously</L>
<L>And helde her lappe abrood for wel she wist</L>
<L>&thorn;e faucon most falle from &thorn;e twist</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at it swouned next for lacke of blode</L>
<L N="444">A longe while to waite her she stode</L>
<L>Til atte last she spake in &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e hawke as &yogh;e shal after here</L>
<L>&para; What is &thorn;e cause if it be forto telle</L>
<L N="448">&thorn;at &yogh;e bene in &thorn;is furial peyn of helle</L>
<L>Quod Canacee vnto &thorn;is hawke aboue</L>
<L>Is &thorn;is for sorowe of deth or losse of loue</L>
<L>ffor as I trowe &thorn;ise bene causes two</L>
<L N="452">&THORN;an causen most a gentil hert woo /</L>
<L>Of other harme it nede&thorn; not to speke</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;i &yogh;oure self vpon youre self &yogh;ou wreke</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at proueth wel &thorn;at ei&thorn;ere ire or drede</L>
<L N="456">Mote bene encheson of &yogh;oure cruel dede</L>
<L>Si&thorn; &thorn;at I see noon o&thorn;er wi&yogh;t &yogh;ou chace</L>
<L>ffor loue of god so do&thorn; &yogh;our self grace</L>
<L>Or what may be &yogh;oure helpe for west nor este</L>
<L N="460">Ne seghe I neuere er nowe ne brid ne beste</L>
<L>&thorn;at ferde wi&thorn; him self so pitously</L>
<L>&yogh;e sclee me wi&thorn; &yogh;oure sorowe verreyly</L>
<L>I haue of &yogh;ou so grete compassioun</L>
<L N="464">ffor goddes loue come fro &thorn;e tree adoun
<PB REF="00000260.tif" N="230"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="492"></L>
<L>And as I am a kingges dou&yogh;thter trewe</L>
<L>If &thorn;at I verrely &thorn;e causes knewe</L>
<L>Of &yogh;oure dis[e]se if it lay in my my&yogh;t</L>
<L N="468">I wold amende it er &thorn;at it were ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>As wisly helpe me grete god of kinde</L>
<L>And Erbes shal I ri&yogh;t ynow fynde</L>
<L>To hele wi&thorn; &yogh;oure hirtes hastely</L>
<L N="472">&thorn;oo shright &thorn;is fawcon &yogh;it more pitously</L>
<L>&thorn;an euere she did and fille to grounde an&omacr;n<MILESTONE N="110a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And lith a swowne dede as is &thorn;e ston</L>
<L>Til Canacee ha&thorn; in hure lappe her take</L>
<L N="476">Vnto &thorn;at tyme she gan of swowne awake</L>
<L>And after &thorn;at she of swowne gan vpbreide</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t in hire hawkes leodene &thorn;us she seide</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;at pite renne&thorn; sone in gentil herte</L>
<L N="480">ffeling his symilitude in peynes smerte</L>
<L>Is proued alday as men may it see</L>
<L>As wel be werk as be auctorite</L>
<L>ffor gentil hert kepe&thorn; gentillesse</L>
<L N="484">I se wele &thorn;at &yogh;e han on my distresse</L>
<L>Compassion my faire Canacee</L>
<L>Of verrey wommanly benignyte</L>
<L>That nature in &yogh;oure principles ha&thorn; sette</L>
<L N="488">But for noon hope forto fare &thorn;e bette</L>
<L>But forto obeye vnto &yogh;oure herte free</L>
<L>And forto maken o&thorn;er be ware by me</L>
<L>As by &thorn;e whelpe chastised is the ly&omacr;n</L>
<L N="492">Ri&yogh;t for &thorn;at cause and for &thorn;at conclusion</L>
<L>While &thorn;at I haue a leisere and a space</L>
<L>Myn harme I wil confessen er I pace</L>
<L>And euere while &thorn;at she her sorowe told</L>
<L N="496">&thorn;at o&thorn;er wepte as she to water wold</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at &thorn;e ffaucon bad hir to be stille</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; a sighe &thorn;us she seide hir tille</L>
<L>Ther I was bredde allas &thorn;at ilk daye</L>
<L N="500">And fostred in a roche of Merbel graye
<PB REF="00000261.tif" N="231"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="493"></L>
<L>So tenderly &thorn;at no &thorn;ing eiled me</L>
<L>I ne wist not what was aduersite</L>
<L>Til I coude flee ful hie vndere &thorn;e skie</L>
<L N="504">Tho dwelled a tercelet me fast by</L>
<L>&thorn;at semed welle of al gentilnesse</L>
<L>Al were he ful of treson and falsnesse</L>
<L>It is wrapped vnder humble chere</L>
<L N="508">And vnder hwe of trou&thorn;e &amp; in such manere ./</L>
<L>Vndere plesaunce and vnder bisy peyne<MILESTONE N="110b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;at no wight cou&thorn;e han wende he coude feyne</L>
<L>So depe in greyne he dyed his coloures /</L>
<L N="512">Ri&yogh;t as a serpent hyd hym vnder floures</L>
<L>Til he may se his tyme forto bite</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t so &thorn;is god of loue ypocrite</L>
<L>Do&thorn; so his serymonijs and obeysances</L>
<L N="516">And kepe&thorn; in semblaunt al his obseruaunces /</L>
<L>That sowne&thorn;e into gentilnesse of loue</L>
<L>As in a tompe is al &thorn;e faire aboue</L>
<L>And vnder is &thorn;e cours which as &yogh;e wote</L>
<L N="520">Such was &thorn;is ypocrite bo&thorn; colde and hote</L>
<L>And in &thorn;is wise he serued his entente</L>
<L>&thorn;at saue &thorn;e feende non wist what he mente</L>
<L>Til he so longe had wepte and compleyned</L>
<L N="524">And many a &yogh;eer his servise to hym feyned</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at myn hert to pitous and to nyce</L>
<L>Al Innocent of his crowned malice</L>
<L>ffor-ferde of his de&thorn; as &thorn;ou&yogh;t me</L>
<L N="528">Vpon his o&thorn;es and his Suerte</L>
<L>Graunted hym loue vpon &thorn;is condicioun</L>
<L>&thorn;at euer moo myn honure and my renoun</L>
<L>Were saued bo&thorn; privey and apert</L>
<L N="532">&thorn;is is to seyn &thorn;at after his dissert</L>
<L>I &yogh;aue hym al myn hert and my &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>God woot and he &thorn;at o&thorn;er wise nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And toke his hert in chaunge of myn for ay</L>
<L N="536">But so&thorn; is seide go si&thorn;en mony a day
<PB REF="00000262.tif" N="232"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="494"></L>
<L>A trewe wight and a &thorn;eef thenke&thorn; not o&omacr;n</L>
<L>And whan he sawe &thorn;e &thorn;ing so fer ygon</L>
<L>&thorn;at I [had] graunted hym fully my loue</L>
<L N="540">In such a gise as I haue seide aboue</L>
<L>An &yogh;euen hym my trewe hert as free</L>
<L>As he swore he &yogh;af his hert to me</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;is tigre ful of doublenesse</L>
<L N="544">ffil on his knees wi&thorn; so deuoute humblesse</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hye reuerence and as by his chere<MILESTONE N="111a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So like a gentile louere of manere</L>
<L>So rauisshed as it semed for &thorn;e Ioye</L>
<L N="548">&THORN;at neuere Iason ne Paris of Troye</L>
<L>Iason certes ne noon o&thorn;ere man</L>
<L>Si&thorn; Lame&thorn; was &thorn;at al&thorn;er furst biganne</L>
<L>To louen two as writen folk to-forne</L>
<L N="552">Ne neuere si&thorn; &thorn;e first man was born</L>
<L>Ne coude man by xx<SUP>ti</SUP> &thorn;ousand part</L>
<L>Countrefete &thorn;e sophymes of his arte</L>
<L>Ne were wor&thorn;i to vnbocle his galoche</L>
<L N="556">&THORN;er dowblenesse or faynyng shuld approche</L>
<L>Ne so cou&thorn;e &thorn;onke a wi&yogh;t as he did me</L>
<L>His manere was an heuene for to see</L>
<L>Til eny womman were she neuere his wys</L>
<L N="560">So peynted he and kembe&thorn; at poynt devis</L>
<L>As wel his wordes as his countenaunce</L>
<L>And I so loued hym for his obeysaunce</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e trou&thorn;e I demed in his hert</L>
<L N="564">&thorn;at if so were &thorn;at eny &thorn;inge hym smerte</L>
<L>Al were it neuere so lite and I it wist</L>
<L>Me &thorn;ou&yogh;t I felt de&thorn; at myn herte twiste</L>
<L>And shortely so ferfor&thorn; &thorn;is &thorn;inge wente</L>
<L N="568">&thorn;at my wille ha&thorn; his willes Instrument</L>
<L>&thorn;is is to seyne my wille obeied his wille</L>
<L>In al &thorn;inge as ferre as reson fille</L>
<L>Kepinge &thorn;e boundes of my worship euere</L>
<L N="572">Ne neuere had I &thorn;inge so leef ne leuere
<PB REF="00000263.tif" N="233"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="495"></L>
<L>As hym; god wote ne neuere shal no moo /</L>
<L>&thorn;is last lenger &thorn;an a &yogh;ere or twoo</L>
<L>&para; That I Suppose of hym no &thorn;ing but good</L>
<L N="576">But fynaly &thorn;us at the ende it stood</L>
<L>&thorn;at fortune wold &thorn;at he most twynne</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;at place which &thorn;at I was Inne</L>
<L>where me were woo it is no question</L>
<L N="580">I can not make of it discripcion</L>
<L>ffor oon &thorn;inge dar I telle boldely<MILESTONE N="111b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I knowe what is &thorn;e peyne of de&thorn; &thorn;erby;</L>
<L>Such harme I felt for he no wi&yogh;t by-leue</L>
<L N="584">So on a day of me he toke his leue</L>
<L>So sorowefulli eke &thorn;at I wende verrely</L>
<L>&thorn;at he had feled as moche harme as I</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at I herde hym speke and segh his hwe</L>
<L N="588">But na&thorn;elees I &thorn;ou&yogh;t he was so trewe</L>
<L>And eke &thorn;at he repeire shuld agayn/</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-Inne a litel while so&thorn; to sayn</L>
<L>And reson wold eke &thorn;at he most goo</L>
<L N="592">ffor his honoure as oft happe&thorn; soo</L>
<L>&THORN;at I made vertue of necessite</L>
<L>And toke it wel si&thorn; &thorn;at it most be</L>
<L>As I best myght I hid fro hym my sorowe</L>
<L N="596">And toke hym by &thorn;e honde seint Iohn to borowe</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;us loo I am &yogh;oures all</L>
<L>Be&thorn; swich as I haue be to you and shal</L>
<L>what he answerd it nede&thorn; not reherce</L>
<L N="600">who can seyn bette &thorn;an he who can do wors</L>
<L>whan he ha&thorn; al wel seide &thorn;an ha&thorn; he done</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore bihoue&thorn; hym a ful longe spone</L>
<L>&thorn;at shal eten with a feend &thorn;us herd I seye</L>
<L N="604">So at &thorn;e last he mote for&thorn; his weye</L>
<L>And for&thorn; he flee&thorn; til he come &thorn;er hym list</L>
<L>whan it come hym to purpoos for to rist</L>
<L>&para; I trowe he had &thorn;ilk texte in mynde<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Redditui suo sui gula gaudent /</NOTE></L>
<L N="608">&THORN;at al &thorn;inge repeiryng to his kinge
<PB REF="00000264.tif" N="234"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="496"></L>
<L>Glade&thorn; hym self &thorn;us seyn men as I gesse</L>
<L>Men louen of propre kinde newfangilnesse</L>
<L>As briddes doon &thorn;at men in cages fede</L>
<L N="612">ffor &thorn;eigh &thorn;ou ny&yogh;t and day take of hym hede</L>
<L>And strawe her cage faire and soft as silk</L>
<L>And &yogh;eue hem sugre . hony . brede and mylk</L>
<L>&YOGH;it right anoon as &thorn;at his door is vppe</L>
<L N="616">He wi&thorn; his feete wil spurne doun his cuppe</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e wode he wil and wormes ete<MILESTONE N="112a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So newfangle bene &thorn;ei of her mete</L>
<L>And louen nouelries of propre kinde</L>
<L N="620">No gentilnesse of blood may hem bynde</L>
<L>So ferde &thorn;is tercelet allas &thorn;e day</L>
<L>Thowe he were gentill born fressh and gay</L>
<L>And goodly forto sene . humble and free</L>
<L N="624">He segh vpon a tyme a kite fle</L>
<L>And sodeynly he loued &thorn;is kite soo</L>
<L>That al his loue is clene fro me goo</L>
<L>And ha&thorn; his trow&thorn;e falsed in &thorn;is wise</L>
<L N="628">Thus ha&thorn; &thorn;e kite my loue in her seruyse</L>
<L>And I am lorn with-outen remedye</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;at worde &thorn;is fawcon gan to crie</L>
<L>And swowned eft in Canaces barme</L>
<L N="632">Grete was &thorn;e sorowe for &thorn;at haukes harme</L>
<L>That Canacee and alle her wommen made</L>
<L>&THORN;ei nyst howe &thorn;at &thorn;ei my&yogh;t &thorn;e faucon glade</L>
<L>But Canace home bere&thorn; her in hir lappe</L>
<L N="636">And softely in plaasters gan hir wrappe</L>
<L>&THORN;er as she with hire beek had hurt her selue</L>
<L>Nowe can not Canace but herbes delue</L>
<L>Out of the grounde and maken salues newe</L>
<L N="640">Of herbes precious and fyne of hewe</L>
<L>To helen wi&thorn; &thorn;e hauke from day to ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>She do&thorn; her bysynesse and al her my&yogh;t</L>
<L>And by hire beddes hede she made a mewe</L>
<L N="644">And keuered it wi&thorn; veluetes blewe
<PB REF="00000265.tif" N="235"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="497"></L>
<L>In signe of trou&thorn;e &thorn;at is in wommen sene</L>
<L>And All wi&thorn;-oute &thorn;e mwee is peinted grene</L>
<L>In whiche were peynted all &thorn;ise fals foules</L>
<L N="648">As bene &thorn;ise tydifs . tercelettes and owles</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t for &thorn;e spite were peynted hem biside</L>
<L>Pies on hem forto crie and chide</L>
<L>&thorn;us lete I Canace her hauke kepinge</L>
<L N="652">I wil no more as nowe speke of her rynge</L>
<L>Til it come eft to purpoos forto seyn<MILESTONE N="112b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Howe &thorn;at &thorn;is faucon gate her loue ageyn</L>
<L>Repentaunt as &thorn;e story telle&thorn; vs</L>
<L N="656">By mediacion of Camballus</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyngges sone of which I &yogh;ou tolde</L>
<L>But hens for&thorn; I wil processe holde</L>
<L>To speken of auentures and of batailles</L>
<L N="660">That &yogh;it was neuere herde so grete merveiles</L>
<L>ffirst wil I telle &yogh;ou of Cambynskan</L>
<L>That in his tyme mony a Cite wan</L>
<L>And aftere wil I speke of algarsif</L>
<L N="664">How &thorn;at he wan Theodora to his wiff</L>
<L>ffor whan ful oft in grete perill he was</L>
<L>Ne had he bene holpen by &thorn;e hors of bras</L>
<L>And aftere wil I speke of Camballo</L>
<L N="668">&thorn;at faught in listes wi&thorn; &thorn;e bre&thorn;eren two</L>
<L>ffor Canace er &thorn;at he my&yogh;t hir wynne</L>
<L>And &thorn;er I left wil I ageyn bygynne<NOTE PLACE="inter">.i. sol.</NOTE></L>
<L>Apollo whirle&thorn; vp his chare so hie<NOTE PLACE="marg">va|cat</NOTE></L>
<L N="672">Til &thorn;at &thorn;e god Mercurius hous &thorn;e sclie</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Explicit secunda pars;</TRAILER>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>&para; Here ende&thorn; &thorn;e squyers tale</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000266.tif" N="236">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="498">
<HEAD>And here<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 112, <I>back</I></NOTE> bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> merchaunte.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In fei&thorn; Squier &thorn;ow hast &thorn;e wel yquytte</L>
<L>And gentely I preise wel &thorn;i witte</L>
<L>Quod &thorn;e merchaunt consideryng &thorn;i &yogh;ou&thorn;e</L>
<L N="676">So felingly &thorn;ou spekest sir I &thorn;e alou&thorn;e</L>
<L>As to my dome &thorn;er is non &thorn;at is here</L>
<L>Of Eloquence &thorn;at shal be &thorn;i pere</L>
<L>[And if &thorn;at &thorn;ow lyue god &yogh;if &thorn;e goode chaunce<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Barlow MS 20]</NOTE></L>
<L N="680">And in vertue sende the Contynaunce]</L>
<L>ffor of &thorn;i speche I haue gret deynte</L>
<L>I haue a sone and by &thorn;e trinite</L>
<L>I had leuere &thorn;an xx<SUP>ti</SUP> pounde wor&thorn; lond</L>
<L N="684">&thorn;ough it were ri&yogh;t nowe fallen in my hond</L>
<L>&YOGH;e ere a man of such discrecion</L>
<L>As &thorn;at &yogh;e ben fy on possession</L>
<L>But &yogh;if a man be uertuous withal</L>
<L N="688">I haue my sone snybbed and &yogh;it shal /</L>
<L>ffor he to vertue liste&thorn; not entende<MILESTONE N="113a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But forto pley atte dys and to dispende</L>
<L>And lese al &thorn;at he ha&thorn; is his vsage</L>
<L N="692">And he ha&thorn; leuere talke wi&thorn; a page</L>
<L>&THORN;an to comune wi&thorn; a gentile wi&yogh;t</L>
<L>where he my&yogh;t lerne gentillesse ari&yogh;t</L>
<L>A strawe for &yogh;oure gentilnesse quod our Hoost</L>
<L N="696">What Marchaunte parde Sir wel &thorn;ou woost</L>
<L>That ech of &yogh;ou mote tellen at &thorn;e leest</L>
<L>A tale or twoo or breken his bihest</L>
<L>That knowe I well quod &thorn;e Merchaunte certeyn</L>
<L N="700">I prey &yogh;ou haue&thorn; not me in disdeyne
<PB REF="00000267.tif" N="237"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="499"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh;e to &thorn;is man I speke a word or twoo</L>
<L>Telle on &thorn;i tale wi&thorn;-outen wordes moo /</L>
<L>Gladly sir ooste quod he I wil obeye</L>
<L N="704">Vnto &yogh;our wille now herkene&thorn; what I seye</L>
<L>I wil &yogh;ou not contrarye in no wise.</L>
<L>As ferre as my wittes wil suffise</L>
<L>I prey to god &thorn;at it may plesen &yogh;ou</L>
<L N="708">&thorn;an woot I wele &thorn;at it is good ynowe</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&thorn;us ende&thorn; &thorn;e prologe /</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="E" TYPE="group">


<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000268.tif" N="238">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="443">
<HEAD>And here by|gynne&thorn; &thorn;e Merchauntes tale.<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 113</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whilom &thorn;er was dwellinge in lumbardy<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; The tale.</NOTE></L>
<L>A wor&thorn;i kny&yogh;t &thorn;at born was at Pavy</L>
<L>In which he lyued in grete prosperite</L>
<L N="1248">And sixty &yogh;ere a wyuelees man was he</L>
<L>And folowed ay his bodely delite</L>
<L>On womman &thorn;er as was his Appetite</L>
<L>As doon &thorn;ise fooles &thorn;at bene seculers</L>
<L N="1252">And whan &thorn;at he was past sixty &yogh;eres</L>
<L>Were it for holynesse or ellis for dotage</L>
<L>I can not seye but suche a corage</L>
<L>had &thorn;is knyght to be a wedded man</L>
<L N="1256">That day and nyght he do&thorn; al &thorn;at he can</L>
<L>To aspie where he my&yogh;t wedded be</L>
<L>Preiynge our lord to graunt hym &thorn;at he /</L>
<L>Might ones knowe &thorn;at blisful liff<MILESTONE N="113b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1260">&thorn;at is bytwixe an husbonde and his wif</L>
<L>And for to lyuen vnder &thorn;at holy band</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; which god furste man to womman band</L>
<L>Noon o&thorn;er lif seide he is wor&thorn; a bene</L>
<L N="1264">ffor wedloke is so esi and so clene</L>
<L>That in &thorn;is world it is a paradys</L>
<L>Thus sei&thorn; &thorn;is olde kny&yogh;t &thorn;at was so wis</L>
<L>And certeynly as so&thorn; as god is kinge</L>
<L N="1268">To take a wif it is a glorious &thorn;inge</L>
<L>And namely whan a man is olde and hoore</L>
<L>&thorn;an is a wif &thorn;e frute of his tresore</L>
<L>&thorn;an shuld he take a &yogh;onge wif and a faire</L>
<L N="1272">On which he my&yogh;t engender him an aire
<PB REF="00000269.tif" N="239"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="444"></L>
<L>And lede his lif in Ioye and solace</L>
<L>Wher as &thorn;e bachilers synggen alas</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ei fynde eny aduersite</L>
<L N="1276">In loue which &thorn;at is but childes vanite</L>
<L>And trewly it sitte wel to be soo</L>
<L>That bachilers han ofte peyne and woo</L>
<L>On brutel grounde &thorn;ei beelde brutelnesse</L>
<L N="1280">&thorn;ei fynde whan &thorn;ei wene sikernesse</L>
<L>&thorn;ei lyue but as a bridde or a beest</L>
<L>In liberte and vnder nyce areest</L>
<L>&thorn;er as a wedded man in his astate</L>
<L N="1284">Lyue&thorn; his lif blisful and ordynate</L>
<L>Vndere &thorn;e &yogh;ok of mariage ybounde</L>
<L>Wel may his hert in Ioye and blisse be founde</L>
<L>ffor who can be so buxom as a wif</L>
<L N="1288">Who is so trewe and eke so tentiff</L>
<L>To kepe him seke and hole as is his make</L>
<L>ffor wel ne woo she wil not hym forsake</L>
<L>She nys not wery hym to loue and serue</L>
<L N="1292">&thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;at he lye bedrede til he sterue</L>
<L>And &yogh;it somme clerkes sein &thorn;at it is not soo</L>
<L>Of which theofraste is oon of &thorn;oo ./</L>
<L>What foorce &thorn;ou&yogh;t Thophrast luste&thorn; lye<MILESTONE N="114a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1296">Ne take no wif quod he for husbondrye</L>
<L>As forto spare in household &thorn;i dispence</L>
<L>A trewe seruaunte do&thorn; more diligence</L>
<L>Thi good to kepe &thorn;an &thorn;ine owne wif</L>
<L N="1300">ffor she wil cleyme half part al her lif</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou be seke so god me saue</L>
<L>Thi verrey frendes or a trewe knaue</L>
<L>Wil kepe &thorn;e better &thorn;an she &thorn;at waite&thorn; ay</L>
<L N="1304">Aftere &thorn;i good and ha&thorn; do mony a day</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou take a wif <SUP>1</SUP>&thorn;at to &thorn;e is vntrewe</L>
