<L>A Cardynal &thorn;at hight seint Ierome</L>
<L>&THORN;at made a boke a&yogh;ein Iouean</L>
<L N="676">In which boke eke &thorn;er was Terculan</L>
<L>Crisippus. Trocula. and holowys</L>
<L>That was Abbas not fer fro Paris/</L>
<L>And eke &thorn;e parables of Salomon</L>
<L N="680">Ovydes art and bokes mony on</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;ise were bounden in oo volom</L>
<L>And euery ny&yogh;t and day was his custom</L>
<L>Whan he had leisere and vacacion</L>
<L N="684">ffrom o&thorn;ere worldly occupacion</L>
<L>To reden in &thorn;is boke of wicked wyues</L>
<L>He knewe of hem mo legendys &thorn;an lyues</L>
<L>&thorn;an bene of good wyues in &thorn;e bible</L>
<L N="688">ffor truste&thorn; wel it is an impossible</L>
<L>&thorn;at eny clerk wil speken good of wyues</L>
<L>But &yogh;if it be of holy seyntes lyues</L>
<L>Ne of noon o&thorn;ere womman neuere &thorn;e moo /</L>
<L N="692">who peinted &thorn;e lyon telle me who /</L>
<L>By god &yogh;if wommen had ywriten stories</L>
<L>As clerkes han wi&thorn;-In her oratories</L>
<L>Thei wold han writen of men more wickednesse</L>
<L N="696">Than al &thorn;e Mark of Adam may redresse</L>
<L>The Children of mercury and Venus</L>
<L>Ben in her worchinge contrarious /</L>
<L>Mercury loue&thorn; wisdom and science</L>
<L N="700">And Venus loue&thorn; riote and dispence</L>
<L>And for her dyuers disposicion</L>
<L>Ech falle&thorn; in o&thorn;er exaltacion</L>
<L>As &thorn;us god wote mercure is disolate</L>
<L N="704">In pisces wher Venus is exaltate</L>
<L>And Venus falle&thorn; &thorn;er mercurye is reysed</L>
<L>&thorn;erfor no womman of no man is preised.</L>
<L>The clerk whan he is olde and may not do<MILESTONE N="139a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="708">Of Venus werkes wor&thorn; his olde shoo
<PB REF="00000321.tif" N="291"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="354"></L>
<L>&thorn;an sitte he doun and writte in his dotage</L>
<L>&THORN;at wommen can not kepe her mariage</L>
<L>But nowe to purpoos whi I told &thorn;e</L>
<L N="712">&THORN;at I was beten for a boke parde.</L>
<L>Vpon a ny&yogh;t Iankin &thorn;at was our sire</L>
<L>Redde on his boke as he satte by &thorn;e fire</L>
<L>Of Eua first &thorn;at for her wickednesse</L>
<L N="716">Was al mankinde brou&yogh;t to wrecchednesse</L>
<L>[ffor whiche &thorn;at Ihesu Crist hym selfe was slayne</L>
<L>That boughte vs with his herte blode agayne</L>
<L>Lo here expresse of women Maye ye ffynde</L>
<L N="720">That women was the losse of All Mankynde<MILESTONE UNIT="MS Reg. 17 D xv folio" N="134b">]</L>
<L>Tho redde he me howe sampson lost his heres</L>
<L>Slepinge his lemman kitt it wi&thorn; her sheres</L>
<L>&thorn;ourgh whiche treson lost he bo&thorn; his eyen /</L>
<L N="724">Tho redde he me if I shal not lyen.</L>
<L>Of Ercules and of his dyanyre</L>
<L>&thorn;at caused hym to sette hym self a fyre</L>
<L>No &thorn;inge forgate he &thorn;e penaunce and woo</L>
<L N="728">&thorn;at Socrates had wi&thorn; his wyues twoo</L>
<L>Howe &thorn;at Ancipa cast pisse on his hede</L>
<L>&thorn;e Sely man satte stille as he were dede</L>
<L>He wiped his hede no more durst he seyn</L>
<L N="732">But er &thorn;at thonder stint comme&thorn; a reyn</L>
<L>Of <NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>at first</I> ph]</NOTE>pasipa &thorn;at was &thorn;e quene of grete</L>
<L>ffor schrewdenesse hym &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> tale swete</L>
<L>ffye speke no more it is a grisly &thorn;inge</L>
<L N="736">Of hure horrible lust and [hure] lykynge</L>
<L>Of Clitermistra for her lecherye</L>
<L>&thorn;at falsly made her husbond forto dye</L>
<L>He redde it wi&thorn; ful good deuocion</L>
<L N="740">He tolde me for what occasion</L>
<L>Amphiorax at thebes lost his lif</L>
<L>Myn husbonde had a legende of his wif</L>
<L>Eriphilem. &thorn;at for an ouch of gold</L>
<L N="744">ha&thorn; prively vnto &thorn;e grekes told
<PB REF="00000322.tif" N="292"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="355"></L>
<L>wher &thorn;at her husbond hidde hym in a place</L>
<L>ffor which he had at Thebes sory grace</L>
<L>Of lyma tolde he mee and of lucye<MILESTONE N="139b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="748">&THORN;ei bo&thorn; made her husbondes forto dye</L>
<L>Thatt on for loue &thorn;at o&thorn;er was for hate</L>
<L>lyma her husbonde on euene late</L>
<L>Enpoysened had for &thorn;at she was his foo</L>
<L N="752">Lucia lykerous loued her husbond soo /</L>
<L>&THORN;at for he shuld vpon her alway &thorn;inke</L>
<L>She &yogh;aue hym such a loue manere drinke</L>
<L>That he was dede or it was by &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> morowe</L>
<L N="756">And &thorn;us algates husbondes han sorowe</L>
<L>&para; Than tolde he me howe on latumyus</L>
<L>Compleyned to his felawe arius</L>
<L>That in his gardyne growed such a tre</L>
<L N="760">On which he seide &thorn;at his wyues &thorn;re</L>
<L>Hangged hem selue for hertes despitous</L>
<L>O leue bro&thorn;er quod &thorn;is arious</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue me a plant of &thorn;at blisful tre</L>
<L N="764">And in my gardyne planted shal he be</L>
<L>Of latter date of wyues ha&thorn; he redde</L>
<L>&thorn;at han sclayn her husbondes in &thorn;e bedde</L>
<L>But lat hure lecchoure di&yogh;t hur al &thorn;e ny&yogh;t</L>
<L N="768">Whan &thorn;at &thorn;e corps lay in &thorn;e floore vpri&yogh;t</L>
<L>And some han dryuen nayles in her brayn</L>
<L>While &thorn;at &thorn;ei sclepe and &thorn;us &thorn;ei han hem sclayn</L>
<L>Somme han &yogh;euen poysen in her drinke</L>
<L N="772">He spak more harme &thorn;an hert may &thorn;enk</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-with-all he knewe of moo prouerbes<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Solo melius est habitare.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;an in &thorn;is world &thorn;er growen grasse or herbes /</L>
<L>Bett is quod he &thorn;ine habitacion</L>
<L N="776">Be wi&thorn; a leon or a foule dragon</L>
<L>&THORN;an wi&thorn; a womman vsing forto chide</L>
<L>Bet is quod he high in &thorn;e roof abide</L>
<L>&thorn;an wi&thorn; an angry wif doun in an hous</L>
<L N="780">&thorn;ey bene so wicked and contrarious /
<PB REF="00000323.tif" N="293"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="356"></L>
<L>&thorn;ei haten &thorn;at her husbondes louen ay</L>
<L>He seide a womman cast her shame away</L>
<L>whan she cast of her smokke and fer&thorn;ermo<MILESTONE N="140a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="784">A faire womman but she be chaast also /</L>
<L>Is lich a gold rynge on a sowes nose</L>
<L>who wold wene or wold suppose</L>
<L>The woo &thorn;at in myn herte was and pyne</L>
<L N="788">And whan I segh he wolde neuere fyne</L>
<L>To reden on &thorn;is cursed boke al ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>Al sodeynly &thorn;re leues haue I pli&yogh;t</L>
<L>Out of his boke ri&yogh;t as he redde and eke</L>
<L N="792">I wi&thorn; my fist so toke him on &thorn;e cheke</L>
<L>That in our fire he fille bakward adoun</L>
<L>And he vp stert as do&thorn; a wood lyoun</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; his fist he smote me on &thorn;e hede</L>
<L N="796">&THORN;at in &thorn;e flore I laie as I were dede</L>
<L>And whan he seegh how stille &thorn;at I lay</L>
<L>He was agast and wold han fledde away</L>
<L>Til at &thorn;e laste out of my swowe I breide</L>
<L N="800">O hastowe sclayne me fals &thorn;eef I seide</L>
<L>And for my londe &thorn;us hastowe mordred me</L>
<L>Or I be dede &yogh;it wil I kisse &thorn;ee</L>
<L>And nere he come and kneled faire adoun</L>
<L N="804">And saide dere sustere Alisoun</L>
<L>As helpe me god I shal &thorn;e neuere smyte</L>
<L>That I haue done it is &thorn;i self to wite</L>
<L>ffor&yogh;eue it me and &thorn;at I &thorn;e biseke</L>
<L N="808">And &yogh;it eftsones I hit hym on &thorn;e cheke</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;eef &thorn;us moche am I wreke</L>
<L>Nowe wil I dye I may no lenger speke</L>
<L>But at &thorn;e last wi&thorn; mochel care and woo</L>
<L N="812">We fille acorded by vs seluen twoo</L>
<L>He &yogh;aue me al &thorn;e bridel in myn honde</L>
<L>To haue &thorn;e gouernaunce of hous and londe</L>
<L>And of his tunge and his hand also</L>
<L N="816">And made him brenne his boke anon ri&yogh;t &thorn;oo
<PB REF="00000324.tif" N="294"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="357"></L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at I had goten vnto me</L>
<L>By maistery al &thorn;e souereynte.</L>
<L>Than he seide myn owne trewe wif<MILESTONE N="140b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="820">Do as &yogh;ou lest &thorn;e terme of al &yogh;oure lif</L>
<L>kepe &yogh;oure honure and kepe eke myn astate</L>
<L>Aftere &thorn;at day we had neuere debate.</L>
<L>God helpe me so I was to him as kinde</L>
<L N="824">As eny wiff from denmarke into Ynde</L>
<L>And also trewe / and so was he to me</L>
<L>I prey to god &thorn;at sitte in mageste</L>
<L>So blesse his soule for his mercy dere</L>
<L N="828">Now wil I seie my tale if &yogh;e wil here</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; Thus ende&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e wiff of bath</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>And here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e Tale.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[that is, The Wrangle between the Summoner and the Friar.]</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; The tale./</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The frere lowe whan he had herd al &thorn;is</L>
<L>Now dame quod he so haue I ioye or blis</L>
<L>&thorn;is is a longe preamble of a tale</L>
<L N="832">And whan &thorn;is somnour herd &thorn;e frere gale</L>
<L>Lo quod &thorn;e somnour goddis armes two</L>
<L>A frere wil entremete hym euermoo</L>
<L>Loo good men a flie and eke a frere</L>
<L N="836">wollen falle in euery dissh and eke matere</L>
<L>what spekest &thorn;ou of preambulacioun</L>
<L>what amble or trotte or pees or go sitte doun</L>
<L>Thou lettest oure disport in &thorn;is manere</L>
<L N="840">&YOGH;e wilt &thorn;ou so somnour quod &thorn;e frere</L>
<L>Now by my fay I shal er &thorn;at I goo</L>
<L>Telle a somnour such a tale or twoo</L>
<L>That alle &thorn;e folk shul laughen in &thorn;is place</L>
<L N="844">Now ellis frere I bishrewe &thorn;i face</L>
<L>Quod &thorn;is somnour and I bishrewe me</L>
<L>But &yogh;if I telle &thorn;e tales two or &thorn;re</L>
<L>Of freres er I come to sidyngburne</L>
<L N="848">&thorn;at I shal make &thorn;ine hert for to mourne
<PB REF="00000325.tif" N="295"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="358"></L>
<L>ffor wel I wote &thorn;i pacience is gon</L>
<L>Our hoost cried pees and &thorn;at anon</L>
<L>And seide lat &thorn;e womman telle her tale</L>
<L N="852">&YOGH;e faren as folk &thorn;at dronken ben of ale./</L>
<L>Do dame telle forth &yogh;our tale &thorn;at is &thorn;e best<MILESTONE N="141a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Al redy sire quod she ri&yogh;t as &yogh;ou lest</L>
<L>If I haue licence of &thorn;is wor&thorn;i frere</L>
<L N="856">&yogh;is dame quod he telle for&thorn; &yogh;oure tale we wil here<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000326.tif" N="296">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="359">
<HEAD>[THE WIFE OF BATH'S TALE]<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 141</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN &thorn;e olde dayes of &thorn;e king arthour<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; ffabula</NOTE></L>
<L>Of which &thorn;at bretons speken grete honour</L>
<L>Al was &thorn;is land fulfilled of fayry</L>
<L N="860">&thorn;e Elfe quene wi&thorn; her Ioly companye</L>
<L>Daunced wi&thorn; out in mony a grene mede</L>
<L>&THORN;is was &thorn;e olde opynyon as I rede</L>
<L>I speke of mony an .C. &yogh;ere a-goo</L>
<L N="864">But nowe can no man se noon elues moo</L>
<L>ffor nowe &thorn;e grete charite and preiers</L>
<L>Of lymytoures and o&thorn;er poor freres</L>
<L>That serchen euery londe and euery streme</L>
<L N="868">As &thorn;ikke as motes in &thorn;e sonne beme</L>
<L>Blessinge halles chambers and boures</L>
<L>Citiees burghes castels hi&yogh;e toures</L>
<L>Thropes . beernys . shipnes . dayrys</L>
<L N="872">This make&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;er bene no fayrys</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;er as wonte to walke was an elf</L>
<L>Ther walke&thorn; nowe &thorn;e lymytour hym self</L>
<L>In vnder meles and in mornyngges</L>
<L N="876">And sei&thorn; his matyns and his holy &thorn;ingges</L>
<L>As he go&thorn; in his lymitacioun</L>
<L>Wommen may go nowe sauf vp and doun</L>
<L>In euery bussh or vnder euery tre</L>
<L N="880">&THORN;er nys non o&thorn;er Incubus but he</L>
<L>And he wil do hem but dishonour</L>
<L>And so felle it &thorn;at &thorn;is king Arthour</L>
<L>Had in his hous a lusty bachilere</L>
<L N="884">That on a day come riding fro ryvere
<PB REF="00000327.tif" N="297"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="360"></L>
<L>And happed alone as she was born</L>
<L>He seegh a maiden walking hym byforn</L>
<L>Of which mayde Maugre her hede</L>
<L N="888">By verrey force he raft hure maydenhede</L>
<L>ffor which oppression was such clamour<MILESTONE N="141b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And such pursute vnto &thorn;e king arthour</L>
<L>That dampned was &thorn;is kny&yogh;t forto be dede</L>
<L N="892">Be cours of lawe and shuld haue lost his hede</L>
<L>Perauenture such was &thorn;e statute &thorn;oo /</L>
<L>But &thorn;at &thorn;e quene and o&thorn;er ladis moo</L>
<L>So longe preide &thorn;e kinge of grace</L>
<L N="896">Til he his liff him graunted in &thorn;at place</L>
<L>And &yogh;aue hym to &thorn;e quene al at her wille</L>
<L>To chese whedere she wold hym saue or spille</L>
<L>The quene &thorn;onke&thorn; &thorn;e kinge wi&thorn; al her my&yogh;t</L>
<L N="900">And after &thorn;is &thorn;us speke she to &thorn;e knyght</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at she seegh her tyme on a day</L>
<L>Thou stondest &yogh;it quod she in such aray</L>
<L>That of &thorn;i lif &yogh;it hastowe no suerte</L>
<L N="904">I graunte &thorn;e lif if &thorn;ou canst telle me</L>
<L>&para; What &thorn;ing is it &thorn;at wommen most desiren</L>
<L>Be ware and kepe &thorn;i nekbone fro yren</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou canst not telle it me anon</L>
<L N="908">&YOGH;it wil I &yogh;eue &thorn;e leue forto gon</L>
<L>A xij. mon&thorn;e and a daye . to seke and lere</L>
<L>An answere suffisaunt in &thorn;is matere</L>
<L>And suerte wil I han er &thorn;at &thorn;ou passe</L>
<L N="912">&THORN;i body forto &yogh;elde in &thorn;is place</L>
<L>woo was &thorn;is kny&yogh;t and sorowfully he sike&thorn;</L>
<L>But what? he may not do al as hym like&thorn;</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e last he chese hym forto wende</L>
<L N="916">And to come a&yogh;ein ri&yogh;t at &thorn;e &yogh;eres ende</L>
<L>With suche answere as god wold hym purveye</L>
<L>And take&thorn; his leue and wende&thorn; for&thorn; his weye</L>
<L>He seke&thorn; euery hous and euery place</L>
<L N="920">Where as he hope&thorn; forto fynde grace
<PB REF="00000328.tif" N="298"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="361"></L>
<L>To lere what &thorn;ing wommen louen most</L>
<L>But he nowe koude aryuen in no cost</L>
<L>where as he my&yogh;te fynde in &thorn;is matere</L>
<L N="924">Twoo creatures acording in fere</L>
<L>Somme seiden wommen louen best ricchesse<MILESTONE N="142a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Somme seide honour somme seiden Iolynesse</L>
<L>Somme riche aray . some seiden lust a bedde</L>
<L N="928">And oft tyme to be wydowe and wedde</L>
<L>Somme seiden &thorn;at we bene most yesed</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at we bene yflatered and yplesed.</L>
<L>He go&thorn; ful ny &thorn;e so&thorn; I wil nat lye</L>
<L N="932">A man shal wynne vs best wi&thorn; flaterye</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; attendaunce and wi&thorn; bisynesse</L>
<L>bene we alyned bo&thorn; more and lesse</L>
<L>And somme men seyn howe &thorn;at we louen best</L>
<L N="936">fforto be free and do ri&yogh;t as vs lest</L>
<L>And &thorn;at no man repreue vs of our vice</L>
<L>But say &thorn;at we bene wise and no &thorn;inge nice</L>
<L>ffor trewly &thorn;er nys noon of vs alle</L>
<L N="940">&YOGH;if eny wi&yogh;t wil clawe vs on &thorn;e galle</L>
<L>&THORN;at we nyl loke or he saye vs soth</L>
<L>Assaie and he shal fynde it &thorn;at he do&thorn;.</L>
<L>ffor be we neuer so vicious wi&thorn;-Inne</L>
<L N="944">We wil be holden wise and clene of synne</L>
<L>And somme seyn &thorn;at grete delit haue we</L>
<L>ffor to be holden stable and eke secree</L>
<L>And in oo purpos stedfastly to dwelle</L>
<L N="948">And not bewrey &thorn;ing &thorn;at men vs telle</L>
<L>But &thorn;at tale is not wor&thorn; a rake stele</L>
<L>Parde we wommen connen no &thorn;ing hele</L>
<L>Witnesse on myda wil &yogh;e here &thorn;e tale</L>
<L N="952">Ovide amonges o&thorn;er &thorn;ingges smale</L>
<L>Sei&thorn; Mida had vnder his longe heres</L>
<L>Growinge vpon his hede two asses eres</L>
<L>The whiche vice he hidde as he best my&yogh;t</L>
<L N="956">fful subtily from euery mannys si&yogh;t
<PB REF="00000329.tif" N="299"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="362"></L>
<L>&thorn;at saue his wif &thorn;er wist it no moo</L>
<L>He loued her most and trested to her also</L>
<L>He preide hir most &thorn;at vnto no creature</L>
<L N="960">She shuld not tellen of his disfigure</L>
<L>She swore hym nay for al &thorn;is world to wynne<MILESTONE N="142b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>She wold do &thorn;at vilanye or &thorn;at synne</L>
<L>To make her husbond han so foule a name</L>
<L N="964">ffor reprevynge of hym and foule shame</L>
<L>But na&thorn;elees her &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at she dide</L>
<L>&thorn;at she so longe shuld a counseile hide</L>
<L>Her &thorn;ou&yogh;t it satte so sore about her herte</L>
<L N="968">&THORN;at nedely som word her mote a-sterte</L>
<L>And si&thorn;e she durst [nat] tellen it no man</L>
<L>Doune to a marise fast she ranne</L>
<L>Til she came &thorn;ere her herte was a fire</L>
