<L>And eke I prei to Ihesu short her lyues</L>
<L>That wil not be gouerned by her wyues</L>
<L>And olde and angry nygard and dispence</L>
<L N="1264">God sende hem sone a verrey pestilence</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; Thus ende&thorn; &thorn;e tale of &thorn;e wif of bath /</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000338.tif" N="308">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="371">
<HEAD>And here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> frere<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 146, <I>back</I></NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This wor&thorn;i lymitour &thorn;is noble ffrere<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; &THORN;e prologe</NOTE></L>
<L>He made alway louring chere</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;e somnour . but for honeste</L>
<L N="1268">No vyleyns word as &yogh;it speke he</L>
<L>But at &thorn;e last he seide vnto &thorn;e wif</L>
<L>Dame good god &yogh;eue &yogh;ou ri&yogh;t good lyf</L>
<L>&YOGH;e han touched here also mote I the</L>
<L N="1272">In scole matere grete difficulte</L>
<L>&YOGH;e han seide mochel &thorn;ing ri&yogh;t wel I seie</L>
<L>But dame here as we riden by &thorn;e weie</L>
<L>Vs nede&thorn; not to speken but of game</L>
<L N="1276">And late auctoritees a goddes name</L>
<L>To prechen and to scole eke of clergie</L>
<L>But &yogh;if it like vnto &thorn;is companye</L>
<L>I wil &yogh;ou of a somnour telle a game</L>
<L N="1280">Parde I may wel knowe by &thorn;i name</L>
<L>That of no somnour may no good be seid</L>
<L>I prey &thorn;at noon of &yogh;ou be euel apeid</L>
<L>A somnour is a romere vp and doun<MILESTONE N="147a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1284">Wi&thorn; a mendement of fornicacioun</L>
<L>And is ibete at euery townes ende</L>
<L>Our hoost &thorn;oo spak a . sire &yogh;e shuld ben hende</L>
<L>And Curteis as man of &yogh;our astat</L>
<L N="1288">In company we wil no debate</L>
<L>Telle&thorn; &yogh;oure tale and lat &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> somnour be</L>
<L>Nay quod &thorn;e somnour lat him say to me</L>
<L>What so him lest . whan it comme&thorn; to my lott</L>
<L N="1292">Be god I&middot; shal hym quyte euery grott</L>
<L>I shal him telle swich a grete honour</L>
<L>It is to be a flateryng lymytour</L>
<L>And eke of ful mony an o&thorn;er crime</L>
<L N="1296">Which nede&thorn; not rehersen at &thorn;is tyme</L>
<L>And his office I shal hym telle ywis</L>
<L>Our hooste answerd pees no more of &thorn;is</L>
<L>And afterward he seide vnto &thorn;e frere</L>
<L N="1300">Telle for&thorn; &yogh;oure tale my owen maister dere</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; Thus ende&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e frere.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000339.tif" N="309">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="372">
<HEAD>And here begynne&thorn; &thorn;e ffreres tale.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whilom &thorn;er was dwelling in my contre<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; The tale./</NOTE></L>
<L>An Archedeken a man of hie degre</L>
<L>That boldely did execusion</L>
<L N="1304">In punysshing of fornicacion</L>
<L>Of which craft and eke of baudry</L>
<L>Of diffamacion and avoutrye</L>
<L>Of chirche reues and of testamentes</L>
<L N="1308">Of contractes and of lak of sacramentes</L>
<L>Of vsure and symonye also</L>
<L>But certes lecchours did he grettest woo</L>
<L>&THORN;ei shulden syngen if &thorn;ei were hent</L>
<L N="1312">And Smale Tythers weren foule shent</L>
<L>If eny person wold vpon hem pleyne</L>
<L>&THORN;er my&yogh;t astert him no pecunyal peyne</L>
<L>ffor smale ty&thorn;es and eke smale offringe</L>
<L N="1316">He made &thorn;e puple spitously to singe</L>
<L>ffor er the bisshope kau&yogh;t hem wi&thorn; his hoke<MILESTONE N="147b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;ei weren in &thorn;e Archedekens boke</L>
<L>And &thorn;an had he &thorn;orowe his Iurisdiction</L>
<L N="1320">Pouer to don on hem correccion</L>
<L>he had a somnour redy to his hand</L>
<L>A sclyer boye was non in engelond</L>
<L>ffor sotilly he had his especiale</L>
<L N="1324">That tau&yogh;t hym where &thorn;at hym my&yogh;t availe</L>
<L>He coude spare of lecchours on or twoo</L>
<L>To techen hym to <I>four and twenty</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS xxiiij]</NOTE> moo</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou&yogh;e this somnour wode were as an hare</L>
<L N="1328">To telle his harlotry I wil not spare
<PB REF="00000340.tif" N="310"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="373"></L>
<L>ffor we bene out of her correcci&omacr;n</L>
<L>&THORN;ei han of vs non Iurisdiction</L>
<L>Ne neuere shullen teerme of al her lyues</L>
<L N="1332">Peter so bene &thorn;e wommen of &thorn;e stewes</L>
<L>Quod this somnour yput out of our cure</L>
<L>Pees wi&thorn; meschaunce and wi&thorn; misauenture</L>
<L>Thus seide our hoost and lat hym telle his tale</L>
<L N="1336">Now telle&thorn; for&thorn; and lat &thorn;e somnour gale</L>
<L>Ne spareth nou&yogh;t myn owne Maister dere</L>
<L>This fals &thorn;eef &thorn;is somnour quod &thorn;e frere</L>
<L>Had alway baudes redy to his honde</L>
<L N="1340">As eny hauke to lure in Engelonde</L>
<L>That telle him al &thorn;e secre &thorn;at thei knewe</L>
<L>ffor hure a-queyntance was nat come of newe</L>
<L>&thorn;ei weren his aprouers prively</L>
<L N="1344">He toke hym silf a grete prophete &thorn;erby</L>
<L>His maistere knewe not al way what he wan</L>
<L>wi&thorn;-outen maundement of a lewde man</L>
<L>He coude sommon vpeyn of cristes curs</L>
<L N="1348">And &thorn;ei were inly glad to fille his purs</L>
<L>And made hym grete festes atte nale</L>
<L>And ri&yogh;t as Iudas had purses smale</L>
<L>And was a &thorn;eef ri&yogh;t such a &thorn;eef was he</L>
<L N="1352">His maister had but half his dwete</L>
<L>He was &yogh;if I shal &yogh;euene hym his laude<MILESTONE N="148a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A theef and eke a somnour and a bawde</L>
<L>He had eke wenches of his retenue</L>
<L N="1356">That whedere &thorn;at sir Roberde or sir hwe</L>
<L>Or Iohn or rauf or who &thorn;at it were</L>
<L>&thorn;at lay by hem &thorn;ei tolde it in his eere</L>
<L>Thus was &thorn;e wenche and he of on assent</L>
<L N="1360">And he wolde focche a feyned maundement</L>
<L>And somne hem to &thorn;e chapitere bo&thorn; twoo</L>
<L>And pille &thorn;e man and lat &thorn;e wenche goo</L>
<L>Than wold he sei frend I shal for &thorn;i sake</L>
<L N="1364">To strike &thorn;e out of oure letters blake
<PB REF="00000341.tif" N="311"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="374"></L>
<L>&THORN;e ther no more as in &thorn;is caas travaile</L>
<L>I am &thorn;i frende &thorn;er I &thorn;e may availe</L>
<L>Certeyn he knewe of bribers moo</L>
<L N="1368">&thorn;an possible is to telle &yogh;ou vnto to/</L>
<L>ffor in &thorn;is world is no dogge for no bowe</L>
<L>&thorn;at knowe&thorn; and hert deer. from an olde bete kowe</L>
<L>&thorn;an &thorn;at &thorn;is somnour knewe a sly lecchour</L>
<L N="1372">Or auouter or ellis a paramour</L>
<L>And for &thorn;at was &thorn;e fruyte of al &thorn;e rent</L>
<L>Therfore on hit he sette al his entent</L>
<L>And so byfelle &thorn;at ones on a day</L>
<L N="1376">This somnour euer wayting on his pray</L>
<L>Rode forto somne an old wif a ribibe</L>
<L>ffeynyng a cause for he wold haue a bribe</L>
<L>And happed &thorn;at he sawe to-fore hym ride</L>
<L N="1380">A gey &yogh;eman vnder a forest side</L>
<L>A bowe he bare and Arowes bri&yogh;t and kene</L>
<L>He had vpon a courtepie of grene</L>
<L>An hatte vpon his hede wi&thorn; stringges blake</L>
<L N="1384">Sire quod &thorn;is somnour. haile and wel ytake</L>
<L>welcome quod he and euery good felawe</L>
<L>whider ridest &thorn;owe vnder &thorn;is grene wood shawe</L>
<L>Seide &thorn;is &yogh;eman wilt thou fer to-day</L>
<L N="1388">This somnour hym answerd and seide nay</L>
<L>Here fast by quod he is myne entent<MILESTONE N="148b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To riden for to reisen vp a rent</L>
<L>It longe&thorn; to my lordes dewte</L>
<L N="1392">Art &thorn;ou &thorn;an a bailyf. &yogh;e quod he</L>
<L>He durste not for verrey fil&thorn;e and shame</L>
<L>Say &thorn;at he was a somnour for &thorn;e name</L>
<L>Depar-dieux quod &thorn;is &yogh;eman dere bro&thorn;er</L>
<L N="1396">&thorn;ou art a baillif and I am ano&thorn;er</L>
<L>I am vnknowen as in &thorn;is contre</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ine aqueyntance I wil prey &thorn;e</L>
<L>And eke of bre&thorn;erhede if &thorn;at &thorn;ou lest</L>
<L N="1400">I haue gold and siluer in my chest
<PB REF="00000342.tif" N="312"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="375"></L>
<L>&yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e happed come into our shire</L>
<L>Al shal be &thorn;ine ri&yogh;t as &thorn;ou wold desire</L>
<L>Graunte mercy quod &thorn;is somnour by my fei&thorn;e</L>
<L N="1404">Euerech in o&thorn;eres honde his trou&thorn;e lei&thorn;e</L>
<L>ffor to be swore bre&thorn;eren to &thorn;ei dye</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word &thorn;ei ride for&thorn; her wey</L>
<L>This somnour wi&thorn; &thorn;at was as ful of Iangles</L>
<L N="1408">As ful of venyme ben &thorn;ise waryangles</L>
<L>And euer enquiring vpon euery &thorn;inge</L>
<L>Bro&thorn;er quod he wher is &yogh;our dwellinge</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er day if I shuld &yogh;ou seche</L>
<L N="1412">&thorn;is &yogh;eman him answerd in softe spech</L>
<L>Bro&thorn;er quod he ferre in &thorn;e north contre</L>
<L>Wher as I hope somtyme I shal &thorn;e See</L>
<L>Or we departe I shal &thorn;e so wel wisse</L>
<L N="1416">&thorn;at of myn hous shalt &thorn;ou neuere mysse</L>
<L>Now bro&thorn;ere quod &thorn;is somnour I &yogh;ou pray</L>
<L>Teche me while we riden by &thorn;e waye</L>
<L>Si&thorn; &thorn;at &yogh;e bene a balif as am I</L>
<L N="1420">Somme subtilite telle me fei&thorn;fully</L>
<L>In myn office howe &thorn;at I may most wynne</L>
<L>And spare&thorn; not for conscience ne synne</L>
<L>But as my bro&thorn;ere telle me howe doo &yogh;e.</L>
<L N="1424">Nowe by my treu&thorn;e bro&thorn;ere dere seide he</L>
<L>As I shal tellen &thorn;e a fei&thorn;ful tale<MILESTONE N="149a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>My wages be ful streit and smale</L>
<L>My lorde is hard to me and daungerous</L>
<L N="1428">And myn office ful laborous</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore by extorcions y lyue</L>
<L>ffor so&thorn; I [take] al &thorn;at men wil me &yogh;eue</L>
<L>Algate by scleyght or violence</L>
<L N="1432">ffrom &yogh;eer to &yogh;eer I wynne al my dispence</L>
<L>I can no better tellen fei&thorn;fully</L>
<L>Now certes quod &thorn;is somnour so fare I</L>
<L>I spare not to take god it wote</L>
<L N="1436">But &yogh;if it be to hevy or to hote
<PB REF="00000343.tif" N="313"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="376"></L>
<L>What I may gete in counseile priveily</L>
<L>No maner conscience of &thorn;at haue I</L>
<L>Ner myn extorcion I my&yogh;t not lyuen</L>
<L N="1440">Of suche Iapes nyl I not be shryuen</L>
<L>Stomake . ne for conscience ne knowe I non</L>
<L>I schrewe &thorn;ise shrift faders euerechon</L>
<L>Wel ben we mette by god and by seint Iame</L>
<L N="1444">But leue bro&thorn;er telle me &thorn;an &thorn;i name</L>
<L>Quo&thorn; &thorn;is somnour in &thorn;is mene while</L>
<L>&THORN;is &yogh;eman gan a litel forto smyle</L>
<L>Bro&thorn;er quod he wiltow &thorn;at I &thorn;e telle</L>
<L N="1448">I am a feende my dwellyng is in helle</L>
<L>And here I ride aboute my purchasing</L>
<L>To wete where men wollen &yogh;eue me eny &thorn;ing</L>
<L>My purchace is to fette of all my rent</L>
<L N="1452">Loke how &thorn;ou ridest for &thorn;e same entent</L>
<L>To wynne good &thorn;ou recchest not howe</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t so fare I for ride wold I nowe</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e worldes eende for a preye</L>
<L N="1456">A quod &thorn;is somnour benedicite what &yogh;e seie</L>
<L>I wende &yogh;e were a &yogh;eman trewly</L>
<L>&YOGH;e han a mannes shappe as wel as I</L>
<L>Han &yogh;e a figure &thorn;an determynate</L>
<L N="1460">In helle &thorn;er &yogh;e bene in &yogh;our estate</L>
<L>Nay certeynly quo&thorn; he &thorn;ere haue we noon<MILESTONE N="149b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But whan vs like&thorn; we can take vs oon</L>
<L>Or ellis make &yogh;ou seme we bene shape</L>
<L N="1464">Somtyme a man or like an ape</L>
<L>Or like an aungel can I ride or goo</L>
<L>It is no wonder &thorn;ing &thorn;ou&yogh;e it be so</L>
<L>A lousy Iogelour can desceyue &thorn;e</L>
<L N="1468">And parde &yogh;it can I more craft &thorn;an he</L>
<L>Why quo&thorn; &thorn;is somnour ride &yogh;e &thorn;an or gon</L>
<L>In sondry shappe and not alway in oon</L>
<L>ffor we quod he wil vs in such forme make</L>
<L N="1472">As most able is our praies forto take
<PB REF="00000344.tif" N="314"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="377"></L>
<L>What make&thorn; &yogh;ou to han al &thorn;is labour</L>
<L>fful mony a cause leeue sir somnour</L>
<L>Seide &thorn;is feende but al &thorn;ing ha&thorn; tyme</L>
<L N="1476">The day is short and it is passed prime</L>
<L>And &yogh;it ne wanne I no &thorn;inge in &thorn;is day</L>
<L>I wil entende to wynnyng &yogh;if I may</L>
<L>And nat entende our wittes to declare</L>
<L N="1480">ffor bro&thorn;er myne &thorn;i witte is alto bare</L>
<L>To vnderstonde &thorn;ou&yogh;e I tolde hem &thorn;e</L>
<L>But for &thorn;owe askest whi labouren we</L>
<L>ffor somtyme be we goddes instrumentes</L>
<L N="1484">And menes to do his comaundementes</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at him list vpon his creatures</L>
<L>In dyuers actes and in dyuers figures</L>
<L>With-outen hym we han no my&yogh;t certeyn</L>
<L N="1488">&YOGH;if &thorn;at him list to stonden &thorn;er a&yogh;ein</L>
<L>And some tyme at our pray han we leue</L>
<L>Only &thorn;e body and nat &thorn;e soule greue</L>
<L>Witnesse on Iob whom &thorn;at we diden woo</L>
<L N="1492">And somtyme han we my&yogh;t of bo&thorn;[e] two</L>
<L>&thorn;is is to seyn of soule and body eke</L>
<L>And somtyme we bene suffered forto seke</L>
<L>Vpon a man and do his soule vnrest</L>
<L N="1496">And nat his body and al is for &thorn;e best</L>
<L>Whan he withstonde&thorn; our temptacion<MILESTONE N="150a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>It is a cause of [his] saluacion</L>
<L>Al be it &thorn;at it was not our entent</L>
<L N="1500">He shulde be sauf but &thorn;at we wold hym hent</L>
<L>And somtyme be we seruauntes vnto man</L>
<L>As &thorn;e erchbisshope seint dunstan</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e appostels seruaunte was I</L>
<L N="1504">&YOGH;it telle&thorn; me quod &thorn;e somnour fei&thorn;fully</L>
<L>Make &yogh;e &yogh;ou newe bodies &thorn;us alway</L>
<L>Of elementz &thorn;e feende answerd nay</L>
<L>Somme tyme we feyne and somtyme we arise</L>
<L N="1508">Wi&thorn; dede bodies in ful sondry wise
<PB REF="00000345.tif" N="315"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="378"></L>
<L>And speke as resonably and faire well</L>
<L>As to &thorn;e Phitonessa. did samuell</L>
<L>And &yogh;it wil somme men say it was not he</L>
<L N="1512">I doo no fors of &yogh;oure dyvynite</L>
<L>But oon &thorn;ing warne I &thorn;e I wil not Iape</L>
<L>Thow wilt algates witte howe we be shape</L>
<L>&THORN;ou shalt here afterward my bro&thorn;er dere</L>
<L N="1516">Come &thorn;er &thorn;e nede&thorn; nat of me to lere</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou shalt be &thorn;ine owne experience</L>
<L>Come into &thorn;e Chaiere rede &thorn;is sentence</L>
<L>Bette &thorn;an virgil while he was a lyue</L>
<L N="1520">Or Dante also now lat vs ride blyue</L>
<L>ffor I wil hold company wi&thorn; &thorn;e</L>
<L>Til it be so &thorn;at &thorn;ou forsake me</L>
<L>Nay quod &thorn;is somnour &thorn;at shal not betide</L>
<L N="1524">I am a &yogh;eman knowe is ful wide</L>
<L>Mi trou&thorn;e wil I holde to &thorn;e as in &thorn;is cas</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ei &thorn;ou were &thorn;e deuel Sathanas</L>
<L>My trou&thorn;e wil I holde to my bro&thorn;er</L>
<L N="1528">As I am sworn and eche of vs to o&thorn;er</L>
<L>ffor to be trewe bro&thorn;er in &thorn;is caas</L>
<L>And bro&thorn;er we goon to our purchas</L>
<L>Take &thorn;ou &thorn;i parte what men wil &thorn;e &yogh;eue</L>
<L N="1532">And I shal myne &thorn;us may we bo&thorn;[e] lyue</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;at eny of vs haue more &thorn;an o&thorn;ere<MILESTONE N="150b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Lat him be trewe and part it with his bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>I graunte quod &thorn;e deuel be my fay</L>
<L N="1536">And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word &thorn;ei ryden forth her way</L>
<L>And ri&yogh;t at &thorn;e enteringe of &thorn;e townes ende</L>
<L>To which &thorn;e sompnour shope hym for to wende</L>
<L>&thorn;ei sey a cart &thorn;at charged was wi&thorn; hay</L>
<L N="1540">Which &thorn;at a carter droof for&thorn; on his way</L>
<L>Depe was &thorn;e way for which &thorn;e carte stoode</L>
<L>This Carter smote and stroof as he were woode</L>
<L>Haite broke haite scotte what spare we for &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> stonys</L>
<L N="1544">&thorn;e feende quod he &yogh;ou fecche bo&thorn; body and bonys
<PB REF="00000346.tif" N="316"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="379"></L>
<L>As ferfor&thorn;ly as euere were &yogh;e foled/</L>
<L>So moche woo as I haue for &yogh;ou tholed</L>
<L>&thorn;e deuel haue all bo&thorn; hors and carte and hay</L>
<L N="1548">&thorn;ou&yogh;t this somnour here shul we haue a play</L>
<L>And nere &thorn;e feende he drou&yogh;e as nau&yogh;t ne were</L>
<L>fful priueyly and rouned in his eere</L>
<L>Harken my bro&thorn;er herken be &thorn;i fei&thorn;</L>
<L N="1552">Herestow nat howe &thorn;e carter sei&thorn;</L>
