<L>That &thorn;ou departe it so my dere bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>&THORN;at euery frere haue as moch as o&thorn;er</L>
<L>This shalt &thorn;ou swere on &thorn;i profession</L>
<L N="2136">Wi&thorn;-outen fraude or cauellacion</L>
<L>I swere it quod &thorn;e frere by my fai&thorn;</L>
<L>And &thorn;erwi&thorn;al his honde in his he lai&thorn;</L>
<L>lo here my fei&thorn; in me shal be no lak</L>
<L N="2140">Now &thorn;an put &thorn;ine honde doun by my bak</L>
<L>Seide &thorn;is man and grope wel behinde<MILESTONE N="159a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Byne&thorn; my buttok &thorn;er &thorn;ou shalt fynde</L>
<L>A &thorn;inge &thorn;at I haue hidde in priuete</L>
<L N="2144">A &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;e frere &thorn;at shal go wi&thorn; me</L>
<L>A-doune his honde he launse&thorn; to &thorn;e clift</L>
<L>I hope for to fynde &thorn;er a &yogh;ift</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is sik man felt &thorn;is frere</L>
<L N="2148">About his trwel grope her and &thorn;ere</L>
<L>A myddes his honde he lete &thorn;e frere a fart</L>
<L>&thorn;er nys no capel drawing in a cart</L>
<L>&thorn;at my&yogh;t han lete a fart of such a soun</L>
<L N="2152">&thorn;e frere vp stert as do&thorn; a [wood] lyoun</L>
<L>A fals cherle quod &thorn;e frere for goddis bonys</L>
<L>This despite &thorn;ou hast done for &thorn;e nonys</L>
<L>&thorn;owe shal aby &thorn;is fart if I may</L>
<L N="2156">His mayne &thorn;at harde &thorn;is affray</L>
<L>Come lepinge Inne and chased out &thorn;e frere</L>
<L>And for&thorn;e he go&thorn; with a ful angry chere</L>
<L N="*2159"><NOTE PLACE="foot">[Spurious ending in the Petworth MS. For the genuine ending of the Tale, see the Appendix.]</NOTE>He ne had nat ellis for his sermon</L>
<L N="*2160">To parten amonge his bre&thorn;eren whan he come home</L>
<L N="2294">And &thorn;us is &thorn;is tale ydon</L>
<L N="2294">ffor we were almost at &thorn;e ton</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; Thus ende&thorn; &thorn;e somnours tale.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="E" TYPE="group">

<PB REF="00000365.tif" N="335">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="403">
<HEAD>GROUP <B>E.</B> FRAGMENT VI.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&sect; 1. THE CLERK'S HEAD-LINK.</HEAD>
<HEAD>PETWORTH MS.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ande here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> clerk of Oxenford<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 159</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sir Clerk of Oxenford our oost saide<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; The prologe;/</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;e ride as stille as Coy as do&thorn; a maide</L>
<L>Were newe spoused sitting at &thorn;e borde</L>
<L N="4">This day ne herd I of &yogh;oure mou&thorn; a word</L>
<L>I trowe &thorn;at &yogh;e stodye about som sophyme</L>
<L>But Salomon sei&thorn; al &thorn;inge ha&thorn; tyme</L>
<L>ffor goddes sake be&thorn; of better chere</L>
<L N="8">It is no tyme nowe to stody here</L>
<L>Telle vs some mery tale by &yogh;our fay</L>
<L>ffor what man is entred into a play</L>
<L>he nedes mote into &thorn;at play assent</L>
<L N="12">But pr[e]che&thorn; not as freres don in lent</L>
<L>To make vs for our olde synnes to wepe<MILESTONE N="159b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ne &thorn;at &thorn;i tale ne make vs not to sclepe</L>
<L>Telle vs somme mery &thorn;ing of auentures</L>
<L N="16">&YOGH;oure termes. &yogh;oure colours and figures</L>
<L>kepe hem in store til &yogh;e hem endite</L>
<L>hi&yogh;e stele as whan men to kyngges write</L>
<L>Speke&thorn; so pleyn at &thorn;is tyme I &yogh;ou prey</L>
<L N="20">That we may vnder-stonde what &yogh;e sey</L>
<L>This wor&thorn;i clerk benygnely answered</L>
<L>Hoost quod he I am vndere &yogh;our &yogh;eerde</L>
<L>&yogh;e han as nowe of vs &thorn;e gouernaunce</L>
<L N="24">And &thorn;erfor wil I do &yogh;ou obeysaunce
<PB REF="00000366.tif" N="336"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="404"></L>
<L>As fer as reson aske&thorn; hardely</L>
<L>I wil &yogh;ou tel a tale which &thorn;at I</L>
<L>lerned at Padowe of a wor&thorn;i clerke</L>
<L N="28">As preued by his wordys and his werk</L>
<L>He is nowe dede and nailed in his chest</L>
<L>I prei to god so send his soule good rest</L>
<L>ffraunceys Petrak &thorn;e laureol poete</L>
<L N="32">Hight/ &thorn;is clerke whoos retorike swete</L>
<L>Enlumyne&thorn; al Itaile &thorn;orgh poetrie</L>
<L>As lynyan did of Philosophye</L>
<L>Or lawe or o&thorn;er art particulere</L>
<L N="36">But de&thorn;e &thorn;at nyl suffre no &thorn;ing here</L>
<L>But as it were a twynkelinge of an ye</L>
<L>Bo&thorn; ha&thorn; he slayn and al shal we dye.</L>
<L>But forto tellen of &thorn;is wor&thorn;i man</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;at tau&yogh;t me &thorn;is tale as I first bygan</L>
<L>I sey &thorn;at he first wi&thorn; hygh steel endite&thorn;</L>
<L>Or he &thorn;e body of his tale write&thorn;</L>
<L>A procheyn in &thorn;e which disseuere&thorn; he</L>
<L N="44">&thorn;e Mounde and of Saluse &thorn;e contree</L>
<L>And speke&thorn; of Appenyn &thorn;e hilles hye</L>
<L>&thorn;at ben &thorn;e bondes of west lumbardye</L>
<L>And of Mount Resulus in special</L>
<L N="48">Wher as &thorn;e Poo out of a welle smal</L>
<L>Take&thorn; his furst spryngginge and his sours<MILESTONE N="160a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Wher as he holt euen strei&yogh;t way his cours</L>
<L>To Emel ward to ferrare and to venyse</L>
<L N="52">The which a longe &thorn;inge were to devise</L>
<L>And trewely as to my Iugement</L>
<L>Mee thenke&thorn; it a &thorn;ing inpertinent</L>
<L>Saue he wil conuey his matere</L>
<L N="56">But &thorn;is is &thorn;e tale which &thorn;at &yogh;e shal here</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; Thus ende&thorn;e &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;is tale &middot;</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000367.tif" N="337">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="405">
<HEAD>And here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e clerk his tale<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 160</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ther is at &thorn;e west side of ytayle<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; The tale;/</NOTE></L>
<L>Doune at &thorn;e rote of vesulus &thorn;e cold</L>
<L>A lusty pleyn abundant of vitaile</L>
<L>wher mony a toune &amp; tour<NOTE PLACE="marg">[&amp; tour <I>inter|lined by perhaps a later hand</I>]</NOTE> &thorn;ou maist bihold</L>
<L>&thorn;at founded were in tyme of elders olde</L>
<L>And mony ano&thorn;er delectable si&yogh;t</L>
<L N="63">And saluce &thorn;is noble cuntre hi&yogh;t</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="64">A Marquis whilom [lord] was in &thorn;at lond</L>
<L>As were his wor&thorn;i elders hym bifore</L>
<L>And Obeisaunt and redy to his hond</L>
<L N="67">Were alle his leeges bo&thorn; lasse and more</L>
<L>&THORN;us in delite he lyued and ha&thorn; do &yogh;ore</L>
<L>Be-loued and drad &thorn;ourgh fauour of fortune</L>
<L N="70">Bo&thorn; of his lordys and of his comune</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="71">Therwi&thorn; he was to speke of lynage</L>
<L>The gentelest y-born of al lumbardy</L>
<L>A faire persone . stronge and &yogh;enge of age</L>
<L N="74">And ful of honure and curteisie</L>
<L>Discrete ynou&yogh;e his cuntrey forto gye</L>
<L>Saue in some &thorn;ingges he was to blame</L>
<L N="77">And Water was &thorn;is yonge lordes name</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="78">I blame him &thorn;us &thorn;at he considered nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>In tyme commynge what my&yogh;t betide</L>
<L>But on his lust present was al his &thorn;ou&yogh;t<MILESTONE N="160b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="81">And forto hauke and hunte on euery side</L>
<L>Wel nye al o&thorn;er cures lete he slide</L>
<L>And eke he ne wold &thorn;at was worst of all</L>
<L N="84">Wedde no wif for ou&yogh;t my&yogh;t byfall
<PB REF="00000368.tif" N="338"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="406"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="85">Only &thorn;at pointe his puple bere so sore</L>
<L>&thorn;at flok-mele on a day &thorn;ei [to him] went</L>
<L>And oon of hem &thorn;at wisest was of lore</L>
<L N="88">Or ellis &thorn;at &thorn;e lorde wold best assent</L>
<L>&thorn;at he shulde telle hym what his puple ment</L>
<L>Or ellis coude he wel shewe such matere</L>
<L N="91">He to &thorn;e Marquis seide as &yogh;e mowe here</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L N="92">O Noble Marquis &yogh;oure humanitee</L>
<L>Assure&thorn; vs and &yogh;eueth vs hardynesse</L>
<L>As ofte tyme as it is necessite</L>
<L N="95">That we &yogh;ou mow telle our heuynesse</L>
<L>Accepte&thorn; lord of &yogh;our gentilnesse</L>
<L>&thorn;at we to &yogh;owe wi&thorn; pitous hert compleyne</L>
<L N="98">And lat &yogh;oure eeres not my vois disdeyne</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L N="99">Al haue I nou&yogh;t to done in &thorn;is matere</L>
<L>More &thorn;an ano&thorn;er ha&thorn; in &thorn;is place</L>
<L>&yogh;it for as moche as &yogh;e my lord so dere</L>
<L N="102">Haue alway shewed [me] fauour and grace</L>
<L>I dare &thorn;e better aske of &yogh;ou a space</L>
<L>Of audience to shewen our request</L>
<L N="105">And &yogh;e my lord to done ri&yogh;t as &yogh;ou lest</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L N="106">For certes lord so wel vs like&thorn; &yogh;ou</L>
<L>And alle &yogh;oure werkes and euer han do &thorn;at we</L>
<L>Ne cowde nat our owne silf devisen howe</L>
<L N="109">We my&yogh;t more lyve in felicite</L>
<L>Saue oo &thorn;inge lord if it &yogh;our wille be</L>
<L>That to be a wedded man if &yogh;ou list</L>
<L N="112">Than were our puple in souereyn hertes rest<MILESTONE N="161a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L N="113">Bowe&thorn; &yogh;oure nek vndere &thorn;at blisful &yogh;ok</L>
<L>Of souereynte nou&yogh;t of seruise</L>
<L>Which men clepe spousale or wedlok</L>
<L N="116">And &thorn;enke&thorn; lord among &yogh;oure &thorn;ou&yogh;tes wise
<PB REF="00000369.tif" N="339"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="407"></L>
<L>That of wedloke comme&thorn; grete emprise</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou&yogh;e we slepe or wake ronne or ride</L>
<L N="119">Ay flee&thorn; &thorn;e tyme it wil no man abide.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L N="120">And &thorn;ou&yogh;e &yogh;our grene &yogh;ou&thorn;e growe as &yogh;it</L>
<L>In crepe&thorn; age alway as stille as stone</L>
<L>And de&thorn;e manase&thorn; euery age and smyt</L>
<L N="123">In eche astate for &thorn;er ascape&thorn; noon</L>
<L>And also certeyn as we knowe euerichon</L>
<L>&THORN;at we shul dye as vncerteyn we all</L>
<L N="126">Ben of &thorn;at day &thorn;at de&thorn; shal on vs falle</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L N="127">Accepteth &thorn;an of vs &thorn;e trewe entent</L>
<L>That neuere &yogh;it refused your heest</L>
<L>And we wil al lord &yogh;if &yogh;e wil assent</L>
<L N="130">Chese &yogh;ou a wif in short tyme at the lest</L>
<L>Born of &thorn;e gentelest and of &thorn;e mest</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;is londe so &thorn;at it out seme</L>
<L N="133">Honure to god and &yogh;ou. so as we con deme</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L N="134">Delyuere vs of al &thorn;is bysy drede</L>
<L>And take a wif for hi&yogh;e goddis sake</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;if it byfelle so as god forbede</L>
<L N="137">&thorn;at &thorn;ourgh de&thorn; &yogh;our lynage shuld sclake</L>
<L>And a straunge lynage shuld take</L>
<L>&YOGH;our heritage. oo woo were vs alyue</L>
<L N="140">Wherfore we prey &yogh;ou hastely to wif</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L N="141">Her meke preier &amp; her pitous chere</L>
<L>Made &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> Marquis haue such pite</L>
<L>Wil &yogh;e quod he myne owne puple dere<MILESTONE N="161b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="144">To &thorn;at I neuer erst &thorn;ou&yogh;t constreyne me</L>
<L>I me reioyse not of my liberte</L>
<L>&thorn;at seelden tyme is found in mariage</L>
<L N="147">Ther I was free I mot bene in seruage
<PB REF="00000370.tif" N="340"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="408"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="148">But na&thorn;elees I se &yogh;oure trewe entent</L>
<L>And trust vpon &yogh;ou and haue don ay</L>
<L>Wherfore of my fre wille I assent</L>
<L N="151">To wedde me as sone as euer I may</L>
<L>But &thorn;er as &yogh;e han profered me to day</L>
<L>To chese me a wif I &yogh;ou relese</L>
<L N="154">That chois; &amp; prei &yogh;ou of &yogh;our propher cese</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L N="155">For god it wote &thorn;at children oft ben</L>
<L>Vnlike her wor&thorn;i eldres hem bifore</L>
<L>Bounte comme&thorn; al of god not of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> strene</L>
<L N="158">Of which &thorn;ei ben engendred and ybore</L>
<L>I Trust in goddys bounte and &thorn;erfore</L>
<L>My mariage and my astate and rest</L>
<L N="161">I hym bitake he may do as hym lest</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L N="162">Lat me allone in chesing of my wiff</L>
<L>That charge vpon my bak I wil endure</L>
<L>But I &yogh;ou prey and charge vpon &yogh;our lif</L>
<L N="165">&THORN;at wif &thorn;at I take &yogh;e me ensure</L>
<L>To worship hur whil our lyf endure</L>
<L>In worde and werke bo&thorn; here and ellys where</L>
<L N="168">As she an emperours dou&yogh;ter were</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L N="169">And fer&thorn;ermore &thorn;is shullen &yogh;e swere &thorn;at &yogh;e</L>
<L>A&yogh;einst my chose shul nei&thorn;er grucche ne stryue</L>
<L>ffor si&thorn; I shal forgo my liberte</L>
<L N="172">At &yogh;oure request as euer mot I thryue</L>
<L>Ther as myn hert is sette &thorn;er wil I wyue</L>
<L>And but &yogh;e wollen assent in such manere</L>
<L N="175">I prey &yogh;ou speke&thorn; no more of &thorn;is matere<MILESTONE N="162a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L N="176">Wi&thorn; harty wille &thorn;ei sweren and assenten</L>
<L>To al &thorn;is &thorn;inge &thorn;er seide no wi&yogh;t nay</L>
<L>Bisechinge hym of grace er &thorn;ei wenten</L>
<L N="179">That he hem wold graunten a certeyn day
<PB REF="00000371.tif" N="341"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="409"></L>
<L>Of his spousale as sone as euer he may</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;it alway &thorn;e puple somwhat dredde</L>
<L N="182">Lesse &thorn;is Marquis wol no wif wedde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="183">He graunted hem a day such as hym lest</L>
<L>On which he wolde be wedded sikerly</L>
<L>And seide he did al &thorn;is at her request</L>
<L N="186">And &thorn;ei wi&thorn; humble entent ful buxomly</L>
<L>Knelinge vpon her knees ful reuerently</L>
<L>Hym &thorn;onken alle and &thorn;us &thorn;ei han an ende</L>
<L N="189">Of her entent and home a&yogh;ein &thorn;ei wende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="190">And here vpon he toke his officers</L>
<L>Commaundinge for &thorn;e fest to purueye</L>
<L>And to his privey kny&yogh;tes and sqwiers</L>
<L N="193">Such charge &yogh;af hem . as hym lust on hem to leye</L>
<L>And &thorn;ei his comaundementz to obeye</L>
<L>And ech of hem do&thorn; his diligence</L>
<L N="196">To done vnto &thorn;e fest reuerence</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[PART THE SECOND.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="197">Nou&yogh;t fer from &thorn;ilk place honurable</L>
<L>wher as &thorn;is Marquis shope his mariage</L>
<L>&thorn;er stoode a Thrope of si&yogh;t delectable</L>
<L N="200">In which poor folk of &thorn;at vilage</L>
<L>Hadden her beestes and her harbigage</L>
<L>And of her labour toke her sustinaunce</L>
<L N="203">After &thorn;e er&thorn;e hem &yogh;aue abundaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="204">Among &thorn;ise poor folk &thorn;er dwelled a man</L>
<L>which &thorn;at was holden porest of hem all</L>
<L>But hegh god somtyme sende can<MILESTONE N="162b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="207">His grace vnto a litel oxes stall</L>
<L>Ianicula men of &thorn;at thrope hym calle</L>
<L>A doughter had he faire and &yogh;ong of si&yogh;t</L>
<L N="210">And Grisild &thorn;is &yogh;onge maiden hi&yogh;t
<PB REF="00000372.tif" N="342"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="410"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="211">But forto speke of vertuous bewte</L>
<L>&thorn;an was she oon &thorn;e fairest vnder sonne</L>
<L>fful poorly yfostred was she</L>
<L N="214">No licorousnesse was on her lust yronne</L>
<L>Wel ofter of &thorn;e well &thorn;an of &thorn;e tunne</L>
<L>She drank / and for she wole vertue plese</L>
<L N="217">She knewe wel labour but non ydel ese</L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(24)</HEAD>
<L N="218">But &thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;is maide were tender of age</L>
<L>&YOGH;it in &thorn;e brest of her virginite</L>
<L>&thorn;ere was enclosed ripe and sad corage</L>
<L N="221">And in grete reuerence and in grete charite</L>
<L>Her olde poor fadere fostred shee</L>
<L>A fewe shepe spynnyng on &thorn;e felde she kept</L>
<L N="224">She wolde not ben ydel til she sclepte</L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(25)</HEAD>
<L N="225">And whan she homward come she wolde bringe</L>
<L>wortes and herbes tymes ful oft</L>
<L>which she shradde and si&thorn; for her lyuyng</L>
<L N="228">And made her bedde ful hard and no &thorn;ing soft</L>
<L>And euere she kept her faders lif on loft</L>
<L>wi&thorn; euery obeisaunce and diligence</L>
<L N="231">That childe may do to faders reuerence</L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(26)</HEAD>
<L N="232">Vppon Grisilde &thorn;e poor creature</L>
<L>fful oft ha&thorn; Marquis sette hys eye</L>
<L>As he on hundyinge rode perauenture</L>
<L N="235">And whan it felle &thorn;at he my&yogh;t hir espye</L>
<L>he not wi&thorn; wa[n]ton lokinge of foly</L>
<L>his eyen cast vpon hur but in sad wise</L>
<L N="238">Vpon her chere he wold hym oft avise<MILESTONE N="163a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(27)</HEAD>
<L N="239">Commending in his hert her wommanhede</L>
<L>And eke her vertue passing eny wi&yogh;t</L>
<L>Of so &yogh;onge age as wel in chere as in dede</L>
<L N="242">ffor &thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;e puple haue no gret insi&yogh;t
<PB REF="00000373.tif" N="343"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="411"></L>
<L>In vertue he considered ful ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>Her bewte and disposed &thorn;at he wold</L>
<L N="245">Hir wedde if euer he wedde shuld</L>
</LG>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(28)</HEAD>
<L N="246">The day of weddyng come but no wi&yogh;t can</L>
<L>Telle what womman it shuld be</L>
<L>ffor which mervaile wondred mony man</L>
<L N="249">And seiden whan &thorn;ei weren in priuete</L>
<L>wil not our lorde leue his vanyte</L>
<L>wil he not wedde alas alas &thorn;e while</L>
<L N="252">whi wil he hym self and vs &thorn;us begile</L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(29)</HEAD>
<L N="253">But na-&thorn;e-lees &thorn;is marquis ha&thorn; do make</L>
<L>Of Gemmes sette in gold and in asure</L>
<L>Broches and ryngges for grisild sake</L>
<L N="256">And of her clo&thorn;ing toke he &thorn;e mesure</L>
<L>Of a maide like to her stature</L>
<L>And eke of o&thorn;er ornamentes all</L>
<L N="259">&thorn;at to such a wedding shul fall</L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(30)</HEAD>
<L N="260">The tyme of vndern &thorn;e same day</L>
<L>Approche&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;is wedding shulde be</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e paleys putt was in aray</L>
<L N="263">Both halle and chambres ech in his degre</L>
<L>Houses of office . stuffed wi&thorn; grete plente</L>
<L>&THORN;er maist &thorn;ou see of deynteuous vitaile</L>
<L N="266">&thorn;at may be found as fer as laste&thorn; ytaile</L>
</LG>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(31)</HEAD>
<L N="267">This rial Marquis rially araied.</L>
<L>lordys and ladys in his companye</L>
<L>&thorn;e which to &thorn;e feest were preied /<MILESTONE N="163b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="270">And of his retenwe &thorn;e bachelerye</L>
<L>wi&thorn; mony a soune of sondry melodye</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e vilage [of &thorn;e] which I told</L>
<L N="273">In &thorn;is aray &thorn;e ri&yogh;te way ha&thorn; hold
<PB REF="00000374.tif" N="344"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="412"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="274">Griseld god wote of &thorn;is ful Innocent</L>
<L>&thorn;at for hure was shape al &thorn;is aray</L>
<L>To fecchen watere at &thorn;e welle is went</L>
<L N="277">And comme&thorn; home as sone as euer she may</L>
<L>ffor wel she herd say &thorn;at ilk day</L>
<L>&thorn;at Marquis shuld wedde and if she my&yogh;t</L>
<L N="280">She wold fayn see somme of &thorn;at si&yogh;t</L>
</LG>
<LG N="33" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(33)</HEAD>
<L N="281">She &thorn;ou&yogh;t I wil wi&thorn; o&thorn;er maidens stond</L>
<L>&thorn;at bene my felawes in oure door and see</L>
<L>The Marquis and &thorn;erfor wil I fonde</L>
<L N="284">To done at home as sone as it may be</L>
<L>&THORN;e laboure which &thorn;at longe&thorn; vnto me</L>
<L>And &thorn;an may I at leisere it byhold</L>
<L N="287">If she &thorn;is way to &thorn;e castel holde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="34" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(34)</HEAD>
<L N="288">And as she wolde ouer &thorn;e thresshold gon</L>
<L>The Marquis come and can hur forto calle</L>
<L>And she sette doune her water pot anon</L>
<L N="291">beside &thorn;e thresshold of &thorn;e oxes stalle</L>
<L>And doun vpon her knees she gan to falle</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; sadde countenaunce kneled stille</L>
<L N="294">Til she had herde what was &thorn;e lordes wille</L>
</LG>
<LG N="35" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(35)</HEAD>
<L N="295">This &thorn;ou&yogh;tful Marquys spake vnto &thorn;is maide</L>
<L>wel soberly and seide in &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>where is &yogh;oure fader Griseld he seide</L>
<L N="298">And she wi&thorn; reuerence and meke chere</L>
<L>Answered lord he is al redy here</L>
<L>And Inne she goo&thorn; wi&thorn;-out lenger lette</L>
<L N="301">And to &thorn;e Marquis she her fadere fette.<MILESTONE N="164a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="36" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(36)</HEAD>
<L N="302">He by &thorn;e honde &thorn;an toke &thorn;is olde man</L>
<L>And seide him &thorn;us whan he hym had a side</L>
<L>Ianicula I nei&thorn;er may ne can</L>
<L N="305">lenger &thorn;e plesaunce of myn herte hide
<PB REF="00000375.tif" N="345"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="413"></L>
<L>If &thorn;at &yogh;e vouchesauf what so be-tide</L>
<L>&thorn;i dou&yogh;ter wil I take er &thorn;at I wende</L>
<L N="308">As for my wif to my lyues end</L>
</LG>
<LG N="37" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(37)</HEAD>
<L N="309">Thow louest me I woot wel certeyn</L>
<L>And art my fei&thorn;-ful liege man ybore</L>
<L>And al &thorn;at like&thorn; me I dar wel seyn</L>
<L N="312">It like&thorn; &thorn;e and specialy &thorn;erfore</L>
<L>Tel me &thorn;at poynt &thorn;at I haue seide byfore</L>
<L>If &thorn;at &thorn;owe wolde vnto &thorn;at purpoos drawe</L>
<L N="315">To take me as for &thorn;ine sone in lawe</L>
</LG>
<LG N="38" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(38)</HEAD>
<L N="316">The sodeyn caas &thorn;e man astonyed soo /</L>
<L>&thorn;at rede he wexe al basshed and al quakinge</L>
<L>He stood and vnne&thorn;es seide wordes moo</L>
<L N="319">But only &thorn;us lord quod he my willinge</L>
<L>Is as &yogh;e wol not a&yogh;einst &yogh;our likinge</L>
<L>I wil no &thorn;inge &yogh;e be my lorde so dere</L>
<L N="322">Ri&yogh;t as &yogh;ou lest gouerne&thorn; &thorn;is matere</L>
</LG>
<LG N="39" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(39)</HEAD>
<L N="323">Than wil I do &thorn;us quod Marquis softly</L>
<L>&thorn;at in to &thorn;e chambre I and &thorn;ou. and she</L>
<L>haue a collacion and woost &thorn;ou why</L>
<L N="326">ffor I wil aske hur &yogh;if hir wil be</L>
<L>To be my wif and rewle hir after me</L>
<L>And al &thorn;is she shal done in &thorn;i presence</L>
<L N="329">I wil not speke out of &thorn;ine audience</L>
</LG>
<LG N="40" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(40)</HEAD>
<L N="330">And in &thorn;e Chambere while &thorn;ei were aboute</L>
<L>Her tretis which &yogh;e shul after here</L>
<L>&THORN;e puple come into &thorn;e hous withoute</L>
<L N="333">And wondred hem in howe honest manere<MILESTONE N="164b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And tentifly she kepte hur fadere dere</L>
<L>But vtterly grisild wonder my&yogh;t</L>
<L N="336">ffor neuere erst sey she shuch a si&yogh;t
<PB REF="00000376.tif" N="346"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="414"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="337">No wonder is &thorn;ou&yogh;e she be astonyed</L>
<L>To se so grete a gest come in &thorn;at place</L>
<L>She was neuere to suche gestys wonned</L>
<L N="340">ffor which she loked wi&thorn; ful pale face</L>
<L>But shortly fro &thorn;is matere forto pace</L>
<L>Thise were &thorn;e wordes &thorn;at &thorn;is marquis saide</L>
<L N="343">To &thorn;is benygne verrey fei&thorn;ful mayde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="42" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(42)</HEAD>
<L N="344">Grisyle he seide &yogh;e wol wel vnderstonde</L>
<L>It like&thorn; vnto &yogh;oure fadere and me</L>
<L>&THORN;at I &yogh;ou wedde and eke it may so stonde</L>
<L N="347">As I suppose &thorn;at &yogh;e wil it so be</L>
<L>But &thorn;is demaunde I axe furst quod he</L>
<L>That si&thorn;en it shal be don on hastif wise</L>
<L N="350">Wol &yogh;e assent or ellis &yogh;owe avise</L>
</LG>
<LG N="43" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(43)</HEAD>
<L N="351">I seye &thorn;is be &yogh;e redy with good hert</L>
<L>To al my lust and &thorn;at I frely may</L>
<L>As me best &thorn;enke&thorn; do &yogh;ou lawgh or smert</L>
<L N="354">And &yogh;e neuer gruch ny&yogh;t ne day</L>
<L>And eke whan I seie &yogh;e say &yogh;e not nay</L>
<L>Nei&thorn;er be word ne fraward countenance</L>
<L N="357">Swere &thorn;is and here I swere our aliance</L>
</LG>
<LG N="44" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(44)</HEAD>
<L N="358">WOndringe vpon &thorn;is worde quaking for drede</L>
<L>She seide Indigne and vnwor&thorn;i</L>
<L>Am I to &thorn;at [honour] &thorn;at &yogh;e me bede</L>
<L N="361">But ri&yogh;t as ye wil &yogh;our self ri&yogh;t so wil I</L>
<L>And [here] I swere &thorn;at neuer willingly</L>
<L>In word ne &thorn;ou&yogh;t I neuere &yogh;ou disobeye</L>
<L N="364">ffor to be dede &thorn;ou&yogh;e me were lo&thorn;e to deye</L>
</LG>
<LG N="45" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(45)</HEAD>
<L N="365">This is ynowe Grisile myn quod he<MILESTONE N="165a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And for&thorn; he go&thorn; wi&thorn; a sobre chere</L>
<L>Out at &thorn;e door after cam she</L>
<L N="368">And to &thorn;e puple he seide in &thorn;is manere
<PB REF="00000377.tif" N="347"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="415"></L>
<L>This is my wif quod he &thorn;at stonde&thorn; here</L>
<L>Honoure&thorn; hir and loueth [hire] I prey</L>
<L N="371">Who so loue&thorn; me &thorn;er nys no more to seye</L>
</LG>
<LG N="46" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(46)</HEAD>
<L N="372">And for no &thorn;ing of hure olde gere</L>
<L>She shuld bring to his hous he bade</L>
<L>&thorn;at wommen shulden spulen hir ri&yogh;t &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="375">Of which &thorn;e ladies were not ri&yogh;t glade</L>
<L>To handel her clo&thorn;es in which she was clad</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles &thorn;is maiden bri&yogh;t of hwe</L>
<L N="378">ffrom fote to hede yclo&thorn;ed han al newe</L>
</LG>
<LG N="47" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(47)</HEAD>
<L N="379">Her heres han &thorn;ei kembed &thorn;at lay vntressed</L>
<L>wel rwdely with her fyngeres smale</L>
<L>And a crowne on her hede &thorn;ei han dressed</L>
<L N="382">Isette ful of owches grete and smal</L>
<L>Of hir aray what shuld I make a tale</L>
<L>Vnne&thorn;es &thorn;e puple hir knewe for her fairnesse</L>
<L N="385">Whan she transformed was in such richesse</L>
</LG>
<LG N="48" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(48)</HEAD>
<L N="386">&para; This Marquis ha&thorn; hure spoused wi&thorn; a rynge</L>
<L>Bou&yogh;t for &thorn;e same cause an &thorn;an hir sette</L>
<L>vppon an hors snowe white and wel amblynge</L>
<L N="389">And to his palaies er he lenger lette</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Ioiful puple &thorn;at he lad and mette</L>
<L>Conveied hir and &thorn;us &thorn;e day &thorn;ei spende</L>
<L N="392">In reuel to &thorn;e sonne canne descende</L>
</LG>
<LG N="49" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(49)</HEAD>
<L N="393">And shortely for&thorn; &thorn;is tale forto chace</L>
<L>I sey &thorn;at to &thorn;is newe Marquissesse</L>
<L>God ha&thorn; ysent such favour of his grace</L>
<L N="396">&thorn;at it semed not as by liknesse</L>
<L>That she was born and fedde in rudenesse<MILESTONE N="165b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As in a Cote ar in an oxes stalle</L>
<L N="399">But norshed in an Emperours halle
<PB REF="00000378.tif" N="348"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="416"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="400">To euery wi&yogh;t she woxen is so dere</L>
<L>And worshipful &thorn;at folk &thorn;er she was bore</L>
<L>And from her birth knewe her fro &yogh;ere to &yogh;ere</L>
<L N="403">Vnne&thorn; trowed &thorn;ei but durst haue swore</L>
<L>&thorn;at to Ianicle of which I speke byfore</L>
<L>She dou&yogh;tere ne were for as by coniecture</L>
<L N="406">hem &thorn;ou&yogh;t she was a no&thorn;er creature</L>
</LG>
<LG N="51" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(51)</HEAD>
<L N="407">ffor [&thorn;ou&yogh;e] &thorn;at euere vertuous was she</L>
<L>She was encresed in such excellence</L>
<L>Of thewe sette in high bounte</L>
<L N="410">And so discrete and faire of eloquence</L>
<L>So benygne and digne of reuerence</L>
<L>And coude &thorn;e puples hertes so enbrace</L>
<L N="413">&thorn;at ech her loued &thorn;at loked on her face</L>
</LG>
<LG N="52" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(52)</HEAD>
<L N="414">Nou&yogh;t only of saluce in &thorn;e toun</L>
<L>Publisshed was &thorn;e bounte of her name</L>
<L>And eke be-side in mony a regioun</L>
<L N="417">If oon seide wel ano&thorn;er seide &thorn;e same</L>
<L>So spradde of hure bounte &thorn;e fame</L>
<L>That men and wommen bo&thorn; &yogh;onge and olde</L>
<L N="420">Goon to saluse hur to be-holde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="53" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(53)</HEAD>
<L N="421">This walter . lowly nay but ryally</L>
<L>wedde&thorn; wi&thorn; fortune honeste</L>
<L>In goddes pees lyuen wel esely</L>
<L N="424">At hoom and outward grace yno&yogh;e had he</L>
<L>And for he sawe vnder lowe degre</L>
<L>was oft vertue hid &thorn;e puple hym helde</L>
<L N="427">A prudent man and &thorn;at is sene wel selde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="54" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(54)</HEAD>
<L N="428">Nou&yogh;t only Grisile &thorn;us &thorn;orgh her witte</L>
<L>Cou&thorn;e al &thorn;e fete of wively humblenesse<MILESTONE N="166a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But eke whan &thorn;e cas required it</L>
<L N="431">The comon profite coude she redresse
<PB REF="00000379.tif" N="349"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="417"></L>
<L>Ther nas no discord rancour ne heuynesse</L>
<L>In al &thorn;e londe &thorn;at she ne coude it cese</L>
<L N="434">And bring hem al wisely in rest and ese</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="435">Though &thorn;at hur husbond present were anon</L>
<L>&yogh;if Gentil men or o&thorn;er of her contre</L>
<L>were wroo&thorn; she cowde bringe hem at on</L>
<L N="438">So wise and rype wordes had she</L>
<L>And Iuggement of so grete equite</L>
<L>That she fro heuene was as men wende<NOTE PLACE="marg">[this line is re|peated in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="441">Puple to saue and euery wrong tamende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="442">Not longe tyme aftere &thorn;at &thorn;is grisild</L>
<L>Was wedded she a dou&yogh;ter ha&thorn; ybore</L>
<L>Al had she leuer born a knaue child</L>
<L N="445">Glad was &thorn;e Marquis and his folk &thorn;erfore</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou&yogh;e a mayde childe come al byfore</L>
<L>She may to a knaue childe atteyne</L>
<L N="448">By liklihede si&thorn;ens she is not bareyne</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[THE THIRD PART.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="449">Therfor as it falle&thorn; tymes moo</L>
<L>That &thorn;is childe ha&thorn; sowked but a thrawe</L>
<L>This marquis in his hert longe&thorn; so</L>
<L N="452">To tempte his wif her sadnesse to knowe</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne my&yogh;t fro his hert throwe</L>
<L>&THORN;is merveilous desire his wif tassay</L>
<L N="455">Na&thorn;e-lees god wote he &thorn;ou&yogh;t hir to affray</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="456">He had assaied hir ynou&yogh;e to-fore</L>
<L>And fonde hur euer good what nede&thorn; It</L>
<L>Hir forto torment and alway more and more</L>
<L N="459">&thorn;ou&yogh;e somme preise it for a subtile witte</L>
<L>But as for me I saie &thorn;at euel it sitte<MILESTONE N="166b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To assaie a wif whan it is no nede</L>
<L N="462">And putten hure in angwissh and in drede
<PB REF="00000380.tif" N="350"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="418"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="463">For which &thorn;is Marquis wrou&yogh;t in &thorn;is ma[ne]re</L>
<L>He came a nyght alon &thorn;er as she lay</L>
<L>wi&thorn; steerne face and trouble chere</L>
<L N="466">And seide &thorn;oo Griseld quo&thorn; he &thorn;at day</L>
<L>&thorn;at I &yogh;ou toke out of &yogh;oure poor aray</L>
<L>And putte &yogh;ou in estate of hie noblesse</L>
<L N="469">&yogh;e han not &yogh;it for&yogh;eten as I gesse</L>
</LG>
<LG N="60" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(60)</HEAD>
<L N="470">I seye Griseld &thorn;is present dignite</L>
<L>In which I haue put &yogh;ou as I trowe</L>
<L>Make&thorn; not &yogh;ou for&yogh;etful forto be</L>
<L N="473">&thorn;at I &yogh;ou toke in poor estate ful lowe</L>
<L>ffor eny &thorn;inge &yogh;e mote &yogh;oure seluen knowe</L>
<L>Take hede of euery word &thorn;at I &yogh;ou seie</L>
<L N="476">ther is no wi&yogh;t &thorn;at here&thorn; &thorn;is but we tweye</L>
</LG>
<LG N="61" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(61)</HEAD>
<L N="477">&YOGH;e wote &yogh;our self wele howe &thorn;at &yogh;e come here</L>
<L>Into &thorn;is hous it is not long ago</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou&yogh;e to me &yogh;e be leef and dere</L>
<L N="480">vnto my gentiles &yogh;e be no &thorn;ing so</L>
<L>&thorn;ei seyn to hem it is grete shame and woo</L>
<L>fforto be sogette and in seruage</L>
<L N="483">To &thorn;e &thorn;at art born of so lowe lynage</L>
</LG>
<LG N="62" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(62)</HEAD>
<L N="484">And namely si&thorn; &thorn;i dou&yogh;ter was bore</L>
<L>&thorn;ise wordes han &thorn;ei spoke doutlees</L>
<L>But I desire as I haue don byfore</L>
<L N="487">To lyve my lif wi&thorn; hem in rest and pees</L>
<L>I may not in &thorn;is cas bene rechelees</L>
<L>I most don wi&thorn; [&thorn;i] dou&yogh;tere for &thorn;e best</L>
<L N="490">nou&yogh;t as I wold but as my gentils lest</L>
</LG>
<LG N="63" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(63)</HEAD>
<L N="491">And &yogh;it god woot &thorn;is is ful lo&thorn; to me</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles wi&thorn; outen &yogh;our wetynge<MILESTONE N="167a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I nyl not doo but &thorn;is I wil quod he</L>
<L N="494">&thorn;at &yogh;e to me assent as in &thorn;is &thorn;inge
<PB REF="00000381.tif" N="351"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="419"></L>
<L>Shewe&thorn; now &yogh;oure pacience in &yogh;our worchinge</L>
<L>That &yogh;e me byhi&yogh;t and swore in &yogh;our vilage</L>
<L N="497">That day &thorn;at maked was our mariage</L>
</LG>
<LG N="64" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(64)</HEAD>
<L N="498">Whan she had herde al &thorn;is she was not amoued</L>
<L>Nei&thorn;er in word or chere or countenaunce</L>
<L>ffor as it semed she was not agreued</L>
<L N="501">She seid lorde all lith in &yogh;oure plesaunce</L>
<L>My childe and I wi&thorn; hertely obeisance</L>
<L>Bene &yogh;oures all and &yogh;e may saue and spille</L>
<L N="504">&yogh;oure owne &thorn;ing wheder &thorn;at &yogh;e wille</L>
</LG>
<LG N="65" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(65)</HEAD>
<L N="505">Ther may no &thorn;inge so god my saule saue</L>
<L>likinge to &yogh;ou &thorn;at may displese me</L>
<L>Ne I desire no &thorn;inge to haue</L>
<L N="508">Ne drede to lese saue only &yogh;e</L>
<L>This wille is my hert and ay shal be</L>
<L>No length of tyme or de&thorn; it may deface</L>
<L N="511">Nei&thorn;e chaunge my corage into o&thorn;er place</L>
</LG>
<LG N="66" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(66)</HEAD>
<L N="512">Glad was &thorn;e Marquis of hur answering</L>
<L>But &yogh;it he feyned as he were not so.</L>
<L>Al drery was his chere and his lokinge</L>
<L N="515">whan she shuld out of &thorn;e chamber goo</L>
<L>Sone after &thorn;is a forlong way or twoo</L>
<L>he pleynly ha&thorn; told his entent</L>
<L N="518">Vnto a man which he to his wif sent</L>
</LG>
<LG N="67" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(67)</HEAD>
<L N="519">A maner sergeaunt was &thorn;is privey man</L>
<L>&thorn;e which &thorn;at feithful fond yhad</L>
<L>In &thorn;ingges grete and eke such folk wel can</L>
<L N="522">Don execucion of &thorn;ingges bad</L>
<L>&thorn;e lord knewe wel &thorn;at he hym loued and drad.</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is sergeaunt wist his lordes will<MILESTONE N="167b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="525">Into &thorn;e chambere he stalked hym ful still
<PB REF="00000382.tif" N="352"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="420"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="526">Madame he seide &yogh;e mote for&yogh;eue it me</L>
<L>&thorn;ough I do &thorn;inge to which I am constreyned /</L>
<L>&YOGH;e bene so wise &thorn;at wel knowe &yogh;e</L>
<L N="529">&thorn;at lordes heestes may not be feyned</L>
<L>&thorn;ei mowen wel be wailed or compleyned</L>
<L>But men mote nede vnto her lust obeye</L>
<L N="532">And so wil I &thorn;er nys no more to seye</L>
</LG>
<LG N="69" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(69)</HEAD>
<L N="533">That childe I am commaunded to take</L>
<L>And spake no more but out &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> child he hent</L>
<L>Despitously and gan a chere make</L>
<L N="536">As he wold han slayn it &thorn;er he went</L>
<L>Griseld mot al suffre and al consent</L>
<L>And as a lombe she sitte&thorn; meke and stille</L>
<L N="539">And lete &thorn;is cruel Seriaunt haue his wille</L>
</LG>
<LG N="70" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(70)</HEAD>
<L N="540">Suspecte was &thorn;e name of &thorn;is man</L>
<L>Suspecte his face . suspecte his world also</L>
<L>Suspecte &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at he &thorn;is bygan/</L>
<L N="543">ffor his dou&yogh;ter &thorn;at she loued soo</L>
<L>She wende he wold haue slayn it ri&yogh;t &thorn;oo</L>
<L>But na&thorn;elees she nei&thorn;er wepte ne seide</L>
<L N="546">Confeermyng hur to &thorn;at &thorn;e Marquis seide</L>
</LG>
<LG N="71" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(71)</HEAD>
<L N="547">And at &thorn;e last speke she bygan</L>
<L>And nekely to &thorn;e sergeant preide</L>
<L>So as he was a wor&thorn;i gentil man</L>
<L N="550">&thorn;at she my&yogh;t kisse her childe er &thorn;at it deide</L>
<L>And in her barme &thorn;is litel childe she leide</L>
<L>wi&thorn; ful sadde face and gan &thorn;e childe to blisse</L>
<L N="553">And lulled it and after gan it kisse</L>
</LG>
<LG N="72" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(72)</HEAD>
<L N="554">And &thorn;us she seide in her benigne voys</L>
<L>fare wele my child I shal &thorn;e neuere see</L>
<L>But si&thorn; I haue Marked &thorn;e wi&thorn; croys</L>
<L N="557">Of &thorn;ilk sadere yblessed mot &thorn;ou be<MILESTONE N="168a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000383.tif" N="353"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="421"></L>
<L>&thorn;at for vs deyed vpon &thorn;e rood tre.</L>
<L>&thorn;i soule litel childe I hym bytake</L>
<L N="560">ffor &thorn;is ny&yogh;t shalt &thorn;ou dyen for my sake</L>
</LG>
<LG N="73" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(73)</HEAD>
<L N="561">I trowe &thorn;at to a norice in &thorn;is caas /</L>
<L>It had ben hard &thorn;is rew&thorn;e forto see</L>
<L>Wel my&yogh;t a modere &thorn;an cry alas /</L>
<L N="564">But na&thorn;eles so sadde and stedfast was she</L>
<L>&THORN;at she endured al hur aduersite</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e Sergeant meke she seide</L>
<L N="567">Haue here a&yogh;ein my litel &yogh;onge maide</L>
</LG>
<LG N="74" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(74)</HEAD>
<L N="568">And go&thorn; now quod she and do&thorn; my lordes heest</L>
<L>And oon &thorn;inge wold I prei of &yogh;oure grace</L>
<L>That but my lorde forbede &yogh;ou at lest</L>
<L N="571">Burie&thorn; &thorn;is litel body in som place</L>
<L>&THORN;at no beestes no briddes it to-race</L>
<L>But he no word to &thorn;o purpoos wold saye</L>
<L N="574">But toke &thorn;e childe and went vpon his way</L>
</LG>
<LG N="75" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(75)</HEAD>
<L N="575">This Sergeant come to &thorn;e lord ageyn</L>
<L>And of Griseldes wordes and of her chere</L>
<L>He tolde hym poynt by poynt in short and pleyn</L>
<L N="578">And hym presented wi&thorn; his dou&yogh;ter dere</L>
<L>Somwhat &thorn;is lord had raw&thorn;e in his manere</L>
<L>But na&thorn;elees his purpoos helde he stille</L>
<L N="581">As lordes don whan &thorn;ei wil han her wille</L>
</LG>
<LG N="76" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(76)</HEAD>
<L N="582">And bad &thorn;is Sergeant ful priveily</L>
<L>he shuld ful soft &thorn;is child welde and wrappe</L>
<L>with al &thorn;e circumstance tenderly</L>
<L N="585">And carie it in a coffre or in a lappe</L>
<L>But vp peyn his hede of for to swappe</L>
<L>&thorn;at no man shuld knowe of his entent</L>
<L N="588">Ne whens he come ne whidere he went
<PB REF="00000384.tif" N="354"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="422"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="589">&para; But at Boloyne to his suster dere<MILESTONE N="168b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;oo of Pavie was countesse</L>
<L>He shuld her take and shew hir &thorn;is matere</L>
<L N="592">Bisechinge hure to don her bysynesse</L>
<L>This childe to fostere in al gladnesse</L>
<L>And whoos childe &thorn;at it was he bad hir hide</L>
<L N="595">ffrom euery wi&yogh;t for ou&yogh;t &thorn;at my&yogh;t betide</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="596">This Sergeaunt go&thorn; and ha&thorn; fulfilled &thorn;is &thorn;inge</L>
<L>But to &thorn;is marquis nowe retourne we</L>
<L>ffor nowe go&thorn; he wel oft ymagynynge</L>
<L N="599">If by his wif [chere] he myght See</L>
<L>And by hir wordes perceyue &thorn;at she</L>
<L>Were chaunged but he coude neuere fynde.</L>
<L N="602">But euere in oon ylik sad and kinde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="603">As glad as humble as bysy in seruise</L>
<L>and Eke in loue as she was wont to be</L>
<L>Was she to hym in euery manere wise</L>
<L N="606">Ne of her dou&yogh;ter oon worde speke she</L>
<L>Noon accident for noon aduersite</L>
<L>Was seen in hir ne neuere her dou&yogh;ter name</L>
<L N="609">Nempned she for ernest ne for game</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="4" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[THE FOURTH PART.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="610">In &thorn;is estate passed ben foure &yogh;ere</L>
<L>Er she wi&thorn; child was but as god wold</L>
<L>A knaue childe she bere by &thorn;is waltere</L>
<L N="613">fful gracious and faire to biholde</L>
<L>And whan folk it to hir fadere tolde</L>
<L>Not oonly he But al &thorn;e contree mery</L>
<L N="616">Was for &thorn;e child and god &thorn;ei &thorn;onke and herye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="617">Whan it was two &yogh;ere olde and from &thorn;e brest</L>
<L>Departed from his norce vpon a day</L>
<L>&thorn;is Marquis kaught &yogh;it anoth[er] lest
<PB REF="00000385.tif" N="355"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="423"></L>
<L N="620">To tempten his wif ofter if he may</L>
<L>O nedeles was she tempted in assay<MILESTONE N="169a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But wedded men knowen no mesure</L>
<L N="623">Whan &thorn;ei fynde a pacient creature</L>
</LG>
<LG N="82" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(82)</HEAD>
<L N="624">Wyf quod &thorn;is Marquis &yogh;e herd er &thorn;is</L>
<L>My puple sekely bere&thorn; our mariage</L>
<L>And namely si&thorn;en my sone born is</L>
<L N="627">Now it is wors &thorn;an euer in our age</L>
<L>&thorn;e murmur slee&thorn; myn. her[te] and my corage</L>
<L>ffor to myn eres come&thorn; &thorn;e vois so smerte</L>
<L N="630">&thorn;at it wel nye destroie&thorn; al my herte</L>
</LG>
<LG N="83" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(83)</HEAD>
<L N="631">Now seye men &thorn;us &middot; whan walter is a goon.</L>
<L>&thorn;an shal &thorn;e blood of Ianicle succede</L>
<L>And bene our lord for o&thorn;er haue we n&omacr;n</L>
<L N="634">Such wordes seyn my puple it is no drede</L>
<L>Wel ou&yogh;te I of such murmur taken hede</L>
<L>ffor certeynly I drede such sentence</L>
<L N="637">&thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;ei not pleynly speke in myn audience</L>
</LG>
<LG N="84" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(84)</HEAD>
<L N="638">I wold lyue in pees if &thorn;at I my&yogh;t</L>
<L>Wherfore I am disposed vtterly</L>
<L>As I his sustere serued by ny&yogh;t</L>
<L N="641">Ri&yogh;t so I &thorn;enke to serue hym prively</L>
<L>&THORN;us warne I &yogh;ou &thorn;at &yogh;e not sodeynly</L>
<L>Out of &yogh;oure self for no woo shuld outray</L>
<L N="644">Be&thorn; patient and &thorn;erof I &yogh;ou pray</L>
</LG>
<LG N="85" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(85)</HEAD>
<L N="645">I haue quod she seide [&thorn;us] and euere shall</L>
<L>I wil desire no &thorn;ing certeyn</L>
<L>But as &yogh;ou lust not greueth me at all</L>
<L N="648">&thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;at my dou&yogh;tere and my sone be sclayn</L>
<L>At &yogh;oure comaundement &thorn;is is to sayn</L>
<L>I haue had no parte of children tweyn</L>
<L N="651">But furst siknesse and after woo and peyn
<PB REF="00000386.tif" N="356"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="424"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="652">&YOGH;e be our lord doo with &yogh;our owe &thorn;inge.</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t as &yogh;ou lust and aske&thorn; no rede of me<MILESTONE N="169b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor as I left at home al my clo&thorn;inge</L>
<L N="655">whan I come first to &yogh;ou ri&yogh;t so quod she</L>
<L>left I my will and al my liberte</L>
<L>And toke &yogh;oure clo&thorn;ing wherfore I &yogh;ou prey</L>
<L N="658">Do &yogh;oure wille I wille to it obeye</L>
</LG>
<LG N="87" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(87)</HEAD>
<L N="659">And certes &yogh;if I had prescience</L>
<L>&yogh;oure will to knowe. or &yogh;e &yogh;oure lust me told</L>
<L>I wold it done wi&thorn; oute necligence</L>
<L N="662">But now I wote &yogh;oure lust and what &yogh;e wolde</L>
<L>Al &yogh;oure plesaunce feerme and stable I hold</L>
<L>ffor wist I &thorn;at my de&thorn; wold do &yogh;ou ese</L>
<L N="665">Gladly wil I suffre it &yogh;ou to plese</L>
</LG>
<LG N="88" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(88)</HEAD>
<L N="666">Deth may make non comparisoun</L>
<L>Vnto &yogh;oure loue and whan &thorn;is Marquis say</L>
<L>&thorn;e constance of his wiff he cast his hede adoun</L>
<L N="669">And his eyen two and wondred how she may</L>
<L>In such penaunce suffre al &thorn;is array</L>
<L>And for&thorn; he go&thorn; wi&thorn; drery countenance</L>
<L N="672">But to his hert it was ful grete plesannce /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="89" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(89)</HEAD>
<L N="673">This ege sergeant in &thorn;e same wise</L>
<L>&thorn;at he her dou&yogh;tere kaught ri&yogh;t so he</L>
<L>Or wors if he coude wors devise</L>
<L N="676">Ha&thorn; kaught hire childe &thorn;at was ful of bewte</L>
<L>And euere in oon so pacient was she</L>
<L>&thorn;at she no chere made of hevynesse</L>
<L N="679">But kise&thorn; her sone and after can hym blesse</L>
</LG>
<LG N="90" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(90)</HEAD>
<L N="680">Saue &thorn;is she preide him if &thorn;at he my&yogh;t</L>
<L>hir litel sone he wold on er&thorn;e graue</L>
<L>his tendere lymmes delicat to si&yogh;t</L>
<L N="683">ffro fowles and beestes forto saue
<PB REF="00000387.tif" N="357"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="425"></L>
<L>But she noon answere of hym my&yogh;t haue</L>
<L>He went his way as he no &thorn;ing wrou&yogh;t<MILESTONE N="170a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="686">But into boloyne tendrely it brou&yogh;t</L>
</LG>
<LG N="91" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(91)</HEAD>
<L N="687">This Marquis wondre&thorn; euere lenger &thorn;e more</L>
<L>Vpon her pacience and if &thorn;at he</L>
<L>Ne had so&thorn;ly knowe &thorn;erfore</L>
<L N="690">&thorn;at parfitly her children loued she</L>
<L>He wold haue wende &thorn;at of some sotilte</L>
<L>And of malice or cruel corage</L>
<L N="693">That she had suffred &thorn;is with sad visage</L>
</LG>
<LG N="92" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(92)</HEAD>
<L N="694">Wut he knewe &thorn;at next hym self certayn</L>
<L>She loued her children best in euery wise</L>
<L>But nowe of wommen wold I aske fayn</L>
<L N="697">&yogh;if &thorn;ise assaies my&yogh;t not suffise</L>
<L>what cowde a stordy husbond [more] devise</L>
<L>To preue her wifhode and her stedfastnesse</L>
<L N="700">And be contynuyng in stordynesse</L>
</LG>
<LG N="93" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(93)</HEAD>
<L N="701">But &thorn;er ben folk of such condicion</L>
<L>&THORN;at whan &thorn;ei han a certeyn purpoos take</L>
<L>&THORN;ey con not stinte of her entencion</L>
<L N="704">But as &thorn;ei were bounden to a stake</L>
<L>&thorn;ei wil not of &thorn;at purpoos sclake</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t so &thorn;is marquis ha&thorn; fully purposed</L>
<L N="707">To tempten his wif as he was first disposed</L>
</LG>
<LG N="94" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(94)</HEAD>
<L N="708">He waite&thorn; if by woordes or countenance</L>
<L>&YOGH;if she to hym was chaunged of corage</L>
<L>But neuere coude he fynde variance</L>
<L N="711">She was euere in hert &amp; in visage</L>
<L>And euer &thorn;e fer&thorn;er &thorn;at he was in age</L>
<L>&thorn;e more trewer if it were possible</L>
<L N="714">She was to hym in loue and more penyble
<PB REF="00000388.tif" N="358"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="426"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="715">For which it seme&thorn; &thorn;us &thorn;at of hem twoo</L>
<L>Ther was but oon will for as walter lust</L>
<L>The same lust was her plesaunce also<MILESTONE N="170b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="718">And god be &thorn;onked al felle for &thorn;e best</L>
<L>She shewed wel for no worldly vnrest</L>
<L>A wif as of her self no &thorn;inge shuld</L>
<L N="721">Willen in effecte but as her husbond wold</L>
</LG>
<LG N="96" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(96)</HEAD>
<L N="722">The sclaundere of waltere oft wide sprad</L>
<L>That a cruel hert wickedly</L>
<L>ffor he a poor womman wedded had.</L>
<L N="725">Ha&thorn; mor&thorn;ered bo&thorn; his children priuely</L>
<L>which murmur was amonge heme comonly</L>
<L>No wonder was for to &thorn;e puples eere</L>
<L N="728">&thorn;er come no worde but &thorn;at &thorn;ei mur&thorn;ered were</L>
</LG>
<LG N="97" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(97)</HEAD>
<L N="729">For swich as of his puple &thorn;erbifore</L>
<L>had loued hym wel desclaundred of his name</L>
<L>Made hem &thorn;at &thorn;ei hated hym therfore</L>
<L N="732">To bene a murdrere is an hatful name</L>
<L>But na&thorn;elees for ernest ne for game</L>
<L>He of his cruelte wold not stynte</L>
<L N="735">To tempte his wif was al his entente</L>
</LG>
<LG N="98" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(98)</HEAD>
<L N="736">Whan &thorn;is dou&yogh;tere xij &yogh;ere was of age</L>
<L>he to &thorn;e courte of Rome in sotile wise</L>
<L>Enformed of his wille sent his massage</L>
<L N="739">Comaunding hem such billes to devise</L>
<L>As to his cruel purpoos may suffise</L>
<L>howe &thorn;at &thorn;e pope for his puples rest</L>
<L N="742">Bad hym wedde ano&thorn;er wif if &thorn;at hym lest</L>
</LG>
<LG N="99" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(99)</HEAD>
<L N="743">I sey he bad &thorn;at &thorn;ei shuld counterfete</L>
<L>&thorn;e popes billes making mencion</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ha&thorn; leue his first wif to lete</L>
<L N="746">As by &thorn;e popes dispensacion
<PB REF="00000389.tif" N="359"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="427"></L>
<L>To stinte rancoure and dissencion</L>
<L>Bitwix &thorn;e puple and hym &thorn;us speke &THORN;e bulle</L>
<L N="749">The which &THORN;ei han publissshed at &thorn;e fulle<MILESTONE N="171a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="100" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(100)</HEAD>
<L N="750">The rude puple as no wonder is</L>
<L>Wende ful wel it had be ri&yogh;t soo</L>
<L>But &thorn;ise tydyngges commen to griseld is</L>
<L N="753">I deme &thorn;at her hert was ful woo</L>
<L>But she was ylike sad euermoo</L>
<L>Disposed was &thorn;is humble creature/</L>
<L N="756">&THORN;e aduersite of fortune al to endure</L>
</LG>
<LG N="101" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(101)</HEAD>
<L N="757">Abydinge euer his lust and his plesance</L>
<L>To whom she was &yogh;euene hert and all</L>
<L>As to her worldely suffisaunce</L>
<L N="760">ffor certeynly for his story telle I shall</L>
<L>This Marquis ywriten ha&thorn; in speciall</L>
<L>A lettre in which he shewe&thorn; his entent</L>
<L N="763">And sikerly he it to boloyne sent</L>
</LG>
<LG N="102" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(102)</HEAD>
<L N="764">To &thorn;e Erle of Pavie which &thorn;at he had so</L>
<L>wedded his sustere he preide specialy</L>
<L>To bringen him a&yogh;ein his children two</L>
<L N="767">In honurable estaat al openly</L>
<L>Bot of on &thorn;ing he hym preide al vtterly</L>
<L>That he to [no] wi&yogh;t &thorn;ough men wold enquere</L>
<L N="770">Shuld not telle whoos children &thorn;ei were</L>
</LG>
<LG N="103" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(103)</HEAD>
<L N="771">But seide &thorn;at &thorn;e mayde shuld wedded be</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e Marquis of Saluce anon</L>
<L>And as &thorn;e erle was preide so did he</L>
<L N="774">ffor at a day Isette he on his way is gon</L>
<L>Toward Saluse and lordes mony on</L>
<L>In riche aray &thorn;is maide forto gyde</L>
<L N="777">Hir yonge bro&thorn;er ridyng by hir side
<PB REF="00000390.tif" N="360"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="428"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="778">Araied was towardes &thorn;is mariage</L>
<L>This mayde fressh ful of gemmys clere</L>
<L>Hir bro&thorn;er that vij. &yogh;ere was of age.</L>
<L N="781">Araied eke was fresshly on his manere<MILESTONE N="171b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And in grete noblesse and glad chere</L>
<L>Toward Saluce shapinge her iournay</L>
<L N="784">ffrom day to day &thorn;ei riden for&thorn; her way</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="5" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[THE FIFTH PART.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="785">Amonge al &thorn;is aftere his wikked vsage</L>
<L>This Marquys &yogh;it his wif to tempten more</L>
<L>To &thorn;e vttrest preef of his corage</L>
<L N="788">ffully to haue experience and lore</L>
<L>&yogh;if &thorn;at she were as stedfast as bifore</L>
<L>he on a day in open audience</L>
<L N="791">wel boistously ha&thorn; seide hir &thorn;is sentence</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="792">CErtes Griseld I had ynowe plesaunce</L>
<L>To han &yogh;ou to my wif for &yogh;oure goodnesse</L>
<L>And for &yogh;oure treuth and &yogh;our obeysaunce</L>
<L N="795">Nou&yogh;t for &yogh;oure lynage ne for &yogh;oure ricchesse</L>
<L>But it is now knowen in verray so&thorn;nesse</L>
<L>&thorn;at in grete lordship if I wil avise</L>
<L N="798">Ther is grete souereynte in sondry wise</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="799">I may not done as euery plowe man may</L>
<L>My puple me constreynen forto take</L>
<L>A no&thorn;er wiff and crien day by day</L>
<L N="802">And eke &thorn;e pope rancour forto sclake</L>
<L>Consente&thorn; it &thorn;at dar I vndertake</L>
<L>And trewly &thorn;us moch wil I &yogh;ou say</L>
<L N="805">My newe wif is commyng by &thorn;e way</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="806">Be stronge of hert and voide anon her place</L>
<L>And &thorn;ilk dowary &thorn;at &yogh;e brou&yogh;t to me</L>
<L>Take it a&yogh;ein I graunte it of my grace
<PB REF="00000391.tif" N="361"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="429"></L>
<L N="809">Retourne&thorn; to &yogh;oure faders hous quod he</L>
<L>No man may alway haue prosperite</L>
<L>wi&thorn; euene hert I rede &yogh;ou to endure</L>
<L N="812">&thorn;e stroke of fortune or of auenture</L>
</LG>
<LG N="109" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(109)</HEAD>
<L N="813">And she a&yogh;ein answerde in pacience<MILESTONE N="172a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>My lord quod she I wote and wist alway</L>
<L>howe &thorn;at I swore &yogh;ou magnificence</L>
<L N="816">And my pouert no man can ne may</L>
<L>Maken noon comparison it is no nay</L>
<L>I helde me neuere digne in no manere</L>
<L N="819">To be &yogh;oure wif ne &yogh;it your chambrere</L>
</LG>
<LG N="110" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(110)</HEAD>
<L N="820">And in &thorn;is hous &thorn;er &yogh;e me lady made</L>
<L>&thorn;e high god take I for my witnesse</L>
<L>So wisly as he my soule glade</L>
<L N="823">I helde me nei&thorn;er lady ne maistresse</L>
<L>But humble seruaunte to &yogh;oure wor&thorn;inesse</L>
<L>And euere shal while my lif may endure</L>
<L N="826">Abouen euery wor&thorn;i creature</L>
</LG>
<LG N="111" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(111)</HEAD>
<L N="827">That &yogh;e so longe of &yogh;our benygnite</L>
<L>haue holde me in honure and in nobleye</L>
<L>where I was not wor&thorn;i forto be</L>
<L N="830">&thorn;at &thorn;onk I god and &yogh;ou [to] whom I prey</L>
<L>ffor-&yogh;eelde it &yogh;ou &thorn;er nys no more to sey</L>
<L>Vnto my fadere gladly wil I wende</L>
<L N="833">And wi&thorn; hym dwelle to my lyves ende</L>
</LG>
<LG N="112" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(112)</HEAD>
<L N="834">Ther as I was fostred a child ful small</L>
<L>Til I be dede my liff [&thorn;er] wil I lede</L>
<L>A widowe clene in hert body and all</L>
<L N="837">ffor si&thorn;en I &yogh;af to &yogh;ou my maydenhede</L>
<L>And am &yogh;oure trewe wif it is no drede</L>
<L>God shild such a lordes wif to take</L>
<L N="840">Ano&thorn;er man to husbonde or to make
<PB REF="00000392.tif" N="362"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="430"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="841">And of &yogh;our newe wif god of his grace</L>
<L>So graunte &yogh;ou wel&thorn;e and prosperite</L>
<L>ffor I wil gladly &yogh;eeld hir my place</L>
<L N="844">In which I was blisful wont to be</L>
<L>ffor Si&thorn;en it like&thorn; &yogh;ou my lord quod she<MILESTONE N="172b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That whilom weren al my hertes rest</L>
<L N="847">That I shal goon I wil goon whan &yogh;ou lest</L>
</LG>
<LG N="114" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(114)</HEAD>
<L N="848">But &thorn;er &yogh;e me profre such dowarie</L>
<L>As I furst brou&yogh;t it is wel in my mynde</L>
<L>It were my wrecched clo&thorn;es no &thorn;ing faire</L>
<L N="851">&thorn;e which to me nowe were ful hard to fynde</L>
<L>How god howe gentile and how kinde</L>
<L>&YOGH;e semed by &yogh;oure spech and &yogh;our visage</L>
<L N="854">&thorn;e day &thorn;at maked was oure mariage</L>
</LG>
<LG N="115" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(115)</HEAD>
<L N="855">But so&thorn; is seide algate I finde it trewe</L>
<L>ffor in effecte is proued nowe on me</L>
<L>Loue is not olde as whan it is newe</L>
<L N="858">ffor certes lord for non aduersite</L>
<L>To dyen in &thorn;is cas it shal not be</L>
<L>That in worde or werk I shal repent</L>
<L N="861">&thorn;at I &yogh;ou &yogh;aue myn hert in good entent</L>
</LG>
<LG N="116" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(116)</HEAD>
<L N="862">My lorde &yogh;e wote &thorn;at in my faders place</L>
<L>&YOGH;e diden me stripen out of my poor wede</L>
<L>And richely &yogh;e cladden me of &yogh;oure grace</L>
<L N="865">To &yogh;ou brou&yogh;t I not ellis out of drede</L>
<L>But fait nakednesse and maidenhede</L>
<L>But here a&yogh;ein &yogh;oure clo&thorn;ing I restore</L>
<L N="868">And eke my weddyng ringe for euermore</L>
</LG>
<LG N="117" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(117)</HEAD>
<L N="869">The remenaunte of &yogh;our Iwels redy be</L>
<L>wi&thorn; in &yogh;our chambre dare I it seyuely seye</L>
<L>Naked out of my faders hous quod she</L>
<L N="872">I come/ and naked I mote turne ageyne
<PB REF="00000393.tif" N="363"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="431"></L>
<L>Al &yogh;oure plesaunce wil I folowe feyne</L>
<L>But if I hope it be not &yogh;oure entente</L>
<L N="875">&thorn;at I smoklees out of &yogh;oure paleis went</L>
</LG>
<LG N="118" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(118)</HEAD>
<L N="876">&YOGH;e cowde not do so dishonest a &thorn;inge</L>
<L>That ilk wombe in which our children lay<MILESTONE N="173a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Shuld byfore &thorn;e puple in my walkinge</L>
<L N="879">Be seyn al bare wherfor I &yogh;ou pray</L>
<L>lat me not like a worm gon by &thorn;e way</L>
<L>Remembre &yogh;ou myn / owne lorde so dere</L>
<L N="882">I was &yogh;oure wif &thorn;ou&yogh;e I vnwor&thorn;i were</L>
</LG>
<LG N="119" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(119)</HEAD>
<L N="883">Wherfore in guerdon of my maidenhede</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at I wrou&yogh;t and not a&yogh;ein bere</L>
<L>As vouche&thorn; sauf to &yogh;eue me to my mede</L>
<L N="886">But such a smokke as I was wont to were</L>
<L>&thorn;at I &thorn;erwi&thorn; may hille &thorn;e wombe of here</L>
<L>&thorn;at was &yogh;oure wif and here I take my leue</L>
<L N="889">Of &yogh;owe myn owne lord lest I &yogh;ou greue</L>
</LG>
<LG N="120" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(120)</HEAD>
<L N="890">The smok quod he &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast on &thorn;i bak</L>
<L>Lat it be stille and bere it for&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;e</L>
<L>But wel vnne&thorn; &thorn;at word he spak</L>
<L N="893">But went his way for reuthe and pite</L>
<L>Byfore &thorn;e folk hure self stripe&thorn; she</L>
<L>And in her smok wi&thorn; hede and fete al bare</L>
<L N="896">Toward her fadres hous for&thorn; is she fare</L>
</LG>
<LG N="121" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(121)</HEAD>
<L N="897">The folk folowed weping in hir way</L>
<L>And fortune euere &thorn;ei cursed as &thorn;ei gon</L>
<L>But she from weping kept her eyen day</L>
<L N="900">Ne in &thorn;is tyme word spak she non</L>
<L>Her fader &thorn;at here of herd anon</L>
<L>Cursed &thorn;e day and tyme &thorn;at nature</L>
<L N="903">Shope him to be a lyues creature
<PB REF="00000394.tif" N="364"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="432"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="904">For out of doute &thorn;is olde poor man</L>
<L>was euer suspecte of her mariage</L>
<L>ffor euer he demed si&thorn;en it bygan</L>
<L N="907">&THORN;at whan &thorn;e lord yfylled had his corage</L>
<L>hym wold &thorn;enk it was a desparage</L>
<L>To his astate so lowe to a li&yogh;t<MILESTONE N="173b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="910">And voiden hir as sone as euere he my&yogh;t</L>
</LG>
<LG N="123" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(123)</HEAD>
<L N="911">A&yogh;einst his dou&yogh;tere hastely go&thorn; he</L>
<L>ffor he by &thorn;e noys of folk knewe her commyng</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; her olde cote as it my&yogh;t be</L>
<L N="914">He keuere&thorn; hir ful sorowfully wepinge</L>
<L>But on hur body my&yogh;t he it not bringe</L>
<L>ffor rude was &thorn;e clo&thorn; and more of age</L>
<L N="917">By dayes fele &thorn;an hur mariage</L>
</LG>
<LG N="124" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(124)</HEAD>
<L N="918">Thus with her fadere for a certeyn space</L>
<L>dwelle&thorn; &thorn;is floure of wively pacience</L>
<L>That neuer by her wordes ne be her face</L>
<L N="921">Bifore &thorn;e folk ne in her absence</L>
<L>Ne shewed she &thorn;at to hir was don offence</L>
<L>Ne of hie astate in remembraunce</L>
<L N="924">Ne had she as by her countenaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG N="125" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(125)</HEAD>
<L N="925">No wonder is for in [her] grete estate</L>
<L>Her goost was euere in pleyn humilite</L>
<L>No tender mou&thorn;e ne hert delicate</L>
<L N="928">Ne pompe ne semblant of Rialte</L>
<L>But ful of pacience and benygnite</L>
<L>Discrete and pruydeles and euere honurable</L>
<L N="931">And to her husbonde euere meke and stable</L>
</LG>
<LG N="126" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(126)</HEAD>
<L N="932">Men speke of Iob and most of his humblesse</L>
<L>As clerkes whan hem lust can wel endite</L>
<L>Namely of men but in so&thorn;fastnesse</L>
<L N="935">&thorn;ou&yogh;e clerkes preise wommen but a lite
<PB REF="00000395.tif" N="365"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="433"></L>
<L>&thorn;er can no man in humblesse hem aquite</L>
<L>As wommen can ne ben half so trewe</L>
<L N="938">As wommen bene but it be fallen newe</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="6" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[THE SIXTH PART.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="939">Fro babyloyne is &thorn;is Erle of Pavie come</L>
<L>Of which &thorn;e word spronge to more and lesse</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e pules eeres al and somme</L>
<L N="942">was cou&thorn;e eke a newe Marquyssesse<MILESTONE N="174a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>He wi&thorn; hym brou&yogh;t in pompe and such ricchesse</L>
<L>&thorn;at was neuere sey wi&thorn; mannys eye</L>
<L N="945">So noble aray in Westlombardye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="946">The Marquis &thorn;at Shope an knewe al &thorn;is</L>
<L>Er &thorn;at &thorn;is erle was commen sent his massage</L>
<L>ffor cely poor Gryseldys</L>
<L N="949">And she with humble hert and glad visage</L>
<L>Nou&yogh;t wi&thorn; swollen hert in her corage</L>
<L>Come at his heest and on here knees her sette</L>
<L N="952">And reuerently and wisely she hym grette</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="953">Griseld quod he my will is vtterly</L>
<L>&thorn;is maide &thorn;at shal wedded be vnto me</L>
<L>Resceyued be to morowe as Really</L>
<L N="956">As it is possible in my hous to be</L>
<L>And eke &thorn;at euery wi&yogh;t in his degre</L>
<L>Haue his estate in sittyng and seruise</L>
<L N="959">And also plesaunce as &yogh;e can best deuyse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="960">I haue no womman suffisant certayn</L>
<L>&THORN;e Chambres to aray in ordynaunce</L>
<L>After my lust and &thorn;erfor wil I fayn</L>
<L N="963">&THORN;at &thorn;ine were al such gouernaunce</L>
<L>&THORN;ou knowest eke of olde al my plesaunce</L>
<L>&thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;ine aray be bad and euel ysey</L>
<L N="966">Do &thorn;ou &thorn;i deuoyre at &thorn;e lest wey
<PB REF="00000396.tif" N="366"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="434"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="967">Nou&yogh;t only lord &thorn;at I am glad quod she</L>
<L>To do &yogh;oure lust but I desire also</L>
<L>&yogh;oure forto plese and serue in my degre</L>
<L N="970">Without fayntise and shal euermoo</L>
<L>Ne neuer for no wele ne for no woo</L>
<L>Ne shal &thorn;e goost within my hert stynt</L>
<L N="973">To loue &yogh;ou best with al my trewe entent</L>
</LG>
<LG N="132" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(132)</HEAD>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word she gan &thorn;e hous to di&yogh;t<MILESTONE N="174b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And tables to sette and beddys to make</L>
<L>And peyned hure to doo al &thorn;at she my&yogh;t</L>
<L N="977">Preying &thorn;e chambreres for goddis sake</L>
<L>To hasten hem and fast swope and shake</L>
<L>And she &thorn;e most seruisable at all</L>
<L N="980">Ha&thorn; euery ychambre araied and his halle</L>
</LG>
<LG N="133" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(133)</HEAD>
<L N="981">Aboute vndern gan &thorn;is Erle ali&yogh;t</L>
<L>That wi&thorn; him brou&yogh;t &thorn;ise noble childre tweie</L>
<L>ffor which &thorn;e puple ranne to se &thorn;at si&yogh;t</L>
<L N="984">And hure araye so richely beseye</L>
<L>And &thorn;an at arst amonges hem &thorn;ei gon seye</L>
<L>That walter was no foole &thorn;ough hym lest</L>
<L N="987">To chaunge his wiff for it was for &thorn;e best</L>
</LG>
<LG N="134" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(134)</HEAD>
<L N="988">For she is fairrer as &thorn;ei demen alle</L>
<L>Than is Grisell and more tender of age</L>
<L>And fairrer fruyte bytwene hem shuld falle</L>
<L N="991">And more plesaunt for hir hi&yogh;e lynage</L>
<L>Hir bro&thorn;er so faire was of his age</L>
<L>&thorn;at hym to seen &thorn;e puple had kau&yogh;t plesaunce</L>
<L N="994">Commendyng nowe &yogh;e Marquis gouernaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG N="135" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(135)</HEAD>
<L N="995">O sterne puple vnsad and [vn]trewe</L>
<L>Euere vndiscrete and chaungyng as a fane</L>
<L>Delitinge euere in Rumour &thorn;at is newe</L>
<L N="998">ffor like &thorn;e mone euere wexe &yogh;e and wane
<PB REF="00000397.tif" N="367"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="435"></L>
<L>Euere ful of clapping dere ynowe a Iane</L>
<L>&YOGH;our dome is fals &yogh;our constance euel preue&thorn;</L>
<L N="1001">A wel grete fool is he &thorn;at on &yogh;ou leue&thorn;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="136" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(136)</HEAD>
<L N="1002">Thus seiden sadde folk in &thorn;at Cite</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;e puple gased vp and doun</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ei were glad ri&yogh;t for &thorn;e nouelte</L>
<L N="1005">To make a newe lady of her toun</L>
<L>No more of &thorn;is make I mencioun<MILESTONE N="175a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But to griseld a&yogh;ein wil I me dresse</L>
<L N="1008">And telle her constance and her bysynesse</L>
</LG>
<LG N="137" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(137)</HEAD>
<L N="1009">Wel bysy was gryseld in euery thinge</L>
<L>&thorn;at to &thorn;e feest was pertinent</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t naught was she abasshed of her clo&thorn;inge</L>
<L N="1012">&thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;ei were Rude and eke somdel to-rent</L>
<L>But wi&thorn; glad chere to &thorn;e gate is went</L>
<L>wi&thorn; o&thorn;er folk to greten &thorn;e Marquissesse</L>
<L N="1015">And after do&thorn; she for&thorn; her bysynesse</L>
</LG>
<LG N="138" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(138)</HEAD>
<L N="1016">Wi&thorn; ful glad chere &thorn;e gestes she receyue&thorn;</L>
<L>And Boxomly euerich in his degre</L>
<L>That no man defawte &thorn;er perceyue&thorn;</L>
<L N="1019">But euere &thorn;ei wondren what she my&yogh;t be</L>
<L>That in so poor aray was forto se</L>
<L>And cowde such honure &amp; reuerence</L>
<L N="1022">And wor&thorn;ely &thorn;ei preisen her prudence</L>
</LG>
<LG N="139" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(139)</HEAD>
<L N="1023">In al &thorn;is me[ne] while she ne stynte</L>
<L>This maiden and eke her bro&thorn;er to commend</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al her hert and benigne entente</L>
<L N="1026">So wel &thorn;at no man koude her prise amende</L>
<L>But at &thorn;e last whan at &thorn;ise lordes wende</L>
<L>To sitten a doun he gan to calle</L>
<L N="1029">Griseld as she was bysy in &thorn;e halle
<PB REF="00000398.tif" N="368"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="436"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1030">Griseld quod he as it were in play</L>
<L>How like&thorn; &thorn;e my wif in her bewte</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t wel quod she my lorde for in good fay</L>
<L N="1033">A fairrer sawe I neuere non quod she</L>
<L>I prey to god so &yogh;eue &yogh;ou prosperite</L>
<L>And so hope I he wil to &yogh;ou sende</L>
<L N="1036">Plesaunce ynou&yogh;e to &yogh;oure lyues ende</L>
</LG>
<LG N="141" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(141)</HEAD>
<L N="1037">Sut oon &thorn;ing I biseche and warne also ./</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;e prik wi&thorn; no tormentynge<MILESTONE N="175b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;is tendere mayden as &yogh;e han don moo</L>
<L N="1040">ffor she is fostred in her norshynge</L>
<L>fful tenderly in her &yogh;ong pleyynge</L>
<L>She coude not aduersite endure</L>
<L N="1043">As coude a poor fostred creature</L>
</LG>
<LG N="142" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(142)</HEAD>
<L N="1044">And whan &thorn;is Walter segh her pacience</L>
<L>her glad chere and no malice at all</L>
<L>And he so oft ha&thorn; done hir offence</L>
<L N="1047">And she euer constant and sad as a wall</L>
<L>Contynuyng euer her innocence ouerall</L>
<L>This stordy marquis gan his herte dresse</L>
<L N="1050">To Rwe vpon hur wifly stidfastnesse</L>
</LG>
<LG N="143" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(143)</HEAD>
<L N="1051">This is ynou&yogh;e Griseld myn quod he</L>
<L>Be no more agast ne euel apayde</L>
<L>I haue &thorn;i fei&thorn; and &thorn;i benignyte</L>
<L N="1054">As wel as euer womman was asaied</L>
<L>In gr[e]te astate and poorly araied</L>
<L>Now knowe I dere wiff &thorn;i stedfastnesse</L>
<L N="1057">And hure in armes toke and gan to kesse</L>
</LG>
<LG N="144" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(144)</HEAD>
<L N="1058">And she for wonder toke &thorn;erof no kepe</L>
<L>She herd not what &thorn;ing &thorn;at he seide</L>
<L>She ferde as she had stert out of her sclepe</L>
<L N="1061">Til she out of &thorn;e maisednesse abreide
<PB REF="00000399.tif" N="369"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="437"></L>
<L>Griseld quod he by god &thorn;at for vs deyde</L>
<L>&thorn;ou art my wif and noon o&thorn;er I haue</L>
<L N="1064">Ne neuere had as god my soule saue</L>
</LG>
<LG N="145" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(145)</HEAD>
<L N="1065">This is &thorn;i dou&yogh;ter which &thorn;ou hast supposed</L>
<L>To bene my wif and noon o&thorn;er fei&thorn;fully</L>
<L>shal bene myn heir as I haue euere disposed</L>
<L N="1068">Thowe bere hem in &thorn;i body trewly</L>
<L>At boylen haue I kepte hem sikerly</L>
<L>Take hem a&yogh;ein for &thorn;ou my&yogh;t not seyn<MILESTONE N="176a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1071">&thorn;at &thorn;ow hast lorn eny of &thorn;i children tweyn</L>
</LG>
<LG N="146" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(146)</HEAD>
<L N="1072">And folk &thorn;at o&thorn;erwise han seide of me</L>
<L>I warne hem wel &thorn;at I haue done &thorn;is dede</L>
<L>ffor no malice ne for no cruelte</L>
<L N="1075">But forto assay &thorn;i wommanhede</L>
<L>And not forto scle my children god forbede</L>
<L>But forto kepen hem prively and stille</L>
<L N="1078">Til I &thorn;i purpoos knewe and al &thorn;i wille</L>
</LG>
<LG N="147" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(147)</HEAD>
<L N="1079">And whan she &thorn;is herd adoun in swowe she falle&thorn;</L>
<L>ffor pitous ioying and after hire swowinge</L>
<L>She bo&thorn; her y&omacr;nge children to hure calle&thorn;</L>
<L N="1082">And in hure armes pitously wepinge</L>
<L>Enbrased bo&thorn; tenderly kissynge</L>
<L>Wel like a modere wi&thorn; her salt teeres</L>
<L N="1085">She ba&thorn;ed bo&thorn; her visage and her heeres</L>
</LG>
<LG N="148" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(148)</HEAD>
<L N="1086">O such a pitous &thorn;inge it was to see</L>
<L>Her sownyng and her pitous vois to here</L>
<L>Gramercy my lord god y thenk &yogh;ou quod she</L>
<L N="1089">&thorn;at &yogh;e han saued me my children dere</L>
<L>Now rech I neuere to be dede ri&yogh;t here</L>
<L>Si&thorn; I stonde in &yogh;our loue and in &yogh;our grace</L>
<L N="1092">No force of de&thorn; ne whan my spirit pace
<PB REF="00000400.tif" N="370"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="438"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1093">A tender o dere .o. &yogh;enge children myn</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure wooful modere wende stedfastly</L>
<L>&THORN;at cruel houndes or some vermyn</L>
<L N="1096">Had eten &yogh;ou but god of his mercy</L>
<L>And &yogh;oure benigne fader tenderly</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; done &yogh;ou kepte and &thorn;at same stounde</L>
<L N="1099">Al sodeynly she swapte doun to &thorn;e grounde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="150" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(150)</HEAD>
<L N="1100">And hin her swowne so sadly holde&thorn; she</L>
<L>her children two whan she gan hem brace</L>
<L>That wi&thorn; grete scleight and difficulte<MILESTONE N="176b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1103">The children from her armes gan &thorn;ei to rase</L>
<L>O mony a tere .o mony a pitous face</L>
<L>Doun ranne of hem &thorn;at stoden hyr beside</L>
<L N="1106">Vnne&thorn; aboute hur my&yogh;t &thorn;ei abide</L>
</LG>
<LG N="151" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(151)</HEAD>
<L N="1107">Walter hir vptake&thorn; and her sorowe glade&thorn;</L>
<L>She arise&thorn; vp al abasshed from her trance</L>
<L>And euery wi&yogh;t hir Ioye and feest make&thorn;</L>
<L N="1110">To she haue kau&yogh;t a&yogh;ein her countenance</L>
<L>Walter her do&thorn; so fei&thorn;fully plesaunce</L>
<L>&thorn;at it was deynte for to se &thorn;e chere</L>
<L N="1113">Bitwixe hem two nowe &thorn;ei bene mette in fere</L>
</LG>
<LG N="152" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(152)</HEAD>
<L N="1114">Thise ladys whan &thorn;ei her tyme say</L>
<L>han taken hur and into chambre gone</L>
<L>And stripen hir out of her rude aray</L>
<L N="1117">And in a clo&thorn;e of gold &thorn;at brighte shone</L>
<L>wi&thorn; a crowne of mony a riche stone</L>
<L>vpon hur hede &thorn;ei hir into halle brou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1120">And &thorn;er she was honoured as she ou&yogh;t</L>
</LG>
<LG N="153" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(153)</HEAD>
<L N="1121">Thus ha&thorn; &thorn;is pitous day a blisful ende</L>
<L>ffor euery man and womman do&thorn; his my&yogh;t</L>
<L>This day in myr&thorn;e and reuel to dispende</L>
<L N="1124">Til on &thorn;e welken shoon &thorn;e sterres bri&yogh;t
<PB REF="00000401.tif" N="371"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="439"></L>
<L>ffor more solempne in euery mannys si&yogh;t</L>
<L>This fest was and gretter of costage</L>
<L N="1127">&THORN;an was &thorn;e reuel of &thorn;e mariage</L>
</LG>
<LG N="154" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(154)</HEAD>
<L N="1128">fful mony a &yogh;eer in high prosperite</L>
<L>lyuen &thorn;ise two in concord and in rest</L>
<L>And richely his dou&yogh;ter maried he</L>
<L N="1131">Vnto a lord on of &thorn;e wor&thorn;iest</L>
<L>Of all ytaile and &thorn;an in pees and rest</L>
<L>His wifes fader in his courte he kepe&thorn;</L>
<L N="1134">Til &thorn;at his soule out of his body crepeth<MILESTONE N="177a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="155" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(155)</HEAD>
<L N="1135">His sone entre&thorn; into his heritage</L>
<L>In rest and pees aftere his faders day</L>
<L>And fortunate was eke in mariage</L>
<L N="1138">Al putte he not his wif in assay</L>
<L>This world is not [so] stronge it is no nay</L>
<L>As it ha&thorn; bene in olde tymes &yogh;ore</L>
<L N="1141">And harkene&thorn; what &thorn;e auctour sei&thorn; &thorn;erfore</L>
</LG>
<LG N="156" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(156)</HEAD>
<L N="1142">&THORN;is storie is seide not &thorn;at wives shuld</L>
<L>ffolowe Gryseld as in humilite</L>
<L>ffor it were importable &thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;ei wold</L>
<L N="1145">But &thorn;at euery wi&yogh;t in his degre</L>
<L>Shulde be constant in aduersite.</L>
<L>This storie which he wi&thorn; high stile endite&thorn;</L>
<L N="1148">Wi&thorn; pacience Griseld he qwite&thorn;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="157" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(157)</HEAD>
<L N="1149">ffor si&thorn;ens a womman was so pacient</L>
<L>Vnto a mortall man moch more we ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Resceyue alle in gree &thorn;at god vs sent</L>
<L N="1152">ffor grete scelys he preue&thorn; &thorn;at he bou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Mankynde &thorn;e which &thorn;at he wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>As sei&thorn; seint Iame if &yogh;e his pistel rede</L>
<L N="1155">He preue&thorn; folk al day it is no drede
<PB REF="00000402.tif" N="372"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="440"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1156">And suffre&thorn; vs as for our exercise</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; sharpe shoures of aduersite</L>
<L>Wel ofte to be leten in sondry wise</L>
<L N="1159">Nowe forto knowe vs for certys he</L>
<L>Er we were born knewe al our freelte</L>
<L>And for our best is al our gouernaunce</L>
<L N="1162">Lat vs it haue &thorn;an in vertuous suffrance</L>
</LG>
<P>[Chaucer's addition to the Tale.]</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1163">But oo witte harkene&thorn; lordyngges er &yogh;e goo /</L>
<L>It were ful harde nowe adayes</L>
<L>In al a toune fynde Griseldys &thorn;re or two</L>
<L N="1166">ffor if &thorn;ei were putte in such assaies</L>
<L>&thorn;e gold of hem ha&thorn; nowe so hard alaies</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; bras &thorn;at &thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;e kynde be faire atte ye</L>
<L N="1169">It woll ra&thorn;er brast a two &thorn;an plye</L>
</LG>
<LG N="160" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(160)</HEAD>
<L>[ffor whiche hiere . for the wifes love of bath</L>
<L>whos lyf and al hirs . swete god maynteigne<NOTE PLACE="marg">[1-<I>line gap in the MS, after l.</I> 1171.]</NOTE></L>
<L>In high maistrie . and ellis were it skath</L>
<L N="1173">I wil with lusty hert . fressh and grene</L>
<L>Say now a song . to gladde yow I wene</L>
<L>And late vs stynt . of Ernestful matiere</L>
<L N="1176">Herknyth my song . that saith in this manere<MILESTONE UNIT="MS Reg. 17 D xv folio" N="175b"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[ <I>Not in Reg.</I> 18 <I>C</I> II, <I>Sloane</I> 1685, <I>or Harl.</I> 1758.]</NOTE>]</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; Le Voy De Chaucere'/<NOTE PLACE="marg">[headline]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG N="161" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(161)</HEAD>
<L>GRiseld is dede and eke her pacience<MILESTONE N="177b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And bo&thorn; at onys yburied in Ytalie</L>
<L N="1179">ffor which I cry in open audience</L>
<L>No wedded man be hardy to assaile</L>
<L>His wyves pacience in trust to fynde</L>
<L N="1182">Griseldes for in certeyn he shal faile
<PB REF="00000403.tif" N="373"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="441"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O noble wyues ful of hegh prudence</L>
<L>lat none humilite &yogh;oure tonge nayle</L>
<L N="1185">Ne lat no clerk haue cause ne diligence</L>
<L>To write of &yogh;ou a storie of such mervaile</L>
<L>As of griselde pacient and kynde</L>
<L N="1188">lest Chychyuache &yogh;ou swelowe in hir entraile</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Folowe&thorn; ekko &thorn;at holde&thorn; no silence</L>
<L>But euere answere&thorn; at &thorn;e countretale</L>
<L N="1191">Be&thorn; not bydaffed for our Innocence</L>
<L>But sharpely take on &yogh;ou &thorn;e gouernaile</L>
<L>Emprinte&thorn; wel &thorn;is lesson in &yogh;oure mynde</L>
<L N="1194">ffor Comon profit sith it may availe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1201">NE drede hem nou&yogh;t doth hem no reuerence</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;ine husbonde araied be in maile</L>
<L N="1203">&thorn;e arowes of &thorn;i crabbed eloquence</L>
<L>Shal perce his brest and eke his aduentale</L>
<L>In Ialowsie I rede eke &thorn;ou hym bynde</L>
<L N="1206">And &thorn;at &thorn;ou shalt make hym couche as do&thorn; a quale</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>If &thorn;ou be faire &thorn;ere folk bene in present</L>
<L>Shewe &thorn;ou &thorn;i visage and &thorn;ine apparaile</L>
<L N="1209">If &thorn;owe be fowle be free of &thorn;i dispence</L>
<L>To gete &thorn;e freendes ay do &thorn;i travaile</L>
<L>Be aye of chere as li&yogh;t as leef on lynde</L>
<L N="1212">And lat hym care and wepe and wryng and waile</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1195">&YOGH;e Arche wiffes stonde&thorn; at &yogh;our defence</L>
<L>Si&thorn; &yogh;e bene stronge as is a grete camaile</L>
<L N="1197">Ne Suffre&thorn; not &thorn;at man do &yogh;ou offence</L>
<L>And sclendere wyves feble as in bataile</L>
<L>Beth egre as a tygre &yogh;ende in Ynde</L>
<L N="1200">Ay Clappe&thorn; as a mylle I &yogh;ou counsaile.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000404.tif" N="374"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="476">
<HEAD>&para; The prologe of &thorn;e ffraunkeleyn. <NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>headline of leaf</I> 178,<I> front</I></NOTE> <NOTE PLACE="head">[For the Squire's Prologue of the Petworth MS see the Man-of-Law-Shipman Link.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>EHY goddis mercy seide oure hoost &thorn;oo /</L>
<L N="2420">Alle euel wyues god kepe vs fro</L>
<L>ffor mony sclei&yogh;tes and sub[t]ilites</L>
<L>Bene in wommen &thorn;at bene euere bisy as bees</L>
<L>Vs foly men forto desceyue</L>
<L N="2424">ffor from &thorn;e so&thorn; euere wil &thorn;ei weive</L>
<L>By mony ensamples it proue&thorn; well</L>
<L>But doutelees as trewe as eny stele</L>
<L>I haue a wiff &thorn;ough she poor be</L>
<L N="2428">But of her tunge a labbyng shrew is she</L>
<L>And she ha&thorn; an hepe of vices moo</L>
<L>&thorn;erof no force lat al such &thorn;ingges goo</L>
<L>But wete &yogh;e what in counsaile be it saide</L>
<L N="2432">Me rewe&thorn; sore &thorn;at I am to her teide</L>
<L>ffor and I shuld rekne eue[r]y vice</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at she ha&thorn; ywis I were not wis</L>
<L>And cause whi for it shuld reported be</L>
<L N="2436">And tolde to hure of somme of &thorn;is mayne</L>
<L>Of whom it nede&thorn; not to declare</L>
<L>Si&thorn; wommen kon out such chaffare</L>
<L>And eke my witte suffise&thorn; not &thorn;erto</L>
<L N="2440">To telle alle &thorn;erfore my tale is doo<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="F" TYPE="group">

<PB REF="00000405.tif" N="375">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="478">
<HEAD>GROUP <B>F.</B> FRAGMENT VII.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&sect; 1. THE SQUIRE'S HEAD-LINK.</HEAD>
<HEAD>PETWORTH MS.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sir ffrannkeleyne come ner if it &yogh;our wille be<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 178</NOTE></L>
<L>And say vs a tale for sertys &yogh;e</L>
<L>Can &thorn;eron as moch as eny man</L>
<L N="4">Nay sir quod he I wil say as I can</L>
<L>With hertely wille for I nyl be rebelle</L>
<L>A&yogh;einst &yogh;oure wille . a tale nowe wil I telle</L>
<L>HAue me excused &yogh;if I sey amys.</L>
<L N="8">My wille is good and loo my tale is &thorn;is &middot;/</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; Here ende&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e ffrannkeleyn</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000406.tif" N="376">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="500">
<HEAD>And here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e ffrannkeleyns tale<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 178</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[THE PROEM.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thise olde gentile bretoynes in her daies</L>
<L>Of dyuers auentures maden laies</L>
<L>Rymeden in her furst bretoyne tonge</L>
<L N="712">Which layes wi&thorn; her instrumentes &thorn;ei songe</L>
<L>Oi&thorn;er ellis radden hem for her plesance<MILESTONE N="178b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And oon of hem haue I in remembrance</L>
<L>Which I shal seie wi&thorn; as good wille as I can/</L>
<L N="716">But sirs by cause &thorn;at I am but a burill man</L>
<L>At my bygynnynge furst I &yogh;ou biseche</L>
<L>Haue me excused of my rwde speche</L>
<L>I lered neuere rethorike certeyne</L>
<L N="720">&thorn;inge &thorn;at I speke it mot be bare and pleyne</L>
<L>I slepte neuere on &thorn;e mounte of parnaso</L>
<L>Ne I neuer lered . Marchus Tullius ne Cithero</L>
<L>Colours of rethorike knewe I none with-out drede</L>
<L N="724">But such coloures as growen in &thorn;e mede</L>
<L>Or ellis such as men dye or peynt</L>
<L>Colours of rethorike bene to me queynt</L>
<L>Mi spirit fele&thorn; not of such matiere</L>
<L N="728">But if &yogh;ou lust my tale shul &yogh;e here<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[THE TALE.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="730">Ther was a knyght &thorn;at loued and did his peyne</L>
<L N="729">In armorike &thorn;at cleped is breteyne</L>
<L>To seruen a lady in his best wise</L>
<L N="732">And mony a laboure &amp; mony a grete emprise
<PB REF="00000407.tif" N="377"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="501"></L>
<L>He for his lady wrou&yogh;t er she were wonne</L>
<L>ffor she was oon &thorn;e fairest vndere sonne</L>
<L>And eke &thorn;erto come of so high kynrede</L>
<L N="736">&thorn;at wel vnne&thorn;es durst &thorn;is knyght for drede</L>
<L>Telle hure his woo his peyne and his distresse</L>
<L>But at &thorn;e last she for his wor&thorn;inesse</L>
<L>And namely for his meke obeysance</L>
<L N="740">Ha&thorn; suche a pite kau&yogh;t of his penaunce</L>
<L>That prively she felle of his acorde</L>
<L>To take hym for hure husbond and her lord</L>
<L>Of suche lordship as men han ouer her wyves</L>
<L N="744">And forto lede &thorn;e more in blisse her lyves</L>
<L>Of his fre wille he swore hure as a kny&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;at neuere in his wille by day ne ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>Ne shuld vpon hym take no maistrie</L>
<L N="748">A&yogh;einst her wille ne kith hure Ialousie</L>
<L>But hure obeye and folowe her wille in all<MILESTONE N="179a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As eny louyere to his lady shall</L>
<L>Saue &thorn;at &thorn;e name of souereynte</L>
<L N="752">That wolde he han for shame of his degre</L>
