<L N="1344">&thorn;at such a meschaunce shuld euere be
<PB REF="00000424.tif" N="394"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="518"></L>
<L>It is a&yogh;einst &thorn;e processe of nature<NOTE PLACE="marg">[These lines are trans|posed in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And home she go&thorn; a soriful creature<NOTE PLACE="marg">[These lines are trans|posed in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor verrey fere vnne&thorn;es may she goo /</L>
<L N="1348">She wepe&thorn; and weille&thorn; a day or twoo</L>
<L>And swowne&thorn; &thorn;at it rauthe was to see</L>
<L>But whi it was to no wi&yogh;t tolde she</L>
<L>ffor out of toune was goon Arueragus</L>
<L N="1352">But to hure self she seide and speke &thorn;us.</L>
<L>In hure compleynte as &yogh;e shul aftere here</L>
<L>With face pale and wi&thorn; soriful chere</L>
<L>Allas quod she on &thorn;e fortune I playn</L>
<L N="1356">&thorn;at vnware hast wrapped me in &thorn;i chayn</L>
<L>ffor which &thorn;e eskape wote I no socour</L>
<L>Saue only de&thorn; ei&thorn;er dishonour</L>
<L>Oon of &thorn;ise two bihoueth me to chese</L>
<L N="1360">But na&thorn;elees &yogh;it had I leuer lese</L>
<L>My lif &thorn;an of my body to haue a shame</L>
<L>Ei&thorn;er knowe my self fals ei&thorn;er lese my name</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; my de&thorn; I may be quytte I-wis</L>
<L N="1364">Han &thorn;er nat mony a wif er &thorn;is</L>
<L>And mony a maiden sclayn her self allas</L>
<L>Ra&thorn;er &thorn;an wi&thorn; her bodies done trespas</L>
<L>And certes loo &thorn;ise stories beren witnesse</L>
<L N="1368">Whan xxx.<SUP>ti</SUP> tirauntz ful of cursednesse.</L>
<L>Had sclayn Phidon in Athenes at &thorn;e lest<MILESTONE N="187b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>They commaunded his dou&yogh;ters to arest</L>
<L>And bringgen [hem] byforn hym in despit</L>
<L N="1372">Al naked to fulfille her foule delite</L>
<L>And in her faders bloode &thorn;ei made hem daunce</L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;e pauement god &yogh;eue hem meschaunce</L>
<L>ffor which &thorn;ise wooful maidens ful of drede</L>
<L N="1376">Rai&thorn;er &thorn;an &thorn;ei wolde lese her maidenhede</L>
<L>&thorn;ei prively bene sterte into a welle</L>
<L>And dreinte hem self as &thorn;e bokes telle</L>
<L>Thei of mesue lete enquere and seke</L>
<L N="1380">Of lacedemye .l. maidens eke
<PB REF="00000425.tif" N="395"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="519"></L>
<L>On which &thorn;ei wolden don her lecherie</L>
<L>But was &thorn;er none of al &thorn;at companye</L>
<L>&thorn;at she nas sclayn and wi&thorn; a glad entent</L>
<L N="1384">Chese &thorn;e ra&thorn;ere to die &thorn;an to assent</L>
<L>To bene enpressed of her maidenhede</L>
<L>Whi shuld I &thorn;an to dye bene in drede</L>
<L>Lo eke &thorn;e tiraunte Austoclides</L>
<L N="1388">&thorn;at loued a maiden which hi&yogh;t Symphalides</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at hure fadere sclayn was on a ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>Vnto Dianes temple go&thorn; she anon ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>And hent &thorn;e ymage wi&thorn; hure armes twoo /</L>
<L N="1392">ffrom which ymage she nolde neuer goo</L>
<L>No wi&yogh;t my&yogh;t fro hit hure handis race</L>
<L>Til she was sclayn in &thorn;e self place</L>
<L>Nowe si&thorn;ens &thorn;at maidens had such despit</L>
<L N="1396">To bene defouled wi&thorn; mannys foule delite</L>
<L>Wel ou&yogh;te a wiff ra&thorn;ere hure self slee</L>
<L>&thorn;an ben defouled as &thorn;enke&thorn; me</L>
<L>What shal I sayn of hasdrubaldys wif</L>
<L N="1400">&thorn;at at Cartage biraft herself hur liff</L>
<L>ffor whan she segh &thorn;at Romayns wan &thorn;e toun</L>
<L>She toke her chuldren alle and swept adoun</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e fuyre and ches rather to dye</L>
<L N="1404">&thorn;an eny Romayn did hure vilenye</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; not lucres ysclayn hure self allas<MILESTONE N="188a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>At Rome &thorn;ere she oppressed was</L>
<L>Of Tarquyne for hure &thorn;ou&yogh;t it was a shame</L>
<L N="1408">To live whan &thorn;at she had lost her name</L>
<L>The .viij. maidens of Melefie also /</L>
<L>Han sclayn hem self for drede and woo /</L>
<L>Ra&thorn;er &thorn;an folk of gaule shuld hem oppresse</L>
<L N="1412">Moo &thorn;an a M<SUP>1</SUP> stories as I gesse</L>
<L>Cou&thorn;e I nowe telle as touching &thorn;is matere</L>
<L>Whan habradas was sclayn his wif so dere</L>
<L>Her self sclowe and lete her blood to glide</L>
<L N="1416">In Habradas woundes brood and wide
<PB REF="00000426.tif" N="396"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="520"></L>
<L>And saide my body at &thorn;e leeste waye</L>
<L>Ther shal no wi&yogh;t defoile if &thorn;at I may</L>
<L>What shuld I moo ensamples herof sayn</L>
<L N="1420">Si&thorn;en &thorn;at so mony han hem self sclayn</L>
<L>Wel ra&thorn;er &thorn;an &thorn;ei wolde defowled be</L>
<L>I wil conclude what is best for me</L>
<L>[Tho sleen my self. than be defouled thus</L>
<L N="1424">I wilbe trewe . vnto Arueragus<MILESTONE UNIT="MS Reg. 17 D 15 folio" N="188a">]</L>
<L>Ei&thorn;er ra&thorn;er slee my self in some manere</L>
<L>As did Demonycions dou&yogh;tere dere</L>
<L>By cause &thorn;at she nolde defoiled be</L>
<L N="1428">O Cedasus it is ful grete pite</L>
<L>To reden how &thorn;i dou&yogh;ters deiden allas</L>
<L>&thorn;at sclowe hem self for suche manere cas</L>
<L>As grete appetit was it or more</L>
<L N="1432">The theban maiden &thorn;at for Nichasore</L>
<L>[Hir selfen slough right for suche a maner woo</L>
<L>Another theban mayden dide right so<MILESTONE UNIT="MS Reg. 17 D 15 folio" N="188a">]</L>
<L>Hure had wedded and sore dressed.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[spurious]</NOTE></L>
<L N="1435">For oon of Masidoigne had hure oppressed.</L>
<L>What shal I seyn of Nicharatyfs wiff</L>
<L>&thorn;at for such caas biraft her self her lif</L>
<L>Howe trewe was eke to Alcebiades</L>
<L N="1440">His loue &thorn;at forto dyen [ra&thorn;er] ches</L>
<L>&thorn;an forto suffre his body vmbreided be</L>
<L>Loo which a wif was alcesteyn quod she</L>
<L>What Emore of good Penolo&thorn;e</L>
<L N="1444">Alle Grece knowe&thorn; of her chaastite</L>
<L>Parde of leodomya is written &thorn;us<MILESTONE N="188b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That whan a Troy was sclayn protheselayus</L>
<L>No lenger nold she lyf aftere his day</L>
<L N="1448">&THORN;e same of noble porcia telle I maye</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen brutus quod she not lyve</L>
<L>To whom [s]he had alhole hure herte &yogh;eue</L>
<L>The parfit wifhode of Archemesie</L>
<L N="1452">Honoured is &thorn;orgh alle &thorn;e barberye
<PB REF="00000427.tif" N="397"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="521"></L>
<L>O teuta quene in &thorn;i wifly chastite</L>
<L>To alle wives may &thorn;ou a myrour be</L>
<L>. . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS: these lines</NOTE></L>
<L N="1456">. . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">known only in Ellesmere MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thus playned Dorigen a day or tweye</L>
<L>Purposinge euere &thorn;at she wolde deye</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles vpon &thorn;e &thorn;red ny&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1460">Home came Arueragus &thorn;e worthi kny&yogh;t</L>
<L>And asked hure whi &thorn;at she wepte so sore</L>
<L>And she gan wepen euere &thorn;e lenger more</L>
<L>Allas quod she &thorn;at euere was I borne</L>
<L N="1464">Thus haue I seide quod she &thorn;us haue I sworn</L>
<L>I tolde hym alle as &yogh;e han herde bifore</L>
<L>It nede&thorn; not rehersen it here-of no more.</L>
<L>This husbonde wi&thorn; glad chere in sondry wise</L>
<L N="1468">Answerde and seide as I shal [&yogh;ou] devise</L>
<L>Is &thorn;er ou&yogh;t ellis Dorigen but &thorn;is</L>
<L>Nay nay quod she god helpe me so as wisse</L>
<L>&THORN;is is to moche if it were goddes wille</L>
<L N="1472">&yogh;e wiff quod he lat sclepe &thorn;at is stille</L>
<L>It may be wel &yogh;it perauenture to saye</L>
<L>&YOGH;e shullen &yogh;oure trou&thorn;e holden be my fay</L>
<L>ffor god so wisly helpe me</L>
<L N="1476">I had wel leuere ystikked forto be</L>
<L>ffor verrey loue which I to &yogh;ou haue</L>
<L>But &yogh;if &yogh;e shuld &yogh;oure trouthe Saue</L>
<L>Trou&thorn;e is &thorn;e hiest &thorn;ing &thorn;at man may kepe</L>
<L N="1480">But wi&thorn; &thorn;at word he brast an&omacr;n to wepe</L>
<L>And seide I &yogh;ou forbede in peyn of deth</L>
<L>That neuer whiles &yogh;ou laste&thorn; lif &amp; breth</L>
<L>To no wi&yogh;t telle of &thorn;is cure<MILESTONE N="189a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1484">As I may I most my lif endure</L>
<L>Ne make no countenaunce of heuynesse</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk of &yogh;ou may deme harme or gesse</L>
<L>And for&thorn; he clepe&thorn; a sqwiere and a mayde</L>
<L N="1488">Go&thorn; for&thorn; anon with Dorigen he saide
<PB REF="00000428.tif" N="398"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="522"></L>
<L>And bringe&thorn; hure to such a place anon</L>
<L>Thei toke her leue and on her way &thorn;ei gon</L>
<L>But &thorn;ei ne wiste whi she thider went</L>
<L N="1492">He nolde no wi&yogh;t telle hure entent</L>
<L>. . . . . <NOTE PLACE="marg">[These lines known only in the Ellesmere MS.]</NOTE></L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="1496">. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>This Sqwier which &thorn;at hi&yogh;t Aurelius</L>
<L N="1500">On dorigen which &thorn;at was so amerous</L>
<L>Of auenture happed hure to mete</L>
<L>Amydde &thorn;e toune ri&yogh;t in &thorn;e qwikke strete</L>
<L>As she was boune to goo &thorn;e way for&thorn; ri&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1504">Toward the gardeyn &thorn;er as she had hi&yogh;t</L>
<L>And he was to &thorn;e gardeyn ward also</L>
<L>ffor wel he aspied whan she wolde goo</L>
<L>Out of her hous to eny manere place</L>
<L N="1508">But &thorn;us &thorn;ei mette by auenture or grace</L>
<L>And he salue&thorn; her wi&thorn; glad entent</L>
<L>And axed of hure whidere &thorn;at she went</L>
<L>And she answerd half as she were madde</L>
<L N="1512">Vnto &thorn;e Gardyne as myn husbond badde</L>
<L>My trou&thorn;e forto hold allas allas</L>
<L>Aurelius gan wondere of &thorn;is cas.</L>
<L>And in his hert had grete compassion</L>
<L N="1516">Of hure and of her lamentacion</L>
<L>And of Arueragus &thorn;e wor&thorn;i kny&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;at bad hure holde al &thorn;at she hight</L>
<L>So lo&thorn;e he was hys wiff sholde breke her trou&thorn;e</L>
<L N="1520">And in his hert he cast of &thorn;is grete routhe</L>
<L>Consideringe &thorn;e best on euery side</L>
<L>&thorn;at from his lust hym were better abide</L>
<L>Than done so high a cherles wrecchednesse</L>
<L N="1524">A&yogh;einst fraunches and al gentilnesse
<PB REF="00000429.tif" N="399"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="523"></L>
<L>ffor which in fewe wordes seide he &thorn;us<MILESTONE N="189b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Madame sei&thorn; to &yogh;oure lorde Arueragus.</L>
<L>&THORN;at si&thorn;en I se his grete gentilnesse</L>
<L N="1528">To &yogh;ou and eke I see wel &yogh;oure distresse</L>
<L N="1530">If &yogh;e by me shulde breke &yogh;oure trou&thorn;e</L>
<L N="1529">Certes me &thorn;enke&thorn; it were grete rou&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">[spurious]</NOTE></L>
<L>I haue wel leuer euere to suffre woo</L>
<L N="1532">&thorn;an I departe &thorn;e loue ytwix &yogh;ou twoo</L>
<L>I &yogh;ou relese madame into &yogh;oure honde</L>
<L>Quite euery surement and euery bonde</L>
<L>That &yogh;e han made to me as here biforn</L>
<L N="1536">&para; Si&thorn;ens &thorn;ilk tyme &thorn;at &yogh;e were born</L>
<L>My trou&thorn;e I pli&yogh;t I shal &yogh;ou neuer repreef. ./</L>
<L>Of no biheest and here I take my leue</L>
<L>As of &thorn;e trewest &amp; &thorn;e beste wiff</L>
<L N="1540">&thorn;at euere &yogh;it I knewe in al my liff</L>
<L>And euery wi&yogh;t be ware of hure bihest</L>
<L>On Dorygen remembre&thorn; at &thorn;e leste</L>
<L>Thus can a squyere don a gentile dede</L>
<L N="1544">As wel as can a kny&yogh;t wi&thorn;-oute drede</L>
<L>She &thorn;onked hym vpon hure knees al bare</L>
<L>And home vnto hure husbonde is she fare</L>
<L>And tolde hym alle as &yogh;e han herd me seide</L>
<L N="1548">And be &yogh;e siker he was ful wel apaide</L>
<L>It were impossible to write</L>
<L>What nede&thorn; lenger in &thorn;is cas endite</L>
<L>&para; Arueragus and Dorigen his wiff</L>
<L N="1552">In souereyn blisse leden for&thorn; her lif</L>
<L>Neuer aftere was &thorn;er anger hem bitwene</L>
<L>He Shershed hure as &thorn;ou&yogh;e she were a quene</L>
<L>And she was to hym trewe for euermore</L>
<L N="1556">Of &thorn;ise two folk &yogh;e gete of me no more</L>
<L>&para; Aurelius &thorn;at his cost ha&thorn; forlorn</L>
<L>Curse&thorn; &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at euere he was born</L>
<L>Allas quod he alas &thorn;at I bihi&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1560">Of pured gold a thousand pounde of wi&yogh;t
<PB REF="00000430.tif" N="400"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="524"></L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;is philosople how shal I doo<MILESTONE N="190a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I se no more but &thorn;at I am fordoo</L>
<L>Mine heritage most I selle</L>
<L N="1564">And bene a begger here I may not dwelle</L>
<L>And shamen al my kynrede in &thorn;is place</L>
<L>But I of him may gete better grace</L>
<L>But na&thorn;elees I wil of hym assaie</L>
<L N="1568">At certeyn dayes &yogh;ere by &yogh;ere to paie</L>
<L>And &thorn;onke him of his grete curtesie</L>
<L>My trou&thorn;e wil I kepe I wil not lie</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; herte sore he go&thorn; vnto his cofre</L>
<L N="1572">And brou&yogh;te golde vnto &thorn;is philysophre</L>
<L>&thorn;e value of .v. C. pounde I gesse</L>
<L>And hym biseche&thorn; of his gentilnesse</L>
<L>To graunte hym daies of &thorn;e remenaunte</L>
<L N="1576">And saide maistere I dar wel make auaunte</L>
<L>I failled neuere of my trou&thorn;e &yogh;it</L>
<L>ffor sikerly my dette shal be quytt</L>
<L>Towardes &yogh;ou how &thorn;at euere I fare</L>
<L N="1580">To goon a begger in my kirtel bare</L>
<L>But wolde &yogh;e vouche sauf vpon swerte</L>
<L>Two &yogh;ere or &thorn;re forto respite me</L>
<L>&THORN;an were I welle for ellis mote I selle</L>
<L N="1584">&para; Myn heritage &thorn;er nys no more to telle</L>
<L>This Philisophre soberly answerde</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;us whan he &thorn;is word herde</L>
<L>Haue I not holde conaunte vnto &thorn;e</L>
<L N="1588">&YOGH;is certes wel and trewly quod he</L>
<L>hast &thorn;ou not had &thorn;i lady as &thorn;e like&thorn;</L>
<L>No no quod he and sorily he sike&thorn;</L>
<L>What was &thorn;e cause telle me &yogh;if &thorn;ou can</L>
<L N="1592">Aurelius his tale anon bygan</L>
<L>And tolde hym alle as &yogh;e han herd bifore</L>
<L>It nede&thorn; not to rehercen it no more</L>
<L>He saide Arueragus of gentilnesse</L>
<L N="1596">Had leuere dey in sorowe and distresse
<PB REF="00000431.tif" N="401"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="525"></L>
<L>Than his wif were of hure trew&thorn;e fals<MILESTONE N="190b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>The sorowe of dorigen he tolde hym als</L>
<L>Howe lo&thorn;e hire was to be a wicked wiff</L>
<L N="1600">And &thorn;at she leuere &thorn;at day lost hure liff</L>
<L>And &thorn;at hure trou&thorn;e she swore &thorn;ourgh Innocence</L>
<L>She neuere erst herde speke of apparence</L>
<L>That made me han of hure so grete pite</L>
<L N="1604">And ri&yogh;t as frely as he sent hire me</L>
<L>As freely sent I hire to hym a&yogh;ein</L>
<L>This is alle and some &thorn;er nys no more to seyn</L>
<L>This Philisophre answerd leue bro&thorn;er</L>
<L N="1608">Euerich of &yogh;ou did gentilich til o&thorn;er</L>
<L>Thou art a squyere and he a kny&yogh;t</L>
<L>But god forbede for his blisful my&yogh;t</L>
<L>But if a clerk cou&thorn;e do a gentile dede</L>
<L N="1612">As wel as eny of &yogh;ou it is no drede</L>
<L>Sir I relece &thorn;e &thorn;i &thorn;ousand pounde</L>
<L>As &thorn;ow ri&yogh;t nowe were cropen out of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> grounde</L>
<L>Ne neuere er nowe haddest &thorn;ou knowe me</L>
<L N="1616">ffor sir I nyl not take a peny of &thorn;e</L>
<L>ffor al my craft and my travaile</L>
<L>&thorn;ow hast ypaied wel for my vitaile</L>
<L>It is ynowe and fare wele &amp; haue good day</L>
<L N="1620">And toke his hors and for&thorn; he go&thorn; his way</L>
<L>&para; Lordingges &thorn;is question wil I aske nowe</L>
<L>Which was &thorn;e most free as &thorn;enke&thorn; &yogh;ou</L>
<L>Nowe telle&thorn; me er &thorn;at I for&thorn;er wende</L>
<L N="1624">I Can no more my tale is at an ende</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>&para; Thus ende&thorn; &thorn;e ffrankleyn his tale</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
