<PB REF="00000432.tif" N="402">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="527">
<HEAD>GROUP <B>G.</B> FRAGMENT VIII.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&sect; 1. THE SECOND NUN'S TALE.</HEAD>
<HEAD>PETWORTH MS.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; And here byginne&thorn; &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> prologe of ij. nonne [THE PROEM.]<NOTE PLACE="head">[No breaks between the stanzas in the MS.]</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 190, <I>back</I></NOTE></HEAD>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">The mynystere and &thorn;e norice vnto vices</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at men clepen in englissh ydelnesse</L>
<L>The porter of &thorn;e gate is of delices</L>
<L N="4">To eschewe and by her contrary hure oppresse</L>
<L>&thorn;at is to sayn by leeful bysynesse</L>
<L>Wel ou&yogh;t we to don our entent</L>
<L N="7">Lest &thorn;at &thorn;e feend &thorn;orgh ydelnesse vs shent<MILESTONE N="191a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="8">For he &thorn;at wi&thorn; his &thorn;ousande cordes scli&yogh;e</L>
<L>Continuelly vs waite&thorn; to be-clappe</L>
<L>Whan he may man in ydelnesse aspie</L>
<L N="11">He can so li&yogh;tly cacche him in his trappe</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at a man be hent ri&yogh;t by &thorn;e lappe</L>
<L>He nys nat ware &thorn;e fende ha&thorn; hym on hond</L>
<L N="14">wel ou&yogh;t vs worch and ydelnesse wi&thorn;stond</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="15">And &thorn;ou&yogh;e men dradden neuere forto deye</L>
<L>&yogh;it seen men wel by resoun doutelees</L>
<L>That ydelnesse is roten scloggardye</L>
<L N="18">Of whiche &thorn;er neuere commeth non encrees</L>
<L>And si&thorn;ens &thorn;at sclouth hure holde&thorn; in a lees</L>
<L>Only to sclepe and forto ete and drinke</L>
<L N="21">And to devouren alle &thorn;at o&thorn;ere swynke
<PB REF="00000433.tif" N="403"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="528"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L N="22">And forto putten vs from such ydelnesse</L>
<L>That cause is of &thorn;e grete confusion</L>
<L>I haue here done my fei&thorn;ful bysynesse</L>
<L N="25">Aftere &thorn;e legende in translaci&omacr;n</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t of &thorn;i glorious lif and passion</L>
<L>Thow wi&thorn; &thorn;i garlond wrou&yogh;t of rooses and lilie</L>
<L N="28">The mene I maiden and marter seint Cicile</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L N="29">And &thorn;ou &thorn;at floure of virgynes art alle</L>
<L>Of whom &thorn;at Barnard lust so wel to write</L>
<L>To &thorn;e at my bygynnyng furst I calle</L>
<L N="32">Thou comforte of vs wrecches do me endite</L>
<L>&thorn;ine maidens de&thorn; &thorn;at was &thorn;orgh &thorn;i merite</L>
<L>&thorn;e eternal lif and of &thorn;e feende victorie</L>
<L N="35">Certes men may aftere reden in his storie</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L N="36">Thow maiden and modere dou&yogh;ter of &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> sone</L>
<L>Thow welle of mercy synful soules cure</L>
<L>In whom &thorn;at god for bounte chees to wone<NOTE PLACE="marg">[wone <I>later</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L N="39">Thowe humble and hegh ouere euery creature</L>
<L>Thou nobledest so ferre oure nature</L>
<L>That no desdeyn &thorn;e maker had of kynde</L>
<L N="42">His sone in blood and flessh to clo&thorn; and wynde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L N="43">Wi&thorn;-Inne &thorn;e cloystere blisful of &thorn;i sidys<MILESTONE N="191b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Toke mannys shappe &thorn;e eterne loue and pees</L>
<L>&thorn;at of &thorn;e trynie compas lorde and gide es</L>
<L N="46">Whom er&thorn;e and see and heuene wi&thorn; out relees</L>
<L>Ay heryen and &thorn;ou virgyne wemlees</L>
<L>Bare of &thorn;i body and dwellest maiden pure</L>
<L N="49">&thorn;e creatour of euery creature
<PB REF="00000434.tif" N="404"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="529"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L N="50">Assembled is in &thorn;e magnificence</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; mercy goodnesse and such pite</L>
<L>That &thorn;ou arte &thorn;e sonne of excellence</L>
<L N="53">Nou&yogh;t only helpest hem &thorn;at preien &thorn;e</L>
<L>But oftetyme of &thorn;i benignyte</L>
<L>fful frely er &thorn;at men &thorn;ine helpe biseche</L>
<L N="56">&thorn;ow goost byforn and art her lyues leche</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L N="57">Now helpe &thorn;ou meke and blisful faire maide</L>
<L>Me flemed wrech in &thorn;is deserte of galle</L>
<L>Thenk on &thorn;e womman Canane &thorn;at saide</L>
<L N="60">&thorn;at whelpes eten somme of &thorn;e crommes alle</L>
<L>&thorn;at from her lordis table bene yfalle</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;at I &thorn;e vnwor&thorn;i sone of Eue</L>
<L N="63">Be sinful &yogh;it accepte my bileue</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L N="64">And for &thorn;at fei&thorn; is dede wi&thorn;-out werkes</L>
<L>So for to worchen &yogh;eue me witte and space</L>
<L>&thorn;at I be quytte from place &thorn;at most derk es</L>
<L N="67">O &thorn;ou &thorn;at art so faire and so ful of grace</L>
<L>Be myne aduocate in so high a place</L>
<L>Ther as wi&thorn;-out ende is songe Osanna</L>
<L N="70">&thorn;ou cristes moder and dou&yogh;ter of Anna</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L N="71">And of &thorn;i li&yogh;t my soule in prison li&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;at troubled is by &thorn;e contagion</L>
<L>Of my body and also by &thorn;e wi&yogh;t</L>
<L N="74">Of er&thorn;ly lust and fals affection</L>
<L>O heuene o. refute .o saluacion</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at bene in sorowe and in distresse</L>
<L N="77">Nowe helpe; for to my werk I wil me dresse
<PB REF="00000435.tif" N="405"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="530"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L N="78">&YOGH;it prey I &yogh;ou &thorn;at reden &thorn;at I write</L>
<L>fforyeue&thorn; me &thorn;at I doo no diligence<MILESTONE N="192a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;is ilk storie subtely to endite</L>
<L N="81">ffor bo&thorn; haue I &thorn;e wordys and &thorn;e sentence</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at at sey[n]tes reuerence</L>
<L>&thorn;e storie wroot and folowen her legende</L>
<L N="84">And prei &yogh;ou &thorn;at &yogh;e wil my werk amende</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13) [THE TALE.]</HEAD>
<L N="85">First wolde I &yogh;ou &thorn;e name of seint Cicile</L>
<L>Expoune as men in her stories see</L>
<L>It is to saye in engelisshe heuenes lilie</L>
<L N="88">ffor pure chaastnesse of virginite</L>
<L>Oi&thorn;er for she witnesse had of honeste</L>
<L>Of grene of consciens and of good fame</L>
<L N="91">The swote sauoure lilie was hure name</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L N="92">Oy&thorn;ere Cicile is to say &thorn;e way to blynde</L>
<L>ffor she ensample was by good techinge</L>
<L>Or ellis Cicile as I writen fynde</L>
<L N="95">Is ioyned by a manere conioynynge</L>
<L>Of heuene and lya and hier in figurynge</L>
<L>&thorn;e heuene is sette for &thorn;ou&yogh;t of holynesse</L>
<L N="98">And lya for hure lastinge bisynesse</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L N="99">Cicile maye eke be seide in &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>Wantyng of blyndenesse for hure grete li&yogh;t</L>
<L>Of sapience and of her thewes clere</L>
<L N="102">Oi&thorn;er ellis loo &thorn;is maidens name bri&yogh;t</L>
<L>Of heuene and leos comme&thorn; for which by ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>Men my&yogh;t &thorn;e heuene of puple hure calle</L>
<L N="105">Ensample of good and wise werkes alle
<PB REF="00000436.tif" N="406"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="531"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L N="106">For leos puple in englissh is to say</L>
<L>And ri&yogh;t as men may in &thorn;e heuen see</L>
<L>The sonne and mone and &thorn;e sterres euery way</L>
<L N="109">Ri&yogh;t so [men] goostly in &thorn;is maiden fre</L>
<L>Seen &thorn;e fei&thorn; of magnificence</L>
<L>And eke of helpe and of sapience</L>
<L N="112">And sondry werkes bri&yogh;t of excellence</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L N="113">And ri&yogh;t as &thorn;ise philisophres write</L>
<L>&thorn;at heuene is swift rounde and brennynge</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t so was faire Cicile &thorn;o white<MILESTONE N="192b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="116">fful swift and bisy euere in werkinge</L>
<L>And rounde and hool in good perseuerynge</L>
<L>And brenne euere in charite li&yogh;t</L>
<L N="119">Now haue I declared &yogh;ou what she hi&yogh;t</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; Thus ende&thorn; &thorn;e prologe / &amp; here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> .ij nonnes tale</HEAD>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L>This maiden bri&yogh;t Cicile as hure lif sai&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; &thorn;e tale.</NOTE></L>
<L>was commen of Romaynes and of noble kynde</L>
<L>And so for&thorn;e fostred vp in &thorn;e fai&thorn;</L>
<L N="123">Of criste and bare hys gospel in her mynde</L>
<L>She neuere sesed as I writen fynde</L>
<L>Of hure preiere and god to loue and drede</L>
<L N="126">Bisechinge hym to kepe her maidenhede</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L N="127">And whan &thorn;is maiden shuld vnto a man</L>
<L>ywedded be &thorn;at was ful &yogh;enge of age</L>
<L>That ycleped was valirian</L>
<L N="130">And &thorn;e day was commen of hure mariage</L>
<L>She fille deuoute and humble in her corage</L>
<L>Vndere hure Robe of gold &thorn;at sat ful faire</L>
<L N="133">And next hure flessh yclad was in an haire
<PB REF="00000437.tif" N="407"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="532"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<L N="134">And while &thorn;e Orgels maden melodie</L>
<L>To god allone &thorn;us in hert songe she</L>
<L>O lorde my saule and eke my body gie</L>
<L N="137">Vnwemmed lest &thorn;at I confounded be</L>
<L>And for his loue &thorn;at dyed on a tree</L>
<L>Euery secounde or <I>thridde</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS .iij.]</NOTE> day she fast</L>
<L N="140">Ay bidynge in here orisons ful fast</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21)</HEAD>
<L N="141">The nyght come and to bed she most goon</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hure husbonde as aften is &thorn;e manere</L>
<L>And priuely she seide an&omacr;n</L>
<L N="144">O swete and welbiloued spouse dere</L>
<L>&thorn;er is a counsaile and &yogh;e wold it here</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at ri&yogh;t fayn I wolde vnto &yogh;ou seien</L>
<L N="147">So &thorn;at &yogh;e me assured it nou&yogh;t bywreien</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(22)</HEAD>
<L N="148">Valeryan gan fast vnto hure swere</L>
<L>&thorn;at for no caas ne &thorn;inge &thorn;at my&yogh;t be</L>
<L>He shold for no &thorn;inge neuere bewrien here<MILESTONE N="193a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="151">And &thorn;an at arst &thorn;us to hym seide she</L>
<L>I haue an aungell which &thorn;at loue&thorn; me</L>
<L>&thorn;at wi&thorn; grete loue whedere I wake or slepe</L>
<L N="154">Is redy ay my body forto kepe</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(23)</HEAD>
<L N="155">And &yogh;if &thorn;at &yogh;e may felen out of drede</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;e wil &yogh;ou gouerne no &thorn;inge amys</L>
<L>He wil &yogh;ou saue and kepe to &yogh;e be dede</L>
<L N="158">ffor &yogh;oure clene lyuyng &amp; &yogh;oure goodnesse</L>
<L>And bring &yogh;ou strei&yogh;te into heuene blesse</L>
<L>He wol &yogh;ou loue as me for &yogh;oure clennesse</L>
<L N="161">And schewen &yogh;ou of his Ioye and his bri&yogh;tnesse
<PB REF="00000438.tif" N="408"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="533"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(24)</HEAD>
<L N="162">Valerian corrected as god wolde</L>
<L>Answerde a&yogh;ein if I shal trust to &thorn;e</L>
<L>lat me &thorn;at aungel se and hym biholde</L>
<L N="165">And &yogh;if &thorn;at it a verrei aungel be</L>
<L>&THORN;an wil I done as &thorn;ou hast preide me</L>
<L>&para; And &yogh;if &thorn;ou loue ano&thorn;er man &thorn;an me</L>
<L N="168">ri&yogh;t wi&thorn; &thorn;is swerde I wil slee &yogh;ou bo&thorn;e</L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(25)</HEAD>
<L N="169">Cicile Answerde anone in &thorn;is wise</L>
<L>And if &yogh;ou lust &thorn;at aungel shul &yogh;e see</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &yogh;e trowe on criste and &yogh;ou baptise</L>
<L N="172">Go&thorn; for&thorn; to Via Apia quod she</L>
<L>&thorn;at from &thorn;is toune ne stant but myles &thorn;re</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e pore folk &thorn;at &thorn;ere dwelle</L>
<L N="175">Say hem ri&yogh;t &thorn;us as &thorn;at I shal &yogh;ou telle</L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(26)</HEAD>
<L N="176">Say &thorn;at I Cicilie &yogh;ou to hem sent</L>
<L>To shewe &yogh;ou &thorn;e good vrban &thorn;e olde</L>
<L>ffor secre nedes and for good entent</L>
<L N="179">And whan &thorn;at &yogh;e seint Vrban han byholde</L>
<L>Telle him &thorn;e wordes which I to &yogh;ou tolde</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at he ha&thorn; purged &yogh;ou fro synne</L>
<L N="182">&thorn;an shul &yogh;e seen &thorn;at aungel er &yogh;e twynne</L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(27)</HEAD>
<L N="183">Valerian is to &thorn;at place yg&omacr;n</L>
<L>And ri&yogh;t as hym was tau&yogh;t by his lurnynge</L>
<L>He fonde &thorn;is holy Vrban anon./</L>
<L N="186">Amonge &thorn;ise seintes buriels lowtynge<MILESTONE N="193b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And he anon wi&thorn;-out tariynge</L>
<L>Did his massage and whan he had [it] tolde</L>
<L N="189">Vrban for ioye gan his hondes vp holde
<PB REF="00000439.tif" N="409"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="534"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(28)</HEAD>
<L N="190">The teeres from his eien lete he falle</L>
<L>Almy&yogh;ty god o Ihesu crist quod he</L>
<L>Sowere of chaast counsaile &amp; herde of vs alle</L>
<L N="193">The fruyte of &thorn;ilke seede of chaastite</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou haste sawe in cicile take to &thorn;ee</L>
<L>Loo like a bisy bee wi&thorn;-out gile</L>
<L N="196">&thorn;e serueth ay &thorn;ine owne thralle Cicile</L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(29)</HEAD>
<L N="197">For &thorn;ilk spouse &thorn;at she toke but nowe</L>
<L>fful like a ferce leon she sende&thorn; here</L>
<L>As meke as eny lombe was to &yogh;ou&middot;</L>
<L N="200">And wi&thorn; &thorn;at worde anon &thorn;er gan apere</L>
<L>An olde man clad wi&thorn; white clo&thorn;es clere</L>
<L>And had a boke wi&thorn; lettres of golde in honde</L>
<L N="203">And gan biforne Valerian stonde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(30)</HEAD>
<L N="204">Valerian as dede fille doune for drede</L>
<L>whan he hym segh and hym vphent <B>&thorn;oo.</B></L>
<L>And on his boke &thorn;us he gan to rede</L>
<L N="207">Oo lord oo fei&thorn; oo god wi&thorn;-oute moo</L>
<L>Of cristendome and fadere of all also.</L>
<L>Abouen alle and oueral euery where</L>
<L N="210">&thorn;ise wordes al wi&thorn; gold [y]writen were</L>
</LG>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(31)</HEAD>
<L N="211">Whan &thorn;is was radde &thorn;at seide &thorn;is olde man</L>
<L>Leuest &thorn;ou &thorn;is &thorn;ing or no sai &yogh;e or nay</L>
<L>I leue al &thorn;is &thorn;in[g] / [quod Valerian</L>
<L N="214">ffor sother thyng<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl. 7335 folio" N="93b">] &amp;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[than <I>Harl.</I>]</NOTE> &thorn;is I dar wel saye</L>
<L>Vndere &thorn;e heuene no wi&yogh;t ne &thorn;enk may</L>
<L>&para; Tho vanshed &thorn;at olde man he nyst wher</L>
<L N="217">And pope Vrban hym cristened ri&yogh;t &thorn;ere
<PB REF="00000440.tif" N="410"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="535"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="32" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(32)</HEAD>
<L N="218">Valerian go&thorn; home to seint Cicile</L>
<L>And withInne his chambre an Aungel he segh stande</L>
<L>&THORN;is aungel had of rose and of lilie</L>
<L N="221">Corownes two &thorn;e whiche he bare on hande</L>
<L>And first to Cicile as I vnderstande</L>
<L>Be &yogh;af &thorn;at oon and aftere gan he take<MILESTONE N="194a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="224">&THORN;at o&thorn;er to Valerian her make</L>
</LG>
<LG N="33" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(33)</HEAD>
<L N="225">Wi&thorn; body clene and wi&thorn; vnwemmed &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>kepe&thorn; ay wel &thorn;ise corownes quod he</L>
<L>ffrom paradise to &yogh;ou haue I hem brou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="228">Ne neuere more shul &thorn;ei roten be</L>
<L>Ne lese her swete sauoure tresteth me</L>
<L>Ne neuere wi&yogh;t shal seene hem wi&thorn; his ye</L>
<L N="231">But he be chaast and hate vilenye</L>
</LG>
<LG N="34" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(34)</HEAD>
<L N="232">And &thorn;ou valerian for &thorn;ou so sone</L>
<L>Assentest to good counsaile also</L>
<L>ffay what &thorn;e lust and &thorn;ou shalt haue &thorn;i bone</L>
<L N="235">I haue a bro&thorn;er quod Valerian &thorn;oo</L>
<L>&thorn;at in &thorn;is world I loue no man soo /</L>
<L>I prey &yogh;ou &thorn;at my bro&thorn;ere may haue grace</L>
<L N="238">To knowe &thorn;e trou&thorn;e as I do in &thorn;is place</L>
</LG>
<LG N="35" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(35)</HEAD>
<L N="239">The aungel answerde god like&thorn; &yogh;our request</L>
<L>And bo&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;e palme of marterdome</L>
<L>&yogh;e shul come vnto &thorn;e blisful fest</L>
<L N="242">And wi&thorn; &thorn;at worde tiburce his bro&thorn;ere come</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at he &thorn;e sauoure vndernome</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e roses and &thorn;e lilies caste</L>
<L N="245">Wi&thorn;-Inne his herte he gan to wonder faste
<PB REF="00000441.tif" N="411"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="536"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="36" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(36)</HEAD>
<L N="246">And saide in &thorn;is tyme I wondere of &thorn;e &yogh;ere</L>
<L>whennys &thorn;is swete sauoure comme&thorn; soo /</L>
<L>And roses and lilies &thorn;at I smelle here</L>
<L N="249">ffor &thorn;ou&yogh;e I had hem in myn hondes twoo</L>
<L>&thorn;e sauoure my&yogh;t in me no depper goo</L>
<L>&thorn;e swete smelle &thorn;at in myn hert I fynde</L>
<L N="252">Ha&thorn; chaunged me al in a no&thorn;er kinde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="37" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(37)</HEAD>
<L N="253">Valerian saide two corownes haue we</L>
<L>Snowe white and rose rede &thorn;at shyne&thorn; clere</L>
<L>which &thorn;at &thorn;ine eyen han no my&yogh;t to see</L>
<L N="256">And as &thorn;owe smellest hem &thorn;our&yogh;e &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> preiere</L>
<L>So Shalt &thorn;ou sene hem leue bro&thorn;er dere</L>
<L>&yogh;if it so be &thorn;ou wilt wi&thorn;-oute sclou&thorn;e.</L>
<L>Byleue a ri&yogh;t and knowe &thorn;e verrey trou&thorn;e<MILESTONE N="194b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="38" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(38)</HEAD>
<L N="260">Tyburce answerd seist &thorn;ou &thorn;is to me</L>
<L>In so&thorn;nesse or in dreeme herken &yogh;e &thorn;is</L>
<L>In dremes quod Valerian han we be</L>
<L N="263">Into &thorn;is tyme bro&thorn;er myn ywis</L>
<L>But nowe at arst our trou&thorn;e dwelling is</L>
<L>Howe woost &thorn;ou quod Tiburce &amp; in what wise</L>
<L N="266">Quod Valerian &thorn;at shal I &thorn;e devise</L>
</LG>
<LG N="39" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(39)</HEAD>
<L N="267">The Aungel of god ha&thorn; me &thorn;e trou&thorn;e tau&yogh;t</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at &thorn;ou shalt seen if &thorn;at &thorn;ow wilt reneye</L>
<L>The ydoles and be clene and ellis nau&yogh;t</L>
<L N="270">But of &thorn;e myracles of &thorn;ise corownes tweye</L>
<L>Seint Ambrose in his preface list to seie</L>
<L>Solempnely this noble doctour dere</L>
<L N="273">Commende&thorn; it and sei&thorn; in &thorn;is manere
<PB REF="00000442.tif" N="412"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="537"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="40" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(40)</HEAD>
<L N="274">The palme of marterdome forto receyue</L>
<L>Seint Cicile fulfilled of goddys &yogh;ift</L>
<L>&thorn;e worlde and [e]ke hure chambre gan she weyue</L>
<L N="277">Witnesse Tiburce and Cicilees shrift</L>
<L>To which god of his bountee wolde shift</L>
<L>Corownes two of flowres wel smellynge</L>
<L N="280">And made &thorn;e aungel hem &thorn;oo corownes bringe</L>
</LG>
<LG N="41" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(41)</HEAD>
<L N="281">This made ha&thorn; brou&yogh;t &thorn;ise men to blisse aboue</L>
<L>&thorn;e world ha&thorn; wist what it is wor&thorn; certeyne</L>
<L>Deuocion of chastite to loue</L>
<L N="284">Tho shewed hym Cicile open and pleyne</L>
<L>That alle ydoles nys but &thorn;ing in veyne</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ei bene dombe and &thorn;erto &thorn;ei bene defe</L>
<L N="287">And charged hym his ydols forto lef</L>
</LG>
<LG N="42" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(42)</HEAD>
<L N="288">Who &thorn;at &thorn;is troue&thorn; nat a beest he is</L>
<L>Quod &thorn;oo tyburce if &thorn;at I shal not ly</L>
<L>She gan &thorn;an kisse his brest &amp; pat herd &thorn;is</L>
<L N="291">And was ful glad he cou&thorn;e trou&thorn; aspie</L>
<L>This daye take I &thorn;e for myne alye</L>
<L>Saide &thorn;is blesful maide faire &amp; dere</L>
<L N="294">ffor aftere &thorn;at she saide as &yogh;e may here ./</L>
</LG>
<LG N="43" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(43)</HEAD>
<L N="295">Loo ry&yogh;t so as &thorn;e loue of crist quod She<MILESTONE N="195a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Made me &thorn;i bro&thorn;eres wif ri&yogh;t in &thorn;at wise</L>
<L>Anoon for myn alie here take I &thorn;e</L>
<L N="298">Si&thorn;ens &thorn;at &thorn;ou wolt &thorn;ine ydoles despise</L>
<L>Go wi&thorn; &thorn;i bro&thorn;er nowe and &thorn;e baptise</L>
<L>And make &thorn;e clene so &thorn;at &thorn;ou maist beholde</L>
<L N="301">&thorn;e Aungels face of which &thorn;i brother tolde
<PB REF="00000443.tif" N="413"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="538"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="44" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(44)</HEAD>
<L N="302">Tyburse answerd and seide bro&thorn;er dere</L>
<L>ffurst telle me whidere I shal and to what man</L>
<L>To whome quod he come for&thorn; wi&thorn; ri&yogh;t goode chere</L>
<L N="305">I wil &thorn;e lede vnto &thorn;e pope Vrban</L>
<L>To Vrban bro&thorn;er myne Valerian</L>
<L>Quod &thorn;oo Tiburce wilt &thorn;ou me &thorn;idere lede</L>
<L N="308">Me &thorn;enke&thorn; &thorn;at it were a wondere dede</L>
</LG>
<LG N="45" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(45)</HEAD>
<L N="309">Remenest &thorn;ou nat Vrban quod he &thorn;oo</L>
<L>That is so ofte dampned to be dede</L>
<L>And wonne&thorn; in halkes to and froo</L>
<L N="312">And dar nat onys put for&thorn; his hede</L>
<L>Men shul hym brenne in a fire so rede</L>
<L>If he were founde &thorn;at men my&yogh;t hym spie</L>
<L N="315">And we also &thorn;at bere hym companye</L>
</LG>
<LG N="46" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(46)</HEAD>
<L N="316">And whiles we seken &thorn;ilk Dyuinyte</L>
<L>&thorn;at is ihidde in heuene prive</L>
<L>Algate ybrent in &thorn;is world shul we be.</L>
<L N="319">To whom Cicile answerd bodily</L>
<L>Men my&yogh;t drede wel and skilfully</L>
<L>This lif to lese myn owne dere bro&thorn;er</L>
<L N="322">&yogh;if &thorn;is were lyuynge only and non o&thorn;er</L>
</LG>
<LG N="47" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(47)</HEAD>
<L N="323">But &thorn;er is better lif in oo&thorn;er place</L>
<L>That neuere shal be lost drede &thorn;e nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Which goddes sone vs tolde &thorn;ourgh his grace</L>
<L>[That fadres sone hath alle thynges wrought<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl. 7335 folio" N="95b"></L>
<L>And al that wrought is with a skilful thoght</L>
<L>The gost that fro the fader gan procede</L>
<L N="329">hath sowled hem with-outen ony drede
<PB REF="00000444.tif" N="414"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="539"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="48" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(48)</HEAD>
<L N="330">By word and by myracle he goddes sone<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Harl. 7335]</NOTE></L>
<L>whan he was in this world declared here</L>
<L>That ther was other lif ther men may wone</L>
<L N="333">Tho answerde Tiburce o. suster dere</L>
<L>Ne sei-destow right now in this manere</L>
<L>Ther nys but o god lord in sothfastnesse</L>
<L N="336">And now of three how maisthow bere witnesse</L>
</LG>
<LG N="49" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(49)</HEAD>
<L>That shal y telle quod she or y go<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Harl. 7335 <I>extract ends</I>]</NOTE>]</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t as a man ha&thorn; sapiences &thorn;re</L>
<L>Memorie engeyne and intellecte also</L>
<L N="340">So in oo beinge of diuinite</L>
<L>Thre persones ri&yogh;t wel &thorn;er may be</L>
<L>Tho gan she hym bisily preche.</L>
<L>Of cristes come and of his peynes teche<MILESTONE N="195b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="50" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(50)</HEAD>
<L N="344">And mony poyntes of his passion</L>
<L>How goddys sonne in &thorn;is wi&thorn;-holde</L>
<L>To do mankynde pleyn remyssion</L>
<L N="347">That was ybounde in cares colde</L>
<L>Al &thorn;is &thorn;inge she vnto Tiburce tolde</L>
<L>And aftere &thorn;is Tiburce in good entent</L>
<L N="350">To pope Vrban wi&thorn; Valerian went</L>
</LG>
<LG N="51" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(51)</HEAD>
<L N="351">Which &thorn;onked god and wi&thorn; glad hert and li&yogh;t</L>
<L>He Cristned hym and made hym in &thorn;at place</L>
<L>Parfit in his lyuynge goddys kny&yogh;t</L>
<L N="354">And after &thorn;is Tiburce gate such grace</L>
<L>&thorn;at euery day he seie in tyme and space</L>
<L>&thorn;e Aungel of god and euery maner bone</L>
<L N="357">&thorn;at he god asked it was spedde ful sone
<PB REF="00000445.tif" N="415"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="540"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="52" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(52)</HEAD>
<L N="358">It were ful harde by order forto seyne</L>
<L>Howe mony wonders Ihesu for hym wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>But atte last to telle short and pleyn</L>
<L N="361">The sergeaunt of &thorn;e towne of Rome hem sou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And hem byforn Almache &thorn;e prouost brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Whiche hem opposed and knewe al her entent</L>
<L N="364">And to &thorn;e ymage of Iubiter he hem sent</L>
</LG>
<LG N="53" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(53)</HEAD>
<L N="365">And saide who so wil not sacrifise</L>
<L>Swap of his heued &thorn;is is my sentence here</L>
<L>Anone &thorn;ise marteers &thorn;at I &yogh;ou deuise</L>
<L N="368">On maximius &thorn;at was an officere</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e prefectis and of Corniculere</L>
<L>Hem hent and whan he for&thorn;e &thorn;e seyntes ladde</L>
<L N="371">Hym self he wepte for pite &thorn;at he hadde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="54" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(54)</HEAD>
<L N="372">Whan maximius had herde &thorn;e seintes lore</L>
<L>he gate hem of &thorn;e turmentours leue</L>
<L>And had hem in his hous wi&thorn;-out more</L>
<L N="375">And wi&thorn; her prechinge er &thorn;at it were eue</L>
<L>&thorn;ei gone from &thorn;e tormentours to reue</L>
<L>And fro maximius and fro his folk echone</L>
<L N="378">&thorn;e fals feith to trowe in god allone.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="55" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(55)</HEAD>
<L N="379">Cicile come whan it was woxen ny&yogh;t<MILESTONE N="196a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; preestes &thorn;at hem cristened al in fere</L>
<L>And afterward whan day was waxen li&yogh;t</L>
<L N="382">Cicile hem seide wi&thorn; a sobre chere</L>
<L>Now cristes owne kny&yogh;tes leef and dere</L>
<L>Caste&thorn; al away &thorn;e werkes of derknesse</L>
<L N="385">And arme&thorn; &yogh;ou in armure of li&yogh;tnesse
<PB REF="00000446.tif" N="416"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="541"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="56" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(56)</HEAD>
<L N="386">&YOGH;e han forso&thorn;e ydone grete bataille</L>
<L>Which is nowe done &yogh;oure fei&thorn; han &yogh;e confermed</L>
<L>Go&thorn; to &thorn;e corowne of lif &thorn;at may not faile</L>
<L N="389">The Ri&yogh;t Iuge which &thorn;at &yogh;e han disserued</L>
<L>Tofore hym &yogh;e bene fei&thorn;fulli preserued</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is &thorn;inge was seide as I deuise</L>
<L N="392">Men ladde hem for&thorn;e to done &thorn;e sacrifise</L>
</LG>
<LG N="57" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(57)</HEAD>
<L N="393">But whan &thorn;ei were vnto &thorn;e place brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>To telle shortely &thorn;e conclusioun</L>
<L>&THORN;ei nolde ensence ne sacrifise ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="396">But on her knees &thorn;ei setten hem adoun</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; humble hert and sad deuocioun</L>
<L>And losten bo&thorn; her hedes in &thorn;e place</L>
<L N="399">Her saules wenten to &thorn;e kinge of grace</L>
</LG>
<LG N="58" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(58)</HEAD>
<L N="400">This Maximius &thorn;at see &thorn;is &thorn;inge betide</L>
<L>wi&thorn; pitous tales tolde it anon ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>That he her sawles seghe to heuene glide</L>
<L N="403">Wi&thorn; aungels ful of cleernesse and of li&yogh;t</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; his worde conuerted mony a wi&yogh;t</L>
<L>ffor which Almachius did hym so to bete</L>
<L N="406">Wi&thorn; whippe of lede til he his lif gan lete</L>
</LG>
<LG N="59" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(59)</HEAD>
<L N="407">Cicile hym toke and buried hym an&omacr;n</L>
<L>By Tiburce and Valerian softely</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-Inne her heriyng place vnder &thorn;e ston</L>
<L N="410">And aftere &thorn;is Almachius hastely</L>
<L>Bad his mynystres fecchen opynly</L>
<L>Cicile so she my&yogh;t in his presence</L>
<L N="413">Don sacrifise and Iubiter ensence
<PB REF="00000447.tif" N="417"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="542"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="60" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(60)</HEAD>
<L N="414">But &thorn;ei conuerted &thorn;orgh her wise lore</L>
<L>Wepten sore and &yogh;af credence<MILESTONE N="196b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Vnto her worde and criden more and more</L>
<L N="417">Crist goddes sone wi&thorn;-oute difference</L>
<L>Is Verrey god &thorn;is is all oure sentence</L>
<L>&thorn;at ha&thorn; so good a seruaunte hym to serue</L>
<L N="420">Thus wi&thorn; oo vois we trowe &thorn;ou&yogh;e we sterue</L>
</LG>
<LG N="61" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(61)</HEAD>
<L N="421">Almachius &thorn;at herde al this [doinge]</L>
<L>Bad foche Cicile &thorn;at he my&yogh;t hure se</L>
<L>And alderfurst loo &thorn;is was his askinge</L>
<L N="424">What maner womman art &thorn;ou &thorn;o quod he</L>
<L>I am a gentile womman born quod she</L>
<L>I aske quod he &thorn;ou&yogh;e it &thorn;e greue</L>
<L N="427">Of &thorn;i religion and of &thorn;i bileue</L>
</LG>
<LG N="62" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(62)</HEAD>
<L N="428">Whi &thorn;an bygan &yogh;oure question folily</L>
<L>Quod she &thorn;at woldest two answers conclude</L>
<L>In oon demannde &yogh;e asked lewedely</L>
<L N="431">Almachy answerde to &thorn;at similitude</L>
<L>Of whennys [comth thyn answeryng so rude</L>
<L>Of whennys<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl. 7335 folio" N="97a">] quod she whan &thorn;at she was refreyned</L>
<L N="434">Of conscience and of good fei&thorn; vnfeyned</L>
</LG>
<LG N="63" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(63)</HEAD>
<L N="435">Almachius seide takest &thorn;ou non hede</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ine answere and she hym answerd &thorn;us</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure my&yogh;t quod she litel is to drede</L>
<L N="438">ffor euery mortell mannys power nys</L>
<L>But lich a bladdere ful of wynde ywis</L>
<L>ffor wi&thorn; a nedelys poynte whan &thorn;at is blowe</L>
<L N="441">May al &thorn;e boost of it be laide ful lowe
<PB REF="00000448.tif" N="418"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="543"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="64" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(64)</HEAD>
<L N="442">Ful wron[g]fully bygonne &thorn;ou quod he</L>
<L>And &yogh;it in wronge is &thorn;i perseueraunce</L>
<L>Woost &thorn;ou nat how oure my&yogh;ty princes fre</L>
<L N="445">Ben &thorn;us comaunded and maken ordinaunce</L>
<L>&thorn;at euery cristen wi&yogh;t shal han penaunce</L>
<L>But &yogh;if &thorn;at he his cristendome wi&thorn;seyn</L>
<L N="448">And goon al quite if he wil it receyne</L>
</LG>
<LG N="65" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(65)</HEAD>
<L N="449">&YOGH;oure princes aren as &yogh;oure noblen do&thorn;</L>
<L>Quod &thorn;oo Cicile and a woode sentence</L>
<L>&YOGH;e make vs gilty and it nys nat soth</L>
<L N="452">ffor &yogh;e &thorn;at knowen wel our Innocence<MILESTONE N="197a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor as moch as we done Reuerence</L>
<L>To criste and for we bere a cristen name</L>
<L N="455">&YOGH;e put on vs a cryme and eke a blame</L>
</LG>
<LG N="66" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(66)</HEAD>
<L N="456">But we &thorn;at knowen &thorn;ilk name soo</L>
<L>ffor vertuous we may it not say</L>
<L>Almachy answerde chese on of &thorn;ise twoo</L>
<L N="459">Do sacrifise or cristendome reney</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;owe may nowe scapen by &thorn;at way</L>
<L>At which &thorn;e holy blisful maide</L>
<L N="462">Gan forto lau&yogh;e and to &thorn;e Iuge she saide</L>
</LG>
<LG N="67" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(67)</HEAD>
<L N="463">O Iuge confuse in &thorn;i nycete</L>
<L>Wilt &thorn;ou &thorn;at I reneye Innocence</L>
<L>To maken me a wicked wi&yogh;t quod she</L>
<L N="466">loo he dissimule&thorn; here in audience</L>
<L>He stare&thorn; and wode&thorn; in his aduertence</L>
<L>To whom Almachius o vnsely wrecch</L>
<L N="469">Ne woost &thorn;ow not howe ferre my my&yogh;t may strecch
<PB REF="00000449.tif" N="419"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="544"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="68" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(68)</HEAD>
<L N="470">Ha&thorn; nou&yogh;t our my&yogh;ty prince to me y&yogh;ouen</L>
<L>&YOGH;e bo&thorn; powere and auctoritee</L>
<L>To make folk to dien or to lyuen</L>
<L N="473">Whi spekest &thorn;ou so proudly &thorn;an to me</L>
<L>I ne speke but stedfastly quod she</L>
<L>Nou&yogh;t proudely for I saie as for my side</L>
<L N="476">I hate dedly &thorn;ilke vice of pride</L>
</LG>
<LG N="69" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(69)</HEAD>
<L N="477">And &yogh;if &thorn;ou drede nou&yogh;t a so&thorn;e to here</L>
<L>&thorn;an wil I shewen al openly by ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou hast made a ful grete lesinge here</L>
<L N="480">Thow seist &thorn;i princes han &yogh;eue &thorn;e my&yogh;t</L>
<L>Bo&thorn; to sleene and forto quyk a wi&yogh;t</L>
<L>Thowe &thorn;at ne maist but only lif here by-reue</L>
<L N="483">Thow nast &thorn;erto nei&thorn;ere power ne leue</L>
</LG>
<LG N="70" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(70)</HEAD>
<L>[But &thorn;ou mayst sayn thi prynces han the maked<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl. 7335 folio" N="98a">]</L>
<L>Mynyster of de&thorn; for &yogh;if &thorn;ou speke of moo</L>
<L>&thorn;ow liest for &thorn;i power is ful naked</L>
<L N="487">Do way &thorn;i boldnesse saide Almachius &thorn;oo</L>
<L>And sacrifise to our goddys twoo.</L>
<L>I ne recche nou&yogh;t what wronge &thorn;at &thorn;ou me profre<MILESTONE N="197b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="490">ffor I can suffre it as a philosofre</L>
</LG>
<LG N="71" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(71)</HEAD>
<L N="491">But &thorn;ilk wronges may I nat endure</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou spekest of oure goddes here quod he</L>
<L>Cicele answerde oo nyce creature</L>
<L N="494">&thorn;ow seidest no word si&thorn; &thorn;ou spekest to me</L>
<L>&thorn;at I ne knewe &thorn;erwi&thorn; &thorn;i nycete</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;owe were in euery maner wise</L>
<L N="497">A lewde officere and a veyn Iustise
<PB REF="00000450.tif" N="420"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="545"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="72" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(72)</HEAD>
<L N="498">Ther lacke&thorn; no &thorn;inge to &thorn;ine vtter eyen</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou nart blynde for &thorn;ing &thorn;at we seen alle</L>
<L>&thorn;at is a stone &thorn;at men may wel aspien</L>
<L N="501">That ilke stoon a god &thorn;ou wolt it calle</L>
<L>I rede &thorn;e lat &thorn;ine h[ond] vppon it falle</L>
<L>And taast it wel and stoon &thorn;ou shalt it fynde</L>
<L N="504">Si&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou seest it nat wi&thorn; &thorn;ine eyen blynde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="73" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(73)</HEAD>
<L N="505">It is a shame &thorn;at &thorn;e puple shal</L>
<L>So scorne &thorn;e and lau&yogh;e at &thorn;i foly</L>
<L>ffor comonly wommen wote it. well ouerall</L>
<L N="508">That my&yogh;ty god is in heuene hie</L>
<L>And &thorn;ise ymages wel &thorn;an maist &thorn;ou spie</L>
<L>To &thorn;e ne to hem self may &thorn;ei nat profite</L>
<L N="511">And in her effecte &thorn;ei bene nat worth a myte</L>
</LG>
<LG N="74" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(74)</HEAD>
<L N="512">Thise and such o&thorn;er wordes saide She</L>
<L>And he wexe wroo&thorn; and bad she shuld be lede</L>
<L>home to her hous and in her hous quod he</L>
<L N="515">Brenne hure in a fuyre wi&thorn; flawmes rede</L>
<L>And as he bad ry&yogh;t so was done &thorn;e dede</L>
<L>And in a bath. &thorn;ei gan hure fast shetten</L>
<L N="518">And nyght and day grete fuyre vnder &thorn;ei maden</L>
</LG>
<LG N="75" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(75)</HEAD>
<L N="519">Al &thorn;e longe ny&yogh;t and eke &thorn;e day also</L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;e fuyre and eke &thorn;e ba&thorn;es hete</L>
<L>She satte al colde and felt of it no woo</L>
<L N="522">Ne made hure a drope nou&yogh;t forto swete</L>
<L>But in &thorn;at bath her lif She most lete</L>
<L>ffor he Almachie wi&thorn; ful wicked entent</L>
<L>To scleen hure in &thorn;e bath his sonde sent /<MILESTONE N="198a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000451.tif" N="421"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="546"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="76" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(76)</HEAD>
<L N="526">Thre strokes in &thorn;e nekke he smote hure &thorn;oo</L>
<L>The turmentour but for no manere chaunce</L>
<L>He my&yogh;t not smyten al her necke a two</L>
<L N="529">And for &thorn;er was &thorn;at tyme an ordynaunce</L>
<L>That none shuld to no man do such penaunce</L>
<L>&thorn;e fer&thorn;e stroke to smyten soft or sore</L>
<L N="532">This turmentour ne durst do no more.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="77" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(77)</HEAD>
<L N="533">But half dede wi&thorn; her necke ycoruen &thorn;ere</L>
<L>He laft hure lye and on his waye he went</L>
<L>&thorn;e Cristen folk which aboute hure were</L>
<L N="536">Wi&thorn; shetes home ful faire hure hente</L>
<L>Thre daies lyued she in &thorn;is torment</L>
<L>And neuere cesed hem &thorn;e fei&thorn; to teche</L>
<L N="539">Whom she had fostred hem she gan to preche</L>
</LG>
<LG N="78" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(78)</HEAD>
<L N="540">And hem she &yogh;af her meueables and her &thorn;inge</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e pope Vrban bytoke hem &thorn;oo</L>
<L>And saide &thorn;us I asked &thorn;is of heuene kynge</L>
<L N="543">To han respite. &thorn;re daies and no moo</L>
<L>To recomaunde to &yogh;ou er &thorn;at I goo</L>
<L>Thise soules loo; and &thorn;at I my&yogh;t to wirche</L>
<L N="546">Here of myn hous perpetuelly a chirche</L>
</LG>
<LG N="79" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(79)</HEAD>
<L N="547">SEynt Vrban wi&thorn; his dekenes priuely</L>
<L>The body fette and buried it by ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>Amonge his o&thorn;er seintes honestly</L>
<L N="550">Hure hous &thorn;e churche of seint Cicile hi&yogh;t</L>
<L>Seint Vrban halawed it as he wel my&yogh;t</L>
<L>In &thorn;e which into &thorn;is daye in noble wise</L>
<L N="553">Men done to crist and to his seinte servise.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>&para; &thorn;us ende&thorn; &thorn;e tale of &thorn;e seconnde nonne</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000452.tif" N="422">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="547">
<HEAD>&para; The prologe.<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 198</NOTE></HEAD>
<HEAD>And here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e chanouns &yogh;eman</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan ended was &thorn;e lif of seinte Cecile</L>
<L>Er we fully had ryden five myle</L>
<L>An boghton vnder &thorn;e ble vs gan a take</L>
<L N="557">A man &thorn;at clo&thorn;ed was in clo&thorn;es blake</L>
<L>And vnder &thorn;at he had a white surplis.</L>
<L>His hakeney &thorn;at was so pomel gris<MILESTONE N="198b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So swete &thorn;at it wondere was to see</L>
<L N="561">It semed he had prikked myles &thorn;re</L>
<L>&thorn;e hors eke &thorn;at his &yogh;eman rode vpon</L>
<L>So swette &thorn;at vnne&thorn;es my&yogh;t he gon</L>
<L>Aboute &thorn;e peitrell stood &thorn;e foom ful hie</L>
<L N="565">He was of fome al flekked as a pie</L>
<L>A male twifolde on his cropour laye</L>
<L>It semed &thorn;at he caried litel araye</L>
<L>Al li&yogh;t for somer roode &thorn;is wor&thorn;i man /</L>
<L N="569">And in myn herte wondre I bygan</L>
<L>What &thorn;at he was til I vnderstode</L>
<L>How &thorn;at his cloke was sewed to his hode</L>
<L>ffor which whan I longe had avised me</L>
<L N="573">I demed hym some chanon forto be</L>
<L>His hatte honge at his bak doune by a laas</L>
<L>ffor he had ryden more &thorn;an trotte or paas</L>
<L>He had aye prikked like as he were wood</L>
<L N="577">A clote leef he had vnder his hode</L>
<L>ffor swote and forto kepe his hede from hete</L>
<L>But it was ioye forto seen hym swete</L>
<L>His forhede dropped as a Stillatorie</L>
<L N="581">Were ful of planteyne and of Pyritorie
<PB REF="00000453.tif" N="423"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="548"></L>
<L N="582">And whan &thorn;at he came he gan to crie</L>
<L>God saue quod he &thorn;is Ioly companye</L>
<L>ffast haue I prikked quod he for &yogh;oure sake</L>
<L N="585">Because &thorn;at I wolde &yogh;ou ouertake</L>
<L>To ryden in &thorn;is mery company</L>
<L>His &yogh;eman eke was ful of curtesie</L>
<L>And sirres now in &thorn;e morowe tide</L>
<L N="589">Out of &yogh;oure ostelrie I segh &yogh;o<SUP>u</SUP> ride</L>
<L>And warned here my lorde and my souereyn</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at to ride wi&thorn; &yogh;ou is ful fayn</L>
<L>ffor his disporte he loue&thorn; daliaunce</L>
<L N="593">ffrende for &thorn;i warnyng god &yogh;eue &thorn;e good chaunce</L>
<L>Seide oure hoste certes it wolde seme</L>
<L>Thi lorde were wise and so I may wel deme<MILESTONE N="199a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>He is ful iocounde also dar I lay</L>
<L N="597">Can he ou&yogh;t telle a mery tale or twaye</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; which he glade may &thorn;is company</L>
<L>Who sir my lord; &yogh;e &yogh;e wi&thorn;-outen lie</L>
<L>He can of merth and eke of Iolite</L>
<L N="601">And &thorn;at ynou&yogh;e also sir tresteth me</L>
<L>And &yogh;e hym knewe as wel as do I</L>
<L>&yogh;e wolde wonder howe wel and thriftelie</L>
<L>He cou&thorn;e worche and &thorn;at in sondry wise</L>
<L N="605">He ha&thorn; take on hym mony sondry aprise</L>
<L>Which were ful hard for eny &thorn;at is here</L>
<L>To bringe aboute but &thorn;ei of hym it lere</L>
<L>As homely as he ritte amonge &yogh;ou</L>
<L N="609">If &yogh;e hym knewe it wolde be &yogh;our prowe</L>
<L>&YOGH;e nolde nat forgon his aqueyntaunce</L>
<L>ffor mochel good I dar laie in balaunce</L>
<L>All &thorn;at I haue in myn possession</L>
<L N="613">He is a man of hi&yogh;e discrecion</L>
<L>I warne &yogh;owe wel he is a passing man</L>
<L>Wel ko&thorn;e our hoost I prey &thorn;e telle me &thorn;an</L>
<L>Is he Clerk or noon telle what he is</L>
<L N="617">Nay he is gretter &thorn;an a clerk ywis
<PB REF="00000454.tif" N="424"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="549"></L>
<L N="618">Seide &thorn;e &yogh;eman and in woordes fewe</L>
<L>Oost of his craft somwhat I wil &yogh;ou shewe</L>
<L>I saie my lorde can such a sotilte</L>
<L N="621">But all his craft &yogh;e may not wit at me</L>
<L>And Somwhat helpe I &yogh;it to his worchinge</L>
<L>&thorn;at al &thorn;is grounde which &thorn;at we ben on ridynge</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at we come to caunterberye toun</L>
<L N="625">He coude al clere turne vp so doun</L>
<L>And paue it al of siluer and of golde</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is &yogh;eman had &thorn;us ytolde</L>
<L>Vnto oure hooste he seide Benedicite</L>
<L N="629">This &thorn;ing is wonder mervelous to me</L>
<L>Si&thorn;ens &thorn;at &thorn;i lord is of so hi&yogh;e prudence</L>
<L>Bycause of which men shulde hym reuerence<MILESTONE N="199b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at of his worship rekke&thorn; he so lite</L>
<L N="633">His ouersclope nys nat wor&thorn; a myte</L>
<L>As in effecte to him as mot I goo/</L>
<L>It is al baudy and to-tore also</L>
<L>Whi is &thorn;i lord so scluttish I &thorn;e prey</L>
<L N="637">And is of power better clo&thorn;es to beye</L>
<L>If &thorn;at his dede accorde wi&thorn; &thorn;i speche</L>
<L>Telle me &thorn;at I &thorn;e biseche</L>
<L>Whi quod &thorn;is &yogh;eman wherto aske &yogh;e me</L>
<L N="641">God helpe me so for he shal neuere the</L>
<L>But I wil nat avowe &thorn;at I say</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore kepe it secre I &yogh;ou pray</L>
<L>He is to wise in fei&thorn; as I bileue</L>
<L N="645">That &thorn;at is ouerdone it nyl not preue</L>
<L>And ri&yogh;t as clerkes seyn it is a vice</L>
<L>wherfore in &thorn;at I holde hym lewde and nyce</L>
<L>ffor whan a man ha&thorn; ouer grete a witte</L>
<L N="649">fful often it happe&thorn; to misusen it</L>
<L>So do&thorn; my lord and &thorn;at me greue&thorn; sore</L>
<L>God it amende I can seye now no more</L>
<L>Therof no fors good &yogh;eman quod our hoost</L>
<L N="653">Sy&thorn; of &thorn;e konyng of &thorn;i lord &thorn;ou wost
<PB REF="00000455.tif" N="425"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="550"></L>
<L N="654">Telle howe he do&thorn; I prey &thorn;e hertely</L>
<L>Si&thorn;&thorn;es &thorn;at he is so crafty and so scly</L>
<L>Where dwellen &yogh;e if it to telle be</L>
<L N="657">In &thorn;e Subarbes of a toune quod he</L>
<L>Lurkynge in hernes and in lanes blynde</L>
<L>Where &thorn;ise Robbers and &thorn;eues be kynde</L>
<L>Holden her p<SUP>i</SUP>rve feerful residence</L>
<L N="661">As &thorn;ei &thorn;at dar not shewen her presence</L>
<L>So fare we if I shal say &thorn;e so&thorn;e</L>
<L>&yogh;it quod [our] oste lat me talke to the</L>
<L>Why art &thorn;ou discolowred on &thorn;i face</L>
<L N="665">Peter quod he god &yogh;eue it harde grace</L>
<L>I am so vsed &thorn;e fire to blowe</L>
<L>That it ha&thorn; chaunged my colour as I trowe<MILESTONE N="200a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I ne am not wonte in no myrour to prie</L>
<L N="669">But swynke sore and lerne to multiplie</L>
<L>We Blundren euere and powren in &thorn;e fire</L>
<L>And for alle &thorn;at we faillen of our desire</L>
<L>ffor euere we lacken our conclusion</L>
<L N="673">To moche folk we bene but illusion</L>
<L>And borowe golde be it a pound or twoo</L>
<L>Or ten or twelue or mony sommes moo</L>
<L>And make hem wenen at the leest wey</L>
<L N="677">&thorn;at of a pounde we cowde make twey</L>
<L>&YOGH;it is it fals and ay we han good hope</L>
<L>It forto doon and aftere it we grope</L>
<L>But &thorn;at science is so fer vs biforne</L>
<L N="681">We mowe not alle &thorn;ou&yogh;e we had it sworne</L>
<L>It ouertake it slitt away so fast</L>
<L>It wil vs make beggers at &thorn;e last</L>
<L>&thorn;e whiles &thorn;is &yogh;eman was &thorn;us in his talkyng</L>
<L N="685">This Chanon drowe hym nere and herd al &thorn;inge</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at &thorn;is &yogh;em[an] spake for suspecion</L>
<L>&para; Of mennys speche euere had &thorn;is chanon</L>
<L>ffor Caton sei&thorn; he &thorn;at gilty is</L>
<L N="689">Deme&thorn; al &thorn;inge be spoke of hym ywis
<PB REF="00000456.tif" N="426"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="551"></L>
<L N="690">By cause of &thorn;at he gan so ny&yogh;e to drawe</L>
<L>His &yogh;eman &thorn;at herd alle his sawe</L>
<L>And &thorn;us he seide vnto his &yogh;eman &thorn;oo</L>
<L N="693">Holde now &thorn;i pees and speke no wordes moo</L>
<L>ffor if &thorn;owe doo &thorn;u shalt it dere aby</L>
<L>&thorn;ow sclaunderest me here in &thorn;is company</L>
<L>And eke diskeuerest &thorn;at &thorn;ou shuldest hide</L>
<L N="697">&yogh;e quod oure hoost telle on what so betide</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;is &thorn;retynge rech &thorn;e not a myte</L>
<L>In fei&thorn; quod he no moore I doo but lite</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is chanon segh it wold nat be</L>
<L N="701">But &thorn;at his &yogh;eman wolde telle his priuete</L>
<L>He fledde a-way for verrey sorowe and shame</L>
<L>A quod the &yogh;eman here shal arise a game<MILESTONE N="200b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>All &thorn;at I can anon wil I telle</L>
<L N="705">Si&thorn;ens he is goon &thorn;e foule fende hym quelle</L>
<L>ffor neuere here after wil I wi&thorn; hym mete</L>
<L>ffor peny ne for pounde I &yogh;ou bihete</L>
<L>He &thorn;at me brou&yogh;t furst vnto &thorn;at game</L>
<L N="709">Er &thorn;at he dye sorowe haue he and shame</L>
<L>ffor it it is ernest to me by my fei&thorn;e</L>
<L>&thorn;at fele I wele what so eny man sei&thorn;e</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;it for all my smerte and al my greff</L>
<L N="713">ffor al my sorowe. labour and meschieff</L>
<L>I kou&thorn;e neuere leue it in no wise</L>
<L>Now wold god my wittes my&yogh;t suffise</L>
<L>To tellen al &thorn;at longen to &thorn;at art</L>
<L N="717">But na&thorn;eles &yogh;it wil I telle &yogh;owe part</L>
<L>Si&thorn;ens &thorn;at my lorde is goon I wil not spare</L>
<L>Such &thorn;inge as I knowe I wil declare</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; Thus ende&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e chanons &yogh;eman</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000457.tif" N="427">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="552">
<HEAD>&amp; here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> tale<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 200, <I>back</I></NOTE></HEAD>
<HEAD>[THE PREAMBLE.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>With &thorn;is chanon [I] dwelt haue seuene &yogh;ere<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; The tale ./</NOTE></L>
<L>And of his science am I neuer &thorn;e nere</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at I had I haue ylost &thorn;erby</L>
<L>And god woo so han many moo &thorn;an I</L>
<L>Ther I was wonte to be ri&yogh;t fressh and gay</L>
<L N="725">Of clo&thorn;inge and of good aray</L>
<L>Now may I were an hose vpon myne heued</L>
<L>And where my coloure was bo&thorn; fresh and rede</L>
<L>Now is it wan and of a lewde hwe</L>
<L N="729">Who so it vse&thorn; sore shal he rwe</L>
<L>And of my swynk &yogh;it blered is myn ye</L>
<L>Loo suche auauntage it is to multiplie</L>
<L>That sclydinge science ha&thorn; me made so bale</L>
<L N="733">That I haue no good wher so euer y fare</L>
<L>And &yogh;it am I endetted so &thorn;erby</L>
<L>Of golde &thorn;at I haue borowed trewly</L>
<L>That whil I lyve I shal it quite neuere</L>
<L N="737">Lat euery man be ware by me for euere</L>
<L>What maner man &thorn;at caste&thorn; hym &thorn;erto<MILESTONE N="201a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>If he contynue I holde his thrift ydo</L>
<L>ffor so helpe me god &thorn;erby shal he nat wynne</L>
<L N="741">But empty his purs and make his wyttes &thorn;inne</L>
<L>And whan he thorgh his madnesse and folye</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; lost his owne good &thorn;orgh Iopardye</L>
<L>&thorn;an he excite&thorn; o&thorn;er men &thorn;erto</L>
<L N="745">To lese her good as hym self ha&thorn; doo /</L>
<L>ffor to shrewes Ioies it is an ese</L>
<L>To haue her felawes in peyn and dissese
<PB REF="00000458.tif" N="428"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="553"></L>
<L>Thus was I ones lerned of a clerk</L>
<L N="749">Of &thorn;at no charge I wil speke of our werk</L>
<L>Whan we bene &thorn;ere as we shul exercise</L>
<L>Oure eluessh craft we seme wonder wise</L>
<L>Our teermes bene so clergial and so queynte</L>
<L N="753">I blowe &thorn;e fyre til &thorn;at myn hert feynte</L>
<L>What shuld I telle eche proporcion</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ingges which &thorn;at we worchen vpon</L>
<L>As on .v. or .vj. vnces may wel be</L>
<L N="757">Of Siluere or of som o&thorn;er quantite</L>
<L>And bisy me to telle &yogh;ou &thorn;e names</L>
<L>Of Orpyment. brent bonys yren. squames</L>
<L>Thatt into powdere grounden bene ful small</L>
<L N="761">And in an erthen pot howe &thorn;at pitte is alle</L>
<L>And salt ypitte In. and also paupere</L>
<L>Byfore &thorn;ise powdres &thorn;at I speke of here</L>
<L>And wel ykeuered wi&thorn; a laumpe of glas</L>
<L N="765">And of moche o&thorn;er &thorn;inge what &thorn;er was</L>
<L>And of the potte and glas englutynge</L>
<L>That of &thorn;e eyre my&yogh;t passe no &thorn;inge</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e Esy fire and smert also</L>
<L N="769">Which &thorn;at was made and of the care and woo</L>
<L>That we had in our maters sublymynge</L>
<L>And in amalgamynge and calcenynge</L>
<L>Of quik siluere ycleped Mercurie crude</L>
<L N="773">ffor all oure scleightes we can not conclude</L>
<L>Our orpyment and sublymed Mercurye<MILESTONE N="201b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Our grounde litarge eke on &thorn;e porphirie</L>
<L>Of eche of &thorn;ise of vnces a certeyn</L>
<L N="777">Nat helpe&thorn; vs oure labour is in veyn</L>
<L>Ne eke oure spirites assencioun</L>
<L>Ne eke our maters &thorn;at lyen al fixe a-doun</L>
<L>Mowen in oure worchinge no &thorn;ing vs availe</L>
<L N="781">ffor lost is al our laboure and travaile</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e cost on twenty deuel weye</L>
<L>Is lost also whiche we vpon it laye
<PB REF="00000459.tif" N="429"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="554"></L>
<L>Ther is also mony a nother &thorn;ing</L>
<L N="785">That is to our craft appertenynge</L>
<L>&thorn;ou&yogh;e I by ordere hem here ne reherce kan</L>
<L>Because &thorn;at I am a lewde man</L>
<L>&yogh;it wil I telle hem as &thorn;ei come to mynde</L>
<L N="789">&thorn;ou&yogh;e I ne can sette hem in her kynde</L>
<L>As boole armonyak. verdegrees. boras</L>
<L>And sondry vessels made of er&thorn;e and glas</L>
<L>Our vrynales and our dyscensories</L>
<L N="793">Violles Creseletys. and sublimatories</L>
<L>Concurbites and alembykes eke</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er suche dere ynowe a leke</L>
<L>Nat nede&thorn; it to rehersen hem alle</L>
<L N="797">Waters rubyfyinge and bolles galle.</L>
<L>Arsenyke sal armonyak and brymston</L>
<L>And herbes coude I telle eke mony on</L>
<L>As Egrymoyn Valerian and lunarie</L>
<L N="801">And o&thorn;er such &yogh;if &thorn;at me list tarie</L>
<L>Our lampes brennyng bo&thorn; ny&yogh;t and day</L>
<L>To bringe about our craft &yogh;if &thorn;at we may</L>
<L>Our furnayes eke of Calcynacion</L>
<L N="805">And of waters albificacion</L>
<L>Vnslekked lyme. Chalk and gleire of an ey</L>
<L>Powders divers. Ashes. dunge. pisse. and cley</L>
<L>Sered pockettes. sal peter. and vitriole</L>
<L N="809">And dyuers fires made of wode and Cole</L>
<L>Salt tartre. alcalie and salt preparate<MILESTONE N="202a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And combust maters and coagulate</L>
<L>Cley made wi&thorn; horses or mannys here and oyle</L>
<L N="813">Of Tartere. alem glas berme wort &amp; argoille</L>
<L>Rysalgere and o&thorn;ere mateers enbykinge</L>
<L>And eke of oure mateers encorporinge</L>
<L>And of [our] Siluer citrinacion</L>
<L N="817">Our sementynge and fermentacion</L>
<L>Our ingotes testes and mony moo /</L>
<L>I wil &yogh;ou telle as was me tau&yogh;t also
<PB REF="00000460.tif" N="430"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="555"></L>
<L>&thorn;e four spirites and &thorn;e bodies seuene</L>
<L N="821">By ordre oft as I herd my lord hem neuene</L>
<L>The first spirit quyk-siluere cleped is</L>
<L>&thorn;e Secounde orpyment &thorn;e <I>thrid</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS iij]</NOTE> ywis</L>
<L>Sal Armonyak and &thorn;e fer&thorn; bremstone</L>
<L N="825">&thorn;e bodies seuene eke lo hem here anon</L>
<L>Sol gold is and luna siluer we threpe</L>
<L>Mars. yren Mercurie quyksiluer we clepe</L>
<L>Saturnus lede. and Iubiter is tynne</L>
<L N="829">And Venus Coper be my fadere kynne</L>
<L>This cursed craft who so wil exercise</L>
<L>He shal no good han &thorn;at may hym suffise</L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;e good he spende&thorn; &thorn;er-aboute</L>
<L N="833">He lese shal &thorn;erof haue I no doute</L>
<L>Who so &thorn;at list to outen his foly</L>
<L>Lat hym come for&thorn; and lerne forto multiplie</L>
<L>And euery man &thorn;at ha&thorn; ou&yogh;t in his cofre</L>
<L N="837">Lat [him] apere and wexe a philosofre</L>
<L>Ascaunce &thorn;at craft is so li&yogh;t to lere</L>
<L>Nay nay god wote al be he monke or frere</L>
<L>Preest chanon or eny o&thorn;er wi&yogh;t</L>
<L N="841">&thorn;ou&yogh;e he sitte at his boke bo&thorn; day and ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>In lernyng of &thorn;is elvissh nyce lore</L>
<L>Al is in veyn and parde moche more</L>
<L>Is to lere a lewde man &thorn;is sotille</L>
<L N="845">ffy speke nat &thorn;erof for it wil nat be</L>
<L>Al coude he lettrure or coude he none<MILESTONE N="202b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As in effecte he shal fynde it all one</L>
<L>ffor bo&thorn; twoo be my saluacion</L>
<L N="849">Concluden in multiplicacion</L>
<L>Iliche wel whan &thorn;ei han al ydoo</L>
<L>This is to seyn &thorn;ei failen bo&thorn; two</L>
<L>But &yogh;it for &thorn;at I to moche rehersaille</L>
<L N="853">Of waters corosif and of lymaille</L>
<L>And of bodyes mollificacion</L>
<L>And also of her induracion
<PB REF="00000461.tif" N="431"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="556"></L>
<L>Oilles abluci&omacr;n &amp; metal fusible</L>
<L N="857">To tellen alle wold passen eny bible</L>
<L>&thorn;at owhere is wher as for &thorn;e best</L>
<L>Of all &thorn;ise names now wil I me rest.</L>
<L>ffor as I trawe I haue &yogh;ou tolde ynowe</L>
<L N="861">To reisen a feende loke he neuere so rowe</L>
<L>A nay lat be &thorn;i philosophres stone</L>
<L>Elixir cleped we sechen fast echone</L>
<L>ffor had we hym &thorn;an were we siker ynou&yogh;e</L>
<L N="865">But vnto god of heuene I make avowe</L>
<L>ffor al our craft whan we han al ydoo</L>
<L>And al oure sclei&yogh;te he wil not come vs too/</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; vs made spende moche good</L>
<L N="869">ffor sorowe of which almost we wexen wode</L>
<L>But &thorn;at good hope crepe&thorn; in our hert</L>
<L>Supposinge euere &thorn;ou&yogh;e we sore smert</L>
<L>To be releued by hym afterward</L>
<L N="873">Supposinge &thorn;at hope is sharpe and hard</L>
<L>I warne &yogh;ou wele it is to seken euere</L>
<L>&thorn;at future temps ha&thorn; made men disseuere</L>
<L>In trest &thorn;erof from alle &thorn;at euere &thorn;ei hadde</L>
<L N="877">&YOGH;it of &thorn;at art &thorn;ei koude not wexen sadde</L>
<L>ffor vnto hem it is a bitterswete</L>
<L>So seme&thorn; it for ne had &thorn;ei but a shete</L>
<L>Which &thorn;ei my&yogh;t wrap hem in a ny&yogh;t</L>
<L N="881">And a bak to walken In by day li&yogh;t</L>
<L>They wold hem Sellen and spenden on &thorn;is craft<MILESTONE N="203a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>They can not stynt til no &thorn;inge be laft</L>
<L>And euermore wher &thorn;at euere &thorn;ei gone</L>
<L N="885">Men may hem knowe by &thorn;e smelle of bremstone</L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;e worlde &thorn;ei stynken as a gote</L>
<L>Her sauour is so rammyssh and so hote</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou&yogh; a man fro hem a myle be</L>
<L N="889">&thorn;e Sauour wil enfecte hym treste&thorn; me</L>
<L>Lo Thus by smellyng and be threde bare aray</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at men lust &thorn;ise folk &thorn;ei know may
<PB REF="00000462.tif" N="432"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="557"></L>
<L>And if a man wil aske hym prively</L>
<L N="893">Whi &thorn;ei bene clo&thorn;ed so vnthriftily</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t anone &thorn;ei wil rownen in his eere</L>
<L>And seie if &thorn;ey aspied were</L>
<L>Men wolde hem slee by cause of her science</L>
<L N="897">Loo &thorn;us &thorn;ise folk bitraien Innocence</L>
<L>Passe ouer &thorn;is I go my tale vnto</L>
<L>Er &thorn;an &thorn;e potte be on &thorn;e fuyre ydoo</L>
<L>Of metalles wi&thorn; a certeyn quantite</L>
<L N="901">My lorde hem tempre&thorn; and no man but he</L>
<L>Now he is goon I dar saie boldely</L>
<L>ffor as men seyne he can do craftely</L>
<L>Algate I wote wel he ha&thorn; such a name</L>
<L N="905">And &yogh;it ful ofte he renne&thorn; in &thorn;e blame</L>
<L>And wete &yogh;e how ful ofte it happeth soo /</L>
<L>The potte to-breke&thorn; and fare-wel al is goo</L>
<L>Thise metalles bene of so grete violence</L>
<L N="909">Our walles may not maken hem resistence</L>
<L>But &yogh;if &thorn;ei [weren] wrou&yogh;t of lyme and stone</L>
<L>&thorn;ei percen so &thorn;at &thorn;or&yogh;e &thorn;e wall &thorn;ei gone</L>
<L>And somme of hym synken into &thorn;e grounde</L>
<L N="913">Thus haue we lost by tymes mony a pound</L>
<L>And somme are scatered al the flore aboute</L>
<L>Somme lepen into &thorn;e Roof with-out doute</L>
<L>Thou&yogh;e &thorn;at &thorn;e feende nat in our si&yogh;t hym shewe</L>
<L N="917">&para; I trowe &thorn;at he wi&thorn; vs be &thorn;at schrewe</L>
<L>In helle wher &thorn;at he is lord and sire<MILESTONE N="203b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ne is &thorn;er no more woo angere ne Ire</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at oure pot is broke as I haue saide</L>
<L N="921">Euery man chitte and halt hym euel paide</L>
<L>Som saide it was longe on &thorn;e fire makinge</L>
<L>Som saide nay it was on &thorn;e blowynge</L>
<L>Than was I aferde for &thorn;at was myn office</L>
<L N="925">Strawe quod &thorn;e &thorn;red &yogh;e bene lewde and nyce</L>
<L>It was nat tempred as it au&yogh;t be</L>
<L>Nay quod &thorn;e fer&thorn;e stynt and harken me
<PB REF="00000463.tif" N="433"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="558"></L>
<L>Be cause oure fire was not made of beche</L>
<L N="929">&thorn;at is &thorn;e cause noon o&thorn;ere so theche.</L>
<L>I can not telle wheron it is alonge</L>
<L>But wel I woot gret strif is vs amonge</L>
<L>What quod my lorde &thorn;er nys no more to done</L>
<L N="933">Of &thorn;ise periles I wil be ware eft sone</L>
<L>I am ri&yogh;t syker &thorn;at &thorn;e pot was craised</L>
<L>Be as be may be &yogh;e no &thorn;inge amased</L>
<L>As vsage is lat swepe &thorn;e flore as swithe</L>
<L N="937">Pluk vp &yogh;oure hert and be &yogh;e glad and blithe</L>
<L>&thorn;e Mullok on an hepe yswoped was</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e floore cast a canvas.</L>
<L>And al this Mullok in a sif yth[r]owe</L>
<L N="941">And ysifted and yplukked many a throwe</L>
<L>Parde quod oon somwhat of oure metall</L>
<L>&YOGH;it is &thorn;er here &thorn;ou&yogh;e we haue nat all</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;is &thorn;inge myshapped ha&thorn; as nowe</L>
<L N="945">Ano&thorn;er tyme It may be wel ynowe</L>
<L>Vs most putt our good in auenture</L>
<L>A Marchaunte parde may not ay endure</L>
<L>Treste&thorn; me wel in his prosperite</L>
<L N="949">Somtyme his good is drowned in &thorn;e see</L>
<L>And somtyme commeth it sauf vnto &thorn;e londe</L>
<L>Pees quod my lord &thorn;e next tyme I wil fonde</L>
<L>To brynge our craft al in ano&thorn;er plite</L>
<L N="953">And but I doo sirs lat me haue &thorn;e wite</L>
<L>Ther was defaute in somwhat wel I wote<MILESTONE N="204a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And o&thorn;er seide &thorn;e fire was ouere hote</L>
<L>But be it hote or cold I dar saie &thorn;is</L>
<L N="957">&thorn;at we concluden euer more amys</L>
<L>We faillen of that which &thorn;at we wold haue</L>
<L>And in oure madnesse euermore we raue</L>
<L>And whan we bene to-gidere euerechon</L>
<L N="961">Euery man seme&thorn; as wise as Salomon</L>
<L>But al &thorn;inge which &thorn;at seine&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>or</I> seme&thorn;]</NOTE> as &thorn;e golde</L>
<L>Is nat golde as I haue herd it tolde
<PB REF="00000464.tif" N="434"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="559"></L>
<L>Ne euery appel &thorn;at is faire at ye</L>
<L N="965">Ne is not god what so men clappe or crie</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t so loo fare&thorn; it amonges vs /</L>
<L>He<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>or</I> Ho]</NOTE> &thorn;at seme&thorn; &thorn;e wisest by Ihesus</L>
<L>Is moost foole whan it comme&thorn; to &thorn;e preef</L>
<L N="969">And he &thorn;at seme&thorn; trewest is a &thorn;eef</L>
<L>That shul &yogh;e knowe er &thorn;at I from &yogh;o<SUP>u</SUP> wende</L>
<L>Be &thorn;at I of my tale haue made an ende<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000465.tif" N="435">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="560">
<HEAD>[THE TALE.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ther is a chanon of Religioun<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; 2<SUP>a</SUP> pars.;.</NOTE></L>
<L N="973">Amonges vs wolde enfecte al a toun</L>
<L>Thou&yogh;e it as grete were as was Nyniue</L>
<L>Rome. Alisaundre . Troie &amp; o&thorn;er &thorn;re</L>
<L>his scleightes and his infinite falsnesse</L>
<L N="977">Ther cou&thorn;e no man writen as I gesse</L>
<L>Thou&yogh;e &thorn;at he my&yogh;t lyuen a thousand &yogh;ere</L>
<L>In al &thorn;is world of falsenesse nys his pere</L>
<L>ffor in his teermes he wil hym so wynde</L>
<L N="981">And speke his wordes in so scle&yogh;e a kynde</L>
<L>Whan he comune shal wi&thorn; eny wi&yogh;t</L>
<L>That he wil make hym dote anon ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>But it &thorn;e feende be as hym seluen is</L>
<L N="985">fful mony a man ha&thorn; he bygyled er &thorn;is</L>
<L>And wil if &thorn;at he may lif a while</L>
<L>And &yogh;it men riden and goon ful mony a myle</L>
<L>Hym forto seke and haue of a-queyntaunce</L>
<L N="989">Nat knowing of his fals gouernaunce</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &yogh;e lust to &yogh;eue me audience<MILESTONE N="204b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I wil it tellen in wi&thorn; &yogh;oure presence</L>
<L>But worshipful Chanon Religious</L>
<L N="993">Ne deme&thorn; not I sclaundere &yogh;our hous</L>
<L>Al-&thorn;ou&yogh;e my tale of a chanon be</L>
<L>Of euery ordere som shrewe is parde</L>
<L>And god forbede &thorn;at all a companye</L>
<L N="997">Shulde rewe a syngule mannys foly</L>
<L>To sclaundere &yogh;ou is nat myn entent</L>
<L>But to correcten &thorn;at mys I-ment
<PB REF="00000466.tif" N="436"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="561"></L>
<L>This tale was not only told for &yogh;ou</L>
<L N="1001">But eke for o&thorn;er moo &yogh;e wote wel howe</L>
<L>That amonges cristes apostels twelue</L>
<L>&thorn;er ne was no traitour but Iudas selue</L>
<L>Than whi shulde &thorn;e remenaunte all haue blame</L>
<L N="1005">&thorn;at giltlees were be &yogh;ou saye I &thorn;e same</L>
<L>Sauf only &thorn;is if &yogh;e wil harken me</L>
<L>If eny Iudas in &yogh;oure couent be</L>
<L>Remeueth hym be tyme I &yogh;ou rede</L>
<L N="1009">If shame or losse may causen eny drede</L>
<L>And be&thorn; no &thorn;inge displesed I &yogh;ou pray</L>
<L>But in this caas herkne&thorn; what I say</L>
<L>In london was a preest an annuelere</L>
<L N="1013">That &thorn;erInne dwelled had mony a &yogh;ere</L>
<L>Which was so plesaunt and so seruisable</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e wiff where he was att table</L>
<L>That she wolde suffre hym no &thorn;ing forto paye</L>
<L N="1017">ffor borde ne . clo&thorn;inge went he neuere so gay</L>
<L>And spending siluere had he ri&yogh;t ynowe</L>
<L>Therof no force I wil procede as nowe</L>
<L>And telle for&thorn; my tale of &thorn;e chanon</L>
<L N="1021">&thorn;at brou&yogh;t &thorn;is preest to confusion</L>
<L>This fals chanon came vpon a day</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e preestes chambere &thorn;er he lay</L>
<L>Bysechinge hym to lene hym a certeyn</L>
<L N="1025">Of golde and he wolde quyte hym ageyn</L>
<L>Lene&thorn; me a marke quod he but daies &thorn;re<MILESTONE N="205a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And at my day I wil it quite &thorn;e</L>
<L>And it so be &thorn;ow fynde me fals</L>
<L N="1029">An o&thorn;er day honge me by &thorn;e hals</L>
<L>This prest him toke a marke and &thorn;at as swithe</L>
<L>And &thorn;is chanon hym &thorn;onked ofte sithe</L>
<L>And toke his leue and went for&thorn; his way</L>
<L N="1033">And at &thorn;e &thorn;red day brou&yogh;t his monay</L>
<L>And to &thorn;is preest he toke his gold ageyn</L>
<L>Therof &thorn;is preest was glad and fayn
<PB REF="00000467.tif" N="437"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="562"></L>
<L>Certes quod he no &thorn;inge anoye&thorn; me</L>
<L N="1037">To lene a man a noble or twoo or &thorn;ree</L>
<L>Or what &thorn;inge were in my possession</L>
<L>Whan he so trewe is of condicion</L>
<L>That in no wise he breke wil his day</L>
<L N="1041">To such a man I can neuere say nay</L>
<L>What quod &thorn;is chanon shuld I be vntrewe</L>
<L>&para; Nay &thorn;at were &thorn;inge fallen al of nwe</L>
<L>Treu&thorn;e is a &thorn;ing &thorn;at I wil euer kepe</L>
<L N="1045">Vnto &thorn;e day in which &thorn;at I shal crepe</L>
<L>Into my graue and ellis god forbede</L>
<L>Bileue&thorn; &thorn;is as siker as is &yogh;oure crede</L>
<L>God thonke I and in good tyme be it seide</L>
<L N="1049">That &thorn;er was neuere man &yogh;it euel apaide</L>
<L>ffor gold ne siluere &thorn;at he to me lent</L>
<L>Ne neuere falshede to myne hert I ment</L>
<L>And sire quod he nowe in my privete</L>
<L N="1053">Si&thorn;ens &yogh;e so goodly haue bene to me</L>
<L>And ky&thorn;ed to me so grete gentilnesse</L>
<L>Somwhat to quiten wi&thorn; &yogh;our kyndenesse</L>
<L>I wil &yogh;ou shewe and &yogh;if &yogh;ou lust to lere</L>
<L N="1057">I shal it shewe to &yogh;ou anon ri&yogh;t here</L>
<L>How I can worchen in philosophie</L>
<L>Take&thorn; good hede &yogh;e shullen see wel at ye</L>
<L>That I wil done a maistrie er I goo</L>
<L N="1061">&YOGH;e quod &thorn;e preest &yogh;e sir and wil &yogh;e so</L>
<L>Marie &thorn;erof I prei &yogh;ou hertely<MILESTONE N="205b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>At &yogh;oure comaundement sir trewly</L>
<L>Quod &thorn;e chanon and ellis god forbede</L>
<L N="1065">Loo howe &thorn;is &thorn;eef kou&thorn;e his seruise bede</L>
<L>fful so&thorn; it is &thorn;at such propferd seruise</L>
<L>Stynke&thorn; as witnessen &thorn;ise olde wise</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ful sone I wil it verefie</L>
<L N="1069">In &thorn;is chan&omacr;n is rote of al trecherye</L>
<L>That euere more delite ha&thorn; and gladnesse</L>
<L>Such feendly &thorn;ou&yogh;tes in his hert empresse
<PB REF="00000468.tif" N="438"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="563"></L>
<L>How cristes puple he may to meschief bringe /</L>
<L N="1073">God kepe vs from his fals dissimulynge</L>
<L>What wist &thorn;is preest wi&thorn; whom &thorn;at he delte</L>
<L>Ne of his harme commyng no &thorn;ing he felte</L>
<L>O sely preest o. sely Innocent</L>
<L N="1077">Wi&thorn; couetise anon &thorn;ou shalt be blent</L>
<L>O gracelees ful blynde is &thorn;i conseite</L>
<L>No &thorn;ing art &thorn;ow war of &thorn;e deceite</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at &thorn;is fox shapen ha&thorn; to &thorn;e</L>
<L N="1081">His wily wrenches &thorn;ou maist not flee</L>
<L>Wherfore to goo to &thorn;e conclusion</L>
<L>&thorn;at referre&thorn; to &thorn;e confusion</L>
<L>Vnhappy man anon I wil me hye</L>
<L N="1085">To tellen &thorn;ine vnwitte and &thorn;i foly</L>
<L>And eke &thorn;e falsenesse of &thorn;at o&thorn;er wrecche</L>
