<L>Of &thorn;is Receite . fare wel it wold nat be</L>
<L N="1385">Loo &thorn;us byiaped and begiled was he</L>
<L>Thus make&thorn; he his Introducci&omacr;n</L>
<L>To bringe folk to her destructi&omacr;n</L>
<L>Considere&thorn; surs howe &thorn;at in eche astaat</L>
<L N="1389">Bytwix men and gold &thorn;er is debaat</L>
<L>So fer for&thorn; &thorn;at vnne&thorn;es &thorn;er is oon<MILESTONE N="210a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>This multiplyinge so blende&thorn; mony &omacr;n</L>
<L>That in good fai&thorn; I trowe &thorn;at it be</L>
<L N="1393">The cause grettest of &thorn;e grete scarcete</L>
<L>Thise philosophres speken so mystely</L>
<L>In &thorn;is craft &thorn;at men can not come &thorn;erby
<PB REF="00000477.tif" N="447"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="572"></L>
<L>ffor eny witte &thorn;at men han now adayes.</L>
<L N="1397">&THORN;ei may wel Chitere and iangle as don &thorn;ise Iaies</L>
<L>And in her teemes sette lust and peyne</L>
<L>But to her purpoos shul &thorn;ei neuere atteyne</L>
<L>A man may li&yogh;tly lerne &yogh;if he haue ou&yogh;te</L>
<L N="1401">To multiplie and bringe his good to nou&yogh;te</L>
<L>Loo suche a lucre is in &thorn;is lusty game.</L>
<L>A mannes mer&thorn;e wil it turne al to grame</L>
<L>And empty also grete and heuy purses.</L>
<L N="1405">And make folk to purchasen curses</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at han &thorn;erto her good ylent</L>
<L>O. fy for shame &thorn;ei &thorn;at han be brent</L>
<L>Allas can &thorn;ei nat flee &thorn;e fires hete</L>
<L N="1409">&YOGH;e &thorn;at it losen I rede &yogh;e it lete</L>
<L>lest &yogh;e lesen all. for bette &thorn;an neuere is late</L>
<L>Neuere to &thorn;rive were to longe a date</L>
<L>Thou&yogh;e &yogh;e prolle ay &yogh;e shul it neuer fynde</L>
<L N="1413">&YOGH;e bene as bolde as is bayard &thorn;e blynde</L>
<L>That blundre&thorn; for&thorn; and perile caste&thorn; non</L>
<L>He was bolde to renne a&yogh;einst a ston</L>
<L>As forto goo be sides in &thorn;e way</L>
<L N="1417">&para; Soo faren &yogh;e &thorn;at multiplien I say</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at oure eyen can nat seen ari&yogh;t</L>
<L>Loke&thorn; &thorn;at &yogh;oure mynde lak nat his si&yogh;t</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou&yogh;e &yogh;e loke neuere so brode and stare</L>
<L N="1421">&yogh;e shul nat wynne a myte in &thorn;at chaffare</L>
<L>But waasten all &thorn;at &yogh;e may rappe and renne</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;drawe &thorn;e fuyre lest it so fast brenne</L>
<L>Medleth no more wi&thorn; &thorn;at art I mene.</L>
<L N="1425">ffor &yogh;if &yogh;e doon &yogh;oure &thorn;rift is goon ful clene</L>
<L>And ri&yogh;t as swi&thorn;e I wil &yogh;ou telle here</L>
<L>What &thorn;at &thorn;e philosophres seyn in &thorn;is matere</L>
<L>Loo &thorn;us sei&thorn; alnold of &thorn;e newe toune<MILESTONE N="210b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1429">As his rosarie make&thorn; mencioun</L>
<L>He sei&thorn; ri&yogh;t &thorn;us wi&thorn;-oute eny lie</L>
<L>Ther may no man mercury mortefie
<PB REF="00000478.tif" N="448"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="573"></L>
<L>But &yogh;if it be wi&thorn; his bro&thorn;ers knowlecchinge</L>
<L N="1433">Howe &thorn;at he which &thorn;at ferst seide &thorn;is &thorn;inge</L>
<L>Of philosophres fader was hermes</L>
<L>He sei&thorn; how &thorn;at &thorn;e dragon doutelees /</L>
<L>Ne dye&thorn; nat but &yogh;if he be sclayn</L>
<L N="1437">Wi&thorn; his bro&thorn;er and &thorn;at is forto sayne</L>
<L>By &thorn;e dragon mercurye and noon o&thorn;er</L>
<L>He vnderstood &thorn;at bremstone were his bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>&thorn;at out of sol and luna were ydrawe</L>
<L N="1441">And &thorn;erfore saide he take hede to my sawe</L>
<L>Lat no man bisie him &thorn;is arte forto seche.</L>
<L>But he &thorn;at &thorn;e entenci&omacr;n and speche</L>
<L>Of philosophres vnderstonde can</L>
<L N="1445">And if he doo he is a lewde man</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;is science and &thorn;is conyng quod he</L>
<L>Is of &thorn;e secree of secrees parde</L>
<L>Also &thorn;er was a disciple of plato</L>
<L N="1449">&thorn;at on a tyme saide his maister too.</L>
<L>As his boke somere wil bere witnesse</L>
<L>And &thorn;is was his demaunde en so&thorn;fastnesse</L>
<L>Tel me &thorn;e name of a priue sto&omacr;n</L>
<L N="1453">And plato answered vnto hym ano&omacr;n</L>
<L>Take &thorn;e stoon &thorn;at Titanos men name</L>
<L>Which is &thorn;at quod he magnasia is &thorn;e same</L>
<L>His disciple seide &yogh;e sire and is it &thorn;us</L>
<L N="1457">&thorn;is is ignotum per ignocius</L>
<L>What is magnasia good sire I pray</L>
<L>It is a watere &thorn;at is made I saye</L>
<L>Of elementes foure quod Plato.</L>
<L N="1461">Telle me &thorn;e roche good sire quod he &thorn;oo.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at watere if it be &yogh;oure wille</L>
<L>Nay nay quod Plato certeyn &thorn;at I nyll</L>
<L>The philosophres were sworn echon</L>
<L N="1465">&thorn;at &thorn;ei shulde diskeuere it to no mon</L>
<L>Ne in no booke it write in no manere<MILESTONE N="211a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor vnto crist it is so leef and dere.
<PB REF="00000479.tif" N="449"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="574"></L>
<L>&thorn;at he wil nat &thorn;at it diskeuered be</L>
<L N="1469">But where it like&thorn; to his deite</L>
<L>Man to enspire and eke forto defende</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at him like&thorn; loo &thorn;is is &thorn;e ende</L>
<L>Than conclude I &thorn;us si&thorn;ens &thorn;at god of heuene</L>
<L N="1473">Ne wil not &thorn;at &thorn;e philisophres neuene</L>
<L>How &thorn;at a man shal come vnto &thorn;is stone</L>
<L>I rede as for the best lat it gone</L>
<L>ffor who so make&thorn; god his aduersarye</L>
<L N="1477">As forto worche eny &thorn;inge in contrarie</L>
<L>Vnto his wille certes neuere shal he thryve</L>
<L>&thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;at he multiplie teerme of his lyue</L>
<L>And &thorn;er a poynt for eended is my tale.</L>
<L N="1481">God seende euery trewe man boote of his bale /</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; Thus ende&thorn; &thorn;e chanons &yogh;eman his tale</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000480.tif" N="450">
<HEAD>And here bigynne&thorn; &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> prologe of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> doctour of Phisike<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 211</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;is &yogh;eman his tale ended hadde<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; The prolog.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;is fals Chanon which &thorn;at was so badde</L>
<L>Our hoost gan say trewly &amp; in certayn</L>
<L N="4">&thorn;is preest was begiled so&thorn;ly forto sayn</L>
<L>He wenynge forto be a philosophre</L>
<L>Til he lift ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t in his Cophre</L>
<L>And so&thorn;ly &thorn;is preest had a li&thorn;er Iape</L>
<L N="8">This cursed chanon put in his hode an ape</L>
<L>But al &thorn;is passe I ouer as nowe</L>
<L>Sir doctour of phisik I prey &yogh;ou</L>
<L>Telle vs a tale of some honest matere</L>
<L N="12">It shal be done &yogh;if &thorn;at &yogh;e wil it here</L>
<L>Saide &thorn;is doctour and his tale bygan anon</L>
<L>Now good men quod he harkene&thorn; euerechon</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; Thus ende&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e doctour of phisik</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="C" TYPE="group">

<PB REF="00000481.tif" N="451">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="303">
<HEAD>GROUP <B>C</B>. FRAGMENT IV.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&sect; 1. THE DOCTOR'S TALE.</HEAD>
<HEAD>PETWORTH MS.</HEAD>
<HEAD>And here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e tale.<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 211</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ther was as telle&thorn; vs tytus lyneus<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; The tale./</NOTE></L>
<L>A knyght &thorn;at cleped was virgineus</L>
<L>ffulfilled of honoures and wor&thorn;inesse</L>
<L N="4">And stronge of frendes and of richesse</L>
<L>A dou&yogh;ter he had be his wiff<MILESTONE N="211b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And neuere had hee moo in al his lif</L>
<L>ffaire was &thorn;is maide in excellent bewte</L>
<L N="8">Abouen euery wi&yogh;t &thorn;at man may see</L>
<L>ffor nature ha&thorn; wi&thorn; souereyn [diligence]</L>
<L>fformed hir in so grete excellence</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou&yogh;e she wold say loo I nature.</L>
<L N="12">Thus can I forme and peynte a creature</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at me list who can me countrefete</L>
<L>Pigmalyon noght &thorn;ou&yogh;e he alway forge and bete</L>
<L>Or graue or peynt for I dar wel sayn</L>
<L N="16">Apollus Zephirus shulde worche in veyn</L>
<L>Te graue. peynte. or forge or bete</L>
<L>If &thorn;ei presumed me to countrefete</L>
<L>ffor he &thorn;at is &thorn;e fourmer principal</L>
<L N="20">Ha&thorn;e made me his vikere general</L>
<L>To forme and peint eche er&thorn;ely creature</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t as me list for al &thorn;inge is my cure.</L>
<L>Vnder &thorn;e mone &thorn;at may wayne and waxe</L>
<L N="24">And for my werk &middot; no &thorn;inge wil I axe
<PB REF="00000482.tif" N="452"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="304"></L>
<L>My lorde and I bene fully atte acorde</L>
<L>I made hir to &thorn;e worship of my lorde</L>
<L>So doo I alle myne o&thorn;er creatures</L>
<L N="28">Of what coloure &thorn;ei be or what figures</L>
<L>Thus seme&thorn; me &thorn;at nature wolde say</L>
<L>This maide was of age .xij. &yogh;ere and tway</L>
<L>In whiche &thorn;at nature ha&thorn; such delite</L>
<L N="32">ffor ri&yogh;t as she can peynt as lily white</L>
<L>And roody as roose ri&yogh;t wi&thorn; such peynture</L>
<L>She peynted ha&thorn; &thorn;is noble creature</L>
<L>Er she was born vpon her lymes fre</L>
<L N="36">Were also bri&yogh;t as such coloures my&yogh;t be.</L>
<L>And phebus died had her tresses grete</L>
<L>Like to &thorn;e stremes of his boorned hete</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;at excellent was her bewte</L>
<L N="40">A thowsand folde more vertuous was she</L>
<L>In hur ne lacke&thorn; no condicion</L>
<L>&THORN;at is to preise as by discrecion.</L>
<L>As wel in body as goost chaast was she<MILESTONE N="212a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="44">ffor which she flowred in virginite</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al humilite and abstinence</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; alle attemperance and pacience</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; mesure eke in beringe of araye.</L>
<L N="48">Discrete she was in answering alwaye</L>
<L>And she was wis as pallas dar I seyn</L>
<L>Hir facon eke ful womanly and pleyn</L>
<L>Noon counterfeted teermes had shee</L>
<L N="52">&para; To seme wise but after her degree.</L>
<L>She spak and alle her wordes more and lasse</L>
<L>Sownynge in vertue and in gentelnasse</L>
<L>Shamefast she was in maidens shamfastnesse</L>
<L N="56">Constant in hert and euere in bysynesse</L>
<L>To drive hur out of her scloggardrie</L>
<L>Bachus had of her mou&thorn;e no maistrie</L>
<L>ffor wille and &thorn;ou&yogh;t done Venus encrece</L>
<L N="60">As men in fire wil casten oile or grece
<PB REF="00000483.tif" N="453"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="305"></L>
<L>And of her owne vertue vnconstreyned.</L>
<L>She ha&thorn;e ful oft tyme hur seke feyned.</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at she wolde flee &thorn;e companye</L>
<L N="64">where likly was to treten of folye</L>
<L>As is at feestys. Reuels. and daunces</L>
<L>Whiche bene occasion of daliaunces</L>
<L>Suche &thorn;ingges maken children forto be.</L>
<L N="68">To sone ripe and bolde as men may see</L>
<L>Which is ful perilous and ha&thorn; bene &yogh;oore</L>
<L>ffor al to sone may she lerne lore.</L>
<L>Of boldnesse whan she is a wiff</L>
<L N="72">And &yogh;e Maistresses in &yogh;oure olde liff</L>
<L>&thorn;at lordes dou&yogh;ters han in gouernaunce</L>
<L>Ne take&thorn; of my wordes no displesaunce</L>
<L>Thingges &thorn;at bene sette in gouernyngges</L>
<L N="76">Of lordys dou&yogh;ters oonly for two &thorn;ingges</L>
<L>Oy&thorn;er for &yogh;e han kepte &yogh;oure honeste</L>
<L>Oy&thorn;ere ellis &yogh;e han falle in freelte</L>
<L>And knowen wel ynou&yogh;e &thorn;e olde daunce</L>
<L N="80">And konne for-sake fully [such] meschaunce.</L>
<L>ffor euermoo &thorn;erfor for cristes sake<MILESTONE N="212b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>kepe&thorn; wel &thorn;oo &thorn;at &yogh;e vndertake</L>
<L>A theef for venyson &thorn;at hath forlaft</L>
<L N="84">His likerousnesse and al his &thorn;eeues craft</L>
<L>Can kepe a forest best of eny man.</L>
<L>Now kepe&thorn; hem wel for and &yogh;e wil &yogh;e can.</L>
<L>loke&thorn; wel to no vice &thorn;at &yogh;e assente.</L>
<L N="88">Lest &yogh;e be dampned for &yogh;oure euel entente.</L>
<L>ffor who so do&thorn; a traitoure is certeyn.</L>
<L>And take&thorn; [kepe] of &thorn;at &thorn;at I shal seyn.</L>
<L>Of al treson suffreyn pestilence.</L>
<L N="92">Is whan a wi&yogh;t bitraie&thorn; innocence.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e faders and &yogh;e moders eke also.</L>
<L>&thorn;ou&yogh;e &yogh;e han children be it on or twoo.</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure is &thorn;e charge of al her suffraunce.</L>
<L N="96">Whiles &thorn;ei bene vnder gouernaunce
<PB REF="00000484.tif" N="454"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="306"></L>
<L>Be ware &thorn;at by ensample of &yogh;our lyuynge</L>
<L>E&thorn;ere by necligence in chaastisinge</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ei ne perisshe for I dar wel saye</L>
<L N="100">&YOGH;if &thorn;at &yogh;e done &yogh;e shul ful sore abaye</L>
<L>vndere a sheparde. soft and negligent</L>
<L>&thorn;e wolf ha&thorn; mony a shepe and lomb to-rent</L>
<L>Suffise&thorn; oon ensample nowe as here</L>
<L N="104">ffor I mot/ turne a&yogh;ein to my matere</L>
<L>&para; This maide of which I telle my tale expresse.</L>
<L>She kept her self her neded no maistresse.</L>
<L>ffor in her lyuynge maidens my&yogh;t rede</L>
<L N="108">As in a booke euery good woord and dede</L>
<L>&THORN;at longe&thorn; to a maide vertuous</L>
<L>She was so prudent and so bounteuous.</L>
<L>ffor whiche [&thorn;e fame] out spronge on euery side.</L>
<L N="112">Both of her bewte and of her bounte wide.</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;orowe &thorn;e londe &thorn;ei preised hure echon.</L>
<L>&THORN;at loued vertue sauf envie allone.</L>
<L>&THORN;at sorie is of o&thorn;er mennys wele</L>
<L N="116">&para; And glad is of his sorowe and vnhele</L>
<L>The doctoure make&thorn; &thorn;is descripcioun</L>
<L>This maide went on a day into &thorn;e toun</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e temple wi&thorn; her modere dere<MILESTONE N="213a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="120">As is of yonge maidens &thorn;e manere</L>
<L>Now was &thorn;er a Iustice in &thorn;e toune</L>
<L>&THORN;at gouernere was of &thorn;at Regioun</L>
<L>And so bifelle &thorn;is Iuge his eyen cast</L>
<L N="124">Vppon &thorn;is mayde avisinge hir ful fast</L>
<L>As she came for&thorn;e by &thorn;ere &thorn;e Iuge stood.</L>
<L>Anon his hert chaunge&thorn; and his mood.</L>
<L>So was he kau&yogh;t wi&thorn; &thorn;e bewte of &thorn;is maide</L>
<L N="128">And to him silf ful priuely he saide</L>
<L>This maide shal be myn for eny man.</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;e feende into his hert ran</L>
<L>And tau&yogh;t him sodeynly by what scli&yogh;t</L>
<L N="132">The maide to his purpoos wynne he my&yogh;t
<PB REF="00000485.tif" N="455"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="307"></L>
<L>ffor certis by no force ne by no mede</L>
<L>Him &thorn;ou&yogh;t he was not able forto spede.</L>
<L>ffor he was stronge of freendes and eke she</L>
<L N="136">Confeermed was in such souereyn bewte</L>
<L>&thorn;at wel he wist he my&yogh;t her neuere wynne</L>
<L>As forto make here wi&thorn; hur body synne</L>
<L>ffor whiche wi&thorn; grete deliberacioun</L>
<L N="140">He sent after a clerk into &thorn;e toune.</L>
<L>&thorn;e whiche he knewe for subtile or for bold</L>
<L>This Iuge vnto &thorn;is clerk his tale ha&thorn; told</L>
<L>In secre wise and made him to assure</L>
<L N="144">He shulde telle it to no creature.</L>
<L>And if he did he shulde lese his hede</L>
<L>whan assented was &thorn;is cursed rede</L>
<L>Glad was &thorn;e Iuge and made glad chere</L>
<L N="148">And &yogh;aue hym &yogh;iftes precious and dere</L>
<L>whan shapen was all &thorn;is conspiracie</L>
<L>ffrom poynt to poynt how &thorn;at &thorn;is lecherie</L>
<L>Perfourmed shulde be ful sotelly</L>
<L N="152">And &yogh;e shul here afterward openly</L>
<L>Home goo&thorn; this clerk &thorn;at hi&yogh;t Claudius</L>
<L>This fals Iuge &thorn;at hi&yogh;t apius</L>
<L>So was his name for it is no fable</L>
<L N="156">But knowen for an historial &thorn;ing notable.</L>
<L>The sentence of hit so&thorn; is out of dowte<MILESTONE N="213b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>This fals Iuge go&thorn; nowe fast aboute</L>
<L>To hasten his delit and &thorn;at he may</L>
<L N="160">And so bifelle sone after on a day.</L>
<L>This fals Iuge as telle&thorn; vs &thorn;e story</L>
<L>As he was wonned in his consistorie</L>
<L>And &yogh;af his doomes vpon sondrie caas</L>
<L N="164">This fals Clerk came for&thorn; a wel good paas.</L>
<L>And saide lord if &thorn;at it be &yogh;oure wille</L>
<L>As do&thorn; me ri&yogh;t vpon &thorn;is pitous bille</L>
<L>In whiche I pleyn vpon Virginius.</L>
<L N="168">And &yogh;if &thorn;at he wol sayn it is nat &thorn;us
<PB REF="00000486.tif" N="456"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="308"></L>
<L>I will proue it and fynde good wittnesse</L>
<L>&thorn;at so&thorn;e is &thorn;at my bille wil expresse</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iuge answerde of &thorn;is in his absence</L>
<L N="172">I may not &yogh;eue diffinitif sentence</L>
<L>Lat doon hym calle and I will gladly here</L>
<L>&thorn;ou shalt haue ri&yogh;t and no wronge here</L>
<L>Virginius came to witte &thorn;e Iuges wille</L>
<L N="176">And ri&yogh;t anoon was rad &thorn;is cursed bille</L>
<L>&para; The sentence of hit was as &yogh;e shul here</L>
<L>To &yogh;owe my lord sir Apius so dere</L>
<L>Shewe&thorn; &yogh;our poor seruaunte Claudius</L>
<L N="180">How &thorn;at a kny&yogh;t called Virginius</L>
<L>A&yogh;einst &thorn;e lawe a&yogh;einst al equite</L>
<L>Holde&thorn; expresse a&yogh;einst &thorn;e wille of me.</L>
<L>My seruaunt which &thorn;at is &thorn;ral be ri&yogh;t</L>
<L N="184">Which from myn hous was stolen on a ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiles she was ful &yogh;enge I wil it preue</L>
<L>By witnesse lord so &thorn;at &yogh;e &yogh;ou nat greue</L>
<L>She is nat his dou&yogh;tere what so he saye</L>
<L N="188">wherfore my lord &thorn;e Iuge to &yogh;ou I praye</L>
<L>&YOGH;eelde me my thrall if &thorn;at it be &yogh;our wille</L>
<L>loo &thorn;is was alle &thorn;e sentence of &thorn;e bille</L>
<L>Virginius gan vpon &thorn;e clerk biholde</L>
<L N="192">&para; But hastely er he his tale tolde</L>
<L>he wold haue defended it as shuld a kny&yogh;t</L>
<L>And by witnesse of mony a trewe wi&yogh;t</L>
<L>That al was fals &thorn;at saide his aduersarie<MILESTONE N="214a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="196">This cursed Iuge wold no lenger tarye</L>
<L>Ne here oon woord more of Virgyneus</L>
<L>But &yogh;af his Iugement and saide &thorn;us.</L>
<L>I deme anoon &thorn;is clerk his seruaunte haue</L>
<L N="200">Thow shalt no longer in &thorn;ine hous hir saue</L>
<L>Goo bringe hir for&thorn; and put hur in our warde</L>
<L>This Clerk shal haue his &thorn;rall &thorn;us I awarde</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is wor&thorn;i kny&yogh;t Virgineus</L>
<L N="204">Thorgh &thorn;e assent of &thorn;e Iuge Apius
<PB REF="00000487.tif" N="457"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="309"></L>
<L>Most by force his dere dou&yogh;tere &yogh;euen</L>
<L>Vnto the Iuge in lecchery to lyuen.</L>
<L>He goo&thorn; hym home and sette hym in his halle</L>
<L N="208">And lete anoon his deer dou&yogh;ter calle.</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; a face dede as asshen colde</L>
<L>Vpon her humble face he can biholde</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; faders pite stikyng &thorn;orgh his herte</L>
<L N="212">Al wold he nat from his purpoos conuerte</L>
<L>Doughtere quod he Virginea be &thorn;i name</L>
<L>&THORN;er bene twoo weies. oi&thorn;er de&thorn; oi&thorn;er shame</L>
<L>&THORN;at thow most suffre allas &thorn;at I was bore</L>
<L N="216">ffor neuer &thorn;ou deseruedest wherfore</L>
<L>To dyen wi&thorn; a sweerd or wi&thorn; a knyf</L>
<L>O dere dou&yogh;ter ender of my lif</L>
<L>Which I haue fostred vp wi&thorn; such plesaunce</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;at &thorn;ou ne were out of my remembraunce</L>
<L>O doughtere which &thorn;at art my last woo.</L>
<L>And in lif my last Ioie also</L>
<L>O gemme of chastite in pacience</L>
<L N="224">Take &thorn;ou &thorn;i de&thorn; for &thorn;is is my sentence</L>
<L>ffor loue and nat for hate &thorn;ou most be dede</L>
<L>My pitous honde mote smyten of &thorn;ine hede</L>
<L>Allas &thorn;at euer Apius &thorn;e say</L>
<L N="228">Thus ha&thorn; he falsly Iuged &thorn;e to day</L>
<L>And tolde hur al &thorn;e caas as &yogh;e bifore</L>
<L>Haue herd it nede&thorn; telle it no more</L>
<L>Mercy dere fadere quod &thorn;is maide</L>
<L N="232">And wit &thorn;at word she bo&thorn; hure armes laide.</L>
<L>Aboute his nek as she was wonned to doo<MILESTONE N="214b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e teeres brosten out of her eyen twoo</L>
<L>A[n]d saide good fadere shal I dye</L>
<L N="236">Is &thorn;ere no grace is &thorn;er no remedye</L>
<L>No certes dere dou&yogh;ter myn quod he.</L>
<L>Than &yogh;eue me leue fader myn quod she.</L>
<L>My de&thorn; [for] to compleyn a litel space</L>
<L N="240">ffor parde Ieffa &yogh;aue his dou&yogh;tere grace
<PB REF="00000488.tif" N="458"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="310"></L>
<L>fforto compleyn er he her sclou&yogh;e alas.</L>
<L>And god it woot no &thorn;ing was his trespas</L>
<L>But &thorn;an she ranne her fader first to see</L>
<L N="244">To welcome him wi&thorn; grete solempnite</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word she felle a swoun anon</L>
<L>And aftere whan her swownyng was agon</L>
<L>She rise&thorn; vp and to her fadere saide</L>
<L N="248">Blessed be god &thorn;at I shal die a maide</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue me my dee&thorn; er &thorn;at I haue a shame</L>
<L>Do&thorn; wi&thorn; &yogh;oure childe &yogh;our wille a goddys name</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word she preie&thorn; [him] ful oft</L>
<L N="252">That wi&thorn; his swerde he shuld smyte her soft</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;at woord in swowne doune she felle</L>
<L>Hur fadere wi&thorn; ful sorowful hert and felle</L>
<L>Hure hede of smote and by &thorn;e top it hent</L>
<L N="256">And to the Iuge he &yogh;aue it to present</L>
<L>As he satte in his doome in consistorie</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;e Iuge it seie as sei&thorn; &thorn;e storie</L>
<L>He bad take him and honge hym also fast</L>
<L N="260">But ri&yogh;t anoon al &thorn;e puple in &thorn;rast</L>
<L>To saue &thorn;e kny&yogh;t for rew&thorn;e and for pite</L>
<L>ffor knowen was &thorn;e fooles iniquite</L>
<L>The puple anoon had suspecte in &thorn;is &thorn;inge</L>
<L N="264">By manere of &thorn;is clerkes chalengynge</L>
<L>&THORN;at it was by &thorn;assent of Apius.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei wist wel &thorn;at he was lecherus</L>
<L>ssor which vnto &thorn;is Apius &thorn;ei gon</L>
<L N="268">And casten hym in prison ri&yogh;t an&omacr;n</L>
<L>Wher as he sclough hym self and Claudius</L>
<L>&THORN;at Seruaunte was vnto &thorn;is Apius</L>
<L>Was demed forto honge vpon a tree<MILESTONE N="215a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="272">But Virginius of his grete pite</L>
<L>Preide for hym &thorn;at he was exiled</L>
<L>And ellis certys he had be begiled</L>
<L>The remenant were honged more and lesse</L>
<L N="276">&thorn;at consented were to &thorn;is cursednesse /
<PB REF="00000489.tif" N="459"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="311"></L>
<L>Here may men see howe synne ha&thorn; his merite</L>
<L>Be ware for no man woote how god wil smyte</L>
<L>In no degree ne in which manere wise</L>
<L N="280">&thorn;e worme of conscience wil arise.</L>
<L>Of wicked lif &thorn;ough it so prive be</L>
<L>&thorn;at no man woote of it. but god and hee</L>
<L>Where he be lewde man or lered</L>
<L N="284">He note howe sone he may be afered.</L>
<L>Therfore I rede &yogh;ou this counsel take</L>
<L>fforsake&thorn; synne er synne &yogh;ou forsake
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000490.tif" N="460"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="312">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Our hoost gan swere as he were wood<NOTE PLACE="marg">&Verbar; The prologe of &thorn;e Pardonere.</NOTE></L>
<L N="288">Harowe quod he by nailles and by blood</L>
<L>This was a cursed &thorn;eef a fals Iustise</L>
<L>As shameful dee&thorn; as herte can deuise.</L>
<L>Come to &thorn;e Iustise and her aduocas.</L>
<L N="292">Algates &thorn;is sely womman is sclayn alas.</L>
<L>Allas dere abou&yogh;te she bewtee.</L>
<L>Wherfore I say alday &thorn;at man may se</L>
<L>That &yogh;ift of fortune or of nature</L>
<L N="296">Bene cause of de&thorn; of mony a creature</L>
<L>[Hir beaute was hir deth I dar well sayn.</L>
<L>Allas so pitously as sche was slayn.<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl. 1758 folio" N="150b">]</L>
<L>As bo&thorn; &yogh;iftes as I speke of nowe</L>
<L N="300">Men han ful oft more harme &thorn;an prowe</L>
<L>But trewly myne owne maister dere</L>
<L>This is a pitous tale for to here</L>
<L>But na&thorn;elees passe ouer is no fors</L>
<L N="304">I prey to god to saue &thorn;i gentile cors /</L>
<L>And &thorn;ine vrynales and &thorn;i Iordans</L>
<L>&THORN;ine ypocras and eke &thorn;i Galyans</L>
<L>And euery box ful of &thorn;i letwarye</L>
<L N="308">God blesse hem and our lady seint Marye</L>
<L>So mote I the &thorn;ou art a propre man.</L>
<L>And like a prelate by seynt Runyan.</L>
<L>Saue &thorn;at I can not speke wel in terme<MILESTONE N="215b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="312">But wel I woote &thorn;ou doost myn hert eerme</L>
<L>That I haue almost kaught a Cardyacle</L>
<L>By corps boones but I haue triacle</L>
<L>Or ellis a drau&yogh;t of moist or corny ale</L>
<L N="316">Or but I here anoon a mery tale
<PB REF="00000491.tif" N="461"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="313"></L>
<L>My hert is lost for pite of &thorn;is maide</L>
<L>&thorn;owe belamy Iohn pardonere he saide</L>
<L>Telle vs some mer&thorn;e or Iapes ri&yogh;t an&omacr;n</L>
<L N="320">he shal be done quod he be seynt Runyon</L>
<L>But furst quod he here at &thorn;e next ale stake</L>
<L>I wil bo&thorn; drink and ete of a cake</L>
<L>But ri&yogh;t anon &thorn;ise gentiles gon to crye</L>
<L N="324">Nay lat hym telle vs of no Rybaudrye.</L>
<L>Telle vs some moral &thorn;ing &thorn;at we may lere</L>
<L>Somme witte and &thorn;an wil we gladly here</L>
<L>I graunt Iwis quod he but I mote &thorn;ink</L>
<L N="328">Vpon som honest &thorn;inge whiles &thorn;at I drink /</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; Thus ende&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e pardoner.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000492.tif" N="462">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="314">
<HEAD>And here bygynne&thorn; the tale.<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 215, <I>back</I></NOTE><MILESTONE N="215b" UNIT="folio"></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Loldingges quod he in church whan I preche<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; The tale</NOTE></L>
<L>I peyn me to haue an hautyn speche</L>
<L>I ryng it out as rounde as go&thorn; a belle</L>
<L N="332">ffor I can al by roote &thorn;at I telle</L>
<L>My teeme is alway oon and euere was.</L>
<L>Radix omnium malorum est cupiditas.</L>
<L>ffirst I pronouns whennys &thorn;at I come</L>
<L N="336">And &thorn;an my bulles schewe all and some /</L>
<L>Our liege lordes seel on my patent</L>
<L>&thorn;at shewe I furst my body to warent</L>
<L>That no man be so bolde preest ne clerk</L>
<L N="340">Me to distrowbe of cristes holy werk</L>
<L>And after &thorn;at telle I for&thorn; my tales</L>
<L>Bulles of popes and of Cardynales.</L>
<L>Of patriarkes and bisshoppes I shewe.</L>
<L N="344">And in latyn I speke a wordys fewe</L>
<L>To sauer wi&thorn; my predicacion</L>
<L>And forto stirre men to deuocion</L>
<L>Than shewe I for&thorn; my longe cristal stones<MILESTONE N="216a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="348">Ycrommed ful of clowtes and of bones.</L>
<L>Relikes &thorn;ei bene as wene men echon</L>
<L>&THORN;an haue I in laton a sholdere bone</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at was an holy Iwes shepe</L>
<L N="352">Good men say I take at my wordes kepe</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at &thorn;is boon be wasshen in a welle</L>
<L>&YOGH;if kowe or calf. shepe or oxe swelle</L>
<L>&THORN;at eny worme hath ete or stonge</L>
<L N="356">About &thorn;e hert or ellis &thorn;e longe
<PB REF="00000493.tif" N="463"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="315"></L>
<L>It is hool anon and fer&thorn;ermore</L>
<L>Of pokkes and of scabbe and of euery sore</L>
<L>Shal euery shepe be hool &thorn;at of &thorn;is welle</L>
<L N="360">Drynke&thorn; a drau&yogh;t take hede what I telle</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at &thorn;e good man &thorn;at &thorn;e beest owe&thorn;</L>
<L>Wil euery weke er &thorn;at &thorn;e Cok hym crowe&thorn;</L>
<L>ffastinge drink of &thorn;is welle a drau&yogh;te.</L>
<L N="364">As &thorn;ilk holy Iwe our eldere tau&yogh;te</L>
<L>His beestees and his stoor shal multiplie</L>
<L>And sirs also it hele&thorn; Ialowsie</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou&yogh;e a man be fallen in a Ialous rage</L>
<L N="368">Lat maken wi&thorn; &thorn;is watere his potage</L>
<L>And neuer shal he [more] his wif mystrust</L>
<L>&thorn;ou&yogh;e he &thorn;e so&thorn; of hure defaute wost</L>
<L>Al had she taken &middot; preestes tweyn &middot; or &thorn;ree</L>
<L N="372">Here is a myten eke &thorn;at &yogh;e may see</L>
<L>He &thorn;at his honde wil putte in &thorn;is myteyn</L>
<L>He shal haue multiplyinge of his greyn</L>
<L>Whan he ha&thorn; sawen be it whete or otys</L>
<L N="376">So &thorn;at he bringe me good pans or ellis grotys.</L>
<L>And men and wommen &middot; oo &thorn;ing I warne &yogh;owe</L>
<L>&YOGH;if eny wi&yogh;t be in &thorn;is churche nowe</L>
<L>&THORN;at ha&thorn; doo synne horrible [so] &thorn;at he</L>
<L N="380">Dar not for shame of it shryuen be</L>
<L>Or eny womman be she &yogh;ong or olde</L>
<L>That ha&thorn; made her husbonde Cukwold</L>
<L>Suche folk shal haue no power ne no grace</L>
<L N="384">To offre to my relikes in &thorn;is place.</L>
<L>And who so finde&thorn; hym out of such blame<MILESTONE N="216b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Thei wil come vp and offre in goddis name</L>
<L>And I assoille hym by &thorn;e autorite</L>
<L N="388">Such as my bulle was graunted to me</L>
<L>By &thorn;is gaude haue I wonnen euery &yogh;eere</L>
<L>An .C. Mark si&thorn;ens I was pardonere.</L>
<L>I stonde like a clerk in my pulpitte</L>
<L N="392">And schewe lewde puples synne ysette
<PB REF="00000494.tif" N="464"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="316"></L>
<L>I preche so as I haue lered by-fore</L>
<L>And telle an hundred Iapes more.</L>
<L>Than peyne I me to streche for&thorn; &thorn;e necke</L>
<L N="396">And eest and west vppon &thorn;e puple I bekke</L>
<L>As do&thorn; a dowue sitting vppon a beerne</L>
<L>Myne hondes and my tunge gon ful &yogh;eerne</L>
<L>&THORN;at it is ioye to see my bysynesse</L>
<L N="400">Of auarice and suche cursednesse.</L>
<L>Is al my prechinge for to make hem free</L>
<L>To &yogh;eue her pans and namely vnto me</L>
<L>ffor myn entent is nat but forto wynne</L>
<L N="404">And no&thorn;inge for correction of synne</L>
<L>I rekke neuere whan &thorn;at &thorn;ei bene buried</L>
<L>&thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;at her saules goo o blakburied.</L>
<L>ffor certes mony a predicacion</L>
<L N="408">Comme&thorn; ofte tyme of euel entencion</L>
<L>Somme of plesaunce of folk and of flaterye</L>
<L>To bene auaunced by ypocresie</L>
<L>And somme for veynglorie and for hate</L>
<L N="412">ffor whan I dar nat o&thorn;er waies debate</L>
<L>Than wil I stynge hem wi&thorn; my tunge smerte</L>
<L>In prechinge so that he shal not sterte</L>
<L>To bene defamed falsely so &thorn;at he</L>
<L N="416">ha&thorn; trespased to my bre&thorn;eren or to me</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou&yogh;e I telle nat his propre name</L>
<L>Men shal wel knowe &thorn;at it is &thorn;e same</L>
<L>By somme signe and o&thorn;er circumstaunces</L>
<L N="420">Thus smyte I folk &thorn;at don vs displesaunces.</L>
<L>Thus spitte I out my venyme vnder hwe</L>
<L>Of holynesse to semen holy and trewe</L>
<L>But shortely myne entent I wil devise ./<MILESTONE N="217a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="424">I preche of no &thorn;inge but of Couetise ./</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore my teeme is &yogh;it and euer was</L>
<L>Radix omnium malorum est cupiditas</L>
<L>Thus can I preche a&yogh;einst &thorn;e same vice</L>
<L N="428">Which &thorn;at I vse and &thorn;at is Auarice
<PB REF="00000495.tif" N="465"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="317"></L>
<L>But &thorn;ou&yogh;e my self be giltif in &thorn;at synne .</L>
<L>&YOGH;it can I make o&thorn;er folk to wynne</L>
<L>ffrom auarice and soor hem repent</L>
<L N="432">But &thorn;at nys not my principal entent</L>
<L>I preche nat but for coueityse</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is matere it ou&yogh;t ynowe suffise</L>
<L>Than telle I hem ensamples mony oon</L>
<L N="436">Of olde stories longe tyme agon</L>
<L>ffor lewde puple louen tales olde</L>
<L>which &thorn;ingges &thorn;ei conne report and hold</L>
<L>What trow &yogh;e &thorn;e whiles I may preche</L>
<L N="440">And wynne gold and siluere forto teche</L>
<L>&thorn;at I wil lyve in pouert wilfully</L>
<L>Nay nay I &thorn;ou&yogh;t it neuere trewly .</L>
<L>ffor I wil preche and begge in sondry londys</L>
<L N="444">I nyl do no laboure wi&thorn; my hondes .</L>
<L>Ne make baskettes for to lyve &thorn;er-by</L>
<L>Because I wil not lyuen ydelly</L>
<L>I wil noon of &thorn;e apostels counterfete</L>
<L N="448">I wil haue money . malt chees and whete</L>
<L>Al were it &yogh;euen of &thorn;e poorest page</L>
<L>Ey&thorn;ere of &thorn;e poorest wydowe in a vilage</L>
<L>Al shulde her children sterue or famyne</L>
<L N="452">And I wil drink &thorn;e licourest of &thorn;e wyne</L>
<L>And haue a ioly wenche in euery toune</L>
<L>But harkene&thorn; lordes in conclusioun</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure liking is &thorn;at I shal telle a tale</L>
<L N="456">Now haue I dronken . a drau&yogh;t of corny ale</L>
<L>By god I hope I shal tel &yogh;ou a &thorn;inge</L>
<L>&thorn;at shal of reson be at &yogh;oure likinge</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou&yogh;e my self be a vicious man &middot;</L>
<L N="460">I morale tale &yogh;it I &yogh;ou telle can .</L>
<L>Whiche Iames went to preche forto wynne .<MILESTONE N="217b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Now holde&thorn; &yogh;oure pees my tale I wil bygynne .
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000496.tif" N="466"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="318">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In fflanndres whilom was a companye<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 217, <I>back</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="464">Of yonge folk &thorn;at haunted folye</L>
<L>As hasard Riot / stewes . and tauernes .</L>
<L>Harpes . Rubibes . lutes and giternes .</L>
<L>&THORN;ei dauncen and pleyen at &thorn;e dys ny&yogh;t and day</L>
<L N="468">and Eten also ouer &thorn;at her my&yogh;t may</L>
<L>Thorgh whiche &thorn;ei do &thorn;e deuel sacrifise</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-in &thorn;e deuels temple in sondry wise</L>
<L>By superfluite abhominable</L>
<L N="472">Her o&thorn;es bene so grete and damnable</L>
<L>&THORN;at it is grisly forto here hem swere</L>
<L>Our blessed lordys body &thorn;ei to-tere</L>
<L>Hem &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;e Iwes rent hym nat ynowe</L>
<L N="476">And ilk of hem at o&thorn;er synne loowe</L>
