<L N="764">Ne for &yogh;oure boost he nyl hym no &thorn;inge hide</L>
<L>See &yogh;e &thorn;at ooke ri&yogh;t &thorn;ere &yogh;e shul hym fynde<MILESTONE N="221b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>God saue &yogh;ou &thorn;at bou&yogh;t a&yogh;ein mankynde</L>
<L>And &yogh;ou amende &thorn;us saide &thorn;is olde man</L>
<L N="768">And euery of &thorn;ise Riatours ranne</L>
<L>Til &thorn;ei come to &thorn;e tree and &thorn;er &thorn;ei fonde</L>
<L>ffloreyns of gold fyne. ykoyned rounde</L>
<L>Wel nyghe a seuen busshells as hem &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="772">No lenger than aftere de&thorn; &thorn;ei sou&yogh;t</L>
<L>But eche of hem so glad was of &thorn;at sy&yogh;t</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at &thorn;e floreynes so faire be and bri&yogh;t</L>
<L>That doune &thorn;ei sette hem by &thorn;e precious hoorde</L>
<L N="776">The worst of hem he spak &thorn;e furst word
<PB REF="00000505.tif" N="475"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="327"></L>
<L>Bre&thorn;eren quod he take hede what I say</L>
<L>My witte is grete &thorn;ough I bourde and play</L>
<L>This tresour ha&thorn; fortune to vs &yogh;euen</L>
<L N="780">In myr&thorn;e and iolite our lyf to lyuen</L>
<L>And lightly so as it comme&thorn; so wil we spende</L>
<L>Ey precious goddys hert who wende</L>
<L>To-day &thorn;at we shulde haue so faire a grace</L>
<L N="784">But my&yogh;t &thorn;is gold be caried fro &thorn;is place</L>
<L>Home into myne hous or ellis to &yogh;oures</L>
<L>ffor wel I woote &thorn;at all &thorn;is gold is oures/</L>
<L>Than were we in high ffelicite.</L>
<L N="788">But trewly by day it may nat be</L>
<L>Men wold say &thorn;at we were &thorn;eues stronge</L>
<L>And for oure owne tresour done vs honge</L>
<L>As wisely and as scli&yogh;ly as it my&yogh;t</L>
<L N="792">This tresour most ycaried be be ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>Wherfore I rede lat loke among vs alle</L>
<L>To drawe and lat see where &thorn;e Cut wil falle</L>
<L>he &thorn;at ha&thorn; &thorn;e curt wi&thorn; herte blith</L>
<L N="796">Shal renne to toune and &thorn;at ful swith</L>
<L>To bringe vs brede and drink ful priuely</L>
<L>And two of vs shal kepen sotilly</L>
<L>This tresour wel and if he wil not tarie</L>
<L N="800">Whan it is ny&yogh;t we wil &thorn;is tresor carie</L>
<L>By oon assent where as vs like&thorn; best</L>
<L>That oon of ham bro&yogh;t gras in his fest</L>
<L>And bad hem drawe and loke wher it wolde falle<MILESTONE N="222a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="804">And it felle on the &yogh;ongest of hem alle</L>
<L>And for&thorn; toward &thorn;e towne he went anoon</L>
<L>And also sone as that he was goone</L>
<L>That oon of hem spak vnto &thorn;at o&thorn;ere</L>
<L N="808">Thewe woost wel &thorn;ou art myn owne sworn bro&thorn;ere</L>
<L>Thi prophite wil I telle &thorn;e anon</L>
<L>Thowe woost wel &thorn;at our felawe is goon</L>
<L>And here is gold and &thorn;at grete plente</L>
<L N="812">&THORN;at shal departed be amonges vs &thorn;ree
<PB REF="00000506.tif" N="476"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="328"></L>
<L>But na&thorn;elees if I can shape it soo</L>
<L>&THORN;at it departed were amonges vs twoo</L>
<L>Had I not done a frendes turne to &thorn;e</L>
<L N="816">&THORN;at o&thorn;er Answered I not howe &thorn;at my&yogh;t be</L>
<L>I wold wel &thorn;at &thorn;e gold were oures twoo.</L>
<L>What shuld wee doo &thorn;at it my&yogh;t be soo.</L>
<L>Shal it be counsaile said &thorn;e first schrewe</L>
<L N="820">And I shal telle [&thorn;e] in wordes fewe</L>
<L>What we shul doon and bringe it aboute</L>
<L>I graunt quod &thorn;at o&thorn;er out of doute</L>
<L>That by my trou&thorn;e I nyl &thorn;e nat bywreien</L>
<L N="824">Now quod the furst &thorn;ou woote wel we be tweyen</L>
<L>And twoo of vs shul strenger be &thorn;an o&omacr;n</L>
<L>loke whan he is sette and &thorn;at an&omacr;n</L>
<L>Arise as &thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;ou woldest wi&thorn; hym play</L>
<L N="828">And I shal ryuen hym &thorn;orgh &thorn;e sides twey</L>
<L>Whiles &thorn;at &thorn;ow strogelest with hym as in game</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;i daggere loke &thorn;ou doo &thorn;e same</L>
<L>And &thorn;an shal al &thorn;is golde departed be</L>
<L N="832">My dere freende bytwixe &thorn;e and me</L>
<L>Than may we boo&thorn; our lustes fulfille</L>
<L>And play at &thorn;e dice at our owne wille</L>
<L>And &thorn;us accorded bene &thorn;ise shrewes tway</L>
<L N="836">To scleen &thorn;e &thorn;red as &yogh;e han herd me say</L>
<L>&para; This &yogh;ongest which &thorn;at went to &thorn;e toune</L>
<L>fful oft in his hert rolled vp and doune</L>
<L>&THORN;e bewte of &thorn;ise floreyns faire and bri&yogh;t</L>
<L N="840">O lord quod he &yogh;if it so were I my&yogh;t</L>
<L>Haue al &thorn;is tresour to myself alone<MILESTONE N="222b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ther nys no man &thorn;at lyue&thorn; vnder trone</L>
<L>Of golde &thorn;at shuld lyve so mery as I</L>
<L N="844">And at &thorn;e last &thorn;e feende oure enemye</L>
<L>Put in his &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at he shuld poysen bey</L>
<L>wi&thorn; which he my&yogh;t scleen his felawes twey</L>
<L>ffor whi &thorn;e feende fonde him in such liuynge</L>
<L N="848">That he had leue hym to sorowe bringe
<PB REF="00000507.tif" N="477"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="329"></L>
<L>ffor &thorn;is was vtterly his entent</L>
<L>To scleen hem bo&thorn;e and neuere to repent</L>
<L>And for&thorn; he go&thorn; no lenger wold he tarye</L>
<L N="852">Into &thorn;e towne vnto apotecarye</L>
<L>And preide hym &thorn;at he hym wolde selle</L>
<L>Somme poysen &thorn;at he my&yogh;t his rattes kelle</L>
<L>And eke &thorn;er was a polcat in his hawe</L>
<L N="856">&THORN;at as he seide his capons had Isclawe</L>
<L>And seide he wolk wreke hym &yogh;if he my&yogh;t</L>
<L>On vermyn &thorn;at destroyen hem by ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>The appoticarie answerd &thorn;ou shalt haue</L>
<L N="860">A &thorn;inge &thorn;at as god my saule saue</L>
<L>In al &thorn;is worlde &thorn;er nys no creature</L>
<L>&THORN;at ete or drink of &thorn;is confecture</L>
<L>Nou&yogh;t but &thorn;e mountance of a corn of whete</L>
<L N="864">&THORN;at he ne shal his lif anoon forlete</L>
<L>&YOGH;e sterue he shal and &thorn;at in lasse while</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;ow wilt goon a pace nat but a myle</L>
<L>This poysen &thorn;at is so hard and violent</L>
<L N="868">This cursed man ha&thorn; in his honde it hent</L>
<L>This poysen in a boxe and si&thorn;ens he ranne</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e nexte strete vnto a man</L>
<L>And borowed hym large botelles &thorn;re</L>
<L N="872">And to his felawes a&yogh;ein repaire&thorn; he</L>
<L>The iij. he kepte clene for his drinke</L>
<L>ffor alle &thorn;e ny&yogh;t he shope hym forto swynk</L>
<L>In cariyng of &thorn;at gold out of &thorn;at place</L>
<L N="876">And whan &thorn;is riotour wi&thorn; sory grace</L>
<L>Had filled wi&thorn; him his grete botels &thorn;re</L>
<L>To his felawes a&yogh;ein repaire&thorn; he./</L>
<L>What nede&thorn; it to sermon &thorn;erof more<MILESTONE N="223a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="880">ffor ri&yogh;t as &thorn;ei had cast his dee&thorn; byfore</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t so &thorn;ei han hym sclayn and &thorn;at anon</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at &thorn;is was doon &thorn;an speke &thorn;at on</L>
<L>Now lat vs sitte and drink and make vs mery</L>
<L N="884">And afterward we wil his body bery
<PB REF="00000508.tif" N="478"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="330"></L>
<L>And after &thorn;at hit happed hem percas</L>
<L>To taken a botell wher-in the poyson was</L>
<L>And drank and &yogh;aue his felawe drink also&thorn;e</L>
<L N="888">&thorn;orghe whiche anoon &thorn;ei steruen bothe</L>
<L>But certes I suppose &thorn;at Auicen</L>
<L>Wroote neuer in no canon ne in no fen</L>
<L>Moo wondere sorowes of empoysenynge</L>
<L N="892">Thus had &thorn;ise wrecches two her endinge</L>
<L>Thus eended be &thorn;ise homycydes twoo</L>
<L>And eke &thorn;is false enpoysoner alsoo</L>
<L>O . cursed synne ful of al cursednesse</L>
<L N="896">O . traterous homycides .o. Wickednesse</L>
<L>O . glotenye luxurye and hasardrye</L>
<L>Thow blasphemour of crist wi&thorn; vileny</L>
<L>And o&thorn;es grete of vsage and of pride</L>
<L N="900">Allas mankinde howe may it betide</L>
<L>That to &thorn;i creatour which &thorn;at &thorn;e wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; his precious blood &thorn;e bou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Thowe art so fals and so vnkynde allas</L>
<L N="904">Now good men god for&yogh;eue &yogh;ou &yogh;our trespas</L>
<L>And kepe &yogh;ou from &thorn;e synne of auarice</L>
<L>Myne holy pardon may &yogh;ou all warisshe</L>
<L>So that &yogh;e offer nobles or sterlyngges</L>
<L N="908">Oi&thorn;er ellis Siluere . spoones . broches . or ryngges</L>
<L>Bowe&thorn; &yogh;oure hede vnder &thorn;is bulle</L>
<L>Comme&thorn; vp &yogh;e Wyues offre&thorn; &yogh;our wille</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure name I entre here in my rolle anon</L>
<L N="912">In to &thorn;e blisse of heuene shul &yogh;e al goon</L>
<L>I &yogh;ou assoille be my highe powere</L>
<L>&YOGH;e &thorn;at wollen offre as clene and eke as cleere</L>
<L>As &yogh;e were born and loo sirs &thorn;us I preche</L>
<L N="916">And Ihesu crist &thorn;at is our saules leche.</L>
<L>So graunte &yogh;ou his pardon to receyue./<MILESTONE N="223b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at is best I wil &yogh;ou not deceyue</L>
<L>&para; But sirs oon word forgate I in my tale</L>
<L N="920">I haue relikes and pardon in my male
<PB REF="00000509.tif" N="479"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="331"></L>
<L>As faire as eny man in engelond</L>
<L>Whiche were &yogh;eue me by &thorn;e popes hond</L>
<L>&YOGH;if eny of &yogh;ow wol of deuoci&omacr;n</L>
<L N="924">Offre and han myn absolucion</L>
<L>Comme&thorn; for&thorn; anon and knele&thorn; here adoun</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e may haue part of my pardoun</L>
<L>Or ellis take&thorn; pardon as &yogh;e wende</L>
<L N="928">Al newe and fressh at euery tounes ende</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &yogh;e offre alway newe and newe</L>
<L>Nobles and pans which &thorn;at bene good and trewe</L>
<L>It is an honure to euery &thorn;at bene here</L>
<L N="932">&THORN;at &yogh;e may haue a suffisant pardonere</L>
<L>To assoile &yogh;ou in contree as &yogh;e ride</L>
<L>ffor auentures which &thorn;at may be-tide</L>
<L>ffor parauenture &thorn;er may falle oon or twoo</L>
<L N="936">Doune of her hors and breke her nek atwoo</L>
<L>Looke swiche a swerte it is to &yogh;ou alle</L>
<L>That I am in &yogh;oure felawship yfalle</L>
<L>&THORN;at may assoile &yogh;ou bo&thorn; more and lasse</L>
<L N="940">Whan &thorn;at &thorn;e soule shal fro &thorn;e body passe</L>
<L>I rede &thorn;at hour [hooste] shal bygynne</L>
<L>ffor he is most enuolupte of synne</L>
<L>Come for&thorn; sire hoost and offre first anon</L>
<L N="944">And &thorn;ou shalt kysse &thorn;e relikes euerechon</L>
<L>&YOGH;e for a groot vnbokel anon &thorn;i purs</L>
<L>Nay nay quod he &thorn;an haue I cristes curs</L>
<L>lat be quod he it shal nat be so theche</L>
<L N="948">&THORN;ow woldest make me kissen &thorn;ine olde breche</L>
<L>And swere it were &thorn;e relike of a seynt</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh;e it were wi&thorn; &thorn;i foundement depeynt</L>
<L>But by &thorn;e crosse which seint Elyne fonde</L>
<L N="952">I wold I had &thorn;i culyons in myne honde</L>
<L>In stede of relikes of seint-wary</L>
<L>Lat kitte hem of and I wil helpe hem cary</L>
<L>They shulde be schryned in an hogges toord<MILESTONE N="224a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="956">This Pardonere answered nat a woord
<PB REF="00000510.tif" N="480"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="332"></L>
<L>So wro&thorn; he was he wolde no word say</L>
<L>Nowe quod our oost I nyl no lenger play</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e ne wi&thorn; noon o&thorn;er angry man</L>
<L N="960">But ri&yogh;t anoon &thorn;e wor&thorn;i kny&yogh;t bygan</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at he seegh &thorn;at alle &thorn;e puple lou&yogh;e</L>
<L>No more of &thorn;is for it is ri&yogh;t ynoghe</L>
<L>Sir Pardonere be mery and glad of chere</L>
<L N="964">And &yogh;ee sir Hoost &thorn;at bene to me so dere</L>
<L>I prei &yogh;ou &thorn;at &yogh;e kisse &thorn;e Pardonere</L>
<L>And pardonere I prei &yogh;ou drawe &yogh;e nere</L>
<L>And as we did lat vs lau&yogh;e and play</L>
<L N="968">And anon &thorn;ei kissed and riden for&thorn; her way</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; Thus ende&thorn; &thorn;e pardoners tale.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="B" TYPE="group">


<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000511.tif" N="481">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="190">
<HEAD>And here bygynne&thorn; The prologe of Thoppas<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; The prologe</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 224</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHan saide was &thorn;is tale euery man</L>
<L>As sober was &thorn;at wonder was to see</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at our oost Iape byganne</L>
<L N="1884">And &thorn;an at erst he loked vpon me .i. chaucers</L>
<L>And saide &thorn;us what man art &thorn;ou quod he</L>
<L>Thow lokest as &thorn;ow woldest fynde an hare</L>
<L N="1887">ffor euer vpon &thorn;e grounde I se &thorn;e stare</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Approche nere and loke meryly</L>
<L>Now war &yogh;ou sirs and lat &thorn;is man han plas</L>
<L>He in &thorn;e waast is shape as wel as I</L>
<L N="1891">This were a popet in armes to embrace</L>
<L>ffor eny womman smal and faire of faice</L>
<L>He seme&thorn; Elnyssh be his cuntenaunce</L>
<L N="1894">ffor vnto no wi&yogh;t do&thorn; he daliaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Say nowe somewhat si&thorn;ens o&thorn;ere folk han saide</L>
<L>Telle vs a tale of merth and &thorn;at anon</L>
<L>Oost quod I ne be nat euel paide.</L>
<L N="1898">ffor o&thorn;er tale certes can I noon.</L>
<L>But of a ryme I lered longe agon</L>
<L>&yogh;e &thorn;at is good quod he shul we it here</L>
<L N="1901">Som deynte &thorn;ing me seme&thorn; by his chere.<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS, and no spaces between the stanzas above and after.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000512.tif" N="482">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="191">
<HEAD>&para; Here bygynne&thorn; be tale of chaucere by Sire Thopace.</HEAD>
<HEAD>&para; Capitulum xix<SUP>m</SUP> &para; Sire Thopace.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Fitte I.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LEstneth lordes in good entent<MILESTONE N="224b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And I will telle verrement</L>
<L N="1904">Of myrth<NOTE PLACE="marg">[in a later hand]</NOTE> and of solace</L>
<L>Of a kny&yogh;t was faire and gent</L>
<L>In bataile and in tornament</L>
<L N="1907">His name was sir thopace.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I-born he was in fer cuntree</L>
<L>In fflaunders al by&yogh;onde &thorn;e see</L>
<L N="1910">Att Poperinge in &thorn;e place</L>
<L>His fader was a man ful free</L>
<L>And lorde he was of &thorn;at cuntre</L>
<L N="1913">As it was goddes grace</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sir Thopas was a doughty swayn</L>
<L>White was his face as payndemayn</L>
<L N="1916">His lippes rede as Roos.</L>
<L>His rudde is like scarlett in grayn</L>
<L>And I &yogh;ow telle in good certayn</L>
<L N="1919">He had a semely nose</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His heer his beerd was lik saffron</L>
<L>&thorn;at to his girdel kau&yogh;t adoune</L>
<L N="1922">His shoon of Cordewayne/</L>
<L>Of brugges were his hosen broun</L>
<L>His Roobe was of Ciclatoun</L>
<L N="1925">That cost mony a rayn
<PB REF="00000513.tif" N="483"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="192"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He cou&thorn;e hunte at wylde dere&middot;</L>
<L>And Ride on hawkyng for &thorn;e Ryuer</L>
<L N="1928">Wi&thorn; grey goshauke on honde</L>
<L>Therto he was a good archere</L>
<L>To wrastling was &thorn;er noon his peer</L>
<L N="1931">Ther eny ram shulde stonde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>fful mony a maide bri&yogh;t in boure</L>
<L>&thorn;ei morn for him Paramoure</L>
<L N="1934">Whan &thorn;ei were bette to sclepe.</L>
<L>But he was chaast and no lecchoure</L>
<L>And swete as is &thorn;e bremble floure</L>
<L N="1937">That bere&thorn; &thorn;e reede heppe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And so byfelle vppon a day</L>
<L>ffor so&thorn;&thorn;e as I &yogh;owe telle may</L>
<L N="1940">Sire Thopaas wold out ride<MILESTONE N="225a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>He wor&thorn; vp on his stede gray</L>
<L>And in his honde a launce gay</L>
<L N="1943">A longe swerde be his side</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He prikke&thorn; &thorn;orowe a faire forest</L>
<L>Ther-in is mony a wilde beest</L>
<L N="1946">&yogh;a bo&thorn; bukke and hare</L>
<L>And as he prikke&thorn; nor&thorn; and eest</L>
<L>I telle &yogh;owe hym had almest</L>
<L N="1949">By-tidde a sory care</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>There springen herbes grete and smale</L>
<L>&thorn;e lykorice and &thorn;e Setuale</L>
<L N="1952">And mony a clowe gyloffre</L>
<L>And notemuges to put in ale</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;ere it be moyst or stale</L>
<L N="1955">Or forto lay in Coffre
<PB REF="00000514.tif" N="484"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="193"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e birdes syngen it is no nay</L>
<L>&thorn;e sparhauke and &thorn;e popeniay</L>
<L N="1958">&thorn;at Ioie it was to here</L>
<L>The &thorn;rostel cok made eke his lay</L>
<L>The woode douve vpon &thorn;e spray</L>
