<HEAD>And here bygnne&thorn; &thorn;e tale of Melebius &amp; prudence.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>There are no line-numbers or breaks between the paragraphs in the MS. Tyrwhitt's breaks are kept here to prevent slight differences in the Six Texts throwing out many lines. Some of the omissions in the MS are supplied from the print of the French original in</I> Le M&eacute;nagier de Paris, ed. 1847, i. 186, <I>as that proves the omissions to be such</I>.]</P><P>[<I>Petworth MS, on leaf</I> 227, <I>back</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<P>[2157] A &YOGH;ong man called Melebius my&yogh;ty and riche bygate vpon his wiff &thorn;at called was Prudence a doughter which &thorn;at called was Sophie.</P>
<P>[2158] Vpon a day byfelle; &thorn;at he for his disporte is went into &thorn;e feldes. him to play; [2159] his wif and his doughtere he ha&thorn; bylaft in-with his hous. of which &thorn;e doores weren fast shette. [2160] Ther of his olde fooen had espied. and satten ladders to &thorn;e walles of his hous. and by &thorn;e wyndowes bene entred. [2161] and bete his wiff and wounded his dou&yogh;ter wi&thorn; .v. mortal woundes in .v. sondry places. [2162] This is to sayn in her feete. in her hondes. in her ceres. in her nose. and in her mou&thorn;e. and laften her for dede. and wenten her way</P>
<P>[2163] Whan Melebius retourned was into his hous and segh al &thorn;is meschief. He like a mad man reending his clo&thorn;es gan to wepe and crie.</P>
<P>[2164] &para; Prudence his wiff as ferfor&thorn; as she durst. bysou&yogh;t hym of his weping for to stynt. [2165] but not for&thorn;i. he gan wepe and crye euere lenger &thorn;e more.</P>
<P>[2166] This noble wif prudence remembred her vpon &thorn;e sentence of Ovide in his booke &thorn;at cleped is &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> remedy of loue. <MILESTONE N="228a" UNIT="folio">De remedio Amoris. Where as he sei&thorn;. [2167] He is a foole &thorn;at distroube&thorn; &thorn;e modere to weepe in &thorn;e dee&thorn; of her childe. til she haue wepte her fulle. as for a certeyn tyme. [2168] And &thorn;an shal man / doon his dyligence wi&thorn; amyable chere hir to recomforte and prei hyr of 
<PB REF="00000523.tif" N="493"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="202"> her wepinge forto stynt. [2169] ffor which reson &thorn;is noble wiff Prudence suffred her husbonde forto wepe and crie as for a certeyn space. [2170] &para; And whan she segh her tyme she saide to him in &thorn;is wise &para; Allas my lord quod she whi maken &yogh;e &yogh;our self forto [<I>sembler fol?</I> [2171] <I>Il n'appartient pas &agrave; sage homme de</I>] maken such a sorowe. [2172] &yogh;oure dou&yogh;tere with &thorn;e grace of god shal warissh and scape. [2173] And al were is so? &thorn;at she ri&yogh;t nowe were dede. &yogh;e ne au&yogh;t not as for her deth &yogh;our self destroie. [2174] &para; Senec sei&thorn; / &thorn;e wise man shal not take to gret discomfort for &thorn;ee dee&thorn; of his children. [2175] but certes he shuld suffre it in pacience / as wel as he abide&thorn; &thorn;e dee&thorn; of his owne propre persone.</P>
<P>[2176] &para; This Melebius answerd anon and sayde. What man quod he shulde of his weping stent. &THORN;at ha&thorn; so grete a cause as I haue. [2177] .Ihesu our lord him self wepte for &thorn;e dee&thorn; of lazarus his frende &para; Qualiter Ihesus <I>christus</I> fleuit propter mortem Lazari. [2178] &para; Pru|dence answerde. Certes wel I woot attempre wepinge is no &thorn;inge defended to him &thorn;at soroweful is. amonges folk in sorowe. but it is rather graunted hym to wepe. [2179] The Appostel paul vnto &thorn;e Romayns. Apostolus a Ro|manos write&thorn;. Man shal reioyse wi&thorn; hem &thorn;at maken Ioie. and wepe with suche folk as wepen: [2180] But &thorn;ou&yogh;e attempre wepinge be graunted. certes outrage wepinge is defended. [2181] &para; Mesure of wepinge shulde be con|sidered aftere &thorn;e loor &thorn;at teche&thorn; vs senec [2182] &para; Whan &thorn;at &thorn;i frende is dede sei&thorn; he. lat not &thorn;ine eyen to moist bene of teeres. commynge to &thorn;ine eyen. lat hem nat falle. [2183] And whan &thorn;owe hast forgoon &thorn;i freende. Do diligence to geten ano&thorn;er. and &thorn;is is more wisdome &thorn;an forto wepe for &thorn;i frende which &thorn;at &thorn;ow hast lorne. for &thorn;er-in nys no boote. [2184] And &thorn;er-fore &yogh;if &yogh;e gouerne &yogh;ou by sapience. putte away sorowe from &yogh;oure hertes. [2185] Remembre&thorn; &thorn;at Ihesus Sirak sei&thorn;. 
<PB REF="00000524.tif" N="494"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="203"> A man &thorn;at is Ioious and glad in hert it conserue&thorn; hym florsshyng in his age But soly sorowful hert make&thorn; his bonys drie. [2186] He sei&thorn; eke &thorn;us. &thorn;at sorowe in hert sclee&thorn; ful mony a man. [2187] Sa|lomon sei&thorn;; &thorn;at ri&yogh;t as mothes in &thorn;e shepes fleese annoyen to &thorn;e clo&thorn;es. and &thorn;e smale wormes to &thorn;e tree. Ri&yogh;t so annoie&thorn; sorowe to &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> herte [2188] <MILESTONE N="228b" UNIT="folio">Wherfore vs au&yogh;t as wel in &thorn;e dee&thorn; of oure children as in &thorn;e losse of our goodes temporeles haue pacience.</P>
<P>[2189] Remembre&thorn; &yogh;owe vpon pacient Iob. Whan he had lost his childere and his temporell sub|staunce and in his body endured mony a greuous tribulacion &YOGH;it saide he &thorn;us. [2190] Our lorde ha&thorn; [&yogh;eue it me / our lorde ha&thorn;] byraft it me Ri&yogh;t so as our lord wolde ri&yogh;t so is it done. yblessed be &thorn;e name of our lord [2191] &para; To &thorn;ise forseide &thorn;ingges answered Melebius vnto his wif Prudence All &thorn;ise wordes quod he bene trewe. and &thorn;erto pro|fitable. But trewly myn hert is troubled soo. wi&thorn; &thorn;is sorowe. so grisly &thorn;at I note what to doon. [2192] Lat calle quod prudence &thorn;i trewe frendes alle. and &thorn;ine lynage which &thorn;at bene wise. telle&thorn; &yogh;our caas and herkene&thorn; what &thorn;ei say in counsailinge And &yogh;ou gouerne aftere her sentence. [2193] Salomon sei&thorn; wirk al &thorn;i &thorn;ing by counsail and &thorn;ou shalt neuere repent</P>
<P>[2194] &para; Than by &thorn;e counsaile of [his wif Pru|dence] [<I>Mellib&eacute;e appella moult de</I>] folk. [2195] as Sirurgyens. Phisiciens. olde folk and &yogh;onge. and som of his olde enemyes reconsiled as by her countenaunce to his loue and into his grace. [2196] And &thorn;erwi&thorn;al &thorn;er commen somme of his nei&yogh;boures &thorn;at didden him reuerence. more for drede &thorn;an for loue as it happe&thorn; oft [2197] &para; Ther commen also ful mony subtile flaterers and wise aduocates lered in &thorn;e lawe.</P>
<P>[2198] And whan &thorn;ise folk to-gydere were assembled. this Melebius in sorowful wise shewed hem his caas 
<PB REF="00000525.tif" N="495"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="204"> [2199] And by &thorn;e manere of his speche it semed &thorn;at in his hert he bere a cruel yre. redy to do venge|aunce vpon his foon. And sodeynly &thorn;an desired &thorn;at &thorn;e werre shuld bygynne [2200] But na&thorn;elees &yogh;it axed he her counsaile vpon &thorn;is matere ./ [2201] &para; A Sirurgien by licence and assent of such as were wise vp aroos and vn|to melebius saide as &yogh;e shul here</P>
<P>[2202] &para; Sir quod he as to vs Syrurgience appente&thorn; &thorn;at we doo to euery wight &thorn;e best &thorn;at we can &middot; wher as we bene wi&thorn;holden. and to our pacience &thorn;at we do no damage. [2203] Wherfore it happe&thorn; mony tyme and oft &thorn;at whan &thorn;at twey men had euerich wounded o&thorn;ere oon Sirurgien hele&thorn; hem bo&thorn;e. [2204] Wherfore vnto our art it is not appertenent to norsshe werre ne parties to supporte / [2205] But certes as to &thorn;e warisshing of &yogh;oure doghtere al be it so &thorn;at she perilously be wounded we shullen do so ententif bysynes fro day to nyght That wi&thorn; &thorn;e grace of god she shal be hool and sounde as sone as is possible [2206] &para; Almost ri&yogh;t in &thorn;e same wise &thorn;e Phisicien answerd saue &thorn;at &thorn;ei seiden a fewe woordes moore. [2207] That ri&yogh;t as maladies <MILESTONE N="229a" UNIT="folio">bene by hure contraries saued Ri&yogh;t soo shal man warisshe werre by vengeaunce. [2208] His neigh|bours ful of envie his feyned frendes &thorn;at semeden reconsiled his flaterers [2209] made semblant of wepinge and enpeiren and engreggen mochel of &thorn;is matere in preising gretely meleby of my&yogh;t. of power. of Richesse and of frendes. Dispisinge &thorn;e power of his aduersaries / [2210] and seiden vttrely &thorn;at he anoon shuld wreke hym. on his foes and bygynne werre.</P>
<P>[2211] &para; Vp roos &thorn;an an aduocate &thorn;at was wise. by leue and by counsaile of o&thorn;ere &thorn;at were wise. and saide. [2212] &para; Lordingges &thorn;e nede for &thorn;e which we bene assembled in &thorn;is place is ful heuy &thorn;inge. and a grete matere [2213] by cause of &thorn;e wronge and of &thorn;e wikkednesse &thorn;at ha&thorn; bene doon. and eke by reson of a grete damage &thorn;at 
<PB REF="00000526.tif" N="496"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="205"> in tyme commyng is possible to fallen. for &thorn;e same. [2214] and eke by reson of &thorn;e grete riches and power of &thorn;e parties bo&thorn;e. [2215] ffor &thorn;e which resons it were a ful grete perile to erren in &thorn;is matere. [2216] Wherfore melebius &thorn;is is oure sentence. we counsaile &yogh;ou abouen al &thorn;inge. &thorn;at ri&yogh;t anoon &yogh;e do diligence in &thorn;e kepinge of &yogh;oure propre persone in such a wise &thorn;at &yogh;e ne wante noon espie ne wacche. &yogh;oure body forto saue. [2217] And after &thorn;at we counsaile &thorn;at in &yogh;oure hous &yogh;e sette suffisant harnays. so &thorn;at &thorn;ei mowe as wel &yogh;oure body as &yogh;our hous defende [2218] But certes forto moue werre . or sodeynly to doo vengeannce we mowe not deme in so litel tyme &thorn;at were profit|able [2219] wherfore we axen leisere and space to haue deliberacion in &thorn;is caas to deme. [2220] ffor &thorn;e Comon prouerbe sei&thorn; &thorn;us. He &thorn;at sone deme&thorn; sone shal repent. [2221] And eke men sayn &thorn;at &thorn;ilk Iuge is wis &thorn;at sone vnderstonde&thorn; a matere. and Iugge&thorn; by leisere. [2222] ffor al be it soo &thorn;at taryinge be noyful. algate it is nat to repreue in &yogh;euynge of Iuggement ne in Vengeaunce takinge whan it is so suffisaunt and resonable. [2223] &amp; swed oure lorde Ihesu crist by en|sample. ffor whan &thorn;e womman &thorn;at was taken in avoutrie / was brou&yogh;t in his presence to knowen what shulde be doon of her persone. al be it &thorn;at he wist wel him self what he wold answere [<I>toutesvoies il ne respondi pas</I>] sodeynly. but he wolde haue deliberacion. And in &thorn;e grounde he wroot threse. [2224] and by &thorn;ise causes we axe deliberacion. And we shul &thorn;an by grace of good counsaile doo &thorn;inge that shal be profitable</P>
<P>[2225] &para; Vp sterten &thorn;en &thorn;e &yogh;onge folk at onys <MILESTONE N="229b" UNIT="folio">and &thorn;e moost partie of &thorn;at companye han scorne of &thorn;is wise olde man and bygonnen to make noyse and saide. [2226] Ri&yogh;t soo &thorn;e while &thorn;at yren is hoote. men shulde smyte. Ri&yogh;t soo shuld men wreken her harmes and wrogges. 
<PB REF="00000527.tif" N="497"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="206"> &thorn;e while &thorn;ei bene fresshe and newe. And wi&thorn; lowde voice &thorn;ei criden werre.</P>
<P>[2227] .Vp roos &thorn;oo oon of &thorn;ise olde wise and wi&thorn; his hondes made countenaunce &thorn;at men shulde holden hem stille and &yogh;euen hym audience. [2228] &para; Lordingges quod he &thorn;er is ful mony a man / &thorn;at crien werre werre &thorn;at woten ful litel what werre amounte&thorn;. [2229] Werre at his bygynnynge ha&thorn; so grete an entre and so large &thorn;at euery wi&yogh;t may entre whan him like&thorn; and li&yogh;tly fynde werre. [2230] But certes what ende shal falle it is nat li&yogh;t to knowe. [2231] ffor so&thorn;ely whan &thorn;at werre is onys bygonne. &thorn;er is ful mony a childe vnborn of his modere. &thorn;at steruen. &yogh;onge by cause of &thorn;ilk werre or ellys lye in swowe and dye in wrecchednesse. [2232] And &thorn;erfore er &thorn;at eny werre be bygonne; men most han grete counsaile and grete deliberacion [2233] And whan &thorn;is olde man had wende to enforsen his tale by resons. wel nygh all at onys bygonne to rise forto breken his tale. and beden hym ful oft his wordes forto abrigge. [2234] ffor so&thorn;ly he &thorn;at preche&thorn; to hem &thorn;at list nat here his wordes his sermon availe&thorn; not. [2235] ffor Ihesus Sirak. sei&thorn;. &thorn;at musike in wepinge is noyous &thorn;inge. This is to saien as moch availe&thorn; to speke to-fore folk to which his speche availl&edot;&thorn; not. as it is to synge byfore hym &thorn;at wepe&thorn;. [2236] And whan &thorn;is wise man segh &thorn;at hym wanted audience al shamefast he sette hym doune ageyne. [2237] ffor Salomon sei&thorn;. Ther as &thorn;ou ne maist not haue audience. enforce &thorn;e nat to speke [2238] &para; I se wel quod &thorn;is wise man &thorn;at &thorn;e comon prouerbe is so&thorn;e. &thorn;at good counsaile whan it is most nede availle&thorn;</P>
<P>[2239] &para; &YOGH;it had &thorn;is Melebius in his counsaile moche folk &thorn;at prively in his eere counsailed hym moche &thorn;inge and counsailed hym &thorn;e contrarye in general audience</P>
<P>[2240] &para; Whan Melebius had herd &thorn;e grettest 
<PB REF="00000528.tif" N="498"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="207"> partye of his counsaile were acorded &thorn;at he shuld make werre. Anon consented to her counseillinge and fully affermed her sentence [2241] &para; Than dame Prudence whan &thorn;at she seye howe &thorn;at her husbonde shope forto wreke hym on his foon and bygynne werre . she in ful vnble wise whan she segh her tyme saide hym &thorn;ise <MILESTONE N="230a" UNIT="folio">wordes [2242] &para; My lord quod she I &yogh;ow biseche as hertely as I dare and can no hast &yogh;ou nat to fast. and for all guerdons as &yogh;eue me audience. [2243] ffor Pirus Alfons. sei&thorn; &thorn;us. who so &thorn;at do&thorn; &thorn;e good or harme. hast &thorn;e nat to qwiten it. ffor in &thorn;is wise &thorn;i frende wil abide and &thorn;ine enemye shal &thorn;e lenger lyve in drede ./ [2244] &para; The prouerbe sei&thorn;. He haste&thorn; wel &thorn;at wisely can abide. And in wicked haast nys no profit</P>
<P>[2245] &para; This Meleby answerd to his wiff Prudence I. purpoos not quod he to wirken after &thorn;i counsaile ffor mony causes and resons. ffor certes euery wi&yogh;t wolde holde me &thorn;an a fooll [2246] &para; This is to sayne If I for &thorn;i counsailing wold chaunge &thorn;ingges &thorn;at aren affermed by so mony wise men. [2247] Sec|oundly I saye &thorn;at alle wommen bene wicke. and non good of hem all. for of a thowsande men sai&thorn; Salomon .I. foond oon good man. But certes of alle wommen good womman fonde I neuer one. [2248] And also certys &yogh;if I gouerned me by &thorn;i counsaille it shuld seme &thorn;at I had &yogh;eue &thorn;e euere &thorn;e maistrie as god forbede &thorn;at it so were. [2249] ffor Syrak sei&thorn; &thorn;at if &thorn;e wif haue &thorn;e maistrie she is contrarious [<I>&agrave; son mary</I>]. [2250] And Salomon sei&thorn; Neuere in &thorn;i lif to &thorn;i wif ne to &thorn;i childe ne to &thorn;i frende ne &yogh;eue no power ouer &thorn;i self. ffor bettere it were &thorn;at &thorn;i children asken of &thorn;i persone &thorn;inge &thorn;at hem nede&thorn; &thorn;an &thorn;ou sese &thorn;i self in &thorn;e hondes of &thorn;i children [2251] &para; And also &yogh;if I wolde wyrk by &thorn;i counsaillinge. Certes my counsaile most somtyme be secree. til it were tyme &thorn;at it most be 
<PB REF="00000529.tif" N="499"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="208"> knowe and &thorn;is ne may not be [2252. For it is written, '&thorn;e Iangelarie of wommen can hide &thorn;ingges &thorn;at &thorn;ei woote nou&yogh;t' [2253] Furthermore, the philosopher saith, 'In wicked counsaille wommen venquissh men;' and for these reasons I ought not to make use of thy counsel. (<I>See l</I>. 2274, 2280, <I>p</I>. 209, 210, <I>below</I>.)]</P>
<P>[2254] &para; Dame Prudence ful debonairly and wi&thorn; grete pacience had harde all &thorn;at her husbonde liked to say. &thorn;an axed she of hym licence forto speke and saide in &thorn;is wise. [2255] &para; My lord quod she as to &yogh;oure furst reson certes it may li&yogh;tly be answerde. for I say &thorn;at it nys no foly to chaunge counsaille whan &thorn;e &thorn;inge is chaunged. ffor ellis whan &thorn;e &thorn;inge seme&thorn; o&thorn;er wise &thorn;an it was byforn [2256 <I>Apr&egrave;s, je dy encores plus, car se tu avoies promis et jur&eacute; de faire</I>] &yogh;oure emprise. And na&thorn;elees &yogh;e wayn to [per]foreme &thorn;ilk same emprise. by iust cause. Men shuld not seyn &thorn;at &yogh;e were a lyer or forsworne. [2257] ffor &thorn;e booke sei&thorn; The while man make&thorn; no lesinge; whan he turne&thorn; his corage to &thorn;e better. [2258] And al be it soo &thorn;at &yogh;oure emprise be establed and ordeyned by grete multitude of folk. &yogh;it ther &yogh;ou not acomplise &thorn;ilk same ordynaunce but &yogh;ou like. [2259] ffor &thorn;e trou&thorn;e of &thorn;ingges and &thorn;e profite bene ra&thorn;er founden. in fewe <MILESTONE N="230b" UNIT="folio">folk &thorn;at bene wise and ful of reson &thorn;an by grete multitude of folk &thorn;er euery man crie&thorn; and clatere&thorn; what hym like&thorn;. Soo&thorn;ly such multitude nys not honest [2260] And to &thorn;e secounde reson wher as &yogh;e seyn &thorn;at wommen bene wicked. saue &yogh;oure grace Certes &yogh;e dispise all wommen in &thorn;is wise. and [he] &thorn;at al dispiseth [al displeseth]. as sei&thorn; &thorn;e boke. [2261] And Senec sei&thorn;. Who-so wil haue sapi|ence shal no man dispreise. but he shal gladly teche &thorn;at he can. wi&thorn;[out] presumpcioun or pride. [2262] and suche &thorn;inge as he nou&yogh;t ne can he shal not bene ashamed to lerne hem / and enquere of lasse 
<PB REF="00000530.tif" N="500"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="209"> folk &thorn;an hym self. [2263] And &thorn;at &thorn;er ha&thorn; bene ful mony good wommen. [<I>l'en le puet prouver l&eacute;gi&egrave;rement</I>. [2264] <I>Premi&egrave;rement, car nostre Seigneur Ih&eacute;su-Crist ne se fust oncques daign&eacute; descendre en femme</I>] &yogh;if alle wommen had be wikke. [2265] but for &thorn;at grete bounte &thorn;at is in wommen; our lorde Ihesus crist whan he was risen from de&thorn;e to lyf appered ra&thorn;er to a womman &thorn;an to his apostels. [2266] And &thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;at Salomon say. &thorn;at he ne fonde neuer no good womman; It folowe&thorn; not &thorn;erfore &thorn;at alle wommen bene wikke. [2267] ffor &thorn;ou&yogh;e. &thorn;at he ne foonde noon good Certes mony an o&thorn;ere man ha&thorn; founde mony a womman ful good and trewe. [2268] Or ellis perauenture &thorn;e entent of Salomon &thorn;is. as in souereyn bounte he saide no womman. [2269] This to sayn &thorn;at &thorn;er is no wi&yogh;t &thorn;at ha&thorn; souereyne bounte sauf god allone. as he hym self recorde&thorn; in his euaun|gely. [2270] ffor &thorn;er nys no creature so good &thorn;at hym ne wante&thorn; somwhat of &thorn;e perfeccioun of god &thorn;at is his [maker] [2271] &para; &YOGH;oure iij. reson is &thorn;is. &yogh;e seyne &thorn;at if &yogh;e gouerned &yogh;ou by counsaile of me it shulde seme &thorn;at &yogh;e had &yogh;eue me &thorn;e maistrie and &thorn;e lordship Ouer &yogh;oure person. [2272] sire saue &yogh;oure grace; it is not soo. ffor &yogh;if it so were &thorn;at man shulde be counsailed but only of hem &thorn;at had maistrie and lordship ouer his persone. men wold nat be counsailled so oft. [2273] &para; ffor so&thorn;ly &thorn;ilk man &thorn;at axe&thorn; counsaile of a purpoos. &yogh;it ha&thorn; he free chois whe&thorn;er he wil wirk by &thorn;at counsaile or n&omacr;&omacr;n. [2274] &para; And as to &yogh;oure fer&thorn;e reson &thorn;er as &yogh;e sayn &thorn;at &thorn;e Iangelarie of wommen can hide &thorn;ingges &thorn;at &thorn;ei woote nou&yogh;t as who sei&thorn;. &thorn;at a womman can not hide. [2275] Sire Thise woordes bene vnder|stonde of wommen &thorn;at bene Iangelers and wicked [2276] of which womme men seiyn &thorn;at &thorn;re &thorn;ingges dryuen a man out of his hous. That is to seyn Smoke. dropping of Reyn/ and wicked wyues [2277] &para; And 
<PB REF="00000531.tif" N="501"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="210"> such womman seith Salomon. &thorn;at it were better a man were in desert by hym self. &thorn;an wi&thorn; a womman at home &thorn;at is riotours. [2278] And Sire by &yogh;oure leue <MILESTONE N="231a" UNIT="folio">&thorn;at am nat I. [2279] ffor &yogh;e haue ful oft assaied my grete silence and my grete pacience. and eke how wel I can hiden and hele &thorn;inges &thorn;at men ou&yogh;ten secrely to hyde [2280] &para; And so&thorn;ly as to &yogh;oure .v. reson. where as &yogh;e sayn &thorn;at in wicked coun|saille wommen venquissh men / god woote &thorn;ilk is no reson in no stede. [2281] ffor vnderstondeth nowe. &YOGH;e axen counsaile forto doo wikkednesse. [2282] and if &yogh;e will wirk wickednesse and &yogh;oure wiff restreyn &thorn;ilk wikkednesse &amp; ouercomme&thorn; &yogh;ou by reson and by good counsaile / [2283] certis &yogh;oure wiff ou&yogh;t ra&thorn;er to be preysed &thorn;an yblamed [2284] &para; Thus shuld &yogh;e vnder|stonde &thorn;e philosophre &thorn;at sai&thorn;. In wikked counsaille wommen venquyssh her husbondes [2285] And &thorn;er as &yogh;e blamen alle wommen and her resons I shal shewe &yogh;ou by mony ensamples &thorn;at mony a womman ha&thorn; bene ful good an &yogh;it bene. and her counsaile hoolsom and profitable [2286] Eke somme men han saide &thorn;at &thorn;e counsail of wommen is ei&thorn;er do dere or to litel of price [2287] But al be it soo &thorn;at ful mony womman is badde and her counsaile vile and not wor&thorn;e / &yogh;it han men founden ful mony a good womman and ful discrete and wise in counsailynge [2288] &para; Loo Iacobe by counsaile of his modere Rebekka wan &thorn;e benyson of Isaak his fadere and &thorn;e lordship of al his // [2289] Iudith by her good counsaille delyuered &thorn;e Cite of Bethulye in which she dwelled out of &thorn;e hondes of Olyfernes &thorn;at had it biseched and wolde it destroye [2290] abigaille deliuered Nabell her husbonde from dauid &thorn;e [<I>roy qui le voloit occire, et appaisa</I>] &thorn;e kinge by her witte and by &thorn;e good counsail|inge [2291] &para; Hester By hure good consaile enhaunsed gretly &thorn;e puple of god in &thorn;e regne of Assuerus. The kinge [2292] and &thorn;e same bunte in good counsailynge of 
<PB REF="00000532.tif" N="502"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="211"> mony a good womman may men telle / [2293] and more|ouer whan our lorde had create Adam our forme fadere he saide in &thorn;is wise [2294] &para; It is nat good to be a man allone. make we to hym an helpe s[e]mblable to him self [2295] &para; Here may &yogh;e see &thorn;at &yogh;if womman were nat good and her counsaile good and profitable [2296] Oure lord god of heuen wolde nei&thorn;er haue wrou&yogh;t hem. ne called hem helpe of man. but ra&thorn;er confusion to man. [2297] And &thorn;at seide onys a clerk in twoo vers. What is bette &thorn;an gold. Iasper. And what is better &thorn;an Iaspe. Wisdome. [2298] And what is better &thorn;an wisdom Womman. and what is better &thorn;an good womman no &thorn;inge. [2299] And sire by mony o&thorn;er resons may &yogh;e see &thorn;at wommen bene good [<I>et leur conseil bon</I>] and profitable. [2300] And &thorn;erfore &yogh;if &yogh;e wil trest to my counsaile I shal restore &yogh;ou &yogh;oure dou&yogh;tere hool<MILESTONE N="231b" UNIT="folio"> and sounde. [2301] And eke I wil do to &yogh;ou so moche &thorn;at &yogh;e haue honure in &thorn;is caas</P>
<P>[2302] &para; Whan meleby harde &thorn;e wordes of his wiff Prudence he saide &thorn;us. [2303] I see wel &thorn;at &thorn;e wordes of Salomon bene so&thorn;e. He sei&thorn; &thorn;at wordes &thorn;at bene spoken discretely by ordinaunce. bene hony combes for &thorn;ei &yogh;euen swetnesse to &thorn;e soule and hoolsomnesse to &thorn;e body [2304] And wif by cause of &thorn;i swete wordes and eke for I haue assaied and preued &thorn;i grete sapience and &thorn;i grete trou&thorn;e I wil gouerne me by &thorn;i counsaile in al &thorn;inge</P>
<P>[2305] &para; Now sire quod dame prudence and si&thorn;en &yogh;e vouche sauf to be gouerned by my counsaile I wol enforme &yogh;owe howe &yogh;e shul gouerne &yogh;oure selfe in chesing of &yogh;oure counsaile. [2306] &yogh;e shal first in al &yogh;oure werkes mekely bysechen to &thorn;e hi&yogh;e god &thorn;at he wil be &yogh;oure counseilour [2307] and shape&thorn; as to such entent &thorn;at he &yogh;eue &yogh;ou counsaile and comforte as tau&yogh;t Thebye his sone. [2308] At al tymes &thorn;ow shalt blesse 
<PB REF="00000533.tif" N="503"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="212"> god and prey hym dresse &thorn;i waies. and loke alle &thorn;i counsailles bene in hym for euermore [2309] &para; Seint Iame eke sai&thorn;. If eny of &yogh;owe haue nede of Sapience. axe it of god. [2310] and afterward &thorn;an shal &yogh;e take counsaile in &yogh;oure self. and examyne wel &yogh;oure &thorn;ou&yogh;tes of such &thorn;ingges as &yogh;ou &thorn;enke&thorn; &thorn;at is best for &yogh;oure profit. [2311] And &thorn;an shal &yogh;e driue from &yogh;oure hert &thorn;oo &thorn;at bene contrarious to good counsayle. [2312] &thorn;at is to sayn Ire. Couetise and hastinesse.</P>
<P>[2313] ffurst he &thorn;at aske&thorn; counsaile of hym self certys he most bene wi&thorn;-out Ire. for many causes [2314] &para; &THORN;e furst is &thorn;is. He &thorn;at ha&thorn; grete Ire and wre&thorn;e in hym self he wene&thorn; alway &thorn;at he may doo &thorn;at he may nat doo [2315] &para; And secoundly he &thorn;at is Irous and wroth. he ne may nat wel deme. [2316] [and he &thorn;at] may nat wel [deme may nat wel] counsaile [2317] &para; The iij. is this &thorn;at he &thorn;at is Irous and wro&thorn;e as sai&thorn; Senec ne may nat speke but blameful &thorn;ingges / [2318] and wi&thorn; his vicious wordes he stire&thorn; o&thorn;er folk to angre and to Ire. [2319] And eke sir &yogh;e most dryue Coueitise out of &yogh;oure hert. [2320] ffor &thorn;e appostel sei&thorn; &thorn;at Couetise is roote of alle harmes. [2321] And truste&thorn; wel &thorn;at a couetous man ne can nat deme [ne thinke] but only to fulfille &thorn;e eende of his couetise [2322] and certes &thorn;at may neuer ben accompliced. ffor euer more &thorn;e habundance &thorn;at he ha&thorn; of Ricchesse &thorn;e more he desire&thorn;. [2323] &para; And sire &yogh;ou most also dryue <MILESTONE N="232a" UNIT="folio">away from &yogh;oure hert hastynesse [2324] for certes &yogh;e may not deme for &thorn;e best a sodeyn &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at falle&thorn; in &yogh;oure hert. &para; but &yogh;e most avise &yogh;ou on it ful oft. [2325] ffor as &yogh;e herde he[re]-to-forn &thorn;e comon prouerbe. It is &thorn;is &thorn;at he &thorn;at sone deme&thorn;. sone repente&thorn;.</P>
<P>[2326] Sire &yogh;e bene not alway in like disposicion [2327] for certes some &thorn;inge &thorn;at seme&thorn; somtyme to &yogh;ou good to do. Ano&thorn;er tyme it seme&thorn; to &yogh;ou &thorn;e contrarie
<PB REF="00000534.tif" N="504"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="213"></P>
<P>[2328] &para; Whan &yogh;e han taken counsaile in &yogh;oure self and so han demed by good deliberacion such &thorn;ingges as &yogh;ou semed best / [2329] &thorn;an rede I &yogh;ou &thorn;at &yogh;e kepe it Secre [2330] Bywrey nat &yogh;oure counsaile to no persone. but if so be &thorn;at &yogh;e wenen &thorn;at sikerly &thorn;at &thorn;orgh &yogh;oure bewreying &yogh;oure condicion shal be &thorn;e more profitable. [2331] ffor Ihesus Cirak sei&thorn;. nei&thorn;ere to &thorn;i ffoo ne to &thorn;i freende diskeuere not &thorn;i secre ne &thorn;i folye [2332] for &thorn;ei wil &yogh;eue &thorn;e audience and lokinge and supportacion in &thorn;i presence and scorne &thorn;e in &thorn;ine absence [2333] &para; Ano&thorn;er clerk sei&thorn; &thorn;at scarcely shalt &thorn;ow fynden eny persone &thorn;at may kepe counsaile secrely. [2334] &THORN;e boke sai&thorn;. Whilst &thorn;at &thorn;ou kepest &thorn;i counsaile in &thorn;ine herte &thorn;ou kepest it in &thorn;i prison. [2335] And whan &thorn;ou bywreyest &thorn;i counsaile to eny wight he holde&thorn; &thorn;e in his snare [2336] And &thorn;erfore it is better hide &thorn;i counsaile in &thorn;ine hert. &thorn;an preien hym to whoom &yogh;e han bywreie&thorn; &yogh;oure counsaile &thorn;at he wil kepen it clooce and stille [2337] &para; ffor Senec sai&thorn;. If so be &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne may &thorn;ine owne counsaile hide. how maist &thorn;ou preien eny o&thorn;er wi&yogh;t &thorn;i secree counsaile to kepe [2338] &para; But na&thorn;elees &yogh;if &thorn;ou wene sikerly &thorn;at &thorn;i bewriyng of &thorn;i counsaile to a persone wil make &thorn;i condicion stonden in a better plite. &thorn;an shalt &thorn;ou telle him &thorn;i counsaile in &thorn;is wise [2339] &para; ffurst &thorn;ou shalt make no semblant whedere &thorn;e were leuer pees or werre. or &thorn;is or &thorn;at. ne schewe hym not &thorn;i wille and &thorn;ine entent. [2340] ffor trest wel &thorn;at comonly &thorn;ise counsailours bene flaterers [2341] and namely &thorn;e counseilours of grete lordys. [2342] ffor &thorn;ei enformen hem alway ra&thorn;er to speke plesannt wordys enclynynge to &thorn;e lordes lust &thorn;an woordes &thorn;at bene trewe and profitable [2343] &para; And &thorn;erfore men sayne &thorn;at &thorn;e riche man ha&thorn; seelden good coun|saile. but &yogh;if he haue it of hym self [2344] And aftere &thorn;at &thorn;ow shalt considere &thorn;i frendes and &thorn;ine enemyes. [2345] and as touchinge &thorn;i freendes &thorn;ou shalt con|sidere 
<PB REF="00000535.tif" N="505"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="214"> &para; which of hem bene most fei&thorn;full. and most wyse and eldest <MILESTONE N="232b" UNIT="folio">and most approued in counseillynge / [2346] of hem shalt &thorn;owe axe &thorn;i counsaile as &thorn;e caas require&thorn;</P>
<P>[2347] I say not furst &yogh;e shul clepe to &yogh;oure coun|saile &yogh;oure frendes &thorn;at bene trewe [2348] &para; ffor Salomon sei&thorn;. &THORN;at ri&yogh;t as &thorn;e hert of a man delite&thorn; in Sauour &thorn;at is swete. ri&yogh;t so &thorn;e counsaile of trewe frendes &yogh;eue&thorn; swetnesse to &thorn;e sowle. [2349] He sei&thorn; also &thorn;at &thorn;er may no &thorn;ing be likned to &thorn;e trewe frende. [2350] ffor certes gold ne siluer bene not so moch wor&thorn; as &thorn;e good wille of a trewe frende. [2351] &para; And eke he sai&thorn; &thorn;at a trewe frende is a grete defence / who so &thorn;at it fynde&thorn;. certis he fynde&thorn; a grete tresoure. [2352] Than shul &yogh;e eke considere if &thorn;at &yogh;oure trewe frendes bene discrete and wise. for &thorn;e boke sei&thorn; Aske alway &thorn;i counsaile of hem &thorn;at bene wise. [2353] And by &thorn;is same reson shulde &yogh;e clepen to &yogh;oure counsaile of &yogh;oure frendys &thorn;at bene of age such as han sayn moch and bene expert in mony &thorn;ingges and bene approued in counsailinge. [2354] ffor &thorn;e boke sei&thorn; &thorn;at in olde men is &thorn;e sapience [<I>et en moult de temps est prudence</I>] [2355] &para; And Tullius sai&thorn; &thorn;at grete &thorn;ingges ne ben not accomplised by strenght ne by delyuernesse of body but by good counsaile By auctorite of persones and be science &thorn;e which iij. &thorn;inges ne bene not feble by age but certes &thorn;ei cnforsen and en|cresen day by day. [2356] And &thorn;an shal &yogh;e kepe &thorn;is for a general rewle &para; ffurst shal &yogh;e kepe to &yogh;oure counsaile a fewe of &yogh;oure frendes &thorn;at especial bene [2357] ffor Salomon sei&thorn; Mony frendes haue &thorn;owe but among a thousand chese &thorn;e oon to be &thorn;i counseil|our. [2358] ffor al be it soo &thorn;at &thorn;owe furst ne telle &thorn;i counsaile but to a fewe. &thorn;ou maist afterward telle it to more folk. &yogh;if it be nede. [2359] But loke alway &thorn;at &thorn;i counsailers haue &thorn;ilk thre condiciouns &THORN;at I haue saide 
<PB REF="00000536.tif" N="506"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="215"> byfore. &thorn;at is to say &thorn;at &thorn;ei bene trewe and wise and of olde experience. [2360] and wirk not alway in euery nede by oon counsailere allon. for some it byhoue&thorn; be counsailed by mony [2361] &para; ffor Salomon sei&thorn; [salvation] of &thorn;ingges; is wher &thorn;er bene mony counselours</P>
<P>[2362] &para; Nowe see&thorn; what I haue tolde &yogh;ou of which folk &yogh;e shuld be counsailed. Now wil I telle &yogh;ou which counsaile &yogh;e au&yogh;t eschewe [2363] &para; ffirst &yogh;e shul eschewe &thorn;e counsaile of foolis. So sei&thorn; Salomon. Take no coun|saile of a foole ffor he can no counsaile. but aftere his owne affeccion [2364] &para; The boke sai&thorn;. &thorn;at &thorn;e proprete of a fool is &thorn;is. He troweth li&yogh;tly harme of euery wi&yogh;t. and li&yogh;tly trowe&thorn; all bounte <MILESTONE N="233a" UNIT="folio">in hym self [2365] Thow eke shal eschewe &thorn;e Counsaillynge of all flaterers suche as enforsen hem ra&thorn;er to preise &thorn;e persone by flaterye &thorn;an forto telle &yogh;ou &thorn;e so&thorn;|fastnesse of &thorn;ingges./</P>
<P>[2366] &para; Therfore Tullius sei&thorn; &para; Amonge alle &thorn;e pestilences &thorn;at ben in frendship &thorn;e grettest is fflatery. And &thorn;erfore is moor nede. &thorn;at &thorn;owe eschewe and drede and flee from &thorn;e swete wordes of flaterers &thorn;an of eny o&thorn;er puple [2367] &para; The booke sei&thorn;. Thow shalt ra&thorn;er drede and fflee from &thorn;e swete wordes of flaterers and preisers &thorn;an fro &thorn;e eger wordes of &thorn;i frende &thorn;at sai&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;i so&thorn;es. [2368] &para; Salomon sei&thorn;; That &thorn;e wordes of a flaterer is a snare to cacchen innocentes wi&thorn;e. [2369] He sei&thorn; also &thorn;at he &thorn;at speke&thorn; to his freende. wordes of swetnesse and of plesaunce sette&thorn; a nett byfore his foote to cacchen him [2370] And &thorn;erfore sei&thorn; Tullius &para; Encline nat &thorn;ine eeres to fflaterers. ne take no counsaile to wordes of fflatery [2371] And Caton sei&thorn; &para; Auise &thorn;e wel and eschewe wordes of swetnesse and of plesaunce. [2372] And eke &thorn;ou shalt eschwe &thorn;e counsaile of &thorn;ine olde enemyes [<I>qui sont reconcili&eacute;s</I>, [2373] <I>car il est escript: nul ne retourne seurement en la</I> 
<PB REF="00000537.tif" N="507"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="216"> <I>gr&acirc;ce de son ennemy.</I>] [2374] &para; And Isope sei&thorn;. Ne trest not to hem to &thorn;e which &thorn;ow hast hadde somtyme werre or enemyte. ne telle not hem &thorn;i counsaile [2375] &para; And senec telle&thorn; &middot; &thorn;e cause whi &middot; it may nat be. He sei&thorn; where &thorn;at grete fuyre ha&thorn; longe endured. &thorn;at &thorn;er dwelle&thorn; somme vapour of warmnesse [2376] &para; And &thorn;erfore sei&thorn; Salomon./ In &thorn;ine olde foo trest neuere. [2377] ffor sikerly &thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;ine enemye be reconsiled and make&thorn; &thorn;e chere of humilite. and lowte&thorn; to &thorn;e his hede. ne trust him neuere. [2378] for certes he make&thorn; &thorn;ilk fayned humilite more for his profite &thorn;an for eny loue. of &thorn;i persone. [<I>afin qu'il puisse avoir victoire de toi</I>] by swich feyned counten|aunce. &thorn;e which victory he my&yogh;t not haue wi&thorn; stryf or werre [2379] &para; And Peter Alfons sei&thorn; &para; Make noon felawship wi&thorn; &thorn;ine olde enemyes. for &yogh;if &thorn;owe doo hem bounte. &thorn;ei wil peruerten it into wykkednesse [2380] &para; And eke &thorn;ou most eschwe &thorn;e counsaile of ham &thorn;at ben &thorn;i se[r]uauntes. and beren &thorn;e grete reuerence. for perauenture &thorn;ei sayn it more for drede &thorn;an for loue [2381] &para; And &thorn;erfore sei&thorn; a Philosophre in &thorn;is wise; Ther nys no wi&yogh;t perfitly trwe to hym &thorn;at he to fore drede&thorn; [2382] &para; And Tullius sai&thorn; &para; Ther is noo my&yogh;t so grete of noon Emperour that longe may endure but &yogh;if he haue more loue of &thorn;e puple &thorn;an drede [2383] &para; Thow shalt also e[s]cheu &thorn;e counsaillynge of folk &thorn;at bene dronklewe. for &thorn;ei ne can no counsaile hide [2384] &para; ffor Salomon sei&thorn; &para; Ther is no counsaile &thorn;er as regne&thorn; dronknesse [2385] &para; &YOGH;e shul also haue in suspecte &thorn;e counsaile of such folk as counsaile &yogh;owe prively. oon. <MILESTONE N="233b" UNIT="folio">and &thorn;e contrarie openly [2386] <B>ffor Cassiodorie sei&thorn;.</B>/ That it is a manere sclei&yogh;t to hindere. whan he sweweth to doon oon &thorn;inge openly and werke&thorn; &thorn;e contrarie prively [2387] &para; Thow shalt also haue in suspecte the counsailing wi&thorn; wicke&thorn; folke <B>ffor &thorn;e boke sai&thorn;</B> The counsailynge of wicked folk is alway ful 
<PB REF="00000538.tif" N="508"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="217"> of fraude [2388] <B>And</B> dauid <B>sei&thorn;</B> Blessed is &thorn;at man &thorn;at ha&thorn; not folowed &thorn;e counsailling of wikked men or schrewen [2389] &para; Thow shalt also eschewe &thorn;e counsaile of &yogh;onge folk. for her counsaile is not ripe</P>
<P>[2390] &para; Now Sire si&thorn; I haue shewde &yogh;ou of such folk &yogh;e shuld take &yogh;oure counsaille And of which folk &yogh;e shul take &yogh;oure counsaile. and of which folk &yogh;e shul folowe &thorn;e counsaille [2391] &para; Now shal I telle &yogh;ou howe &yogh;e shul examyne &yogh;oure counsaile. after &thorn;e doctrine of Tullius [2392] in examynynge. &thorn;an of &yogh;oure counseillour. &yogh;e shul considere mony &thorn;ingges [2393] &para; Al&thorn;er furst &yogh;e shul considere &thorn;at in &thorn;ilk &thorn;inge &thorn;at &thorn;owe purposest. and vppon what &thorn;inge &thorn;ow wolt haue counsaille &thorn;at verrey trou&thorn;e be saide and considered. This is to sayn telle trewly &thorn;i tale. [2394] for he &thorn;at sei&thorn; fals may not wel be counsailed in &thorn;at tale [in which he lyeth] [2395] And after This &thorn;ou shalt considere &thorn;oo &thorn;ingges &thorn;at accorden to &thorn;at &thorn;ou purposest forto doo by &thorn;i counsail|lours. &yogh;if reson. accorde &thorn;erto. [2396] &amp; eke &yogh;if &thorn;i myght may atteyne &thorn;erto. And &yogh;if &thorn;e more party and &thorn;e better part of &thorn;i counsailours accorde &thorn;erto anoon. [2397] &thorn;an shalt &thorn;ou considere &thorn;at &thorn;inge &thorn;at shal folowe of &thorn;at counsailleng. as. pees. werre. grace. profite or damage and mony o&thorn;er &thorn;ingges. [2398] [<I>et en toutes ces choses</I>] &thorn;ow shalt chese &thorn;e best and wayue all o&thorn;er. [2399] &para; Than shalt &thorn;ow considere of what roote is engendred &thorn;i matere of &thorn;i counsaile and whatt fruyte may be conseyued and engendred &thorn;er-of [2400] &para; Thow shalt also considere all &thorn;ise cases from whannes &thorn;ei bene sprongen [2401] And whan &yogh;e han examyned &yogh;oure counsaille as I haue saide. which parte is &thorn;e better and more profitable and haue approued it by mony wise folk and eelde. [2402] Than shalt &thorn;ow considere if &thorn;ow maist performe it and make of it a good ende. [2403] ffor reson wil not &thorn;at eny man shuld bygynne a &thorn;inge but &yogh;if he myght performe it as hym lest or au&yogh;t [2404] Ne no wi&yogh;t shuld 
<PB REF="00000539.tif" N="509"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="218"> take vpon him so heuy a charge &thorn;at he my&yogh;t not bere it. [2405] ffor &thorn;e prouerbe sei&thorn;. He &thorn;at to moche embraiseth; destrayne&thorn; litel &middot; [2406] And Caton sai&thorn; &para; Assaie to doo such &thorn;ingges as &thorn;ow hast pouer to doo. lest &thorn;at &thorn;i charge oppresse &thorn;e so soor &thorn;at &thorn;e byhoue&thorn; to wayue. &thorn;inge &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast bygonne [2407] &para; And &yogh;if so be <MILESTONE N="234a" UNIT="folio">&thorn;at &thorn;owe be in doute whedere &thorn;ou maist performe a &thorn;inge or noon. chese ra&thorn;er to suffre &thorn;an bygynne [2408] <B>And Petrus Alfons</B> / sai&thorn;; If &thorn;ou hast myght to done a &thorn;inge of which &thorn;e most repent. it is bettere nay &thorn;an &yogh;ee. [2409] This is to sayn &thorn;at &thorn;e is bettere to holde &thorn;i tunge stille. &thorn;an forto speke. [2410] Than may &yogh;e vnderstonde by strenger resons. &thorn;at &yogh;if &thorn;ou hast powere to perfourme a warke of which &thorn;ou shalt repent. &thorn;an is it better &thorn;at &thorn;owe suffre &thorn;an bygynne [2411] &para; Wel sayne &thorn;ei &thorn;at defenden euery wi&yogh;t to assay a &thorn;ing of which he is in doute whedere he may performe it or noon. [2412] And after whan &yogh;e han examyned &yogh;oure counsaile as I haue saide biforn. and knowen wel &yogh;e may per|fourme &yogh;oure emprise. conforme it &thorn;an sadly til it be at an eend</P>
<P>[2413] &para; Nowe is it reson and tyme. &thorn;at I shewe when and wherfore &thorn;at &yogh;e may chaunge &yogh;oure counsail|lours wi&thorn;-out repreef [2414] &para; So&thorn;ely a man may change his counsaille. and his purpoos if &thorn;e cause sese&thorn;. or whan a newe cause bynde&thorn;. [2415] ffor &thorn;e lawe sei&thorn; &thorn;at vpon &thorn;ingges &thorn;at newly betiden byhoue&thorn; newe consaille. [2416] <B>And</B> Senec <B>sei&thorn;</B> / &yogh;if &thorn;i counsaile be commen to &thorn;e eeres of myn enemye; chaunge &thorn;i counsaille [2417] &para; Thow maist also chaunge &thorn;i counsaille. &yogh;if so be &thorn;at &thorn;ou fynde &thorn;at by errour or by o&thorn;er cause harme or damage may be-tide [2418] &para; Also &yogh;if &thorn;i counsaille be dishonest. or ellis comme&thorn; of dishonest cause chaunge &thorn;i consaille [2419] <B>ffor &thorn;e lawes sayn</B> &middot; &thorn;at al byheestes &thorn;at bene dishonest bene of no valewe. 
<PB REF="00000540.tif" N="510"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="219"> [2420] And eke &yogh;if it so be &thorn;at it be inpossible or may not goodly be performed or kept.</P>
<P>[2421] And take &thorn;is for a general rewle &thorn;at euery counsaile &thorn;at is affermed so strongly &thorn;at it may nat be chaunged for no condicion &thorn;at may be-tide I saye &thorn;at &thorn;ilk counsayle is wikked</P>
<P>[2422] &para; This Melebius whan he had herde &thorn;is doctrine of his wiff Dame Prudence. Answerde in &thorn;is wise. [2423] &para; Dame quod he as &yogh;it into &thorn;is tyme &yogh;e han wel and connably tau&yogh;t me. as in generall howe I shal gouerne as in chesinge and in wi&thorn;holding of my counsaillours [2424] But nowe wolde I fayn &thorn;at &yogh;e wolden condescenden in especiall. [2425] and tel me howe like&thorn;. or what seme&thorn; &yogh;owe by our counsaillours &thorn;at we haue chosen in our present nede</P>
<P>[2426] &para; My lord quod she I biseche &yogh;owe in alle hum|blesse &thorn;at &yogh;e wil not wilfully replie a&yogh;einst my resons / and mystemper nat &yogh;our hert &thorn;ou&yogh;e I <MILESTONE N="234b" UNIT="folio">say or speke &thorn;inge &thorn;at &yogh;ou displese&thorn;. [2427] ffor god woote &thorn;at as &thorn;at as in myn entent I speke it for &yogh;oure best for &yogh;oure honure and &yogh;oure profite. [2428] and so&thorn;ly. I hope &thorn;at &yogh;oure be|nignite wil taken in pacience. [2429] Treste&thorn; me wel quod she &thorn;an &thorn;at &yogh;oure counsaille as in &thorn;is caas ne shuld nat as forto speke proprely. be called a consaillinge. but a moci&omacr;n or mouynge of foly. [2430] in which counsaille &yogh;e han erred [<I>en moult de mani&egrave;res</I>]</P>
<P>[2431] [<I>Premi&egrave;rement, tu as err&eacute;</I>] in &thorn;e assem|blyng of &yogh;oure counsaillers. [2432] ffor &yogh;e shuld first haue cleped a fewe folk [<I>et puis apr&egrave;s plusieurs</I>] &yogh;if it had bene nede. [2433] But certes &yogh;e han sodeynly cleped to &yogh;oure counsaille a grete multitude of puple. fful chargeant and ful noyous forto here [2434] Also &yogh;e han erred. for &thorn;ere as &yogh;e shuld oonly haue cleped to &yogh;oure counsaille &yogh;oure trewe freendes olde and wise [2435] &yogh;e haue ycleped straunge folk. &yogh;onge folk. fals flaterers and enemyes 
<PB REF="00000541.tif" N="511"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="220"> reconsiled and folk &thorn;at done &yogh;ou reuerence without loue [2436] &para; Also &yogh;e haue erred. for &yogh;e haue brou&yogh;t wi&thorn; &yogh;ou to &yogh;oure counsaille. Ire. Coueityse. and hastynesse [2437] &thorn;e which &thorn;re &thorn;ingges [<I>sont contraires &agrave; conseil, et</I>] [2438] &yogh;e han not avyncesed or destroyed hem / nei&thorn;er in &yogh;oure self ne in &yogh;oure counsaillours as &yogh;e ou&yogh;t [2439] &para; &YOGH;e haue erred also for &yogh;e han shewed to &yogh;oure counsailers &yogh;oure talent and &yogh;oure affection to make werre anoon and forto do vengeance. [2440] &thorn;ei han espied by &yogh;oure wordes to what &thorn;ing &yogh;e bene enclined. [2441] &amp; &thorn;erfore han &thorn;ei counsailled &yogh;ou ra&thorn;er to &yogh;oure talent &thorn;an to &yogh;oure prophete [2442] &para; &YOGH;e haue erred also. ffor it semed &thorn;at &yogh;ou suffised to haue bene coun|sailled by &thorn;ise counsailloures oonly &amp; with &thorn;at litel avice./ [2443] Where as in so grete and so highe a nede it had ben necessarie moo counsaillours and more deliberacion to performe &yogh;oure emprise [2444] &para; &yogh;e haue erred also. for &yogh;e haue nat examened &yogh;oure counsaile in &thorn;e forseide matere ne in dwe manere. as &thorn;e cace require&thorn; [2445] &para; &yogh;e han erred also for &yogh;e han maked no dyuysion bytwix &yogh;oure counsaillours. &THORN;is is to sayn bytwix &yogh;oure frendes &amp; &yogh;oure fayned counsaillours [2446] ne &yogh;e han not knowe &thorn;e wille of &yogh;oure trewe frendes. olde and wise [2447] But &yogh;e han cast all her wordes in an hochepote and enclyned &yogh;oure herte to &thorn;e more parte and to &thorn;e gretter nombre and &thorn;er by &yogh;e condescended. [2448] And si&thorn; &yogh;e wote wele &thorn;at men shal fynde a gretter multitude of fooles &thorn;an of wise men. [2449] and &thorn;erfor &thorn;e counsaillours &thorn;at ben at congregacions and mul|titudes of folk &thorn;er as men take more reward to &thorn;e nombre &thorn;an to &thorn;e sapience of persones [2450] &para; &YOGH;e se wel &thorn;at <MILESTONE N="235a" UNIT="folio">in such counsaillyngges fooles haue &thorn;e maistrie [2451] .Melebius answerd ageyn and saide &para; I graunte wel &thorn;at I haue erred. [2452] but &thorn;er as &thorn;owe saist me here bifore &thorn;at he nys nat to blame &thorn;at chaunge&thorn; his coun|saillours 
<PB REF="00000542.tif" N="512"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="221"> in certeyn cases and for certeyn iust causes [2453] I am al redy to chaunge my counsailours ri&yogh;t as &thorn;owe wolt devise [2454] &para; The prouerbe sei&thorn;. &thorn;at forto do synne is mannyssh But certes forto perseuere longe in synne is werke of &thorn;e deuell</P>
<P>[2455] &para; To &thorn;is sentence anoon answered dame pru|dence and saide [2456] Examyne&thorn; quod &thorn;an she &yogh;oure coun|saile. and lat vs see whiche of hem ha&thorn; spoken moost resonable &amp; taught &yogh;ou best counsaile. [2457] And for as moche as &thorn;at &thorn;e examynacion is necessarie lat vs bygynne at Cirurgiens and at &thorn;e phisicience &thorn;at furst speken in &thorn;is matere. [2458] I say &yogh;ou &thorn;at &thorn;e Cirurgiens and &thorn;e phisiciens haue seiden &yogh;ou in &yogh;oure coun|saile discretly as hem au&yogh;te. [2459] and in her speche seiden ful wisely as to &thorn;e office &thorn;at hem appente&thorn; to done to euery wight honoure and profite and no wi&yogh;t to anoye [2460] and aftere her craft to doon grete diligence vnto &thorn;e cure of hem which &thorn;at &thorn;ei han in gouern|aunce. [2461] And sir ri&yogh;t as &thorn;ei han answered wisely and discretely [2462] ri&yogh;t so rede I &thorn;at &thorn;ei bene heghly and souereynly guerdoned for her noble speche. [2463] and eke for &thorn;ei shuld do &thorn;e more ententif bysynes in &thorn;e Curacion of &yogh;oure dou&yogh;ter / [2464] ffor al be it soo &thorn;at &thorn;ei bene &yogh;oure freendes &thorn;erfore shal &yogh;e not suffre &thorn;at &thorn;ei serue &yogh;ou for nou&yogh;t [2465] But &yogh;e au&yogh;t &thorn;e ra&thorn;er to gerdone hem and shewe hem &yogh;our largesse. [2466] And as tochinge &thorn;e proposicion &thorn;e which &thorn;e phisiciens encresden in &thorn;is caas. &thorn;is is to sayn [2467] &thorn;at in maladies. &thorn;at oon contrarie&thorn; is warshed by ano&thorn;er contrarie [2468] .I wold fayn knowe how &thorn;ei vnderstonde &thorn;ilk text And what is her sentence [2469] &para; Certes quod Melebius vnderstonden it in &thorn;is wise. [2470] &thorn;at ri&yogh;t as &thorn;ei han [<I>m'(ont) fait un contraire, que je leur face un autre</I>, [2471] <I>et pour ce qu'ils (se) sont</I>] venged ham on me and done me wronge Ri&yogh;t so shal I venge me vpon hem. 
<PB REF="00000543.tif" N="513"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="222"> and done hem wronge [2472] and &thorn;an haue I cured oon contrary by a no&thorn;er</P>
<P>[2473] &para; lo lo quod dame Prudence. how li&yogh;tly is euery man enclyned to his owne desire and to his awne plesaunce [2474] Certes quod she. wordes of &thorn;e phisiciens ne shulden nat haue bene vnderstonden in &thorn;is wise. [2475] ffor certys wikkednesse is nat contrarie to wicknesse. ne vengeance to vengeaunce. ne wrong to wronge. but &thorn;ei bene semblable [2476] and &thorn;er|for on vengeaunce is not warisshed by ano&thorn;er venge|aunce. ne oon wrong by a no&thorn;er <MILESTONE N="235b" UNIT="folio">wronge. [2477] but euer-ych of hem encrese&thorn; and angre&thorn; and gregge&thorn; o&thorn;er. [2478] But certes &thorn;e wordes of &thorn;e phisicien shuld ben vnderstonden in &thorn;is wise. [2479] ffor goodnesse and wikked|nesse ben two contraries and pees and werre and venge|aunce and suffrance. discord and accorde and mony o&thorn;er &thorn;ingges. [2480] But certes wikkednesse shal be warsshed by goodnesse. discord by accord. werre by pees. and so for&thorn; of o&thorn;er &thorn;ingges. [2481] And also to hem accorde&thorn; [<I>saint Pol</I>] &thorn;e appostel in mony places [2482] He sei&thorn;. ne &yogh;elde&thorn; nou&yogh;t harme for harme ne wikked speche for wikked speche. [2483] but do&thorn; wel to hem &thorn;at don &yogh;ou harme. and blesse hem &thorn;at sayn to &thorn;e harme [2484] and in mony o&thorn;er places he amoneste&thorn; pees and accorde. [2485] &para; But now wil I speke to &yogh;ou of &thorn;e coun|saile which &thorn;at was &yogh;euen to &yogh;ou by &thorn;e men of lawe and &thorn;e wise folk [2486] &thorn;at seiden all by oon acorde as &yogh;e han herd bifore. [2487] That ouer alle &thorn;ingges &yogh;e shal do &yogh;oure diligence to kepe &yogh;oure persones and to warnestore &yogh;oure hous [2488] and saiden also. &thorn;at in &thorn;is &yogh;e ou&yogh;t forto worchen ful wisely and bisily and wi&thorn; grete deliberacion [2489] And sire as to &thorn;e furst poynt &thorn;at touche&thorn; to &thorn;e keping of &yogh;our persone [2490] &yogh;e shul vnderstonde &thorn;at he &thorn;at ha&thorn; werre shal euermore deuoutely and mekely preien by-forn alle &thorn;ingges [2491] &thorn;at Ihesu crist of his mercy. wol 
<PB REF="00000544.tif" N="514"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="223"> haue hym in his protection and bene his souereyn helpinge at his nede. [2492] ffor certes in &thorn;is world &thorn;er nys no wi&yogh;t &thorn;at may be counsailled or kepte sufficiently wi&thorn;|out &thorn;e kepinge of our lord Ihesu crist. [2493] To &thorn;is sentence accorde&thorn; &thorn;e profete Dauid &thorn;at sei&thorn;. [2494] &YOGH;if god ne kepe &thorn;e Citee in ydel waite&thorn; he &thorn;at it kepe&thorn;. [2495] Now sire &thorn;an shul &yogh;e committe [<I>la garde</I>] of &yogh;oure persone to &yogh;oure trewe frendes &thorn;at bene appreued and yknowe [2496] and of hem shul &yogh;e asken helpe &yogh;oure body forto kepe ffor caton sei&thorn; &para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou hast nede of helpe aske it of &thorn;i frendes [2497] ffor &thorn;er is noon so good a phisicien as &thorn;i trewe frende [2498] &para; After &thorn;is &thorn;an shal &yogh;e kepe &yogh;ou from al straunge folk and fro leers and haue alway in suspecte her companye [2499] &para; ffor Pers Alfons sei&thorn; &thorn;us ne take no company by &thorn;e waye of a straunge mon. but &yogh;if so be &thorn;at &thorn;owe knowe him of a lenger tyme. [2500] And &yogh;if so be &thorn;at he falle to &thorn;i companye per|auenture wi&thorn;-outen &thorn;ine assent [2501] enquere &thorn;an as sotilly as euer &thorn;ou maist of his conuersacion and of his lyf byfore and feyne &thorn;i way. Say &thorn;ow wolt goo &thorn;idere as &thorn;ou wilt not goo. [2502] and &yogh;if he bere a spere holde &thorn;e on &thorn;e ri&yogh;t side. And &yogh;if he bere <MILESTONE N="236a" UNIT="folio">a swerde holde &thorn;e on &thorn;e lift side [2503] and so after &thorn;is &thorn;an shal &yogh;e kepe &yogh;ou wisely from al such manere puple as I haue saide byfore and hem and her counsaile eschewe. [2504] And &thorn;an after &thorn;at shal &yogh;e kepe &yogh;ou in such a manere [2505] &thorn;at for eny presumpcion of &yogh;oure strength. &thorn;at &yogh;e ne despise nat &thorn;e my&yogh;t of &yogh;oure enemye and of &yogh;our aduersarie. so lite &thorn;at &yogh;e lete &thorn;e kepinge of &yogh;oure persone for &yogh;oure presumpci&omacr;n. [2506] ffor euery wise man drede&thorn; his enemye. [2507] Salomon sai&thorn;. wakeful is he &thorn;at oft ha&thorn; drede. [2508] ffor certes he &thorn;at &thorn;orowe hardynesse of his hert and &thorn;orowe &thorn;e hardynesse of hym self ha&thorn; to grete presumpci&omacr;n him shal euel betide [2509] &para; Than 
<PB REF="00000545.tif" N="515"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="224"> shal &yogh;e euermore countrewaite enbusshmentys and al especials. [2510] ffor Senec sai&thorn;. &thorn;at &thorn;e wise man &thorn;at drede&thorn; harmes; eschewe&thorn; harmes. [2511] he ne falle&thorn; not into periles; &thorn;at periles eschewe&thorn; [2512] &para; And al be it so &thorn;at it seme &thorn;at &thorn;ou art in siker place &yogh;it shaltowe alway doo &thorn;i diligence in kepinge of &thorn;i persone. [2513] &thorn;is is to sayn be not necligent to kepe &thorn;i persone not oonly from &thorn;i grettest enemyes; but fro &thorn;i leest enemyes. [2514] Senec sai&thorn;. A man &thorn;at is wel avised he drede&thorn; his leest enemye [2515] Ovide. sai&thorn;. &thorn;at &thorn;e litel wesell wil slee &thorn;e grete Owle and &thorn;e wilde hert [2516] And &thorn;e boke sei&thorn;; A litel &thorn;orne may prik a kinge ful sore. And an hounde wil holde &thorn;e wilde bore. [2517] But na&thorn;elees I say. &para; not &thorn;ou shalt be so moch cowarde &thorn;at &thorn;ou doute &thorn;er as it is no drede [2518] &para; The boke sai&thorn; / &thorn;at some folk han grete lest to desceyue. but &yogh;it &thorn;ei dreden hem to be de|sceyued. [2519] &YOGH;it shalt &thorn;ou drede to be empoysened and kepe &thorn;e from &thorn;e company of scorners [2520] &para; ffor &thorn;e booke se&thorn;; Wi&thorn; scorners make no companye. but flee hem and her wordes as venyme.</P>
<P>[2521] Now as to &thorn;e secounde poynt when as &yogh;oure wise counsailours counsailed &yogh;ow to warnstore &yogh;oure hous wi&thorn; grete diligence. [2522] I wold fayn knowe how &thorn;at &yogh;e vnderstonden &thorn;ilk wordys and what is &yogh;oure Sentence.</P>
<P>[2523] Melebius Answerd and saide. Certes I vnder|stonde it in &thorn;is wise &thorn;at I shal warnstore myn hous wi&thorn; towres such as haue castels and o&thorn;er manere edifi[c]es and armure and arcelries [2524] by such &thorn;ingges as I may my persone and my hous kepe and defende. &thorn;at myn enemyes shul be in drede myn hous to approche.</P>
<P>[2525] To &thorn;is sentence anon answerd Dame Prudence &para; Warnstoringe quod she of hegh toures and grete edifices [appertaineth sometimes to pride [2526] Men make towers and great edifices] with grete 
<PB REF="00000546.tif" N="516"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="225"> costages and wi&thorn; grete travaile. and whan &thorn;at &thorn;ei be accompliced. &yogh;it bene &thorn;ei nat wor&thorn; a stree. but &yogh;if &thorn;ei ben deffended by trewe frendes &thorn;at bene olde and wise./ [2527] <MILESTONE N="236b" UNIT="folio">And vnderstonde wel &thorn;at &thorn;e strengest and &thorn;e grettest garison &thorn;at &thorn;e riche man may haue as wel to kepe his persone as his goodes. is [2528] &thorn;at he be beloued wi&thorn; his subiectys. and wi&thorn; his nei&yogh;bours [2529] ffor &thorn;us sai&thorn; Tullius &para; That &thorn;er is a maner garneson &thorn;at no man may venquyssh ne discomfett. And &thorn;at is [2530] a lord to be byloued wi&thorn; his Citeseins and of his puple</P>
<P>[2531] Now sir as to &thorn;e iij. poynt where as &yogh;oure olde and wise counsaillours. seiden &thorn;at &yogh;owe ne au&yogh;t not sodeynly ne hastely proceden in &thorn;is nede. [2532] but &thorn;at &yogh;ou au&yogh;t purveien and apparailen &yogh;ou in &thorn;is caas wi&thorn; grete diligence and grete deliberacion. [2533] trewly I trowe &thorn;at &thorn;ei seiden ri&yogh;t wisely and ri&yogh;t so&thorn;e. [2534] ffor Tullius sei&thorn; &para; In euery nede er &thorn;ow bygynne it apparaille &thorn;e wi&thorn; grete diligence [2535] Than say I &thorn;at in vengeance takinge in werre in bataile and in warne-storinge. [2536] er &thorn;an &thorn;ou bygynne. I rede &thorn;at &thorn;ou apparaile &thorn;e &thorn;erto. and do it with grete deliberacion. [2537] ffor Tullius sai&thorn;; &para; That longe apparaylinge to-forn &thorn;e bataile; make&thorn; shorte victorie. [2538] And so Cassidorus sai&thorn;. &para; The garneson is strenger whan it is longe tyme avised.</P>
<P>[2539] But now lat vs speke more of &thorn;e counsaile. &thorn;at was accorded by &yogh;oure neighbours which as doon &yogh;ou reuerence wi&thorn;-out loue [2540] &yogh;oure olde enemyes recon|siled. &yogh;oure flaterers [2541] &thorn;at counsailden &yogh;ou cer|teyn &thorn;ingges prively. and openly counsailden &yogh;ou &thorn;e contrarie [2542] &para; The &yogh;onge folk also &thorn;at counsailed &yogh;ou to venge &yogh;ou / and make werre anoon [2543] &para; And certes sire as I haue saide byforn &yogh;e haue gretly erred to han cleped Such manere folk to &yogh;oure counsaile. [2544] which counsailours bene nowe repreued. by &thorn;e resons to-fore saide. [2545] But na&thorn;elees lat nowe descende to 
<PB REF="00000547.tif" N="517"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="226"> &thorn;e speciall. &para; &yogh;e shullen furst proceden aftere &thorn;e doctrine of Tullius [2546] &para; Certes &thorn;e trou&thorn;e of &thorn;is or &thorn;is counsaile nede&thorn; nat diligently enquere. [2547] for it is wel wist which &thorn;ei bene &thorn;at done to &yogh;ou &thorn;is trespace and vilanye [2548] and how mony trespasours. and in what manere &thorn;ei han to &yogh;ou done. All &thorn;is wronge and al &thorn;is vylanye [2549] And aftere &thorn;is &thorn;an shal &yogh;e examyne &thorn;e .ij. condicions whiche &thorn;at &thorn;e same Tullius adde&thorn; in &thorn;is matere. [2550] ffor Tullius put to a &thorn;inge. &thorn;e which he clepe&thorn; consentinge. &thorn;is is to sayn [2551] &para; Who ben &thorn;ei and which bene &thorn;ei. and how mony. &thorn;at consenten to &thorn;i counsaile in &thorn;i wilful|nesse to doo hastely &para; vengeaunce. [2552] And lat vs con|sidere also. Who bene &thorn;ei and howe mony &amp; which bene &thorn;ei &thorn;at consenten to &yogh;oure aduersaries. [2553] And certys as to &thorn;e <MILESTONE N="237a" UNIT="folio">furst poynt it is wel knowen which folk bene &thorn;ei &thorn;at consenten to &yogh;oure hastif wilful|nes. [2554] ffor trewly al &thorn;oo &thorn;at counsailden &yogh;ou to make sodeyn werre ne bene nat &yogh;oure frendes [2555] [<I>Or v&eacute;ons doncques qui tu es et qui sont ceulx que tu tiens tant &agrave; ennemis.</I>] as to &yogh;oure persone. [2556] ffor al be it soo &thorn;at &yogh;e bene myghty and riche. certes &yogh;e bene but alloon. [2557] for certes &yogh;e ne haue no childe but a dou&yogh;tere. [2558] ne &yogh;e ne haue no bre&thorn;eren ne Cosyns Germaynns ne noon o&thorn;er nygh kynrede./ [2559] wherfore &thorn;at &yogh;oure enemyes for drede shulden stent to plede with &yogh;owe ne destroye &yogh;oure persone [2560] &para; &YOGH;e knowe also &thorn;at &yogh;oure richesses mosten be dalt in diuers parties. [2561] and whan &thorn;at euery wi&yogh;t ha&thorn; his parte &thorn;ei ne wol not take but litel reward to venge &thorn;i deth. [2562] but &thorn;ine enemyes bene &THORN;re. And &thorn;ei han mony children. bre&thorn;eren Cosynes and o&thorn;er nygh kinrede. [2563] And &thorn;ou&yogh;e it so were &thorn;ow haddest sclayn of hem twoo or &thorn;ree. &yogh;it dwellen &thorn;er ynowe to wreke her deeth. and to slee &thorn;i persone [2564] And &thorn;ou&yogh;e so were &thorn;at &yogh;oure kynrede were more siker and stedfast &thorn;an 
<PB REF="00000548.tif" N="518"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="227"> &thorn;e kyn of &yogh;oure aduersaries. [2565] &yogh;it na&thorn;elees &yogh;oure kynrede nys but litel kynrede. and litel sibbe to &yogh;owe. [2566] And &thorn;e kynne of &yogh;oure enemyes ben nygh sibbe to hem. And certis as to &thorn;at. Her condicione is bett &thorn;at &yogh;owres. [2567] Than lat vs considere also. &yogh;if &thorn;e counsaillinge of hem &thorn;at counsailed &yogh;owe to take sodeyn vengeaunce whedere it accorde to reson. [2568] Certys &yogh;e knowe wel nay. [2569] ffor as by ri&yogh;t and reson &thorn;er may no man take vengeaunce on no wi&yogh;t but &thorn;e Iuge &thorn;at ha&thorn; &thorn;e Iurisdiction of it [2570] whan it is ygraunted hym to take &thorn;ilk vengeance hastely or at|temperally as &thorn;e lawe require&thorn;. [2571] And &yogh;it more|ouere of &thorn;ilk word &thorn;at Tullius clepe&thorn; consentynge. [2572] Thow shalt considere &yogh;it &thorn;ow my&yogh;t and &thorn;i power my&yogh;t consent and suffice to &thorn;i wilfulnesse and to &thorn;i counsailours. [2573] &para; And certes &thorn;ou maist wel say nay. [2574] for sikerly as forto speke proprely. we may do no &thorn;inge. but oonly &thorn;ing as we may done ri&yogh;tfully. [2575] And certes ri&yogh;tfully ne mowe &yogh;e take no vengeaunce as of &yogh;oure propre auctorite [2576] &thorn;an mowe &yogh;e sene &thorn;at &yogh;oure power consente&thorn; nat ne accorde&thorn; not to &yogh;oure wilfulnesse [2577] &para; lat vs nowe examyne &thorn;e iij poynt &thorn;at Tullius clepe&thorn; consequent [2578] [<I>Tu dois doncques savoir que &agrave; vengence que tu veulx faire, est cons&eacute;quent</I>] [2579] And &thorn;erof folowe&thorn; a-no&thorn;er vengeaunce perile and werre. and o&thorn;er damages wi&thorn;-out nombre of which we bene litel warre as at &thorn;is tyme./ [2580] &para; And as tou&thorn;ing &thorn;e fourte poynt &thorn;at Tullius clepe&thorn; en|gendringe [2581] &thorn;ou shalt considere &thorn;is wronge which &thorn;at is done to &thorn;e is engendred of &thorn;e hate of &thorn;ine enemyes [2582] and of &thorn;e <MILESTONE N="237b" UNIT="folio">vengeance takinge vpon &thorn;at wolde engendre ano&thorn;ere vengeaunce And mochel sorowe and waastinge of Richesse as I saide eerst.</P>
<P>[2583] &para; Now sire as &thorn;an touchinge to &thorn;e poynt. That Tullius causes which &thorn;at is &thorn;e last poynte [2584] &thorn;ou 
<PB REF="00000549.tif" N="519"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="228"> shalt vnderstonde &thorn;at &thorn;e wronge &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast receyued ha&thorn; certeyne causes. [2585] whiche &thorn;at clerkes clepen orience. And officience. And causa longinqua and causa propinqua. This is say &thorn;e fer cause and &thorn;e ny&yogh;e cause. [2586] The fer cause is almy&yogh;ty god &thorn;at is cause of al &thorn;ingges. [2587] The nere cause is by &thorn;re enemyes [2588] &para; The cause accidentale was hate. [2589] &thorn;e cause materiall be&thorn; .v. woundes of &thorn;i dou&yogh;tere [2590] The cause formal is &thorn;e maner of her worching &thorn;at brou&yogh;ten ladders and clomben Inne at &thorn;i wyndowes. [2591] The cause ffynal was. for to scle &thorn;i doughtere. It letted nou&yogh;t in as moch as in hem was / [2592] Than to speke of &thorn;e fer&thorn;e cause as to what ende &thorn;ei shal come or what shal fynaly bytide of hem in &thorn;is caas. ne can I not deme but by countyng and by supposinge [2593] &para; ffor we shul suppose. &thorn;at &thorn;ei shul come to a wikked ende. [2594] by cause &thorn;at &thorn;e booke of Decrees sei&thorn; &para; Seeldome or wi&thorn; grete peyne bene causes ybrou&yogh;t to good ende whan &thorn;ei bene bodely begonne.</P>
<P>[2595] &para; Now sire &yogh;if men wold aske me whi &thorn;at &yogh;e suffred men to doo &yogh;ou &thorn;is wronge and vilenye. Certes I can nat wel answere as for no so&thorn;fastnesse. [2596] ffor &thorn;e apostell sai&thorn;. &thorn;at &thorn;e sciences and &thorn;e Iugementes of our lord god almy&yogh;ty. bene ful depe. [2597] &thorn;er may no man conprehende ne Serchen hem suffisantly [2598] &para; Na&thorn;elees by certeyne presumpcions of coniectyngges I holde and bileue [2599] &thorn;at god which &thorn;at is ful of iustice. and of ri&yogh;twisnesse ha&thorn; suffred &thorn;is bitidde by Iustise &para; cause resonable</P>
<P>[2600] &para; Thi name is Melebye &para; This is to sayne a man &thorn;at drynke&thorn; hony. [2601] thow hast ydronke so moche hony of which swete temporell richesses / and delicious hon|oures of &thorn;is world [2602] &thorn;at &thorn;ou art dronken. and hast for&yogh;eten Ihesu crist &thorn;ine creature [2603] Thow ne hast not doon to hym such honoure and reuerence as &thorn;e au&yogh;t [2604] ne &thorn;ou ne hast nat wel taken kepe to 
<PB REF="00000550.tif" N="520"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="229"> &thorn;e wordes of O &para; Ovide &thorn;at sei&thorn;. [2605] Vndere &thorn;e hony of &thorn;e goddes of &thorn;i body. is hidde &thorn;e venyme &thorn;at sclee&thorn; &thorn;i soule [2606] &para; And Salomon sai&thorn;. &YOGH;if &thorn;ou hast found hony. eete of it &thorn;at suffise&thorn; the. [2607] ffor &yogh;if &thorn;ou ete of it out of mesure. &thorn;ou shalt spewe and be nedy and poore. [2608] and perauenture criste haue &thorn;e in despite. and ha&thorn; turned away from &thorn;e his face and his eeres of mysericord [2609] And also he ha&thorn; suffred &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast be <MILESTONE N="238a" UNIT="folio">punshed in &thorn;e manere &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast trespased. [2610] Thou hast doon synne a&yogh;einst our lord crist [2611] ffor certes iij. enemyes of man|kynde &thorn;at is to seyne &thorn;e flessh. &thorn;e feende. and &thorn;e worlde [2612] thowe hast suffred hem entred into &thorn;ine hous wilfully by &thorn;e wyndowe of &thorn;i body. [2613] And hast nat defended &thorn;i self sufficiently a&yogh;einst her assawtes and her temptacions so &thorn;at &thorn;ei han wounded &thorn;e saule in .v. places. [2614] &thorn;is is to sayn &thorn;e dedly synnes &thorn;at bene entred into &thorn;ine hert by &thorn;i .v. wyndowes [2615] and in &thorn;e same manere our lord crist ha&thorn; suffred and willed &thorn;at &thorn;ise iij. enemyes bene entred into &thorn;i hous by &thorn;i wyndowes [2616] and haue ywounded &thorn;i dou&yogh;tere in &thorn;e forsaide manre</P>
<P>[2617] &para; Certes quod Melebius I se wel &thorn;at &yogh;e en|force &yogh;ou moche by wordis to ouercome me in suche a manere &thorn;at I shal not venge me on myn enemyes. [2618] shewing me &thorn;e periles and &thorn;e eueles &thorn;at myghten falle of &thorn;is vengeaunce [2619] But who so wold considere in all vengeances &thorn;e periles and euels &thorn;at my&yogh;ten swe of vengeance takinge [2620] a mon wold neuere take vengeance and &thorn;at were harme [2621] ffor by &thorn;e venge|aunce takinge. bene &thorn;e wikked men disseuered from &thorn;e good men. [2622] And &thorn;ei &thorn;at han wille to do wikked|nesse restreynen her wikked purpoos whan they sene &thorn;e punshynge and chastising of trespasoures.</P>
<P>[2623] [And to this answered dame Prudence: 'Certes,' said she, 'I grant you that from vengeance come many 
<PB REF="00000551.tif" N="521"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="230"> advantages as well as many evils; [2624] yet vengeance be|longeth not to a "senglere persone," but only to the judges, and to those who have jurisdiction over evil-doers.'] [2625] And &yogh;it say I more &thorn;at as ri&yogh;t as so senglere persone synne&thorn; in takinge vengeaunce of a no&thorn;er man [2626] Ri&yogh;t so synne&thorn; &thorn;e Iuge &yogh;if he doo no vengeaunce on hem &thorn;at it haue deserued [2627] &para; ffor Senec sei&thorn; &thorn;us &para; &thorn;at maister he sai&thorn; is good &thorn;at repreue&thorn; shrewes [2628] &para; And as Cassiodorie sei&thorn;. A man drede&thorn; to do outrage whan he woote and knowe&thorn; &thorn;at it displese&thorn; to &thorn;e Iugges and &thorn;e souereyns. [2629] And ano&thorn;er sei&thorn; &para; The Iuge &thorn;at drede&thorn; to do ri&yogh;t. make&thorn; men schrewes [2630] &para; And seint Paule &thorn;e appostel sei&thorn; in his epistel whan he write&thorn; to &thorn;e Romayns &THORN;at &thorn;e Iuge berent not &thorn;e spere wi&thorn;-outen cause. [2631] but &thorn;ei beren it to punshe &thorn;e schrewes and mysdoers and forto defende &thorn;e good men. [2632] &yogh;if &yogh;e wil &thorn;an take vengeance of &yogh;oure enemyes &yogh;e shal retourne or haue &yogh;oure recours to &thorn;e Iuge &thorn;at ha&thorn; &thorn;e Iurisdiction vpon him [2633] and he shal punsshe hem as &thorn;e lawe aske&thorn; and requere&thorn;</P>
<P>[2634] &para; A quod Melebies &thorn;is vengeance like&thorn; me no &thorn;inge [2635] I by-&thorn;enk me nowe and take hede. howe fortune ha&thorn; norsshed me fro my childhode. and ha&thorn; hulpen me to passe mony a stronge paas [2636] &para; Now wil I assaien her trowinge wi&thorn; goddes helpe &thorn;at he shal helpe me my shame forto <MILESTONE N="238b" UNIT="folio">venge</P>
<P>[2637] &para; Certes quod Prudence &yogh;if &yogh;e wil wirk by my counsaill &yogh;e shul not assaien fortune by no way [2638] ne &yogh;e shul not lene ne bowe vnto hire. after &thorn;e wordes of Senec. [2639] ffor &thorn;ingges &thorn;at bene folily done. and &thorn;at bene in hope of fortune shullen neuere come to good eende. [2640] &para; And as &thorn;e same senc sai&thorn; . &thorn;e more clere and &thorn;e more shynynge &thorn;at fortune is. &thorn;e more brotel and &thorn;e sonner breke&thorn; she. [2641] treste&thorn; not on her for she nys nat stedfast. [2642] ffor whan &thorn;owe wenest or trowest to be more swre or siker of her 
<PB REF="00000552.tif" N="522"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="231"> helpe. she wil faile &thorn;ee. [2643] &para; And &thorn;er as &yogh;e sayn &thorn;at fortune ha&thorn; norsshed &yogh;ou from &yogh;oure child|hode. [2644] I say &thorn;at in so mochel shal &yogh;e &thorn;e lasse trest in her. and in her witt [2645] &para; ffor Senec sai&thorn;. what man &thorn;at is norsshed by fortune; she make&thorn; him to grete a foole [2646] &para; Now &thorn;an si&thorn; &yogh;e desire and aske vengeaunce. and &thorn;e vengeance &thorn;at is done [<I>selon l'ordre de droit et devant le juge ne te plaist</I>, [2647] <I>et la vengence qui se fait</I>] in hope of fortune is peril|ous and vncerteyn. [2648] &thorn;en haue noon o&thorn;er remedy. but forto haue &yogh;oure cours vnto &thorn;e souereyn Iuge &thorn;an venge&thorn; all vilanyes and wrongges. [2649] and he shal venge &yogh;ou. After hym self witnesse&thorn;; where as he sai&thorn; [2650] &para; leue&thorn; &thorn;e vengeance to me./ &amp; I shal doo it</P>
<P>[2651] &para; Melebius answered. &YOGH;if I ne venge me no&yogh;t of &thorn;e vilanye &thorn;at men han done to me. [2652] I shal somne or warne hem &thorn;at han do to me &thorn;oo vilanyes and al o&thorn;er to doo me ano&thorn;er vilanye. [2653] &para; ffor it is writen. &yogh;if &thorn;ou take no vengeaunce of an olde vilanye / &thorn;ow somn|est &thorn;ine aduersaries to doo an newe vilanye. [2654] And also for my suffraunce men wolden doo me so moche vilanye &thorn;at I my&yogh;t nei&thorn;er bere it ne sus|teyne it. [2655] And so &thorn;an I shulde be kept ouer lawe [2656] &para; ffor men sayn In mochel suffringe shul mony &thorn;ingges vnto &thorn;e which &thorn;ow shalt not mow suffre</P>
<P>[2657] &para; Certes quod prudence I graunte &yogh;ow &thorn;at ouer mochel suffraunce is not good [2658] But &yogh;it ne folowe&thorn; it not &thorn;er-of. That euery persone to whome men doo vilany take of it vengeaunce. [2659] ffor &thorn;at apper|tene&thorn; &amp; longe&thorn; oonly to the Iuges. ffor &thorn;ei shul venge vilanyes and Iniuries. [2660] And herfore &thorn;oo two autoritees &thorn;at &yogh;e han saide aboue ben oonly vnderstonden in &thorn;e Iuges [2661] for whan &thorn;ei suffre ouer &para; mykel &thorn;e wrongges and vilenyes to be done 
<PB REF="00000553.tif" N="523"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="232"> wi&thorn;-out ponshinge. [2662] &thorn;ei sommone nat a man al only forto doo newe wrongges but &thorn;ei commaunden it [2663] &para; Also a wise man sei&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e Iuge &thorn;at cor|recte&thorn; not &thorn;e synner. Commaunde&thorn; and bidde&thorn; hym to synne [2664] and &thorn;e Iuges and <MILESTONE N="239a" UNIT="folio">souereynes my&yogh;ten in her londe so moche suffre of &thorn;e Shrewes and mysdoers [2665] &thorn;at &thorn;ei shulden bye such suffraunce by processe of tyme wexen of such power and my&yogh;t. &thorn;at &thorn;ei shuld putte out &thorn;e Iuges and souereynes from her places. [2666] and at &thorn;e last do hem lose her lordshippes</P>
<P>[2667] &para; I put caas ri&yogh;t nowe &yogh;e had leue to venge &yogh;ou. [2668] I say &thorn;at &yogh;e ben nou&yogh;t of myght ne power as nowe to venge &yogh;ou. [2669] ffor &yogh;if we wil make comparison vnto &thorn;e my&yogh;t of &yogh;our aduersaries. &yogh;e shul fynde in many &thorn;ingges &thorn;at I haue shewed &yogh;o<SUP>u</SUP> er &thorn;is &thorn;at her condicion is better &thorn;an &yogh;oure. [2670] And &thorn;erfore say I &thorn;at it is good as nowe &thorn;at &yogh;e suffre and be pacient</P>
<P>[2671] &para; ffer&thorn;er more &yogh;e knowen wel &thorn;at after &thorn;e comon Sawe it is a woodenesse a man to stryue wi&thorn; a strenger. or wi&thorn; a more my&yogh;ty man &thorn;an hym self. [2672] And forto stryue wi&thorn; a man of euen strength &thorn;at is to say wi&thorn; as stronge a man as he is it is perile. [2673] And forto stryue wi&thorn; a waikere man it is foly [2674] And &thorn;erfore shuld a man flee stryuynge as mochel as he my&yogh;t [2675] &para; ffor Salomon sai&thorn;. It is a grete worship a man to kepe hym from noyse and stryf. [2676] And &yogh;if it so byfalle or happe &thorn;at a man of gretter my&yogh;t and strenger &thorn;an &thorn;ou art do &thorn;e greuaunce. [2677] stody and byse &thorn;e ra&thorn;er to stille &thorn;e same greuaunce &thorn;an forto venge &thorn;e [2678] &para; ffor Senec sai&thorn; That he putte&thorn; hym in grete perile. &thorn;at stryue&thorn; wi&thorn; a gretter man &thorn;an he is him self [2679] And Caton sai&thorn;. &YOGH;if a man of hier astate or of degre or more my&yogh;ty &thorn;an &thorn;ou. do &thorn;e an o&thorn;er greuaunce suffre hym [2680] for he &thorn;at onys ha&thorn; greued &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000554.tif" N="524"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="233"> may ano&thorn;er tyme releue &thorn;e. and helpe &thorn;e. [2681] &yogh;it sette I caas &yogh;e haue bo&thorn; my&yogh;t and licence forto venge &yogh;ou. [2682] I saie &thorn;at &thorn;er bene ful mony &thorn;ingges &thorn;at shuld restreyn &yogh;ou of vengeance takinge [2683] and make &yogh;ou forto enclyne to suffre and for|to haue pacience in &thorn;e wrongges &thorn;at bene done to &yogh;ou. [2684] ffurst and forward &yogh;if &yogh;e wil considere &thorn;e defautes &thorn;at bene in &yogh;oure persone. [2685] for which defautes god ha&thorn; suffred &yogh;ou to haue tribulacion as I haue saide byfore [2686] &para; ffor &thorn;e Poete sai&thorn;. &thorn;at we ou&yogh;ten paciently &thorn;e tribulacions to take &thorn;at commen to vs whan &thorn;at we &thorn;enken and consideren &thorn;at we han deserued to haue hem [2687] &para; And seint Gregor sei&thorn;. That whan a man considere&thorn; wel &thorn;e nombre of his defautes and of his synnes [2688] &thorn;an peynes and &thorn;e tribulacions &thorn;at he suffre&thorn; semen &thorn;e lasse vnto him [2689] And in as moche as him &thorn;enk|e&thorn; his synnes more hevie and greuous [2690] in so moche his peyne is &thorn;e li&yogh;ter / and &thorn;e <MILESTONE N="239b" UNIT="folio">esier vnto hym [2691] &para; Also &yogh;e owen to enclyne and bowe &yogh;oure herte to take &thorn;e pacience of our lorde Ihesu crist. As sei&thorn; seint Petre in his epistell [2692] Ihesu crist he sei&thorn; ha&thorn; suffred for vs and &yogh;euen ensample to euery man to folowe and to swee hym [2693] for he did neuere &para; synne ne neuere cam a vileyns worde out of his mou&thorn;e [2694] whan men cursed hym he cursed hem nou&yogh;t . . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> [2695] Also &thorn;e grete pacience &para; whiche &thorn;at seintes &thorn;at bene in paradis han had in tribulacions &thorn;at &thorn;ei han suffred wi&thorn;-outen her desert or gilt. [2696] aught moch stire &yogh;ou to pacience [2697] &para; ffer&thorn;er|more &yogh;e shal conforte &yogh;ou to haue pacience [2698] consideringe &thorn;at &thorn;e tribulaci&omacr;ns of &thorn;is worlde. but litel &para; while enduren. and soon bene ypassed and goon [2699] And &thorn;e Ioye &thorn;at a man seche&thorn; to haue by pacience in tribulacions is perdurable. after &thorn;at &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000555.tif" N="525"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="234"> appostel sei&thorn;. in his Epistel [2700] &para; The Ioie of god he sei&thorn; is perdurable. &thorn;at is to saye euerlastinge. [2701] Also troue&thorn; and bileue&thorn; stedfastly &thorn;at he nys nat wel norsshed ne wel ytau&yogh;t &thorn;at cannot haue pacience ne wil not receyue pacience [2702] &para; ffor Salomon sei&thorn;. That &thorn;e doctrine and &thorn;e witte of man is knowe by pacience. [2703] And in ano&thorn;ere place he sei&thorn;. &thorn;at he &thorn;at kepe&thorn; hym by pacience &para; gouerne&thorn; him by grete prudence [2704] &para; And &thorn;e Same Salomon sei&thorn; The angre and &thorn;e wrethful man make&thorn; noyses. and &thorn;e pacient man attempre&thorn; and stille&thorn; him self [2705] &para; he sai&thorn; also it is more worth to be pacient &thorn;an for to be ri&yogh;t stronge. [2706] And he &thorn;at may haue lordship of his owne hert is more to preise &thorn;an he &thorn;at by his fors take&thorn; grete Citees and townes [2707] Therfore sei&thorn; seint Iame in his Epistell. &thorn;at pacience in a grete vertue of perfection.</P>
<P>[2708] [<I>Certes, dit Mellib&eacute;e, je vous ottroye, dame Prudence, que patience est une grant vertu</I>,] [2709] But euery man may nat haue &thorn;e perfection &thorn;at we seken. [2710] ne I. am not of &thorn;e nombre of ri&yogh;t per|fit men. [2711] for myn hert may neuer be in pees; vnto &thorn;e tyme it be venged [2712] &para; And al be it so &thorn;at it was grete perile to myne &para; ennemyes to done me a vilanye in takinge vengeance vpon me. [2713] &yogh;it token &thorn;ei noon hede vppon &thorn;e perile. but fulfilleden her wik&para;ked wille and her corage [2714] And &thorn;er-for me &thorn;enke&thorn; men ou&yogh;t not repreue me &thorn;ou&yogh;e I putte me in a litel perile to venge me. [2715] and &thorn;ou&yogh;e I doo a grete excesse. &thorn;at is to say &thorn;ou&yogh;e I venge oon outrage by a no&thorn;ere</P>
<P>[2716] &para; O quod dame prudence &yogh;e say &yogh;oure wille. and as &yogh;ou like&thorn;. [2717] But in no caas of &thorn;e world a man shuld not do outrage ne excesse forto venge hym [2718] &para; ffor Cassidore sei&thorn; &thorn;at as euel do&thorn; he &thorn;at auenge&thorn; him by outrage. as he &thorn;at do&thorn; &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000556.tif" N="526"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="235"> outrage. [2719] And &thorn;er-for &yogh;e shul venge &yogh;ou after &thorn;e ordere of ry&yogh;t &thorn;at is to sain <MILESTONE N="240a" UNIT="folio">by &thorn;e lawe and by noon excesse ne noon outrage. [2720] And also if &yogh;e wil venge &yogh;ou of &thorn;e outrage of &yogh;oure aduersaries in o&thorn;er manere &thorn;an ri&yogh;t comaunde&thorn; &yogh;e synnen [2721] &para; And &thorn;erfore sai&thorn; Senec. &thorn;at a man shal neuere venge schrewdenesse by schrewdenesse / [2722] And if &yogh;e say &thorn;at ri&yogh;t axe&thorn; a man to defende violence by violence. and fi&yogh;tynge by fi&yogh;tinge. [2723] certes &yogh;e say soth. whan &thorn;e defence is done anoon with-outen interualle or wi&thorn;-out taryinge or delay. [2724] for to defenden hym and not forto vengen hym. [2725] And it bihoue&thorn; &thorn;at a man put such attemperance in his defence [2726] &thorn;at men haue no cause no matere to repreuen hym &thorn;at defende&thorn; hym of excesse and of outrage. [<I>car autrement ce seroit contre droit et contre raison</I> (Le M&eacute;n.)] [2727] &para; Parde &yogh;e knowen well &thorn;at &yogh;e maken noon defence as nowe forto defende &yogh;ou but forto venge &yogh;ou [2728] And so swe&thorn; it &thorn;at &yogh;e han no wille to doo &yogh;oure dede attemperally. [2729] and &thorn;erfore me &thorn;enke&thorn; &thorn;at pacience is goode &para; ffor Salomon sei&thorn;; &thorn;at he &thorn;at is nat pacient shal haue grete harme</P>
<P>[2730] &para; Certes quod meleby I graunte &yogh;ou &thorn;at whan a man is impacient and wroo&thorn; of &thorn;at &thorn;at touche&thorn; hym nat and of &thorn;at &thorn;at pertene&thorn; not to hym. &thorn;ou&yogh;e it harme him it is no wondere [2731] &para; ffor &thorn;e lawe sai&thorn;. &thorn;at he is coupable. &thorn;at entermete&thorn; hym or melle&thorn; hym wi&thorn; suche &thorn;inge as apperteyne&thorn; nat to hym [2732] &para; And Salomon sai&thorn;. That he &thorn;at entermete&thorn; hym of &thorn;e noise or of &thorn;e strif of an o&thorn;er man is like to hym. &thorn;at take&thorn; &thorn;e hounde by &thorn;e eeres [2733] and [<I>aussi comme cellui qui prent le chien par les oreilles</I>] is o&thorn;er while biten wi&thorn; &thorn;e hounde. [2734] &para; Ri&yogh;t in &thorn;e same wise is it reson &thorn;at he haue harme &thorn;at by his impacience medle&thorn; him of &thorn;e noise of an o&thorn;er man. wher &thorn;at it appertene&thorn; not to him [2735] &para; But &yogh;e knowe wel &thorn;at &thorn;is dede and 
<PB REF="00000557.tif" N="527"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="236"> &thorn;is greef and &thorn;is dissese touche&thorn; me ri&yogh;t nygh. [2736] And &thorn;erfore &thorn;ou&yogh;e I be wro&thorn;e and im|pacient it is no mervaile. [2737] and sauynge &yogh;oure grace I can not see &thorn;at it my&yogh;t gretlich harme me. &thorn;ou&yogh;e I toke vengeance [2738] ffor I am Riccher and more my&yogh;ty &thorn;an myn enemyes bene. [2739] And wel knowen &yogh;ee &thorn;at by money and by hauyng grete posses|sions bene all &thorn;ingges of &thorn;is world ygouerned [2740] &para; And Salomon sei&thorn;. &thorn;at all &thorn;ingges obeyen to monay.</P>
<P>[2741] [<I>Prudence, quant elle oy son mary vanter de sa richesse et de sa puissance, et soy esjouir, et</I>] dispreis|ing &thorn;e poor of his aduersaries. Tho she spak and seide in &thorn;is wise. [2742] Certes dere sire I graunt &yogh;ou &thorn;at &yogh;e bene riche and my&yogh;ty. [2743] and &thorn;at richesses ben good to hem &thorn;at han wel goten hem. and &thorn;at wel can vsen hem [2744] ffor ri&yogh;t as &thorn;e body of a man; may not lyue wi&thorn;-out &thorn;e saule. no more may it live wi&thorn;-out temporal goodes. [2745] And by rich|esse may a <MILESTONE N="240b" UNIT="folio">man gete hym grete worship [2746] &para; And &thorn;erfore sei&thorn; Pamphilles. &yogh;if an neterdes dou&yogh;tere he sai&thorn; be riche she may chese of a thowsand men [<I>lequel qu'elle veult pour son mary</I> [2747] <I>car</I> (Le M&eacute;nagier, tome i)] . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> oon wil not forsake her ne refuse her. [2748] And &thorn;us Pamphilles seith also &para; &yogh;if &thorn;ou be ri&yogh;t happy &thorn;at is to say ri&yogh;t riche &thorn;ow shalt fynde a grete nombre of felawes and frendes. [2749] And &yogh;if &thorn;i fortune that &thorn;ou wexe poor. fare wel frendship and felawship. [2750] for &thorn;ou shalt bene allone wi&thorn;-oute eny companye. but &yogh;if it be &thorn;e company of poor folk [2751] // And &yogh;it sei&thorn; &thorn;is Pamphilles more ouer &thorn;at &thorn;ei &thorn;at bene thral and bonde of lynage. shullen be made wor&thorn;i and noble by richessesse [2752] And ri&yogh;t so as by richesses &thorn;er commen mony goodes. Ri&yogh;t so by pouert &thorn;er commen mony harmes and euels. [2753] ffor grete pouerte con|streyneth 
<PB REF="00000558.tif" N="528"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="237"> a man to doo mony euels [2754] &para; And &thorn;er|fore clepe&thorn; Cassidore pouert. &thorn;e modere ruyne. [2755] That is to say &thorn;e modere of ouer&thorn;rowinge or falling downe [2756] &para; And &thorn;erfore Pers Alfons sai&thorn;. Oon of &thorn;e grettest aduersitees of &thorn;is world is [2757] whan a free [man] by kinde is constreyned by pouert to eten &thorn;e almesse of his enemye [2758] &para; And &thorn;e Same Sei&thorn; Innocent in oon of his bokes. He sei&thorn; &thorn;at soriful and vnhappy is &thorn;e condition of a poor begger. [2759] ffor &yogh;if he aske&thorn; not his mete he dye&thorn; for hungere. [2760] [<I>et se ils demandent, ils meurent de honte;</I>] Necessite constreyne&thorn; hym to aske. [2761] And &thorn;erfore sei&thorn; Salomon. That better is to dye &thorn;an forto haue suche pouerte [2762] &para; And as &thorn;e Same Salo|mon sei&thorn; Better is to dye a bitter dee&thorn; &thorn;an forto lyuen in swich wise [2763] &para; By &thorn;ise resons &thorn;at .I haue seide vnto &yogh;owe and by mony resons &thorn;at I coude saie [2764] I graunte &thorn;at richesses bene good to hem &thorn;at geten hem well And vsen hem wel. [2765] And &thorn;erfore wil I shewe &yogh;ow how &yogh;e shul haue &yogh;ou. and howe &yogh;e shal bere &yogh;ou in gaderinge of richesses. and in what manere &yogh;e shul vsen hem</P>
<P>[2766] ffirst &yogh;e shul geten hem with-out grete desire. by good leisere sokingly. and not ouerhastely. [2767] ffor a man &thorn;at is to desiringe to geten richesse. abandone&thorn; hym to &thorn;eft and to all o&thorn;er evels [2768] &para; And &thorn;erfore sei&thorn; Salomon &para; he &thorn;at haste&thorn; hym to bysily to wexe ricche; shal be noon Innocent [2769] &para; He sai&thorn; also &thorn;at &thorn;e Richesse &thorn;at hastely comme&thorn; to a man. sone and li&yogh;tly goo&thorn; and passe&thorn; from hym [2770] &para; But &thorn;at richesse &thorn;at comme&thorn; alway litel and litel. wexe&thorn; alway and multiplie&thorn; [2771] &para; And sire &yogh;e shul gete richesse by &yogh;oure witte. and by &yogh;oure travaile. vnto &yogh;oure profite [2772] and &thorn;at wi&thorn;-outen wronge or harme doynge to eny o&thorn;ere persone. [2773] ffor &thorn;e lawe 
<PB REF="00000559.tif" N="529"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="238"> sei&thorn; &para; That he ne make&thorn; nat hym self riche. &yogh;if he do harme to a no&thorn;er wight [2774] &para; This is to say &thorn;at nature defende&thorn; and forbede&thorn; by ryght. &thorn;at <MILESTONE N="241a" UNIT="folio">no man make him self riche wi&thorn; &thorn;e harme of a no&thorn;ere person. [2775] &para; And Tullius sai&thorn;. &thorn;at no sorowe ne no drede of deth ne of &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at may falle to a man [2776] is so mochel a&yogh;einst nature as a man to encrees his owne profite to &thorn;e harme of ano&thorn;er man [2777] &para; And &thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;e grete men and &thorn;e riche men geten rychesses more li&yogh;tly &thorn;an &thorn;ou. [2778] &yogh;it shalt &thorn;ou nat be ydel ne sclowe to &thorn;i prophete. ffor &thorn;ou shalt in al &thorn;inge and in al wise fle ydelnesse [2779] &para; ffor Salomon sei&thorn;; That ydelnesse teche&thorn; a man to do mony eueles [2780] &para; And &thorn;e Same Salomon sei&thorn;. &thorn;at he &thorn;at travaille&thorn; and bysie&thorn; him to tille his londe shal ete &thorn;e brede. [2781] But he &thorn;at is ydel and caste&thorn; him to doo no bysynesse ne occupacion shal falle into pouert and dye for hungere. [2782] And he &thorn;at is ydel and sclowe. can neuer fynde conable tyme forto do his profite [2783] &para; ffor &thorn;er is a versifiour &thorn;at sai&thorn;. That &thorn;e ydel man excuse&thorn; hym in wyntere. be cause of &thorn;e grete colde. And in somer by encheson of &thorn;e grete hete [2784] &para; ffor &thorn;ise causes sei&thorn; Caton &para; Wake&thorn; and enclyne&thorn; &yogh;ou not ouermoche forto sclepe. for ouer moche rest norsshe&thorn; and cause&thorn; mony vyces [2785] &para; And &thorn;erfore sei&thorn; seint Ierom &para; Do&thorn; somme good dedys &thorn;at &thorn;e deuel which is oure enemye ne fynde &yogh;ou nat vnocupied. [2786] ffor &thorn;e deuel ne take&thorn; not li&yogh;tly vnto