<P>[2787] &para; Than &thorn;us in geting of Richesse &yogh;e moten flee ydelnesse / [2788] &para; and afterward &yogh;e shul vse &thorn;e richesse which &yogh;e han geten by &yogh;oure witte and by &yogh;oure travaile [2789] in such a manere &thorn;at men holde &yogh;ou nat to scarce. ne to sparinge. ne to fool large. &thorn;at is to sayn ouer large a spendere [2790] &para; ffor ri&yogh;t as men blamen an Auarous man by cause of his scarsete and chyncherie [2791] In &thorn;e same manere is he blamed 
<PB REF="00000560.tif" N="530"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="239"> &thorn;at spende&thorn; ouer largely. [2792] &para; And &thorn;erfore sei&thorn; Caton. vse he sai&thorn; &thorn;e Richesse &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast ygeten. [2793] in such a manere. &thorn;at &thorn;er be no matere ne cause to calle &thorn;e nei&thorn;er wrecche ne chynche. [2794] ffor it is grete shame a man to haue a poor hert and a rich purs [2795] &para; He sei&thorn; also &thorn;e goodes &thorn;at thow hast geten vse hem by mesure &thorn;at is to say. spende mesurably [2796] ffor &thorn;ei &thorn;at folyly waasten and dispenden &thorn;e goodes &thorn;at &thorn;ei haue. [2797] whan &thorn;ei han no more propre of her owne &thorn;ei shape hem to take &thorn;e goodes of a no&thorn;er man. [2798] &para; I say &thorn;an &thorn;at &yogh;e shal flee Auarice / [2799] vsinge &yogh;oure richesse as in such manere &thorn;at men say not &thorn;at &yogh;oure goodes bene yburied. [2800] but &thorn;at &yogh;e <MILESTONE N="241b" UNIT="folio">haue hem in &yogh;oure myght and in &yogh;oure weldinge [2801] ffor &thorn;e wise repreeue&thorn; &thorn;e Auerous man and sei&thorn; in twoo versus. [2802] Wherto and whi bere&thorn; a man his goodes by his Auarice and knowe&thorn; wel &thorn;at nedes he most deye. [2803] for de&thorn; is &thorn;e ende of euery man as in &thorn;is present lif [2804] and for what cause or encheson ioyne&thorn; he him or knytte&thorn; he hym so fast vnto his goodes [2805] &thorn;at all his wittes mowe not disseuere hym or departen hym fro his goodes. [2806] and knowe&thorn; wel or aught knowe &thorn;at whan he is dede he shal no &thorn;inge bere wi&thorn; him out of &thorn;is world [2807] &para; And &thorn;erfore sei&thorn; seynt Austyne. That &thorn;e Auerous man is likned into helle. [2808] &thorn;at &thorn;e more it swolowe&thorn;. &thorn;e more desire it ha&thorn; to swalowe and deuowre [2809] And as wel as &yogh;e wolde eschwe to be cleped an Auarous man or chynche [2810] as wel shul &yogh;e kepe &yogh;ou and gouerne &yogh;ou so and in such a wise so &thorn;at men ne cleped &yogh;ou not fool large [2811] &para; Therfore sei&thorn; Tullius The goodes he sei&thorn; of &thorn;ine hous shuld nat bene hidde ne kept so cloos but &thorn;at &thorn;ei my&yogh;t be opned by Pite and by bonairte [2812] &thorn;at is to sayn to &yogh;eue hem parte &thorn;at han grete nede [2813] 
<PB REF="00000561.tif" N="531"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="240"> Ne &thorn;i goodes shuld not bene so open to be euery mannys goodes [2814] &para; Afterward in getinge of &yogh;oure richesse &amp; in vsyng of hem &yogh;e shul alway haue &thorn;re &thorn;ingges in &yogh;oure hert. [2815] &thorn;at is to sayn. our lorde god. conscience and good name [2816] &para; ffirst &yogh;e shul haue god in &yogh;oure hert [2817] and for no ricchesse &yogh;e shul doo no &thorn;inge which may in eny manere displese crist &thorn;at is youre creatour and &yogh;our maker [2818] &para; ffor after &thorn;e worde of Salomon. it is better to haue a litel good with &thorn;e loue of god [2819] &thorn;an to haue moche good and tresour and lese &thorn;e loue of his lorde god [2820] &para; And &thorn;e prophet sei&thorn;. &thorn;at better it is to bene a good man. and haue a litel good and tresour. [2821] &thorn;an to be holden a shrewe and haue grete Ricchesse. [2822] And &yogh;it say I fer&thorn;ermore &thorn;at &yogh;e shulden alway doon &yogh;our bisynesse to gete &yogh;ou richesses [2823] so &thorn;at &yogh;e gete hem wi&thorn; good conscience [2824] &para; And &thorn;e Appostel sai&thorn;. Ther nys no &thorn;inge in this world of which we shuld haue so grete Ioye as whan our conscience bere&thorn; vs witnesse of good [2825] &para; And &thorn;e wise man sai&thorn;. The substance of a man is ful good whan synne nys nat in his coscience [2826] &para; Afterward in getinge of &yogh;oure richesses / and in vsing of hem [2827] &thorn;e most haue grete bysynesse and grete diligence &thorn;at &yogh;oure <MILESTONE N="242a" UNIT="folio">good name be alway kept and conserued [2828] &para; ffor Salo|mon sei&thorn; That better it is and more availle&thorn; a man to haue good name &thorn;an to haue grete richesse [2829] &para; And &thorn;erfore he sai&thorn; in a no&thorn;er place Doo grete diligence sei&thorn; Salomon in kepinge of &thorn;i frend and of &thorn;i good name. [2830] ffor it shal lenger abide wi&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;an eny tresour be it neuere so precious. [2831] And certes he shuld not be cleped a gentil man. &thorn;at after god and good conscience all &thorn;ingges left ne do&thorn; his dyligence and bysynesse to kepen his good name [2832] &para; And Cassidore sai&thorn;; &thorn;at it is signe of a gentill hert whan a man desire&thorn; and loue&thorn; to haue a goode name./ 
