<P>[2996] &para; And ri&yogh;t anoon &thorn;ei token her way to &thorn;e courte of Meleby [2997] and token to hem some of her trewe frendys to make fei&thorn; for hem and forto bene her borowes [2998] &para; And whan &thorn;ei were commen to 
<PB REF="00000570.tif" N="540"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="249"> &thorn;e presence of melebius he seide hem &thorn;ise wordes [2999] It stonde&thorn; &thorn;us quod Melebie and so&thorn; it is &thorn;at &yogh;e [3000] causelees and wi&thorn;-out skille and reson [3001] haue done grete iniuries and wronges to me and to my wiff Prudence And to my &para; dou&yogh;tere also. [3002] ffor &yogh;e han entred into myn hous by violence [3003] and haue done such outrage &thorn;at alle men knowe wel &thorn;at &yogh;e han deserued &thorn;e dee&thorn; [3004] And &thorn;erfore wil I knowe and witt of &yogh;ou [3005] whe&thorn;ere &yogh;e putte &thorn;e punsshment and &thorn;e chastisement and &thorn;e vengeaunce of &thorn;is outrage in &thorn;e will of me and of my wif Dame Prudence or &yogh;e wil not</P>
<P>[3006] Than &thorn;e wisest of hem &thorn;re answerd for hem alle and seide [3007] &para; Sire quod he we knowe wel &thorn;at we bene vnwor&thorn;i to come vnto &thorn;e Suerte vnto so grete [a lord] and so wor&thorn;i as &yogh;e bene. [3008] ffor we han so gretely mystaken vs and haue offended and gilted in such a wise. ageyn &yogh;oure hegh lordship. [3009] &thorn;at trewly we han deserued &thorn;e dee&thorn;. [3010] But &yogh;it for &thorn;e grete goodnesse and debonairte &thorn;at all men don witnesse of &yogh;oure persone / [3011] We submytten vs to &yogh;our excellence and benygnyte of &yogh;oure gracious lordship. [3012] for we bene redy to obey to all &yogh;oure comaundementes [3013] bysekinge &yogh;ou &thorn;at of &yogh;oure merciable pite &yogh;e wil considere our grete repentaunce and lowe submyssion [3014] and graunt us for&yogh;euenesse of oure outrageous trespas and offence. [3015] ffor wel we knowen &thorn;at &yogh;oure liberall grace and mercie strecche&thorn; for&thorn;ere into good|nesse &thorn;an do&thorn; our outrageous trespas into wikked|nesse. [3016] <MILESTONE N="245b" UNIT="folio">al be it &thorn;at cursedly and damp|nably we han ygilt a&yogh;einst &yogh;oure grete lordship</P>
<P>[3017] &para; Than Melebye toke hem vp fro &thorn;e grounde ful benygnely [3018] and receyued her oblacions and her londes by her o&thorn;es vpon her plegges and borowes. [3019] And assigned hem a certeyn day to retourne vnto his courte [3020] forto accepte and to receyue &thorn;e sentence and 
<PB REF="00000571.tif" N="541"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="250"> Iuggement of &thorn;at Melebye wil comaunde to be done to hem by &thorn;ise causes to-fore seide. [3021] which &thorn;ingges ordeyned / euery man &middot; retourned home to his hous</P>
<P>[3022] &para; And whan &thorn;at Dame Prudence segh her tyme. she f[r]ayned and asked her lorde [3023] what vengeaunce he &thorn;ou&yogh;t to take on his aduersaries</P>
<P>[3024] To which Melebius answerd and saide. Certys quod I I thenk and purpoos me fully [3025] to dis|herite hem and al &thorn;at euere &thorn;ei haue and forto putte hem in exile for euere moo</P>
<P>[3026] &para; Certis quod dame Prudence &thorn;is were a cruel sentence and mochel a&yogh;einst reson. [3027] ffor &yogh;e bene riche ynou&yogh;e and haue no nede of o&thorn;er mennys good / [3028] and &yogh;e my&yogh;ten lightely gete &yogh;ou a coueitous name [3029] Whiche is a vicious &thorn;inge and ou&yogh;te to bene eschewed of euery man [3030] &para; ffor aftere &thorn;e sawe of &thorn;e word of &thorn;e apostel Coueityse is roote of alle harmes [3031] And &thorn;erfore it were better to &yogh;ou to lese so mochel good of &yogh;oure owne. &thorn;an forto take of her good in &thorn;is manere. [3032] ffor bettere it is to lese good with Worship &thorn;an it is to wynne good wi&thorn; vileny and shame./ [3033] And euery man ou&yogh;t to doo his diligence of his bysynesse to geten hym a good name. [3034] And &yogh;it shal he not oonly bysyen him in kepinge his good name [3035] But he shal also enforsen him alway to doon somme &thorn;inge by which he may renouelle his good name [3036] &para; ffor it is written &para; The olde good lose or good name of a man &middot; is sone done or goon or passed whan it is not newed ne re|nouelled [3037] And as touching &thorn;at &yogh;e sayn &yogh;e wil exile &yogh;oure aduersaries [3038] &thorn;at &thorn;enke&thorn; me moch a&yogh;einst reson. and out of mesure [3039] con|sidered. &thorn;e power &thorn;at &thorn;ei han &yogh;euen &yogh;ou vpon hem self [3040] &para; And it is writen &para; that he is wor&thorn;i to lesen his privelegge &thorn;at mysvse&thorn; &thorn;e my&yogh;t and &thorn;e power &thorn;at is &yogh;euen hym [3041] And I sette caas &yogh;e my&yogh;t enioyne hem &thorn;at peyne by ri&yogh;t and lawe [3042] which I 
<PB REF="00000572.tif" N="542"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="251"> trowe &yogh;e mowe not doo [3043] I say &yogh;e my&yogh;t not put it to execucion perauenture / [3044] and &thorn;an were it likly to retourne to &thorn;e werre as it was byforne [3045] And &thorn;erfore &yogh;if &yogh;e &thorn;an wol &thorn;at men don <MILESTONE N="246a" UNIT="folio">&yogh;ou obeis|aunce &yogh;e most deme more curtaisly [3046] This is to sayn &yogh;e most &yogh;eue more esy sentences and Iuggementys. [3047] ffor it is writen &thorn;at he &thorn;at most curteisly comaunde&thorn; to hym men most obeyen [3048] &para; And &thorn;er|fore I prey &yogh;ou &thorn;at in &thorn;is necessite and in &thorn;is nede &yogh;e cast &yogh;ou to oouercome &yogh;oure hert. [3049] ffor Senec sai&thorn;. He &thorn;at ouercomme&thorn; his hert ouercomme&thorn; twies./ [3050] &para; And Tullius sai&thorn;. Ther nys no &thorn;ing so comendable in a grete lord [3051] as whan he is debonaire and meke and apaiseth hym self lightly. [3052] And I prey &yogh;ou &thorn;at ye wil forbere nowe to do vengeaunce [3053] in such a maner &thorn;at &yogh;our good name may be kept and conserued [3054] and &thorn;at men mow han a cause and matere to preise &yogh;ou of pite and of mercy [3055] and &thorn;at &yogh;e haue no cause to repent &yogh;ou of &thorn;inge &thorn;at &yogh;e do&omacr;n [3056] &para; ffor Senec sai&thorn;. He ouercomme&thorn; in an euel manere &thorn;at repente&thorn; hym of his victorie. [3057] Wher|fore I prey &yogh;ou lat mercy be in &yogh;oure hert [3058] to &thorn;e effecte and entent &thorn;at god almy&yogh;ty haue mercy on &yogh;ou in his last Iuggement [3059] &para; ffor seint Iame sei&thorn; in his Epistel &para; Iuggement wi&thorn;|oute mercy shal be do to hym &thorn;at ha&thorn; no mercy on another wi&yogh;t</P>
<P>[3060] Whan Melebius had herd &thorn;e grete skilles and resons of dame &middot; Prudence and her wise enformaci&omacr;n and techinge. [3061] His hert gan enclyne to &thorn;e wille of his wif. considerynge her trewe entent. [3062] Con|fermed. hym an&omacr;n and contened fully to worchen aftere her counsaile [3063] and &thorn;onked god of whome procede&thorn; al goodnesse &thorn;at hym sent a &para; wif of so grete discreci&omacr;n [3064] And whan &thorn;e day come &thorn;at his aduer|saries shuld apperen &middot; in his presence [3065] he speke 
<PB REF="00000573.tif" N="543"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="252"> to hem ful goodely And saide in &thorn;is wise. [3066] Al be it soo &thorn;at of &yogh;oure pride and hegh presumpci&omacr;n and foly. and of &yogh;oure negligence and vnkonyng [3067] &yogh;e han mysborn &yogh;ou. and trespased vnto me [3068] &yogh;it for as moche as I See and byholde &yogh;oure grete humilite [3069] and &thorn;at &yogh;e bene sory and repentaunte of &yogh;oure giltes. [3070] It constreyne&thorn; me to do &yogh;ou grace./ and mercy [3071] and wherfore I receyue &yogh;ou to my grace. [3072] And for&yogh;eue &yogh;ou vtterly al &thorn;e offences Iniuries and wrongges &thorn;at &yogh;e have done a&yogh;einst me and myne [3073] to &thorn;is effecte and to &thorn;is eende &thorn;at god of his endelees mercye [3074] wil at &thorn;e tyme of our deyinge for&yogh;eue vs our giltes &thorn;at we han trespased vnto hym in &thorn;is wrecched world. [3075] ffor doutelees &yogh;if we bene sory and repentaunte of &thorn;e synnes and giltes in &thorn;e which we han trespased in &thorn;e si&yogh;t of oure lorde god. [3076] he is so free and so merci|able. [3077] &thorn;at he <MILESTONE N="246b" UNIT="folio">wil for&yogh;eue vs oure giltes [3078] and brynge vs to &thorn;e blisse &thorn;at neuere ha&thorn; eende .AmeN.</P>
<TRAILER>&para; Here ende&thorn; chaucers tale of melebye</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000574.tif" N="544">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="253">
<HEAD>And here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e Monke./<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 246, <I>back</I></NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan ended was my tale of Meleby</L>
<L N="3080">And of Prudence and her benygnyte</L>
<L>Our hoost saide as I am fei&thorn;ful man</L>
<L>And by &thorn;e corps precious Matrian</L>
<L>I had leuer &thorn;an a barel of ale.</L>
<L N="3084">That good loue my wif had herd &thorn;is tale</L>
<L>ffor she nys no &thorn;inge of such pacience</L>
<L>As was &thorn;ilk Melebies Dame Prudence</L>
<L>By goddes bones whan I bete my knaues</L>
<L N="3088">She bringe&thorn; me for&thorn; &thorn;e grete clubbed staues</L>
<L>And crieth Slee &thorn;oo dogges euerychon</L>
<L>And breke of hem bo&thorn; bak and boon</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;at eny neighbour of myne</L>
<L N="3092">Wil nat to my wif in church enclyne</L>
<L>Or be so hardy to hure do trespas</L>
<L>Whan she comme&thorn; hoom she rampe&thorn; in my face</L>
<L>And crie&thorn; fals coward kepe and wreke &thorn;i wiff</L>
<L N="3096">By goddes bonys I wil haue &thorn;i knyff</L>
<L>And &thorn;ow shalt haue my distaff and go spynne</L>
<L>ffrom day to nyght &thorn;us she wil bygynne</L>
<L>Allas she sei&thorn; &thorn;at euer I was yshape</L>
<L N="3100">To wedde a Milksop or a coward ape</L>
<L>That wil be ouercome wi&thorn; euery wi&yogh;t</L>
<L>Thow darst not stonde by &thorn;i wyues ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;is is my lif but &yogh;if &thorn;at I wil fi&yogh;t</L>
<L N="3104">Out at &thorn;e door anoon I mot me di&yogh;t</L>
<L>Or ellys I am lest but &yogh;if &thorn;at I.</L>
<L>Be like a wilde lyon fool hardy.</L>
<L>I wote wele she wil do me sclee som day</L>
<L N="3108">Somme neighhoure of myne and &thorn;ennes renne away</L>
<L>ffor I am perilous wi&thorn; knyf in honde</L>
<L>Al be it I dar nat her withstonde
<PB REF="00000575.tif" N="545"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="254"></L>
<L>ffor she is bigge in Armes be my faith</L>
<L N="3112">&THORN;at shal he fynde &thorn;at hir mysdo&thorn; or sai&thorn;</L>
<L>But lat vs passe away fro &thorn;is matere</L>
<L>My lorde &thorn;e Monke quod he be mery of chiere<MILESTONE N="247a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor &yogh;e shul telle a tale trewly</L>
<L N="3116">Loo Rouchester stant here fast by</L>
<L>Ride for&thorn; myn owne lord breke not &yogh;oure game</L>
<L>But by my trou&thorn;e I knowe nou&yogh;t &yogh;oure name</L>
<L>Whedere shal I calle &yogh;ou my lord dan Iohn</L>
<L N="3120">Or danne Thomas or dann Albon</L>
<L>Of what hous be &yogh;e by &yogh;oure fader kyn</L>
<L>It is a gentile pasture &thorn;at &yogh;e goon In</L>
<L>Thow art not like a penannte or a goost</L>
<L N="3124">Thus to &thorn;e Monke seide oure oste</L>
<L>Vppon my fai&thorn;e &thorn;ou art some officere</L>
<L>Som wor&thorn;i Sexteyn or som selerere</L>
<L>ffor by my fadere saule as to my dome</L>
<L N="3128">Thow art a maistere whan &thorn;ou art at home</L>
<L>No poor cloistrere ne no novise</L>
<L>But gouernour bo&thorn; wily and wise</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-wi&thorn;-al of braune and of bonys</L>
<L N="3132">A wel farynge persone for &thorn;e nonys</L>
<L>I pray god &yogh;eue hym confusion</L>
<L>That &thorn;e furst brou&yogh;t to Religion</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou woldest haue bene a tredefor&thorn; ari&yogh;t</L>
<L N="3136">Haddest thou as grete leue as &thorn;ou hast my&yogh;t</L>
<L>To performe al &thorn;i lust in engendrure</L>
<L>Thow haddest ygete mony a creature</L>
<L>Allas whi werest &thorn;ow so wide a cope</L>
<L N="3140">God &yogh;eue sorowe to me and I were pope</L>
<L>Not oonly &thorn;ou but euery my&yogh;ty man.</L>
<L>Thou&yogh;e he were shore brode vpon &thorn;e pan.</L>
<L>Shuld haue a wiff for al &thorn;e world is lorn</L>
<L N="3144">Religion ha&thorn; take vp al &thorn;e c&omacr;rn</L>
<L>Of tredyng; and we burile men b&emacr;n but shrympes.</L>
<L>Of feble trees &thorn;er commen symple ympes.
<PB REF="00000576.tif" N="546"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="255"></L>
<L>This make&thorn; &thorn;at oure heires bene so sclendere</L>
<L N="3148">And feble &thorn;at &thorn;ei may not wel engendere</L>
<L>This make&thorn; &thorn;at our wyues wil assay</L>
<L>Relygious folk for &thorn;ei may bettere paye</L>
<L>Of Venes payment &thorn;an may we</L>
<L N="3152">God woot no lasshebourues pay &yogh;e<MILESTONE N="247b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Be nat wro&thorn;e my lorde &thorn;ou&yogh;e I play</L>
<L>ffor ofte in game a so&thorn;e I haue herd say</L>
<L>This wor&thorn;i monke toke all in pacience</L>
<L N="3156">And saide I wil doon al my diligence</L>
<L>As fer as sowneth unto honeste</L>
<L>To telle &yogh;ou a tale or two or &thorn;re</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;e list to herken hiderwarde</L>
<L N="3160">I wil &yogh;ou say &thorn;e lif of seint Edward</L>
<L>Or elles furst tregedies wil I &yogh;ou telle</L>
<L>Of which I haue an hundred in my Selle</L>
<L>Tregedie is forto seyn a certeyn storie</L>
<L N="3164">As olde bookes make vs memorie</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at stood in grete prosperite</L>
<L>And is falle out of hie degree</L>
<L>Into Miserye and ende&thorn; wrechedly</L>
<L N="3168">And &thorn;ei bene versefied comonly</L>
<L>Of sex fete of which men callen exametron</L>
<L>In proose eke bene endited mony on</L>
<L>In metere eke and in sondry wise</L>
<L N="3172">loo &thorn;is claring au&yogh;t ynow suffise</L>
<L>Now herkene&thorn; &yogh;if &yogh;ou like to here</L>
<L>But furst I &yogh;ou biseche in &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>&thorn;ou&yogh;e I be ordred tel not &thorn;ise &thorn;ingges</L>
<L N="3176">Be it of Popes Emperours or kyngges</L>
<L>After her Age as men may writen fynde</L>
<L>But telle hem som byfore and some behynde</L>
<L>As it comme&thorn; nowe in my remembraunce</L>
<L N="3180">Haue me excused of myn ignoraunce</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&para; Here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e monke
</HEAD>
<PB REF="00000577.tif" N="547"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="256">
<HEAD>And here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e monkes tale<NOTE PLACE="head">[No breaks between the stanzas in the MS, except for the red headings.]</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 247, <I>back</I></NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I wol by-waile in ma[ne]re of tregedie<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; &THORN;e tale</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e harme of hem &thorn;at stonden in hie degrie</L>
<L>And fallen so &thorn;at &thorn;er nys no remedye</L>
<L N="3184">To bringe hem out of her aduersite</L>
<L>ffor certeynly whan fortune list to flee</L>
<L>&thorn;er may no man of hir &thorn;e cours wi&thorn;holde</L>
<L>Lat no man trest on blynde prosperite</L>
<L N="3188">Be&thorn; ware of &thorn;ise ensamples trewe and olde<MILESTONE N="248a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; Primo de Lucifero;</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At lucifere &thorn;ou&yogh;e he an aungel were</L>
<L>And nat a man. but at hym I wil bygynne</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou&yogh;e fortune may noon aungel dere</L>
<L N="3192">ffroo high degre &thorn;er felle he for hys synne</L>
<L>Downe into helle wwere he &yogh;it is Inne</L>
<L>O lucifer bri&yogh;test of aungels alle</L>
<L>Now art &thorn;ou Sathanas &thorn;at maist nat twynne</L>
<L N="3196">Out of myserie in which &thorn;at &thorn;ou art falle</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; De Adam./</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Loo Adam in &thorn;e feelde of Damyssene</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; goddes oune fyngers wrou&yogh;t was he</L>
<L>And nou&yogh;t bygeten of mannes sperme vnclene</L>
<L N="3200">And wolt al Paradys sauyng oon tree</L>
<L>Had neuere worldly man so hie degre</L>
<L>As Adam vnto he wy&thorn; nyce gouernance</L>
<L>Was dryue out of his high prosperite</L>
<L N="3204">To laboure and to helle and to meschance
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000578.tif" N="548"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="257">
<HEAD>&para; De Sampsone</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lo sampson &thorn;at was annunciate</L>
<L>By &thorn;e Aungel longe er his natiuite</L>
<L>And was to god almy&yogh;ty consecrate</L>
<L N="3208">And stoode in noblesse while &thorn;at he my&yogh;t see</L>
<L>Was neuer such a no&thorn;er as was he</L>
<L>To speke of strength, and &thorn;erto hardynesse</L>
<L>But to his wyues tolde he his secree</L>
<L N="3212">Thourgh which he sclou&yogh;e hym self for wrecchednesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sampson &thorn;is noble and my&yogh;ty champion</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-oute wepen saaf his hondes tway</L>
<L>He sclough and also to-rent &thorn;e lyon</L>
<L N="3216">Toward his weddyng walking by &thorn;e way</L>
<L>His fals wif coude hym so wel plese and pray</L>
<L>Til she his counsaile knewe and she vntrewe</L>
<L>To his foos his counsaile gan to wrye</L>
<L N="3220">And hym forsoke and toke ano&thorn;er newe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thre hundred foxes toke Sampson for Ire</L>
<L>And alle her tailes he to-gyder bonde.</L>
<L>And Sette &thorn;e foxes tailles a fire<MILESTONE N="248b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3224">ffor he in euery taile had knytte a bronde</L>
<L>And &thorn;ei brent al &thorn;e cornes of &thorn;at londe</L>
<L>And al her oliuerus an vynes eke</L>
<L>A thowsand he sclough eke wi&thorn; his honde</L>
<L N="3228">And had no wepon but an asses cheke</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan &thorn;ei were sclayn so &thorn;rested hym &thorn;at he</L>
<L>was wel nye lorn wherfor he gan to preye</L>
<L>&thorn;at god wolde of his peyne haue som pite</L>
<L N="3232">And sende hym drynke or ellys most he deye</L>
<L>And out of his asses cheke &thorn;at was so dreye</L>
<L>Out of a wonge toth spronge anon a welle</L>
<L>Of whiche he dronk ynou&yogh;e shortly to . .</L>
<L N="3236">. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> telle
<PB REF="00000579.tif" N="549"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="258"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>By verray force at Algason vpon a ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>Maugre the philistiens of &thorn;at Cite</L>
<L>&thorn;e gatys of &thorn;at toune he ha&thorn; vp pli&yogh;t</L>
<L N="3240">And on his bak caried hem ha&thorn; he</L>
<L>Hie vpon an hille &thorn;at men my&yogh;t See</L>
<L>O noble almy&yogh;ty sampson leef and dere</L>
<L>Haddest &thorn;ou nat to wommen told &thorn;i secre</L>
<L N="3244">In al &thorn;is world ne had ben &thorn;i pere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This Sampson nei&thorn;er Sither dronk ne wyne</L>
<L>Ne on his hede come nei&thorn;ere rasour ne Shere</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3248">ffor al &thorn;e strength in his heres were</L>
<L>And fully xx<SUP>ti</SUP> wynter &yogh;eer by &yogh;ere</L>
<L>He had of Israel &thorn;e gouernaunce.</L>
<L>But he shal wepe mony a tere</L>
<L N="3252">ffor wommen men bryngen to meschaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To his lemmon his Dalyaunce he told</L>
<L>That in his herus al his strengthe lay</L>
<L>And falsly to his foomen she hym sold</L>
<L N="3256">And sclepinge in her barme vpon a day</L>
<L>She made to clippe or shere his heer away</L>
<L>And made his foomen all his craft to aspyen</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at &thorn;ei foonde hym in &thorn;is aray</L>
<L N="3260">&thorn;ei bounde hym fast and put out his yen</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But er his heer was yclipped or shaue</L>
<L>Ther was no boonde wi&thorn; which men my&yogh;t hym bynde</L>
<L>But now he is in prison put in a kaue<MILESTONE N="249a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3264">Where as &thorn;ei made hym at &thorn;e querne grynde</L>
<L>O noble Sampson strengest of mankynde</L>
<L>O whilom Iuge in glorie &amp; richesse</L>
<L>Now maist &thorn;ow wepe wi&thorn; &thorn;ine eyen blynde</L>
<L N="3268">Si&thorn;ens &thorn;ow art from wele falle into wrecchednesse
<PB REF="00000580.tif" N="550"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="259"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The eende of &thorn;ise catyfs was as I shal say</L>
<L>His ffoomen made a feest vpon a day</L>
<L>And made hym as her foole to-forn hem play</L>
<L N="3272">And &thorn;is was [in] a temple of a grete aray</L>
<L>But at &thorn;e last he made a foule afray</L>
<L>ffor he two postes shoke and made hem falle</L>
<L>And downe fill temple and al &thorn;er it lay</L>
<L N="3276">And sclough hym self and eke his foomen alle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This is to say &thorn;e princes euerechon</L>
<L>And eke a thowsand bodyes were &thorn;ere sclayn</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; falling of &thorn;e grete temple of ston</L>
<L N="3280">Of Sampson ne wil I no more sayn</L>
<L>Be ware of &thorn;ise ensamples olde and playn</L>
<L>&thorn;at no man telle her counsaile to her wyves</L>
<L>Of suche &thorn;inge as &thorn;ei wolde haue secre fayn</L>
<L N="3284">&YOGH;it &thorn;at it touche her lymmes or hir lyues.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; De Ercule./</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of Ercule this souereyn conquerour</L>
<L>Syngen his werkes lewde and high renoun.</L>
<L>ffor in his tyme of strength he bere &thorn;e flour</L>
<L N="3288">He slowe and raft &thorn;e skyn fro &thorn;e lyoun</L>
<L>He of Sentawres laide &thorn;e boost a doun</L>
<L>He Arpies sclowe &thorn;e cruel briddes felle</L>
<L>He golden apples byraft &thorn;e dragoun</L>
<L N="3292">He drowe out Serbyrois &thorn;e hound of helle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He sclowe &thorn;e cruel tyraunt Buserus</L>
<L>And made his hors to frete hym flessh and bon</L>
<L>He sclough &thorn;e verrey serpent venemous</L>
<L N="3296">Of Achiles two hornes breke he on</L>
<L>An he sclowgh Cacus in a kaue of ston</L>
<L>He sclowgh &thorn;e geaunte Anteus &thorn;e strong</L>
<L>He sclowe &thorn;e grisly boore and &thorn;at anon</L>
<L N="3300">And bare &thorn;e hede vpon his nek longe<MILESTONE N="249b" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000581.tif" N="551"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="260"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Was neuer wi&yogh;t si&thorn;en &thorn;e world bygan</L>
<L>&thorn;at sclowe so mony monstres as did he</L>
<L>&THORN;orgh-out &thorn;is wide world his name ran</L>
<L N="3304">What for his strength and for his bounte</L>
<L>And euery Rewme went he forto See</L>
<L>He was so stronge no man my&yogh;t hym lette</L>
<L>And bo&thorn; &thorn;e worldes ende sai&thorn; trophe</L>
<L N="3308">In stede of bondes he a piler sette</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A lemman had &thorn;is noble Campion</L>
<L>That hight Dianyre fressh as may</L>
<L>And as &thorn;e clerkes maken mencion</L>
<L N="3312">She ha&thorn; hym sent a shert fressh and gay</L>
<L>Allas &thorn;is shert and welaway</L>
<L>Evenymed was subtilly wi&thorn;-all</L>
<L>That ere &thorn;at he had wered it half a day</L>
<L N="3316">It made his bones from his flesshe falle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But na&thorn;eles some clerkes her excusen</L>
<L>By oon &thorn;at hight Nessus &thorn;at it maked.</L>
<L>Be as be may I wil her not accusen &middot;</L>
<L N="3320">But on his bakke &thorn;e shert he weres al naked.</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at his flessh was for &thorn;e venyme blaked</L>
<L>And whan he segh noon o&thorn;er remedye</L>
<L>In hote cooles he ha&thorn; hym-self raked</L>
<L N="3324">ffor wi&thorn; no venyme deyned he to dye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thus sterf &thorn;is wor&thorn;i myghty Ercules</L>
<L>Lo who may trust on fortune eny throwe</L>
<L>ffor hym &thorn;at folowe&thorn; al &thorn;is world of prees</L>
<L N="3328">Er he be ware is oft yleide ful lowe</L>
<L>fful wise is he &thorn;at hym self can knowe</L>
<L>Be&thorn; ware for whan &thorn;at fortune lest to glose</L>
<L>&THORN;an waite&thorn; she her man doun to throwe</L>
<L N="3332">By suche a way as he wold leest suppose
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000582.tif" N="552"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="261">
<HEAD>&para; De rege Nabugodonosor./</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The my&yogh;ty trone &thorn;e precious tresour</L>
<L>The glorious sceptre and real mageste</L>
<L>&THORN;at had &thorn;e kynge Nabugodonosor</L>
<L N="3336">Wi&thorn; tunge vnne&thorn; may / discrived be</L>
<L>He twyes nam Ierusalem &thorn;e Cite<MILESTONE N="250a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>The Vessell of &thorn;e temple he wi&thorn; hym lad</L>
<L>At Babiloyne was his souereyn See</L>
<L N="3340">In which his glorie and his delit he had.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The fairest children of &thorn;e blood Royal</L>
<L>Of Ierusalem he ded do gilde anonon</L>
<L>And maked eche of hem to bene his cherle</L>
<L N="3344">Amon[ge] all o&thorn;er Danyel was oon</L>
<L>&thorn;at was &thorn;e wysest childe of euerychon</L>
<L>ffor he &thorn;e dremes of &thorn;e kynge expowned</L>
<L>Wher as in Caldey clerk was &thorn;er noon</L>
<L N="3348">&thorn;at wist to what fyne his dremes sowned</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This prowde kynge lete make a stature of gold</L>
<L>Sixty cubites longe and Seuen in brede</L>
<L>To whiche ymage bo&thorn; &yogh;onge and olde</L>
<L N="3352">Comaunded he to loute and haue in drede</L>
<L>Or in a fornays ful of flawmes rede.</L>
<L>He shal be brent &thorn;at wold nat obeye</L>
<L>But neuere wold assent vnto &thorn;at dede</L>
<L N="3356">Danyel ne his &yogh;onge felawes tweye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This kynge of kyngges prowde was and elate</L>
<L>He wende god &thorn;at sitte in maieste</L>
<L>Ne myght hym nat byreue of his estate</L>
<L N="3360">But sodeynly he lost his dignyte</L>
<L>And like a beest hym semed forto be</L>
<L>And ete hay as an oxe and lay &thorn;erout</L>
<L>In reyne wi&thorn; wilde beestes walked he</L>
<L N="3364">Til a certeyn tyme was come aboute
<PB REF="00000583.tif" N="553"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="262"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And like an Egles fetheres was his heeres</L>
<L>His nailes like briddes clawes were</L>
<L>[Til] God releued hym a certeyn &yogh;eres</L>
<L N="3368">And &yogh;af hym witte and &thorn;an wi&thorn; mony a tere</L>
<L>He &thorn;onked god and euere his lyf in fere</L>
<L>was he to doon amys in more trespas</L>
<L>And or &thorn;at tyme ylaide was on his bere</L>
<L N="3372">He knewe wel &thorn;at god was ful of my&yogh;t and grace</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De Baltazar dicti Regis Nabugodonosor filio.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His sone which &thorn;at hi&yogh;t Baltazar</L>
<L>That heelde &thorn;e regne aftere his faders day<MILESTONE N="250b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>He by his fadere cou&thorn;e not be war</L>
<L N="3376">ffor proude he was of hert and of aray</L>
<L>And eke an ydolater was he ay</L>
<L>His high astate assured hym in pride</L>
<L>But fortune cast hym doune and &thorn;er he lay</L>
<L N="3380">And sodeynly his regne gan devide</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A feest he made vnto his lordes alle</L>
<L>Vppon a tyme and made hem bli&thorn;e be</L>
<L>And &thorn;an his officers can he calle</L>
<L N="3384">Goo&thorn; brynge&thorn; for&thorn; &thorn;e vessels quod he</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at my fader in his prosperite</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e temple of Ierusalem byraft</L>
<L>And to oure heghe goddes &thorn;onke wee</L>
<L N="3388">Of honur &thorn;at our elders wi&thorn; vs laft</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His wif his lordes and his concubynes</L>
<L>Ay dronken &thorn;e whiles her appetite last</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;ise noble vessels sondry wynes</L>
<L N="3392">And on a wal &thorn;is kyng his eyen cast</L>
<L>And sawe an honde armelees &thorn;at wrote ful fast</L>
<L>ffor fere of which he quoke and sighed sore</L>
<L>This honde &thorn;at baltazar made so soor agast</L>
<L N="3396">Wrote mane techel phares and no more
<PB REF="00000584.tif" N="554"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="263"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In al &thorn;at londe Magytien was &thorn;er noon</L>
<L>&thorn;at cou&thorn;e expoune what &thorn;is lettre ment</L>
<L>But Danyel expouned it anoon</L>
<L N="3400">And saide king god &thorn;i fader sent</L>
<L>Glorie and honour Regne tresour and rent</L>
<L>And he was proude and god no &thorn;ing dradde</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore god grete wreth vpon hym Sent</L>
<L N="3404">And hym by-raft &thorn;e regne &thorn;at he hadde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He was out cast of mannys companye</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; asses was his habitacion</L>
<L>And ete hay as a beest in wete and drye</L>
<L N="3408">Til &thorn;at he knewe by grace and by reson</L>
<L>That god of heuene ha&thorn; domynacian</L>
<L>Ouer euery regne and euery creature</L>
<L>And &thorn;an had god of hym compassion</L>
<L N="3412">And hym restored his regne and his figure<MILESTONE N="251a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Eke &thorn;ou &thorn;at art his sone art proude also</L>
<L>And knowest all &thorn;ise &thorn;ingges prively</L>
<L>And art rebel to god and art his foo</L>
<L N="3416">Thow drank eke of his vessels boldly</L>
<L>Thi wif eke and &thorn;i wenches synfully</L>
<L>Drank of &thorn;e same vessels sondry wynes</L>
<L>And heried fals goddys cursedly</L>
<L N="3420">&THORN;erfore to &thorn;e shapen grete peyn es</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This hand was sent fro god &thorn;at on &thorn;e wall</L>
<L>wrote mane techel phares trest me</L>
<L>Thy regne is done &thorn;ou waiest not at all</L>
<L N="3424">Devided is &thorn;i regne and it shal be</L>
<L>To Medes and to perses &yogh;euen quod he</L>
<L>And &thorn;ilk same ny&yogh;t &thorn;e kyng was sclawe</L>
<L>And Darius occupie&thorn; his degre</L>
<L N="3428">They he &thorn;erto nad nei&thorn;er ri&yogh;t ne lawe
<PB REF="00000585.tif" N="555"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="264"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lordyngges her-by ensamples mowe &yogh;e take</L>
<L>How &thorn;at in lordship is no sikernesse</L>
<L>ffor whan fortune wil a man forsake</L>
<L N="3432">He bere&thorn; away his regne and his richesse</L>
<L>And eke his frendes bo&thorn; more and lesse</L>
<L>And what man ha&thorn; frendes &thorn;orowe fortune</L>
<L>Mishappe wil make hem enemyes I gesse</L>
<L N="3436">This prouerbe is ful so&thorn;e and ful commune</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; De Cenobia;/</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>CEnobia of Palamere &thorn;e quene</L>
<L>As writen Persiens of her noblesse</L>
<L>So wor&thorn;i was in Armes and so kene</L>
<L N="3440">&thorn;at no wi&yogh;t passed hure in hardynesse</L>
<L>Ne in lynage ne in o&thorn;er gentilnesse</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e kyngges blood of percy is she descended.</L>
<L>I say &thorn;at she nad not moost fairenesse</L>
<L N="3444">But of hure Shap she my&yogh;t not be amended</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fro childhode I fynde &thorn;at she fledde</L>
<L>Office of wommen and into woode she went</L>
<L>And Mony a wilde hertes blode she shedde</L>
<L N="3448">wi&thorn; arowes brode &thorn;at she to hym sent</L>
<L>She was so swift &thorn;at she anoon hem hent<MILESTONE N="251b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at she was elder she wold kille</L>
<L>Lyons . lybardes and beres alto-rent</L>
<L N="3452">And in hure armes weelde hem at her wille</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>She durst wilde beestes dennes seke</L>
<L>And renne in &thorn;e mountayn al &thorn;e nyght</L>
<L>And sclepe vndere a bussh she coude eke</L>
<L N="3456">Wrastelen by verray force and myght</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; eny yong man were he neuer so wi&yogh;t</L>
<L>Ther myght no &thorn;inge in her Armes stonde</L>
<L>She kepte her maidenhode from euery wi&yogh;t</L>
<L N="3460">To no man deyned hure to be bonde
<PB REF="00000586.tif" N="556"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="265"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But at &thorn;e last her frendes han hure maried</L>
<L>To Odonak a prince of &thorn;at Cite</L>
<L>Al were it so &thorn;at she hem longe taried</L>
<L N="3464">And &yogh;e shal vnderstonde how &thorn;at he</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; suche fantasies as had she</L>
<L>But na&thorn;elees whan &thorn;ei were knyt in fere</L>
<L>&thorn;ei lyueden in Ioie and in felicite</L>
<L N="3468">ffor eche of hem had o&thorn;er leef and dere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sauf oon &thorn;inge that &yogh;e nolde neuere assent</L>
<L>By no way &thorn;at he shulde by hire lye</L>
<L>But onys for it was her pleyn entent</L>
<L N="3472">To haue a childe &thorn;e world to multiplie</L>
<L>And also sone as she my&yogh;t aspie.</L>
<L>That she was nou&yogh;t wi&thorn; child with &thorn;at dede</L>
<L>&thorn;an wil she suffre hym doon his fantasie</L>
<L N="3476">Eftsone and not but onys out of drede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &yogh;if she were wi&thorn; childe at &thorn;ilke cast</L>
<L>No more shulde he playe &thorn;ilke game</L>
<L>Till xl<SUP>ti</SUP>. daies were past</L>
<L N="3480">Than wolde she onys suffre hym doo &thorn;e same</L>
<L>Al were this Odenake wilde or tame</L>
<L>He gate no more of hure. for &thorn;us she saide</L>
<L>It was to wyues lechery an shame</L>
<L N="3484">In o&thorn;er caas if &thorn;at men wi&thorn; hem plaide</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Twoo sones by &thorn;is odynak had She</L>
<L>The whiche she kepte in vertue and in letture</L>
<L>But nowe vnto oure tale turne wee<MILESTONE N="252a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3488">I say &thorn;at worshipful creature</L>
<L>And wise &thorn;er-wi&thorn; and large with mesure</L>
<L>So penyble in &thorn;e werre and curteyse eke</L>
<L>No more labour my&yogh;t in werre endure</L>
<L N="3492">was noon &thorn;ou&yogh;e in al &thorn;is world men shuld seke
<PB REF="00000587.tif" N="557"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="266"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hire Riche aray my&yogh;t not be tolde</L>
<L>As wel in vessel as in clo&thorn;inge</L>
<L>She was al clad in perry and in gold</L>
<L N="3496">And eke she laft not for noon huntynge</L>
<L>To haue of sondry tungges folk knowing</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at she leisere had and forto entende</L>
<L>To lerne bookes was al hure likynge</L>
<L N="3500">How she in vertue my&yogh;t her lyf dispende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And shortely of &thorn;is storie forto entrete</L>
<L>So dughty was her husbonde as she</L>
<L>That &thorn;ei conquered mony regnes grete</L>
<L N="3504">In &thorn;e Orient wi&thorn; mony a faire Cite</L>
<L>Appertenent vnto &thorn;e mageste</L>
<L>Of Rome and wi&thorn; stronge hond helde hem fast</L>
<L>Ne neuer my&yogh;t her foomen doon hem flee</L>
<L N="3508">Ay whiles &thorn;at Odenake dayes last</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Her batailles who so lest hem forto rede</L>
<L>Ageyn sopere &thorn;e kyng and o&thorn;er moo</L>
<L>And howe &thorn;at all &thorn;e processe felle in dede</L>
<L N="3512">whi she conquered and what titel had &thorn;erto.</L>
<L>And after of her mescheef and of her woo</L>
<L>Howe &thorn;at she was byseged and Itake</L>
<L>Lat hym vnto my maister Petrarke goo.</L>
<L N="3516">&THORN;at writte Inowe of &thorn;is I vndertake.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan Odenak was dede she my&yogh;tily</L>
<L>&thorn;e Regnes heelde and wi&thorn; hur propre honde</L>
<L>A&yogh;einst her foos she fau&yogh;t trewly</L>
<L N="3520">&thorn;at &thorn;er nas kyng no prince in al &thorn;at londe</L>
<L>&thorn;at he nas glad &yogh;if he &thorn;at grace fonde</L>
<L>&thorn;at she ne wolde vpon his lond werreye</L>
<L>wi&thorn; hire &thorn;ei made alliance by bonde</L>
<L N="3524">To bene in pees and lat hure ride and pleye /
<PB REF="00000588.tif" N="558"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="267"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The Emperour of Rome Claudius<MILESTONE N="252b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ne hym byforn &thorn;e Romayne galiene</L>
<L>Ne durst neuer be so coragius</L>
<L N="3528">Ne noon ermyne ne noon Egipciene</L>
<L>Ne Surryene ne noon Arabiene</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-in &thorn;e feelde &thorn;at durst wi&thorn; hire fi&yogh;t</L>
<L>Lest &thorn;at she wolde wi&thorn; hure hondes hym scleen</L>
<L N="3532">Or wi&thorn; her mayne putten hem to fli&yogh;t</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In kyngges habite went her sonys twoo</L>
<L>As heires of her regnes alle</L>
<L>And hermanno and Tymalao</L>
<L N="3536">Her names were as perciens hem calle</L>
<L>But ay fortune ha&thorn; in her hony galle</L>
<L>This my&yogh;ty qwene may not longe endure</L>
<L>ffortune out of her regne made her falle</L>
<L N="3540">To wrecchednesse and to mysauenture</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Aurelion whan &thorn;at &thorn;e gouernaunce</L>
<L>Of Rome come into his hondes tweye</L>
<L>He shope vpon &thorn;is quene to do vengeaunce</L>
<L N="3544">And wi&thorn; his legyons he toke his waye</L>
<L>Toward Cenoby and shortly forto seye</L>
<L>He made hur flee and at &thorn;e last her hent</L>
<L>And fettred hure and eke her children tweye</L>
<L N="3548">And wan &thorn;e londe and home to Rome is went</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Amonge &thorn;ise o&thorn;er &thorn;ingges &thorn;at he wan</L>
<L>her chare &thorn;at wrou&yogh;t was with gold and perre</L>
<L>This grete Romayn &thorn;is Aurelian.</L>
<L N="3552">ha&thorn; wi&thorn; hym lad for &thorn;at men shuld see</L>
<L>Byforn hys trihumphe walke&thorn; she</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Gilt cheynes in her nek hongynge</L>
<L>Corowned she was as after her degre</L>
<L N="3556">And ful of Perry charged her clo&thorn;inge
<PB REF="00000589.tif" N="559"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="268"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Allas fortune she &thorn;at whilom was</L>
<L>Dreedful to kyngges and to emperours</L>
<L>Now gaure&thorn; alle &thorn;e puple on hir allas</L>
<L N="3560">And she &thorn;at helmed was in stronge stoures</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Shal on her hede bere a Vitremyte</L>
<L>And she &thorn;at bare &thorn;e sceptre ful of floures</L>
<L N="3564">Shal bye a dystaf her coste forto quite<MILESTONE N="253a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Peter the Cruel, of Spain.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O noble o wor&thorn;i peter glory of Spayn</L>
<L>Whoom fortune helde so hi&yogh;e in maieste</L>
<L>Wel ou&yogh;t men &thorn;i pitous dee&thorn; complayn</L>
<L N="3568">Thi bastard bro&thorn;er made &thorn;e to flee</L>
<L>And aftere at a siege by subtilte</L>
<L>Thowe were bytraied and lad to his tent</L>
<L>Wher as he wi&thorn; his owne honde sclogh &thorn;e</L>
<L N="3572">Succeedynge in &thorn;i regne and in &thorn;i rent</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The felde of snowe wi&thorn; &thorn;e Egle blak &thorn;er-Inne<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Bertrand du Guesclin.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Caught wi&thorn; &thorn;e lyme rodde colours as &thorn;e glede</L>
<L>He brewe &thorn;is cursednesse and al &thorn;e synne</L>
<L N="3576">&thorn;e wicked nest was werker of &thorn;is nede.</L>
<L>Nou&yogh;t charles Olyfere &thorn;at ay toke good hede</L>
<L>Of trou&thorn;e of honure but Armorekke<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Oliver de Mauny of Britanny.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Genilon Olyuer corupte for nede</L>
<L N="3580">Brou&yogh;test &thorn;is wor&thorn;i king in suche brekke</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Peter of Cyprus.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; wor&thorn;i Petre kynge of Cipre alsoo.</L>
<L>That Alisaunder wan by high maistrie</L>
<L>fful mony a he&thorn;en wrou&yogh;test &thorn;ou for woo.</L>
<L N="3584">Of which &thorn;ine owne leeges had enuye</L>
<L>And for no &thorn;ing but for &thorn;i chyualrie</L>
<L>They in &thorn;i bed han sclayn &thorn;e by &thorn;e morue</L>
<L>Thus gan fortune gouerne and gie</L>
<L N="3588">And out of Ioie bringe into sorowe
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000590.tif" N="560"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="269">
<HEAD>[Bernabo Visconti, of Milan.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of Melane grete Barnabo Viscounte</L>
<L>God of delite and scourge of lumbardie</L>
<L>Whi shuld not I &thorn;i fortune acounte</L>
<L N="3592">Si&thorn; in estaat &thorn;ou clomben were so hie</L>
<L>Thy bro&thorn;er sone &thorn;at was &thorn;i double alie</L>
<L>ffor he &thorn;i Neuewe was and sone in lawe</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-in his prison made &thorn;e to die</L>
<L N="3596">But whi ne howe wote I &thorn;at &thorn;ou were sclawe</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Ugolino, Count of Pisa.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of the Erle Hugelyne of pise &thorn;e languour</L>
<L>Ther may no tunge telle for pite</L>
<L>But litel out of Pise stant a tour</L>
<L N="3600">In whiche towre in prison put was he</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; hym bene his litel children &thorn;re</L>
<L>&thorn;e eldest scarcely .v. &yogh;ere was of age<MILESTONE N="253b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Allas fortune it was grete crueltee</L>
<L N="3604">Such briddes forto putte into a cage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Dampned he was to dye in &thorn;at prison</L>
<L>ffor Roger which &thorn;at bisshop was of pise</L>
<L>Had on hym made a fals suggestion</L>
<L N="3608">Thorgh which &thorn;e puple gan on hym arise</L>
<L>And putten him in prison in such a wise</L>
<L>As &yogh;e han herd and mete and drinke he had.</L>
<L>So smal &thorn;at vnne&thorn;es it may suffise</L>
<L N="3612">And &thorn;erwi&thorn;al it was ful poor and bad</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In a day byfelle &thorn;at in &thorn;at houre</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at his [mete] was wonte to be wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;e Gailour shette &thorn;e doores of &thorn;e toure</L>
<L N="3616">He herde it wel but he seegh it nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And in his hert anoon &thorn;er felle a &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ei for hunder wolde done hym dyen</L>
<L>Allas quod he allas &thorn;at I was wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="3620">&thorn;er-wi&thorn; &thorn;e teeres felle from his eyen.
<PB REF="00000591.tif" N="561"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="270"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His &yogh;onge sones &thorn;re &thorn;er were of age</L>
<L>Vnto hym seide fadere whi do &yogh;e wepe</L>
<L>whan wil &thorn;e Gailoure brynge our potage</L>
<L N="3624">Is &thorn;er no morsel brede &thorn;at [ye] doo kepe</L>
<L>I am so hungry &thorn;at I may nat sclepe</L>
<L>Nowe wolde god &thorn;at I my&yogh;t sclepen euere</L>
<L>&thorn;an shuld noon hungre in myn herte crepe</L>
<L N="3628">&thorn;er nys no &thorn;inge sauf brede &thorn;at me were leuere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thus day by day &thorn;is childe gan to crie</L>
<L>Til in his faders barme adoune it lay</L>
<L>And saide fare wel fadere I mote dye</L>
<L N="3632">And kissed his fadere and dyed &thorn;e same day</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;e wooful fadere did hym say</L>
<L>ffor woo his armes two he gan to bite</L>
<L>And saide allas fortune and welaway</L>
<L N="3636">Thy fals whele my woo I may al wite</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His childer [wende] &thorn;at hit for hunger was</L>
<L>&thorn;at he his armes gnowe and nou&yogh;t for woo.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei seiden fadere do not so allas</L>
<L N="3640">But ra&thorn;er ete &thorn;e flessh vpon vs twoo.<MILESTONE N="254a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Our flesshe &thorn;ou &yogh;af vs take our flessh vs froo</L>
<L>And ete ynou&yogh;e ri&yogh;t &thorn;us to hym &thorn;ei saide</L>
<L>And after &thorn;at wi&thorn;-Inne a day or twoo</L>
<L N="3644">&THORN;ei leide hem doune in his lappe and dayde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hym self dispeirede eke and for hu[n]ger starf</L>
<L>Thus ended is &thorn;e my&yogh;ty erle of pise</L>
<L>ffor highe astate fortune fro hym carf</L>
<L N="3648">Of his tregetrie it ou&yogh;te ynou&yogh;e suffise</L>
<L>Who so wil here it in a lenger wise</L>
<L>Rede&thorn; &thorn;e grete poete of ytaile</L>
<L>&thorn;at hi&yogh;te Daunte, for he can it devise</L>
<L N="3652">ffrom poynt to poynte for no &thorn;ing wil he faile.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000592.tif" N="562"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="271">
<HEAD>&para; De nerone Imperatore.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Al &thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;at Nero were as vicious</L>
<L>As eny feende &thorn;at lieth ful lowe adoune</L>
<L>&YOGH;it he as telle&thorn; vs swetheneus</L>
<L N="3656">This wide world had in subieccion</L>
<L>Both eest and west and Septemptrion</L>
<L>Of Rubies Saphires and peerles white</L>
<L>Were al his [clo&thorn;es] browd[ed] vp and doune</L>
<L N="3660">ffor he [in] gemmes grete gan delite</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>More delicate more pompous of araye</L>
<L>More proude was neuere Emperour &thorn;an he</L>
<L>&thorn;at ilke clo&thorn;e &thorn;at he had wered a day</L>
<L N="3664">Aftere &thorn;at tyme he nolde it neuer see</L>
<L>Nettes of gold threde had he grete plente</L>
<L>To fisshen in Tibre whan hym list to pleye</L>
<L>His lustes [were] as lawe in his degre</L>
<L N="3668">ffor fortune as his frende wold hym obeye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He Rome brent for his delicasie</L>
<L>The Senatoures he sclou&yogh;e vpon a day</L>
<L>To here howe &thorn;at men wolde wepe and crie</L>
<L N="3672">And sclou&yogh;e his bro&thorn;er and by his sustere [lay]</L>
<L>His modere made he in pitous aray</L>
<L>ffor he her wombe sclitte to byhold</L>
<L>wher he conceyued was so welaway</L>
<L N="3676">That he so litel of his moder tolde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>No teer out of his eyen for &thorn;at si&yogh;t<MILESTONE N="254b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ne came but saide a faire womman was she</L>
<L>Grete wondere is &thorn;at he cowde or my&yogh;t</L>
<L N="3680">Be Domes man of her dede bewte.</L>
<L>The wyne to brynge comaunded he</L>
<L>And dronke anoon noon o&thorn;er woo he made</L>
<L>Whan my&yogh;t is Ioyned vnto cruelte</L>
<L N="3684">Alas to depe wil &thorn;e venyme wade
<PB REF="00000593.tif" N="563"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="272"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In &yogh;outhe a maister had &thorn;is emperour</L>
<L>To teche hym letture and curtesye</L>
<L>ffor of moralite he was &thorn;e floure</L>
<L N="3688">As in his tyme but &yogh;if bokes lye</L>
<L>And whiles his maister had of hym maistrie</L>
<L>He made hym so conynge and so souple</L>
<L>That longe tyme it was or tyrannye</L>
<L N="3692">Or eny vice in hym durst vncouple</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This Seneca of which [that] I devise</L>
<L>By cause Nero had of hym such drede</L>
<L>ffor he for vices wold hym chastise</L>
<L N="3696">Discretely as by worde and nat by dede</L>
<L>Sire wolde he sayne an Emperour mot nede</L>
<L>Be vertuous and hate tyrannye</L>
<L>ffor which he hym in bathe made to blede</L>
<L N="3700">On boo&thorn; his Armes til he most dye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This Nero had eke of a custumance</L>
<L>In &yogh;ou&thorn;e a&yogh;einst his maister forto rise</L>
<L>Which afterward hym &thorn;ou&yogh;t a grete greuance</L>
<L N="3704">Therfore he made hym dye in &thorn;is wise</L>
<L>But nathelees &thorn;is Senec &thorn;e wise</L>
<L>Chees in a bathe to dye in &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>Ra&thorn;er &thorn;an han a no&thorn;er tormentri[s]e</L>
<L N="3708">And &thorn;us ha&thorn; Nero sclayn his maister dere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now felle it so &thorn;at fortune lest no lenger</L>
<L>&thorn;e highe Pride of Nero to cherice</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou&yogh;e he were stronge &yogh;it was she strenger</L>
<L N="3712">She &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;us by god I am to nyce</L>
<L>To sette a man &thorn;at is fulfild in vice</L>
<L>In heghe degre and Emperour hym calle.</L>
<L>By god out of his sete I wil him trice.<MILESTONE N="255a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3716">whan he leest wene&thorn; sonnest shal he falle.
<PB REF="00000594.tif" N="564"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="273"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The puple roos vp on hym on a ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>ffor his defaute and whan he it aspied.</L>
<L>Out of his doores anoon he ha&thorn; hym di&yogh;t</L>
<L N="3720">Allone and &thorn;er he wende haue bene alied.</L>
<L>He knokked fast and ay &thorn;e more he cried</L>
<L>The faster schitten &thorn;ei &thorn;e doores alle</L>
<L>&THORN;o wist he wel he had hym self mysgied.</L>
<L N="3724">And went his way no lenger dorst he calle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The puple cried and rombled vp and doun</L>
<L>That wi&thorn; his eeres herde he what &thorn;ei seide</L>
<L>Where is &thorn;is fals traitour &thorn;is Neroun</L>
<L N="3728">ffor fere almost out of his witte he breide</L>
<L>And to his goddes pitously he seide</L>
<L>ffor socoure but it my&yogh;t nat be-tyde</L>
<L>ffor drede of &thorn;is him &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at he dyde</L>
<L N="3732">And ranne into a gardeyne hym to hyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And in &thorn;is gardyne fonde he cherles tweye</L>
<L>That sitten by a fuyre ful gret and rede</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e cherles twey he gan to preie</L>
<L N="3736">To scleen hym and to girden of his hede</L>
<L>That to his body whan &thorn;at he were dede</L>
<L>Were no despite ydon for his diffame</L>
<L>Hym self he sclow&yogh;e he coude no better rede</L>
<L N="3740">Of which fortune lough and made a game</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Holofernes.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Was neuere Captayne vnder a kinge<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De Olyferno./</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at regne&thorn; more putte in subiectioun</L>
<L>Ne strenger was in feelde of al &thorn;inge</L>
<L N="3744">As in his tyme ne gretter of renoun</L>
<L>Ne more pompous in high presumpcioun</L>
<L>Than olyferne which that fortune ay kest</L>
<L>So lycorously and lad hym vp and doun</L>
<L N="3748">Til &thorn;at his hede was of er &thorn;at he wist
<PB REF="00000595.tif" N="565"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="274"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Not oonly &thorn;at this world ha&thorn; of hym awe</L>
<L>ffor lesinge of Richesse and of liberte</L>
<L>But he made euery man renaye his lawe</L>
<L N="3752">Nabugodonosor was lord saide he.</L>
<L>Noon o&thorn;er god shulde honoured be<MILESTONE N="255b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A&yogh;einst his heest no wi&yogh;t dar trespace</L>
<L>Saue in Betulia a stronge Cite</L>
<L N="3756">Wher Eliachym a preest was of &thorn;at place</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But take kepe of &thorn;e deth of Olyferne</L>
<L>Amydde &thorn;e hooste he dronke lay al ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Inne his tente large as is a beerne</L>
<L N="3760">And &yogh;it for al his pompe and al his my&yogh;t</L>
<L>Iudith a womman as he lay vpri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Sclepinge his hede of smote and fro his tent</L>
<L>fful prively she stale from euery wi&yogh;t</L>
<L N="3764">. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Antiochus.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>What nede&thorn; it of kynge Antiochus<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De Antiocho Rege</NOTE></L>
<L>To telle his high and Ryal maieste</L>
<L>His hie pride his werke venymus</L>
<L N="3768">ffor suche ano&thorn;er was neuer noon as he</L>
<L>Rede&thorn; which &thorn;at he was in machabe</L>
<L>And rede&thorn; &thorn;e proude wordes &thorn;at he seide</L>
<L>And whi he felle fro his prosperite</L>
<L N="3772">And in an halle how wrechedly he deide</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fortune hym had enhaunsed so in pride</L>
<L>That verrely he wende he my&yogh;t atteyne</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e sterres vppon euery side</L>
<L N="3776">And in a balaunce to wey &thorn;e mounteyne</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e floodes of the See Restreyne</L>
<L>And goddes puple had he most in hate</L>
<L>Hem wolde he sclee in torment and [in] peyn</L>
<L N="3780">wenynge &thorn;at god ne my&yogh;t his pride abate
<PB REF="00000596.tif" N="566"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="275"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And for &thorn;at Nichamour and thymothe</L>
<L>wi&thorn; Iwes were venquysshed my&yogh;tely</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e Iwes such an hate had he</L>
<L N="3784">That he bad gra&thorn;ed his chare ful hastifly</L>
<L>And swore and saide ful dispitously</L>
<L>Vnto Ierusalem he wolde eftsone</L>
<L>To wreke his Ire on it ful cruelly</L>
<L N="3788">But of his purpos he was lette ful sone</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>God of his manace hym so sore smote</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; vnvysible wounde ay vncurable</L>
<L>That in his guttes carf soo and bote</L>
<L N="3792">That his peynes were importable<MILESTONE N="256a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And certeinly &thorn;e wrech was resonable</L>
<L>ffor many mannys guttes did he peyne</L>
<L>But fro his purpoos cursed and dampneable</L>
<L N="3796">ffor al his smerte he nolde hym restreyne</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But bad anoon apparaile his Ooste</L>
<L>And sodeynly er he was of it ware</L>
<L>God daunted al his pride and al his boost</L>
<L N="3800">ffor he so sore felle out of his chare</L>
<L>That hurte his lymmes and his skyn to-tare</L>
<L>Soo &thorn;at he ne my&yogh;t goo ne ride</L>
<L>But in a chaier men about hym bare</L>
<L N="3804">Al for-brused bo&thorn; bak and side</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The wreth of god hym smote so cruelly</L>
<L>That in his body wikked wormes crepte</L>
<L>And &thorn;er wi&thorn; al he stonke so horryblye</L>
<L N="3808">That noon of alle his mayne &thorn;at hym kepte</L>
<L>whedere &thorn;at he woke or ellis sclepte</L>
<L>Ne myght not &thorn;e stynk of hym endure</L>
<L>In &thorn;is meschief he wailled and eke wepte.</L>
<L N="3812">And knewe god lorde of euery creature
<PB REF="00000597.tif" N="567"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="276"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To alle his hooste and to hym self also</L>
<L>fful wlatsom was &thorn;e stink of his careyne</L>
<L>No man my&yogh;t hym bere to ne froo.</L>
<L N="3816">And in his stynk and in his horrible peyne</L>
<L>He starfe ful wrechedly in a mounteyne</L>
<L>Thus ha&thorn; &thorn;is robbour and homycide</L>
<L>That mony a man made to wepe and pleyne</L>
<L N="3820">Such guerdon as by-longe&thorn; vnto pride</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Alexander the Great.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The Storie of Alisaundre is so comune.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De Alex|andro Rege</NOTE></L>
<L>That euery wi&yogh;t &thorn;at ha&thorn; discrecioun</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; herd somwhat or all of his fortune</L>
<L N="3824">This wide world as in conclusioun</L>
<L>He wanne by strength or for his hie renoun</L>
<L>They weren glad for pees vnto hym sende</L>
<L>&THORN;e pride of man and beest he laid adoun</L>
<L N="3828">Wher so he come vnto &thorn;e worldes ende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Comparison my&yogh;t neuere be maked.</L>
<L>Bytwix hym and ano&thorn;er conquerour<MILESTONE N="256b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;is world for drede of hym Ha&thorn; quaked.</L>
<L N="3832">He was of knyghthode and of fredom flour</L>
<L>ffortune him made &thorn;e heir of hur honour</L>
<L>Saue wyne and wommen no &thorn;ing my&yogh;t a-swage</L>
<L>His hegh entente in armes and laboure</L>
<L N="3836">So was he ful of louying corage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>What pite were it to hym &thorn;ou&yogh;e I &yogh;ou tolde</L>
<L>Of Darius and an hundred thowsand moo.</L>
<L>Of kyngges Princes. and Erles bold</L>
<L N="3840">Which he conquered and brou&yogh;t into woo</L>
<L>I say as fer as man may ride and goo.</L>
<L>The worlde was his what shuld I more devise</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou&yogh;e I write and told &yogh;ou euer moo.</L>
<L N="3844">Of his kinghode it my&yogh;t not suffise
<PB REF="00000598.tif" N="568"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="277"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Twelue &yogh;ere he regned as sai&thorn; Machabe</L>
<L>Philippes sone of Macedoyne he was</L>
<L>That furst was kinge of Grece &thorn;e cuntree</L>
<L N="3848">O wor&thorn;i gentile Alisaunder alas</L>
<L>That euer shuld [thee] falle Such a caas</L>
<L>Enpoysened of &thorn;i folk &thorn;ou were</L>
<L>Thine . sise . fortune ha&thorn; turned into an aas</L>
<L N="3852">And &yogh;it for &thorn;e ne weppe she neuere a tere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Who shal &yogh;eue teeres men to compleyne</L>
<L>The dee&thorn; of gentilnesse and of ffraunchise</L>
<L>That al &thorn;e worlde weelded in his demeyne</L>
<L N="3856">And &yogh;it him &thorn;ou&yogh;t hit my&yogh;t not suffise</L>
<L>So fful was his corage of high emprise</L>
<L>Allas who shal me helpe to endite</L>
<L>ffals fortune and poyson to despise</L>
<L N="3860">The which twoo of al this woo I wite</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Julius C&aelig;sar.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>By wisdome manhode and by labour<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Iulius Cesar/.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffro humblehede and fro Roial Maieste</L>
<L>Vp roos he Iulius &thorn;e Conquerour</L>
<L N="3864">That all &thorn;e Occident by londe and See</L>
<L>By strength of honde or ellis by trete</L>
<L>And vnto Roome made hem tributarie.</L>
<L>And Sithens of Rome &thorn;e Emperour was he /</L>
<L N="3868">Til &thorn;at fortune wexe his aduersarie<MILESTONE N="257a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A Mighty Cesar &thorn;at in Tessalye.</L>
<L>A&yogh;einst Pompius fader &thorn;ine in lawe</L>
<L>That of &thorn;e Orient had al &thorn;e chyualrie</L>
<L N="3872">As fer as &thorn;at &thorn;e day bygynne&thorn; dawe</L>
<L>Thogh &thorn;ou &thorn;orgh &thorn;i knyghthode ha&thorn; hem take and sclawe</L>
<L>Sauf fewe folk &thorn;at wi&thorn; Pompius fledde</L>
<L>Thorghe which &thorn;ou puttest al &thorn;e orient in awe</L>
<L N="3876">Thonke fortune &thorn;at so wel &thorn;e spedde
<PB REF="00000599.tif" N="569"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="278"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But now a litel while I wil bywaile</L>
<L>This Pompeus &thorn;is noble gouernour</L>
<L>Of Roome which &thorn;at fleigh at this bataille</L>
<L N="3880">I saye oon of his men a fals traitour</L>
<L>His hede of smote to wynne hym fauour</L>
<L>Of Iulius and hym &thorn;e hede brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Allas Pompey of the Orient conquerour</L>
<L N="3884">That fortune vnto such a funte brou&yogh;t</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>TO Rome a&yogh;eine repeire&thorn; Iulius.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; triumphe laureat ful high</L>
<L>But on a tyme Brutus Cassius</L>
<L N="3888">&thorn;at euere had of his astate Envie</L>
<L>fful priuely had made Conspiracie</L>
<L>A&yogh;einst &thorn;is Iulius in subtile wise /</L>
<L>And cast &thorn;e place in which he shuld dye</L>
<L N="3892">With boydekyns as I shal &yogh;ou &middot; devise</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This Iulius to &thorn;e Capithole went</L>
<L>Vppon a day as he was wonte to goon</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e Capitole anoon hym hente</L>
<L N="3896">This fals Brutus and his foule foon</L>
<L>And stiked hym wi&thorn; boydekyns anon</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; mony a wounde and &thorn;us &thorn;ei lete hym lye</L>
<L>But neuere grunte he at no stroke but oon</L>
<L N="3900">Or ellis at twoo but &yogh;if his storie lye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So manly was &thorn;is Iulius of herte</L>
<L>And so wel loued estately honeste</L>
<L>That &thorn;ou&yogh;e his dedly woundes so sore smerte</L>
<L N="3904">His mantel ouer his hippes cast he</L>
<L>ffor no man shuld se his privete</L>
<L>And as he lay on dyinge in a traunce<MILESTONE N="257b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And wist verrely &thorn;at dede was he</L>
<L N="3908">Of honeste &yogh;it had he remembraunce
<PB REF="00000600.tif" N="570"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="279"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Lucane to &thorn;is storie I recomende</L>
<L>And to Sweton and Valerius also.</L>
<L>That of His storie write&thorn; word and ende</L>
<L N="3912">How &thorn;at &thorn;ise grete conquerours twoo</L>
<L>ffortune was furst frende and si&thorn;en a foo/</L>
<L>No man ne trust vpon his fauour longe</L>
<L>But haue hure in a-waite euermoo</L>
<L N="3916">Witnes on alle &thorn;ise conquerours stronge</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Cresus.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This riche Cresus whilom kyng of lyde</L>
<L>O which Cresus Cyquus sore hym dradde</L>
<L>&YOGH;it was he kau&yogh;t amonges al his pride</L>
<L N="3920">And to be brent men to &thorn;e fure hym ladde</L>
<L>But suche a Reyne doune fro &thorn;e walken shadde</L>
<L>&thorn;at sclou&yogh;e &thorn;e fuyre and made hym to eskape</L>
<L>But to be war &yogh;it no grace he hadde</L>
<L N="3924">Til fortune on &thorn;e galous made hym gape</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan he askaped was he can not stent</L>
<L>ffor to bygynne a newe reyne a&yogh;eine</L>
<L>He wende wele for &thorn;at fortune hym sente</L>
<L N="3928">Suche happe &thorn;at he askaped &thorn;or&yogh;e &thorn;e reyne</L>
<L>&THORN;at of his foos he my&yogh;t not be sclayn</L>
<L>And Suche a sweuen vpon a ny&yogh;t he mette</L>
<L>Of which he was so proude and so fayn</L>
<L N="3932">That in vengeance he al his hert sette</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Vpon a tree he was as hym &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Ther Iubiter hym wassh bo&thorn; hals and Side</L>
<L>And Phebus eke a faire towale hym brou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="3936">To drye hym wi&thorn; an &thorn;erfore wex his pride</L>
<L>And to his dou&yogh;tere &thorn;at stood hym beside</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at he knewe in his sentence habounde</L>
<L>He bad hure telle hym what it signyfied</L>
<L N="3940">And she his dremes byganne ri&yogh;t &thorn;us expounde
<PB REF="00000601.tif" N="571"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="280"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The tree quod she &thorn;e galous is to mene</L>
<L>And Iubiter bitokene&thorn; snowe and reyne</L>
<L>And Phebus wi&thorn; his towale so clene.</L>
<L N="3944">Thoo bene the sone stremes forto sayn<MILESTONE N="258a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Thow shalt an honged be fadere certayn</L>
<L>Rayn shal &thorn;e wassh and sonne shal &thorn;e drye</L>
<L>Thus warned she hym ful plat and ful playn</L>
<L N="3948">His dou&yogh;ter [which] &thorn;at called was Phanye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>An honged was Cresus &thorn;e proude kinge</L>
<L>His Roial trone my&yogh;t hym not availe</L>
<L>Tregedie is noon o&thorn;er maner &thorn;inge</L>
<L N="3952">Ne can in synnynge cry ne bywaile</L>
<L>But &thorn;at fortune alway wil assaile</L>
<L>wi&thorn; vnware stroke &thorn;e regnes &thorn;at bene proude</L>
<L>ffor whan men trusten hir &thorn;an wil she faile</L>
<L N="3956">And keuere her bri&yogh;t face wi&thorn; a clowde</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>&para; Thus ende&thorn; &thorn;e monke his tale</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000602.tif" N="572">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="281">
<HEAD>And here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e nonpreest his prologe<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; The prologe;</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 258</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ho quod &thorn;e kny&yogh;t no more good of &thorn;is</L>
<L>That &yogh;e han said is ri&yogh;t ynowe ywis</L>
<L>And mochel more for litel heuynesse</L>
<L N="3960">Is ri&yogh;t ynough to mochel folk I gesse<NOTE PLACE="marg">[no gap in Petworth]</NOTE></L>
<L>[I sey for me / hit is a gret disese<MILESTONE UNIT="Addit. MS 5140 folio" N="272a"><I>and back</I></L>
<L>Wher as men haue ben / in gret welth and ese</L>
<L>To here of her sodeyn falle allas</L>
<L N="3964">And the contrarye / is Ioye and gret solas</L>
<L>And whan a man hath be / in poor estat</L>
<L>And clymbeth vp / and waxeth fortunat</L>
<L>And ther abidith / in prosperite</L>
<L N="3968">Such thyng is gladsom / as thynketh me</L>
<L>And of such thyng / were goodly for to telle</L>
<L>ya quod our hoost / bi seynt poules belle</L>
<L>ye sey soth / this monk hath clappid lowd</L>
<L N="3972">He spak how fortune / couered was with a clowd</L>
<L>I nat nere what / and also tragedie</L>
<L>Riht now ye herde / and parde no remedie</L>
<L>I[t i]s forto be wailyng and compleyne</L>
<L N="3976">ffor that that is don / and also it is a peyne</L>
<L>As ye han seid to heer of hevynesse</L>
<L>Sir monk nomore of this / so god you blesse</L>
<L>[You]r tale anoyeth / alle this companye</L>
<L>Such thyng / is nat worth / a bottirflye<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<B>Addit. MS 5140,</B> <I>extract stops</I>]</NOTE>]</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure tales done vs no sporte ne game</L>
<L>Wherfore sir monke or daun pers by &yogh;our name</L>
<L>I prey &yogh;ou hertely telle vs somwhat ellys</L>
<L N="3984">ffor sikerly ne were &thorn;e Clynkyng of &yogh;our bellis
<PB REF="00000603.tif" N="573"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="282"></L>
<L>That on &yogh;oure bridel honge on euery side</L>
<L>By heuene kynge &thorn;at for vs alle deyde</L>
<L>I shuld er &thorn;is haue falle doun for sclepe</L>
<L N="3988">Al &thorn;ough [&thorn;e] sclou&thorn;e had neuer be so depe</L>
<L>Than had &yogh;oure tale ben told in veyn</L>
<L>ffor certeynly as al &thorn;ise clerkes seyn</L>
<L>wher as a [man] may haue non audience</L>
<L N="3992">Nou&yogh;t helpe&thorn; it to telle his sentence</L>
<L>And wel I woote &thorn;e substaunce is in me</L>
<L>&YOGH;if eny &thorn;inge shal wel reported be</L>
<L>Sir say somwhat of huntyng I &yogh;ou preie</L>
<L N="3996">Nay quod &thorn;is monke I haue no lust to pleie</L>
<L>Now lat ano&thorn;er telle as I haue told</L>
<L>&THORN;an spak our hoost with rude spech and bold</L>
<L>And saide vnto &thorn;e nonnes preest anon</L>
<L>Come nere sir preest Come hider Sire Iohn<MILESTONE N="258b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4001">Telle vs such &thorn;ingges as may our hertis glade</L>
<L>Be bli&thorn; &thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;ou ride vpon a Iade</L>
<L>What &thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;ine hors be bo&thorn; foule and lene</L>
<L N="4004">&YOGH;if he wil serue &thorn;e rek nat a bene</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;at &thorn;i hert be mery euermoo.</L>
<L>&YOGH;is sir quod he &yogh;is hoost so mote I goo</L>
<L>But I be mery Iwis I wil be blamed.</L>
<L N="4008">And Ri&yogh;t anoon his tale he ha&thorn; atamed.</L>
<L>And &thorn;us seide to vs euerychon</L>
<L>My tale I wil bygynne anon<NOTE PLACE="marg">[spurious]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<TRAILER><B>&para; Thus ende&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e nonnes</B> preste</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000604.tif" N="574">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="283">
<HEAD><B>And here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e nonne</B> preest <B>his tale</B><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 258, <I>back</I></NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A poor wydowe somdel stope in age</L>
<L N="4012">was whilom dwelling in a narowe cotage</L>
<L>Besides a groue stonding in a dale</L>
<L>This widowe of which I telle &yogh;ou my tale</L>
<L>Si&thorn;ens &thorn;ilk day &thorn;at she was last a wiff</L>
<L N="4016">In paciens lad a ful sympul liff</L>
<L>ffor litel was hur Catel and hur rent</L>
<L>By Husbondry of such as god her sent</L>
<L>She fonde hure self and eke her doughtred twoo</L>
<L N="4020">Thre large sowes had she and no moo.</L>
<L>Thre kyen and eke a shepe &thorn;at hight malle</L>
<L>fful soty was hur boure and eke her halle</L>
<L>In whiche she ete mony a sclender mele</L>
<L N="4024">Of poynant sause hir neded neuer a dele</L>
<L>No deynte morsel passed hur &thorn;rote</L>
<L>Hir diete was acordant to her cote</L>
<L>Replecio ne made her neuer seke</L>
<L N="4028">Attemper diete was all her phisike</L>
<L>And exercise and hert sufficiance</L>
<L>The goute letted hur no &thorn;ing to daunce</L>
<L>Ne poplexie shent not her hede</L>
<L N="4032">Noo wyne dronke she nei&thorn;er white ne rede</L>
<L>Her boord was serued most wi&thorn; white and blake</L>
<L>Milk and broune brede in which she fond no lake</L>
<L>Seyned Bacon and somtyme an eye or tweye</L>
<L>ffor she was as It were a manere of a deye<MILESTONE N="259a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4037">A gardyne she had enclosed al aboute</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; stikkes and a drie diche wi&thorn;-oute</L>
<L>In which she had a cok &thorn;at hi&yogh;t chauntilere</L>
<L N="4040">In all &thorn;e londe of crowing was his pere
<PB REF="00000605.tif" N="575"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="284"></L>
<L>His mou&thorn; was myrier &thorn;an &thorn;e mery orgon</L>
<L>On masse daies &thorn;at in &thorn;e churche goon</L>
<L>Wel sikerer was &thorn;e crowyng in his logge</L>
<L N="4044">&THORN;an is a clokke or an abbay orlogge</L>
<L>By nature he crewe eche ascencioun</L>
<L>Of Equinoxial of &thorn;ilk toun</L>
<L>ffor whan degrees .xv. were descended.</L>
<L N="4048">&thorn;at knewe he &thorn;at it my&yogh;t not bene amended</L>
<L>His Combe was redder &thorn;an &thorn;e fyne Curall</L>
<L>And bateled as it were a castel wall</L>
<L>Ilike azure were his legges and his toone</L>
<L N="4052">His bille was blake and as &thorn;e gete it shone</L>
<L>His nailles witter &thorn;an &thorn;e lily floure</L>
<L>And ylike burnysshed gold was his coloure</L>
<L>This gentile Cok had in his gouernaunce</L>
<L N="4056">Vij. hennys forto doon his plesaunce</L>
<L>Which weren his sustres and his paramours</L>
<L>And wonder like to hym as of colours</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e which &thorn;e fairest hwed vnder &thorn;rote</L>
<L N="4060">Was clepe fair Damysel Pertilote</L>
<L>Curtais she was discrete and debonaire</L>
<L>And Companable and bere her self so faire</L>
<L>Si&thorn;ens &thorn;ilk day &thorn;at she was vij. ny&yogh;t olde</L>
<L N="4064">That trewly she ha&thorn; &thorn;e hert in hold</L>
<L>Of Chauntelere loukyn in euery lith</L>
<L>He loued hure so &thorn;at wel was hym &thorn;er with</L>
<L>But such a Ioie as it was to here hem singe</L>
<L N="4068">Whan &thorn;at &thorn;e bri&yogh;t sonne gan to sprynge</L>
<L>In swete accorde my lief is fare a londe</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ilk tyme as I haue vnderstonde</L>
<L>Beestes and briddes coude speke and synge</L>
<L N="4072">And so byfelle &thorn;at in &thorn;e dawynge</L>
<L>As Chauntecleer amonges his wyues alle</L>
<L>Sat on his perch &thorn;at was in &thorn;e halle<MILESTONE N="259b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And next hym sat &thorn;is faire Pertilote</L>
<L N="4076">This Chaunteclere gan gronen in his &thorn;rote
<PB REF="00000606.tif" N="576"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="285"></L>
<L>As a man &thorn;at is in his dreme drecched sore</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at Pertilote &thorn;us herd hym rore</L>
<L>She was a-gast and seide hert dere</L>
<L N="4080">What eile&thorn; &yogh;ou to grone in &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>&YOGH;e bene a verray scleper fy for shame</L>
<L>And he answerd and saide &thorn;us madame</L>
<L>I prey &yogh;ou &thorn;at &yogh;e take it not a greef</L>
<L N="4084">By god me mette &thorn;at I was in such mescheef</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t nowe &thorn;at &yogh;it myn hert is sore afri&yogh;t</L>
<L>Nowe god [quod] he my sweuen rede ari&yogh;t</L>
<L>And kepe my body out of foule prisoun</L>
<L N="4088">Me mette &thorn;at I romed vp and doun</L>
<L>With-in our yerde wher as I segh a beest</L>
<L>Was lik an hounde and wold haue made arest</L>
<L>Vpon my body and wold haue had me dede</L>
<L N="4092">His colour was bytwix white and red</L>
