<L>That in &thorn;e groue had wonned &yogh;eeres &thorn;re</L>
<L>By high ymagynacion to-fore cast</L>
<L N="4408">&thorn;e same nyght &thorn;orgh-out &thorn;e hegges brast</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e &yogh;eerd &thorn;er chauntelere &thorn;e faire</L>
<L>was wonte and eke his wyues to repaire</L>
<L>And in a bedde of wortes stille he lay</L>
<L N="4412">Till it was passed vndren of &thorn;e day</L>
<L>Waitynge his tyme on chaunteler to falle</L>
<L>As gladly done &thorn;ise homycydes alle</L>
<L>That in a-waite ligge to murdre men &middot;</L>
<L N="4416">O fals murdere rowkyng in &thorn;i den</L>
<L>O newe Scariot o. newe Genylon</L>
<L>ffals dissimylour o greke Symon</L>
<L>&THORN;at brou&yogh;test troye al vtterly to sorowe</L>
<L N="4420">O chauntelere acursed be &thorn;at morowe</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou into [&thorn;i] &yogh;eerd flegh from &thorn;e bemes</L>
<L>Thow were ful wel ywarned by &thorn;i dremes<MILESTONE N="264a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That ilke day was perilous to &thorn;e</L>
<L N="4424">But &thorn;at .&thorn;at god a-fore wote most nedes be</L>
<L>Aftere &thorn;e opynyon of certeyn clerkes</L>
<L>Wittnesse of hym &thorn;at eny clerk es</L>
<L>That in scole [is] grete altercacion</L>
<L N="4428">In &thorn;is mater and grete disputacion</L>
<L>And ha&thorn; bene of an C. thousand men /</L>
<L>But I ne can[not] bult it to &thorn;e brenne</L>
<L>As can &thorn;e holy doctour augustyne</L>
<L N="4432">Or boys or &thorn;e Bisshop Bradwardyne</L>
<L>Whedere &thorn;at goddys wille a-fore wetyng</L>
<L>Streyne&thorn; me nedely forto doon a &thorn;ing</L>
<L>Nedely clepe I symple necessite</L>
<L N="4436">Or ellis &yogh;if &thorn;e free chois be graunted me
<PB REF="00000616.tif" N="586"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="295"></L>
<L>To do &thorn;at same &thorn;ing or do it nou&yogh;t &middot;</L>
<L>Thou&yogh;e god forwote it er it was wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Er of his wetyng streyne&thorn; neuer a dele</L>
<L N="4440">But by necessite condicionele</L>
<L>I wil not haue to done of such matere</L>
<L>My tale is of a cokke as &yogh;e shullen here</L>
<L>That toke his counsaile of his wif with sorowe</L>
<L N="4444">To walken in &thorn;e &yogh;eerde vpon &thorn;e morowe</L>
<L>That he had mette &thorn;e dreme &thorn;at I &yogh;ou tolde</L>
<L>Womm[an]es counsaile is ful ofte colde</L>
<L>Womm[an]es counsaile brou&yogh;t vs first to woo</L>
<L N="4448">And made Adam from paradys to goo.</L>
<L>Ther he was ful mery an wel at ese</L>
<L>But for I note whom I my&yogh;t displese</L>
<L>If I counsaile of wommen wold blame</L>
<L N="4452">Passe ouere for I seide it in my game</L>
<L>Rede awters wher &thorn;ei trete of such matere</L>
<L>And what &thorn;ei seyne of wommen here</L>
<L>Thise bene &thorn;e cokkes wordes and not myne</L>
<L N="4456">I can no harme of no womman devyne</L>
<L>ffaire in &thorn;e sonde to bath hur merely</L>
<L>lith pertelote and al hure susters bye</L>
<L>A&yogh;einst &thorn;e sonne and chauntelere so fre</L>
<L>Songe meryer &thorn;an &thorn;e meermaiden in &thorn;e See<MILESTONE N="264b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4461">ffor phisialogus sai&thorn; witterly</L>
<L>How &thorn;at &thorn;ei syngen wel and merely</L>
<L>And so byfelle as he cast his ye</L>
<L N="4464">Amonges &thorn;e wortes vppon a botterflie</L>
<L>He was war of this fox &thorn;at lay ful lowe</L>
<L>No &thorn;inge ne lust hym &thorn;an for to crowe</L>
<L>But cries anon cok cok and vp he sterte</L>
<L N="4468">As a man &thorn;at was affraied in his herte</L>
<L>ffor naturelly a beest desire&thorn; to flee</L>
<L>ffro his contrarie if he may it See</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh;e he neuer had seye it erst with his ye</L>
<L N="4472">This chauntelere whan he hym gan aspie
<PB REF="00000617.tif" N="587"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="296"></L>
<L>He wold haue fledde but &thorn;at &thorn;e fox anon</L>
<L>Saide gentile sir allas what hast &thorn;ou don</L>
<L>Bene &yogh;e affraied of me &thorn;at am &yogh;oure frende</L>
<L N="4476">Certes sir &thorn;an ben &yogh;e vnhende</L>
<L>If I to &yogh;ou wil harme or vilanye</L>
<L>I am not come &yogh;our counsaile to aspie</L>
<L>But trewly &thorn;e cause of my comynge</L>
<L N="4480">was oonly to harken how &thorn;at &yogh;e singe</L>
<L>ffor trewly &yogh;e han as mery a steuen</L>
<L>As aungel ha&thorn; &thorn;at is in heuen</L>
<L>Ther-with &yogh;e han in musike more felinge</L>
<L N="4484">&thorn;an had boys or eny &thorn;at can synge</L>
<L>My lorde &yogh;our fadere god his saule blisse</L>
<L>And eke &yogh;oure modere and hur gentilnesse</L>
<L>Han in myn hous bene to &yogh;ou grete ese</L>
<L N="4488">And Certes sir ri&yogh;t fain wold I &yogh;ou plese</L>
<L>But for men speken of syngynge I wil seye</L>
<L>So mot I brouke myn eien tweye</L>
<L>Sauf &yogh;e I ne herd neuer man so synge</L>
<L N="4492">As did &yogh;oure fader in &thorn;e mornynge</L>
<L>Certes it was of hert al &thorn;at he songe</L>
<L>And forto make his vois &thorn;e more stronge</L>
<L>He wold so peyn hym &thorn;at wi&thorn; both his yen</L>
<L N="4496">He most wynke so loude he did crien</L>
<L>And stonden on his typtoon &thorn;erwi&thorn;al&middot;</L>
<L>And strecche for&thorn; his nek longe and small<MILESTONE N="265a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And eke he was of such discrecion</L>
<L N="4500">That &thorn;er nas no man in no region</L>
<L>That him in songe or wisdom my&yogh;t passe</L>
<L>I haue wel red daun Burnel &thorn;er as</L>
<L>Amonge his vers &thorn;er was a cok</L>
<L N="4504">[That] ffor a preestes sone &yogh;aue hym a knok</L>
<L>Vpon his legge whiles he was &yogh;onge and nyce</L>
<L>He made hym forto lese his benefice</L>
<L>But certeyn &thorn;er nys noon comparison</L>
<L N="4508">Bytwix &thorn;e wisdom and discrecion
<PB REF="00000618.tif" N="588"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="297"></L>
<L>Of &yogh;oure fadere and of his subtilite</L>
<L>Now synge&thorn; sir for seint charite</L>
<L>Lat see conne &yogh;e &yogh;oure fadere countrefete</L>
<L N="4512">This Chauntelere his wenges gan to bete</L>
<L>As man &thorn;at coude nat his treson aspie</L>
<L>So was he rauessed wi&thorn; his flaterye</L>
<L>Allas &yogh;e lordes mony a fals flatour</L>
<L N="4516">Is in &yogh;our court and mony a losengour</L>
<L>That plesen &yogh;ou more by my fei&thorn;</L>
<L>That he &thorn;at so&thorn;fastnesse vnto &yogh;o<SUP>u</SUP> sei&thorn;.</L>
<L>Rede&thorn; Ecclesiastre of flaterye</L>
<L N="4520">Be&thorn; ware &yogh;e lordes of her trecherye</L>
<L>This Chaunteclere stood high vpon his toos</L>
<L>Strecchinge his nek and held his eien cloos</L>
<L>And gan to crowe loude for &thorn;e nones</L>
<L N="4524">And daun Russel stert vp al at ones</L>
<L>And by &thorn;e Gargaige hent Chaunteclere</L>
<L>And on his bak toward the wood hym bere</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;it was ther no man hym swed</L>
<L N="4528">O Destany &thorn;at maist not bene eschewed</L>
<L>Allas &thorn;at chaunteclere fel fro &thorn;e bemes</L>
<L>Allas his wif ne rou&yogh;t not of dremes</L>
<L>And on a friday felle all &thorn;is mesch&amacr;unce</L>
<L N="4532">O Venus &thorn;at art goddes of plesaunce</L>
<L>Si&thorn;ens &thorn;at &thorn;i seruaunte was &thorn;is chaunteclere</L>
<L>And in &thorn;i seruise did al his powere</L>
<L>More for delit &thorn;an &thorn;e world to multiplie</L>
<L>Whi woldest &thorn;ou suffre on &thorn;i day to dye<MILESTONE N="265b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4537">O Gaufrede dere maistere souereyn</L>
<L>&THORN;at whan &thorn;e wor&thorn;i kinge Richard was sclayn</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; shot compleyndest his de&thorn; so sore</L>
<L N="4540">Whi ne had I nowe &thorn;i sentence and &thorn;i lore</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffriday forto chide as did &yogh;e</L>
<L>ffor on a friday shortely sclayne was he</L>
<L>&THORN;an wolde I shewe howe &thorn;at I coude playne</L>
<L N="4544">ffor chaunteclere and for his peyne
<PB REF="00000619.tif" N="589"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="298"></L>
<L>Certus such crye ne lamentacion</L>
<L>was of ladies made whan &thorn;at Ilyon</L>
<L>Was wonne. and pirrus with his strei&yogh;t swerd</L>
<L N="4548">Whan he hent king Prian by &thorn;e beerd</L>
<L>And sclayn hym as seide Enneidos</L>
<L>As maden all &thorn;e hennes in &thorn;e cloos</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ei had seie of chaunteclere &thorn;e si&yogh;t</L>
<L N="4552">But souereyn dame pertelote shri&yogh;t</L>
<L>wel lodder &thorn;an did Hasdrubaldes wif</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at her husbonde had lost his lif</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;e romaynes had brent Cartage</L>
<L N="4556">She was so ful of torment and of Rage</L>
<L>That wilfully into &thorn;e fire she stert</L>
<L>And brent her self wi&thorn; a stedfast hert</L>
<L>O wooful hennys ri&yogh;t so criden &yogh;e</L>
<L N="4560">As whan &thorn;at Nero brent &thorn;e Cite</L>
<L>Of Rome criden &thorn;e Cenatours wyues</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at her husbondes shulden lese her lyues</L>
<L>wi&thorn;-outen Gilt [&thorn;is] Nero ha&thorn; hem sclayn</L>
<L N="4564">Now wil I turne to my tale a&yogh;ein</L>
<L>This sely widowe and hure dou&yogh;ters two</L>
<L>Herden &thorn;e hennys crien and make woo</L>
<L>And out atte door sterten &thorn;ei anoon</L>
<L N="4568">And segh &thorn;e fox toward &thorn;e groue goon</L>
<L>And bare on his bak &thorn;e Cok away</L>
<L>They criden out and harawe and welaway</L>
<L>A ha &thorn;e fox and after hym &thorn;ei ran</L>
<L N="4572">And eke wi&thorn; staues mony an o&thorn;er man</L>
<L>Ran Coll our dogge. talbot and Garlonde</L>
<L>And Malkyn wi&thorn; her dystaf in hure honde<MILESTONE N="266a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ran cowe and calf and eke the verrey hogges</L>
<L N="4576">Sore afferd for berking of dogges</L>
<L>And shetinge of men and wommen eke</L>
<L>&thorn;ei ronne so &thorn;eire hertes &thorn;ei &thorn;ou&yogh;t to breke</L>
<L>&thorn;ei &yogh;elden as feendes don in helle</L>
<L N="4580">The dogges criden as men wold hem quelle
<PB REF="00000620.tif" N="590"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="299"></L>
<L>Out of the hyues come &thorn;e swarme of bees</L>
<L>The gees for fere flowen in &thorn;e trees</L>
<L>So hidous was the noise .O benedicite</L>
<L N="4584">Certes he Iak strawe and his mayne</L>
<L>Ne made neuer showtes half so shrille</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at &thorn;ei wolde eny flemmyng kille</L>
<L>As &thorn;at ilk day was made vpon &thorn;e fox</L>
<L N="4588">Of bras &thorn;ei brou&yogh;t bemes and of box</L>
<L>Of horn and boon in which &thorn;ei pouped</L>
<L>And &thorn;erwi&thorn;al &thorn;ei schrited and showted.</L>
<L>It semed as &thorn;at heuene shulde falle</L>
<L N="4592">Now good I prey &yogh;ou harkene&thorn; alle</L>
<L>Lo how fortune turne&thorn; sodeynly</L>
<L>The hope and eke pride of her envie</L>
<L>This cok/ &thorn;at lay vppon the fox bak</L>
<L N="4596">In al his drede vnto &thorn;e fox spak</L>
<L>And saide Sire if I were as &yogh;e</L>
<L>&YOGH;it shuld I say as wis god helpe me</L>
<L>Turne a&yogh;eine &yogh;e proude cherles alle</L>
<L N="4600">A verrey pestilence vppon &yogh;ou falle</L>
<L>Nowe am I come vnto &thorn;is wodys side</L>
<L>Maugre &yogh;oure hede &thorn;e cok shal here abide</L>
<L>I wol hym ete in fei&thorn; and &thorn;at anon</L>
<L N="4604">The fox answerde in fai&thorn; it shal be don</L>
<L>And [as] he spak &thorn;at worde al sodeynly</L>
<L>This Cok brak from his mou&thorn; delyuerly</L>
<L>And high vppon a tree he flegh anon</L>
<L N="4608">And whan &thorn;e fox segh &thorn;at he was gon</L>
<L>Allas quod he O chauntelere allas</L>
<L>I haue quod he done to &yogh;ou trespas</L>
<L>In as moch as I made &yogh;ou aferd</L>
<L>Whan I &yogh;ou hent and brou&yogh;t out of &thorn;e &yogh;erde<MILESTONE N="266b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4613">But sire I did it not in no wicked entent</L>
<L>Comme&thorn; doune and I shal telle &yogh;ou what I ment</L>
<L>I shal saie so&thorn; god helpe me soo</L>
<L N="4616">Nay &thorn;an quod he I schrewe vs bo&thorn; twoo
<PB REF="00000621.tif" N="591"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="300"></L>
<L>And first I schrewe my self bo&thorn; blood and bones</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou bigile me ofter &thorn;an ones</L>
<L>Thow shalt no more wi&thorn; &thorn;i flaterie</L>
<L N="4620">Do me swynk and wink wi&thorn; myn ye</L>
<L>ffor he &thorn;at wynket whan he shuld see</L>
<L>As wisly god lat hym neuer &thorn;ee</L>
<L>Nay quod &thorn;e fox god &yogh;eue hym meschaunce</L>
<L N="4624">That is so vndiscrete of gouernaunce</L>
<L>That Iangele&thorn; whan he shuld haue pees</L>
<L>Loo such is forto be rechelees</L>
<L>And necligent and truste&thorn; on flaterie</L>
<L N="4628">But &yogh;e &thorn;at holden &thorn;is foly</L>
<L>As of a Cok of a fox and of an henne</L>
<L>Take&thorn; &thorn;e Moralite good men&middot;</L>
<L>ffor seint poule sei&thorn; al &thorn;at writen is</L>
<L N="4632">To our doctrine it is writen ywis /</L>
<L>Take&thorn; &thorn;e fruyte and lat &thorn;e chaf be stille</L>
<L>Nowe good god if it be &thorn;i wille</L>
<L>As sei&thorn; my lorde so make vs all good men</L>
<L N="4636">And bringe vs al to his blisse Amen.</L>
</LG>
