<HEAD>GROUP <B>H.</B> FRAGMENT IX.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&sect; <B>1.</B> THE MANCIPLE'S HEAD-LINK.</HEAD>
<HEAD><B>PETWORTH MS.</B></HEAD>
<HEAD><B>And &thorn;us bygynnes &thorn;e manciples tale.</B><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 266, <I>back</I></NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WEte &yogh;e not where stont a litel toune<NOTE PLACE="marg"><B>&para; The prologe/</B></NOTE></L>
<L>Which &thorn;at is cleped bob vp and doune</L>
<L>Vnder &thorn;e blee in Caunterbery waye</L>
<L N="4">Ther gan our hooste to Iape and playe</L>
<L>And saide Sirres donne is in &thorn;e myre</L>
<L>Is &thorn;er no man for preiere ne for hyre</L>
<L>That wil awake our felawe behinde</L>
<L N="8">A theef my&yogh;t hym robbe and bynde</L>
<L>Se howe he nappe&thorn; for goddys bones.</L>
<L>Awaite he wil falle from his hors at ones</L>
<L>This is a coke of london wi&thorn; meschaunce</L>
<L N="12">Do hym come for&thorn; he knowe&thorn; his penaunce<MILESTONE N="267a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor he shal telle a tale be my fay</L>
<L>Al &thorn;ou&yogh;e it be nat worth a botel of hay</L>
<L>Awake &thorn;ou coke god &yogh;eue &thorn;e Sorowe</L>
<L N="16">What aile&thorn; &thorn;e to slepe so by &thorn;e morowe</L>
<L>Hast &thorn;ou had fleen to ny&yogh;t or &thorn;ou art dronke</L>
<L>Or hast &thorn;ou al ny&yogh;t wi&thorn; som quene yswonke</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;ou maist not holde vp &thorn;ine hede</L>
<L N="20">This Coke &thorn;at was [ful] pale and no &thorn;ing rede</L>
<L>Saide to oure hooste so god me blesse</L>
<L>As &thorn;er is holden on me such heuynesse</L>
<L>That I not wheder me were leuer sclepe</L>
<L N="24">Than &thorn;e best Galon wyne in chepe
<PB REF="00000623.tif" N="593"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="577"></L>
<L N="25">wel quod &thorn;e manciple it wil done ese</L>
<L>To &thorn;e Sir Coke and to no wi&yogh;t mysplese</L>
<L>whiche &thorn;at riden in &thorn;is company</L>
<L N="28">&thorn;at soo our hoost wil of his curtesy</L>
<L>I wil as nowe excuse &thorn;e of &thorn;i tale</L>
<L>ffor in good fay &thorn;i visage is ri&yogh;t pale</L>
<L>&thorn;ine eyen dasen as me &thorn;enke&thorn;</L>
<L N="32">And wel I woot &thorn;i breth sore stynke&thorn;</L>
<L>That shewe&thorn; &thorn;ou nart not wel disposed.</L>
<L>Of me certaine &thorn;ou shalt not bene glosed.</L>
<L>See howe he goleth &thorn;is dronken wi&yogh;t</L>
<L N="36">As &thorn;owe he wolde swoune anon ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>Hold cloos &thorn;i mou&thorn;e man by &thorn;i fader kyn</L>
<L>The deuel of helle sette his foote &thorn;erIn.</L>
<L>Thy cursed breeth wil affecte vs alle</L>
<L N="40">ffy stynkinge hogge foule mot &thorn;e byfalle</L>
<L>Now take&thorn; hede sirs of &thorn;is lusty man</L>
<L>Now swete sir wil ye Iust at &thorn;e fan</L>
<L>Therto me &thorn;enke&thorn; &yogh;e be wel yshape</L>
<L N="44">&para; I trowe &yogh;e han dronken wyne grape</L>
<L>And &thorn;at is whan men pley with a strawe</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;is speche &thorn;e coke wex al wrawe</L>
<L>[And on the Maunciple. gan to nodde fast</L>
<L N="48">ffor lak of speche. and downe the hors hym cast</L>
<L>Where as he lay til that men hym vptoke</L>
<L>This was a faire cheuache. of a cooke</L>
<L>Allas that he nad. hold hym bi his ladill</L>
<L N="52">And or that he ageyn. were in his sadill<MILESTONE UNIT="MS Reg. 17 D 15 folio" N="285a">]</L>
<L>Ther was grete schovuyng to and froo</L>
<L>To lift hym up and mykel care and woo</L>
<L>So vnweldy was &thorn;is appalled goost</L>
<L N="56">And to &thorn;e manciple &thorn;an speke our hoost<MILESTONE N="267b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>By cause drink ha&thorn; Dominacion</L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;is man by my sauacion</L>
<L>I trowe he wolde lewdely telle his tale</L>
<L N="60">ffor were it wyne or ellis moyst ale
<PB REF="00000624.tif" N="594"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="578"></L>
<L N="61">That he ha&thorn; dronken he speke&thorn; in his nose</L>
<L>And galpe&thorn; fast and eke he ha&thorn; &thorn;e pose</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; also to doo more &thorn;an ynogh</L>
<L N="64">To kepe hym and his capel out of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> sclou&yogh;gh</L>
<L>And if he falle fro his capel eft sone</L>
<L>Than shal we alle haue ynogh to done</L>
<L>In liftinge vp of his heuy corps</L>
<L N="68">Telle on &thorn;i tale of hym make I no force</L>
<L>But nowe Maunciple in fei&thorn; &thorn;ou art to nyce</L>
<L>Thus openly to repreue hym of his vice</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er day he wil perauenture</L>
<L N="72">Recleyme &thorn;e and bringe &thorn;e to lure</L>
<L>I mene he speke wold of smale &thorn;ingges</L>
<L>As forto pynchen at &thorn;i rekenyngges</L>
<L>That were not honest &yogh;if it come to preef</L>
<L N="76">Nowe quod the maunciple &thorn;at were a gret mescheef</L>
<L>So my&yogh;t he bringe me in &thorn;e snare</L>
<L>&YOGH;it had I leuer paien for &thorn;e mare</L>
<L>Which he rit vpon &thorn;an he shuld with me strive</L>
<L N="80">I wil not wre&thorn; hym as mot I &thorn;rive</L>
<L>what &thorn;at I spak I saide it in my bourde</L>
<L>And wote &yogh;e what I haue here in a gourde</L>
<L>A drau&yogh;t of wyne &yogh;e of a ripe grape</L>
<L N="84">And ri&yogh;t anoon &yogh;e shul se a good Iape</L>
<L>This Coke shal drynk &thorn;erof &yogh;if &thorn;at I may</L>
<L>Vp peyne of de&thorn; he wil nat say me nay</L>
<L>And certeynly to tellen as it was</L>
<L N="88">Of &thorn;is vessel &thorn;e Coke dronk fast alas</L>
<L>What nede&thorn; hit he dronk ynou&yogh;e to-forn</L>
<L>And whan he had poped in his horn</L>
<L>To &thorn;e Manciple he toke &thorn;e gourde ageyn</L>
<L N="92">And of &thorn;at drinke &thorn;e Coke was wonder feyn</L>
<L>And &thorn;onked hym in such wise as he coude</L>
<L>Than gan oure hoost to laughen wondere loude<MILESTONE N="268a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And saide I see wel it is necessarie</L>
<L N="96">Where &thorn;at we goon good drink wi&thorn; vs to carie
<PB REF="00000625.tif" N="595"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="579"></L>
<L N="97">ffor &thorn;at wil turne rancour and dissese</L>
<L>To pees and loue and mony a wronge to sese</L>
<L>O Bachus blessed be &thorn;i name</L>
<L N="100">That so can turne ernest into game</L>
<L>Worship and &thorn;onk be vnto &thorn;e</L>
<L>ffor of &thorn;is matere &yogh;e gete no more of me</L>
<L>Telle on &thorn;ou manciple I &thorn;e pray</L>
<L N="104">Wel sir quod he now herkene&thorn; what I say</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; Thus ende&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e Manciple</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000626.tif" N="596">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="580">
<HEAD>&para; The Tale.;&verbar;. And here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e manciple his tale<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 268</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="105">WHan Phebus dwelt here in &thorn;is er&thorn;e adoun</L>
<L>As olde bokes maken mencioun</L>
<L>He was &thorn;e most lusty bachilere</L>
<L N="108">Of al &thorn;is world and eke &thorn;e best archere</L>
<L>He sclough Phiton &thorn;e serpent as he lay</L>
<L>Scleping a&yogh;einst &thorn;e sonne vpon a day</L>
<L>And mony a no&thorn;er wor&thorn;i noble dede</L>
<L N="112">He wi&thorn; his bowe wrou&yogh;t as men may rede</L>
<L>Pleien he coude on euery mynstralcie</L>
<L>And syngen &thorn;at it was a melodye</L>
<L>To harken of his cleere voys &thorn;e soun</L>
<L N="116">Certes &thorn;e kynge of Thebes Amphioun</L>
<L>That wi&thorn; hys syngging walled &thorn;at cite</L>
<L>Coude neuere synge half so wel as he</L>
<L>Therto he was &thorn;e semeliest man</L>
<L N="120">That is or was si&thorn; &thorn;e world bygan.</L>
<L>What nede&thorn; it is fetures to discrive</L>
<L>ffor in &thorn;is world was noon so faire alyue</L>
<L>He was &thorn;er-with fulfilled of gentilnesse</L>
<L N="124">Of honure and of parfit wor&thorn;inesse</L>
<L>This Phebus &thorn;at was flour of bachelerie</L>
<L>As wel in fredom as in Chiualrie</L>
<L>ffor disport and in signe eke of victorie</L>
<L N="128">Of Pheton so as telle&thorn; vs &thorn;e storie</L>
<L>was wont to beren in his honde a bowe</L>
<L>Now ha&thorn; &thorn;is Phebus in his hows a crowe<MILESTONE N="268a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Which in a Cage he fostred mony a day</L>
<L N="132">And tau&yogh;t it to speke as men doon a Iaye
<PB REF="00000627.tif" N="597"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="581"></L>
<L N="133">White was &thorn;is crowe as is a white swan</L>
<L>And countrefeted &thorn;e speche of euery man</L>
<L>He cowde whan he shuld telle a tale</L>
<L N="136">Ther-wi&thorn; in al &thorn;is londe &thorn;er nys no ny&yogh;tyngale</L>
<L>That cowde by an hundred thousan dele</L>
<L>Synge so mery and eke so wel</L>
<L>Now had &thorn;is phebus in his hous a wif</L>
<L N="140">Which &thorn;at he loued more &thorn;an his owne lif</L>
<L>And nyght and day did euer diligence</L>
<L>Her for to plese and done reuerence</L>
<L>Sauf oonly &yogh;if I &thorn;e so&thorn; shal sayn</L>
<L N="144">Ialous he was and wold haue kept hure fayn</L>
<L>ffor hym were lo&thorn;e Iiaped forto be</L>
<L>And so euery man wold in such degre</L>
<L>But al for nau&yogh;t for it availe&thorn; no&yogh;t</L>
<L N="148">A good wif &thorn;at is clene of werk and &thorn;o&yogh;t</L>
<L>Shuld not be kepte in noon awaite certeyn</L>
<L>And trewly &thorn;e labour is in veyn</L>
<L>To kepe a schrewe for it wil not be</L>
<L N="152">This hold I for a verrey nycete</L>
<L>To spille labour forto kepe wyues</L>
<L>Thus writen olde clerkes in her lyues</L>
<L>But nowe to purpos as I first bygan &middot;</L>
<L N="156">This wor&thorn;i phebus doo&thorn; al &thorn;at he can/</L>
<L>To plesen hure wenyng by such plesaunce</L>
<L>And for his manhode and his gouernaunce</L>
<L>That no man shuld haue put hym from hir grace</L>
<L N="160">But god it wote &thorn;er may no man enbrace</L>
<L>As to destroie a &thorn;inge which &thorn;at nature</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; naturelly sette in a creature</L>
<L>Take eny bridde and put it in a cage</L>
<L N="164">And doo al &thorn;ine entent and &thorn;i corage</L>
<L>To fostere it tenderly wi&thorn; mete and drink</L>
<L>Of alle deyntise &thorn;at &thorn;ou canst by-&thorn;enk</L>
<L>And kepe it also clenly as he may</L>
<L N="168">Al &thorn;ou&yogh;e his Cage of gold be neuer so gay<MILESTONE N="269a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000628.tif" N="598"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="582"></L>
<L N="169">&YOGH;it ha&thorn; &thorn;is brid by twenty &thorn;ousand fold</L>
<L>Leuer in a forest &thorn;at is wilde and cold</L>
<L>Goon ete wormes and suche wrecchednesse</L>
<L N="172">ffor euer &thorn;is bridde wol doon his bysynes</L>
<L>To escape out of his cage if he may</L>
<L>His liberte &thorn;e bridde desire&thorn; ay</L>
<L>Lat take a cat and fostre hym wel with mylk</L>
<L N="176">And tendere flesshe and make his couche of silk</L>
<L>And lat hym seen a mous goo by &thorn;e wall</L>
<L>And anoon he wayueth mylk flessh and all</L>
<L>And euery deynte &thorn;at is in &thorn;e hous</L>
<L N="180">Suche appetit ha&thorn; he to ete a mous</L>
<L>Lo here ha&thorn; lust his domynaci&omacr;n</L>
<L>And appetit fleme&thorn; discreci&omacr;n</L>
<L>As &thorn;e wolf ha&thorn; also a vileyns kynde</L>
<L N="184">The lewdest wolf &thorn;at she may fynde</L>
<L>Or leest of reputacion &thorn;at wil she take</L>
<L>In tyme whan hur lust to haue a make</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ise ensamples speke I. by &thorn;ise men</L>
<L N="188">That bene vntrewe and no &thorn;ing by wommen</L>
<L>ffor men han euer a likerous appetit</L>
<L>On lower &thorn;ing to performe her delite</L>
<L>Than on her wyues bene &thorn;ei neuere so faire</L>
<L N="192">Ne neuere so trewe ne so debonaire</L>
<L>fflesshe is so newefongel wi&thorn; meschaunce</L>
<L>That we ne konne no &thorn;inge han plesaunce</L>
<L>That sowne&thorn; in vertue eny while</L>
<L N="196">This Phebus which &thorn;at &thorn;ou&yogh;t vpon no gile</L>
<L>Deceyued was for al his Iolite</L>
<L>ffor vnder hym ano&thorn;er had she</L>
<L>A man of litel reputaci&omacr;n</L>
<L N="200">Not wor&thorn; to phebus in comparison</L>
<L>The more harme is it happe&thorn; oft soo</L>
<L>Of whoch &thorn;er commeth mochel harme and woo</L>
<L>And so byfelle whan phebus was absent</L>
<L N="204">His wif anoon ha&thorn; for her lemman sent
<PB REF="00000629.tif" N="599"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="583"></L>
<L N="205">Here lemman certes &thorn;is is a knauyssh speche</L>
<L>ffor&yogh;eue&thorn; it me and &thorn;at I &yogh;ou biseche<MILESTONE N="269b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>The wise Plato sei&thorn; as &yogh;e may <NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>first</I> here rede]</NOTE>rede</L>
<L N="208">&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> Word mot nedes accorde wi&thorn; &thorn;e dede</L>
<L>&YOGH;if men shal telle proprely a &thorn;inge</L>
<L>The worde mot Cosyn be to &thorn;e workinge</L>
<L>I am a boistous man ri&yogh;t &thorn;us say I</L>
<L N="212">Ther nys no difference trewly</L>
<L>Bitwix a wif &thorn;at is of hie degre</L>
<L>&YOGH;if of her body dishonest she be</L>
<L>And a poor wenche o&thorn;er &thorn;an &thorn;is</L>
<L N="216">&YOGH;if it so be &thorn;ei wirk bo&thorn; amys</L>
<L>But &thorn;at &thorn;e gentile is in state aboue</L>
<L>She shal be cleped his lady as in loue</L>
<L>And for &thorn;at o&thorn;er is a poor womman</L>
<L N="220">She shal be cleped his wench and his lemman.</L>
<L>And god it woote myn owne der bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>Men sayn &thorn;at oon lith as lowe as do&thorn; &thorn;at o&thorn;er</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t so bitwix a titles tyraunt</L>
<L N="224">And an houlaw<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>or</I> honlaw]</NOTE> and a &thorn;eef erraunt</L>
<L>The same I say &thorn;er nys no difference</L>
<L>To Alisaunder was tolde &thorn;at sentence</L>
<L>That for &thorn;e tyraunt is of gretere my&yogh;t</L>
<L N="228">By force of mayne for sclen doun ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>And brennen hous and home and make al playn</L>
<L>Lo &thorn;erfore is cleped a Capitayn</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e outlaw ha&thorn; but smal mayne</L>
<L N="232">And may not doon so grete an harme as he</L>
<L>Ne bringe a contre to so grete meschief</L>
<L>Men clepen hym an outlay or a &thorn;eef</L>
<L>But sor I am a man not text wel</L>
<L N="236">I wil not telle of Titus neuer a dele</L>
<L>I wil go to my tale as I byganne</L>
<L>Whan phebus [wif] had sent for her lemman</L>
<L>Anoon &thorn;ei wrou&yogh;ten al her lust volage</L>
<L N="240">This white crowe &thorn;at henge ay in &thorn;e cage
<PB REF="00000630.tif" N="600"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="584"></L>
<L N="241">Bihelde her werk and saide neuer a word</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at home was come Phebus &thorn;e lord</L>
<L>&thorn;is crowe songe Cokkow. cokkow. Cukkowe</L>
<L>What brid quod phebus what songe singest thowe<MILESTONE N="270a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ne were &thorn;ou wonte so merely to synge</L>
<L>That to myn hert it was a reioysinge</L>
<L>To here &thorn;i vois allas what songe is &thorn;is</L>
<L N="248">By god quod he I synge nat a mys</L>
<L>Phebus quod he for al &thorn;i wor&thorn;inesse</L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;i bewte and &thorn;i gentilnesse</L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;i songe and al &thorn;i mynstralcye</L>
<L N="252">ffor al &thorn;i waytinge blered is &thorn;ine ye</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; oon of litel reputaci&omacr;n</L>
<L>Nou&yogh;t wor&thorn; to &thorn;e as in comparison</L>
<L>The mountaunce of a gnatte so mote I thryue</L>
<L N="256">ffor on &thorn;i bed &thorn;i wiff I segh hym swyve</L>
<L>What wil &yogh;e more &thorn;e crawe anoon hym tolde</L>
<L>By sad tokens and by wordes bolde</L>
<L>How &thorn;at his wif had doon her leccherie</L>
<L N="260">Hym to grete shame and to gret vilenye</L>
<L>And tolde hym oft he segh it wi&thorn; his eyen</L>
<L>This Phebus gan awaiward forto wryen./</L>
<L>Hym &thorn;ou&yogh;t his sorowful hert brast atwoo</L>
<L N="264">His bowe he bent and sette &thorn;er-Inne a floe</L>
<L>And in his Ire ha&thorn; he his wif sclayn</L>
<L>This is &thorn;effecte &thorn;er nys no more to sayn</L>
<L>ffor sorowe of which he brak his mynstralcie</L>
<L N="268">Bo&thorn; harpe and lute. gitern &middot; and sawtrie</L>
<L>And eke he brak his harowes and his bowe</L>
<L>And after &thorn;at &thorn;us speke he to &thorn;e crowe</L>
<L>Traitour quod he wi&thorn; tunge of scorpion</L>
<L N="272">Thou hast/ me brou&yogh;t to my confusion</L>
<L>Allas &thorn;at I was wrou&yogh;t why ner I dede</L>
<L>O dere wiff o. gemme of lustihede</L>
<L>&thorn;at were to me so sad and eke so trewe</L>
<L N="276">Now liest &thorn;ou dede wi&thorn; face pale of hwe
<PB REF="00000631.tif" N="601"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="585"></L>
<L N="277">fful giltles &thorn;at durst I swere ywis</L>
<L>O Rakel hounde to doon so foule amys</L>
<L>O trouble witte .o. yre rechelees</L>
<L N="280">That vnavised smytest giltlees</L>
<L>O wan-trest ful of fals suspeci&omacr;n</L>
<L>Wher was &thorn;i witt and &thorn;i discrecion<MILESTONE N="270b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>O euery man be war of rechelesnesse</L>
<L N="284">Ne trow no &thorn;inge wi&thorn;-out strong witnesse</L>
<L>Smyte not to sone er &thorn;ow wit why</L>
<L>And be avised wel and soberly</L>
<L>Er &yogh;e doon eny executi&omacr;n</L>
<L N="288">Vppon &yogh;oure Ire for suspeci&omacr;n</L>
<L>Allas an Ml. folk han rakel yre</L>
<L>ffully fordoon or brou&yogh;t hem in &thorn;e myre</L>
<L>Allas for sorowe I wil my self scle</L>
<L N="292">And to &thorn;e Crawe o&middot; fals &thorn;eef saide he</L>
<L>I wil &thorn;e qwite anoon &thorn;i fals tale</L>
<L>Thow songe whilom like a ny&yogh;tyngale</L>
<L>Now shalt &thorn;ou fals &thorn;eef &thorn;i songe forgone</L>
<L N="296">Eke &thorn;i white fetheres euerechone</L>
<L>Ne neuer in al &thorn;i lif shalt &thorn;ou speke</L>
<L>Thus shal men on a traitour ben ywreke</L>
<L>Thowe and &thorn;ine ospringe euer shul be blake</L>
<L N="300">Ne neuer swete noys shul &yogh;e make</L>
<L>But euer crie a&yogh;einst tempest and reyne</L>
<L>In tokenynge &thorn;at &thorn;orgh &thorn;e my wif is scleyn</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e crowe he stert and &thorn;at anone</L>
<L N="304">And pulled his white fe&thorn;eres euerechone</L>
<L>And made hym blak and raft hym al his songe</L>
<L>And eke his speche and out atte dore hym sclonge</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e deuel to whoom I hym bitake</L>
<L N="308">And for &thorn;is caus bene al[le] crowes blake</L>
<L>Lordyngges by &thorn;is ensample I &yogh;ou preie</L>
<L>&para; Be&thorn; war and take&thorn; kepe what &thorn;at &yogh;e seie</L>
<L>Ne telle&thorn; neuer no man &yogh;oure liff</L>
<L N="312">How &thorn;at ano&thorn;er man ha&thorn; di&yogh;t &thorn;i wiff
<PB REF="00000632.tif" N="602"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="586"></L>
<L N="313">He wil &yogh;ou hate mortelly certayn</L>
<L>Dann salomon as wise clerkes sayn</L>
<L>Teche&thorn; a man to kepe his tunge wel</L>
<L N="316">But as I seide I am not text wel</L>
<L>But na&thorn;elees &thorn;us tau&yogh;t me my dame</L>
<L>My sone &thorn;enk on &thorn;e crowe a goddys name</L>
<L>My sone kepe wel &thorn;i tunge and kepe &thorn;i frende</L>
<L N="320">A wicked tunge is wors &thorn;an a feende<MILESTONE N="271a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>My sone from a feende men may hem blisse</L>
<L>My sone god of hise endelees goodnesse</L>
<L>Walled a tunge wi&thorn; tee&thorn; and lippes eke</L>
<L N="324">ffor man shuld hym avise what he speke</L>
<L>My sone ful oft for to mochel speche</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; mony a man be spilt as clerkes teche</L>
<L>But for litel speche avisely</L>
<L N="328">Is no man shent to speke generally</L>
<L>My sone &thorn;i tunge shuldest &thorn;ou restreyn</L>
<L>Att al tyme but whan &thorn;ou dost &thorn;i peyn</L>
<L>To speke of god in honure and preiere</L>
<L N="332">The furst vertue sone &yogh;if &thorn;ou wilt lere</L>
<L>Is to restreyne and kepe wel &thorn;i tonge</L>
<L>Thus lernen children whan &thorn;ei bene &yogh;onge</L>
<L>My sone of moche speking euel avised</L>
<L N="336">Ther lasse speking had ynow suffised</L>
<L>Come&thorn; moche harme &thorn;us was me told and tau&yogh;t</L>
<L>In mochel speche synne wante&thorn; nau&yogh;t</L>
<L>Woost &thorn;ou wherof a Rakel tunge serue&thorn;</L>
<L N="340">Ri&yogh;t as a swerd forkutte&thorn; and for-kerueth</L>
<L>An arme a twoo my dere sone ri&yogh;t soo</L>
<L>A tonge kitte&thorn; frendship al a twoo</L>
<L>A Ianglere is to god abhomynable</L>
<L N="344">Rede Salomon so wise and honurable</L>
<L>Rede Dauid and his Psalmes. rede Senek</L>
<L>My sone speke not but with &thorn;i hede &thorn;ou bek</L>
<L>Dissimule as &thorn;ou were deef if &thorn;at &thorn;ou here</L>
<L N="348">A Iangelere speke of parilous matere
<PB REF="00000633.tif" N="603"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="587"></L>
<L N="349">&thorn;e fflemyng sei&thorn; and lerne it &yogh;if &thorn;e list</L>
<L>That litel Iangelinge cause&thorn; mochl ryst</L>
<L>My sone &yogh;if &thorn;ou no wikked word hast seide</L>
<L N="352">The ther not drede forto be bywreiede</L>
<L>But he &thorn;at ha&thorn; myssaide I dar wel sayn</L>
<L>He may by no way clepe his word agayn</L>
<L>&thorn;ing &thorn;at is saide. is saide and for&thorn; it go&thorn;</L>
<L N="356">&thorn;ou&yogh;e hym repent or be he neuer so loo&thorn;</L>
<L>He is his &thorn;ral to whom &thorn;at he ha&thorn; saide</L>
<L>A taile of which he is nowe euel a-payde<MILESTONE N="271b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>My sone be war and be not autour newe</L>
<L N="360">Of tydingges whedere &thorn;ei be fals or trewe</L>
<L>Where so &thorn;ou come amonges hie or lowe</L>
<L N="362">Kepe wel &thorn;i tunge and &thorn;enk vpon &thorn;e crowe</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; &thorn;us ende&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e manciple.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="I" TYPE="group">

<PB REF="00000634.tif" N="604">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="589">
<HEAD>GROUP <B>I.</B> FRAGMENT X.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&sect; <B>1.</B> THE BLANK-PARSON LINK. PETWORTH MS.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[This is really a link between some unwritten Tale and the Parson's. It has been made into the Manciple-Parson Link (or Yeoman-Parson by the Christ-Church MS) by Chaucer's copiers, though not meant for it.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<HEAD>And here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e persone<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 271, <I>back</I></NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1">BY &thorn;at &thorn;e manciple had his tale ended</L>
<L>&thorn;e sonne fro &thorn;e south is descended.</L>
<L>So lowe &thorn;at he was nau&yogh;t to my si&yogh;t</L>
<L N="4">Degrees <I>nyne and twenti</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>MS</I> xxix]</NOTE> as of hight</L>
<L>Ten of &thorn;e clok it was so as I gesse</L>
<L>ffor xj foote or litel more or lesse</L>
<L>My shadowe was at &thorn;ilke tyme as &thorn;er</L>
<L N="8">Of suche fete as my lengthe parted were</L>
<L>In sex foote equal of proporcion</L>
<L>&thorn;er-wi&thorn; &thorn;e moones exaltacion</L>
<L>I mene libra alway gan ascende</L>
<L N="12">As we were entringe at a throppes ende</L>
<L>ffor wi&thorn; our hoost as he was wont to gye</L>
<L>As in &thorn;is caas our Ioly companye</L>
<L>Saide in &thorn;is wise lordyngs euerechon</L>
<L N="16">Now lakke&thorn; vs no tale more &thorn;at oon</L>
<L>ffulfilled is my sentence and my degre</L>
<L>Who wil nowe telle a tale lat see</L>
<L>Almost fulfilled is myn ordynaunce</L>
<L N="20">I prei to god so &yogh;eue hym ri&yogh;t good chaunce</L>
<L>That telle&thorn; &thorn;is tale to vs lustely</L>
<L>Sir preest quod he art &thorn;ou a vikarie</L>
<L>Or art thou a persone sei &thorn;e so&thorn; by &thorn;i feye</L>
<L N="24">Be what &thorn;ou be ne breke nat our pleye
<PB REF="00000635.tif" N="605"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="590"></L>
<L N="25">ffor euery man sauf &thorn;ou ha&thorn; told his tale</L>
<L>Vnbocle and schewe what is in &thorn;i male</L>
<L>ffor trewly me &thorn;enke&thorn; by &thorn;i chere</L>
<L N="28">Thow shuldest knet vp wel a grete matere</L>
<L>Telle vs a fable anoon for Cokkes bonys</L>
<L>This person answerd al at onys</L>
<L>&THORN;ow getest fable noon ytold for me</L>
<L N="32">ffor Poule &thorn;at write&thorn; vnto Timothe&middot;<MILESTONE N="272a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Repreuen hem &thorn;at waiven so&thorn;fastnesse</L>
<L>And tellen fables and such wrechednesse</L>
<L>Whi shuld I shewen draf out of my fest</L>
<L N="36">Whan I may shewe whete if &thorn;at me lest</L>
<L>ffor which I say if &thorn;at &thorn;e lust to here</L>
<L>Moralite and vertuous matere</L>
<L>And &thorn;an &thorn;at &yogh;e wil &yogh;eue me audience</L>
<L N="40">I wil ful fayne at cristes reuerence</L>
<L>Doon &yogh;ou plesaunce leeful as I can</L>
<L>But truste&thorn; wel I am a so&thorn;eren man</L>
<L>I can not gest. rum ram. ruf by letter</L>
<L N="44">Ne god woote Ryme hold I but lite better</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore if &yogh;ou lust I nyl nat glose</L>
<L>I wil &yogh;ou telle a mery tale in prose</L>
<L>To knytte vp al &thorn;is feest and make an ende</L>
<L N="48">And Ihesu for his grace wit me sende</L>
<L>To schew &yogh;ou &thorn;e way in &thorn;is viage</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ilk parfite glorious pilgrimage</L>
<L>That hight Ierusalem celestiall</L>
<L N="52">And if &yogh;e vouchesauf anon &yogh;e shall</L>
<L>Bygynne vpon my tale for which I prey</L>
<L>Telle &yogh;our avis I can no better seye</L>
<L>But na&thorn;elees &thorn;is meditaci&omacr;n</L>
<L N="56">I putt aye vnder correccion</L>
<L>Of clerkes for I am not textwell</L>
<L>I take but &thorn;e sentence truste&thorn; well</L>
<L>Therfore I make protestacion</L>
<L N="60">That I wil stonde to correccion
<PB REF="00000636.tif" N="606"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="591"></L>
<L N="61">Vpon &thorn;is woord we han assented sone</L>
<L>ffor as it semed it was forto done</L>
<L>To enden in som vertuous sentence</L>
<L N="64">And forto &yogh;eue hym space and audience</L>
<L>And bad our hoost he shulde to hym seie</L>
<L>&thorn;at alle we to telle his taile hym preye</L>
<L>Our hoost had &thorn;e wordes for vs alle</L>
<L N="68">Sir preest quod he now faire mot &yogh;ou byfalle</L>
<L>Say what &yogh;ou lust and we shullen gladly here</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word he saide in &thorn;is manere<MILESTONE N="272b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Telle&thorn; quod he &yogh;oure meditacioun</L>
<L N="72">But haste&thorn; &yogh;ou &thorn;e sonne wil a-doun</L>
<L>Bee&thorn; fructuous and &thorn;at in litel space</L>
<L N="74">And to do wel god sende &yogh;ou his grace.</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; Thus ende&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e persons tale</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
