<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="593">
<HEAD>And here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e person his tale.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Capitulum xxiiij<SUP>m</SUP>.</NOTE></HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Petworth MS, on leaf</I> 272, <I>back</I>.]</P><P>[There are no breaks in the MS. Tyrwhitt's are kept here to prevent slight differences in the texts throwing the Six-Text out of gear.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<EPIGRAPH><BIBL>Ieremie vj<SUP>to</SUP>.</BIBL>
<Q>&para; State super vias &amp; videte &amp; interrogate de Semitis / antiquis que sit/ via bona &amp; ambulate in ea &amp; inuenietis refrigerium animabus vestris;</Q></EPIGRAPH>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<P>[75] OWre swete lord god of heuene &thorn;at no man wil perisshe but wil &thorn;at we commen all to the knowlecch of hym and to &thorn;e blisful lif &thorn;at is perdurable [76] ammosshe&thorn; vs by &thorn;e prophet Ieremye &thorn;at sei&thorn; in &thorn;is wise [77] &para; Stonde&thorn; vp-on &thorn;e wayes and see&thorn; and aske&thorn; of olde Patthes &thorn;at is to sayne of olde sentences which is &thorn;e good way [78] and walke&thorn; in &thorn;at way and &yogh;e shul here refresshyng for &yogh;oure saules. &amp;c [79] &para; Mony bene &thorn;e waies espiritual &thorn;at leden folk to oure lord Ihesu crist and to &thorn;e regne of glorie. [80] Of which way &thorn;er is a ful / noble waye and a ful couenable which may not faile to man / ne to womman &thorn;at &thorn;ourgh synne ha&thorn; mysgoon from &thorn;e ri&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nota de pani|tencia./</NOTE> way of Ierusalem Celestiall [81] &para; And &thorn;is way is cleped Penytence of which men shuld gladly harken and enquere wi&thorn; al his herte [82] to wete what is Pen|aunce. and whi it is cleped penitence / and in how mony maners bene &thorn;e accions of worchynge of penytence. [83] and howe mony spices &thorn;er bene of penytences. and whiche &thorn;ingges appertenen and byhouen to penytence. [and] which &thorn;ingges distrouben penytence
<PB REF="00000644.tif" N="610"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="594"></P>
<P>[84] &para; Seynt Ambrose sei&thorn;. That penitence is &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ambrosius</NOTE> laynyng of man for &thorn;e gilt &thorn;at he ha&thorn; done. <SUP>1</SUP>What is peny|tence<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="marg">[<SUP>1_1</SUP> <I>A sidenote copied into the text.</I>]</NOTE> and no more to doon eny &thorn;inge for which hym ou&yogh;t to playne. [85] And somme doctour sei&thorn;. Penytence is &thorn;e way|mentyng of man &thorn;at sorowe&thorn; for his synne. and pyne&thorn; hym self for he ha&thorn; mysdone. [86] Penytence wi&thorn; certeyn circumstaunces is verray repentaunce of man &thorn;at halt hym self in sorowe and o&thorn;er payn for his giltes. [87] And for he shal be verrey penytent. he shal first bywaillen &thorn;e synnes &thorn;at he ha&thorn; done and stedfastly proposed in his hert to haue shrift of mou&thorn; and to doon satisfaccion [88] and neuere to doon &thorn;inge for whiche <MILESTONE N="273a" UNIT="folio">hym ou&yogh;te more to be-wayle or to compleyn and to con|tynue in good werkes or ellis his repentaunce may not availe. [89] ffor as sei&thorn; ysidere &para; he is a Iaper and<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Isidore./</NOTE> a gabber and no verrey repentaunt &thorn;at eftsone doon &thorn;inge for whiche hym ou&yogh;t to repent [90] wepinge and nou&yogh;t forto stint to do synne may nou&yogh;t auaile [91] &para; But na&thorn;eles men shullen hope &thorn;at at euery time &thorn;at man / falle&thorn; be it neuer so oft &thorn;at he may arise &thorn;orgh peny|tence. if he haue grace // But certeynly it is grete dout. [92] ffor as sei&thorn; seint <I>gregorie</I>. Vnne&thorn;es arise&thorn; he out<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; gregorius./</NOTE> of his synne &thorn;at is charge&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;e charge of euel vsage. [93] annt &thorn;er-fore repentaunt folk &thorn;at stint forto synne and forlete synne. er &thorn;at synne forlete hem holy churche holt hem siker of her sauaci&omacr;n [94] &para; And he &thorn;at synne&thorn; and verrely repente&thorn; hym in his last [day]. holy church &yogh;it hope&thorn; his saluacion by &thorn;e grete mercy of our lord Ihesu crist for his repentaunce. but take &thorn;e siker way certeyn:</P>
<P>[95] And now si&thorn;ens I haue declared &yogh;ou what &thorn;inge is penitence &para; Now shul &yogh;e vnderstond &thorn;at &thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; tres accione[s] panitencie I<SUP>a</SUP>. aocio.</NOTE> bene iij. actions of penytence [96] &para; The first is &thorn;at a man be baptist aftere &thorn;at he ha&thorn; synned [97] &para; Seynt Austyn sei&thorn; But he be penitent for his olde synful lif; he may no bygynne &thorn;e newe 
<PB REF="00000645.tif" N="611"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="595"> clene lif. [98] ffor certes if he be paptised wi&thorn;-out penitence of his olde gilt. he resceyue&thorn; &thorn;e mark of bapteme. but not &thorn;e grace ne &thorn;e remyssion of his synnes til he haue repentaunce verray [99] &para; Ano&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="marg">2<SUP>a</SUP>. accio.</NOTE> defaute is &thorn;is. &thorn;at men doon dedly synne aftere &thorn;at &thorn;ei han resceyued bapteme [100] &para; The iij. defaute<NOTE PLACE="marg">3<SUP>a</SUP>. accio./</NOTE> is &thorn;at men falle in venyal synnes after her bapteme fro day to day. [101] &thorn;erof sei&thorn; seynt Austyne.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Augustinus</NOTE> &thorn;at penitence of good and humble folk. is &thorn;e penitence of euery day</P>
<P>[102] &para; The spices of penaunce bene &thorn;re. &thorn;at oon<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> spices of penaunce</NOTE> of hem is solempne Another is comune. and the iij. is prive. [103] Eche penaunce &thorn;at is so|lempne is in two maners. as is to be put out of holy church in lent for sclaughtere of children and such maner &thorn;ingges [104] &para; Another is whan man<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; penitencia communis</NOTE> ha&thorn; synned openly of whiche synne &thorn;e fame is openly spoken in &thorn;e contre. and &thorn;an holy churche by Iugge|ment distreyne&thorn; hym forto doo penaunce open. [105] Somme penaunce is &thorn;er is &thorn;at preestes enioynen men. comonly in certeyn caas as forto goon perauenture naked in pilgrimage. or bare &thorn;e feet [106] &para; Privey penaunce is<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De secreta penitencia</NOTE> &thorn;ilk &thorn;at men doon al day for privey synnes of which we shryuen vs prively and receyuen prive penaunce</P>
<P>[107] <MILESTONE N="273b" UNIT="folio">&para; Now shalt &thorn;ou vnderstond what by[ho]ue&thorn; and is necessarie to verrey parfite penytence and &thorn;ise stonden on &thorn;re &thorn;ingges. [108] Contricion of hert. con|fession of mou&thorn;. And satisfaction [109] &para; ffor which sei&thorn; Iohn Grisostom &para; Penytence distreyne&thorn; man<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Grisostomus</NOTE> to accept benignely euery peyne &thorn;at is enioyned hym wi&thorn; contrici&omacr;n of hert and shrift of mou&thorn;e. wi&thorn; satis|faccion and worching of al manere humilite. [110] And &thorn;is is fruytful penytence a&yogh;einst iij. &thorn;ingges in whiche we wre&thorn;en our lord Ihesu crist. [111] &thorn;is is to / sayn be delite in &thorn;enkinge. by rechelesnesse in spekinge. by wikked synful worchinge. [112] and a&yogh;einst &thorn;ise 
<PB REF="00000646.tif" N="612"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="596"> wikked giltes is penytence. &thorn;at may be likned vnto a tre<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Hou penaunce may be likned to a tree</NOTE> [113] The rote of &thorn;is tree is contricion &thorn;at hide&thorn; hym in &thorn;e herte of him &thorn;at is verrey repentaunt. ri&yogh;t as &thorn;e roote of a tree hide&thorn; hym in &thorn;e er&thorn;e. [114] &para; Of &thorn;e roote of contricion sprynge&thorn; a stalk &thorn;at bere&thorn; braunches and leeues of confession. and fruyt of satisfactioun [115] &para; ffor which Crist sei&thorn; in &thorn;e gospell &para; Do&thorn; digne fruyte of penytence. for by &thorn;is fruyte may men knowe &thorn;is tre. and not by &thorn;e roote &thorn;at is in &thorn;e hert of man. ne by &thorn;e braunches ne by &thorn;e leeues of confession [116] &para; And &thorn;erfore our lord Ihesu crist sei&thorn; &thorn;us By<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Textus.</NOTE> &thorn;e fruyte of hem shul &yogh;e knowe hem [117] &para; Of &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Of &thorn;e seed of contricioun.</NOTE> roote springeth a sede of grace. .&thorn;e which sede is modere of sikernesse. &thorn;us &thorn;is sede is eger and hote. [118] The grace of &thorn;is / sede springe&thorn; of god &thorn;orowe &thorn;e re|membraunce of &thorn;e day of dome. and on &thorn;e peynes of helle [119] &para; Of &thorn;is matere seith salomon. &thorn;at in &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Salomon.</NOTE> degre of god man forlete&thorn; his synne [120] The hete of this seede is &thorn;e loue of god / and &thorn;e desiring of &thorn;e Ioie perdurable. [121] &thorn;is hete drawe&thorn; &middot; &thorn;e hert of man to god and do&thorn; him hate his synne. [122] ffor so&thorn;ly &thorn;er nys no &thorn;inge &thorn;at sauoure&thorn; so wel to a childe as &thorn;e mylk of his norice. ne no &thorn;ing is to hym more abhom|inable &thorn;at &thorn;ilk mylk what it is medled wi&thorn; o&thorn;er mete. [123] Ri&yogh;t so &thorn;e synful man &thorn;at loue&thorn; his synne. hym seme&thorn; &thorn;at it is to hym most swete of eny &thorn;inge. [124] But fro &thorn;at tyme &thorn;at he loueth sadly our lord Ihesu crist and desireth &thorn;e lif perdurable. ther nys to hym [no &thorn;ing] more abhominable. [125] ffor so&thorn;. &thorn;e lawe of god is &thorn;e loue of god. ffor which Dauid &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> prophet sei&thorn;. I haue loued &thorn;i lawe and hated<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De propheta./</NOTE> wikkednesse &para; he [&thorn;at] loueth god kepe&thorn; his lawe and his worde. [126] This reson sei&thorn; &thorn;e prophete Danyell in spirit<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Daniel./</NOTE> vppon a vision of Nabugodonosor whan he<MILESTONE N="274a" UNIT="folio">coun|sailled hym to doo penaunce. [127] Penaunce is &thorn;e tree of liff to hem / &thorn;at it receyuen. And he &thorn;at holde&thorn; hym 
<PB REF="00000647.tif" N="613"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="597"> in verrey penytence is blessed aftere &thorn;e sentence of<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Salomon.</NOTE> Salomon</P>
<P>[128] In &thorn;is penitence or contrici&omacr;n man shal vn|derstonde .iiij. &thorn;ingges. &thorn;at is to seyn what is contrici&omacr;n and whiche bene &thorn;e causes &thorn;at meuen a man to con|trici&omacr;n and howe he shuld be contrite. and what con|tricion availed to &thorn;e soule. [129] Than is it &thorn;us. &thorn;at contricion is &thorn;e verrey sorowe &thorn;at a man receyue&thorn; in his hert for his synnes with sad purpoos to schryuen hym and to do penaunce and neuere more to do synne. [130] And &thorn;is sorowe shal be in &thorn;is manere as seith seint Bernard &para; It shal be greuous and hevie and ful<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Bernardus</NOTE> sharp and poynant in hert. [131] ffirst for a man ha&thorn; a-gilt his lorde and his creature. and more sharpe and poynant; for he hath agilt his fadere celestiall. [132] And &yogh;it more sharpe and poynant ffor he ha&thorn; wre&thorn;ed and agult hym &thorn;at bou&yogh;t hym. &thorn;at with his precious blood ha&thorn;e delyuered vs fro the boondes of synne and fro &thorn;e cruelte of &thorn;e deuell. and fro &thorn;e paynes of helle. [133] &para; The causes &thorn;at ou&yogh;ten to meuen a man to con|tricion<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Sex mouimenta ad contricionem.</NOTE> ben .vj. &para; ffurst a man shal remembre him of his synnes. [134] but loke &thorn;at &thorn;ilk remem|braunce be to him no delite by no way. but gret shame and sorowe for his gilt. ffor Iob sei&thorn;. Synful men don<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Iob./</NOTE> werkes wor&thorn;i of confession. [135] And &thorn;erfore sei&thorn; Ezechie. I wil remembre me al &thorn;e &yogh;eeres of my lif.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ezechiel.</NOTE> my bitternesse of myn hert [136] &para; And god sei&thorn; in &thorn;e apocalips &para; Remembre &yogh;ou from whennes &thorn;at &yogh;e be<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Apocalypsis./</NOTE> falle. ffor byforn &thorn;at tyme &thorn;at &yogh;e synned &yogh;e were &thorn;e children of god. and lymmes of &thorn;e reigne of god. [137] But for &yogh;oure synne &yogh;e bene woxe &thorn;rall and foule. and membres of &thorn;e feende. hate of aungels sclaunder of holy church. and foode of &thorn;e fals serpent perpetuele matere of the fuyre of hell [138] and &thorn;at more foule and abhom|ynable for &yogh;e trespasen so often tyme as do&thorn; &thorn;e hounde &thorn;at turne&thorn; to eten his vomyte. [139] And &yogh;it 
<PB REF="00000648.tif" N="614"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="598"> bene &yogh;e foulere for &yogh;oure longe contynuyng in synne and &yogh;oure synful usage. for which &yogh;e bene roten in &yogh;our synne as a beest in his dunge. [140] &para; Suche maner of &thorn;ou&yogh;tes maken a man haue shame for his synne and no delite. As / god sai&thorn; by &thorn;e prophete Ezechiele<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ezechiell</NOTE> [141] &para; &YOGH;e shul remembre &yogh;ou of &yogh;oure waies; and &thorn;ei shul displese &yogh;ou so&thorn;ely &para; Synnos ben &thorn;e waies &thorn;at lede folk to hell</P>
<P>[142] &para; The ij. cause &thorn;at ou&yogh;t to / <MILESTONE N="274b" UNIT="folio">make a man to haue disdeyne of synne is &thorn;is. That as sei&thorn; seint Peter &para; Who so doth synne; is &thorn;ral to synne and<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Petrus</NOTE> synne putte&thorn; a man in gret &thorn;raldome. [143] And &thorn;er|fore seith &thorn;e prophete Ezechiel &para; I went soryful in<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ezechiele</NOTE> disdeyn of my silf. Certes &para; wel au&yogh;t a man haue disdeyn of synne and wi&thorn;-drawe / hym from &thorn;at &thorn;raldom and vilanyc. [144] And lo what sei&thorn; Senec<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Seneca</NOTE> &para; In &thorn;is matere he sei&thorn; &thorn;us &para; Thou&yogh;e I wist &thorn;at nei&thorn;er god ne man ne shuld neuere knowen it. &yogh;it wolde I haue desdeyne forto / do synne. [145] And the same Senec sei&thorn; &para; I am born to gretter &thorn;ingges<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Seneca /</NOTE> &thorn;an to be &thorn;rall to my body. . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [146] A [fouler] &thorn;ral may no man no womman make of his body &thorn;an &yogh;eue is body to synne [147] A[l] were it the foulest cheerle or womman &thorn;at lyue&thorn; and leest of valewe. &yogh;it is he chaunged and most foule and more in seruitute. [148] euer fro &thorn;e hyer degre &thorn;at man falle&thorn;; &thorn;e more is he &thorn;rall and more vnto god and to &thorn;e world vile and abhomyn|able. [149] O / &yogh;ood god wel au&yogh;t men haue desdeyn of synne. si&thorn;en &thorn;at &thorn;orgh synne. &thorn;er he was free nowe is he maked boonde. [150] &amp; / &thorn;erfore sei&thorn; seint Austyn. &para; If &thorn;ou haue desdeyn of &thorn;i seruaunt if he<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Augustinus./</NOTE> a-gilt or synne. haue &thorn;ou &thorn;an disdeyn &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;i silf shuldest do synne. [151] Take reward of &thorn;ine valewe &thorn;at &thorn;ou / ne be to foule to &thorn;i self. [152] Allas wel ou&yogh;ten &thorn;ei &thorn;an to haue desdeyne to be 
<PB REF="00000649.tif" N="615"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="599"> seruauntes and &thorn;ralles to synne and sore bene ashamed of hem self. [153] &thorn;at god of his endelees goodnesse ha&thorn; sett hem in hie astaat and &yogh;euen hem witt. strength of body. hel&thorn;e. bewte. and prosperite. [154] and bou&yogh;t hem fro &thorn;e dee&thorn; with his hert blood. &thorn;at &thorn;ei so vnkyndely a&yogh;einst gentelnesse aquiten hym so vilenistly to sclowghter of her owne soules. [155] &para; O good god. &yogh;e wommen &thorn;at bene of so grete bewte. remembre&thorn; &yogh;ou of &thorn;e prouerbe of Salamon &para; He<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Salomon.</NOTE> [156] likne&thorn; a fair womman &thorn;at is a foole of her body. ylik to a ryng of gold &thorn;at is wre&thorn;ed in &thorn;e Groyne of a sowe. [157] ffor ri&yogh;t as a sowe &para; wrote&thorn; in euery ordure. So wrote&thorn; she her bewte in stynkinge ordure of synne</P>
<P>[158] &para; The iij cause &thorn;at ou&yogh;t to meuen a / man to contricion and drede of &thorn;e day of dome. and of &thorn;e / horrible peynes of helle. [159] ffor as seint Ierom sei&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ieromias;/</NOTE> &para; Att euery tyme &thorn;at me remembre&thorn; of &thorn;e day of dome I quake [160] ffor whan I ete or drinke or doo what so I doo / euer me seme&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e trompe sowne&thorn; in myn ere. [161] Riseth vp <MILESTONE N="275a" UNIT="folio">&thorn;at bene dede and comme&thorn; to &thorn;e Iuggement. [162] O Good god mochel. owe&thorn; a man to drede such Iuggement &thorn;er as we shulne bene alle as sei&thorn; seint Poule by-forne the strete of our lord Ihesu<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Paulus</NOTE> crist [163] wher as he shal make a general con|gregacion. Wher as no man had be absent. [164] for certes &thorn;er ne veile&thorn; non assoyn ne excusacion [165] and not only &thorn;at our defautes shullen / be Iugged but eke &thorn;at all our werkes shul openly be knowe [166] And as seint Bernard sei&thorn;. There ne<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Bernardus</NOTE> shal no pledyng availe ne no sclei&yogh;t we shul &yogh;euen reknyng of euery ydel word [167] Ther shul we haue a Iugge &thorn;at may not be deceyued. ne corrupte and whi for certes al oure &thorn;ou&yogh;tes ben diskeuered as to hym. ne for preiere ne for mede he wil not bene corrupte. [168] And &thorn;erfore sei&thorn; Salomon. &thorn;e wre&thorn;e of god<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Salomon</NOTE> wil not be corrupte / And &thorn;erfor sei&thorn; Salomon &para; &thorn;e / wreche<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Idem.</NOTE> 
<PB REF="00000650.tif" N="616"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="600"> of god ne wil not spare no wi&yogh;t for preier ne for &yogh;ift. And &thorn;er&para;fore at &thorn;e day of dome &thorn;er nys no hope to escape. [169] Wherfore Anselme sei&thorn; &para; fful grete Angwissh shullen &thorn;e synful folk haue at &thorn;at tyme [170] Ther shal be &thorn;e sterne and &thorn;e wro&thorn;e Iuge sitte aboue and vnder hym &thorn;e horrible pitte of helle open to di|stroye hym &thorn;at most byknowe his synne. which synnes openly bene shewed byforn god and biforne euery creature. [171] And on &thorn;e left side moo deuels / than hert may &thorn;enk forto harie and to drowe &thorn;e synful soules / to &thorn;e pyne of helle. [172] And wi&thorn;|in &thorn;e hertes of folk shal be &thorn;e bitynge conscience and wi&thorn;-out for&thorn; shal be &thorn;e world al brennynge. [173] whidere shal &thorn;an &thorn;e wrecched synful soule flee / to hide hym. Certes he may not hide hym. he most come for&thorn; and schewe hym. [174] ffor certes as sei&thorn; seint Ierom &para; The er&thorn;e shal cast hym out of hym.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ieronimus</NOTE> and &thorn;e see also and the Eiere. &thorn;at shal be ful / of &thorn;ondere clappes / and li&yogh;tnynge [175] Now so&thorn;ly who so wil remembre hym of &thorn;ise &thorn;ingges I gesse &thorn;at his &thorn;ingges shal not turne hym into delite. but to grete sorowe for drede of the payne of helle. [176] And &thorn;er|fore sei&thorn; Iob. &para; Suffre lord &thorn;at I may a while<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Iob./</NOTE> biwaile and wepe or I goo and wepe wi&thorn;-out retournynge to &thorn;e derk londe keuered wi&thorn; &thorn;e derknesse of de&thorn;e [177] to &thorn;e londe of myssese and of derknesse. where as is shadowe of dee&thorn;. wher as &thorn;er nys noon o&thorn;er or|dynaunce. but grisly drete &thorn;at euere shul last [178] &para; Loo here may &yogh;e seen &thorn;at Iob preied of respite a while to bywepe and waile his trespas. ffor so&thorn;ly oo / day of respite is bettere &thorn;an al &thorn;e tresoure of &thorn;is world [179] And <MILESTONE N="275b" UNIT="folio">for as moche as a man may acquite hym self to forn god by penitence in &thorn;is world and nou&yogh;t by tresour &thorn;erfor shuld he prei to god to &yogh;eue hym respite a while to bywepen and bywaillen his trespas [180] ffor certes al &thorn;e sorowe &thorn;at a man my&yogh;t make fro &thorn;e bygynnynge 
<PB REF="00000651.tif" N="617"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="601"> of &thorn;e world nys but a litel &thorn;ing at &thorn;e regard of &thorn;e sorowe of helle [181] &para; The cause why &thorn;at Iob clepe&thorn; helle &thorn;e londe of derknesse. [182] Vnderstonde&thorn; &thorn;at he clepe&thorn; it londe or er&thorn;e. for it is stable and neuere shal faile. derknesse. for he &thorn;at is in helle ha&thorn; defaute of li&yogh;t materiall [183] ffor certes &thorn;e derk li&yogh;t &thorn;at shal come out of &thorn;e fire &thorn;at euere shal brenne shal turne hym al to peyne &thorn;at is in helle. ffor it shewe&thorn; hym to &thorn;e horrible deuels &thorn;at hym tormenten [184] keuered wi&thorn; &thorn;e derknesse of de&thorn;e . . . . . [185] . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> bene &thorn;e synnes &thorn;at &thorn;e wrecched / man ha&thorn; don which &thorn;at distourben hym to se &thorn;e face of god. ri&yogh;t as a derk cloude bytwix vs and &thorn;e sonne. [186] londe of myssese by cause &thorn;at &thorn;er bene .iij. manere of defautes a&yogh;einst &thorn;re &thorn;ingges &thorn;at folk of &thorn;is world han in &thorn;is present liff. &thorn;at is to say honours. delices. and Richesse. [187] A&yogh;einst honour han &thorn;ei in helle shame and confusion. [188] ffor wel &yogh;e woote &thorn;at men clepen honour &thorn;e reuerence &thorn;at men doon to man. But in helle nys noon honur ne reuerence. ffor certes no more reuerence shal be do to a kinge &thorn;an to a knaue [189] &para; ffor which god seith by &thorn;e prophetys wordes Ieremye. &para; Thilk folk &thorn;at me despisen<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Textus Ieremie</NOTE> shullen bene despised. [190] &para; Honur is eke cleped gret lord Ther shal no wi&yogh;t / seruen o&thorn;er. but of harme and torment &para; Honure is eke cleped grete dignite and high|nesse. But in helle shul &thorn;ei bene al for-troden of deuels. [191] as god sei&thorn; The horrible deuels shal goon and come vpon &thorn;e hedes of dampned folk And &thorn;is is for as moche as &thorn;e hier &thorn;at &thorn;ei were in &thorn;is present lif. &thorn;e more shullen &thorn;ei bene abated and defouled in helle. [192] &para; A&yogh;einst &thorn;e richesse of &thorn;is world. shullen &thorn;ei haue myssese and pouerte. and &thorn;is pouert shal be .iiij. &thorn;ingges [193] in defaute of tresour. of which 
<PB REF="00000652.tif" N="618"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="602"> Dauid &thorn;e prophete sei&thorn; &para; The riche folk &thorn;at enbraceden and<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Dauid pro|pheta</NOTE> oneden in al her hert to tresoure of &thorn;is world shullen sclepe in &thorn;e sclepinge of de&thorn;. As no &thorn;inge shul &thorn;ei fynden in her hondes of al her tresour [194] &para; And more ouer &thorn;e dissese of helle shal bene in &thorn;e defaute of mete and drynk. [195] &para; ffor god sei&thorn; &thorn;us by moyses &para; Thei shullen<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Deus per moysem</NOTE> be wasted with <MILESTONE N="276a" UNIT="folio">hunger and &thorn;e briddes of helle shal deuoure hem with bitter de&thorn; and &thorn;e galle of &thorn;e dragon . . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> her morsell. [196] And fer&thorn;er ouer her myssese shal bene in defaute of clo&thorn;inge ffor &thorn;ei shullen be naked in body as of clo&thorn;ing sauf &thorn;e fuyr in which &thorn;ei brenne and o&thorn;er fil&thorn;es. [197] and naked shul &thorn;ei bene of saule. of al manere vertues which &thorn;at is &thorn;e clo&thorn;inge of saule. Wher bene &thorn;an &thorn;e gay Roobes and &thorn;e soft shetes and &thorn;e smal / shertes [198] &para; loo what sei&thorn; god to hem by &thorn;e prophete Ysay<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Isayas./</NOTE> &para; That vndere hem shullen be strawed motthes. and her couertours / shul be of wormes of helle [199] &para; And fer&thorn;er ouere her dissese shal / bene in defaute of frendes. ffor he nys not poor &thorn;at ha&thorn; good / freendes. but &thorn;er nys no frende. [200] ffor nei&thorn;er god ne creature / shal be frende to hem. and euery of hem shal haten o&thorn;ere wi&thorn; dedly hate. [201] The sones of &thorn;e doughtren shullen rebellen a&yogh;einst &thorn;e fadere and modere and kynrede a&yogh;einst kynrede and chiden and despisen euerech of hem o&thorn;er bo&thorn; day and ny&yogh;t As god sei&thorn; by &thorn;e prophet Michias [202] &para; And &thorn;e louyng children.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Machias./</NOTE> &thorn;at whilom loued so flesshly euerech o&thorn;er. wolden euerech of hem eten o&thorn;er if &thorn;ei my&yogh;t. [203] ffor howe shuld &thorn;ei loue hem to-gydere in &thorn;e peynes of helle. whan &thorn;ei hated eche of hem o&thorn;er in &thorn;e prosperite of &thorn;is lif. [204] ffor trust wel her flesshly loue was dedly hate as sei&thorn; &thorn;e prophete dauid &para; who so &thorn;at loue&thorn; wicked|nesse<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Dauid./</NOTE> he hate&thorn; his saule. [205] and who &thorn;at hate&thorn; his owne soule. certes he may loue noon o&thorn;er wi&yogh;t 
<PB REF="00000653.tif" N="619"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="603"> in no manere. [206] and &thorn;erfor in helle is no frendship. But euer &thorn;e moo flesshly kynredes &thorn;at bene in helle. &thorn;e more cursyng &thorn;e more chyd|inge. and &thorn;e more dedly hate &thorn;er is amonges hem [207] &para; And for&thorn;ermor &thorn;er shal be defaute of al maner delyces. ffor why &thorn;e delices ben &thorn;e appetites of &thorn;e .v. wittes. as. si&yogh;t. heryng. smellynge. sauer|yng and towchynge. [208] But in helle her si&yogh;t shal be ful of derkenesse and of smoke and ful of teeres. and her heryng ful of waymentynge and of gnaistynge of tee&thorn; as seith Ihesus / crist [209] &para; her nose|&thorn;relles<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ihesu</NOTE> shullen be ful stynkyng stynks &para; And as sei&thorn; Isay &thorn;e prophete. Her saueryng shal be ful of bitter<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Isayas.</NOTE> galle. [210] and touchyng of her body ykeuered wi&thorn; fuyr &thorn;at neuere shal be quenched. and wi&thorn; wormes &thorn;at never shul dye &para; As god sei&thorn; / by &thorn;e mou&thorn; of<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ihesus./</NOTE> ysay. [211] &para; And for as moch as &thorn;ei shullen not wene &thorn;at &thorn;ei may dyen for peyne. and by her de&thorn; flee fro peyne. <MILESTONE N="276b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;at may &thorn;ei vnderstonde by &thorn;e worde of Iob.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Iob.</NOTE> &thorn;at sei&thorn;. There as is &thorn;e shadowe of de&thorn;e [212] &para; Certes a shadowe ha&thorn; &thorn;e liknesse of a &thorn;inge of which it is shadowe. But shadowe nys not &thorn;e same &thorn;inge of which it is shadowe. [213] Ri&yogh;t so fare&thorn; &thorn;e peyne of helle. it is like dee&thorn; for &thorn;e angwisshe horrible. and why for it peyne&thorn; hem euere as &thorn;oo men shulden dye anon But certes &thorn;ei shullen not dye. [214] ffor as sei&thorn; seynt Gregore. &para; To wrecched Catyfe shal be de&thorn;e wi&thorn;-out<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Gregorius./</NOTE> de&thorn;e. ande ende wi&thorn;-outen ende. and defaute wi&thorn;-out failynge. [215] for her de&thorn;e shal alway lyve. and her eende shal euermor bygynne and her defaute shal not faile. [216] And &thorn;erfore sei&thorn; seint Iohn &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Iohannes Euaungelista</NOTE> euaungeliste They shullen folowe de&thorn; and &thorn;ei shul not fynden hym. And &thorn;ei / desiren to deye. and de&thorn;e shul flee fro hem / [217] And eke Iob seith That in helle<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Iob./</NOTE> is noon order ne rewele [218] And al be it soo &thorn;at god ha&thorn; created al &thorn;ing in ri&yogh;t ordre and no &thorn;ing wi&thorn;|out 
<PB REF="00000654.tif" N="620"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="604"> ordere. but alle &thorn;ingges ben ordred and nom|bred. &yogh;it na&thorn;elees &thorn;ei &thorn;at bene dampned bene no &thorn;inge in order ne holden / noon order. [219] for &thorn;e er&thorn;e ne shal bere hem no fruyte. [220] ffor as &thorn;e / prophete<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; dauid pro|pheta./</NOTE> dauid sei&thorn; &para; God shal destroy &thorn;e froyte of &thorn;e er&thorn;e as fro / hem. ne watere shal &yogh;eue hem no moystere. ne &thorn;e eyre no refresshynge. ne &thorn;e fuyre no li&yogh;t. [221] ffor as sei&thorn; seynt Basile. &thorn;e brennyngges of &thorn;e fuyre of &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Basilius./</NOTE> worlde shal god &yogh;euen to hem in helle &thorn;at bene dampned. [222] But &thorn;e li&yogh;t and &thorn;e clernesse shal be &yogh;euen in to heuene to his children./ Ri&yogh;t as &thorn;e good man &yogh;eue&thorn; flesshe to his children. and bonys to his houndes [223] for &thorn;ei shullen have noon hope to escape sei&thorn; Iob. At &thorn;e last &thorn;at ther shal horrour and grisly drede<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Iob./</NOTE> dwelle. wi&thorn;-outen ende [224] &para; Horroure is alway drede of harme &thorn;at is to come and &thorn;is drede shal euer dwelle in &thorn;e hertes of hem &thorn;at bene dampned. and &thorn;er-fore han &thorn;ei lorn all her hope. for vij. causes. [225] ffirst for god &thorn;at is her Iuge shal be wi&thorn;-oute mercy to hem. ne &thorn;ei may not plese hym. ne noon of his halowes. ne &thorn;ei may &yogh;eue no &thorn;inge for her raunsom. [226] ne &thorn;ei han no voys to speke to hym. ne &thorn;ei may nat flee fro peyne ne &thorn;ei han no goodnesse in hem &thorn;at &thorn;ei may schewe to delyuere hem fro peyne [227] &para; And &thorn;erfore sei&thorn; Salomon &para; The wikked man<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Salomon./</NOTE> dye&thorn;; and whan he is dede he shal haue no hope to / eskape fro peyne. [228] who so shame wolde wel vn|derstonde and bythenk hym wel on &thorn;ise peynes and &thorn;at he ha&thorn; deserued &thorn;e same peynes / for his synne. Certes he shuld haue more talent to sike and to wepe <MILESTONE N="277a" UNIT="folio">&thorn;an for syngen and to pley. [229] ffor as sei&thorn; Salomon.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Salomon</NOTE> Who so &thorn;at had &thorn;e science forto knowe &thorn;e peynes &thorn;at bene establisshed and ordeyned / for synne he wold make sorowe. [230] Thilk science as sei&thorn; seint Austyn<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Augustinus.</NOTE> Maketh a man to weymenten in his hert</P>
<P>[231] &para; The iiij. poynte &thorn;at aught make a man 
<PB REF="00000655.tif" N="621"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="605"> haue contrition is &thorn;e soryful remembraunce of &thorn;e good &thorn;at he ha&thorn; lost to doon here in er&thorn;e. and eke &thorn;e good / &thorn;at he ha&thorn; lorne [232] &para; So&thorn;ly &thorn;e good werkes &thorn;at he ha&thorn; lost ei&thorn;er &thorn;ei bene &thorn;e good werkes &thorn;at he ha&thorn; wrou&yogh;t er he felle into dedly synne Or ellys &thorn;e good werkes &thorn;at he wrou&yogh;t &thorn;e while he lay in synne [233] &para; So&thorn;ly &thorn;e good werkes &thorn;at he did byforne &thorn;at he fille in synne ben all mortefied and astonyed and dulled by &thorn;e oft synnynge [234] That o&thorn;er good werkes &thorn;at he wrou&yogh;t &thorn;e whiles he lay in synne &thorn;ei bene vtterly dede as to &thorn;e liff perdurable in heuene. [235] Than / &thorn;ilk good werkes &thorn;at bene mortefied by oft synnynge which good werkes he did &thorn;e whiles he was in charite ne mowen neuere / quicken a&yogh;ein with-outen verrey penytence. [236] And &thorn;erfore sei&thorn; god by &thorn;e mou&thorn;e of Ezechiele &thorn;at is &thorn;e ri&yogh;tful man. Re|tourne<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ezechiele</NOTE> a&yogh;ein from his ri&yogh;twissnesse and to worch wikked|nes shal he lyue. [237] nay. ffor all &thorn;e good werkes &thorn;at he ha&thorn; wrou&yogh;t ne shul neuere be in remembraunce for he shal deye in his synne. [238] &para; And vpon &thorn;ilk chapitere sei&thorn; seint Gregorie thus. than we shuld vnder|stonde<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Gregorius super Eze|chielem</NOTE> &thorn;is principaly. [239] &thorn;at whan we doon dedly synne. it is for no&yogh;t &thorn;an to reherce or drawe into memorie &thorn;e good werkes &thorn;at we han wrou&yogh;t biforn. [240] ffor certys in &thorn;e wirking of dedly synne &thorn;er nys no trest to no good werk &thorn;at we han doon to-forne / &thorn;at is to sayn as forto haue &thorn;er-by &thorn;e lif per|durable in heuene [241] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> Whan we han contricion. [242] But so&thorn;ly &thorn;e good werkes &thorn;at men / doon whiles &thorn;at &thorn;ei bene in dedly synne. for as moch as &thorn;ei weren doon in dedly synne &thorn;ei mowe neuer quycken a&yogh;ein [243] ffor certes &thorn;ing &thorn;at neuere ha&thorn; lif; neuere may quycked. And na&thorn;elees al be it &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne availe nou&yogh;te to han &thorn;e lif perdurable &yogh;it availen 
<PB REF="00000656.tif" N="622"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="606"> &thorn;ei to abreggen of &thorn;e peyne of helle or ellis to geten temporell richesse. [244] Or ellis &thorn;at god wil rather enlumyne and / lighten &thorn;e hert of &thorn;e synful man to han repentaunce. [245] and eke &thorn;ei availen forto vsen a man to do goode werk &thorn;at &thorn;e fende / haue &thorn;e lasse power of his soule [246] &para; And &thorn;us &thorn;e curtaise Lord Ihesu crist ne wil &thorn;at no good werk be lost. ffor in somwhat it shal availe. [247] But for as moche as &thorn;e good werkes <MILESTONE N="277b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;at men doon whan &thorn;ei bene in &thorn;is liff bene al mortefied by synne folowinge. And eke si&thorn;ens al &thorn;e good werkes &thorn;at men done &thorn;e whiles &thorn;ei bene in dedly synne bene vtterly dede as forto haue &thorn;e lif perdurable [248] &para; wel may &thorn;at man &thorn;at no good werk ne / doo&thorn; &middot; syngyn &thorn;ilk newe songe. Iay tout perdue mon temps et mon labour [249] ffor certes synne byreue&thorn; a man goodnes and nature and eke &thorn;e goodnes of grace [250] &para; ffor so&thorn; &thorn;e grace of &thorn;e holy goost fare&thorn; as fuyre &thorn;at may not be ydell. ffor fire faille&thorn; / anoon as it forlese&thorn; his worch|inge . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [251] &thorn;an lese&thorn; &thorn;e synful man &thorn;e goodnes of glorie &thorn;at oonly is bihi&yogh;t to good men &thorn;at labouren and worken [252] wel may he be sory &thorn;en that owe&thorn; al his lif to god as longe as he lyue&thorn; ha&thorn; lyued and eke as longe as he shal bene &thorn;at no goodnes ne ha&thorn; to pay wi&thorn; his dette to god. to whom he owe&thorn; al his lif. [253] ffor trust wel he shal &yogh;eue acountes as sei&thorn; seint Bernard of alle &thorn;e goodes &thorn;at han bene &yogh;euen hym.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Bernardus</NOTE> in &thorn;is present lif and how he ha&thorn; hem dispended. [254] not so moch &thorn;at &thorn;er shal not perisshe an heer of his hede. ne a moment of an / houre ne shal not perisshe of &thorn;is tyme &thorn;at he ne shal &yogh;eue of it a rekenynge</P>
<P>[255] &para; The .v. &thorn;inge &thorn;at ou&yogh;t to meue a man to contricion is remembraunce of &thorn;e passion of our Lord Ihesu crist suffred for oure synnes [256] ffor as sei&thorn; seynt Bernard whiles &thorn;at I lyue &para; I shal haue remem|braunce<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Bernardus</NOTE> 
<PB REF="00000657.tif" N="623"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="607"> of &thorn;e travailes &thorn;at our lord Ihesu crist suffred in preching [257] in werynesse in travailynge. his tempt|acions whan he fasted. his longe waking whan he preied. his teeres whan &thorn;at he wepte for pite of good puple. [258] &thorn;e woo and &thorn;e shame and &thorn;e fil&thorn;e &thorn;at men seiden to hym oft foule spittyng &thorn;at men / spitten on his face / and &thorn;e buffettes &thorn;at men &yogh;auen hym of &thorn;e // foule mou&thorn;es and of &thorn;e re|preeus &thorn;at men to hym seiden. [259] Of &thorn;e nailles wi&thorn; &thorn;e which he was nailled to &thorn;e cros. and of all &thorn;e remenaunte of his passion &thorn;at he suffred for my synnes. / and no &thorn;inge for his gilt. [260] And &yogh;e shul vnder|stond &thorn;at in mannys synne is euery maner order of ordynaunce turned vp so doun. [261] ffor it is so&thorn; &thorn;at god and reson and sensualite and &thorn;e / body of man bene so ordeyned &thorn;at euerech of &thorn;ise iiij. &thorn;ingges shuld haue lordship of &thorn;at o&thorn;er. [262] As &thorn;us. god shuld haue lordship ouer reson. and reson ouer sensualite. and sensualite ouer &thorn;e / body of man. [263] And so&thorn;ly whan man synne&thorn; al &thorn;is ordere of ordynaunce is turned vp so doune [264] &para; And &thorn;erfore &thorn;an for as moch <MILESTONE N="278a" UNIT="folio">as &thorn;e reson of man wil not be subiette ne obeysaunt to god &thorn;at is his lord by ri&yogh;t &thorn;er|fore lese&thorn; it &thorn;e lordship &thorn;at it shuld haue in sensualite and eke ouer &thorn;e body of man. [265] And whi for sensualite rebelle&thorn; &thorn;an a&yogh;einst reson. And by &thorn;at way leseth resoun his lordship ouer sensualite and ouere &thorn;e bodye. [266] ffor ri&yogh;t as reson is rebelle to god. ri&yogh;t so is bo&thorn; Sensualite rebell to reson and &thorn;e body also. [267] &para; And certes this ordynaunce and &thorn;is rebellion. oure lord Ihesu crist abou&yogh;t vppon his precious body ful dere and herkene&thorn; in which wyse. [268] ffor as moche &thorn;an is reson rebelle to god. &thorn;er|fore is man wor&thorn;i to haue sorowe and to be dede [269] &para; This suffred our lord Ihesu for man aftere &thorn;at he had be bytraied of his disciple and destreyned and 
<PB REF="00000658.tif" N="624"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="608"> bounde so &thorn;at &thorn;e blood brast out at euery naile of his hondes as sei&thorn; seint Austyn [270] &para; And fer&thorn;ermore<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Augustinus.</NOTE> for as moche as reson of man wil not daunte Sensu|alite whan it may. therfore is man wor&thorn;i to haue shame. and &thorn;is / suffred our lorde Ihesu crist for man whan &thorn;ei spitten in his visage [271] &para; And fer&thorn;er ouere for as moch &thorn;an as the catif body of man is rebelle bo&thorn; to reson and to sensualite. &thorn;erfore is it wor&thorn;i &thorn;e dee&thorn; [272] &para; And &thorn;is suffred our lord Ihesu crist for man vpon &thorn;e crosse wher as &thorn;er was no parte of his body free with-oute grete peyne and bitter passion [273] and al &thorn;is suffred Ihesu crist &thorn;at neuer forfeited . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> To mochel am I peyned for &thorn;e same &thorn;ingges &thorn;at I neuer deserued and to mochel defoiled for frendship &thorn;at man bene wor&thorn;i for to haue [274] And &thorn;er|fore may &thorn;e synful man wel saye as sei&thorn; seint Bernard<NOTE PLACE="inline">&para; Bernardus</NOTE> &para; Acursed be &thorn;e bitternesse. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [275] ffor certes aftere &thorn;e dyuers discordaunces of oure wikkednes was &thorn;e passion of Ihesu crist yordeyned in dyuers &thorn;ingges [276] as &thorn;us. Certys synful man saule [is] bytraied of the deuel by coueityse of temperele prosperite and scorned by disceite whan he chese&thorn; flesshly delites and &yogh;it is he tormented by impacience of aduersite. and by-spette by seruage of subieccion in synne / and at &thorn;e last it is sclayn fynally. [277] ffor &para; &thorn;is disordinaunce of synful man was Ihesus crist first bytraied and aftere &thorn;at was he bounde that come forto vnbynde vs of synne and of peyne [278] &para; Than was he byscorned &thorn;at only shuld be honoured. in alle &thorn;ingges of al &thorn;ingges. [279] Than was his visage &thorn;at au&yogh;t be desired to be seyn of al mankynd <MILESTONE N="278b" UNIT="folio">In which visage aungels desiren to loken vileynsly byspitte. [280] Than was he scourged &thorn;at no &thorn;ing gilt And fynaly &thorn;an was he / crucified and sclayn [281] Than was he accomplised &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000659.tif" N="625"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="609"> wordes of Ysay / He was wounded for<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; ysaias;/.</NOTE> our mysdedys and defouled by oure vilanyes. [282] &para; Now si&thorn;ens &thorn;at Ihesu crist toke vppon hym self &thorn;e peyne of al oure wikkednesse &para; Michel ou&yogh;t synful men by-wepe and by-waile &thorn;at for his synnes goddis sone of heuene shuld al &thorn;is peyne endure [283] &para; The sixt &thorn;inge &thorn;at au&yogh;t meue man to contricion is &thorn;e hope of iij. &thorn;ingges. &thorn;at is to say for&yogh;euenes of synne and &thorn;e &yogh;ift of grace wel forto doo. And &thorn;e / glorie of heuene wi&thorn; &thorn;e which god shal guerdon man for his good dedys. [284] and for as moche as Ihesu crist &yogh;eueth vs &thorn;ise &yogh;iftes of his larges and of his souereyn bounte. &thorn;erfor is he cleped / Ihesus Nazarenus rex iudeorum. [285] Ihesus is forto seyn Saueour or sa|uaci&omacr;n on whoom men shullen hope to haue for&yogh;euenesse of synnes which &thorn;at is proprely sauacion of synnes [286] &para; And &thorn;erfore seide &thorn;e aungel to Ioseph. &thorn;ow<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; qualiter an|gelus locutus est Iosepho./</NOTE> clepest his name Ihesus &thorn;at shal saue his puple from her synnes [287] And here-of sei&thorn; Seint Petrer &para; Ther nys noon o&thorn;er name vnder heuene &thorn;at is &yogh;eue to eny man by which a man may be saued. but oonly Ihesus [288] Nazarenus is as moche for to seyn as florsshinge in which a man shal hope &thorn;at he &thorn;at &yogh;eueth hym remission of synnes shal &yogh;eue also hym grace wel to doo for in &thorn;e floure is hope of fruyte in tyme comynge and in for&yogh;euenesse of synnes hope of grace wel to doo. [289] I was at &thorn;e door of &thorn;ine hert seith Ihesus and cleped forto entre. He &thorn;at opne&thorn; to me shal haue for&yogh;euenesse of synne [290] I wil entre into hym by my grace and soupe wi&thorn; hym by &thorn;e good werkes &thorn;at he shal don which werkes bene &thorn;e foode of god. and he shal soupe wi&thorn; me by &thorn;e grete Ioie &thorn;at shal be &yogh;eue to hym [291] Thus shal man hope. &thorn;at for his werkes of penaunce god shuld &yogh;eue hym his regne as he bihote&thorn; hym in the gospel</P>
<P>[292] &para; Now shal man vnderstonde in which 
<PB REF="00000660.tif" N="626"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="610"> manere shal be &thorn;is contricion I say &thorn;at it shal bene vniversale and total This is to saie. a man shal be verrey repentaunt for al his synnes &thorn;at he ha&thorn; doon in delite of his &thorn;ou&yogh;t. ffor delite is ful perilous [293] ffor &thorn;er bene twoo / manere of consentyngges that oon of hem is cleping consentynge of affection whan a man is meued to do synne and delite&thorn; hym longe forto &thorn;enk on &thorn;at synne [294] he ha&thorn; reson aperceyued / <MILESTONE N="279a" UNIT="folio">wel &thorn;at it is synne a&yogh;einst &thorn;e lawe of god . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> al &thorn;ou&yogh;e his reson ne consent not to doon &thorn;e synne in dede. [295] &para; &YOGH;it seyn somme doctours &thorn;at suche delite &thorn;at dwelleth longe it is ful perilous al be it neuere so lite [296] And also a man shuld sorowe namely for al &thorn;at euere he ha&thorn; desired a&yogh;einst &thorn;e lawe of god wi&thorn; parfite consentynge of his reson. ffor &thorn;erof is no &para; doute &thorn;at it is dedly synne in &thorn;e consentinge [297] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> and into dede. [298] Wherfore I say &thorn;at mony men. ne repenten hem neuer of such &thorn;ou&yogh;tes and delices ne neuere shryuen hem of it. but only of &thorn;e dede. of grete synnes outward. [299] wherfore I say &thorn;at such wicked delites and wicked &thorn;ou&yogh;tes bene subtile bygylers of hem &thorn;at shullen be dampned [300] &para; More ouere man ou&yogh;t to sorowen for his wicked wordes and for his wicked dedys ffor certes &thorn;e repentaunce of a syngulere synne and no&yogh;t repent of al her o&thorn;er synnes. or ellis repente hym of al his o&thorn;er synnes and not of syngulere synne may not availe. [301] ffor certes god almy&yogh;ty is al good. and &thorn;erfore he for&yogh;eue&thorn; all or ellis ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t [302] and hereof sei&thorn; seynt Austyne &para; I wote certeynly [303] &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Augustinus ./</NOTE> god is enemye to euery synner &para; and how &thorn;an he &thorn;at obserue&thorn; oon synne. shal he haue for&yogh;euenesse of &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000661.tif" N="627"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="611"> remenaunt of his o&thorn;er synnes. Nay [304] &para; And for&thorn;er ouere / contricion shulde be woundes soryful and ang|uisshous and &thorn;erfore &yogh;eue&thorn; hym god pleynly his mercye. And / &thorn;erfore whan my soule was angwisshous wi&thorn;-in me I had remembraunce of god &thorn;at my preiere myght come to hym. [305] &para; ffer&thorn;er ouer contricion most be continuell. and &thorn;at men han sted|fast purpoos to shryue hym and forto amende hym of his lif. [306] ffor so&thorn;ly &thorn;e whiles contrition laste&thorn; man may haue hope of for&yogh;euenes. And of &thorn;is comme&thorn; hate of synne. &thorn;at destroie&thorn; synne bo&thorn; in hym self and eke in o&thorn;er folk at his power. [307] ffor whiche sei&thorn; dauid / &para; &YOGH;e &thorn;at louen / god haten wikkednes. ffor<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Dauid ./</NOTE> treste&thorn; wel to loue god is forto to loue &thorn;at he loue&thorn;. and hate &thorn;at he hate&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">nota</NOTE></P>
<P>[308] &para; The last &thorn;ing &thorn;at men shal vnderstond in contricion is &thorn;is. wherof availe&thorn; contricion &para; I say &thorn;at somtyme contricion delyuere&thorn; man fro synne. [309] of which &thorn;at dauid sei&thorn;. I say (quod dauid)<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Dauid ./</NOTE> &thorn;at is do say &para; I purpose me fermely to shryve me. And &thorn;ou lord relesedest my synne. [310] And ri&yogh;t so as contrition <MILESTONE N="279b" UNIT="folio">availeth not wi&thorn;-outen sad purpoos of shrift . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> or Satisfaction wi&thorn;-out contricion. [311] And more; &para; Contricion destroie&thorn; &thorn;e prison of helle and maketh it waike and feble&thorn; &thorn;e strengthes of &thorn;e deuels and restore&thorn; &thorn;e &yogh;ift of &thorn;e holy goost and of all vertues [312] and enterly clense&thorn; &thorn;e saule of synne and delyuere&thorn; &thorn;e soule from &thorn;e peyne of helle and fro &thorn;e company of deuels and fro &thorn;e seruage of synne. and restore&thorn; [it] to all goodys espirituell in|to &thorn;e company [and] comunyon of holy churche. [313] And fer&thorn;er ouer it make&thorn; hym &thorn;at whilom was &thorn;e sone of yre &thorn;e sone of grace. And all thise &thorn;ingges he proue&thorn; by holy writt. [314] and &thorn;erfore he &thorn;at wil sette his entent to / &thorn;ise &thorn;ingges he is 
<PB REF="00000662.tif" N="628"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="612"> wis. ffor so&thorn; he shuld not &thorn;an in al his liff haue corage to synne But &thorn;an his body and al his hert to &thorn;e seruise of Ihesu crist and &thorn;erof done him homage. [315] ffor certes our swete lord Ihesu crist ha&thorn; spared vs so / deuourly in our folies &thorn;at &yogh;it he ne had pite of mannys / soule a sory songe my&yogh;t we alle synge.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; 2a pars peni|tencie</NOTE></P>
<TRAILER>&para; Explicit prima pars penitencie.</TRAILER>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Incipit secunda / pars eiusdem./</HEAD>
<P>[316]</P>
<P>&para; THe seconde parte of penitence is confession &thorn;at is signe of contricion [317] &para; Now shul &yogh;e vnderstonde what is confession. and whedere it ou&yogh;t nedes to be or noon. and which &thorn;ingges bene conable to verrey confession</P>
<P>[318] &para; ffirst shalt &thorn;ou vnderstonde &thorn;at confession is verrey shewinge of synnes to &thorn;e preest [319] &thorn;is is to sey verrey. ffor he mot confessen hym of al &thorn;e condicions &thorn;at bylongen to his synne as ferfor&thorn; as he can. [320] al mote be seide and no &thorn;ing excused ne hid ne forwrapped. and nou&yogh;t auaunte him of his good werkes. [321] &para; And for&thorn;er ouer. It is necessary to vnder|stonde whennes &thorn;at synne springe&thorn; and how &thorn;ei encresen. And which &thorn;er bene</P>
<P>[322] in spryngynge of synnes. as sei&thorn; seint poule in &thorn;is wise. / &para; That ri&yogh;t as by a man. synne entred furst into &thorn;e &para; worlde. and &thorn;orghe &thorn;at synne deide. Ri&yogh;t so &thorn;ilk dee&thorn; entre&thorn; into al men &thorn;at synden. [323] And &thorn;is man was // Adam by whom &thorn;at synne entred into &thorn;is world whan he brak &thorn;e comaundement of god. [324] and &thorn;erfore he &thorn;at first was so myghty &thorn;at he shuld not haue deyde. bycame suche oon &thorn;at he most nedys dye whedere he &para; <MILESTONE N="280a" UNIT="folio">wolde or noon. and al his progeny &thorn;at is in &thorn;is world &thorn;at in &thorn;ilk manere synne dyen. [325] Loke &thorn;at in &thorn;e astate of Innocentys &para; whan A[dam a]nd Eue 
<PB REF="00000663.tif" N="629"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="613"> naked weren in paradise. and no &thorn;ing shame ne hadden of her nakednesse. [326] How &thorn;at serpent &thorn;at was most wily of all o&thorn;er beestes &thorn;at god ha&thorn; maked seide to &thorn;e womman &para; Comaunded god to &yogh;ou &yogh;e shuld not eten of euery tree in paradys [327] &para; The womman answerd of &thorn;e fruyte quod she of &thorn;e trees in paradise we feden vs. But so&thorn;ly of &thorn;e froyte of &thorn;e tree &thorn;at is in &thorn;e myddel of paradys god for-bede vs forto ete ne not touche it. lest parauenture we shuld dyen [328] &para; The serpent saide to &thorn;e womman. nay. nay. &yogh;e shullen deye of dethe. ffor so&thorn; god woote &thorn;at what day &thorn;at &yogh;e eten &thorn;erof. &yogh;our eien shullen open. and &yogh;e shullen ben as goddys knowynge good [and] harme [329] &para; The womman seie &thorn;at &thorn;e tree was good to fedynge and faire to &thorn;e eyen and delitable to &thorn;e si&yogh;t she toke of &thorn;e fruyte of &thorn;e tree and ete of hit./ and &yogh;af it to her husbonde and he eete. and anoon &thorn;e eyen of hem bo&thorn; opned / [330] and whan &thorn;at &thorn;ei knewe &thorn;at &thorn;ei were naked &thorn;e[i] sewed of fige leeues in manere of breche to hiden her membres [331] &para; Here may &yogh;e see &thorn;at dedly synne ha&thorn; furst suggestion of &thorn;e feende as schewe&thorn; here by the naddere. And afterward &thorn;e delit of &thorn;e flessh as schewe&thorn; here by Eua. And after &thorn;at &thorn;e consenting of &thorn;e reson as schewe&thorn; by. adam [332] &para; ffor trust wel &thorn;o&yogh;e so were &thorn;at &thorn;e fende tempted oon &thorn;at is to saie &thorn;e flessh. And / &thorn;e flessh had delite in &thorn;e bewte and &thorn;e froyte deffended &yogh;it certes til &thorn;at reson &thorn;at is to sayn Adam con|sented. to &thorn;e etinge of &thorn;e fruyte &thorn;at stood hi&yogh;e in astate of Innocence. [333] &thorn;ilk Adam toke &middot; &thorn;ilk synne of Originall. ffor of hem flesshly descended. bene we all and engendred. of vile and corrupte matere. [334] And whan &thorn;e soule is putt in our body. ri&yogh;t anoon is con|tracte origynal synne. and &thorn;at was eerst but only peyne of concupiscens; is afterward bo&thorn; peyne and synne. [335] And &thorn;erfore be we all yborn sones of 
<PB REF="00000664.tif" N="630"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="614"> wreth and of dampnacion perdurable if it nere baptisme &thorn;at we receyuen which bynyme&thorn; vs &thorn;e Culpe. But for|so&thorn; &thorn;e peyne dwelle&thorn; wi&thorn; vs as &thorn;e <MILESTONE N="280b" UNIT="folio">temptacion which peyne hi&yogh;t concupissens. [336] And &thorn;is concupissence whan it is wrongfully disposed or ordeyned in man it make&thorn; hym to coueite coueitise of flessh flesshly synne by si&yogh;t of his eyen as to er&thorn;ly &thorn;ingges and eke couetise of hynes of pride of hert</P>
<P>[337] &para; Now as to speke of &thorn;e furst Coueitise &thorn;at is concupiscence After &thorn;e lawe of our membres &thorn;at weren lawfully maked and by rightful Iugge|ment of god. [338] I say for as moche as man is not obeysaunt to god &thorn;at is his lord &thorn;erfo is his fleissh to hym disobeisaunt &thorn;orghe concupiscens . . . . . [339] . . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> it is impossible but if he be tempred. somtyme in his flessh and anoyed to synne [340] And &thorn;is &thorn;ing may not faille as longe as &thorn;at he lyue&thorn;. it may wel wexe feble and faile. by vertue of bapteme and by &thorn;e grace of god. &thorn;ourghe penitence. [341] but fully shal it neuere quenche &thorn;at he ne shal som|tyme be neued in hym self. but he were all refreyned by siknes or by malefice of sorcerie or cold drinkes [342] ffor what sei&thorn; seint Poule. &thorn;e flessh coueiten<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Paulus;/</NOTE> a&yogh;eint &thorn;e &para; spirit. and &thorn;e sprit a&yogh;einst &thorn;e flessh &thorn;ei bene so contrarie and so striuen &thorn;at a man may not allway as he wolde [343] &para; The same seint paule aftere his grete penaunce in water and in lond in water by nyght. and in day by grete perile and in grete peyne in londe and enfamyne and thrust in colde and clo&thorn;es. &amp; onys scorned almost to &thorn;e de&thorn;e. [344] &yogh;it seid he allas I catiff man. who shal deliuere me from &thorn;e prison of my catif body [345] And seint Ierom whan he<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ierominus</NOTE> longe tym had w&omacr;nned in deserte where as he had no company. but beestes. wher as he had 
<PB REF="00000665.tif" N="631"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="615"> no mete but herbes. and watere to his drink. ne no bed / but &thorn;e naked er&thorn;e. for whiche his flessh was blak as an / Ethiopen for hete and neighe destroied for colde [346] &yogh;it seide he. &thorn;e brennynge of lecherie boiled in al his body. [347] Wherfore I woote wel sikerly &thorn;at &thorn;ci bene desceyued &thorn;at saien &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne bene not tempted in her body. [348] Witnesse of seynt Iame &thorn;e apostel.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Iacobus;/</NOTE> &thorn;at sei&thorn; &thorn;at euery wi&yogh;t is tempted in his owne con|cupiscence. &thorn;at is to say &thorn;at euerich of vs ha&thorn; matere and occasion to be tempted of &thorn;e norsshinge of synne &thorn;at is in his body. [349] And &thorn;erfor sei&thorn; seint Iohn<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Iohannes Euaungelista./</NOTE> &thorn;e Euaungelist &para; &yogh;if &thorn;at we seyne &thorn;at we be wi&thorn;-outen synne we disceyuen our self. and trou&thorn;e is not in vs.</P>
<P>[350] Now <MILESTONE N="281a" UNIT="folio">shullen &yogh;ee vnderstonde in what manere &thorn;at synne wexe&thorn; and encrese&thorn; in man. The furst &thorn;ing is &thorn;ilk norshyng of synne of which I spak byforn &thorn;ilk concupiscens [351] and after &thorn;at comme&thorn; &thorn;e subieccion of the deuel. &thorn;is is to saye the deueles bely &thorn;i which he blowe&thorn; in man &thorn;e fire of concupiscence. [352] &para; And aftere &thorn;at a man by|&thorn;enke&thorn; hym whedere he wil doo or noon &thorn;ilk &thorn;inge to which he is tempted [353] and &thorn;an if &thorn;at a man wi&thorn;stonde and waye Off &thorn;e furst entisinge of his flessh and of &thorn;e feende &thorn;an is it no synne And if it so be &thorn;at he do not soo &thorn;an fele&thorn; he an&omacr;n a flaumbe of delite [354] and &thorn;an it is good to be ware and to kepe hym wel. Or ellis he wil falle anon into consentyng of synne and &thorn;an wil he do it if he mowe haue tyme and space. [355] And / of &thorn;is matere sei&thorn; Moyses by<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Moyses;/</NOTE> &thorn;e deuel in &thorn;is manere. The fende sei&thorn; I wil chace and pursue &thorn;e man by wicked suggestions and I wil hent hym by mouyng or stiringe of synne And I wil departe my prise or my prey by de|liberacioun. and my lust shal be accomplised by delite &para; I wil drawe my swerde in consentynge. [356] ffor certes ri&yogh;t as a sweerde departe&thorn; a &thorn;inge in twoo peces Ri&yogh;t 
<PB REF="00000666.tif" N="632"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="616"> so consenting departe&thorn; god fro man and than wil I sclee hym wi&thorn; myn honde in dethe / of synne. &thorn;us sei&thorn; &thorn;e feende [357] ffor certes &thorn;an is a man al dede in saule and &thorn;us is synne conplised by tempt|acion by delite and by consentinge and &thorn;an is synne cleped <NOTE PLACE="marg">[&umacr; <I>for</I> ct <I>or</I> cc]</NOTE>a&umacr;uiel //</P>
<P>[358] ffor so&thorn;e synne is in two maners / ei&thorn;er it is venial synne or dedly synne. &para; So&thorn;ly whan man loue&thorn; eny creature more &thorn;an Ihesu crist our creature &thorn;an is it dedly synne And venial synne it is if man loue Ihesu crist lasse &thorn;an hym ou&yogh;te. [359] for so&thorn; &thorn;e dede of &thorn;is venial synne is ful perilous. ffor it amenuse&thorn; &thorn;e loue &thorn;at man shuld haue to god more and more [360] And &thorn;erfor if a man charge more hym self wi&thorn; mony such venyal synnes. certes but if it so be &thorn;at he som|tyme discharge hym of hem by shrift &thorn;ei may ful li&yogh;thly amenuse in hym al &thorn;e loue &thorn;at he ha&thorn; to Ihesu crist [361] and &thorn;is scipped venial into dedly synne. ffor certes &thorn;e more &thorn;at a man charge&thorn; his saule wi&thorn; venial synnes. &thorn;e more is he enclyned to falle in dedly synne [362] And &thorn;erfor lat vs nat be negligent to discharge vs of venyal synnes. ffor &thorn;e prouerbe sei&thorn; &thorn;at mony smale make&thorn; a grete. [363] And harken &thorn;is ensample A grete wawe of the See comme&thorn; somtyme wi&thorn; so grete a violence &thorn;at it drenche&thorn; &thorn;e shippe and &thorn;e same harme doon somtyme &thorn;e smale dropes of water &thorn;at entre&thorn; &thorn;orgh a litel creues into &thorn;e thorrok and into &thorn;e botme of &thorn;e shipp. if men be so necligent &thorn;at men ne <MILESTONE N="281b" UNIT="folio">discharge hem not by tyme [364] And &thorn;erfore al &thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;ere be difference bytwixe &thorn;ise twoo causes of drenching. algates &thorn;e ship is dreint [365] &para; Ri&yogh;t so fare&thorn; it somtyme of dedly synne and of annoyous / venyal synnes whan &thorn;ei multiplie in a man so gretly &thorn;at &thorn;ilk worldly &thorn;ingges &thorn;at he loue&thorn; &thorn;orgh which he synne&thorn; venyally is as grete in his hert as &thorn;e loue of god or more [366] 
<PB REF="00000667.tif" N="633"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="617"> And &thorn;erfor &thorn;e loue of euery &thorn;inge &thorn;at is not bysette in god ne doon principaly for goddes sake al &thorn;of a man loue it lasse &thorn;an god. &yogh;it is it venyal synne. [367] And dedly synne whan &thorn;e loue of eny &thorn;inge. weie&thorn; in &thorn;e hert of a man as moch as &thorn;e loue of god. or more [368] more dedly synne as sei&thorn; seint Austyn.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Augustinus</NOTE> is whan man turne&thorn; his hert fro god which &thorn;at is verrey souereyne bounte &thorn;at may nat chaunge. and &yogh;eue&thorn; his hert to a &thorn;inge &thorn;at may change and flitte. [369] and certes &thorn;at is every &thorn;inge sauf god only of heuene. ffor so&thorn; is &yogh;if &thorn;at a man &yogh;if his loue &thorn;e which &thorn;at he owe&thorn; al to god wi&thorn; al his hert vnto a creature. certes as moche of loue as he &yogh;eueth to whiche creature so moche [he] byreue&thorn; fro god [370] and &thorn;er|fore doo&thorn; he synne. ffor he &thorn;at is dettour to god ne &yogh;elde&thorn; not al his dette to god &thorn;at is to sayn al &thorn;e loue of his hert</P>
<P>[371] &para; Now si&thorn;ens a man vnderstonde&thorn; generally which is venyal synne. &thorn;an is it conable to tellen of special synnes which &thorn;at mony a man parauenture ne deme&thorn; hem not synnes ne schryuen hem nat of &thorn;e same &thorn;ingges and &yogh;it na&thorn;elees &thorn;ei bene synnes [372] and so&thorn;ly as clerkes writen &thorn;is is to say &thorn;at euery tyme &thorn;at a man ete&thorn; or drinke&thorn; more &thorn;an suffiseth to &thorn;e sustinaunce of his body in certeyn he do&thorn; synne [373] &para; And eke whan he speke&thorn; more &thorn;an it nede&thorn;. it is synne. eke whan he harkene&thorn; not mekely &thorn;e complaynt of &thorn;e poore. [374] eke whan he is in hele of body and wil not fast whan o&thorn;ere men fast withouten cause resonable. Eke whan he sclepe&thorn; more &thorn;an nedeth or whan he comme&thorn; by &thorn;ilk encheson late to church or to o&thorn;ere workys of charite. [375] Eke whan he vse&thorn; his wiff wi&thorn;-outen souereyne desire of engendrure to honure of god. Or for &thorn;e entent to &yogh;eelde to his wiff &thorn;e dette of his body. [376] Eke whan he wil not visite &thorn;e seke or &thorn;e prisoners when he maye. 
<PB REF="00000668.tif" N="634"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="618"> Eke if he loue wiff or child or eny worldely &thorn;ing more &thorn;an reson require&thorn;. Eke if he flatere or blaundissh more &thorn;an hym ou&yogh;t for eny necessite./ [377] &para; Eke if he amenuse or wi&thorn;drawe &thorn;e almesse of &thorn;e poor./ <MILESTONE N="282a" UNIT="folio">&para; Eke if he apparaille&thorn; his mete more deliciously &thorn;an nede is. or ete it to hastely by licourous|nesse [378] &para; Eke if he tale vanytees at &thorn;e churche or at goddes seruise. or &thorn;at he be a talker of ydel wordys of foly or of vilanye. for he shal &yogh;eelde accountes of it at &thorn;e day of dome [379] &para; Eke whan he bihote&thorn; or assure&thorn; to done &thorn;ingges &thorn;at he may not perfourme &para; Eke whan &thorn;at by li&yogh;tnesse of foly [he] mysseie&thorn; or scorne&thorn; his neighbour [380] &para; Eke whan he ha&thorn; eny wikked suspeci&omacr;n of &thorn;inge &thorn;er he ne wote of it no so&thorn;|fastnesse [381] &para; Thise / &thorn;inges and moo wi&thorn;-out nombre bene synnes as sei&thorn; seynt Austyne<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Augustinus.</NOTE></P>
<P>[382] &para; Now shul men vnderstonde &thorn;at al be it soo &thorn;at noon / er&thorn;ely man may eschwe all venial synnes. &yogh;it may he refreyn hym by &thorn;e brennyng loue &thorn;at he ha&thorn; to our lord Ihesu crist and by preiers and confessioun and o&thorn;er good werkes so &thorn;at it shal but litel greue. [383] ffor as sei&thorn; seynt Austyne. If a man loue god<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Idem./</NOTE> in such manere &thorn;at al &thorn;at euere he doo&thorn; is in &thorn;e loue of god / or for &thorn;e loue of god verreyly. for he brenne&thorn; in &thorn;e loue of god. [384] &para; loke howe moche &thorn;at a drope of watere &thorn;at falle&thorn; in a fournays ful of fuyre annoye&thorn; or greue&thorn; so moche annoye&thorn; a venyal synne vnto a man &thorn;at is parfit in &thorn;e loue of Ihesu crist [385] &para; Men may also refreyne venyal synne by &thorn;e receyuynge of &thorn;e precious body of Ihesu crist [386] By receyuyng eke of holy watere. by almes dede. by general confession of confiteor at &thorn;e mas. at complyne. and by blessing of bisshoppys and of preestes and by other good werkes.
</P>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000669.tif" N="635"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="619">
<HEAD>&para; Sequitur de septem peccatis mortalibus. scilicet de Superbia. et eorum dependencijs. circumstancijs &amp; spectantibus. /.</HEAD>
<P>[387]</P>
<P>&para; Now is it bihouely &thorn;inge to tellen which bene dedly synnes &thorn;at is to say Caytifnesse of synnes al &thorn;ei renne in cooles. but in dyuers manere &para; Now bene &thorn;ei cleped Caytif for as moche as &thorn;ei bene cheef. and spryngen of all o&thorn;er synnes [388] Of &thorn;e roote of &thorn;ise vij. synnes. pride is &thorn;e general rote of al harmes. ffor of &thorn;is roote springen certeyn braunches. as Ire. Envie. Accidie. or scloweth. Auarice. or couetise to comon vnderstondinge. Glotenye. and lechery. [389] And euerich of &thorn;ise chief synnes ha&thorn; his braunches and his twigges. as shal be declared in her chapiters folowynge.</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[De superbia.]</HEAD>
<P>[390] And &thorn;ou&yogh;e so be &thorn;at no man can / telle vtterly &thorn;e nombre of &thorn;e twigges and of &thorn;e harmes &thorn;at comme&thorn; of pride. &yogh;it wil I shewe a party of hem as &yogh;e shul vnderstond. [391] Ther is <B>Inobedience</B> Auauntinge. <B>Ypocresie. Despite. arro</B><MILESTONE N="282b" UNIT="folio"><B>gance. Imprudence. Swellinge of hert. Insolence.</B> Elacioun. <B>Pertinacie. veynglorie; Inpacience &para; strif. Contumacie.</B> presumcioun. <B>irreuer|ence</B> &para; and mony ano&thorn;er twigge &thorn;at I can not declare [392] &para; Inobedient is he &thorn;at disobeie&thorn; for despite to &thorn;e comaun|ment of god and to his souereyns and to his goostly fadere [393] &para; Auauntour is he &thorn;at booste&thorn; of &thorn;e harme or of &thorn;e bounte &thorn;at he ha&thorn; doon [394] &para; Ipocresie is hee &thorn;at hide&thorn; hym to shewe hym such as he is. and schewe&thorn; hym suche as he is not [395] &para; Dispitous is he &thorn;at ha&thorn; disdeyne of his neighbours &thorn;at is to sayn of his euen / cristen or ha&thorn; despite to doo &thorn;at hym ou&yogh;t to doo [396] &para; Arrogance is he &thorn;at &thorn;enkc&thorn; &thorn;at he ha&thorn; &thorn;ilk bountes in hym that he ha&thorn; not. or 
<PB REF="00000670.tif" N="636"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="620"> wene&thorn; &thorn;at he shuld haue hem of his desertes. or ellis &thorn;at he deme&thorn; &thorn;at he be. &thorn;at he nys nou&yogh;t [397] &para; Im|pudent is he &thorn;at for his pride ha&thorn; no shame for his synne [398] &para; Swelling of herte is he. whan a man reioyse&thorn;. hym of harme &thorn;at he ha&thorn; don [399] &para; Inso|lent is he. &thorn;at despise&thorn; in his Iuggement al o&thorn;er folk as to regarde of his valewe and of his connynge. and of his spekinge. and / of his berynge [400] &para; Elacion is whan &thorn;at he ne may nei&thorn;er suffre to haue maistrie ne felawe [401] &para; Inpacient is he &thorn;at wil not bene ytau&yogh;t ne vnder|nome of his vices and by strif werreie&thorn; / trou&thorn;e wittyngly and defende&thorn; his folye [402] &para; Contymax is he &thorn;at &thorn;orghe his indignaci&omacr;n is a&yogh;einst euerich auttorite or power of hem &thorn;at bene his souereyns [403] &para; Pre|sumpci&omacr;n is he. whan a man take&thorn; an emprise &thorn;at hym ou&yogh;t not to doo. or ellis he may it nou&yogh;t doo and &thorn;at is called Surquidrie &para; Irreuerence is whan men done nat honure &thorn;er as hem ou&yogh;t to doon. and waiten to be reuerensed [404] &para; Pertynacy is. whan a man defende&thorn; his foly. and truste&thorn; to moche to his owne witte. [405] &para; Veynglorie is forto haue pompe and delite in temporel heuynesse and glorifie hem in worldly estates [406] &para; Iangelynge is whan a man speke&thorn; to moche toforn folke and clappe&thorn; as a mylle. and take&thorn; no kepe what he sai&thorn;.</P>
<P>[407] and &yogh;it is &thorn;er a privey spice of pride &thorn;at waite&thorn; first to be halowed or he wil be salwed al be he lasse wor&thorn;i &thorn;an &thorn;at o&thorn;ere is parauenture and eke he waite&thorn; or desire&thorn; to sitte or to goo aboue hym in &thorn;e way or kys paxe or bene ensensed or goon / to offringe byforn his neighbour [408] and such . . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> a proude desire to be magnyfied / and honoured to forn &thorn;e puple.</P>
<P>[409] &para; Nowe ben &thorn;ere twoo maners of pride. &thorn;at oon of hem is wi&thorn;-in &thorn;e herte <MILESTONE N="283a" UNIT="folio">of man and &thorn;at 
<PB REF="00000671.tif" N="637"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="621"> o&thorn;er is wi&thorn;-out [410] &para; Of which so&thorn;ly &thorn;e for seide &thorn;ingges and moo &thorn;an I haue seide appertenaunte to pride &thorn;at is in &thorn;e herte of man. And &thorn;erto o&thorn;er spices of pride bene wi&thorn;-outen [411] But na&thorn;elees oon of &thorn;ise spices of pride is signe of &thorn;at o&thorn;er/ Ri&yogh;t as / &thorn;e gay leeuesell att tauerns is signe of &thorn;e wyne &thorn;at is in &thorn;e salere. [412] As &thorn;is is in mony &thorn;ingges as in speche and in countenaunces. And in outrageous araye of clo&thorn;inge / [413] for certes of &thorn;is nad he no synne<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nota de super|bia vestimento|rum.</NOTE> in clo&thorn;inge. Crist wold not so sone haue noted and spoke of &thorn;e clo&thorn;inge of &thorn;ilk riche men in &thorn;e gospell [414] &para; And as sei&thorn; seynt Gregore. &thorn;at precious clo&thorn;ing is cou|pable for &thorn;e der&thorn;e of hit. and for his so&thorn;nesse and for his straungenesse. and for his disgisenesse and for &thorn;e super|fluite. or for &thorn;e inordinate scantnesse . . . . [415] . . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></P>
<P>[416] as to &thorn;e furst synne &thorn;at is in superfluyte of clo&thorn;inge which &thorn;at make&thorn; it so dere to harme of &thorn;e puple [417] &thorn;at only &thorn;e cost of enbrawdynge. &thorn;e degyse endentynge or barringe. owdyng palynge. or bendinge. and semblable waast of clo&thorn;inge in vanyte [418] But &thorn;er is also costlewe furringe in her gownes / so moch pownsenynge of Chisels to maken holes. so mochel daggyng of sheres [419] for&thorn;with the Superfluyte in length of &thorn;e forseide gownes tral|ynge in &thorn;e dunge and in &thorn;e myre on hors and eke on foote as wel of man as of womman &thorn;at al &thorn;ilk traillyng is verrely as in effecte waasted. consumed. thred|bare and roten wi&thorn; dunge ra&thorn;er &thorn;an it is &yogh;euen to &thorn;e poor to grete damage of &thorn;e forseid poor folk [420] and &thorn;at in sondrie wise This is to seyn. &thorn;e more &thorn;at cloo&thorn; is waasted &thorn;e more mote it cost to &thorn;e puple for &thorn;e scarcenesse [421] &para; And fer&thorn;erouere if it so be &thorn;at &thorn;ei wolde &yogh;eue suche pounsoned and 
<PB REF="00000672.tif" N="638"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="622"> dagged clo&thorn;ing to &thorn;e poor folk. it is not conuenient to were for her estate ne suffisaunt to bete her necessite to kepe hem from &thorn;e desperaunce of &thorn;e firmament [422] &para; On &thorn;at o&thorn;er side to speke of &thorn;at disordynat scanternesse of clo&thorn;inge as bene thise Cutted scloppes or hanselynes &thorn;at &thorn;orgh her schortnesse ne keuere not &thorn;e shameful membres of man to wikked entent [423] Alas somme of hem shewen &thorn;e Shappe and &thorn;e bote of &thorn;e horrible swollen menbres &thorn;at seme&thorn; like to &thorn;e malady of hirnia in the wrapping of her hosen. [424] and eke &thorn;e buttokkes of hem &thorn;at faren as it were &thorn;e hynder part of asshe ape in &thorn;e ful of &thorn;e mone. [425] And more ouer the wrecched swollen membres &thorn;at &thorn;ei / shewe &thorn;orgh disgisinge in departinge of her hosen white and <MILESTONE N="283b" UNIT="folio">rede seme&thorn; &thorn;at half hyre shame|ful prive membres weren flayne [426] and so be &thorn;at &thorn;ei departen her hosen in o&thorn;ere colours as is white and blak or white and blewe or blak and rede and so / for&thorn;. [427] &thorn;an ne seme&thorn; it as by variaunce of coloure &thorn;at half &thorn;e party of his privey membres bene corrupte by &thorn;e fuyr of seynt Antonye or by cancre or by o&thorn;er such meschaunces [428] &para; &yogh;it of &thorn;e hyndere parte of her buttokkes it is ful horrible forto see. for certes in &thorn;at party of her body &thorn;er as &thorn;ei purgen her stynkinge ordure [429] &thorn;at foule party shewe &thorn;ei proudely to &thorn;e puple in despite of honeste. which honeste &thorn;at Ihesu crist and his frendes obserued to shewe in his lif [430] &para; Now as to outragious aray of wommen god woote &thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;e visage of hem semen ful chaaste and debonaire. &yogh;it notefyen &thorn;ei in her aray of a-tyre likerousnesse and pride [431] &para; I say not &thorn;at honeste in clo&thorn;inge of man and womman is vncon|able. but certes &thorn;e superfluite or &thorn;e disordynate scantite of clo&thorn;inge is reproueable [432] &para; Also &thorn;e synne of anornament or apparaile in &thorn;ingges &thorn;at appertenen to ridynge. as into mony delicate horses &thorn;at bene holden 
<PB REF="00000673.tif" N="639"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="623"> for delite. &thorn;at &thorn;ei bene so faire. fatte and costlewe. [433] and also mony a vicious knaue Meyntened by cause [of hem] and in to curious harnays and in sadels. In cropours in peytrellis and bridell keuered wi&thorn; precious clo&thorn;e and riche barres and plates of golde and of siluere. [434] ffor which god sei&thorn; by Sakarye &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Zacharia pro|pheta</NOTE> prophete &para; I wil confounde &thorn;e riders of suche horses [435] &para; This folk taken litel rewardinge of &thorn;e rydinge of goddes sone of heuene and of his harnays whan he rode vpon an asse and had noon o&thorn;er harnayes but clo&thorn;es of his poor disciples. ne w[e] ne rede not &thorn;at euere he rode on o&thorn;er beest // [436] I speke &thorn;us of &thorn;e synne of superfluyte and not for &thorn;e resonable honeste whan reson it require&thorn;. [437] And fer&thorn;er / ouer certes pride is gretly notefied in holdinge of grete mayne whan &thorn;ei bene of litel profit or of ri&yogh;t of no profite [438] And namely whan &thorn;at Mayne is felenous and damag|ous to &thorn;e puple by hardynesse of hie lordship or by wey of office. [439] ffor certus such lordes foylen &thorn;an her lordshipes to &thorn;e deuel of helle whan &thorn;ei sustene &thorn;e wikkednesse of her mayne [440] &para; Or ellis whan &thorn;ise folk of lowe degree. as &thorn;ilk &thorn;at halden ostelers. sustene &thorn;e &thorn;eft for her ostilers and &thorn;at is in mony <MILESTONE N="284a" UNIT="folio">maners of disceytes. [441] Thilk manere of folk bene &thorn;e flies &thorn;at folowen &thorn;e honye Or ellis &thorn;e houndes &thorn;at folowen &thorn;e Careyn which forseide folk stranglen spirituelly her lordshipes. [442] ffor which &thorn;us sei&thorn; Dauid &thorn;e prophet &para; Wikked<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Dauid pro|pheta./</NOTE> de&thorn; mote come on &thorn;ilk lordeshipes and [god] &yogh;eue &thorn;at &thorn;ei mote descende a doune into helle. ffor in her houses bene iniquitees and shrewdenesses and not god of heuene. [443] And certes but if &thorn;ei done amende|ment Ri&yogh;t so as god &yogh;af his blessinge to Pharao by &thorn;e seruise of Iacob. &amp; to Laban by the seruise of Ioseph. Ri&yogh;t so god wil &yogh;eue his malison to suche lordshippes as to sustene &thorn;e wikkednesse of her seruauntes . . . . 
<PB REF="00000674.tif" N="640"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="624"> . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [444] &para; Pride of &thorn;e table appere&thorn; eke ful oft. for certes / riche men bene cleped to feestes and poor folk ben putte away and rebuked [445] in excesse of dyuers metes and drynkes and namely suche manere of bake metes . . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> and of semblabled waast so &thorn;at it is / abusion forto &thorn;enk [446] and eke in grete preciousnesse of vessell and curiosite of Mynstralcie by &thorn;e which a man is stired &thorn;e more to delices of luxurie [447] If so be &thorn;at he sette his hert lesse vpon our lord Ihesu crist certeyn it is a synne And certeynly &thorn;e delites / my&yogh;t bene so grete in &thorn;e caas &thorn;at men my&yogh;t li&yogh;tly falle by hem into dedly synne [448] &para; The Espices &thorn;at sourden of pride. so&thorn;ly whan &thorn;ei sourden of malice ymagyned and avised and forn cast . . or ellis of vsage bene dedly synnes. it is no doute. [449] And whan &thorn;ei sourden by freelte vn|avised sodeynly and sodeynly wi&thorn;drawe a&yogh;ein. all bene &thorn;ei greuous synnes I. gesse &thorn;at &thorn;ei be not dedly [450] &para; Nowe myght men aske wherof &thorn;at pride sourde&thorn; and springeth. And I say somtyme it springe&thorn; of &thorn;e goodes of nature and somtyme of &thorn;e goodes of fortune. and somtyme of &thorn;e goodes of grace. [451] Certes &thorn;e goodes of nature stonden in &thorn;e goodes of body or goodes of soule [452] Certes &thorn;e goodes of body bene hele of body strength delyuernesse. beute. gentrie. ffraunchises [453] &para; Goodes of nature of &thorn;e saule bene good wi&thorn; sharpe vnderstondinge sotile engin &para; vertu material. good memorie [454] &para; Goodes of fortune ben richeses hye degrees of lordshipes. preisynges of &thorn;e puple [455] &para; Goodes of grace bene sciences. power to suffre spirituell trauaile benygnitees vertuous contemplacion. wi&thorn;stondyng of temptacion and semblable &thorn;ingges [456] of which forseide goodes certes it is a ful grete foly a man to priden hym in eny of hem alle. [457] 
<PB REF="00000675.tif" N="641"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="625"> Now as forto speke of goodes of nature. god wote &thorn;at somtyme <MILESTONE N="284b" UNIT="folio">we han hem in nature as moche to our damage as to our profit [458] As forto speke of hel&thorn;e of body; certys it passe&thorn; ful li&yogh;tly. and eke it is ful oft encheson of &thorn;e siknesse of &thorn;e saule for god wote &thorn;e flessh is a ful grete enymye to &thorn;e soule And &thorn;erfore &thorn;e more &thorn;at a body is hool &thorn;e more be we in perile to falle [459] &para; Eke forto pride hym in his strenght of body it is an hie foly for certes &thorn;e flessh coueite&thorn; a&yogh;einst &thorn;e spirit And ay &thorn;e more stronge &thorn;at &thorn;e flessh is; &thorn;e sorier may &thorn;e saule be [460] &para; And oueral &thorn;is strength of body and worldly hardnesse cause&thorn; ful often many men to perile and meschaunce [461] &para; Eke forto pride hym of his gentrie is ful grete foly. ffor often tyme &thorn;e gentry of &thorn;e body. bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e gentry of the saule And eke we bene al of oon fadere and al of oo modere. and al we be of oo nature roten and corrupte bo&thorn; riche and poor [462] &para; fforso&thorn; a manere gentrie is to preise &thorn;at apparaille&thorn; mannys corage wi&thorn; vertues of moralitees and make&thorn; hym cristes child [463] &para; ffor treste&thorn; wel &thorn;at ouer what man &thorn;at synne ha&thorn; maistrie he is verrey cherle to synne.</P>
<P>[464] &para; Nowe bene &thorn;ere general &thorn;ingges of gentilnesses. as schewyng of vices or ribawdry and seruage of synne. in worde. in werk. in contenaunce [465] &amp; vsyng vertu. Curtesie. and clennesse and to be liberal &thorn;at is to sayn / large by mesure. ffor &thorn;ilk &thorn;at passen mesure is foly and synne [466] &para; A no&thorn;er is to remembre hym of bounte &thorn;at he of o&thorn;ere folk ha&thorn; receyued. [467] Ano&thorn;ere is to be benigne of his sogette. wher-fore as sei&thorn; Senek. Ther is no &thorn;inge more<NOTE PLACE="marg"><B>&para; Seneca</B></NOTE> conable to a man of hie estate &thorn;an debonairte [468] &para; And &thorn;erfore &thorn;ise flies &thorn;at men / clepen bees whan &thorn;ei maken her kynge &thorn;ei chesen oon &thorn;at ha&thorn; no prikke wherwi&thorn; he may stynge [469] 
<PB REF="00000676.tif" N="642"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="626"> &para; Ano&thorn;er is a man to haue a noble hert and a diligent to atteyn to hie vertuous &thorn;ingges <NOTE PLACE="inline">[470<SUP>*</SUP> <I>see after</I> 474 <I>and Hengwrt and Petworth MSS.</I></NOTE> . . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [471] &para; Certes also who &thorn;at pride&thorn; hym in &thorn;e goodes of fortune he is a ful grete fool. ffor somtyme is a man a ful grete lord by &thorn;e morowe; &thorn;at is a wrecche and a caytif er it be nyght [472] And somtyme &thorn;e . . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> delites of a man ben cause of &thorn;e greuous malady &thorn;orgh which he dyeth [473] Certes &thorn;e commendacion of &thorn;e puple is som|tyme ful fals and ful/ brutile forto trest. This day &thorn;ei preise to morowe &thorn;ei blame. [474] God woote desire to haue commendaci&omacr;n eke of puple ha&thorn; caused de&thorn;e to mony a bisy man [<SUP>*</SUP>470] Now certys a man <MILESTONE N="285a" UNIT="folio">to pride hym in goodes of grace is eke an outrageous foly for &thorn;ilk &yogh;iftes of grace &thorn;at shuld haue turned hym to goodnesse and to medecyne. turne&thorn; hym to venym and to confusion as seith seynt Gregor.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; gregorius</NOTE> [475] &para; Now sy&thorn;ens &thorn;at so is &thorn;at &yogh;e han vnderstonden what is pride. and which bene &thorn;e spices of it and whennys pride sourde&thorn; and springe&thorn;</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[The Remedy against Pride.]</HEAD>
<P>[476] Now shal &yogh;e vnderstonde which is &thorn;e remedy a&yogh;einst<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Remedium <I>contra</I></NOTE> pride. and &thorn;at is humilite or<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Superbiam</NOTE> mekenesse [477] &thorn;at is a vertue &thorn;orgh which a man ha&thorn; verrey &para; knowlecch of hym self and holde&thorn; of hym self no pris ne deynte as in regarde of his desertes consideryng euer his freelte [478] &para; Now bene &thorn;er thre maners of humilite. as humilite in hert anno&thorn;er in mou&thorn; / and &thorn;e iij. is in werkes [479] &para; The humilite of herte is in iiij. maners. &thorn;at oon is whan a man bolde&thorn; hymself as nou&yogh;t wor&thorn; by-fore god in heuene. Ano&thorn;er is whan he despise&thorn; 
<PB REF="00000677.tif" N="643"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="627"> noon o&thorn;er man [480] &para; The iij. is whan he rekketh nou&yogh;t &thorn;o&yogh;e / men holde hym nou&yogh;t wor&thorn; &para; The iiij. is whan he nys not sory of his humiliaci&omacr;n [481] &para; Also &thorn;e humilite of mou&thorn; is in 4 &thorn;ingges In attemprure speche and in humblesse of speche. And whan he byknowe&thorn; wi&thorn; his owne mou&thorn; &thorn;at he is such as hym &thorn;enke&thorn; &thorn;at he is in his hert. Ano&thorn;er is whan he preise&thorn; &thorn;e bounte of ano&thorn;er man and no&thorn;eng &thorn;erof amenuse&thorn; [482] humilite &para; Eke in werk is in 4. maners. The furst is whan he putte&thorn; o&thorn;er men to-forn hym. The secounde is to chese &thorn;e lowest place ouerall The iij. is gladly to assent to good counsaile [483] &para; The 4. is gladly to stonde to &thorn;e award of his souereyn or of hym &thorn;at is hier in degre Certeyn &thorn;is is a grete werk of humilite.</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; De Peccato. Inuidie.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De inuidia;/ /</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>[484]</P>
<P>Aftere pride wil I speke of &thorn;e foule synne of envie which &thorn;at is as by &thorn;e word of &thorn;e philisophre sorow of o&thorn;ere mannys prosperite And aftere &thorn;e word of seynt Austyne. it is sorowe of o&thorn;er mennes wele and Ioie of o&thorn;er mennys harme [485] &para; This foule synne is platly a&yogh;einst &thorn;e holy goost. al be it so &thorn;at euery synne be a&yogh;einst &thorn;e holy goost. &yogh;it for as moche as bounte appertene&thorn; proprely to &thorn;e holy goost. and envie comme&thorn; proprely of malice &thorn;er|fore is proprely a&yogh;enist &thorn;e bounte of &thorn;e holy goost [486] &para; Now ha&thorn; malice ij. spices. &thorn;at is to sayn hardnes of herte. And wikkednesse or ellis &thorn;e flessh of a man is so blynde &thorn;at he <MILESTONE N="285b" UNIT="folio">considere&thorn; not &thorn;at he is in synne . . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> which is &thorn;e hardnesse of &thorn;e deuell [487] &para; That o&thorn;ere spice of envie is whan &thorn;at a man / werre&thorn; trou&thorn;e whan &thorn;at he wote &thorn;at it is trou&thorn;e. And eke whan &thorn;at he werreie&thorn; &thorn;e grace of &thorn;at god ha&thorn; &yogh;eue to his 
<PB REF="00000678.tif" N="644"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="628"> nei&yogh;boure. and al &thorn;is is by envie [488] Certes &thorn;an is envie &thorn;e worst synne &thorn;at is. ffor so&thorn;ly al o&thorn;er synnes bene somtyme a&yogh;ein oo special vertue [489] But certes envie is a&yogh;einst alle vertues and of alle goodnesses for it is sory of alle bountes of neighbour. and in &thorn;is manere it is dyuers from alle maner synnes. [490] ffor wel vnne&thorn;es is &thorn;er eny synne &thorn;at it ne ha&thorn; somme delite in hym self sauf only envie &thorn;at euer ha&thorn; in [hym]self anguyssh and sorowe [491] &para; The spices of envie bene &thorn;ise. &thorn;er is furst sorowe of o&thorn;er mennys goodnesse and of her pros|perite . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> is kyndely matere of Ioye. &thorn;an is enuye a synne a&yogh;einst kinde. [492] &para; The seconnde spice of envie is Ioie of o&thorn;er mennys harme. . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [493] Of &thorn;is seconnde spice comme&thorn; bakbitynge . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> or detraccion and &thorn;at ha&thorn; ij. spices as thus; &para; Somme man preise&thorn; his nei&yogh;bour by a wikked entent. [494] for he make&thorn; alway a wikked knotte at the last ende. alwey he make&thorn; a but at &thorn;e last ende. &thorn;at is digne and more blame than wor&thorn;e is al the plesinge [495] &para; The seconnde spice is &thorn;at if a man be good and do&thorn; and sai&thorn; a &thorn;inge to good entent &thorn;e bakbiter wil turne al &thorn;e goodnesse vp so doun to his schrewde entent [496] &para; The iij. is to amenuse &thorn;e bounte of his neigh|boure [497] &para; &thorn;e .4. spice of bakbityng is &thorn;is. &thorn;at if men speke goodnesse of a man wil &thorn;e bakkbyter sayn parfay such a man &yogh;it is bette &thorn;an he in dispreysinge of hym that men preise [498] &para; The .v. spice is forto consent gladly harken &thorn;e harme &thorn;at men speken of o&thorn;er folk. &thorn;is synne is ful grete and ay encrese&thorn; after &thorn;e wikked entent of &thorn;e bakbiter [499] &para; aftere bakbitynge comme&thorn; grucchynge or murmuraunce and somtyme it springe&thorn; of inpacience a&yogh;einst god and somtyme a&yogh;einst man 
<PB REF="00000679.tif" N="645"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="629"> [500] A&yogh;einst god it is whan a man gruccheth a&yogh;einst &thorn;e peyn of helle or a&yogh;einst pouert or losse of catell or a&yogh;einst reyne or tempest or ellis grucche&thorn; &thorn;at shrewes han prosperite. or ellis good men han ad|uersite. [501] and alle thise &thorn;ingges shuld men suffre paciently. for &thorn;ei commen by the ri&yogh;tful Iuggement and ordinaunce of god [502] &para; Somtyme <MILESTONE N="286a" UNIT="folio">comme&thorn; grucchinge of auarice as Iudas grucched a&yogh;einst &thorn;e Mawdelene whan she ennoynted &thorn;e hede of oure lorde Ihesu crist wi&thorn; her precious oynement [503] This maner of murmur is such as whan men grucchen of goodnesse and &thorn;at men selue done er &thorn;at o&thorn;er folk doon of her owne Catell [504] &para; Somtyme comme&thorn; murmur of pride / as whan symon &thorn;e phiryse grucched a&yogh;einst Maudeleyn. whan she approched to Ihesu crist and wepte at his fete for her synnes. [505] And somtyme it sourde&thorn; to envie whan man diskeuere&thorn; a mannys harme &thorn;at was pryvey or bere&thorn; hym / on honde &thorn;inge &thorn;at is fals [506] &para; Murmur eke is oft amonges seruauntes &thorn;at grucchen whan her souereynes bidden / hem to doon leeful &thorn;ingges. [507] and for as moche as &thorn;ei dure not openly say nay. ne wi&thorn;|saye the comaundementz of her souereyn. &yogh;it wil &thorn;ei saye harme and grucche and murmure priuely for verrey despite. [508] which wordes men clepe &thorn;e deuels Pater noster. Thou&yogh;e so be &thorn;at &thorn;e deuel had neuere Pater noster. but &thorn;at folk &yogh;euen it such a name. [509] Somtyme it comme&thorn; of Ire or of prive hate &thorn;at norssheth rancour in hert as afterward I shal declare. [510] &thorn;an comme&thorn; eke bitternesse of hert &thorn;orgh which bitternesse euery good dede of his nei&yogh;bour seme&thorn; to hym bitter and vnsauery [511] Than comme&thorn; discord &thorn;at ynbynde&thorn; al maner of frendship Than comme&thorn; scornynge of . . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> his nei&yogh;|bour al doo he neuer so wel [512] &para; Than comme&thorn; accusinge as whan a man seke&thorn; occasion to annoyen his 
<PB REF="00000680.tif" N="646"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="630"> neighbour which &thorn;at is like &thorn;e craft of &thorn;e deuel &thorn;at waite&thorn; bo&thorn; ny&yogh;t and day to accusen vs alle [513] &para; Than commeth malignite &thorn;orgh which a man annoye&thorn; his neighbour prively if he may [514] And if he no&yogh;t ne may algate his wikked wille ne shal not wante. as forto brenne his hous prively. or enpoysen or scleen / his beestes and semblable &thorn;ingges</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; Remedium <I>contra</I> <B>Inuidiam</B> [<I>from the margin</I>]</HEAD>
<P>[515] &para; Now wil I speke of &thorn;e remedie a&yogh;einst &thorn;is foule synne of Envie &para; ffirst is &thorn;e loue of god principal and louyng of hym self and of his neighbour. ffor so&thorn;ly &thorn;at oon ne may not be wi&thorn;outen &thorn;at o&thorn;er [516] And trust wel &thorn;at in &thorn;e name of &thorn;i neighbour &thorn;ou shalt vnderstonde &thorn;e name of &thorn;i bro&thorn;er ffor certes al we han oo fader flesshly. and oo Modere <MILESTONE N="286b" UNIT="folio">that is to say Adam and Eve and eke oo fadere spirituel &thorn;at is to say god of heuene [517] Thine nei&yogh;boure art &thorn;ou holden forto louen And willen hym al goodnesse and &thorn;erfore sei&thorn; god loue &thorn;ine neigbour as &thorn;ine self &thorn;at is to say to saluacion bo&thorn; of lif and of saule [518] And more ouer &thorn;ou shalt loue hym in word and benigne amonesynge and chastisynge and conforte hym in his anoyes and prey for hym wi&thorn; al &thorn;ine hert [519] &para; And in/ dede &thorn;ou shalt loue hym in such wise &thorn;at &thorn;ou shalt done to hym in charite as &thorn;ow woldest men did to &thorn;ine owne persone. [520] &amp; &thorn;erfore &thorn;ow shalt not done hym no damage ne wikked worde ne harme in his body ne in his catel ne in his saule by entising of wikked ensample. [521] &thorn;ow shalt not desiren his wif ne noon / of his &thorn;ingges &para; Vnderstonde eke &thorn;at in &thorn;e name of &thorn;i neighboure his com|prehended his enemye. [522] Certes a man shal loue his enemye for &thorn;e comaundmentz of god And so&thorn;ely &thorn;i frende shalt &thorn;ou loue in god. [523] I say &thorn;ine Enemye shalt &thorn;ou loue for goddis sake by his comaunde|ment. 
<PB REF="00000681.tif" N="647"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="631"> ffor if it were reson &thorn;at man shuld hate his enemye. forso&thorn; god wold not receyue vs to his loue &thorn;at bene his enemyes [524] a&yogh;einst iij manere of wrongges &thorn;at his enemye do&thorn; to hym he shal do &thorn;re &thorn;ingges as &thorn;us. [525] A&yogh;einst hate and rancour of hert he shal loue hym in hert. A&yogh;einst chidynge and wikked wordes. he shal prey for his enemye. A&yogh;einst &thorn;e wikked dede of his enemye he shal doon hym bounte [526] ffor crist sei&thorn;. Loue&thorn; &yogh;oure enemyes and preie&thorn; for hem &thorn;at speke&thorn; &yogh;ou harme And eke for hem &thorn;at &yogh;ou chasen and purswen and doth bounte to hem &thorn;at yow haten &para; Loo &thorn;us comaunde&thorn; vs our lord Ihesu crist to doo to oure enemyes. [527] ffor so&thorn;ly nature dryue&thorn; vs to loue our frendes. And parfay oure enemyes han more nede to loue &thorn;an our frendes. and &thorn;ei &thorn;at more nede haue certes to hem shal men doo good|nes. [528] and certes in &thorn;ilk dede haue [we] remem|braunce of &thorn;e loue of Ihesu crist &thorn;at deyed for his enemyes. [529] And in as moche as &thorn;ilk loue is &thorn;e more greuous to perfourme so moche is more grete &thorn;e merite And &thorn;erfore the louyng of our enemye ha&thorn; confounded &thorn;e venyme of &thorn;e deuell. [530] ffor ri&yogh;t as &thorn;e deuel is discomfited by humilite ri&yogh;t so is he wounded to the dee&thorn; by &thorn;e loue of oure enemye [531] Certes &thorn;an is loue &thorn;e medecyne &thorn;at chaseth out &thorn;e ve<MILESTONE N="287a" UNIT="folio"> nym of Envie fro mannys herte [532] The spices of &thorn;is pas shullen be more largely declared in her chapiters folowinge</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; <B>De Ira;</B> / [<I>from the margin</I>]</HEAD>
<P>[533]</P>
<P>Aftere Envie wil I declare &thorn;e synne of Ire ffor so&thorn;ly who &thorn;at ha&thorn; Enuye vpon his nei&yogh;bour anoon comonly he wil fynde hym matere of wreth in worde or in dede a&yogh;einst hym to whoom he ha&thorn; envie [534] And as wel comme&thorn; Ire of pride 
<PB REF="00000682.tif" N="648"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="632"> as of enuye. ffor so&thorn;ly he &thorn;at is proude or envious is li&yogh;tly wroo&thorn;</P>
<P>[535]</P>
<P>This synne of Ire aftere &thorn;e descriuynge of seint Austyne is wikked will to bene auenged. by<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; &Verbar; Augustinus</NOTE> worde or by dede &Verbar; [536] Ire aftere &thorn;is Philisophre is &thorn;e veruent blood of man yquykked in his hert &thorn;orgh which he wil / harme to hym &thorn;at he hate&thorn;. [537] ffor certes &thorn;e hert of man. by eschawfynge and moovinge of his blood waxe&thorn; so trouble &thorn;at he is out of all Iugement of resoun [538] &para; But &yogh;e shullen / vnderstonde &thorn;at Ire is in two maners &thorn;at oon of hem is good and &thorn;at o&thorn;er is wikked [539] The good is by Ialousie of goodnesse &thorn;orgh &thorn;e which a man is wro&thorn;e wi&thorn; wikkednesse . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> And &thorn;er|for seith &thorn;e wise man &thorn;at Ire is bette &thorn;an play [540]<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; sapiens ./</NOTE> This Ire is with debonairete and it is wroo&thorn; wi&thorn;|outen bitternesse not wro&thorn; a&yogh;einst &thorn;e man but wroo&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;e mysdede of &thorn;e man. As sei&thorn; &thorn;e prophete david <B>Irascimini &amp; nolite peccare</B> [541] &para; Now vnderstonde &thorn;at wikked Ire is in two maners &thorn;at is to seyn sodeyn Ire or hastif Ire wi&thorn;-outen avisement and consentynge of his reson [542] &thorn;e menyng and &thorn;e sens of &thorn;is is &thorn;at &thorn;e reson of a man ne con|sent not to &thorn;ilk sodeyn Ire and &thorn;an is it venial [543] Ano&thorn;er Ire is ful wikked &thorn;at comme&thorn; of vilany of herte avised and cast bifore wi&thorn; wikked will to do vengeaunce and &thorn;erto his reson consente&thorn;. and so so&thorn;ly &thorn;is is dedly synne [544] &para; This Ire is so dis|plesaunt to god &thorn;at it trouble&thorn; his hous and chase&thorn; &thorn;e holy goost out of manne saule . . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [545] and putte in hym &thorn;e lik|nes of &thorn;e deuell and bynymme&thorn; &thorn;e man fro god &thorn;at is his ri&yogh;tfull lorde [546] This Ire is a ful grete plesaunce to &thorn;e deuell. for it is &thorn;e deuels fornays &thorn;at is eschauffed wi&thorn; &thorn;e fuyre of helle. [547] ffor certes 
<PB REF="00000683.tif" N="649"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="633"> as fuyre is more my&yogh;ty to distroye er&thorn;ly &thorn;ingges &thorn;an another element Ri&yogh;t so Ire is my&yogh;ty to destroye all spirituel &thorn;ingges. [548] Loke howe &thorn;at fire of smale gledys that bene almost dede vnder asshen wollen quyk<MILESTONE N="287b" UNIT="folio">ke a&yogh;ein whan &thorn;ei bene touched wi&thorn; bremstone Ri&yogh;t soo Ire wil euermore quikke a-&yogh;ein whan it is touched by pride &thorn;at is kered in mannys hert. [549] ffor certes fire may not come out of no &thorn;inge but if it were first in &thorn;e same &thorn;ing naturelly as fire is drawen out of &thorn;e flyntes wi&thorn; steele [550] And ri&yogh;t so as pride is often matere of Ire Right so is rancoure norssher and keper of &thorn;e [551] Ther is a maner of tree as sei&thorn; seint Isodere &thorn;at whan men<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Isodre</NOTE> maken fire of &thorn;ilk tree and keuere&thorn; &thorn;e cooles of it with asshen so&thorn;ly &thorn;e fuyre of it wil last last al a &yogh;ere or more [552] &para; And ri&yogh;t so fare&thorn; it of rancour whan he is onys conceyued in &thorn;e hertis of somme men. Certeyne it wil last perauenture from oon / Ester day til ano&thorn;er day or more [553] But Certes &thorn;ilk man is ful ferre from &thorn;e mercy of god al &thorn;ilk while</P>
<P>[554] &para; In &thorn;is forsaide deuels fornays &thorn;er foorgen. thre shrewes Pride &thorn;at all blowe&thorn; and encrese&thorn;e &thorn;e fire by pride and wikked wordes. [555] Than stant Envie and holde&thorn; &thorn;e hote yren vppon &thorn;e hertes of man wi&thorn; a peire of longe tongges of longe Rancour [556] and &thorn;an stant &thorn;e synne of contynnynge or strif and &thorn;eest and batere&thorn; and forge&thorn; by vileyns reprouyngges [557] &para; Certes &thorn;is cursed synne annoye&thorn; bo&thorn;e &thorn;e man hym self and eke to his neighbour. ffor so&thorn;ly al &para; most al &thorn;e harme &thorn;at eny man do&thorn;e to his neighboure comme&thorn; of wrath. [558] ffor certes outrageous wra&thorn;e do&thorn; all &thorn;at euer the deuel hym comaunde&thorn; for he ne spare&thorn; nei&thorn;er crist ne his swete modere [559] And in his out|rageous angre &amp; Ire allas allas ful mony one at &thorn;at tyme fele&thorn; in his / herte ful wikkedly 
<PB REF="00000684.tif" N="650"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="634"> bo&thorn; of crist and of all his halowes. [560] Is not &thorn;is a cursed vice . . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> his debonaire wif espirituell &thorn;at shulde kepen his saule [561] Certes it bygynne&thorn; eke goddys dieu lordship and &thorn;at is mannys saule and &thorn;e loue of his neigbours It strive&thorn; eke alday a&yogh;einst &thorn;e trou&thorn;e. It reue&thorn; hym &thorn;e quiete of his hert and subuerte&thorn; his saule</P>
<P>[562]</P>
<P>&para; Of Ire commen &thorn;ise stynkinge engendrures. ffirst hate &thorn;at is olde wre&thorn;e discord &thorn;orgh which a man forsake&thorn; his olde frende &thorn;at he ha&thorn; loued ful longe. [563] and &thorn;an comme&thorn; werre and euery manere of wronge &thorn;at man doth to his neighbour in body or in catell [564] &para; Of &thorn;is cursed. <MILESTONE N="288a" UNIT="folio">synne of Ire comme&thorn; eke mannys sclaughtere And vnderstonde&thorn; wel &thorn;at homycide &thorn;at is mannys sclau&yogh;tere is in dyuers wise Some manere of Omycide is espirituel and somme is bodely. [565] Spirituel mannesslaughter is in vj. &thorn;ingges ffirst by hate as sei&thorn; seint Iohn. That he &thorn;at hate&thorn; his bro&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Iohannes.</NOTE> is an homicide. [566] [Homicide] Is eke by bakbytinge. of whiche bakbiters sei&thorn; salomon. &thorn;at &thorn;ei han. twoo<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Salomon</NOTE> swerdes with which &thorn;ei scleen her neighbours. ffor so&thorn;ly as wikked is to bynyme his good name as his liff [567] &para; Omycide is eke in &yogh;euynge of wikked counsaile by fraude as forto &yogh;eue / counsaile to array wikkedly custumes and taliages [568] Of which sei&thorn; Salomon &para; lyoun rorynge. bere hungry bene like to<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Idem</NOTE> cruel lordshippes in wi&thorn;holding or a-breggynge of &thorn;e Shepe or &thorn;e hire of &thorn;e wages of . . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> &thorn;e almesse of poor folk [569] ffor which &thorn;e wise man sei&thorn; ffede&thorn; hym &thorn;at almost die&thorn; for hunger. for so&thorn;ly but &thorn;ou fede hym &thorn;ou scleest hym. and alle &thorn;ise bene dedly synnes [570] Bodyly mansclaunter is whan &thorn;ou scleest hym wi&thorn; &thorn;i tunge in o&thorn;ere manere as whan &thorn;ou comaundest to sclene a man or ellis &yogh;euest hym counsaile to scleen a 
<PB REF="00000685.tif" N="651"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="635"> man. [571] Mansclaughtere in dede is in foure maners That oon is by lawe Ri&yogh;t as a Iustice dampne&thorn; hym &thorn;at is copable to &thorn;e dee&thorn; But lat &thorn;e Iustise be ware &thorn;at he do it ri&yogh;tfully. and &thorn;at he do it not for delit to spille bloode. but for ri&yogh;twis|nesse. [572] Ano&thorn;ere homycide is doon for necessite as whan a man sclee&thorn; ano&thorn;er in his defendaunt and &thorn;at he may noon o&thorn;er wise eskape for his owne de&thorn;e. [573] But certeynly if he may eskape wi&thorn;|out sclaughter of his aduersary and scle&thorn;e hym he do&thorn; synne and he shal bere penaunce as for dedly synne [574] &para; Eke if a man by caas or auenture shete an arowe or cast a stone wi&thorn; whiche he sclee&thorn; a man it is homycide [575] &para; Eke if a womman by necligence ouerlei&thorn; her childe in sclepinge it is homycide. and dedly synne. [576] Eke whan a man distourbe&thorn; con|cepcion of a childe or make&thorn; a womman barayn by drynkinge of venemous herbes &thorn;orgh which she may not conceyue or sclee&thorn; a childe by drynkes or ellis putte&thorn; in certeyn material &thorn;ingges in her secre places to sle &thorn;e child [577] or ellis do&thorn; vnkinde synne by which man or wom<MILESTONE N="288b" UNIT="folio">man shede&thorn; his nature in manere or in place &thorn;er as a childe may not be con|ceyued or ellis if a womman ha&thorn; conceyued and hurte he[r] self and sclee&thorn; her childe &yogh;it is it homycide [578] &para; What say we eke of wommen &thorn;at Mordren her children for drede or worldly shame certes an horrible homicide [579] Homicyde is eke if a mon ap|proche&thorn; to a womman by desire of leccherie &thorn;orghe which &thorn;e childe is pershed or ellis smyte&thorn; a womman witingly &thorn;orgh which she lese&thorn; her childe all &thorn;ise bene homy|cides and horrible dedly synnes / [580] &yogh;it comme&thorn; &thorn;erof Ire and mony moo synnes as wel in worde as in &thorn;ou&yogh;t and in dede as he &thorn;at arette&thorn; vpon god or blame&thorn; god of &thorn;inge of which he is hym self gilty or dispise&thorn; god and all his halowes as done &thorn;ise cursed hasardours 
<PB REF="00000686.tif" N="652"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="636"> in dyuers cuntrees. [581] &thorn;is cursed synne doon &thorn;ei whan &thorn;ei felen in her hert ful wikkedly of god and his halowes [582] &para; Also whan &thorn;ei treten vnreuerently &thorn;e sacrament of &thorn;e autere Thilk synnes is so grete &thorn;at vnne&thorn;es may it be relesed but &thorn;at mercy of god passe&thorn; his werkes it is so grete and he so benigne. [583] Than comme&thorn; of Ire attry Angre whan a man [is] sharpely amonased. in his shrift to for|lete synne [584] &thorn;an wil he be angry and answere hokerly and angerly or defende and excuse his synne by vnstedfastnesshe of his flessh or ellis he did it forto holde company with wise felawes. or ellis he sei&thorn; &thorn;e fende entised / hym [585] or ellis he did it for his &yogh;ou&thorn;e. or ellis complexion is so corragious that he may not forbere. or ellis it is his destanye as he sei&thorn; vnto a certeyn age. or ellis he sei&thorn; hit comme&thorn; hym of gentilnesse of his owncestres and semblable &thorn;ingges [586] &para; Alle &thorn;ise manere folkes so wrappen hem in her synnes &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne wol not delyuere hem self. So&thorn;ly no wi&yogh;t &thorn;at excusel hym wilfully of his / synne may not be delyuered of her synne til &thorn;at he mekely byknowe&thorn; his synne [587] &para; Aftere &thorn;at comme&thorn; sweringe &thorn;at is expresse a&yogh;einst &thorn;e comaundement of god. and &thorn;is bifalle&thorn; oft of anger and of Ire [588] God sei&thorn; &thorn;ou shalt not<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Textus</NOTE> take &thorn;e name of &thorn;i lorde god in veyn nor in ydell &para; Also our lorde Ihesu crist sei&thorn; by &thorn;e word of seynt Mathewe<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Matheus</NOTE> . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [589] Ne wil &yogh;e not swere in al manere. Nei&thorn;er by heuene for it is goddes trone. ne by &thorn;e er&thorn;e for it is &thorn;e benche of his fete <MILESTONE N="289a" UNIT="folio">ne by Ierusalem for it is &thorn;e cite of a grete kynge Ne by &thorn;ine hede. for &thorn;ou maist not make an heer white ne blak [590] But sei&thorn; by &yogh;our &yogh;ee &yogh;ee. and nay nay and what &thorn;at is more it is euell &thorn;us seith crist [591] &para; ffor cristes sake ne swere&thorn; not so synfully in dismembringe of crist by soule 
<PB REF="00000687.tif" N="653"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="637"> herte bonys and body for certes it seme&thorn; &thorn;at &yogh;e &thorn;enk &thorn;at &thorn;e cursed Iwes ne dismenbred / hym nou&yogh;t ynou&yogh;e &thorn;e precious persone of crist But &yogh;e dismembren hym more [592] And if so be &thorn;at &thorn;e lawe com|pelle &yogh;ou to / swere &thorn;an rewle&thorn; &yogh;ou after &thorn;e lawe of god in &yogh;oure sweryng as sei&thorn; Ieremye 4<SUP>to</SUP>. capitulo. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> Thou<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ieremie quarto capitulo</NOTE> shalt kepe thre condicions. Thou shalt swere in trou&thorn;e in doom and in ri&yogh;twisnesse [593] This is to sayn<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Iurabis in veritate in iudicio et iustitia [<I>same side-note and quotation in the Sompnour's Tale. MS. leaf 219, back</I>]</NOTE> &thorn;ou shalt swere soo&thorn;. for euery lesinge is a&yogh;einst crist ffor crist is verrey trou&thorn;e And &thorn;enk wel &thorn;is &thorn;at euery grete swerer not compelled lawfully to swere &thorn;e wounde shal not departe fro his hous &thorn;e whiles he vseth such vnlieful sweringe [594] &para; Thow shalt swere eke in doom whan &thorn;ow arte constrayned by &thorn;i domes man to witnesse &thorn;e trou&thorn;e [595] &para; Eke &thorn;ou shalt not swere for envie ne for fauour ne for mede but for ri&yogh;twisnesse for declarynge to worship of god and in helping of &thorn;ine euen|cristen [596] And &thorn;erfore euery man &thorn;at take&thorn; goddis name in ydel or falsely swere&thorn; wi&thorn; his mou&thorn; or ellis take&thorn; on hym &thorn;e name of crist to be called a cristen man and lyue&thorn; a&yogh;einst cristes lyuyyng and his techinge alle &thorn;ei taken goddes name in ydell [597] &para; Loke eke what sei&thorn; seint Petere<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Petrus:/</NOTE> Actus 4<SUP>o</SUP>. Non est aliud nomen sub c&oelig;lo. Ther nys non o&thorn;er name sei&thorn; seint Peter vnder heuene y&yogh;euen to men in which &thorn;ei mote be saued &thorn;at is to seyn but in &thorn;e name of Ihesu crist [598] &para; Take kepe eke how &thorn;at &thorn;e precious name of Ihesu crist as sei&thorn; seynt paule Ad philipenses 2<SUP>o</SUP> In nomine Ihesu &amp;cetera. That in &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ad philipenses</NOTE> name of Ihesu euery knee of heuenly creatures or er&thorn;ly or of helle shuld bowen for it is so hi&yogh;e and so worshipfull that &thorn;e cursed fende in helle shuld tremblee to heren it nempned [599] than seme&thorn; it &thorn;at men &thorn;at sweren / so horribly by his 
<PB REF="00000688.tif" N="654"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="638"> blessed name &thorn;at &thorn;ei dispisen it more boldely &thorn;an did &thorn;e cursed Iwes. or ellis &thorn;e deuel &thorn;at tremble&thorn; whan he here&thorn; his name</P>
<P>[600] &para; Now certes si&thorn;ens &thorn;at swerynge but it be doo al lawfully is holy defended me The wors is forswering falsly. and &yogh;it nedelees.</P>
<P>[601] What say <MILESTONE N="289b" UNIT="folio">we eke of hem &thorn;at deliten hem in swerynge and holden it a gentrye or a manly dede to swere grete o&thorn;es And what of hem &thorn;at of verrey vsage ne cessen not to swere grete o&thorn;es al &thorn;e cause not wor&thorn; oon strawe Certes &thorn;is is horrible synne [602] swering sodeynly wi&thorn;-out avisement is eke a synne [603] &para; But lat vs nowe goo to &thorn;ilk horrible and cursed/ swerynge of adiuracion and coniuracion as don &thorn;ise fals en|chauntours or nigromanciens in basyns ful of water or in a bri&yogh;t swerde. in a sercle or in a fuyre or in a shulder bone of a shepe [604] I can not seyn but &thorn;at &thorn;ei doon cursedly and &para; dampnably a&yogh;einst crist and al &thorn;e fei&thorn; of holy church.</P>
<P>[605] What say we of hem &thorn;at byleuen on dyuynales as by fli&yogh;t or by noys of briddes or of beestes or of sorte by Egrimauncye. by dremes. by chirking of doores by gnewyng of rattye or crakinge of howses and such maner wrecchednesse [606] Certes al &thorn;is thynge is defended by god and by holy churche for // which &thorn;ei bene acursed to &thorn;ei come to amendement &thorn;at on such fil&thorn;e setten her byleue [607] &para; Charmes for woundes and maladies of men or of beestes if &thorn;ei taken eny effecte it bene perauenture &thorn;at god suffre&thorn; it for folk shuld &yogh;eue &thorn;e more fai&thorn;e and reuerence to his name</P>
<P>[608] &para; Now wil I speke of lesyngges which gener|ally is fals signyfiaunt or woord in entent to deceyuen his euen cristen [609] &para; Some lesing is of which &thorn;er comme&thorn; noon auauntage to no wi&yogh;t and somme lesyng turne&thorn; to &thorn;e ease ei&thorn;er profit of a man and to 
<PB REF="00000689.tif" N="655"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="639"> damage of a no&thorn;er man [610] A no&thorn;ere lesing is for to saue his liff or his catell. Ano&thorn;er lesynge comme&thorn; of delit forto lye In which delite &thorn;ei willen / forge a longe tale and peynte it wi&thorn; all circumstannces. wher alle &thorn;e grounde of &thorn;e tale is fals [611] &para; Some lesynge comme&thorn; for he wil sustene his word and some lesing commeth of recchelessnesse with-outen avisement and Sem|blable &thorn;ingges</P>
<P>[612] &para; Lat vs nowe touche &thorn;e vice of fflaterie which ne comme&thorn; not gladly but for drede or for coueityse. [613] fflatery is generally wrongfull presinge. fflater|ers bene &thorn;e deuel norrces &thorn;at norshe&thorn; his chylldren wi&thorn; mylk of losengry. [614] ffor so&thorn; sei&thorn; Salomon;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Salomon.</NOTE> &thorn;at flaterie is wors &thorn;an detracci&omacr;n. ffor. somtyme de|traccion make&thorn; an haunteyn man be &thorn;e more humble. ffor he drede&thorn; detraccion But certes fflaterye make&thorn; a man to vn<MILESTONE N="290a" UNIT="folio">haunten his hert and his countenaunce [615] &para; fflaterers bene &thorn;e deuels Enchaunters for &thorn;ei make a man to wene of hym self be like &thorn;at he nys not like [616] Thei bene like Iudas &thorn;at bytraied . . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> a man to selle hym to his enemye &thorn;at is to &thorn;e deuell [617] &para; fflaterers bene &thorn;e deuels Chapileyns &thorn;at synggen euer Placebo [618] I rekken flaterye in &thorn;e vices of Ire. ffor oft tyme if a man be wroo&thorn; wi&thorn; a-no&thorn;ere &thorn;an wil he flater some wi&yogh;t to susteyne hym in his querell</P>
<P>[619] Speke we now of such cursyng as comme&thorn; out of yrous herte &para; Malisoun may be seide generally Euery maner power of harme such cursyng byreue&thorn; man fro &thorn;e regne of god. as sei&thorn; seynt paule [620] And oft<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Paulus./</NOTE> tyme such cursing wrongfully retourneth a&yogh;ein to hym &thorn;at curse&thorn; as a brid retourne&thorn; a&yogh;ein to his owne nest [621] And ouer al &thorn;ing men ou&yogh;t eschewe to curse her children and &yogh;eue to &thorn;e deuell her engendrure as ferfor&thorn; as in hem is &para; Certes it is a grete perile and grete synne.
<PB REF="00000690.tif" N="656"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="640"></P>
<P>[622] Lat vs &thorn;an speke of chidynge and reproche which bene grete woundes in mannys hert ffor &thorn;ei vnsewen &thorn;e semes of ffrendship in mannys hert. [623] ffor certes vnne&thorn;es may a man pleynly ben accorded wi&thorn; hym &thorn;at ha&thorn; hym openly revyled and reproued and disclaundred &thorn;is is a ful grisly synne &para; And crist sei&thorn; in &thorn;e gospell [624] &para; And take kepe nowe<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Textus./</NOTE> &thorn;at he &thorn;at reproue&thorn; his neighbour ei&thorn;ere he reproue&thorn; hym by som harme of peyne &thorn;at he ha&thorn; on his body. as mesell croked harlot or by some synne &thorn;at he do&thorn; [625] &para; Now if he reproue hym by harme of peyn &thorn;an turne&thorn; &thorn;e prophete to Ihesu Crist. ffor peyne is sent by &thorn;e ri&yogh;twis sonde of god and by his suffraunce be it meselrye or maym or maladie [626] and if he reproue hym vncharitably of synne as &thorn;ou hullour &thorn;ou dronklewe harlot and so for&thorn; &thorn;at appertene&thorn; &thorn;at to &thorn;e roioysyng of &thorn;e deuell &thorn;at euer ha&thorn; ioye &thorn;at men don synne [627] &para; And certes chyding may not come but of vileyns hertes. ffor after &thorn;e habundaunce of &thorn;e hert speke&thorn; &thorn;e mou&thorn; ful oft [628] And &yogh;e shullen vnderstonde &thorn;at loke by eny way whan eny man shal chastise a no&thorn;er &thorn;at he be ware fro chydyng or reprouynge ffor trewly but he be ware he may ful li&yogh;tly quykken &thorn;e fyre of angre and of wretth which &thorn;at he shuld quenche. and perauenture sclee&thorn; <MILESTONE N="290b" UNIT="folio">him &thorn;at he my&yogh;t chastise wi&thorn; benyg|nyte [629] &para; ffor as sei&thorn; Salomon &para; The amyable tunge is<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Salomon./</NOTE> &thorn;e tree of lif &thorn;at is to saye of lif spirituel. and a disselaue tunge sclee&thorn; &thorn;e spirit of hym &thorn;at reproue&thorn; and eke of hym &thorn;at is reproued [630] &para; Loo what sai&thorn; seint Austyn &para; Ther nys no &thorn;inge ylike &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Augustinus./</NOTE> deuels child as he &thorn;at oft chide&thorn; &para; Seynt Poule sei&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Paulus./</NOTE> eke &para; I &thorn;e Seruaunte of god by-houe&thorn; not to chide. [631] and howe &thorn;at chydyng is a vileyns &thorn;inge bytwix al manere folk. &yogh;it is it certes most vnconnable by-twix a man and his wiff. for &thorn;er nys neuer rest 
<PB REF="00000691.tif" N="657"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="641"> &para; And &thorn;erfor sei&thorn; Salomon &para; An hous &thorn;at is vnkeuered<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Salomon.</NOTE> in reyn and dropping and a chidyng wiff bene ylike [632] a man &thorn;at is in a dropping hous in mony places. they hee eschewe &thorn;e dropping in oon place it droppe&thorn; on hym in a no&thorn;er place &para; So fare&thorn; it be a chiding wiff. but she chide hym in oo place she wol chide hym in ano&thorn;er [633] And &thorn;erfore better is<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Idem.</NOTE> a morsel of brede with Ioye &thorn;an an hous ful of delices wi&thorn; chidynge sei&thorn; Salomon [634] &para; And poule sei&thorn; O &yogh;e wommen be &yogh;e subiectys to &yogh;oure<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Paulus./</NOTE> husbondes as byhoue&thorn; in god. And &yogh;e men loue&thorn; &yogh;oure wyves. Ad colonisenses .3<SUP>o</SUP>.</P>
<P>[635] &para; Afterward speke we of scornynge which is a wikked synne And namely whan he scorne&thorn; a man for his good werkes. [636] for certes suche scorners faren like &thorn;e foule tode &thorn;at may not endure to smell &thorn;e swete sauour of &thorn;e vyne what it florsshe&thorn; [637] &para; Thise scorners bene partyng felawes wi&thorn; &thorn;e deuell. for &thorn;ei han Ioie whan &thorn;e deuel wynne&thorn; and sorowe whan he lese&thorn; [638] &para; They bene aduersaries to Ihesu crist for &thorn;ei haten &thorn;at he loue&thorn; &thorn;at is to say sauacion of saule</P>
<P>[639] &para; Speke we nowe of wikked counsaille. ffor he &thorn;at wikked counsaille &yogh;eueth is a traitour. ffor he disceyue&thorn; hym &thorn;at truste&thorn; in hym Vt Achitofel de Absolonem &para; But na&thorn;elees &yogh;it is it wikked counsaile ffirst a&yogh;einst hym self [640] for as sei&thorn; &thorn;e wise man Euery fals lyuyng ha&thorn; his propre in hym self &thorn;at he &thorn;at will anoy ano&thorn;er man he annoye&thorn; furst hym self. [641] And men shullen vnderstonde &thorn;at man shal not take his counsaille of fals folk ne of to angry folk or greuous folk ne of folk &thorn;at louen specialy to moche her owne profite ne to moch worldly folk namely in counsailling of saules</P>
<P>[642] &para; Now comme&thorn; &thorn;e synne of hem &thorn;at maken discorde amonges / folk which is a synne &thorn;at 
<PB REF="00000692.tif" N="658"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="642"> crist hate&thorn; vtterly and no wonder is. ffor he deyed forto make concorde. [643] And more shame done &thorn;ei to crist <MILESTONE N="291a" UNIT="folio">&thorn;an did &thorn;ei &thorn;at hym crucified ffor god loue&thorn; better &thorn;at frendship be amonges folk &thorn;an he did his owne body &thorn;e which he &yogh;af for vnitees. therfore bene &thorn;ei likned to &thorn;e deuel &thorn;at euer is about to make discord</P>
<P>[644] &para; Now comme&thorn; &thorn;e synne of double tunge. such as speken faire to-fore folk and wikkedly behynde or ellis &thorn;ei / maken semblaunt as &thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;ei speken of good entencion or ellis in game and pley and &yogh;it &thorn;ei speke of wikked entent</P>
<P>[645] &para; Now comme&thorn; bywreying of counsaille &thorn;orgh which a man is defamed vnne&thorn;es may he restore &thorn;e damage</P>
<P>[646] &para; Now comme&thorn; manace &thorn;at is an open foly ffor he &thorn;at open manase&thorn; he trete&thorn; more &thorn;an he may performe ful often tyme</P>
<P>[647] &para; Now comme&thorn; ydel wordes &thorn;at is wi&thorn;-outen profite of hym &thorn;at speke&thorn; &thorn;e wordes. and eke of hym &thorn;at harkene&thorn; &thorn;oo wordes // or ellis ydel wordes. ben / &thorn;oo &thorn;at bene nedelees or wi&thorn;-outen entent of naturel profite. [648] and al be it &thorn;at ydel wordes be som|tyme venial synne &yogh;it shuld men doute hem. for we shullen &yogh;eue rekenyng of hem to-fore god</P>
<P>[649] &para; Now comme&thorn; Iangelynge &thorn;at may not come wi&thorn;|oute synne. And as sei&thorn; Salomon &para; It is signe of a-pert<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Salomon</NOTE> foly [650] and &thorn;erfor a philisophre seide whan a man asked hym how men shulde plese &thorn;e puple. And he answerd to mony good werkes and speke fewe Iangelynggs</P>
<P>[651] &para; After &thorn;is comme&thorn; &thorn;e synne of Iapes. &thorn;at bene deuels apes. for &thorn;ei maken folk to lau&yogh;e at her Iaprie as folkes doon at &thorn;e gaudes of an ape. Suche Iapes defende&thorn; seint Poule [652] &para; Loke how &thorn;at vertuous wordes and hooly conforten hem 
<PB REF="00000693.tif" N="659"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="643"> &thorn;at travaillen in &thorn;e seruise of criste Ri&yogh;t so conforten &thorn;e vileyns words and knakkes of Iapers hem &thorn;at trauaillen in &thorn;e servise of &thorn;e deuell [653] &para; Thise bene &thorn;e synnes / &thorn;at commen of &thorn;e tunge &thorn;at commen of Ire and of other synnes</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Remedies against Ire.]</HEAD>
<P>[654] &para; The remedye a&yogh;einst Ire is a vertue &thorn;at men clepen mansuetude &thorn;at is debonairete and eke a nother vertue &thorn;at men clepe pacience . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></P>
<P>[655] &para; Debonairte wi&thorn;drowe&thorn; and refreyne&thorn; &thorn;e styryngges and &thorn;e meuyngs of mannys corage in his hert and such manere &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne skippe not out by anger ne by Ire [656] suffraunce suffre&thorn; swetly al &thorn;e annoyaunces and &thorn;e wrongges &thorn;at men doon to a man outward [657] &para; Seint Ierom sei&thorn; &thorn;us of debonairte<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ieronimus</NOTE> &thorn;at hit doo&thorn; noon harme to no wi&yogh;t ne sei&thorn; for noon harme &thorn;at men hym done ne sayn He ne eschaunge&thorn; nou&yogh;t a&yogh;einst his reson. [658] This vertue som / <MILESTONE N="291b" UNIT="folio">somtyme comme&thorn; of nature &para; ffor as sei&thorn; &thorn;e philisophre. A man is a quyk &thorn;inge by nature . debonaire and treteable by goodnes But whan debonairte is enfourmed by grace. it is &thorn;e more wor&thorn;</P>
<P>[659] &para; Pacience &thorn;at is ano&thorn;er remedye a&yogh;einst Ire is a vertue &thorn;at suffre&thorn; swetely euery mannys goodnesse and is not wor&thorn; for non harme &thorn;at is doon to hym [660] &para; The philisofre sei&thorn; &thorn;at pacience is &thorn;ilk vertue &thorn;at suffre&thorn; debonairly all &thorn;e outrages of aduersite and euery wikked worde. [661] This vertue make&thorn; a man like to god. and make&thorn; hym his owne dere childe as sei&thorn; crist. This vertu discomfite&thorn; &thorn;ine enemye And &thorn;erfore sei&thorn; &thorn;e wise man If &thorn;ou wilt venquyssh &thorn;ine / ennemye. lerne to suffre [662] And &thorn;ou shalt vnderstonde &thorn;at a / man suffreth four maner 
<PB REF="00000694.tif" N="660"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="644"> of greuaunce in outward &thorn;ingges. a&yogh;einst which foure he mote haue iiij. maners of paciences./</P>
<P>[663] &para; The furst greuaunce is of wikked wordes. &thorn;ilk greuaunce suffre&thorn; Ihesu crist wi&thorn;-outen grucchinge ful paciently whan &thorn;e Iwes despised hym and reproueden hym ful oft [664] Suffre &thorn;ou &thorn;erfore paciently. ffor &thorn;e wise man eke sei&thorn; &para; If &thorn;ou stryue wi&thorn; a fool &thorn;oughe<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Sapiens</NOTE> &thorn;e fool be wro&thorn;. or &thorn;ou&yogh;e he lau&yogh;e algate &thorn;ou shalt haue no rest. [665] That o&thorn;er greuaunce outward is forto haue damage of &thorn;i catell &para; Ther a&yogh;einst suffred crist ful paciently whan he was dispoilled of al &thorn;at he had in this liff and &thorn;at nas but his clo&thorn;es [666] &para; The iij. greuaunce is a man to haue harme in his bodye. and &thorn;at suffred crist ful paciently in all his passion [667] &para; The iiij. greuaunce is in an outrageous labour in werkes. wherfore I say &thorn;at folk &thorn;at maken her seruauntes to travaille to greuously or out of tyme as in holy days. so&thorn;ly &thorn;ei doon grete synne. [668] Here a&yogh;einst suffred crist ful paciently and taught vs patience whan he bare vpon / his blessed shulder &thorn;e crois vpon which he shuld suffre dispitous dee&thorn;. [669] Here may men lerne to be pacient. ffor so&thorn;ly not oonly cristen men bene pacient for &thorn;e loue of Ihesu crist and for guerdon of &thorn;e blisse of heuene and of &thorn;e blisful liff &thorn;at is perdurable But certes &thorn;e olde paynyms &thorn;at neuere were cristen com|menden &amp; vseden &thorn;e vertue of pacience</P>
<P>[670] A philisophre vpon a tyme &thorn;at wolld haue<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Philosophus</NOTE> beten his disciple for his grete trespace. for which he was gretly ameued and brou&yogh;t a &yogh;eerd to scoure &thorn;e <MILESTONE N="292a" UNIT="folio">childe [671] and whan &thorn;e childe segh &thorn;e &yogh;eerde he seide to his maister what wil &yogh;e doo. I wil bete &thorn;e quod his maistere. for &thorn;ine correctioun. [672] ffor so&thorn; quod &thorn;e childe &yogh;e ou&yogh;t first correcte &yogh;oure self &thorn;at ha&thorn; lost &yogh;oure pacience for &thorn;e gilt of a childe. [673] ffor so&thorn; quod &thorn;e maister al wepinge &thorn;u 
<PB REF="00000695.tif" N="661"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="645"> saiest &thorn;e soo&thorn;. Haue &thorn;ou &thorn;e &yogh;erde my dere sone and correcte me for myn Inpacience [674] &para; Of pacience commeth obedience &thorn;orgh which a man is obedien to crist and into alle hem to which he ou&yogh;t be obedient in crist [675] and vnderstonde wel &thorn;at obedience is parfite whan men doon gladly and hastely wi&thorn; good hert entierly al &thorn;at he shuld do. [676] Obedience / generally is to perfourme &thorn;e doctrine of god and of his souereins to whiche hym ou&yogh;te to bene obeysaunt in al ri&yogh;twisnesse</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; <B>De</B> peccato accidie [<I>from margin</I>]</HEAD>
<P>[677]</P>
<P>Aftere &thorn;e synnes of Envie I wil speke of &thorn;e synne of Accidie. ffor Envie blynde&thorn; &thorn;e hert of a man. And Ire troubleth a man. and accidy make&thorn; hym hevye &thorn;ou&yogh;tful and wrowe [678] &para; Envie and Ire maken bitternesse in hert which bitternesse is / modere of accide and bynyme&thorn; hym &thorn;e loue of al goodnes &thorn;at is accyde &thorn;e angwissh of a trouble hert and seynt Austyne sei&thorn; it is anoye of goodnesse and anoy of harme. [679] / Certes &thorn;is is a dampnable synne for it doo&thorn; wronge to Ihesu crist in as moch as he nyme&thorn; &thorn;e seruice &thorn;at men ou&yogh;t to doo Ihesu crist wi&thorn; al diligence as sei&thorn; salomon /<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Salomon./</NOTE> [680] But accide doo&thorn; noon suche diligence He do&thorn; al &thorn;ing wi&thorn; anoy and wrawnesse sclaknesse and escusaci&omacr;n and wi&thorn; dulnesse and vnlust &para; ffor which &thorn;e booke sei&thorn;. Accursed be he &thorn;at do&thorn; &thorn;e seruise of god negligently [681] Than is accidy enmye to euery estate of man for certes &thorn;e estate of man is in &thorn;re maners. [682] ei&thorn;er It is &thorn;e estate of Innocence as was &thorn;e estate of Adam byforn &thorn;at he felle in to synne in which estate he was halden to wirche as in heryng and in adourynge of god [683] &para; Ano&thorn;er estate is &thorn;e estate of synful men in which estate men ben halden 
<PB REF="00000696.tif" N="662"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="646"> to labour in preying to god for amendement of her . . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> synnes [684] &para; Ano&thorn;er estate is &thorn;e estate of grace in which estate he is halden to do werkes of penitence and certes to all &thorn;ise &thorn;ingges is accidye / enemye and con|trary for he loue&thorn; no bysynes at all [685] &para; Now certes &thorn;is foule synne accidye is eke a ful gret enemye to &thorn;e liflode of &thorn;e body for it ha&thorn; no purvyaunce <MILESTONE N="292b" UNIT="folio">a&yogh;einst temporel necessite ffor it is for|slew&thorn;e and for-sclugge&thorn; and distroie&thorn; al good temporels by rechelesnesse</P>
<P>[686] The iiij. &thorn;inge is &thorn;at accidie is like hem &thorn;at bene in &thorn;e peyne of helle by cause of her sclou&thorn;e and of her heuynesse. for &thorn;ei &thorn;at bene dampned bene so bounde &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne may wel do ne wel &thorn;enk. [687] Of accidy comme&thorn; first &thorn;at a man is anoied and encombred to doon eny goodnesse and make&thorn; &thorn;at god ha&thorn; abhomynacion of such accidye as seith seynt Iohn<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; sanctus Iahannes./</NOTE></P>
<P>[688] &para; Now comme&thorn; scleuth &thorn;at wil not suffre noon hardnesse ne no penaunce ffor so&thorn; sclou&thorn;e is so tendere and so delicate as sei&thorn; Salomon &thorn;at he wil not<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Salomon</NOTE> suffre noon hardnesse ne penaunce and &thorn;erfore he sheende&thorn; all &thorn;at he doo&thorn; [689] a&yogh;einst his roten herted synne of accidie and sclou&thorn;e shulde men exercise by hem self to done good werkes and manly and vertuousli cacchen corage wel to done &thorn;enk|yng &thorn;at our lorde Ihesu crist quite&thorn; euery good dede be it neuere so lite./ [690] Vsage of labour is a grete &thorn;ing for it make&thorn; as sei&thorn; Seynt Bernard &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Bernardus</NOTE> laborers to haue stronge armes and harde Synewes and sclouthe make&thorn; hem feble and tendere [691] Than commeth drede forto bygynne to wirkes ffor certes he &thorn;at is enclyned / to synne hym &thorn;enke&thorn; it is so grete an emprise forto vndertake to do werkes of goodnesse [692] . . . . . 
<PB REF="00000697.tif" N="663"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="647"> . . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> as sei&thorn; Seint gregorie.</P>
<P>[693] &para; Now comme&thorn; wanhope &thorn;at is despeire of &thorn;e mercy of god &thorn;at comme&thorn; somtyme of to moch out|rageous sorowe and somtyme of moche drede ymagyn|ynge &thorn;at he ha&thorn; do so moch synne &thorn;at it wil not auaille hym &thorn;ou&yogh;e he wolde repent hym and forsake synne and doon good [694] &thorn;or&yogh;e which dispeire or drede he boundene&thorn; his hert to euery maner synne as sei&thorn; seint Austyne [695] &para; Which dampnable synne if &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Augustinus</NOTE> it contynue vnto his ende . it is cleped synnyng in &thorn;e holy goost [696] This orible synne is so perilous &thorn;at he &thorn;at is despeired &thorn;er nys no felonye ne no synne &thorn;at he doute&thorn; for to doo as shewed wel by Iudas [697] Certes &thorn;en abouen all synnes is &thorn;is synne most displesaunt to crist and most aduersarie to crist. [698] So&thorn;ly he &thorn;at dispeire&thorn; he is like &thorn;e coward champion recreaunt and sei&thorn; creaunt wi&thorn;outen nede Allas / alas / nedelees is he recreaunt <SUP>1</SUP>and sei&thorn; creaunt<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="marg">[<SUP>1_1</SUP> <I>repeated in MS.</I>]</NOTE> and nedeles / despeired [699] ffor certes &thorn;e mercy of god is euer redy to &thorn;e penytent. it is abouen all his werkis [700] &para; Allas can a man not<MILESTONE N="293a" UNIT="folio"> vmby&thorn;enke hym of &thorn;e gospel of Luke xv<SUP>o</SUP>. Where as crist sei&thorn; &thorn;at as wel shal<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Luc&aelig; xxv<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE> &thorn;er be ioye in heuene vpon a synful / man &thorn;at do&thorn; penytence &thorn;an vppon 90. 19.Ri&yogh;tful men &thorn;at . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> neden to penytence [701] &para; Loke for&thorn;er in &thorn;e gospell &thorn;e Ioye and / &thorn;e feestes of &thorn;e good man &thorn;at had lost his / sone. Whan his sone wi&thorn; repentaunce was retourned to his fadere. [702] Can / &thorn;ei not remembre hem eke &thorn;at as sei&thorn; seint luca xxiii<SUP>o</SUP>. Hou &thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;eef &thorn;at was honged<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Luce xxiij<SUP>o</SUP></NOTE> besides Ihesu cristes side &para; Lord remembre on me whan &thorn;ou commest into &thorn;i regne. [703] fforsoth seide crist to day shalt &thorn;ou be wi&thorn; me in paradys [704] Certes &thorn;er nys noon so horrible synne of 
<PB REF="00000698.tif" N="664"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="648"> man &thorn;at it ne may in his lif be destroied by penytence &thorn;orgh vertue of &thorn;e passioun and of &thorn;e dee&thorn; of crist [705] &para; Allas what nede&thorn; man &thorn;an to be despeired si&thorn;ens his mercy so redy is to aske and haue [706] &para; &thorn;an / comme&thorn; sompnolence &thorn;at is scluggy sclumbringe which make&thorn; a man be hevie and dulle in body and in saule and &thorn;is synne comme&thorn; of sclou&thorn;e [707] And certys &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at by way of reson men shuld not sclepe &thorn;at is by &thorn;e morowe but if &thorn;er were cause resonable [708] &para; ffor so&thorn;ly in &thorn;e morowe tyde is most conable a man to say his preiers and for|to &thorn;enken on god. and to honouren god and to &yogh;euen almesse to &thorn;e poor &thorn;at first commen in &thorn;e name of criste [709] &para; Lo what sei&thorn; Salomon. who so wil<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Salomon.</NOTE> by &thorn;e morowe awake to seke me. he shal fynde [710] &para; Than commeth necligence or rechelesnesse &thorn;at rekketh of no &thorn;inge and how &thorn;at ignoraunce is modere of al harme &para; Certes necligence is &thorn;e norice. [711] necligence ne do&thorn; no force whan he shal done eny &thorn;inge whedere he do it wel or badly</P>
<P>[712] &para; Of &thorn;e remedie of &thorn;ise two synnes as sei&thorn; &thorn;e wise / man &thorn;at he &thorn;at drede&thorn; god spare&thorn; not<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; sapiens</NOTE> to done &thorn;at hym ou&yogh;t to done [713] and he &thorn;at loue&thorn; god. he wil do diligence to plese. god by his werkes and abounden hym self wi&thorn; al his my&yogh;t wel forto doon. [714] &thorn;an comme&thorn; ydelnes &thorn;at is &thorn;e &yogh;ate of al harmes. An ydel man is like to a place &thorn;at ha&thorn; no walles &thorn;e deuell may entre on euery side or shete at hym at discouerte by temptacion on euery side [715] This ydelnesse is &thorn;e thurrok of al wikked and vyleyns &thorn;ou&yogh;tes. and of alle Iangelingges trowfuls and al ordure [716] &para; Certes &thorn;e heuene is y&yogh;eue to hem &thorn;at wil laboure. and nou&yogh;t to ydel folk &para; Eke dauid <MILESTONE N="293b" UNIT="folio">sei&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; dauid</NOTE> &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne be not in &thorn;e labour of men. ne &thorn;ei shul not be whipped wi&thorn; men &thorn;at is to say in purgatorie 
<PB REF="00000699.tif" N="665"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="649"> [717] &para; Certes &thorn;an seme&thorn; it. &thorn;ei shul be tormented wi&thorn; &thorn;e deuel in helle but if &thorn;ei done penitence</P>
<P>[718] &para; Than comme&thorn; &thorn;e synne &thorn;at men clepen tarditas as was a man is so lattred and so tarying er he wil turne to god. and certes &thorn;at is a grete foly. he / is like hym &thorn;at falle&thorn; in &thorn;e diche and wil not arise. [719] And / &thorn;is vice comme&thorn; of fals hope. &thorn;at he &thorn;enke&thorn; he shal lyue longe. but &thorn;at hope failleth ful oft</P>
<P>[720] Than commeth lacchesse &thorn;at is he &thorn;at whan he bygynne&thorn; eny good werk. anoon / he wil forlete it and stynt. as done &thorn;ei &thorn;at han eny wi&yogh;t to gouerne and ne taken of hym no more kepe anoon as &thorn;ei / fynden eny contrary or eny anoye [721] &para; Thise ben &thorn;e newe shipardes &thorn;at laten her shepe wetyngly go rennen to &thorn;e / wolf &thorn;at is in &thorn;e breres or doon no force of her owne gouernaunce [722] &para; Of &thorn;is comme&thorn; pouerte and distruction bo&thorn; of spirituel and of temporel &thorn;ingges. Than commeth a manere of coldnesse &thorn;at frese&thorn; all &thorn;e hert of a man [723] &para; Than commeth vndeuocion &thorn;orghe which a man is so blent. And as sei&thorn; seint Bernard ha&thorn; such langour in<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Bernardus</NOTE> soule &thorn;at he may nei&thorn;ere rede ne synge in holy church ne &thorn;enk on deuocion ne travaille wi&thorn; his hondes in no good werk &thorn;at it ne is / to hym vnsauery and al appalled [724] &thorn;an wexe&thorn; he sore and / sclowe and slumbry and sone wil be wroo&thorn; and sone is / enclyned to hate and to Envie [725] &para; Than comme&thorn; &thorn;e synne of worldly sorowe. which &thorn;at is cleped tristicia &thorn;at sclee&thorn; a<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Tristicia./</NOTE> man. as sei&thorn; seint Paule [726] ffor certes such sorowe wirke&thorn; to &thorn;e dee&thorn; of &thorn;e saule and of &thorn;e body &para; Also for &thorn;erof commeth &thorn;at a man is annoyed of his owne liff [727] Wherfore such sorowe shorte&thorn; ful often &thorn;e lyf // of a man er &thorn;at his tyme commen is by way of kinde
</P>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000700.tif" N="666"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="650">
<HEAD>[The Remedy against Accidie.]</HEAD>
<P>[728] &para; A&yogh;einst &thorn;is horrible Synne of Accide and &thorn;e braunches of &thorn;e same Ther is a vertue &thorn;at is called ffortitudo or strenght &thorn;at is an affeccion &thorn;orgh<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; ffortitudo ./</NOTE> which a man despise&thorn; al noyous &thorn;inge [729] &para; This vertue is so my&yogh;ty and so vigorous; &thorn;at it dar wi&thorn;stonde my&yogh;tely and wrastel a&yogh;einst &thorn;e Sawtes of &thorn;e deuell and wisly kepen hym self fro periles &thorn;at bene wikked [730] for it enchaunse&thorn; and enforse&thorn; &thorn;e soule <MILESTONE N="294a" UNIT="folio">ri&yogh;t as accidy abate&thorn; it and make&thorn; it feble. ffor &thorn;is fortitudo may endure by longe suffraunce &thorn;e travailes &thorn;at bene conable</P>
<P>[731] &para; This vertue ha&thorn; mony spyces &para; The furst is cleped magnanimitas. &thorn;at is to / saye grete corage. ffor so&thorn;ly &thorn;er byhoue&thorn; grete corage a&yogh;einst Accidye lest &thorn;at it swelowe &thorn;e soul by &thorn;e synne of sorowe. or destroy it by wanhope. [732] This vertu make&thorn; folk vndertake harde &thorn;ingges. and greuous &thorn;ingges by her owne wille wisely and resonably [733] And for as moch as the deuel fighte&thorn; a&yogh;einst man. more by queynteyse &amp; by scleight &thorn;an by strenghth &thorn;erfore a man shal withstonde hym by witte and by reson and by dis|crecion [734] &para; Then ben / &thorn;er &thorn;e vertues of fei&thorn; and hope in god and in his seyntes to atcheuen and accomplise &thorn;e good werkes in which he purpose&thorn; feermely to contynue [735] &para; Than comme&thorn; suerte or sikernesse and &thorn;at is whan a man ne doute&thorn; no travaile in tyme commynge of &thorn;e good werk &thorn;at a man / ha&thorn; bygonne [736] &para; Than comme&thorn; Magnificence. and &thorn;at is to sayn whan a man do&thorn; and perfourme&thorn; grete werkes of goodnesse &thorn;at he ha&thorn; bygonne. and &thorn;at is &thorn;e ende whi &thorn;at men shuld doo good werkes. ffor in &thorn;e accomplesing of good werkes lith &thorn;e grete guerdoun [737] &para; Than is &thorn;er constaunce &thorn;at is stablenesse of corage and &thorn;is shulde be in hert by stedfast fei&thorn; and in mou&thorn;e and in 
<PB REF="00000701.tif" N="667"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="651"> berynge and in chere and in dede [738] &para; Eke &thorn;er bene moo / special &thorn;ingges and remedies a&yogh;einst Accidie in dyuers werkes and in consideracions of &thorn;e pyne of helle and of &thorn;e Ioye of heuene and in &thorn;e trust of &thorn;e grace of &thorn;e holy goost &thorn;at wil &yogh;euen hym my&yogh;t to perfourmen his entent</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; De auaricia.</HEAD>
<P>[739]</P>
<P>Aftere Accidie wil I speke of avarice and of<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De Auaricia</NOTE> coueytise of which synne sei&thorn; seint Poule<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Paulus</NOTE> &thorn;at &thorn;e Roote of all synne is coueitise &para; And Thimothei 2<SUP>o</SUP> Capitulo. [740] ffor trewly . whan &thorn;at &thorn;e hert of<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Timothei secundo.</NOTE> a man is confounded in it self and trouble and &thorn;at &thorn;e saule ha&thorn; lost &thorn;e comforte of god &thorn;an seke&thorn; he an ydel solace of worldly &thorn;ingges</P>
<P>[741] &para; Auarice aftere &thorn;e scripcion of seynt Austyne<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Augustinus</NOTE> is a likerousnesse in herte to haue er&thorn;ely &thorn;ingges. [742] Som <MILESTONE N="294b" UNIT="folio">o&thorn;er folk seyn &thorn;at auarice is forto purchace mony er&thorn;ely &thorn;ingges and no &thorn;inge &yogh;eue to hem &thorn;at han nede . [743] And vnderstonde &thorn;ow wel &thorn;at auarice nys not oonly in land ne catell but som|tyme in science and in glorie and in euery manere of outrageous &thorn;ingges is auarice and coueitise [744] And &thorn;e difference ytwix Auarice and couetise is &thorn;is Coueitise is forto coueite suche &thorn;ingges as &thorn;ow hast not And auarice is forto wi&thorn;holde and kepe suche &thorn;ingges as &thorn;ou hast wi&thorn;-out ri&yogh;tful nede [745] So&thorn;ly &thorn;is Auarice is a synne &thorn;at is ful dampnable for al holy writte curse&thorn; it and speke&thorn; a&yogh;einst it ffor it do&thorn; wronge to Ihesu crist [746] for it byreue&thorn; hym &thorn;e loue &thorn;at men to hym owen and turne&thorn; it bakward a&yogh;einst all reson [747] and make&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e auaricious man ha&thorn; more hope in his catel &thorn;an in Ihesu crist And . . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [748] &thorn;erfore sei&thorn; 
<PB REF="00000702.tif" N="668"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="652"> <NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ephesianos 5<SUP>o</SUP> capitulo</NOTE>seyn Paule Ephesios .5<SUP>o</SUP>. That auerous man / ha&thorn; more hope in his &thorn;raldome of ydolatrie</P>
<P>[749] &para; What difference is ytwix an ydolastre and an auarous man but &thorn;at an ydolastre and an auarous man ne ha&thorn; but a mawmet or twoo; and &thorn;e auaricious man ha&thorn; monye ffor certes euery floreyn in his Coffre is his mawmet [750] And certes &thorn;e synne of Maumetrie is &thorn;at god in &thorn;e ten / comaundmentes <NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Exodi xx<SUP>o</SUP>. capitulo./</NOTE>as bere&thorn; witnesse in Exodi capitulo .xx<SUP>o</SUP>. [751] Thou / shalt haue no fals goddes byforn me. Ne &thorn;ou shalt make to &thorn;e no grauen &thorn;inge. Thus as is an Auaricious man . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> &para; And ydolastre [752] &thorn;orgh his synne of Auarice and of coueitise commen &thorn;ise hard lordshippes &thorn;orgh which men ben strayned by taliages. custumes and cariages more &thorn;an / her duete or reson is &para; And ellis take &thorn;ei of her bonde men amercementz which myghten more resonably be cleped extorcions &thorn;an amercymentz. [753] Of which amercymentes and raunsonynge of boond men some lordes Stuardes seyn &thorn;at it is ri&yogh;htfull for as moche as a cherle ha&thorn; no temporell &thorn;inge. &thorn;at it ne is his lordes as &thorn;ei sayne. [754] But certes &thorn;ise lordshippes doon wronge &thorn;at byreuen her bonde folk &thorn;ingges &thorn;at &thorn;ei <NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Augustinus de civitate. libro. ix<SUP>o</SUP></NOTE>neuere ne &yogh;af hem./ Augustinus de Civitate libro ix<SUP>o</SUP>. [755] &para; Soo&thorn; is &thorn;at &thorn;e condicion of &thorn;raldome and &thorn;e furst <NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Genesis .5<SUP>to</SUP>/</NOTE>cause of &thorn;raldome is for synne. G[e]nesis v<SUP>to</SUP>.</P>
<P>[756] Thus may &yogh;e seen &thorn;at &thorn;e gilt deserueth thraldom <MILESTONE N="295a" UNIT="folio">But not nature [757] Wherfor &thorn;ise lordes ne shuld not moche glorifie hem in her lordship si&thorn;ens &thorn;at by naturell condicions &thorn;ei bene [not] lordes ouer her &thorn;ralles . but for &thorn;at &thorn;raldom come furst by desert of synne. [758] And fer&thorn;er ouer &thorn;er as &thorn;e lawe sei&thorn; &thorn;at temporell goodes of bonde folk bene &thorn;e goodes of her lordshippes &yogh;e &thorn;at is forto vnderstonde &thorn;e goodes of &thorn;e Emperour to defende hem in her ri&yogh;t but not <NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Seneca</NOTE>to robbe hem ne to reue hem. [759] &para; And &thorn;erfore 
<PB REF="00000703.tif" N="669"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="653"> sei&thorn; Senec. Thy prudence shuld lyue benignely wi&thorn; &thorn;ine &thorn;rall. [760] Thilk &thorn;at &thorn;ou clepest &thorn;ine &thorn;rall bene goddys puple. ffor humble folk bene cristes frendes &thorn;ei bene contubernial wi&thorn; &thorn;e lord</P>
<P>[761] &para; Thenk eke &thorn;at suche sede as churles &para; springen; of suche seed springgen lordes. as wel may &thorn;e cherle be saued as &thorn;e lorde. [762] &thorn;e same de&thorn; &thorn;at take&thorn; &thorn;e cherle. &thorn;e same dee&thorn; take&thorn; &thorn;e lorde. wherfore I rede do ri&yogh;ht so wi&thorn; &thorn;i cherle as &thorn;ou woldest &thorn;i lorde did wi&thorn; &thorn;e if &thorn;ou were in his plite [763] Euery synful man is a cherle to synne &para; I rede &thorn;e Certes &thorn;at &thorn;ou lorde worche in suche wise &thorn;at &thorn;i cherles ra&thorn;er loue &thorn;e than drede &thorn;e [764] &para; I woote wel &thorn;er is degree aboue degre as reson is and skill is &thorn;at men / done her devoyre &thorn;er as it is dwe But certes extorcions and despites of &yogh;oure vnderlyngges is dampnable.</P>
<P>[765] And forther ouer vnderstonde well &thorn;at conquerours or tyrauntz maken ful often &thorn;ralles of hem &thorn;at bene born of as Royal blood as bene &thorn;ei &thorn;at hem conqueren. [766] This name of thraldome was neuere knowe erst til &thorn;at Noe seid &thorn;at his sone<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De Noe</NOTE> Canaan shuld be &thorn;rall to his bre&thorn;eren for his synne. [767] &para; What say we &thorn;an of hem &thorn;at pillen and done extorcions to holy churche &para; Certes &thorn;e swerd &thorn;at me &yogh;euen furst to a knyght whan he is newe dubbed signifie&thorn; &thorn;at he shuld defende holy church and nou&yogh;t robbe it and who so doo&thorn; is a traitour to crist. [768] as sei&thorn; seynt Austyne &para; They bene<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Augustinus</NOTE> deuels wolfes &thorn;at stranglen &thorn;e shepe of Ihesu criste and bene wors &thorn;an wolfes. [769] ffor so&thorn;ly whan &thorn;e wolf ha&thorn; ful his wombe. He stynteth to strangle shepe. But so&thorn;ly &thorn;e pylours and distroy|ours of good of holy church ne doon not so for &thorn;ei ne stynte neuere to pillen. [770] Now as I haue seide so si&thorn;ens so is <MILESTONE N="295b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;at synne was furst cause of thraldome Than it is 
<PB REF="00000704.tif" N="670"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="654"> &thorn;us &thorn;at &thorn;ilk tyme &thorn;at al &thorn;is world was in synne &thorn;an was al &thorn;is worlde in &thorn;raldome and in subiection./ [771] But certes si&thorn;en &thorn;e tyme of grace cam god ordeyned &thorn;at some folk shuld be more highe in estate and hie degree. and some folk more lowe and &thorn;at eueryche shulde be serued in his estaat/ and in degre. [772] And &thorn;erfore in some contrey &thorn;er &thorn;ei bene &thorn;ralles whan &thorn;ei / han turned hem to &thorn;e fei&thorn; &thorn;ei maken her &thorn;ralles free out of &thorn;raldome And &thorn;erfor certes &thorn;e lorde owe&thorn; to his man &thorn;at &thorn;e man owe&thorn; to his lorde [773] &para; &thorn;e pope clepe&thorn; hym self seruaunte of Seruauntes of god. But for as moche as &thorn;e state of holy church ne my&yogh;t not han bee ne &thorn;e comon profite ne my&yogh;t han be kept ne pees and rest in er&thorn;e but if god had ordeyned &thorn;at som men han hier degre and somme men lowere [774] &para; &thorn;erfor was souereynte ordeyned to kepe and mayntene and de|fende her vnderlyngges or her subiectes in reson as fer|for&thorn;e as it li&thorn;e in her power and not to distroye hem ne as ferfor&thorn; confounde. [775] wherfore I say &thorn;at &thorn;ilk lordes &thorn;at bene &thorn;ilk wolfes &thorn;at deuouren &thorn;e possessions or &thorn;e catel of poor folk wrongfully wi&thorn;-outen mercy or mesure [776] &thorn;er shullen resceyue by &thorn;e same mesure &thorn;at &thorn;ei han mesured to poor folk &thorn;e mercy of Ihesu crist but it be amended [777] &para; Now comme&thorn; despite bytwix Marchaunt and marchaunt. And &thorn;ou shalt vnder|stonde &thorn;at Marchaundise is in mony maners. &thorn;at oon is bodyly &amp; &thorn;at o&thorn;er is goostly. &thorn;at oon is leeful and &thorn;at o&thorn;er is dishonest and vnlieful [778] &para; of &thorn;ilk bodily marchaundyse &thorn;at is leeful and honest is &thorn;is &thorn;at &thorn;er as god hath ordeyned &thorn;at a regne or a contre is sufficient him self &thorn;an is it honest and lieful &thorn;at of &thorn;e habundaunce of &thorn;is cuntre &thorn;at men helpe ano&thorn;er cuntre &thorn;at is more nedye [779] and &thorn;erfore &thorn;ei mote be Marchauntz to bringe from &thorn;at oon cuntre to &thorn;at o&thorn;er her march|aundise. 
<PB REF="00000705.tif" N="671"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="655"> ./ [780] &para; That o&thorn;ere marchaundise &thorn;at men haunte wi&thorn; fraude trecherye and disceyte wi&thorn; lesyngges and fals o&thorn;es is cursed and dampnable. [781] &para; Espirituel Marchaundise <MILESTONE N="296a" UNIT="folio">is proprely Symonye &thorn;at is ententif desire to by &thorn;enk espirituel that is &thorn;ing &thorn;at apperteyne&thorn; to &thorn;e sentuary of god and to cure of &thorn;e soule. [782] This desire if so be &thorn;at a man do hys diligence to perfourme it al be it &thorn;at his desire ne take noon effecte &yogh;it is it to hym a dedly synne and if he be ordred he is aregulere [783] &para; Certes Symony is cleped of Symon magus &thorn;at wolde haue bou&yogh;t &thorn;e temporel Catell./ &thorn;e &yogh;ift &thorn;at god had &yogh;euen / by &thorn;e holy goost to seint Peter and to &thorn;e apostels./ [784] And &thorn;erfore vnderstonde&thorn; &thorn;at bo&thorn; he &thorn;at selle&thorn; and he &thorn;at byeth &thorn;ingges espiritull bene cleped Symonyals be it catel be it procurynge or by flesshly preier of his frendes or of spirituel frendes [785] . . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> So&thorn;ly if &thorn;ei prey for hym &thorn;at is not able ne wor&thorn;i. it is Symonye. If he take &thorn;e benefice and if he be wor&thorn;i and able he nys noon. [786] &para; That o&thorn;er maner is if a man or a womman preye&thorn; for folk to auaunsen hem / only for wikked flesshly affection &thorn;at &thorn;ei han vnto &thorn;e persones and &thorn;at is in foule Symonye. [787] But certes in seruice for which men &yogh;euen &thorn;ingges espirituels vnto her seruauntes It most be vnderstonde &thorn;at &thorn;e seruise most be honest and ellis not. and eke &thorn;at hit be wi&thorn; out barganynge and &thorn;at &thorn;e persone be able. [788] ffor as sei&thorn; seint Damasie &para; Alle &thorn;e synnes of &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Damasius</NOTE> world at &thorn;e regarde of this synne bene as a &thorn;inge of nou&yogh;t. ffor it is &thorn;e grettest synne &thorn;at may be aftere <SUP>2</SUP>&thorn;e synne of lucifer<SUP>2</SUP><NOTE PLACE="marg">[<SUP>2_2</SUP> <I>repeated in MS.</I>]</NOTE> and of antecrist [789] for by &thorn;is synne god forlese&thorn; &thorn;e churche and &thorn;e soule &thorn;at he bou&yogh;t wi&thorn; his precious blood by hem &thorn;at &yogh;euen chirches to hem &thorn;at bene not digne. [790] ffor &thorn;ei putten in &thorn;eues &thorn;at 
<PB REF="00000706.tif" N="672"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="656"> stelen &thorn;e soules of Ihesu crist and distroye&thorn; his patry|moyne [791] by suche vndigne preestes and curates han men &thorn;e lasse reuerence of &thorn;e sacramentes of holy churche. And suche &yogh;euers of churches putten out &thorn;e children of crist. and putten in &thorn;e churche &thorn;e deuels owne sone. [792] &thorn;ei sellen &thorn;e soules &thorn;e lombes shulden kepen to &thorn;e wolf &thorn;at strangle&thorn; hem and &thorn;erfore shul &thorn;ei neuere haue parte of &thorn;e pasture of lambes &thorn;at is &thorn;e blisse of heuene. [793] &para; Now comme&thorn; hasardy with his a<MILESTONE N="296b" UNIT="folio"> pur|tynaunces<NOTE PLACE="marg">Of Hasardry</NOTE> as tables and Rafuls of which comme&thorn; disceite fals o&thorn;es chidyngges and all ravanys blasphemynge and reneiynge of god and hate of his neghbours waast of good in spendyng of tyme and somtyme mannys sclaughter [794] Certes hasardours ne may not be wi&thorn;-out grete synne &thorn;e whiles &thorn;ei haunte &thorn;at craft [795] Of Auarice comme&thorn; eke lesingges. &thorn;eeft and fals witnesse. and fals o&thorn;es and &yogh;e shal vnderstonde &thorn;at &thorn;ise bene grete synnes and expresse a&yogh;einst &thorn;e comaundementz of god as I haue said [796] &para; ffals witnesse is in worde and eke in dede<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De falso testi|monio</NOTE> In worde as forto byreue &thorn;ine nei&yogh;bours good name by &thorn;i fals witnessinge or byreue hym his Catell or his heritage by &thorn;i fals witnessinge. whan &thorn;ou for Ire or for mede or for envie berest fals witnesse or accusest hym. or excusest hym by &thorn;i fals witnesse. or ellis ex|cusest &thorn;ine self falsly. [797] ware &yogh;ou questmongers and notaries. Certes for fals witnessyng was Susanna in grete sorowe &amp; peyn and mony ano&thorn;er moo [798] &para; The synne of &thorn;eft is eke expres a&yogh;einst goddes heest and &thorn;at in<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De ffurto</NOTE> two maners corporell and spirituell [799] [Corporell] as for to take &thorn;ine neighbours catell a&yogh;einst his wille. be it by force or by scleight by it by mette or by mesure. [800] By stelynge eke of fals enditementz vpon hym and in borowinge of &thorn;ine neighbours Catell in entent neuer to pay. And semplable &thorn;ingges [801] es|pirituell &thorn;eft is sacrilege &thorn;at is to seyn hurt|ynge 
<PB REF="00000707.tif" N="673"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="657"> of holy &thorn;ingges or of &thorn;ingges sacred to crist in two maners by reson of &thorn;e holy place as churches or chirch hawes. [802] for euery vyleyns synne &thorn;at men doon in suche places may be cleped Sacrilegge or euery violence in &thorn;e semblable places./ &para; Also &thorn;ei &thorn;at wi&thorn;drawen falsly &thorn;e ri&yogh;tes &thorn;at longen to holy church. [803] And pleynly and generally sacrilege is to &yogh;eue holy &thorn;inge fro holy place. or vnholy &thorn;inge out of holy place. or holy &thorn;ing out of vn|holy place</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[The Remedy against Avarice.]</HEAD>
<P>[804] &para; Now shul &yogh;e vnderstonde &thorn;at &thorn;e releuyng of<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Reuelacio Auaricie</NOTE> Auarice is misericord and pite largely taken./ &para; And men my&yogh;ten axen why &thorn;at misericorde and pite is releuynge of auarice [805] &para; Certes &thorn;e Auarous <MILESTONE N="297a" UNIT="folio">man scheweth no pite ne misericord to &thorn;e nedeful man ffor he delite&thorn; hym in &thorn;re kepingges of his tresoure and not in &thorn;e reskowinge ne releuing of his euen|cristen and &thorn;erfore speke I furst of misericorde [806] &thorn;an is misericorde as sei&thorn; &thorn;e philosophre<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Philosophus</NOTE> &para; A vertue by whiche &thorn;e corage of a man is stired by &thorn;e myssese of hym &thorn;at is myssesed [807] vpon which misericord folowe&thorn; pite in perfourmynge of charitable werkes of misericord. [808] And certes &thorn;ise meuen man to &thorn;e misericord of Ihesu crist &thorn;at hym self for our gilt suffred deeth for misericord and for&yogh;aue vs our origynal synnes [809] and &thorn;er-by relesed vs fro &thorn;e peyne of helle and amenuse&thorn; &thorn;e peynes of purgatorie by penytence. and &yogh;eue&thorn; grace wel to doo. and at &thorn;e last &thorn;e Ioie of heuene [810] The spices of misericorde bene as forto lene. and forto &yogh;eue / and forto . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> relees. and for to haue pite in hert and compassion of &thorn;e meschief of his 
<PB REF="00000708.tif" N="674"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="658"> euencristen. and eke. chastise &thorn;er as nede is [811] &para; Ano&thorn;er maner remedy a&yogh;einst Auarice is resonable largesse. But so&thorn;ly here byhoueth &thorn;e con|sideracion of &thorn;e grace of Ihesu crist and of his temporell goodes and eke of &thorn;e goodes perdurables &thorn;at crist &yogh;aue vs. [812] and eke to haue remembrannce of &thorn;e dee&thorn; &thorn;at he shal haue he noot not whan. and eke &thorn;at he shal forgoon all &thorn;at he ha&thorn;e . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> dispended in good</P>
<P>[813] &para; But for as moche as some folk bene vnmesur|able men ou&yogh;ten eschewe fool largesse &thorn;at men clepen waast [814] Certes he &thorn;at is fool large ne &yogh;eueth not his catell. but he lese&thorn; his catell. Soo&thorn;ly what &thorn;inge &thorn;at he &yogh;eue&thorn; for veyn glorie as to Mynstralles and to folk forto byreuen his renoun in &thorn;e world he ha&thorn; do / [synne and non] almesse. [815] ce[r]tes he lese&thorn; foule his good &thorn;at he ne seke&thorn; no &thorn;inge of his good but synne. [816] he is like to an hors &thorn;at seke&thorn; ra&thorn;er to drink drovy or troubly watere &thorn;an of &thorn;e clere welle [817] And for as moche as &thorn;ei &yogh;eue &thorn;ere as &thorn;ei shuld not &yogh;eue to hem apperteyne&thorn; &thorn;ilk malyson &thorn;at criste shal &yogh;euen at &thorn;e day of dome to hem &thorn;at shul be dampned. /</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De Gula /</HEAD>
<P>[818]</P>
<P>Aftere Auarice comme&thorn; glotenye which is expresse eke<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Gula ./.</NOTE> a&yogh;einst &thorn;e comaundement of god &para; Gloteny is vnmesurable appetit to ete or to drink or ellis to doon ynogh to &thorn;e vnmesurable and discord coueityse to ete and to drynk [819] &para; This synne cor|rumpe&thorn; al &thorn;is world as is wel shewde in <MILESTONE N="297b" UNIT="folio">in &thorn;e synne of Adam and of Eua &para; Loo eke what sei&thorn; seynt Paule of<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Paulus</NOTE> gloteny [820] &para; Mony sei&thorn; seint Paule goon of which 
<PB REF="00000709.tif" N="675"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="659"> I haue oft seide to &yogh;ou. and nowe I seie it wepynge &thorn;at &thorn;ei bene Enemyes of &thorn;e crois of crist of which &thorn;e ende is dee&thorn; and of which her woombe is her god and her glorye in confusion of hem &thorn;at so saueren er&thorn;ely &thorn;ingges [821] he &thorn;at is vsant to &thorn;is synne of glotenye he ne may no synne wi&thorn;stonde. he / mote bene in seruage of all vices. for it is &thorn;e deuels hoorde &thorn;er [he] hide&thorn; him and reste&thorn; [822] &para; This synne ha&thorn; mony spices &para; The furst is drenknes &thorn;at is &thorn;e horrible sepulcre of mannys reson And &thorn;er|fore whan &thorn;at a man is dronken. he ha&thorn; lost his reson and &thorn;is is dedly synne [823] &para; But certes whan a man is nat wonte to straunge drynk and perauenture ne knowe&thorn; not &thorn;e strength of &thorn;e drynk or ha&thorn; feblenesse in his hede or ha&thorn; travailled &thorn;orgh which he drinke&thorn; &thorn;e moore al be he sodeynly cau&yogh;te wi&thorn; drink it is no dedly synne. but venial [824] &para; The secounde spice of Gloteny is &thorn;at &thorn;e spirit of a man wexe&thorn; al trouble. for dronknesse byreue&thorn; hym &thorn;e discrecion of his witte [825] &para; The &thorn;red spice of gloteny is whan a man deuoure&thorn; his mete and ha&thorn; no ri&yogh;t-ful maner of etynge [826] &para; The fourte is whan &thorn;orgh &thorn;e grete habund|aunce of his mete &thorn;e humours of his body bene dis|tempred [827] &para; The v. is for&yogh;etelnesse by to mochel drynkynge. ffor which somtyme a man for&yogh;ete&thorn; by &thorn;e morowe what he did at Eue or on &thorn;e ny&yogh;t byfor</P>
<P>[828] &para; In o&thorn;er manere bene distincte of vices &amp; spices of glotenye aftere seint Gregorie &para; The furst is forto ete by|fore<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Gregorius./</NOTE> tyme. The secounde whan a man gete&thorn; hym to delicate mete [829] &para; The iij. is whan men taken to moche ouere mesure &para; The 4 is curiosite wi&thorn; grete entent to maken and apparailen his mete &para; The .v. is forto eten to gredely [830] Thise bene the .v. fyngers of &thorn;e / deueles honde. by which he drawe&thorn; folk to synne
</P>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000710.tif" N="676"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="660">
<HEAD>[The Remedy against Gluttony.]</HEAD>
<P>[831] &para; A&yogh;einst glotenye is the remedy abstinence of his<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Remedium./</NOTE> body as sei&thorn; Galien. but &thorn;at hold I not meritorie if he do it only for &thorn;e hel&thorn; of his body &para; Seynt austyne wil &thorn;at abstinence be doon for vertue &amp;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Augustinus.</NOTE> wi&thorn; pacience [832] &para; Abstinence he sei&thorn; is litel wor&thorn;. but if a / man haue good wille &thorn;erto / and but if it be enforced by pacience and by charite and &thorn;at men doon it for goddys / sake and in hope to haue &thorn;e blisse of heuene</P>
<P>[833] &para; The felowes of abstynence. bene attemper|aunce &thorn;at halde&thorn; &thorn;e mene in alle <MILESTONE N="298a" UNIT="folio">&thorn;ingges &para; Eke shame &thorn;at eschewe&thorn; all dishoneste. Suffisaunce &thorn;at seke&thorn; no riche metes ne drinkes ne doo&thorn; noo force of noon / outrageous apparaillynge of mete [834] Mesure also &thorn;at restreyne&thorn; by reson &thorn;e delaue appetite of etynge. Sobrenesse also &thorn;at restreyne&thorn; &thorn;e outrage of drynk. [835] Sparyng also &thorn;at restreyne&thorn; &thorn;e delicate eese to sitte longe atte mete and softly // wherfore some folk stonden of her owne wille and to eten at &thorn;e lasse leisere</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; De luxuria Sequitur ./</HEAD>
<P>[836]</P>
<P>Aftere Gloteny comme&thorn; lecherye. ffor &thorn;ise<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Luxuria</NOTE> two synnes ben so nygh Cosyns &thorn;at often tyme &thorn;ei wil not departe./ [837] God woote &thorn;is synne is ful displesaunt &thorn;ing to god. ffor he / sei&thorn; hym self. do no lecherye. And &thorn;erfore he putte&thorn; grete peynes a&yogh;einst &thorn;is synne. As in &thorn;e olde lawe. [838] &para; If wom|man &thorn;ral were taken in &thorn;is synne. she shuld be beten wi&thorn; staues to &thorn;e dethe And if she were a gentile womman she shulde be sclayn with stones And if she were a bishoppes dou&yogh;ter; she shuld be brent by goddis comanndement [839] &para; ffer&thorn;ermore by &thorn;e synne of lecherye; god draynt al &thorn;e world at &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000711.tif" N="677"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="661"> diluve. And after &thorn;at he brent .v. Citees wi&thorn; li&yogh;t and sonke hem into helle</P>
<P>[840] &para; Nowe lat vs speke &thorn;an of &thorn;ilk stynkinge synne of lechery. &thorn;at men clepen aduoutrie of wedded folk &thorn;at is to say if &thorn;at oon of hem be wedded or ellis boo&thorn; [841] &para; Seint Iohn sei&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e aduoutrers<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Sanctus Iohannes./</NOTE> schullen be in helle in a stynk brennyng of fuyre and of bremstoon. In fuyre for lechery. In bremstone for &thorn;e stynke of her ordure [842] &para; Certes &thorn;e brekinge of &thorn;is sacrament is an horrible &thorn;inge. it was made of god hym self in Paradise and confermed by Ihesu crist as wittnesse&thorn; seint Mathewe in &thorn;e gospell &para; A man shal lete fadere and modere and take hym to his wiff and &thorn;ei shul be twoo in oo flessh [843] &para; This sacrament bytoken|e&thorn; &thorn;e knyttyng to-gidere of crist and of holy churche. [844] and nat oonly &thorn;at god forbad aduoutrie in bedde. but eke he comaunded &thorn;at &thorn;ou shuldest not coveyte &thorn;ine neighbours wiff [845] &para; In &thorn;is heest sei&thorn; seint Austyne is for-boden al manere coueitise to doon lecherie &para; Loo what sei&thorn; seint Mathewe &thorn;e .v. chapitle / in &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Augustinus</NOTE> gospell. &thorn;at who so see&thorn; a womman to coueitise of his lust. he<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Matheus</NOTE> ha&thorn; doon lecchery wi&thorn; her in his hert [846] &para; Here may &yogh;e see &thorn;at not oonly &thorn;e dede of this synne is forbode; but eke &thorn;e desire to doon &thorn;at synne [847] &para; This cursed <MILESTONE N="298b" UNIT="folio">synne annoye&thorn; greuously hem &thorn;at it haunten and first to her saule for he oblige&thorn; it to synne and to peyne of &thorn;e dee&thorn; / &thorn;at is perdurable. [848] vnto &thorn;e body annoye&thorn; it greuously also for it drie&thorn; hym and waaste&thorn; hym / and . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in MS.</NOTE> of his blood he make&thorn; sacrifice to &thorn;e feende of helle. hit waaste&thorn; eke his catell and his substannce. [849] &amp; certes if it be a foule &thorn;ing a man to waast his catell on wommen. &yogh;it is it a foulere &thorn;inge whan &thorn;at for such ordure wommen dispenden vpon men her catell and her substannce [850] &para; This synne as sei&thorn; the prophete<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Propheta ./</NOTE> byreue&thorn; man and womman her good fame and al her honure and it is ful plesaunt to &thorn;e deuel. for &thorn;erby 
<PB REF="00000712.tif" N="678"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="662"> wynneth he &thorn;e most partie of &thorn;is world [851] And ri&yogh;t as a marchannte delite&thorn; hym most in chaffare &thorn;at he ha&thorn; most auauntage of Ri&yogh;t. so delite&thorn; &thorn;e feende in &thorn;is ordure</P>
<P>[852] this is &thorn;at o&thorn;er hand of &thorn;e deuel wi&thorn; .v. fyngres to cacche &thorn;e puple to his vilanye [853] &para; The first fynger is &thorn;e foolissh lokinge of the foolyssh man or the folissh womman &thorn;at sclee&thorn; ri&yogh;t as &thorn;e basilicok sclee&thorn; folk by &thorn;e venyme of his / sight. ffor &thorn;e Coueityse of &thorn;e eyen folowe&thorn; &thorn;e couetise of &thorn;e herte [854] &para; That o&thorn;er fynger is &thorn;e vileyns touchynge in wicked maner And &thorn;erfore sei&thorn; Salomon. &thorn;at who so touche&thorn; and handle&thorn; a womman. he fare&thorn; like hym &thorn;at handle&thorn; &thorn;e scorpion &thorn;at stynge&thorn; and sodeynly sclee&thorn; &thorn;ourgh his enuenemynge. As who so touche&thorn; warme picch. he shent his fyngres [855] &para; The iij is foolissh wordes &thorn;at fare&thorn; lich fire &thorn;at brenne&thorn;. &thorn;at ri&yogh;t anoon brenne&thorn; &thorn;e herte. [856] &para; The iiij. is &thorn;e kissynge. And so&thorn;ly he were a grete fool &thorn;at wolde kysse &thorn;e mou&thorn; of a brennyng ouen or of a forneys. [857] And / more fooles bene &thorn;ei &thorn;at kissen in vileynye for &thorn;at mou&thorn; is &thorn;e mou&thorn;e of helle. And namely &thorn;ise olde dotardes holours &yogh;it wil &thorn;ei kisse &thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;ei may not do. and smatere hem [858] &para; Certes &thorn;ei bene like to houndes. ffor an hounde whan he comme&thorn; by &thorn;e Rosere or by o&thorn;er bewtees &thorn;ou&yogh;e he may not pisse. &yogh;it wil he heuene vp his legge and make coun|tenaunce to pisse. [859] And for &thorn;at mony man weneth &thorn;at he may no&yogh;t synne for no likerousnesse &thorn;at he do&thorn; with his wiff Certes &thorn;at opynyon is fals &para; God woote a man / may scle hym self wi&thorn; his owne knyff. And maken hym drunke wi&thorn; his owne tunge [860] Certes be it wif or childe or eny worldly &thorn;ing &thorn;at he loueth to-fore god it is his mameut and he is his ydolastre [861] &para; A man shuld loue his wiff by discrecion paciently and temperally And &thorn;an is she as it 
<PB REF="00000713.tif" N="679"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="663"> were his suster [862] &para; The .v. <MILESTONE N="299a" UNIT="folio">fynger of &thorn;e deuels honde is &thorn;e stynkynge dede of lecherie [863] Certes &thorn;e .v. fyngers of glotenye &thorn;e fende putte in &thorn;e wombe of a man. and wi&thorn; &thorn;ise .v. fyngers of lecherie he gripe&thorn; hym by &thorn;e Raynes forto &thorn;rowe hym into &thorn;e fornais of helle. [864] &thorn;er as &thorn;ei / shul han &thorn;e fuyr and &thorn;e wormes &thorn;at euere shul lasten. and wepyng and waillyng. sharp hunger and &thorn;rest. Grislynesse of deuels &thorn;at shullen alto treden hem wi&thorn;-outen respite and with|outen eende [865] &para; Of lecchery as I seide sourden dyuers spices As fornicacion &thorn;at is bytwix man and womman &thorn;at bene not maried. and &thorn;is is dedly synne and a&yogh;einst nature. [866] for al &thorn;at is enemye and destruction to nature is a&yogh;einst nature. [867] Parfay &thorn;e reson of a man telleth hym eke wel &thorn;at it is dedly synne for as moch as god forbode lechery. And seint Paule &yogh;eue&thorn; hym &thorn;e regne &thorn;at is due to no wi&yogh;t &para; But to hem &thorn;at doon dedly synne [868] &para; A no&thorn;er synne of lechery is forto byreuen a maide of her maidenhode. ffor certes he &thorn;at so doo&thorn; he caccheth a mayde out of &thorn;e hiest degree &thorn;at is in &thorn;is present liff [869] and byreue&thorn; hure &thorn;ilk pr[e]cious fruyte &thorn;at &thorn;e boke clepe&thorn; &thorn;e hundred fruyte I ne can not say it in noon o&thorn;er way in englissh. but in latyne it hight Centesimus fructus [870] Certes he &thorn;at so do&thorn; is cause of mony damages and vilenyes moo &thorn;an eny man can rekne Ri&yogh;t as he somtyme is cause of all Damages &thorn;at beestes doon in &thorn;e feelde &thorn;at breke&thorn; &thorn;e hegge or &thorn;e closure &thorn;orowe which he distroie&thorn; &thorn;at may not be restored. [871] ffor certes no more may maidenhede be re|stored. &thorn;an an harme smyte fro &thorn;e body may retourne a&yogh;ein to wexe. [872] She may haue mercy &thorn;is wote I well if she doo penitence. but neuer shal it be &thorn;at she nas corrupte. [873] And al be it so &thorn;at I haue spoken somwhat of aduoutrie. it is good to shewen moo periles &thorn;at longen to aduoutrie forto eschewe &thorn;e foule 
<PB REF="00000714.tif" N="680"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="664"> synne of [874] aduoutrie &para; Auoutry in latyne is forto seyne approchinge of an o&thorn;er mannys bed. &thorn;oorgh which &thorn;oo &thorn;at whilom were oo flessh. abounden her body to o&thorn;er persones [875] &para; Of &thorn;is synne as sei&thorn; &thorn;e wise man comme&thorn; mony harmes &para; ffirst brekinge of &thorn;ei fei&thorn;. And certes fei&thorn; is keye of cristendome [876] And whan &thorn;at fei&thorn; is broke and lorne. so&thorn;ly cristendome stant. [veyne] And wi&thorn;-out fruyte [877] &thorn;is synne is eke a &thorn;eef./ &para; ffor &thorn;eeft generalli to speke is forto Reue a wi&yogh;t his &thorn;ing a&yogh;einst his wille. [878] Certes &thorn;is is &thorn;e foulest &thorn;eft that may be. whan <MILESTONE N="299b" UNIT="folio">a womman stele&thorn; her body from her husbond and &yogh;eue&thorn; it to her holour to defoule her and stele&thorn; her soule from crist &amp; &yogh;eue&thorn; it to &thorn;e deuel. [879] This is a foule[r] &thorn;eft &thorn;an forto stele or breke &thorn;e chalice from &thorn;e autere. ffor &thorn;ise aduoutrers breken &thorn;e temple of god spirituelly and stelen &thorn;e vessell of grace &thorn;at is &thorn;e body and &thorn;e saule. ffor which crist shal destroien hem as sei&thorn; seynt Paule. [880] &para; So&thorn;ly<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Paulus.</NOTE> of &thorn;is &thorn;eft douted gretly Ioseph whan &thorn;at his lordys wif preide hym of vilanye whan he saide &para; lo my lorde howe my lady ha&thorn; take to me vnder my ward al &thorn;at he ha&thorn; in &thorn;is world. ne no &thorn;ing of his ou&yogh;t of my pouer but oonly &yogh;e &thorn;at bene his wiff [881] and howe shuld I &thorn;an doon &thorn;is wikkednesse &amp; synne so horribli a&yogh;einst god. god it forbede. Allas al to litel is suche trou&thorn;e now yfounde [882] &para; The iij. harme is the fil&thorn;e &thorn;orowe &thorn;e which &thorn;ei breken &thorn;e comaundemen of god and defoulen &thorn;e autere of her matrimoyne &thorn;at is crist [883] ffor certes in so moche as &thorn;e sacrament of mariage is so noble and so digne. So moche it is &thorn;e gretter synne forto breke it. ffor god made mariage in paradys in &thorn;e estate of Innocence to multiplie mankynde to &thorn;e seruice of god. [884] and &thorn;erfore is &thorn;e brekinge &thorn;erof greuous. Of which breking commen fals heires often tyme &thorn;at wrongfulli occupien folkes heritage and &thorn;erfore wil crist putte 
<PB REF="00000715.tif" N="681"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="665"> hem out of &thorn;e regne of heuene &thorn;at is heritage to good folk [885] &para; Of &thorn;is breking comme&thorn; eke oft tymes &thorn;at folk vnware wedden or synnen with her owne kynrede. and namely &thorn;ilk harlottes &thorn;at haunten bordels &para; Of thise fool wommen &thorn;at mowen be likned to a comune gonge wher as men purge her ordure [886] &para; What say we eke of putours &thorn;at lyuen by &thorn;e horrible synne of Putrie and constreynen wommen &yogh;e somtyme his owne wiff or his childe as doon &thorn;ise bawdes to &yogh;eelden hem a certeyn rent of her bodily putrie Certes &thorn;ise bene cursed synnes [887] &para; Vnderstonde&thorn; eke &thorn;at aduoutrie is sette gladly in the x. comaundementz bytwix &thorn;eft and man|nys sclaughter. for it is &thorn;e grettest &thorn;eft &thorn;at may be. ffor it is &thorn;eeft of body and soule [888] and it is like homycide ffor it kerue&thorn; a twoo and breke&thorn; a twoo hem &thorn;at furst were ymaked oo flessh. and &thorn;erfor by &thorn;e olde lawe &thorn;ei <MILESTONE N="300a" UNIT="folio">shuld be sclayn [889] But na&thorn;elees by &thorn;e lawe of Ihesu crist &thorn;at is &thorn;e lawe of pite whan he saide to &thorn;e womman &thorn;at was / founde in aduoutrie and shuld haue bene sclayn wi&thorn; stones aftere &thorn;e wille of &thorn;e Iwes as was her lawe &para; Go quod ihesu crist and haue no more wille to do synne or wil no more to do synne [890] So&thorn;ly vengeaunce of aduoutrie is a-warded to &thorn;e peyne of helle but it be destroubled by penaunce [891] &para; &YOGH;it bene &thorn;ere moo spices of &thorn;is cursed synne. as whan &thorn;at oon of hem is religious or ellis boo&thorn;. or of folk &thorn;at bene entred into ordere as subdeken or deken or preest or hospitalers. and euer &thorn;e hier &thorn;at he is in ordere &thorn;e gretter is &thorn;e synne [892] The &thorn;ingges &thorn;at gretly aggreggen. his synne is &thorn;e breking of his avowe of chaastite whan he receyue&thorn; order. [893] And fer&thorn;er ouer. soo&thorn; is &thorn;at holy order is cheef of all &thorn;e tresour of god. And his especial syngne and marke of chaastite to shewe &thorn;at &thorn;ei bene Ioyned to chastite which &thorn;at is &thorn;e moost precious lif &thorn;at is. [894] And eke &thorn;ise ordred folk bene specially tytled to god. and of &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000716.tif" N="682"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="666"> special mayne of god . ffor which whan &thorn;ei doon dedly synne &thorn;ei bene &thorn;e special traitours of god and of his puple. ffor &thorn;ei lyuen of &thorn;e puple to prey for &thorn;e puple. And while &thorn;er bene such traitours her preiers availlen not to &thorn;e puple./ [895] &para; Preestes bene as aungels as by &thorn;e dignite of hir mysterye &para; But forso&thorn; seynt poule<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Paulus.</NOTE> sei&thorn;. &thorn;at sathanas transforme&thorn; hym into an aungell of li&yogh;t. [896] So&thorn;ly &thorn;e preest &thorn;at haunte&thorn; synne he may be likned vnto &thorn;e aungel of derknesse. transformed in &thorn;e aungel of li&yogh;t &para; He seme&thorn; aungel of li&yogh;t. but forso&thorn; he is aungel of derknesse [897] &para; Suche preestes bene &thorn;e sones of Belye. as schewe&thorn; in &thorn;e boke of kyngges &thorn;at &thorn;ei weren &thorn;e sones of Belial &thorn;at is &thorn;e deuell [898] Belial is to say wi&thorn;-out Iuge. and so faren &thorn;ei. hem &thorn;enke &thorn;ei bene free and han no Iuge no more &thorn;an ha&thorn; a free boole &thorn;at take&thorn; which kowe &thorn;at him litek in &thorn;e toune. [899] So faren &thorn;ei by wemmen. ffor ri&yogh;t [as] a fre bulle is ynou&yogh;e for al a toune Ri&yogh;t so is a / wikked preest corrupte ynough for al a parissh or all a cuntree [900] Thise preestes as sei&thorn; &thorn;e boke ne kon nott &thorn;e mysterye of preesthode to &thorn;e puple. ne god ne knowe&thorn;<MILESTONE N="300b" UNIT="folio"> hem nou&yogh;t They ne holden hem nou&yogh;t a-paide as sei&thorn; &thorn;e boke of soden flessh &thorn;at was to hem offred but &thorn;ei toke by force &thorn;e flesshe &thorn;at is rawe [901] Certes ri&yogh;t so &thorn;ise schrewes ne holdene hem not a-paide of rosted flessh and soden flessh wi&thorn; &thorn;e which &thorn;e pupell fedden hem in grete reuerence. But &thorn;ei wil haue rawe flessh as folkes wyues and her doughtren [902] &para; And certes wommen &thorn;at consenten to her harlotrie done grete wronge to crist and to holy churche and to alhalowes and to all saules ffor &thorn;ei byreuen al &thorn;ese hym &thorn;at shulde worshipen crist and holy church and prey for cristen saules [903] And &thorn;erfore han suche preestes and her lemmans eke &thorn;at consenten to her leccherie &thorn;e malison of &thorn;e/ courte cristen to &thorn;ei come to amendement 
<PB REF="00000717.tif" N="683"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="667"> [904] &para; The iij spice of aduoutrie is somtyme by-twene a man and his wiff. &amp; &thorn;at is whan &thorn;ei taken no reward in her assemblynge but only to her flesshly delite as sei&thorn; seint Ierom. [905] and ne rekken of no&thorn;inge but<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ieronomus</NOTE> &thorn;at &thorn;ei bene assembled by cause &thorn;at &thorn;ei bene ymaried. al is good ynou&yogh;e as &thorn;enke&thorn; to hem [906] But in suche folk ha&thorn; &thorn;e deuel pouer as seide &thorn;e aungel Raphael<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Angelus Raphael</NOTE> to/ Thobie. ffor in her assemblynge &thorn;ei putten Ihesu crist out of her hertes and &yogh;eue hem self to all ordure [907] &para; &thorn;e iiij spice is &thorn;e assemblynge of hem &thorn;at bene of her kynrede. or of hem &thorn;at bene of oon affinite or ellis wi&thorn; hem wi&thorn; &thorn;e which her faders or her kynrede han deled wi&thorn; in &thorn;e synne of lecherie This synne make&thorn; hem liche houndes &thorn;at taken no kepe of kynrede [908] and certes Parentela is in two maners oi&thorn;er / goostly or flesshly. Goostely as forto delen wi&thorn; her gossipes [909] ffor ri&yogh;t so as . . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> is his godfader his fadere espirituel ffor which a womman may in no lasse synne assemble wi&thorn; her Gossipe &thorn;an wi&thorn; her owne flesshly bro&thorn;ere [910] &para; The v. spice is &thorn;ilk abhominable synne of which &thorn;at no man vnne&thorn;es ou&yogh;t to/ speke ne write // Na&thorn;elees it is openly rehersed in holy writt [911] . . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> speke of horrible synne Certes holy writt may not be defouled no more &thorn;an &thorn;e sonne &thorn;at shyne&thorn; on a myxen./ [912] &para; Ano&thorn;er synne appertene&thorn; to lecherie &thorn;at comme&thorn; in sclepinge and &thorn;is synne comme&thorn; oft to hem &thorn;at bene maydens and eke to hem &thorn;at bene corrupte And &thorn;is synne men clepen pollucion &thorn;at comme&thorn; in iiij. maners [913] Somtyme of a langwisshing <MILESTONE N="301a" UNIT="folio">of body for &thorn;e humours bene to rank and habundant in &thorn;e body of man. somtyme for &thorn;e infirmite for &thorn;e feblesse of &thorn;e vertue retentif as phisik make&thorn; menci&omacr;n. somtyme for sorfete of mete and drinke [914] and somtyme for 
<PB REF="00000718.tif" N="684"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="668"> vileyns &thorn;ou&yogh;tes &thorn;at bene enclosed in mannes mynde whan he goo&thorn; to sclepe which may not bene wi&thorn;-outen synne fro whiche &thorn;ei may not kepe hem wisely or ellis may men synne ful greuously</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; Remedium <I>contra</I> luxuriam</HEAD>
<P>[915] &para; Now comme&thorn; &thorn;e remedy a&yogh;einst leccherie and &thorn;at is generalli chaastite and contynence at re|freyne&thorn; al &thorn;e disordeyne meuyngges &thorn;at commen of flesshly talentes [916] And euere &thorn;e gretter merite shal he haue &thorn;at most restreyne&thorn; &thorn;e wikked enchaw|finge of ordure of &thorn;is synne and this is in two maners / &thorn;at is to sayn. chaastite of mariage and chastite of widowhede [917] &para; Now shalt &thorn;ou here &thorn;at matrimoyne is leeful assemblyng of man and woman &thorn;at resceyuen by &thorn;e vertue of &thorn;e sacrement &thorn;e boond &thorn;orgh which &thorn;ei may not bene departed in all hir liff &thorn;at is to say. &thorn;e whiles &thorn;ei lyuen bo&thorn;. [918] this is as / sei&thorn; &thorn;e book a ful grete sacrament. god made it as I haue saide in paradis and wold hym|self be born in maryage. [919] and for [to] halowe mariage he was at a weddinge. Where as he turned water into wyne which was &thorn;e furst myracle &thorn;at he wrou&yogh;t in er&thorn;e byforn his disciples. [920] Trewe effecte of mariage clense&thorn; fornicacion &amp; replenysshe&thorn; holy church in good lynage. ffor as &thorn;e ende of mariage as it chaunge&thorn; dedly synne into venial ytwix hem &thorn;at bene wedded / and make&thorn; &thorn;e hertys allon of hem &thorn;at bene ywedded as wel as the bodies [921] &thorn;is is verrey mariage &thorn;at is established by god er &thorn;at synne bygan. whan naturel lawe was in his ri&yogh;t poynt in paradys. And it was ordeyned &thorn;at oo man shuld haue but oo womman and oo womman but oo man as sei&thorn;e seynt Austyne by mony resons<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Augustinus</NOTE></P>
<P>[922] ffurst for &thorn;at mariage is figured bitwix man. and 
<PB REF="00000719.tif" N="685"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="669"> holy churche. And ano&thorn;er is. for &thorn;e man is hede of &thorn;e womman. Algate by ordynaunce it shulde be doo soo. [923] ffor if a womman haue moo men &thorn;an oon. &thorn;an shuld she haue moo hedes &thorn;an oon. and &thorn;at were and horrible &thorn;inge byfore god./ <MILESTONE N="301b" UNIT="folio">And eke oon womman ne my&yogh;t not plese to mony men at ones And also &thorn;er ne shuld be neuer pees no rest amonges hem for euereche wold aske his owne &thorn;inge [924] And fer&thorn;ermore no man shulde knowe his owne en|gendrure ne who shuld haue his heritage and &thorn;e woman shuld &thorn;e lasse be byloued fro &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at she were commytte to mony men</P>
<P>[925] &para; Nowe commeth how &thorn;at a man shuld bere hym wi&thorn; hys wiff. and/ namely in two &thorn;ingges &thorn;at is to say in suffrannce and in reuerence and &thorn;at shewed first crist whan he made furst womman [926] ffor he ne made her nou&yogh;t of &thorn;e hede of Adam. for / she shulde not haue to grete lordship. [927] ffor &thorn;er as &thorn;e womman ha&thorn; &thorn;e maistrie she make&thorn; to mochel disaraye &thorn;er neden noon ensamples of &thorn;is. The experience of &thorn;is au&yogh;t suffise [928] &para; Also certes god ne made not womman of &thorn;e foote of Adam for she shuld not be holden to lowe for she can not pacyently suffre But god made womman of the ribbe of Adam for womman shulde be felawe vnto man [929] &para; Man shulde bere hym to his wiff in fei&thorn;. in trou&thorn;e an in loue. as sei&thorn; seint paule that a man shal loue his wiff as crist loued<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Paulus./</NOTE> holy chirch &thorn;at loued it so wel &thorn;at he dyed for it. So shal a man for his wiff if it were nede</P>
<P>[930] &para; Now how &thorn;at a womman shuld be subiecte to her husbond &thorn;at telle&thorn; seint Peter / . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Petrus</NOTE> in the MS.</NOTE> [931] and eke as sei&thorn;e &thorn;e decree. A womman as longe as she is a wiff she ne ha&thorn; noon auctorite to swere ne bere witnesse wi&thorn;-out leue of her husbonde &thorn;at is her lord it shuld be so by reson. [932] she shulde eke serue hym in all 
<PB REF="00000720.tif" N="686"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="670"> honeste and bene attempre. of her aray I woot well &thorn;at &thorn;ei shulden setten her entent to plese her hus|bondes but not by her queyntise of aray./ [933] Seynt Ierom sei&thorn;. &thorn;at wyves &thorn;at bene apparalled in silk and<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ieronimus</NOTE> in purpure ne mowe not clo&thorn;en hem in Ihesu crist . . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [934] &para; Seynt Gregor sei&thorn; eke &thorn;at no wi&yogh;t seke&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; gregorius./</NOTE> precious aray but oonly for veynglorie to bene honoured &thorn;e more toforn &thorn;e puple [935] &para; It is a foly a womman to haue a grete aray outward and her self be foule inward [936] &para; A wiff shuld eke be mesurable in lokynge and in berynge and / in laughinge and discrete in all her wordes and dedys [937] and / abouen alle worldly &thorn;ingges. She shulde loue her husbonde wi&thorn; al her herte and to hym by trewe of her body [938] <MILESTONE N="302a" UNIT="folio">So shuld an husbonde eke by trewe to his wif. ffor si&thorn;ens &thorn;at al &thorn;e body is &thorn;e husbondes. soo shuld her hertes bene oon Or ellis &thorn;er is bytwix hem twoo as in &thorn;at no parfite mariage [939] &para; Than shal a man vnder|stond &thorn;at for iij. &thorn;ingges a man and his wiff mowen assemblen &para; The furst is for engen|drure of children to serue god. ffor certes &thorn;at is &thorn;e cause fynall of matrimoynye [940] &para; Ano&thorn;er is to &yogh;eelde eueriche of hem to o&thorn;er &thorn;e dette of her body. ffor nei&thorn;er of hem ha&thorn; power of her owne bodye &para; The iij. is forto eschewe leccherye and vilenye &para; The iiij. forso&thorn; is dedly synne./ [941] As to &thorn;e furst it is meritorie &thorn;e seconnde also for as sai&thorn;e &thorn;e decree. &thorn;at chase&thorn; merite of chaastite &thorn;at &yogh;elde&thorn; to her husbonde &thorn;e dette of her body. &yogh;e &thorn;ou&yogh;e it be a&yogh;einst her lykinge and &thorn;e lust of her herte [942] &para; The iij. manere of venial synne. And trewly scarcely may eny of &thorn;ise be wi&thorn;-outen venyal synne for &thorn;e corrupcion and for &thorn;e delite [943] &para; The iiij. manere is forto vnderstonde if &thorn;ei assemble oonly for amerous loue. and for noon of &thorn;e forsaide causes but 
<PB REF="00000721.tif" N="687"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="671"> forto accomplise &thorn;ilk brennyng delite &thorn;ei rech neuere hou often &middot; so&thorn;ly it is a dedly synne. And &yogh;it wi&thorn; sorowe some folk wil peynen hem more to doo &thorn;an her appetit suffise&thorn;</P>
<P>[944] &para; The secounde maner of chastite is to be a clene wydowe and to eschewe &thorn;e enbrasing of man and to desire &thorn;e enbrasing of Ihesu crist. [945] Thise bene &thorn;oo &thorn;at han ben wyues and han forgoon her hus|bondes And eke wommen &thorn;at han / doon lecherye and bene releued by penaunce [946] And certes if &thorn;at a wiff cou&thorn;e kepe her al chaast by licence of her husbonde so &thorn;at she ner noon occasion &thorn;at he a-gilt it were to hir a grete merite [947] Thise maner of wommen &thorn;at obseruen chaastitee most be clene in herte as wel as in body and in &thorn;ou&yogh;t and mesurable in clo&thorn;inge and in contynaunce &para; Abstynent in etynge and drynkynge in spekinge and in dede and &thorn;an is she &thorn;e vessell of &thorn;e boyst of &thorn;e blessed Mawdeleyne &thorn;at fulfille&thorn; holy church ful of good odure [948] &para; The iij. maner of chaastite is virgynyte. And it byhoue&thorn; &thorn;at she be holy in hert and clene of body &thorn;an is she spouse to Ihesu crist and she is &thorn;e lif of aungels. [949] She is &thorn;e preysyng of &thorn;is world And she is as &thorn;ise marters in regalite <MILESTONE N="302b" UNIT="folio">she ha&thorn; in hure &thorn;at tunge may not telle [950] Virgynite bare our lorde Ihesu crist and virgyne was hymself</P>
<P>[951] &para; Another remedy a&yogh;einst lecherye is specialy to wi&thorn;drawe such &thorn;ingges as &yogh;euen occasion to &thorn;ilk vilanye as ease and etynge and drinkinge. ffor certes whan &thorn;e potte boyle&thorn; strongly &thorn;e best remedy is to wi&thorn;|drawe &thorn;e fuyre [952] &para; Scleping longe in grete quiete is eke a grete norice to leccherie</P>
<P>[953] &para; Another remedye a&yogh;einst lecherie is &thorn;at a womman or a man eschewe companye of hem by which he doute&thorn; to be tempted. for al be it soo &thorn;at &thorn;e dede be wi&thorn;-stonde &yogh;it is &thorn;ere grete temptacion 
<PB REF="00000722.tif" N="688"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="672"> [954] &para; So&thorn;ly a white wall al-&thorn;ou&yogh;e it ne brenne not fully by stikkynge of a Candell &yogh;it is &thorn;e walle blak of &thorn;e leyte [955] ful oft tyme I rede &thorn;at no man trest in his owne perfeccion But he be strenger &thorn;an Sampson. Holyer &thorn;an david. wiser &thorn;an &para; Salomon</P>
<P>[956] &para; Now after &thorn;at I haue declared &yogh;ou as I can of &thorn;e vij. dedly synnes and some of her braunches and her remedies. so&thorn;ly if I cou&thorn;e I wold telle &yogh;owe &thorn;e ten Comaundementz. [957] but so hi&yogh;e a doctrine I lete to devynes. Na&thorn;elees I hope to god &thorn;ei bene touched in &thorn;is tretys euerech of hem alle</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; De confessione;</HEAD>
<P>[958]</P>
<P>NOW for as moche as &thorn;e secounde part of penitence<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Confessioun</NOTE> stant in confession of mou&thorn; as I byganne in &thorn;e [first] chapitere I seye Seint Austyn sei&thorn;.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Augustinus</NOTE> [959] Synne is euery word and euery dede and al &thorn;at men coueiten a&yogh;einst &thorn;e lawe of Ihesu crist. And &thorn;is is forto synne. in herte in mou&thorn; and in dede be &thorn;i .v. wittes &thorn;at bene si&yogh;t hering smellynge taasting or sauouringe and felynge [960] &para; Now is it good to vnderstonde &thorn;e circumstances &thorn;at aggreggen mochel euery synne./ [961] &para; Thow shalt considere what &thorn;ou art &thorn;at dost &thorn;e synne. whedere &thorn;ou be male or female. &yogh;ong or olde. gentile or &thorn;rall ffre or seruaunte. hool or seke. wedded or syngell. Ordred or vnordred. wise or fool. clerk or Seculere. [962] If she be of &thorn;i kynrede bodily or goostly or noon. If eny of &thorn;i kynrede haue synned wi&thorn; hure or noon. and mony moo/ &thorn;ingges</P>
<P>[963] &para; That other circumstaunce is this. Whedere it be doon in fornicacion or noon. or in aduoutrie. or in incest. or noon maiden / or noon in maner of homicede or noon horrible grete synne or smale. and how longe &thorn;ou <MILESTONE N="303a" UNIT="folio">hast contynued in synne [964] &para; The iij. circumstaunce is &thorn;e place where &thorn;ou hast doon synne whedere in o&thorn;er 
<PB REF="00000723.tif" N="689"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="673"> mennys house or in &thorn;ine owne. in feeld or in church. or in chirch hawe In church dedicate or noon [965] For if &thorn;e church were halowed and man or womman spillen her kynde in wi&thorn; &thorn;at place by-twene way of synne or by wikked temptacion &thorn;e church were enterdited til it were reconsiled by &thorn;e bisshope [966] and &thorn;e preest shuld be enterdited &thorn;at did such a vilany &thorn;e teerme of al his liff. he shuld no more synge masse. and if he did he shuld do dedly synne at euery tyme &thorn;at he songe masse [967] &para; The 4. circumstannce is by which mediat|ours as by massagers or for enticement or for consentement to bere company wi&thorn; felawship for mony a wrecch forto bere companye willen goo to &thorn;e deuel of helle. [968] ffor &thorn;ei &thorn;at eggen or con|senten to &thorn;e synne bene partniers of &thorn;e synne and of &thorn;e dampnacion of &thorn;e synnere</P>
<P>[969] &para; The .v. is of how mony tymes &thorn;at he ha&thorn; synned and / it be in his mynde. and howe oft &thorn;at he ha&thorn; falle. [970] ffor he &thorn;at oft falle&thorn; in synne he despise&thorn; &thorn;e mercy of god and encrese&thorn; his synne and is vnkynde to god and he wexe&thorn; &thorn;e more feble to wi&thorn;stonde synne. and synne&thorn; &thorn;e more li&yogh;tlier [971] and &thorn;e latter arise&thorn;. and is &thorn;e more eschewe for to schryuen hym and namely to hym &thorn;at ha&thorn; bene his con|fessoure. [972] ffor which &thorn;at folk whan &thorn;ei falle a&yogh;ein in her old folies. ou&yogh;t &thorn;ei forleten her confessours al vtterly or ellis &thorn;ei departen her shrift in dyuers place But so&thorn;ly such departed shrift deserue&thorn; no mercy of god of his synnes. [973] &para; The sext circum|stannce is &thorn;is why &thorn;at a man synne&thorn; as by whiche temptacion And if hym self procure &thorn;ilk temptacion or by ex|cityng of o&thorn;er folk. or if &thorn;ou synne with a womman by force or by hure owne assent [974] /Or if &thorn;e womman Maugre her hede ha&thorn; bene enforsed or noon. &thorn;is shal she telle for coueityse or for pouert. And if it were her procurynge or noon and such manere 
<PB REF="00000724.tif" N="690"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="674"> harnays. [975] &para; The .7. circumstaunce is in what manere he ha&thorn; doon his synne. or noon or / how &thorn;at he ha&thorn; suffred. howe folk han done to her. [976] Of &thorn;e same shal men telle pleynly all circumstannces and whedere he ha&thorn; synned wi&thorn; comune bordell wommen or noon [977] <MILESTONE N="303b" UNIT="folio">or do his synne in holy tymes or non. In fast|yng tymes or non. or be longe from his shrift. or after his latter schrift [978] ha&thorn; perauenture broken his penaunce enioyned. by whos helpe and whoos counsaile by sorcery or craft all &thorn;ise &thorn;ingges mosten be tolde. [979] After &thorn;at &thorn;ei bene grete or smale engreggen &thorn;e conscience of man &para; And eke &thorn;e preest &thorn;at is &thorn;i Iuge may &thorn;e better be auysed of his Iuggement in &yogh;euyng of &thorn;i penaunce and &thorn;at is after &thorn;i contricion. [980] ffor vnderstonde&thorn; wel &thorn;at aftere tyme &thorn;at a man hath defouled his bapteme by synne if he wil come to sauacion. ther nys noon o&thorn;er way but by penitence and schrift and by satisfaccion / [981] and namely by &thorn;e two if &thorn;er be a confessour to which he may schryve hym. And &thorn;e iij. if he haue lif to perfourme it</P>
<P>[982] Than shal man loke and considere if he wil make a trewe and a profitable confession. Ther most be 4. condici&omacr;ns [983] &para; ffirst it most be in sorowful bitternes of herte as seide &thorn;e kyng Ezechiell to god &para; I wil remembre all &thorn;e &yogh;eeres of my liff in bitternesse of myn herte [984] &para; This condycion of bitter|nesse ha&thorn; .v. signes. The furst is &thorn;at confession most be shamefast not forto keueren ne to hiden his synne but for he ha&thorn; agilt his god and defoiled/ his soule [985] And here of sei&thorn; seynt Austyne &para; The herte<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Augustinus</NOTE> travaille&thorn; for shame of his synne. And for he hath grete shamfastnesse he is digne to haue grete mercie [986] which was &thorn;e confession of &thorn;e publycane &thorn;at wold not heue vp his yen to heuene for he had offended god in heuene. ffor which shamefastnesse he had anoon &thorn;e mercy of god [987] &para; And therfore sei&thorn; 
<PB REF="00000725.tif" N="691"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="675"> seint Austyne. &thorn;at such shamefast folk bene next for&yogh;euenes and remission [988] &para; That o&thorn;er signe is humylite of confessi&omacr;n / of which sei&thorn; seint Petre<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Petrus</NOTE> &para; Vmble&thorn; &yogh;ou vnder &thorn;e my&yogh;t of god &thorn;e hand of god is my&yogh;ty in confession for &thorn;er-by god for&yogh;eue&thorn; &thorn;e synnes. ffor he allon ha&thorn; &thorn;e power / [989] and &thorn;is humilite shal be in hert and in sygne outward &para; ffor ri&yogh;t as he ha&thorn; humilite to god in his herte Ri&yogh;t so shulde he humble his body outward to &thorn;e preest &thorn;at sitte in goddes place [990] for which in no manere si&thorn;es &thorn;at crist is souereyne and / <MILESTONE N="304a" UNIT="folio">&thorn;e preest mene and mediatour by twix crist and &thorn;e synner. and &thorn;e synner is &thorn;e last by way of reson [991] &thorn;an shuld not &thorn;e synner sitte as high as his confessoure but knele toforn hym or at his fete but if malady distroubed it. ffor he shal not take kepe who sitte &thorn;er but in whos place &thorn;at he sitte&thorn;. [992] A man &thorn;at ha&thorn; trespased to a lorde and comme&thorn; for to aske mercy and maken his accorde and sette hym downe a-noon by &thorn;e lorde men wolden holde hym outrageous and not wor&thorn;i so sone forto haue remission ne mercy. [993] &para; The iij. signe is &thorn;at &thorn;i shrift shul be ful of teeres if man may wepe or if man may not wepe wi&thorn; his bodely eyen./ lat hym wepe in his herte. [994] ffor suche was &thorn;e confession of seynt petre ffor aftere &thorn;at he had forsake Ihesu crist he went out and wepte ful bitterly [995] &para; The iiij. signe is &thorn;at he ne lette not for his / shame to shewen his confession. [996] Such was &thorn;e confession of &thorn;e maudeleyn &thorn;at sche ne spared for no shame of hem &thorn;at weren at &thorn;e ffeest forto go to our lorde Ihesu crist and byknowe to hym her synne [997] &para; The .v. signe is &thorn;at a man &amp; a womman be obeysaunte to receyue &thorn;e penaunce &thorn;at is hym enioyned. ffor certes Ihesu crist for &thorn;e giltes of oon man was obedient to his de&thorn;e</P>
<P>[998] &para; The secounde condicion of verrey confession<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; 2<SUP>a</SUP> condicio./</NOTE> is &thorn;at it be hastely don. ffor certes if a man had a dedly wounde; euer &thorn;e lenger &thorn;at he tarie&thorn; to warisshe 
<PB REF="00000726.tif" N="692"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="676"> him self &thorn;e more wold it corrupte and hast hym to his de&thorn;e and eke &thorn;e wounde wold be &thorn;e wors forto hele [999] &para; And ri&yogh;t so fare&thorn; synne &thorn;at longe tyme is in a man vnschewed [1000] &para; Certes a man ou&yogh;t hastely to shewe his synne. for mony causes as for drede of de&thorn;e &thorn;at comme&thorn; often sodeynly and is in no certeyn what tyme it shal be ne in what place. And eke &thorn;e strecchyng of oo synne drawe&thorn; in ano&thorn;er [1001] &para; And eke &thorn;e lenger &thorn;at he tarieth; &thorn;e fer&thorn;er is he from crist. And if he abide vnto his last day scarcely may he shryve hym or amende hym of his synnes ne repenten hym for &thorn;e greuous maladye of his deth. [1002] &amp; for as moche as he ha&thorn; not in his lif herkened Ihesu Crist whan he ha&thorn; spoken vnto hym. he shal crien to our lord Ihesu crist at his last day. and scarcely wil he harken hym [1003] &para; Vnder-stonde &thorn;at &thorn;is condicion moste haue four &thorn;ingges <MILESTONE N="304b" UNIT="folio">thi schrift most be purueide byforn and avised for wikked hast doo&thorn; no profite and &thorn;at a man konne shryue hym of his synnes be it of pride ei&thorn;er of Envie and so for&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;e spices and circumstaunces / [1004] and &thorn;at he haue comprehended / in his mynde &thorn;e nombre and &thorn;e gretnesse of his synnes and/ how longe &thorn;at he ha&thorn; layne in synne [1005] and eke &thorn;at he be contrite of his synnes and in stedfast purpoos by &thorn;e [grace of god] neuere eft to falle a&yogh;ein in synne and eke &thorn;at he drede and countrewaite hym self &thorn;at he flee &thorn;e occasions of synne to which he is enclyned [1006] &para; Also &thorn;at &thorn;ow shalt schryve &thorn;e of alle &thorn;i synnes to oo man and nou&yogh;t parcell mele to oon man and parsel mele to a no&thorn;er man &thorn;at is to vnderstonde in entent to parten &thorn;i confession as for shame or for drede. ffor it nys but stronglyng of &thorn;e soule [1007] ffor certes Ihesu crist is al good in hym is noon inperfeccion and &thorn;erfore euere he for&yogh;eue&thorn; alle parfitly or ellis neuere a dele [1008] &para; I say not if &thorn;owe be sygned to &thorn;e penytauncere for certeyn synne &thorn;at &thorn;ou art bounden to shewe hem all &thorn;e remenaunt of &thorn;i synnes of which 
<PB REF="00000727.tif" N="693"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="677"> &thorn;owe hast be shryuen of &thorn;i curate but it like &thorn;e of &thorn;ine humilite This is no departing of shrift [1009] ne I ne say not &thorn;er as I speke of dyuision of confes|sion &thorn;at if &thorn;ou haue licence. forto shryue &thorn;e to a discrete and honest preest and where &thorn;e like&thorn; / and by &thorn;e licence eke of &thorn;e curate &thorn;at &thorn;owe ne maiste wel shryue &thorn;e of alle &thorn;i synnes [1010] but lat no blot be behynde. lat no synne be vntold as fer as &thorn;ou hast remem|braunce [1011] And whan &thorn;ou shalt bene shryuen of &thorn;i Curate telle hym eke of alle &thorn;e synnes &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast done si&thorn;ens &thorn;ou were last yshriuen as &thorn;is is &thorn;e wikked entent of dyuision of shrift</P>
<P>[1012] &para; Also &thorn;e verrey shrift aske&thorn; certeyn con|dicions. ffurst &thorn;at &thorn;ou shryue &thorn;e by &thorn;i free wille not constreyned ne for shame of folk ne for maladie or such &thorn;ingges ffor it is reson &thorn;at he &thorn;at trespase&thorn; by his ffree wille / . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> confesse his trespas. [1013] noon o&thorn;er man shal telle his synne but he hym self ne he shal not nay or denye his synne ne wra&thorn;e him a&yogh;einst &thorn;e preest for his amonysynge to lete synne [1014] &para; The seconnde condicion is &thorn;at &thorn;ine shrift be lawfull. &thorn;at is to say &thorn;ou &thorn;at shryuest &thorn;e and eke &thorn;e preest &thorn;at here&thorn; &thorn;i confession bene verrely <MILESTONE N="305a" UNIT="folio">in &thorn;e fei&thorn; of holy church [1015] and &thorn;at a man be not despeired. of &thorn;e mercy of Ihesu Crist And Caym or Iudas [1016] And eke a [man] mote accuse hym of his owne trespace and nou&yogh;t ano&thorn;er but he shal blame &amp; witen hym self of his owne malice of his synne and noon o&thorn;er. [1017] But na&thorn;eles if ano&thorn;er man be encheson or entiser of his synnes Or &thorn;at if &thorn;e state of a persone be such thorgh which his synne is a-gregged or ellis &thorn;at he may not pleynly shryuen hym. but he telle &thorn;e persone &thorn;e which he ha&thorn; synned wi&thorn;e. &thorn;an may he telle it [1018] so &thorn;at his entent ne be not to bakbite &thorn;e persone but oonly to declaren his con|fession.
<PB REF="00000728.tif" N="694"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="678"></P>
<P>[1019] &para; Thowe &thorn;e shalt not eke make no lesing in &thorn;ine confession for humilite parauenture to say &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast doon synnes of which &thorn;ou were neuere gylty [1020] &para; ffor seint Austyn sei&thorn; if<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Augustinus./</NOTE> &thorn;ow be cause of humilite makest lesing of &thorn;i self &thorn;ough &thorn;owe ne were nou&yogh;t in synne aforn; &yogh;it art &thorn;owe &thorn;an in synne &thorn;orgh &thorn;i lesynges. [1021] Thow most eke shewe &thorn;i synne by &thorn;i propre mou&thorn;e but &thorn;ou be wexe dombe and not by no letter ffor &thorn;ou &thorn;at hast done synne &thorn;ou shalt haue &thorn;e same confessir [1022] &para; Thow shalt not eke peynt &thorn;i confession be faire and subtile wordes to keuere more &thorn;i synne ffor &thorn;an bygilest &thorn;ou &thorn;i self &amp; nought &thorn;e preest. Thow most tel it platly be it neuere so foule ne so horrible [1023] &para; Thow shalt eke shryue &thorn;e to a preest &thorn;at is discrete to counsaile &thorn;ee. and eke &thorn;ou shalt not shryue &thorn;e for veynglorie ne for ypocrecy ne for no cause but oonly for &thorn;e doute of Ihesu crist and &thorn;e hel&thorn;e of &thorn;i soule. [1024] Thow shalt not eke renne to &thorn;e preest al sodeynly to telle hym li&yogh;tly &thorn;i synne as who so telle&thorn; a Iape or a tale but avisely and wi&thorn; grete deuocion [1025] &amp; generally shryve &thorn;e oft if &thorn;ou often falle oft arise by confession [1026] And if &thorn;ow shryue &thorn;e ofter &thorn;an onys of synne which &thorn;ou hast be shryuen it is &thorn;e more merite as sei&thorn; seint Austyne. Thow<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Augustinus</NOTE> shalt haue &thorn;e more lightly relesinge and grace of god bo&thorn;e of synne and of peyne. [1027] And certes onys a &yogh;ere at &thorn;e leest way it is lawful forto bene howseled. ffor so&thorn;ly onys [a &yogh;ere] al &thorn;ingges renouellen</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De satisfaccione.</HEAD>
<P>[1028]</P>
<P>NOw haue I tolde of verrey confession &thorn;at is &thorn;e Secounde part of penytence
<PB REF="00000729.tif" N="695"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="679"></P>
<P>[1029] &para; The iij. parte of penytence is Satisfaccion and<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Satisfaccio</NOTE> &thorn;at stant generalli in almesse and in bodily peyne. [1030] Nowe bene &thorn;ere &thorn;re manere of Almesse. Contricion of hert wher a man offre&thorn; hym self to god. Ano&thorn;er is to haue pite of &thorn;e defaute of his neighbours. &thorn;e <MILESTONE N="305b" UNIT="folio">3 is in &yogh;euyng of good counsaile and confort goostly and bodily where men han nede and namely in sustynaunce of mannys foode. [1031] And take kepe &thorn;at a man ha&thorn; nede of &thorn;ise &thorn;ingges generalli he ha&thorn; nede of foode of clo&thorn;inge and harborowe. he ha&thorn; / nede of charitable counsaillinge and visitynge of prison and / maladie and sepulture of his dede body. [1032] And if &thorn;ow maist not visite &thorn;e nedeful wi&thorn; &thorn;i persone. visite hym with &thorn;i massage &amp; / &thorn;i &yogh;iftes [1033] &para; Thise bene &thorn;e generall almasses or werkes of charite of hem &thorn;at han temporell richesses or discrecion of consailling Of &thorn;ise werkes shalt &thorn;ou here at &thorn;e day of dome</P>
<P>[1034] &para; Thise almesses shuldest &thorn;ou doon of &thorn;ine owne propre &thorn;ingges and hastely and / prively if &thorn;ou maist [1035] But na&thorn;elees if &thorn;ow maist not doon it prively &thorn;ou shalt not forbere almesse &thorn;ou&yogh;e men it See. So &thorn;at it be not ydo for &thorn;onke of &thorn;e worlde. but oonly forto haue &thorn;e &thorn;onke of oure / lorde Ihesu crist [1036] &para; ffor as witnesse&thorn; seint Mathewe .v<SUP>o</SUP>. A. Cite may not be hid<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Matthei. v<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE> &thorn;at is sette on a mounteyn. ne men lighten not a lanterne and putte it vnder a busshell. but men sette it on a candel|stik to lighten &thorn;e men in &thorn;e hous. [1037] Ri&yogh;t so shal &yogh;oure li&yogh;t li&yogh;ten toforn men &thorn;at &thorn;ei mowe seen &yogh;oure good werkes and glorifien &yogh;our fadere &thorn;at is in heuene</P>
<P>[1038] &para; Now as to speken of bodily peyne. It stont in preiers. in wakingges and in fastingges and in vertuous 
<PB REF="00000730.tif" N="696"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="680"> techingges of orisons [1039] &para; &yogh;e shul vnderstonde &thorn;at orisons or preiers is / forto seyn a pitous wille of hert &thorn;at redresse&thorn; in god and expresse&thorn; it by worde outward to remooue harmlees. and to han &thorn;inges espirituel and durable. and somtyme temporel &thorn;ingges of which orisons certes &thorn;e orison of &thorn;e pater noster ha&thorn; Ihesu crist enclosed most &thorn;ingges [1040] &para; Certes it is priuilegged of .3. &thorn;ingges. in his dignite ffor which it is more digne &thorn;an eny o&thorn;er preiere for &thorn;at ihesu crist hym self made it. [1041] and it is short for it shuld be conned more li&yogh;tly and forto wi&thorn;holde it &thorn;e more esely in herte and helpen hym self &thorn;e ofter wi&thorn; &thorn;e orison [1042] and for a man shuld be &thorn;e lasse wery to sey it / and for a man ne may not excusen hym to lerne it it is so short and so esy. and for it comprehendeth in it self alle good preiers [1043] &para; The exposicion of &thorn;is holy preier &thorn;at is so excellent and digne I bytake to &thorn;ise maisters of theologie sauf &thorn;us moche wil I seyne. &thorn;at whan &thorn;ou preiest &thorn;at god / for&yogh;eue &thorn;e &thorn;i giltes as &thorn;ou for&yogh;euest hem &thorn;at a-gilten &thorn;e be ful wel ware &thorn;at &thorn;ow ne be not out of charite [1044] This holy <MILESTONE N="306a" UNIT="folio">orison amenuse&thorn; eke venyal synne and &thorn;erfore it aperteneth specialy to penitence.</P>
<P>[1045] This preiere most be trewly saide in verrey fei&thorn; and &thorn;at men prey to god ordynatly &amp; discretely and deuoutly. Alway a man shal putt his will to be subiecte to &thorn;e wille of god [1046] This orison most eke be saide wi&thorn; gret humblesse and ful pure honesty and not to annoyance of eny man or womman. It most nedes be contynued with &thorn;e werkes of charite [1047] it availle&thorn; eke a&yogh;einst &thorn;e vices of &thorn;e saule. ffor as sei&thorn; seynt Ierom &para; By fastyng ben saued &thorn;e vices of<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ieronimus</NOTE> flessh and by preiers &thorn;e vices of &thorn;e saule</P>
<P>[1048] &para; Aftere &thorn;is &thorn;ou shalt vnderstonde &thorn;at bodily peyne stant in wakinge. ffor Ihesu crist sei&thorn;.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ihe/</NOTE> wake&thorn; and preie&thorn; &thorn;at &yogh;e ne entre in wikked 
<PB REF="00000731.tif" N="697"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="681"> temptaci&omacr;ns [1049] &para; &yogh;e shul vnderstonde &thorn;at fast|ynge stont in .3. thyngges. In forberynge of bodily mete and drink and in forberynge of worldly Iolitees. and in for|berynge of dedly synne. This is to say &thorn;at a man shal kepe hym / from dedly synne with al his my&yogh;t.</P>
<P>[1050] And &thorn;ow shalt vnderstonde eke &thorn;at god ordayned fastyngges And to fastyng apperteneth four &thorn;ingges. [1051] largenesse to poor folk. Gladnes of hert espirituell nou&yogh;t to be angred nor anoyed ne to gruch for he fasteth and also resonable houre forto ete by mesure. &thorn;at is to say &thorn;at a man shuld not eten in vntyme. ne sitte &thorn;e lenger at his table for he faste&thorn;.</P>
<P>[1052] Than shalt &thorn;ou vnderstonde &thorn;at bodily peyne stant. in disciplyne or techynge. by word or by // writynge or by ensample Also in weryng of heires. ei&thorn;er of stamyne ei&thorn;er of haberion on her naked flessh for cristes sake and such manere penaunces [1053] &para; But ware &thorn;e wel &thorn;at such manere penaunces ne make not &thorn;ine hert bitter or angry. anoyed of hym self. ffor better is to cast away &thorn;ine heire. &thorn;an forto cast away &thorn;e swetnesse of our lord Ihesu Crist [1054] And &thorn;erfore sei&thorn; seint Poule<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Paulus./</NOTE> &para; Clo&thorn;e &yogh;ou as &thorn;ei &thorn;at ben chosen of god in hert of mysericord. debonairte. suffrance and such maner of clo&thorn;inge of whiche Ihesu crist is more apaide &thorn;an of heire or of hawberkes.</P>
<P>[1055] Then is disciplyne eke in knokkynge of &thorn;i brest. in scourgyng wi&thorn; &yogh;eerdes. in knelynge in tribulacions [1056] in suffryng paciently wrongges &thorn;at bene doon to hym. and eke in pacient suffraunce of maladies or lesyngges. of worldly Catell of wiff or childe or o&thorn;er <MILESTONE N="306b" UNIT="folio">frendes</P>
<P>[1057] Than shalt &thorn;ow vnderstonde which &thorn;ingges distrowben penaunce as &thorn;is is in &thorn;re maners. &thorn;at is drede. Shame. and hope. And whanhope &thorn;at is desperacion. [1058] And forto speken / furst of drede for whiche he 
<PB REF="00000732.tif" N="698"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="682"> wene&thorn; &thorn;at he may suffre no penaunce [1059] &thorn;er a&yogh;einst is remedye fforto &thorn;enk &thorn;at bodily penaunce. is but short and litell at &thorn;e regarde of &thorn;e peyne of helle. &thorn;at is cruel and so longe &thorn;at it laste&thorn; wi&thorn;-outen ende.</P>
<P>[1060] &para; Now a&yogh;einst &thorn;e shame &thorn;at a man ha&thorn; to shryuen hym . . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [1061] a&yogh;einst &thorn;e shame shuld a man &thorn;enk &thorn;at by &thorn;e way of reson &thorn;at he &thorn;at ha&thorn; not bene ashamed. to doo foule &thorn;ingges Certes hym ou&yogh;t not be ashamed to doo fair &thorn;ingges and good &thorn;ingges and &thorn;at is confessions. [1062] A man shuld &thorn;enk &thorn;at god see&thorn; and woote al his &thorn;ou&yogh;tes and his werkes to hym may no &thorn;inge be hidde ne keuered [1063] &para; Men shuld eke remembre hem of &thorn;e shame &thorn;at is to come at &thorn;e day of dome to hem &thorn;at bene nou&yogh;t penytent and lif in present liff. [1064] ffor alle &thorn;e creatures in heuene in er&thorn;e and in helle shuln seen / apertly al &thorn;at &thorn;ei hyden in &thorn;is world.</P>
<P>[1065] &para; Now forto speke of &thorn;e hope of hem &thorn;at bene so negligent and sclowe to shryuen hem it stant in two maners. [1066] That oon is &thorn;at he hope&thorn; to lyve longe and forto purchase mochel Richesse for his delite and &thorn;an he wil shryuen hym as he sei&thorn; he may as hym seme&thorn; tymely ynowe come to shrift [1067] &para; Ano&thorn;er is of &thorn;e Surquidrye &thorn;at he ha&thorn; in cristes mercye. [1068] And a&yogh;einst &thorn;e first he shal &thorn;enk that our liff is in no sikernesse And eke &thorn;at alle &thorn;e richesse of &thorn;e world bene in aduenture and passinge as a shadowe on a walle [1069] &para; And as sei&thorn; seynt gregorie<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Gregorius./.</NOTE> That it appertene&thorn; to &thorn;e grete ri&yogh;twisnesse of god &thorn;at neuer shal &thorn;e peyn stynt of hem &thorn;at neuer nolde wi&thorn;drawe hem from synne her &thorn;onkes. but euer contynued &thorn;er Inne. &para; ffor &thorn;ilk perpetuel wille to done synne shullen &thorn;ei haue perpetuel peyne.</P>
<P>[1070] &para; Whan-hope is in two maners &para; &thorn;e furst whan|hope<NOTE PLACE="marg">Or Wanhope, or Despair</NOTE> is in &thorn;e mercy of Crist &para; That o&thorn;er is &thorn;at &thorn;ei 
<PB REF="00000733.tif" N="699"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="683"> &thorn;enk &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne my&yogh;t not longe perseuere in good|nesse [1071] &para; The furst wanhope comme&thorn; of &thorn;at he deme&thorn; &thorn;at he hath synned so gretly so ofte and so longe liggyng in synne &thorn;at he shal not be saued [1072] &para; Certes a&yogh;einst &thorn;at cursed wanhope he shuld &thorn;enk &thorn;at &thorn;e passion of Ihesu crist is more <MILESTONE N="307a" UNIT="folio">stronge for|to vnbynde &thorn;an synne is forto bynde [1073] &para; And a&yogh;einst &thorn;e seconnd wanhope he shal &thorn;enk &thorn;at as often as he falle&thorn; he shal arise by penytence. And &thorn;ou&yogh;e he neuer so long haue lyen in synne &thorn;e mercy of crist is alway redy to receyuen hym to mercy [1074] a&yogh;einst &thorn;e wanhope &thorn;at he deme&thorn; &thorn;at he shuld not longe perseuere in goodnesse &para; he shal &thorn;enk &thorn;at &thorn;e feblenesse of the deuel may no &thorn;ing doon but men willen suffre hym [1075] And eke he shal haue strength and &thorn;e helpe of god and of al holy churche and of &thorn;e protection of aungels if him lust</P>
<P>[1076] &para; Than shullen men vnderstonde what is &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Verba salua|toris</NOTE> fruyte of penaunce as aftere &thorn;e wordes of Ihesu Crist it is &thorn;e endelees blisse of heuene [1077] &thorn;er Ioie ha&thorn; no contrariouste of woo ne greuaunce &thorn;er alle harmes ben passed of &thorn;is present liff wher as is &thorn;e sikernesse fro &thorn;e peyn of helle &thorn;er as &thorn;e blisful company &thorn;at reioysen hem euermoo euery of o&thorn;ers Ioie [1078] &thorn;er as &thorn;e body of man &thorn;at whilom was foule and derk is more cleer &thorn;an &thorn;e sonne Ther as whilom &thorn;e body was seke and frele and feble and mortell is vnmortell and so stronge and so hool &thorn;at &thorn;er may no &thorn;inge enpeire it. [1079] wher as nei&thorn;er is hunger &thorn;rest. ne cold but euery soule repleynshed wi&thorn; &thorn;e si&yogh;t of &thorn;e parfit knowynge of god [1080] This blisful regne may man purchace by pouert espirituell and &thorn;e glorie by low|nesse. &thorn;e plente of Ioy by hunger and &thorn;rest. and &thorn;e rest by travaille and &thorn;e liff by dee&thorn; and mortificacion of synne.
<PB REF="00000734.tif" N="700"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="684"></P>
<P>To &thorn;ilk liff he vs bringe &thorn;at bou&yogh;t vs wi&thorn; his pre|cious blood./ Amen./</P>
<TRAILER>&para; Explicit fabula Rectoris./</TRAILER>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Here take&thorn; &thorn;e maker of &thorn;is booke his leue;/</HEAD>
<P>[1081]</P>
<P>NOwe prey I to hem alle &thorn;at harken &thorn;is litel tretise. or rede &thorn;at &yogh;if &thorn;er be eny &thorn;ing in it &thorn;at like&thorn; hem &thorn;at &thorn;erof &thorn;ei &thorn;onk our lord Ihesu crist of whom procede&thorn; al witte and al goodnes. [1082] And &yogh;if &thorn;er be eny &thorn;ing &thorn;at displese hem./ I prey hem also &thorn;at &thorn;ei arette it to &thorn;e defaute of myne vnkonnynge and not to my wille &thorn;at wold ful fayn haue seide better &yogh;if &thorn;at I had hade connynge. [1083] ffor our boke sei&thorn; &para; All &thorn;at is writen is writen for our doctrine &amp; &thorn;at is myn entent [1084] <MILESTONE N="307b" UNIT="folio">Wherfore I biseche &yogh;ou mekely for &thorn;e mercy of god &thorn;at &yogh;e prei for me &thorn;at crist haue mercy on me and for&yogh;eue me my geltys [1085] and namely of my translaci&omacr;ns and endit|ingges of worldly vanytes &thorn;e which I reuoke in my re|traccions [1086] As is &thorn;e boke of Troiles. The book also of fame. The boke of the xxv. ladies./ The boke of &thorn;e duchesse. The boke of seynt valentynes day of &thorn;e parlement of briddes. The tales of Canter|bury &thorn;ilk &thorn;at sownen into synne [1087] The book of &thorn;e ly&omacr;n and mony o&thorn;er bokes &yogh;if &thorn;ei were in my remembraunce. and mony a songe. And mony a lecherous lay &thorn;at Crist for his gret mercy for&yogh;eue me &thorn;e synne. [1088] &para; But of &thorn;e translacion of Boys de consolacione and o&thorn;er bokes of legendys of seyntes and omelies and moralite &amp; deuocion [1089] of &thorn;at I &thorn;onke our lord Ihesu crist and his blessed/ modere and alle &thorn;e seyntes of heuene [1090] bysechyng hem &thorn;at &thorn;ei from hens for&thorn; vnto my lyues ende sende me grace to bywaile my giltes and to stody to &thorn;e sauacion of my soule. and graunt me grace of verrey penaunce. con|fession 
<PB REF="00000735.tif" N="701"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="685"> and satisfaccion to doon in &thorn;is present liff [1091] &thorn;orghe &thorn;e benigne grace of hym &thorn;at is kyng of kyngges and preest of alle preestes &thorn;at bou&yogh;t vs wi&thorn; &thorn;e precious blode of his hert [1092] So &thorn;at I may bene oon of hem at &thorn;e day of dome &thorn;at shal be saued./ Qui cum patre &amp; spiritu sancto vivis &amp; regnas deus &amp;cetera.</P>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>Here ende&thorn; &thorn;e boke of &thorn;e talys of Canter|bury compiled by Geffray Chawcer on whoos soule Ihesu crist haue mercy. &Verbar; AmeN &Verbar;<NOTE PLACE="end">[<I>Square painting of the arms of Henry Percy,</I> 4<I>th Earl of Northumberland, K.G., quartering Poynings, Fitz Payn and Bryan.</I> H <I>on the right,</I> P <I>on the left of the shield, in a Garter with the legend</I> 'hony . soit . qui . mal . y . pence. .' <I>A lion, unicorn, &amp;c, in the</I> 4 <I>corners.</I>]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="B" TYPE="group">

<PB REF="00000736.tif" N="702">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="301">
<HEAD>APPENDIX (to Group <B>B</B>, p. 591). [<I>Christ Church MS.</I> 152.]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[on leaf 173, back, sign. k 2, back]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sire Nonnes preest oure hoost seyde a none</L>
<L>y-blessed be thy breth &amp; euery stoone</L>
<L>This was a mery tale of Chaunteclere</L>
<L>But be my trouthe if thou were seculere</L>
<L>Thow woldeste bene a tredefoul a right</L>
<L>ffor if thow haue corage as thou haste myght</L>
<L>The were nede of hennes as I wene</L>
<L>Ye moo than .vij. tymes seventene</L>
<L>See whiche braunnes hath this gentel preeste</L>
<L>So grete a nekke &amp; so large a breeste</L>
<L>He loketh as a Sparhauke with his yen</L>
<L>Hym nedeth nat his colour for to dyen<MILESTONE UNIT="Christ Church MS. 152 folio" N="174a, sign. k 3"></L>
<L>with Brasile ne with Greyne of Portyngale /</L>
<L>Now sire faire falle yow for youre tale</L>
<L>And aftir he with full mery chere</L>
<L>Saide vnto a nother as ye shulle here</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Here is ended the Nonnes prestes tale And folowith the prologe of the Maunciples tale</TRAILER>
